\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Thursday night, 30 November [1837]
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Charleston
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just finished drinking my tea, have left Mamma & the girls & have come upstairs to write to you.\'a0 I would have written yesterday, but I had been shopping from after breakfast until 3 oclock & was so much fatigued that in the afternoon I was obliged to lie down, & in the evening Aunt Eliza & Aunt Hayne took tea with us.\'a0 I have been in King street all of the morning, but as I rode I do not feel so much fatigued as yesterday.\'a0 I have bought a great many articles & priced almost all, some things are dearer & some \ul cheaper\ulnone  than I expected.\'a0 When I tell you what I have given for the different things you must not scold, for what I have given a high price for, I have made up\'a0 by giving a low price for other things.\'a0 I have bought carpeting for the Drawing room $2. a yard & the dining room $1.40.\'a0 To make up I have gone without a chamber carpet, & have got the Entry & staircase carpet \ul very\ulnone  \ul cheap\ulnone , only 50 cts a yd, & \ul beautiful\ulnone ; the oil cloth would have been for the Entry $40, for it is a dollar & a half by the \ul square\ulnone  \ul yd\ulnone  & the carpeting for the Entry has cost only $17.50, & the staircase $12.50 cts.\'a0 For the entry & staircase carpeting I have given but $30 & the oil\'a0 cloth for the \ul Entry\ulnone  \ul only\ulnone  would have\'a0 been $40.00.\'a0 In addition to going without the chamber carpet, I have determined to buy \ul one\ulnone  Calico dress only, & I think I will even go without a shawl.\'a0 I consult \ul good\ulnone  \ul judges\ulnone  as to the carpeting, & they advised me to think of the quality, & instead of getting such as would last one or two winters, give more & get carpets that would wear well for \ul years\ulnone .\'a0 All of the carpeting I have got for the two rooms, Entry & staircase comes to $170.00 & if I have given \ul less \ulnone for the carpeting & bought a chamber carpet, it would have come to more.\'a0 But I think I have argued the subject sufficiently, & if you see me favourably inclined to one side, your natural disposition will lead you\'a0 to take the other, & you will never be convinced that I am right.\'a0 I have tried to act for the best & if even you \ul my\ulnone  \ul husband\ulnone , do not approve of my conduct I will not be unhappy, for my \ul conscience\ulnone  acquits me.\'a0 I have bought a pair of Astral Lamps for $30, a pair of Pitchers $4.50, a pretty little pair of castors $3.00, nice plated ones are $12, or 14.\'a0 The pair I have got are a new kind & \ul very\ulnone  \ul pretty\ulnone .\'a0 I have got two pair of glass candle sticks $1.00, a pair of Decanters $8.00.\'a0 Other articles I have \ul priced\ulnone  but not bought.\'a0 Tomorrow I intend to look at spoons, Mantel glass, Fenders, Andirons &c.\'a0 Shopping is very fatiguing.\'a0 Sometimes I am inclined to buy a thing at the store I am at, rather than go further.\'a0 I have never been so worried in\'85& constantly thinking can I afford this, can I afford that.\'a0 Shopping is pleasant when you have \ul plenty\ulnone  of money, but not when you are limited to a little sum.\'a0 However you must have \ul confidence\ulnone  in me & \ul believe\ulnone  that \ul all\ulnone  I do is right, & that I have a \ul better\ulnone  \ul judgement \ulnone & more \ul experience\ulnone  in these things than you. I will stop with this subject, & write of what will interest you more.\'a0 You did not expect my first letter to you to be filled up with \ul one\ulnone  subject, \ul shopping\ulnone .\'a0 I will now write of \ul you\ulnone , \ul myself\ulnone  & \ul others\ulnone .\'a0 I \ul miss\ulnone  you a great \ul deal\ulnone , & would have \ul even\ulnone  \ul more\ulnone , if I had not been so engaged in King street.\'a0 Last night I thought sleep had forsaken me.\'a0 I lay so long awake, I suppose it was because I had not \ul you\ulnone \'a0 to caress & put me to sleep.\'a0 I hope it will not be the case tonight.\'a0 You must write to me \ul often\ulnone  to make up for your absence.\'a0 I promise to answer \ul every\ulnone  \ul letter\ulnone , which will be doing \ul well\ulnone , so engaged as I am.\'a0 You recollect last year I was not so punctual, but I\'a0 love you \ul more\ulnone  \ul now\ulnone , than I did \ul then\ulnone .\'a0 I take more pleasure in writing to you.\'a0 My love for my husband is \ul great\ulnone .\'a0 Your wife \ul longs\ulnone  to see you.\'a0 The Diamond Rings are finished, & are \ul very\ulnone  \ul pretty\ulnone .\'a0 Susan & Ann are delighted with them.\'a0 I think they are \ul prettier\ulnone  than the one you first gave me.\'a0 It is a nice guard to my wedding ring.\'a0 I am writing with a very bad pen.\'a0 You must excuse both composition & penmanship.\'a0\'a0 I feel \ul quite\ulnone  \ul tired\ulnone .\'a0 I expect to hear from you on Saturday.\'a0 I hope I will not be disappointed.\'a0 Believe me, your \ul affectionate\ulnone  \ul wife\ulnone , E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\

\f1\b 2
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b 18 December [1837]
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Charleston
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear Sir\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received a letter from you yesterday and answered it immediately, but in reading my answer today, I am not altogether pleased with it, and have determined to write another.\'a0 In future\'a0 I will always send a letter the day I write it, for if you keep it any time, and read it over often, you find so many errors to correct, that you are not satisfied, and in the end destroy it. I was as usual very happy to hear from you.\'a0 When deprived of your \ul presence\ulnone , my greatest pleasure is to \ul hear \ulnone as \ul often\ulnone  as I can, that you are \ul well\ulnone , \ul happy\ulnone  and \ul enjoying\ulnone  yourself. I am sorry my supposed neglect has been the occasion of ruffling your good temper, but I do not think I have neglected you.\'a0 I have not only answered all of your letters but written others besides, which now I am very sorry I sent, as you thought me unkind, and your feelings were hurt. Never mention that word \ul purchases\ulnone  to me.\'a0 I am sick and tired of it.\'a0 If I have been unkind, and neglected you, that has been the occasion of it.\'a0 If you have reproached me, that word has occasioned your reproaches.\'a0 This is the last letter I am to write to you, and I expect to receive but one more from you. Thursday morning you will be here, and I assure you, you return to a wife who loves you, she loves the husband who now returns to her, more than the \ul lover\ulnone  she greeted last year. Mamma and Susan are waiting for me to go out with them.\'a0 This is my excuse for a short letter.\'a0 Excuse the paper on which I have written.\'a0 If you are as interesting as you were last year, it is unnecessary to make an apology. Last night was most tempestuous, yet today is\'85. Uncle Wm is married last Tuesday in the country.\'a0 Believe me, \ul Yours\ulnone  \ul very\ulnone  \ul affectionately\ulnone , E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

\f1\b 3
\f0\b0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\

\f1\b Friday morning, 29 November [1837]
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received your letter last Wednesday, and it gave me \ul much\ulnone  \ul pleasure\ulnone .\'a0 A week has not elapsed yet since I have written to you, but as I think you would like to hear a little oftener than \ul once\ulnone  a week, I will not write you a few lines.\'a0 I will try to write to you \ul twice \ulnone a week.\'a0 If that is not \ul too often\ulnone , perhaps you have not leisure to \ul read \ulnone my letters, if so, tell me.\'a0 \ul You \ulnone must only write to \ul me\ulnone  when at \ul leisure\ulnone , and \ul perfectly\ulnone  \ul convenient\ulnone .\'a0 I do not wish your letters to interfere with any \ul business\ulnone  \ul whatever\ulnone .\'a0 If I do not hear from you I have too much \ul vanity\ulnone  to think it proceeds from \ul neglect\ulnone .\'a0I read your letter in the Mountaineer this morning, and I am glad I did, as it gives me an opportunity of expressing my opinion, and advising you with regard to some of the subjects that will come up before the Legislature for discussion.\'a0\'a0 For instance the Rail Road.\'a0 I \ul hope\ulnone  the State \ul will\ulnone  \ul not\ulnone  give her security for the loan of a million of dollars.\'a0 She has involved herself already, and has better get out of the difficulty as fast as she can, instead of involving herself further.\'a0 The Rail Road was too great an undertaking ever to have been commenced by one State, and everyone has come to that conclusion, though afraid to express it.\'a0 Let the company go on as well as they can, with individual aid, and not impose upon the generosity of the State.\'a0 If they fail, it is well they should at once, without going any further.\'a0 I think my arguments have convinced you, If you were of the contrary opinion.\'a0 I will therefore proceed to the next subject. Retailing Spirits.\'a0 If you read those resolutions passed in Colleton with regard to temperance, you have my opinions.\'a0 I do not think the Legislature ought to act on the subject yet.\'a0 Wait until it has been longer before the people.\'a0 Try other means, before prohibiting the Retailing.\'a0 Next Session, (when you are again elected) will be time enough for the Legislature to consider the subject. Your bill to make Judges go out of office at sixty, is a very good one, if you expect to go in, when one comes out.\'a0 I think it will generally be approved, except by the Judges and their families.\'a0 If it affects those presiding at present, you will lose the vote of Judge Gantts family.\'a0 However as I suppose they are not of much influence in the district, I can get over that objection. Although you are from home, I wish you not only to be \ul satisfied\ulnone , but \ul happy\ulnone  (as I am).\'a0 I would think you would find it very pleasant in Columbia, and after a time when the Conventions are over, it will not be so crowded.\'a0 If you mind being absent from me, the next time perhaps I may go with you.\'a0 Next year our expenses will be so much less than this, that we may have a little money to spare, and it will be quite a pleasant trip.\'a0 You must write a description of the Bride (Mrs. Cunningham).\'a0 I dare say she is pretty.\'a0 If I was Pamela I would have forgiven her for marrying my brother; gone to Columbia in their company, and passed a delightful Session. I received a letter from Susan last Mail.\'a0 She says Mamma has received your letter, and it has given her \ul great\ulnone  satisfaction.\'a0 She says they are all much obliged to you for the trouble you have taken about the house, that now Uncle Robert is gone, they would rather be next you than anyone; that Uncle Arthur is enthusiastic about you (so \ul I\ulnone  say, take care and behave well to him), and that Mamma considers herself favored to have such a Son in law.\'a0 They are pleased with the plan of the house; only wish it higher from the ground if possible.\'a0Mrs. Mays came to see me the other day.\'a0 She says the baby looks like both of us.\'a0 She seemed though to think he looked most like you.\'a0 [word obscured] he has your smile.\'a0 She admired him greatly.\'a0 I like her very much.\'a0 The weather has been so bad I have not been out once since you left, and have seen no one, but Mrs. Mays & Sally Sloane, except Robert who has been here twice every day, after Breakfast and at Tea.\'a0 He goes tonight in the Stage. The Servants do \ul quite\ulnone  \ul well\ulnone , even \ul James\ulnone  attends to his business.\'a0 The Cow gives as much Milk as usual.\'a0 Victoria is well.\'a0 Minerva burned the Chimneys this morning.\'a0 It was raining at the time.\'a0 Willy is quite well, and has \ul grown\ulnone  since you left.\'a0 He improves every day in beauty & interest.\'a0 He sleeps at night in my \ul arms\ulnone , and we have \ul good\ulnone  nights.\'a0 I am not much disturbed.\'a0 I kissed him for you.\'a0 He was in my lap when I read your letter, and he seemed anxious to devour its contents.\'a0 He is a \ul precious\ulnone  \ul little\ulnone  \ul darling\ulnone .\'a0 I am afraid I am not \ul thankful\ulnone  enough for him.\'a0 Delia is very fond of him, and makes him a goo[d] nurse. I must soon stop writing, as I have to writ[page torn] by Robert.\'a0 Excuse the bad writing.\'a0 I write[page torn]\'a0 hurry with a bad pen.\'a0 I pass my time q[page torn] ly; get up early, and do not go to bed until[page torn] am occupied all day, and find the days quite short.\'a0 Do send the Shoes and other things by the first opportunity.\'a0 The Shoes, Gaiter boots I mean will save my buying stockings. Hoping to hear soon from you, and that you are quite well and happy.\'a0 I remain your affectionate Wife, E.F. Perry\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

\f1\b 4
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Sunday afternoon, 1 December 1839
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Having rained the whole week, the walking is so bad, I have not been able to go to church today, and as the baby is quiet with Delia, and I am now at leisure, I think I cannot spend a part of the day better than in writing to you, particularly as I this morning read the Services for the day, and one of Bradley\'92s good sermons, so my conscience acquits me. I hope this letter will arrive in time to \ul prevent\ulnone  your doing what has \ul worried\ulnone  me since I received your last.\'a0 Buy a \ul Rattle\ulnone  for the baby at \ul $6.50\ulnone !\'a0 My husband, how could you think of such a thing when I told you to buy a Rattle.\'a0 I meant a common Straw one, such as I have seen for 25 cts or 50 cts at furthest.\'a0 If we were rich, and had money to throw away, I would not spend such a sum on a\'85to be and you to buy a \ul Rattle\ulnone  for $6.50.\'a0 If you had the money to spare, and had got something useful, or entertaining, such as a Waggon for him, or a Musical box for me, I would have no objection, but to give so large a sum for a handsome toy, when you could have got a common one, for little or nothing, to answer the same purpose. Is what provokes me.\'a0 I think it an actual sin to spend money in such a way, and can hardly think you have done it.\'a0 If you have, do I beseech you carry the Rattle back to the Jeweller, and get him to exchange it for something more useful or interesting.\'a0 If you can think of nothing else, a \ul Musical\ulnone  \ul Box\ulnone , if it does not cost more than $6.50, which you know I always said when we\'a0 had money to spare I would like to \ul have\ulnone , but if you can think of anything more useful get it.\'a0 \ul Do\ulnone  \ul not\ulnone  \ul keep\ulnone  \ul the\ulnone  \ul Rattle\ulnone .\'a0 The bell I bought the other day for 37 \'bd cts will answer the same purpose.\'a0 For once get over your scruples about changing your mind, and exchange the Rattle, the prettier it is, the more loth I would be to put it in a baby\'92s hand.\'a0 The \ul little\ulnone  \ul Waggon \ulnone I would like to have \ul above\ulnone  \ul all\ulnone  \ul things\ulnone .\'a0 That would be \ul indeed\ulnone  \ul useful\ulnone .\'a0 Willie should ride in it every day.\'a0 If you have no other way of getting it home, you must box it up and bring it in the Stage.\'a0 I would deny myself of anything to get it for Willie.\'a0 Riding will be such an amusement for him.\'a0 I will be disappointed if you do not get him the waggon, and truly grieved if you bring home the Rattle.\'a0 I do hope you have \ul not\ulnone  \ul bought\ulnone  it, or if bought it, that you will \ul exchange\ulnone  it.\'a0 In this instance my dear husband please your Wife. Your letters with that \ul one\ulnone  \ul exception\ulnone , have given me \ul much\ulnone  \ul pleasure\ulnone .\'a0 I would like to hear every Mail, if writing to me does not interfere with your other business.\'a0 You have seen Professor Lieber.\'a0 Robert says he \ul has\ulnone  a Wife, that himself, his wife and son, have been at his father\'92s house. A \'93refresher\'94 in Mr. Alston\'92s case would be very acceptable, and cause you to be indebted to the settlers on Paris Mountain.\'a0 Judge Butler\'92s reason for liking you was a very good one. I have not been out of the house since you left.\'a0 It has rained every day until today, the Sun is shining beautifully, but the ground is wet.\'a0 Mr. Townes has a son.\'a0 Minerva says she heard it is so small it can get in a quart cup, that it must have been born prematurely.\'a0 I do not know that this is \ul correct\ulnone .\'a0 I only heard it from \ul Minerva\ulnone .\'a0 Mrs. Sloane is to move into Mr. Roberts\'92 house next week.\'a0 Roberts left yesterday morning.\'a0 He has been to see me \ul twice\ulnone  every day since you left, after breakfast, and at supper.\'a0\'a0 When he bid me good bye, he said, \'93he was much obliged to you and me for our kindness to him.\'94\'a0 I sent by him the box your recollect Aunt Elizabeth Hayne left with me.\'a0 I put in it a pin cushion apiece for Susan and Ann; a little Shoe for Susan Hayne;\'85box I filled up with eatables for Robert.\'a0 I have finished making Delia\'92s Calico dress.\'a0 It is made as nicely as Margaret could have made it.\'a0 She looks so improved in it you would hardly know her.\'a0 I am afraid Willy even feels strangely in her arms.\'a0 This last mentioned personage is \ul now\ulnone  \ul asleep\ulnone  in the cradle.\'a0 May he have a \ul long\ulnone  \ul nap\ulnone .\'a0 I love him more and more every day.\'a0 He increases in interest daily. I think I may get a letter from you this evening, so will stop writing, as I may wish to add a little more tonight.\
\'a0\

\f1\b 5
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Sunday night
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband,\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have this moment received your letter.\'a0 How \ul delighted\ulnone  I am that you have not purchased the Rattle.\'a0 I have almost a mind to tear up this letter and write another, \ul omitting\ulnone  the \ul scold\ulnone , but I think I will let it remain so, as it may serve you as a lesson for the future.\'a0 You must if you are able to get the Waggon and send it home some way or other. Wills hat fits to perfection.\'a0 It is a little beauty, and so becoming to him, you would scarcely believe \ul I\ulnone  made it.\'a0 It is made of striped silk, & the rim turned up.\'a0 I have made one for the society of the same shape. They gave me the materials.\'a0 We have not met since you left as it rained yesterday.\'a0 He has only been to Mrs. Sloanes once.\'a0 I intend sending him to Mrs. Hoke\'92s soon.\'a0 Mrs. Gower sent for him this evening, but he was asleep.\'a0 When he has a \ul carriage\ulnone  \ul of\ulnone  \ul his\ulnone  \ul own\ulnone , he shall go out a great deal. James does quite well.\'a0 Victoria\'92s misconduct was not his fault.\'a0 It seems to me Rose gives as much Milk as usual.\'a0 I have now a bowl full of Cream.\'a0 Carlos has acted badly.\'a0 She almost killed the Duck.\'a0 I thought it had better be put to death, but contrary to my expectations it has recovered.\'a0 The other night after I was in bed, & the candle put out, I heard him howling in the Drawing room.\'a0 Delia was obliged to come down & let him out, and this evening he was at the front door & knocking & looking for admittance in a furious manner.\'a0 He was turned away with the broom stick.\'a0 Uncle Arthur had better give up all thoughts of Presiding & quietly go home & preside over his own household.\'a0 Good night, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
\'a0\
Columbia\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 6
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Thursday morning, 5 December 1839
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I was disappointed last night in not hearing from you.\'a0 I believe no Columbia package arrived, or if it did nothing for me.\'a0 I received a letter from Susan, which in some measure made up for not hearing from you. Your Waggons from Pickens arrived yesterday.\'a0 The Man (I do not know his name) says the agreement was to bring one Waggon for 95 dollars, and the \ul wooden\ulnone  part of another Waggon of the same size for 25 dollars, which made up the debt of a hundred dollars.\'a0 He says the Waggon was not to have been \ul painted\ulnone , but someone offered to paint it, if he could have the use of it for a few days, and he drove it to some place (E\'85I believe) and was offered 90 dollars right off for the Waggon, so that though you have got it for 75 dollars only.\'a0 You can sell it for 90 dollars.\'a0 It is a Red Waggon, and is now standing in the Stable yard.\'a0 The pieces of the other Waggon, I have had put in the Lumber room, that they may not be exposed to the rain.\'a0 A Blacksmith will have to put them together.\'a0 You must expect in parting with the Waggon to ask \ul 90 dollars\ulnone . The weather is now good, and has given me an opportunity of returning some of my visits, and of others coming to see me.\'a0 Tuesday Miss Harrison & Charlotte Smith came, and afterwards Mr. Pinckney, who said, he was afraid I might be sick as I was not at church on Sunday, so had come to see me.\'a0 He was very kind, and said his Sister was coming to see me, to ask me to spend the day with them this week.\'a0 So accordingly Miss Pinckney came yesterday, paid me a long visit, and said, I must take my work, and my baby, and go early tomorrow morning and spend the day with them, so I am to dine with them tomorrow.\'a0 Miss McBee afterwards came and then Mrs. Dr. Butler.\'a0 I showed Mrs. Butler the hat I had made for my baby, and she admired it so much, and said \ul her\ulnone  \ul baby\ulnone  was \ul greatly\ulnone  in want of one, and that she did not know \ul where\ulnone  she could get one, that I offered to \ul make\ulnone  her one, furnish the Silk and all.\'a0 You know she has been kind in sending us things, and she admires Willy so much, that she has quite won my heart.\'a0 So I intend to deny myself of something or other I may need, and spend the money in getting the materials to make the hat for her baby.\'a0 I assure you I am so beautiful a Milliner, that if reduced I could even gain a livelihood, by bringing into use my accomplishments in that line.\'a0 Miss McBee said she had no idea I was so ingenious, that one not accustomed or \ul obliged\ulnone  to work, should work so beautifully.\'a0 I told her, since I could recollect I always had been fond of my needle, that we \ul all\ulnone  could work.\'a0 I commenced showing her how to knit Socks. Yesterday afternoon Mrs. Coleman came to see me, but I was out.\'a0 I had gone to see Mrs. Hoke and Mrs. Townes.\'a0 Mrs. Townes\'92 baby is really the \ul ugliest\ulnone  \ul little\ulnone  \ul thing\ulnone  I have ever seen, though rather \ul too\ulnone  \ul large\ulnone  to get into a \ul quart\ulnone  \ul cup\ulnone .\'a0 It was born a month too soon, so Mrs. Gordon says it will \ul sleep\ulnone  for \ul one\ulnone  \ul month\ulnone  instead of being able to\'85like Willy.\'a0 It looks as if it hardly \ul breathed\ulnone .\'a0 It is a weak, puny little thing, but do not \ul mention\ulnone  what I say to anyone, as it may seem \ul ill\ulnone  \ul natured\ulnone , but I only tell the truth.\'a0 I carried Will with me, and Mrs. Townes says he is the \ul prettiest\ulnone  \ul baby\ulnone  she has ever seen.\'a0 She thanked me kindly for some Syllabubs I had sent her the day before, & which she said were the \ul nicest\ulnone  she had ever tasted.\'a0 Mrs. Wm Roberts was there and as she held Willy, she said, \'93this baby is just ten days older than mine would have been.\'94\'a0 I felt \ul sorry\ulnone  when I thought what \ul comfort\ulnone  she had been deprived of.\'a0 Mrs. Roberts, Mrs. Sloane\'92s daughter seems an amiable lady. The Servants have all gone to the \ul Show\ulnone .\'a0 It has been the subject of conversation for days past, so I told them if they behaved well, I would give them 25 cts apiece & let them go.\'a0 Minerva & Delia, so I gave them quarter of a dollar, but James staid so long last night at the Post office playing, I was obliged to send Delia after him so I would not give him the money but have made him pay his \ul own\ulnone  \ul expenses\ulnone .\'a0 They have all three just gone off, so Willy and me are alone.\'a0 He is on the carpet amusing himself. Mrs. Butler says it is paying Willy \ul no\ulnone  \ul compliment\ulnone , but he is the image of you, particularly his \ul nose\ulnone  (which you know is the exact opposite to yours).\'a0 Willy\'92s eyes are particularly admired & are pronounced by all, \'93\ul very\ulnone  \ul fine\ulnone  \ul eyes\ulnone .\'94\'a0 Everything said of my \ul husband\ulnone  & \ul child\ulnone  goes \ul straight\ulnone  to \ul my\ulnone  \ul heart\ulnone .\'a0 I have quite forgotten myself. All seem \ul very\ulnone  \ul kind\ulnone  to me, now that I am alone.\'a0 Dr. Crook has been to see me \ul twice\ulnone  and even Mr. Wells, when he came to get your Office key, said \'93recollect if you wish anything call upon some of us.\'94\'a0 I had the baby in my arms, and he said , \'93it was a remarkably fine baby.\'94\'a0 I get along astonishingly.\'a0 Dr. Crook said, \'93who would think for a Charleston g[page torn] come up here, keep house so well \ul alone\ulnone \'85a little \ul Soldier\ulnone .\'a0 Delia and little William are my protectors at night.\'a0 Minerva takes care of the Kitchen & James. Mrs. Henry Earle has a Son.\'a0 Sarah writes word that Eloisa\'92s baby is a \ul weak\ulnone  \ul puny\ulnone  \ul little\ulnone  thing.\'a0 It is a seven months child, and Eloisa is suffering excruciatingly with a Milk fever, which confines her entirely to her bed.\'a0 It must be something like Rheumatism.\'a0 Aunt Eliza\'92s is a remarkably fine child, fat and plump.\'a0 Susan says they saw Mrs. Thompson as she passed through Charleston.\'a0 They went to see her. Dr. Crook offered to take me to see the Giraffe, but I did not care to go.\'a0 Augustus Hoke has this moment come to ask me to go.\'a0 He is the \ul image\ulnone  of his \ul Father\ulnone , even his \ul manner\ulnone .\'a0 Mamma prefers a \ul small\ulnone  \ul door\ulnone  between her Drawing & Dining Rooms &[word obscured] \ul Railing\ulnone , what I call \ul Banisters\ulnone  to her back steps.\'a0I have come to the\'85of the sheet my dear husband, & Willy is crying.\'a0 I am quite \ul well\ulnone , & hope to hear by the next mail that \ul you\ulnone  \ul are\ulnone ; so adieu for the present.\'a0 Your ever affectionate wife, E.F. Perry\
\'a0\
Benjmain Perry\
Columbia\
