\f1\b Sunday night, 8 December 1839
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received two letters from you.\'a0 There must have been some mistake in the Mail, or I would have received one last Friday.\'a0 I am anxious to see the things you have purchased, but you must run no risk in sending them; wait for a safe opportunity.\'a0 Do not purchase the Rattle.\'a0 The Waggon (unless it costs \ul too\ulnone  \ul much\ulnone , for if it costs a \ul great\ulnone  \ul deal\ulnone  I do not wish you to buy it).\'a0 You must contrive some way of bringing home.\'a0 Could you not box it up, and bring it behind the Stage, as if it were a trunk?\'a0 The Waggons that carry cotton to Columbia, are these not returning by the way of Greenville in which you could send a box? You have not mentioned Col. Brockman.\'a0 I suppose you see him often.\'a0 You must not forget \ul Greenville\ulnone  \ul friends\ulnone .\'a0 You are everything to them.\'a0 I think you might as well have given Mr. Powell a certificate.\'a0 I am not sorry he is rejected.\'a0 I feared him as your rival.\'a0 I see by the papers your bill has not passed. Mrs. Beattie came to see me yesterday.\'a0 She said she had heard such accounts of my baby, that though she did not owe me a visit, she had come to see \ul him\ulnone .\'a0 She said Willy is thought the prettiest baby in the village.\'a0 \ul That\ulnone  however is no compliment; the baby\'92s here are so ugly.\'a0 Willy might be the \ul prettiest\ulnone  and yet \ul ugly\ulnone  \ul still\ulnone .\'a0 \ul I\ulnone \'a0 think him the prettiest baby in the \ul State\ulnone .\'a0 He has not only pretty features, but he has a sweet, intelligent countenance.\'a0 He is so strong, lively, and active.\'a0 Mr. Pinckney said the other day looking at him, \'93you are certainly a \ul wise\ulnone  \ul looking\ulnone  little being,\'94 and Miss Pinckney said, he seemed ready to \ul fly\ulnone  \ul away\ulnone  with animation.\'a0 I am shortning his frocks a little, making them all the length of pin\'85 which you may recollect.\'a0 They are still a good ways below his feet.\'a0 Mrs. Butler, Mrs. Beattie and others say it is time for him now to be wearing \ul Shoes\ulnone , so if your \ul funds\ulnone  \ul allow\ulnone  \ul of\ulnone  \ul it\ulnone , I wish to buy him two or three pair of \ul Kid\ulnone  \ul Slippers\ulnone ; you can guess the size.\'a0 Remember the bootees that come up to the \ul ankle\ulnone , but \ul Shoes\ulnone , with a \ul Strap\ulnone  in the \ul back\ulnone , that comes\'85and ties in front.\'a0 If you have not money enough (I know it was pretty scarce with you) it is of no consequence.\'a0 Willy can by holding on to a Chair, \ul almost\ulnone  stand alone. I dined with Miss Pinckney last Friday, and spent a pleasant day.\'a0\'a0 Willy staid upstairs with the children.\'a0 There was no one there but myself.\'a0 Mr. Pinckney was engaged all day on business.\'a0 I only saw him at dinner, and a short time afterwards.\'a0 He seemed \ul depressed\ulnone .\'a0 I know he feels \ul deeply\ulnone  the death of his Wife, though he appears so cheerful in company.\'a0 He must feel her loss every moment on his \ul childrens\ulnone  account.\'a0 I know not a greater affliction that can befal[l] children, than to be deprived of their Mother in Infancy.\'a0 \ul No one\ulnone  can supply \ul her\ulnone  \ul place\ulnone .\'a0 No one else has that instinct, by which she knows at once all their wants, and how to supply them.\'a0 Neither do I know a greater affliction that can befall[l] a husband , than to be deprived of a Wife whom he has married in youth, whom he has fondly, devotedly loved, preferred to all the world beside, and to whom he has been accustomed to impart every thought, wish, and feeling.\'a0 The loss can never be supplied.\'a0 No, not even by a \ul second\ulnone  \ul Wife\ulnone . Mr. Pinckney lent me a Book to read on the \'93Lords Supper.\'94\'a0 I told Miss Pinckney she must return my visit.\'a0 They have things very plain.\'a0 It is a nicely furnished house; so \ul comfortless\ulnone , it has such a \ul bare\ulnone  \ul look\ulnone .\'a0 Large windows glaring open without curtains, a carpet not covering the whole of the room, no fenders &c; a small pine table, in the Dining Room, not even painted, answers as a Sideboard.\'a0 Even Minerva said, \'93Why Mistress. Mr. Pinckney must be very stingy; I never saw such a scant looking house.\'94\'a0 Yesterday the working society was to have met, but it rained.\'a0 So they have not met but \ul once\ulnone  since I joined it. Mrs. Coleman has been to see me \ul twice\ulnone , and left word she could never find me at home.\'a0 The weather has been such, I have been out \ul twice\ulnone  visiting since you left, and those times she came to see me.\'a0 Her little niece (Mr. Young\'92s daughter) is with her.\'a0 I will be so busy this week \ul working\ulnone , perhaps I will not be able to write again until next Sunday.\'a0 Perhaps as it is, I write \ul too\ulnone  \ul often\ulnone .\'a0 I only promised to write \ul once\ulnone  a week, & I have written \ul twice\ulnone .\'a0 I hope you have received \ul all\ulnone  of my \ul letters\ulnone .\'a0I did not know what I was undertaking when I promised Mrs. Butler to make her baby a hat.\'a0 She has sent me the size of the head, and it is larger than mine.\'a0 That must be my first employment.\'a0 I have also a Calico Cloak & Bonnet to make for Willy to wear in the yard; a flannel night dress for him; and some flannel shirts; also to shorten some of his frocks and petticoats; and enlarge his caps, besides mending for myself, and various other things.\'a0 Willy will be \ul six\ulnone  \ul months\ulnone  old tomorrow. I have been to church today morning and afternoon.\'a0 The wind is blowing now.\'a0 It seems to be getting quite cold.\'a0 Mr. Hooker has at last cleaned the roof of the house, and put in the glasses.\'a0 Allan has not done anything yet.\'a0 He says he is employed for his master, will come as soon as he can.\'a0 Carlos has at last \ul killed\ulnone  the Duck.\'a0 Jessie has not made her appearance.\'a0 Victoria is well.\'a0 Rose gives as much Milk as usual.\'a0 The Shoults get their [word obscured] portion of Food, so I suppose are satisfied.\'a0 Minerva, Delia and james were delighted with the \ul Show\ulnone .\'a0 For myself, \ul last\ulnone ; though not \ul least\ulnone ; I am suffering a little with pain in my face.\'a0 A \ul Wisdom\ulnone  \ul Tooth\ulnone  I think is coming.\'a0 I can hardly open my mouth wide enough to eat. Mr. Jacobs sends Butter every Friday, and I always weigh it.\'a0 Last Friday when the Butter came, we had not touched the Butter of the week before.\'a0 I have bought a bushel of Apples.\'a0 I like to give them to the Servants every now and then.\'a0 They are so fond of them.\'a0 I still have some of those left that you bought.\'a0 They improve from keeping.\'a0 I am sorry Wiliam Hayne is drooping.\'a0 I hope his prospects are not so. It is time to go to bed.\'a0 Willy is asleep in the Cradle, Delia on the Rug, and it is twenty minutes past ten oclock.\'a0 I commenced writing late, so good night my good husband.\'a0 Ever Your affectionate wife, E.F. Perry\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

