\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Thursday afternoon, 12 December 1839
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received two letters from you last night.\'a0 Owing to some mistake in the Mail, I was disappointed twice last week in not hearing from you, so to make up I have received by each of the last two Mails two letters.\'a0 Last night I received a letter Dec. 2d, which ought to have been received before the letters that came Sunday night.\'a0 However it has at last come, and I dare say there will be no mistake again.\'a0As you say my letters give you \ul much\ulnone  \ul pleasure\ulnone .\'a0 I will not write to you by \ul every\ulnone  \ul Mail\ulnone .\'a0 I am sorry you are tired of Columbia, and so \ul impatient\ulnone  to get home.\'a0 If you know how \ul well\ulnone  Will and me get along, you would give yourself not a \ul moments\ulnone  concern about us.\'a0 He gives me not the \ul least\ulnone  \ul trouble\ulnone .\'a0 In the day Delia attends to him \ul entirely\ulnone , \ul except\ulnone  when I am nursing him, and at night I manage him so \ul well\ulnone , that I am thinking when you come back, you will be so much in the way, we will have to put you in \'93Old Missi\'92s chamber,\'94 as Delia calls it.\'a0 Will and myself are enough to occupy one bed.\'a0 Now do not give yourself \ul any\ulnone  \ul uneasiness\ulnone  about us, only envy me the happiness of being able to attend to him, and administer to his little wants.\'a0 I am afraid you would be rather \ul mortified\ulnone , if you saw how happy both he and me are during your absence.\'a0 I assure you we employ out time \ul very\ulnone  \ul pleasantly\ulnone , and are \ul very\ulnone  \ul happy\ulnone .\'a0 I do not even feel \ul lonely\ulnone . I am glad you are occupied, and that you think you are gaining a little reputation.\'a0 Oh! My dear husband, I do hope you will continue in the Legislature.\'a0 It is to your \ul interest\ulnone  that you should.\'a0 I think a \ul Lawyer\ulnone  should desire to be a member of the Legislature more than any other person.\'a0 I do not see why Col. Brockman wishes it.\'a0 It is no advantage to him, but to you it is,, and it is the wish of \ul my\ulnone  \ul heart\ulnone  that you may \ul still\ulnone  be a \ul member\ulnone .\'a0 I do \ul hope\ulnone  you \ul will\ulnone .\'a0 The next time perhaps you will be \ul Senator\ulnone .\'a0 You must be \ul quite\ulnone  \ul happy\ulnone  though away from me.\'a0 If you were not sometimes absent from home, you would not know how to value it, so the remainder of your time be \ul contented\ulnone  and \ul happy\ulnone .\'a0 Why do you not send \ul papers\ulnone , \ul pamphlets\ulnone  &c to Dr. Crook, Mr. Duncan, Mr. Earle and \ul all\ulnone  the \ul gentleman\ulnone  here?\'a0 You \ul must\ulnone , If you have not already done so.\'a0 I hope Mr. Powell will not \ul injure\ulnone  you. I would rather you have attended the Commencement of the College, and spent some \ul other\ulnone  \ul time\ulnone  in writing to me, for then you would have told me about it when you come home.\'a0 I mean to ask you many questions.\'a0 Miss Pinckney, Mrs. Sloane and others, say Mrs. J. Cunningham is not pretty, but that she is lively and pleasant, that she is remarkably short and thick.\'a0 It is a pity she dresses in bad taste.\'a0 Pamela is so particular and observant in dress.\'a0 John dresses well.\'a0 He ought to direct his Wife, as I did you.\'a0 You recollect what a change I made in your appearance.\'a0 By the by, have you had your hair cut?\'a0 And has the Barber disfigured you by cutting it too short? I have not seen anything of Mr. Blassinghame.\'a0 I went to see Miss Williford\'92s the other evening, and on the way stopped and showed the baby to Mrs. Curtis.\'a0 She was much gratified & praised him very\'85says he looks like you.\'a0 Miss Margaret Williford says he looks like Ann particularly his mouth & chin.\'a0 Mrs. Service says he looks like me.\'a0 Mrs. [word obscured] yesterday sent me some Jelly.\'a0 Mrs. Sloane this week has borrowed eggs from me.\'a0 Mrs. Hoke has sent for Milk.\'a0 Mrs. Mooney Milk, Mrs. Horton Milk and Meal twice.\'a0 \ul I\ulnone  have \ul ceased\ulnone  \ul borrowing\ulnone  & \ul never\ulnone  will again, because I have an independent spirit.\'a0 It gives me pleasure to give or lend (except to Mrs. Horton who is too en\'85ing).\'a0 It shows I am friendly with my neighbours, and that they think me willing to oblige, but I myself will never borrow.\'a0 The reason I wish you my dear husband to economize, is that you may put up money enough, to render us always independent.\'a0 Until this house is paid for I feel uneasy.\'a0 If you have not spent much money in books I will not \ul scold\ulnone , but you know how much [two words obscured] you have already.\'a0 I am sorry Uncle Arthur is so foolish to continue a Candidate. So Mr. McBee is president of the Rail Road Company.\'a0 Pity so rich a man should have an addition of $4000 a year.\'a0 He ought to attend to it for \ul nothing\ulnone .\'a0 Have you heard anything of William and Pamela?\'a0 Is Mr. Cunningham in Columbia? I always thought Mamma had about $30,000 that if divided equally among us we would have $10,000 apiece, $22,000 in money, 8000 for house and 2000 for negroes would be $32,000.\'a0 I do not see why $5,000 is too much to invest in house and lands.\'a0 The money the house sells for in town will pay for the Greenville place, and Mamma will have the same money to live on she had in town, which will go further here, and bring higher interest.\'a0 I suppose she could not build a house \ul much\ulnone  cheaper, to be comfortable, than [page torn] she is to build.\'a0 It is the \ul land\ulnone  that is so expensive, 50 dollars an acre, though perhaps she could not get it cheaper [word obscured].\'a0 Judge Earle\'92s place is \ul too\ulnone  \ul far\ulnone .\'a0 Mamma would be willing to live on less every year, to enable her to get a place that she fancies, & near the village.\'a0 I wish now her land was just next Mrs. Hornbuckles, as it is, it is rather far.\'a0 However I will \ul talk\ulnone  about all this; writing it takes up too much paper.\'a0If Mr. Brown is in Columbia taking likenesses as he did last year, I wish you would have yours taken \ul without\ulnone  your \ul hat\ulnone .\'a0 I would value it much. I have a \ul commission\ulnone  for you, and if you wish to \ul please\ulnone  me, you must \ul execute\ulnone  it, if \ul within\ulnone  \ul your\ulnone  \ul power\ulnone .\'a0 It is this I wish you to get for me, \'93some \ul pieces\ulnone  of \ul Morocoo\ulnone  of \ul different\ulnone  \ul colours\ulnone .\'94\'a0 You can get it at a Shoemakers or Sadlers.\'a0 I suppose you could get a good parcel for 75 cts or 1 dollar.\'a0 I do not know the price however.\'a0 I wish it to make boxes, pin cushions, needle hooks &c.\'a0 If you can get the Morocoo \ul reasonable\ulnone , \ul do\ulnone  \ul get\ulnone  \ul me\ulnone  \ul some\ulnone , but if they ask a \ul great\ulnone  \ul deal\ulnone , you \ul need\ulnone  \ul not\ulnone .\'a0 At any rate inquire the price.At a Shoemakers or Sadlers, & if it is \ul reasonable\ulnone  \ul remember\ulnone , get me some.\'a0 With this request my dear husband I must close my letter.\'a0 Your affectionate wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

