Sunday night.
\f0\b0 \'a0 \
\
My dear husband, \
\
	I have just received your letter, & it has given me \ul great\ulnone  \ul pleasure\ulnone .\'a0 It also removed any uneasiness, as you do not mention your cold incommoding you.\'a0 Mamma has not yet returned from Mrs. Crofts so I will write until she comes.\'a0 As you took my advice in such good part, instead of ceasing I will continue giving it, on this condition, that you do not follow it unless you \ul choose\ulnone  to.\'a0 Perhaps it may profit you.\'a0 I was just wondering before I received your letter whether you saw as much of Mr. Burt as you used to & whether Mrs. Burt or any of the members wives dictated to them as I do to you.\'a0 I dare say you are the only one who are so much favored; how \ul thankful\ulnone  you ought to be.\'a0 I am glad you remembered me to Mr. Burt.\'a0 You may remember me to whoever you think proper.\'a0 I think you must pass your time quite pleasantly, & would like you to spend it so for \ul years\ulnone  to come, but that is as you think.\'a0 I shall never advise you again on this subject, at least so \ul urgently\ulnone  as I did before, as my advice [word obscured] to have proved so \ul fatal\ulnone .\'a0 I hope while you enjoy pleasant company, you are not \ul inattentive\ulnone  to your \ul Colleagues\ulnone .\'a0 Do be \ul kind\ulnone  to \ul them\ulnone , or when they come home they will tell the people you are \ul proud\ulnone , & as you are \ul not\ulnone  \ul proud\ulnone , you may not make that impression.\'a0 You can \ul gain\ulnone  & \ul lose\ulnone  by \ul them\ulnone  than all the other Members put together.\'a0 It is your \ul Interest\ulnone  to be kind to them.\'a0 Give them no reason for speaking against you here.\'a0 I hope they will not be jealous of you; if you are attentive they will not.\'a0 I hope you send pamphlets, papers, reports & all sorts of things to your constituents, Whigs & Democrats.\'a0 They will then see that you have not forgotten them but are thinking of them \ul all\ulnone  the \ul time\ulnone .\'a0 Do not return home until the Legislature adjourns.\'a0 Stand at your post until the last moment.\'a0 But I hope all this advice is needless. The books you mention as having bought do not suit my taste, except Moore\'92s Life of Bryon, Nicholas Nickleby.\'a0 I am glad to have if it was \ul cheap\ulnone , but the others you mention are \ul mere\ulnone  \ul trash\ulnone .\'a0 I would rather have the works of Bulwer, that you have \ul not\ulnone  got.\'a0 I like them \ul very\ulnone  \ul much\ulnone , & twenty volumes for $2.50!\'a0 I never heard of anything so cheap.\'a0 Do keep the set you have bought already for \ul yourself\ulnone , or get \ul another\ulnone  set \ul like
\f1\b \ulnone  
\f0\b0 them.\'a0 Mamma will either take the numbers you do not wish, or those you have \ul now\ulnone  at \ul home\ulnone . \'a0I would like to have twenty volumes all alike, & so \ul cheap \ulnone too.\'a0 You have none of Bulwers last\'a0 works & I would like to have them.\'a0 The Pickwick papers nobody likes & the others from their very names must be as worthless.\'a0 I like Bulwers writings & that long list I sent you & \'93\ul Madame D\'92Arblay\'92s Life of Dr. Burney\ulnone ,\'94 which I have heard was very interesting.\'a0 Those are the kind of books that I like, at least if they are \ul cheap\ulnone .\'a0 I don\'92t wish them if they \ul cost\ulnone  much.\'a0 I hope you will buy your books at Auction, & then as Bargains; but my dear husband don\'92t buy too many & in those you do buy make a good selection.\'a0 I like not trash, nor valuable books, but \ul pretty\ulnone  books.\'a0 The Pickwick papers are trash; the Family Library are valuable books.\'a0 Neither of them do I expect to read, but the pretty, light works I like.\'a0 But even in books I leave it to your judgement.\'a0 I suppose you will select well. Mamma has come home.\'a0 She with all of us were \ul Surprised\ulnone  to hear that Mr. Rhett should think the Friendship with him had \ul ever\ulnone  been broken off.\'a0 Mamma was not aware that anything had ever occurred to interrupt it.\'a0 Mamma says that she is Surprised & \ul grieved\ulnone  to hear that he should be under the impression that their had ever been any interruption to the friendship except the circumstance of their living in different places & consequently but seeing very little of each other for some years past, & \ul that\ulnone  though it interrupted their intercourse,\'a0 produced no change in [word obscured] towards him.\'a0 Tell him since their friendship first commenced, Mamma has never changed or ceased to have the \ul greatest\ulnone  \ul regard\ulnone  for him.\'a0 She considers him one of the best & most disinterested friends she every had.\'a0 Uncle Roberts feelings & behaviour to him\'a0 would not in the slightest degree have influenced her.\'a0 The Friendship she has for him will continue through life, even if they never meet again. & she hopes he knows there was no real interruption to their feelings of regard except in his imagination, that the friendship which she hopes he still feels for her will always continue.\'a0 There are such sacred feelings connected with him\'a0 & his regard for our family that nothing could make us change in our feelings towards him.\'a0 The advice he alludes to as having given was on this occasion; when my brother returned from the North in bad health, when he recovered, his Uncles did not wish him\'a0 to go back again, but Mr. Rhett advised that he should return & finish his Collegiate course.\'a0 Mamma followed his advice.\'a0 She sent him back & when his health again became bad, Mr. Rhett went on for him, brought him home, carried him to Beaufort & kept him there for several months pursuing his studies.\'a0 Uncle Robert was not offended at his advising differently from himself.\'a0 Mamma says she knows he was not.\'a0 Miss Cheves [word obscured] might have had something to do with his coldness.\'a0 She was staying at his house when Mr. Rhett became engaged to her.\'a0 Aunt Brewton at first wished the match very much & I believe assisted in different ways conveying notes &c.\'a0 Afterwards when Miss Cheves broke off the match from fear of her father, she misrepresented him & spoke against him.\'a0 I believe she denied that she had been engaged to him when \ul he\ulnone  said she was (& of course they were engaged).\'a0 These things perhaps prejudiced Uncle Robert & Aunt Brewton against him.\'a0 Mr. Rhett I believe thought Aunt Brewton afterwards took Miss Cheves part & perhaps influenced her.\'a0 This made him dislike Aunt Brewton & treat her with neglect, & she thought he had treated her ungratefully.\'a0 I do not know if you understand it, but what I mean is that if Uncle Robert behaved coldly this affair might have had something to do with it, & Uncle Robert I believe thought he was conceited & turbulent & [word obscured].\'a0 \ul Do tell what I have told you\ulnone  to Mr. Rhett, or else he will think we have been very ungrateful.\'a0 Tell him Mamma always has & always will have the \ul greatest\ulnone  \ul regard\ulnone  for him.\'a0\'a0 There never was any interruption to their friendship on her \ul part\ulnone .\'a0 It was only a suspicion of his, for Uncle Roberts feelings would not have influenced her.\'a0 She considers him of the best & most disinterested friends she ever had, & hopes his friendship will always continue for her even if they never met again.\'a0 I have always liked & admired him \ul very\ulnone  \ul much\ulnone  & take the greatest interest in him.\'a0 I would like to see him again.\'a0 Mamma regrets they have been able to see so little of each other for the last years.\'a0 Remember & tell him all I have said.\'a0 [word obscured] word about Miss Cheves if you would \ul rather\ulnone  not, but tell the first part & the last part.\'a0 Mamma requests it & it must seem to him so ungrateful, that anything should cause Mammas friendship for him to cease.\'a0 Ann is delighted with the [word obscured] box, Susan with the Gold thimble.\'a0 They would rather have them than anything.\'a0 Bring Mamma a butter knife like ours instead of a book.\'a0 She will be very much pleased with it.\'a0 If you see no hat suitable for Will it is no consequence.\'a0 I can make one or send to town for one where they will be cheaper than in Columbia.\'a0 If you see a suitable one it is \ul dear\ulnone  I would rather not have it.\'a0 I wish you to bring me \ul no\ulnone  \ul present\ulnone .\'a0 Those things you have bought for the [word obscured]\'a0 particularly the silver forks I will consider as my present.\'a0 You cant afford to buy so many different things, so I would much rather you buy nothing more 