\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received a letter from you, and it has given me such \ul pleasure\ulnone  that I cannot rest until I have expressed it to you.\'a0 I read the Cheraw paper before I opened your letter.\'a0 I know from your sending it, that it contained something complimentary to yourself, and I am \ul very\ulnone  \ul much\ulnone  \ul pleased\ulnone  with it.\'a0 The description is \ul so\ulnone  \ul correct\ulnone , and I am glad to find that you are appreciated by some at last.\'a0 Oh if you only lived among the intelligent and refined how much you would be valued.\'a0 I am grieved to think that if you were a Candidate another year, you might not even be elected; \ul you\ulnone  who ought to be considered an \ul honour\ulnone  to your district.\'a0 I wish you would write word to have that peice published in the Mountaineer that it may open the eyes of your Constituents.\'a0 What a discriminating man Col. Dudley is.\'a0 I like him very much, & have the highest opinion of his judgement.\'a0 He was right in putting you at the head of all.\'a0 Perhaps he has the same opinion of you as Mr. Luther McBee thinks I have.\'a0 The other evening at Mrs. Croft\'92s, he said to me, \'93Why Mrs. Perry thinks there is nobody equal to Major Perry.\'94\'a0 Without my intending it, he discovered my real opinion of you.\'a0 By the way I wish to tell you\'a0 that I like some of the Whigs very much, & he among them, as I wish you to be \ul just\ulnone , \ul liberal\ulnone  & \ul honourable\ulnone  towards them.\'a0 I wish I had given you this advice at \ul first\ulnone , but I hope you have acted upon it from your own high sense of justice & honour.\'a0 Mr. Adams is a particular friend of Mamma\'92s; though like Mr. Rhett, from not being in the same place. They have not seen much of each other lately.\'a0 The acquaintance commenced in New Haven. I am delighted to hear that you have made such a triumphant speech.\'a0 I wish I could have heard it.\'a0 I hope to have that pleasure some day.\'a0 You ought to send a great many of that Cheraw paper to your constituents, that they may see what you really are.\'a0 I am much comforted to find that you have only followed the last & best part of my advice.\'a0 I was quite worried to think that from the \ul high\ulnone  \ul opinion\ulnone  you had of me, you might be influenced by me, contrary to your own judgement.\'a0 I am glad to find that you had a higher opinion of yourself.\'a0 My only advice to you now, for I cant help giving some,\'a0 is to be \ul just\ulnone , \ul liberal\ulnone  , & honourable to \ul all\ulnone  \ul parties\ulnone ; not to be influenced by party spirit.\'a0 For all parties are alike.\'a0 There are good & bad ones\'a0 among all, & the next political subject that comes up, you do not know\'a0 who you will be thrown amongst; perhaps the very ones you now oppose, so that ought to make a man moderate, liberal, just & honourable.\'a0 But you know all this as well as I do & better too.\'a0 I am going out of my proper sphere. But I was afraid you might be \ul unjust\ulnone  to the Whigs because you thought \ul I\ulnone  disliked them very much, & I wish you to understand that you must act \ul well\ulnone  towards them in the legislature whenever you think proper.\'a0 To conc[ink blotted] do as you think best.\'a0 You must not bring Mamma an expensive \ul Butter\ulnone  \ul Knife\ulnone .\'a0 You cant \ul afford\ulnone  it.\'a0 You must bring a \ul plain\ulnone  one.\'a0 Susans & Anns presents have cost so much, that you ought not to spend much on the butter knife.\'a0 Mamma would not care for such an extraordinary handsome one.\'a0 Ours were very pretty.\'a0\'a0 Susan & Ann are very much pleased & say they will keep the presents in remembrance of you as long as they live.\'a0 I am afraid the knives & spoons you have bought are too pretty, through I should judge they were reasonable.\'a0 I must take care next year to have some nice pickles to bring the pickle knives into notice.\'a0 They will then be quite useful.\'a0 [ink blotted] recollect that children of Will\'92s age wear pretty little \ul cloth\ulnone  \ul caps\ulnone  of various [ink blotted] ; perhaps you may see one that may suit him, & it will look better for winter than a straw hat; not a \ul fur\ulnone  cap, but a \ul cloth\ulnone  \ul cap\ulnone  so you may display your taste in selecting him one; a pretty little \ul cloth\ulnone  \ul cap\ulnone  suitable for his age & size.\'a0 I have seen \ul velvet\ulnone  ones also, but they perhaps might look too fine.\'a0 I leave it to your taste, but if you do not see a pretty suitable one, then bring him a Fathers love, & it will be as acceptable to him I am sure as anything else.\'a0 The other day Dr. Crook was here.\'a0 Will went to him, but did not take him for \ul you\ulnone  again, so tell Mr. Burt on a nearer\'85to him, Will finds there is not the least likeness\'a0 between Dr, Crook & his Papa.\'a0 I am certain he will recognize you, but I long to have the opportunity of seeing the recognition.\'a0 I do not think the Legislature will adjourn the 18
