\f1\b 23
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Thursday night, 5 May 1842
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 It is now past eight oclock.\'a0 Margaret has just left me.\'a0 She has been here all day,\'a0 She is coming again tomorrow which would prevent my writing to you, so I am obliged to embrace this opportunity to enable you to hear by Sunday\'92s Mail.\'a0 I received your letter last night and as you may suppose it gave me great pleasure.\'a0 I was glad to hear you arrived safely and enjoyed the stores Mamma and myself provided for you.\'a0 I wish I had furnished you more abundantly, for I was afraid among you all you had hardly enough to stay your appetites.\'a0 I hope you found the Cherry bounce an agreeable addition to your bread stuff, at any rate that it was not in the way. I am sorry you have not been able to purchase \'93Destiny\'94, my heart was set upon your reading it.\'a0 It is so interesting, and I was desirous you should see that my taste and judgement were better than you imagined.\'a0 I think to make up you will have to bring me \'93Womans Reward\'94 or \'93The three Eras in Womans Life.\'94 You say you hope I have had no trouble with the servants.\'a0 I have had none except with George, who I am sorry to tell you has not done as well as usual.\'a0 He will not do anything except when he pleases, and it only pleases him to work in the garden.\'a0 Day after day he goes into the garden and hoes, hoes, when there are no weeds to be hoed.\'a0 He will neither whitewash, scour or cut up wood.\'a0 The wood is so large it can hardly be used in the kitchen much less in the house, and these cold days, particularly cold morning I have been obliged to sit without fire, and with my baby looking blue with cold until today when I paid Mr. Goodlet\'92s Jacob 12 \'bd cts for cutting up some wood,\'a0 Do you not think It would have been much more comfortable for myself & children to have been seated by a warm fire [on] a cold morning, than to have the weeds hoed in the garden.\'a0 As for the Scouring I excused him, because he said he had a pain in his shoulder, which he thinks perhaps he will never get rid of and that he may never again be able to scour.\'a0 But it put me to great inconvenience to hold the baby while Delia was scouring.\'a0 He will not Whitewash either, the only thing he likes to do is to work in the Garden.\'a0 I tell you these things to amuse you, and show you what an odd disposition he has.\'a0 I am glad you did not purchase him at $500.\'a0 It is too much to give for an old man, who will be less and less valuable every day that passes over his head, and who is disabled by Rheumatism from doing almost any kind of hard work.\'a0 I think another year you ought to get him\'85dollars, and the next year for less, particularly if the pain in his shoulder continues. Susan & myself rode to Mrs. Tabers one evening\'a0 and went over the house; there is scarcely any furniture in it, but of the little there is, there are a few peices I would like to have.\'a0 I dare say if she can neither sell or rent the place, she would like to dispose of the furniture, and that she would take very little for it.\'a0 There is a painted press such a one\'a0 as I have often told you I would like to have; also a wooden Sofa, stuffed, very comfortable, almost exactly the shape of our drawing room, with a pretty cover on it.\'a0 It would look very nice in the dining room.\'a0 It would be delightful to loll on by the window in summer and by the fire in winter.\'a0 You would like it exceedingly.\'a0 There were two nice bedsteads, a looking glass, 3 basin stand[s], & a few painted chairs.\'a0 These things with a few tables some paint stained, some common pine ones, & two Ottomans is all the furniture in the house.\'a0 You must ride there when you come back. I am getting quite sleepy & as you can perceive from the mistakes I make, you disapprove of going to bed late, and as it always gives me pleasure to act according to your wishes, present or absent, I must soon close my letter and retire.\'a0 I have no news to tell you.\'a0 I will be very glad to see you again, but you must not return before you have finished your business.\'a0 Do not be worried about me.\'a0 I get along quite smoothly and comfortably.\'a0 George, I dare say will do better.\'a0 I have not been worried by him, only provoked a little at his obstinacy.\'a0 You must write when convenient.\'a0 You forgot to take the measure of Wills Shoe.\'a0 I will send it in this letter.\'a0 Do not forget Anna\'92s carri[a]ge.\'a0 She and the rest of us are quite well.\'a0 Susan was here today, Ann is suffering a great deal.\'a0 Willy says Pa is coming Sunday night.\'a0 I bought this pen on purpose to write to you, and Delia has spoilt it by making nose eyes & mouth on a cloth baby.\'a0 I heard from Mrs. Townes today.\'a0 She was quite well.\'a0 Good night.\'a0 Your affectionate Wife, E.F.P. If you do not hear by Wednesdays Mail you may know I have nothing to write about.Be sure to get the shoes large enough.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

\f1\b 24
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Sunday night, 27 November [1842]
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b [Greenville]
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 According to promise I take up my pen to write you a few lines.\'a0 The children have just gone to sleep.\'a0 They are both upstairs, & I hope will sleep soundly until I have finished my letter.\'a0 I neglected getting from you good pens & paper, so my first letter will present to the eye very little to boast of.\'a0 Tomorrow I will provide myself with better materials from Mr. Nicol, & you must make many apologies for this one. The children are both well, & behave pretty well.\'a0 I asked Will at supper what I should tell you for him.\'a0 He said, Tell Pa to buy me a horse, & that I have been a good boy.\'a0 There was no service this afternoon at the Episcopal church, so I let Delia go out, & took charge of the children myself.\'a0 I amused Willy by telling him stories about the pictures in his book, & he seemed very much interested.\'a0 Anna in the meanwhile walked about tearing up paper, snatching every now & then at Willy\'92s book, & busying herself in various ways, & looked so sweet & healthy, that I wished you were here to admire her.\'a0 I heard this morning Mr. Pinckney\'92s fifth sermon on the Millenium.\'a0 It was an interesting one.\'a0 He gave no reason for not preaching this afternoon.\'a0 I saw Mrs. Sam Earle at church.\'a0 She is now staying with her mother.\'a0 She said she intends coming to see me tomorrow.\'a0 She rode home in the carri[a]ge with Susan & myself.\'a0 Her mothers carri[a]ge was full.\'a0 She said she was sorry you are not a member of the Legislature & that she heard a great many regret you did not offer.\'a0 You may be sure I agreed with her. For I will never cease to regret your refusing to be a member.\'a0 If you have any regard for me you must offer for the senate the next time.\'a0 I am sure you could beat any one man in the district, though you do not stand so good a chance when four are to be elected, & for the senate you will have the trouble of electioneering but once in four years.\'a0 Mrs. Earle said her mother since she had seen Willy in church was almost crazy about him.\'a0 She thought him so beautiful, & now quite abused her child\'a0 because Willy was so much prettier than him; that until her Mother saw Willy, she had thought her child quite pretty.\'a0 Susan slept here last night.\'a0 She had been so much disturbed the previous night on account of Ann, that she wished to have a good nights rest, to enable her to sit up tonight & relieve Mamma.\'a0 They think Ann suffers as much, if not more than she ever has done, & they are constantly witnessing her sufferings.\'a0 Now I feel \ul greatly\ulnone  for Ann, but I cannot realize how she suffers, for I am not in the house with her & do not see her at the time she suffers the most but I know she is a great sufferer.\'a0 Last night was the seventh night she had not slept. Aunt Eliza in her last letter \ul requested\ulnone  Mamma to invite \ul you\ulnone  & \ul myself\ulnone  to pay her a visit this winter, that she would be very happy to have us with her.\'a0 She says nothing but Mr. Hayne\'92s \ul desperate\ulnone \'a0 situation would induce him to offer for an office, & that she will feel bitterly his defeat, that she thinks his \ul few\ulnone  \ul real\ulnone  friends & they are few indeed will exert themselves greatly.\'a0 I really think my dear husband you might do something for him.\'a0 You might ask Mr. Johnson, Mr. Cox, Mr. Earle to make Mr. Hayne at any rate their \ul second\ulnone  choice.\'a0 I would be gratified at your doing something for him. Judge Earle the morning he left authorized Mr. Choice to give George a ticket to look out for an owner for himself at 300 dollars until Thursday.\'a0 Mamma is strongly inclined to purchase him & I have advised her to, but she does not like to take so important a step without consulting you.\'a0 What a pity Judge Earle did not come to this determination before you left.\'a0 George seems suddenly to have acquired the use of his limbs & looks quite well.\'a0 He says he will give up drinking &Mamma can supply him with Tobacco (she says).\'a0 She will only lose 18 or 21 dollars interest a year, & that is not as much as she pays now for the hire of an additional servant.\'a0 George can work well for 10 or 15 years at least, & when he is too old to work, the expense of supporting him will not be much. He is very anxious Mamma would purchase him.\'a0 He dislikes leaving Greenville & his wife.\'a0 All to whom he has applied say they would like if they could to own him very much, that he can do everything so well.\'a0 You know we have never had \ul proof\ulnone  of his being dishonest.\'a0 We have only \ul suspected\ulnone  him.\'a0 With Mamma he would be out of the village, away from temptation, & John who is perfectly honest would be a guard upon him & himself has the superintendence of the Stable & Crib. So that George [if] he is dishonest would not have it in his power to be dishonest as he had here & when Mr. Croft takes home Rachel he can cook for Minerva & he can cut up wood, & keep the garden & whole place in such good order.\'a0 If Mamma thought you would approve of it, she would buy him instantly, & she wishes she could hear from you before George leaves but as no one is authorized to detain him longer than Tuesday he will have to go, but if you approve of the purchase, she wishes you to ask Judge Earle to let George return to Greenville & she will be his purchaser.\'a0 If Judge Earle has a kind heart he will certainly consent, if it is only on account of George\'92s wife, but not being himself a husband, perhaps he will have no sympathy on that point.\'a0 But I really think it is cruel to treat a man at George\'92s time of life in that way, now that he is in Greenville & former connexions, he ought to be allowed to remain for the rest of his life, & not for a hundred or 2 dollars carried to a strange place, separated from his wife, and perhaps be unhappy for the remainder of his existence.\'a0 Perhaps to have gai.. my cause I ought to have been less warm, & taken less interest in the subject, for now from obstinacy you will take the other[word obscured by repair tissue]advise Mamma not to buy him & refuse to say anything to Judge Earle but I request you to consider the subject well.\'a0 I am certain you will come to the conclusion to request Judge Earle to send George back to Greenville & let Mamma become his owner.\'a0 He servants have done quite well except Eliza one day[word obscured by tissue repair]me a little, but if she behaves well the remainder of your absence she need not forfeit her present.\'a0 I \ul miss\ulnone  you of \ul course\ulnone  but do not be anxious about me or hurry back on my account.\'a0 Stay as long as you ought.\'a0 Write me all the news.\'a0 I am ashamed of my letter.\'a0 If I thought it would get safe I would send it by George, but I afraid he might not find you.\'a0 My next shall be more creditable.\'a0 I have no news to tell.\'a0 I wrote more than I intended on this last page & have had to cut the sheet longer than I purposed\'85have therefore spaces left at the bottom of these pages & not room enough on this page.\'a0 I have been reading an account of Colts suicide.\'a0 What a warning his fate brought on by his own conduct, ought to be to others.\'a0 Mr. Simms ought to make it the foundation of a novel.\'a0 Good night.\'a0 Ever your affectionate wife, E.F.P.\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
