\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Wednesday morning, 29 November 1843
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Though very busy working, I have stopped to write you a few lines, to prevent you being disappointed Friday night & to inform you how we are coming on.\'a0 You forgot to leave me good pens.\'a0 Those in the desk are so bad, I can hardly work with them, so you must make many allowances for bad writing.\'a0 I look forward with great pleasure to hearing from you tonight.\'a0 It seems an age since you left home. The incident of greatest importance that has occurred, has been a visit from Delia\'92s mother.\'a0 She came Sunday evening in the stage & left this morning.\'a0 She said this was the time she intended visiting Delia, that her little girl made a mistake when she said Christmas, that at Christmas if convenient she would like Delia to visit her, when she expects to see some of her other children.\'a0 I was very much pleased with Milly. She was far superior to what I expected to find her, & much younger & better looking.\'a0 She seemed very much pleased to find Delia so well situated, & gave her a great deal of good advice, to behave herself well & be thankful for having such good owners.\'a0 Very differently situated did she find Caroline, who she went to see & passed one night with.\'a0 She says Mrs. Lynch gave her a most dreadful character which she does of all of her servants except one, that she gives her very little to eat, & that all the clothes she had on, would not be enough to make an apron, & after working out all day, when she comes home at night from the fields, she has to spin a card of cotton, which would take her until 10 oclock, & Mrs. Lynch wont let her have the bed clothes to sleep on, which she gave her when she was sold (her share of the family estate).\'a0 She must be treated very badly.\'a0 I have always heard Mrs. Lynch was very cross.\'a0 Milly took off one of her petticoats, & made it into one for Caroline, & made her something else out of Hom\'85 she carried her.\'a0 She & Delia both cried at the thoughts of Caroline\'92s situation.\'a0 I have promised that Delia shall go to Spartanburgh at Christmas if she is a good girl.\'a0 Delia is 16 years old next July.\'a0 I will tell you all about the visit when you return.\'a0 Milly was delighted with Mamma who she went to see.\'a0 I told her she must see the old Missus as well as the young.\'a0 Miss Susan was very pretty but not prettier than me although I was married. Your trunk has come home & is a beautiful one.\'a0 If you had it with you where you were not known, you would certainly be taken for an old bachelor.\'a0 I have had no trouble with servants.\'a0 Jim is today helping John kill hogs, (Mamma bought five from Mr. McClanahan) & John says he will return the favour.\'a0 Jim I think is a very good servant.\'a0 I don\'92t know that you would have got a better one.\'a0 Eliza has been several days at Mamma\'92s working, but is now at home ironing.\'a0 Delia I hope will be better for her mothers visit.\'a0 Lindy & Edward do quite well, but are often in each others way.\'a0 Minerva I have scolded \ul once\ulnone  for sitting in \ul her\ulnone  \ul room\ulnone  in the morning \ul working\ulnone , instead of getting breakfast & James I know nothing about. The children of course you wish to hear about, & in compliment to you I will commence with Frank.\'a0 He is a sweet creature, now sleeps in Delia\'92s lap.\'a0 I am seated in the chamber.\'a0 Anna & Will every now & then run against the table & shake it.\'a0 I give them a slap & send them off & tell them I will inform you what bad children they are.\'a0 Anna is now rocking my chair.\'a0 Well!\'a0 Frank is quite well & grows & improves.\'a0 He laughs aloud, & can almost creep.\'a0 Anna has been very unfortunate, & burnt her arm against the chimney dog.\'a0 She was standing on the Fender trying to reach something from the Mouth peice when she fell forward; fortunately she was at the side of the chimney, instead of directly in front.\'a0 So instead of her face, her arm went against the dog & was burnt.\'a0 It is getting well, & you need not be uneasy.\'a0 I am determined she shall not get burnt again.\'a0 I was near her when she fell, & pulled her out instantly.\'a0 Willy fell out of bed one night & bruised his nose.\'a0 I put him on the outside, that I might be between Anna & himself. & keep Anna covered, but after the fall I took Anna in my bed, as well as Willy, so we all now sleep together.\'a0 The Bedstead must think it a great imposition.\'a0 We have reserved the cot for you.\'a0 I am so well pleased with the present arrangement, I could not be induced to change it.\'a0 Willy one night complained of being sick. & I gave him a dose of oil.\'a0 It did him \ul good\ulnone  & he is now \ul quite\ulnone  \ul well\ulnone .\'a0 Ann has been very poorly, but the weather has been disagreeable.\'a0 I have not been able to go to see her.\'a0 It rains every night, continues cloudy through the day, & the walking is very bad.\'a0 Mamma sends messages to say I must go whenever I can.\'a0 I intended going today if the weather permitted, but it rained hard last night.\'a0 Susan bought Anna a dress last week [page torn].\'a0 Ann sleeps very little now.\'a0 I will go to see them tomorrow if I can.\'a0 I have not been out of the house ounce since you left.\'a0 I am so busy, I have not even \ul opened\ulnone  Miss Bremer\'92s \'93Neighbours\'94.\'a0 I think it best not, for if I commence it, I cant stop until I have finished it. I know of nothing new to tell you.\'a0 I may not write again for several days, so do not be disappointed or uneasy, when you do not hear.\'a0 And give yourself no trouble about your large family at home.\'a0 They are getting along quite well. I saw the death of Mr. Cunningham bookseller in Columbia.\'a0 I suppose it is the person from whom you have bought books.\'a0 I have heard nothing more of Judge Earle.\'a0 I suppose he is still in the land of the living. No letters have come for you.\'a0 A paper from the commissioner of pensions has come, telling some pensioner that he has been removed from the list in this state to Tennessee I believe.\'a0 Will sends a great many messages about his cocked hat with a feather stuck up in it, his belt. Sword, gun &c. that he had new shoes, that Delia\'92s\'a0 ma has been here\'85.\'a0 And now my dear husband adieu, until tonight. When I expect to have a very pleasant, though short interview with you after the Mail comes it.\'a0 E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

\f1\b 32
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Monday morning, 4 December 1843
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received a letter from you this morning by Col. Townes, & it was only doubly welcome from having received one last night, for like the drunkard & his glass, getting one letter only makes wish for another.\'a0 I have now three letters of yours to answer. If you know what pleasure they give me, you will feel yourself well repaid for writing them. Since writing the above I have been out to shop with Susan.\'a0 I have now eat[en] dinner & will go on with my letter.\'a0 You must not be uneasy when you do not hear from me, but conclude that I have been very busy, & have nothing to write about.\'a0 Anna\'92s arm is getting better.\'a0 It does not seem to have given her much pain.\'a0 It was a \ul bad\ulnone  burn, but not \ul very\ulnone  bad.\'a0 I have been obliged to send Willy out of the bed into the crib.\'a0 We were so crowded, that if we moved in the least we would strike each other, & little Frank was in great danger. Willy is delighted at the presents you have bought him.\'a0 You must do as you think best about the horse.\'a0 I do not know what to advise you.\'a0 The Camera Obscura must be very pretty.\'a0 I am glad you have sent some oranges to Ann.\'a0 She is pleased at being remembered.\'a0 Susan says she liked the \ul Cocoa\ulnone  \ul nut\ulnone  you bought last year very much.\'a0 So you had better bring her two or three & if you see any presents pretty & \ul reasonable\ulnone  for Susan & herself I would like you to bring them, or at any rate one for Ann.\'a0 It is not like the \ul value\ulnone  of the present, but the \ul remembrance\ulnone  that I like, so you need not bring anything costly.\'a0 Mr. Mauldin has some pretty prayer books for $1.25.\'a0 I wish you to give one of them to Susan at Christmas as a present, but if you were to see a \ul very\ulnone  \ul pretty\ulnone  one at that price, you might buy it for me instead of Mr. Mauldins, but not a cent more must you give.\'a0 Susan says Ann wants you to buy her some good \ul Lavender\ulnone  water.\'a0 You know it is to \ul smell\ulnone .\'a0 I hope the watches will keep good time.\'a0 I will be careful of mine in future. I am sorry you have been obliged to sacrifice your Rail Road stock, as it was in reality worth 1500 dollars.\'a0 You have lost 540 dollars.\'a0 I am glad however that you can pay your debts.\'a0 I hope next year as you will be\'85that you will be able to support your family, invest 1000 dollars profitably, & pay a visit to Washington. Mr. Foster has sent 52 barrels of corn.\'a0 I hope you will pay for it as soon as you return.\'a0 I gave John your message this morning.\'a0 He thanked you & seemed pleased to hear of his son.\'a0 I hope you will see Thomas & bring a letter from him when you return.\'a0 I believe John did not live happily with his first wife & you know coloured persons seem to have a right to many wives. If they are separated from one, they console themselves with another.\'a0 I dare say George has found a helpmate in Columbia long since.\'a0 Have you seen him?\'a0 He ought to send a present by you\'a0 to his wife. I received a letter from Pamela last night, who said she had not been able to invite before.\'a0 Her Mother arrived as she was about finishing her letter with Mrs. Yancey\'92s two children.\'a0 She left Mrs. Yancey in a critical situation with a third attack of bleeding at the lungs.\'a0 She is too sick to think of any removal during the winter & too feeble to have her children with her.\'a0 Pamela says she feels her solitude more than ever, that her head & eyes are so weak she is not able to occupy herself as she used to, that she has often wished for me to be with her.\'a0 It was an affectionate letter.\'a0 I will answer it this week.\'a0 I wish you would pass a night with them on your way home.\'a0 You would then see Mrs. Cunningham who you have not seen for such a long time, & Pamela to will be there as I expect she will not go to town until Mrs. Croft goes.\'a0 Mr. Hayne has sent one of Mr. James G. Holmes Therapeutic chairs to Ann which she finds a great comfort.\'a0 Indeed if she had it not, Susan says she would have been obliged to have been held constantly by Mamma or herself.\'a0 It can be rolled all over the house.\'a0 You can lay down in it, or sit up, & has a place for the feet.\'a0 Susan says it is a delightful chair even for a well person, that it cost twenty dollars but looks as if it were worth a great deal more. This is Sale day.\'a0 I have never seen so many persons in the village.\'a0 We have had very bad weather.\'a0 Today is almost the first good day we have had since you left.\'a0 The streets are very muddy.\'a0 Some reviews have come the Westminster & Quarterly, & a letter from Mr. Fabers agent, Mr. Matthews.\'a0 He says Mrs. Faber will take 2000 dollars for the house clear of all expenses, & that you must not forget the \ul Furniture\ulnone ; that you can have it valued by two disinterested persons & sold separately or to the person who buys the house.\'a0 You would think such a rich lady as Mrs. Faber would forget the little Furniture she has in Greenville, but she remembers it & is afraid you will forget it.\'a0 I wish you would have it valued, & take out your fee in furniture, for I would like very much to have the Wardrobe, some chairs, looking glass &c.\'a0 I am glad you bought a new hat.\'a0 You must bring your old one home, & also another that I think you left in Columbia once.\'a0 Your hatter can alter them to fit himself & James.\'a0 You ought to have sent them by Col. Townes or Mr. Ward.\'a0 I hope you did not wear your new cloak in the rain to the Post office.\'a0 My letter was not worth the wetting yourself & cloak & risking a cold likewise, & now that I think of cold, you must gratify me & get something to cover that spot on your \ul head\ulnone , that will feel the cold so much this winter.\'a0\'a0 When persons say you look \ul young\ulnone , they do not see the back of your head & think how young you look, considering you are so old as to be bald headed. Mamma has just sent word by Sarah Gridley, that I must give her love to you.\'a0 I think with Mr. Pettigru that there are a poor set of Candidates for Judge.\'a0 The country little know what I have deprived them of.\'a0 If it had not been for me, you would now be Judge or one of the greatest Statesmen of the day.\'a0 You ought to be President of the United States.\'a0 The best President you would make, we have ever had.\'a0 But I hope you are happy & that it is all ordered for the best.\'a0 Let us be economical & now put up money, & in time you may go to Congress.\'a0 The country would be better if it had your good Judgment to assist in directing its affairs.\'a0I repeat, you must not be uneasy when you do not hear from me.\'a0 Your letters give me great pleasure.\'a0 I must take Frank so adieu my dear husband.\'a0 E.F.P. Willy thanks you for his presents.\'a0 How large is the horse you think of bringing.\'a0 Can you not describe it exactly.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

