My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 As you do not seem to know exactly when you will be at home & you will be uneasy if you do not hear, I will write a letter, so if you remain in Columbia this week you will hear from me.\'a0 You must not return home \ul one\ulnone  \ul day\ulnone  \ul sooner\ulnone  than your \ul business\ulnone  \ul permits\ulnone .\'a0 Stay as long as you \ul ought\ulnone  to; work \ul hard\ulnone  now, for you will have a \ul long\ulnone  \ul rest\ulnone .\'a0 If you run for \ul Solicitor\ulnone , do not think of returning until the election is \ul over\ulnone .\'a0 Mr. Croft told me yesterday he heard \ul you\ulnone  were to be Solicitor.\'a0 If you think you \ul would\ulnone  be \ul elected\ulnone , I would like you to be a Candidate.\'a0 The Legislature you have served so \ul well\ulnone , \ul ought\ulnone  to give you any office you ask for.\'a0 But I will not give you any advice on the subject, but leave you to act as you think best.\'a0As you will be uneasy about home, the \ul next\ulnone  time you leave, I will write \ul every\ulnone  Mail.\'a0 I will do anything to \ul satisfy\ulnone  you, to make you \ul happy\ulnone  & \ul easy\ulnone  & \ul willing\ulnone  to \ul stay\ulnone  from home.\'a0 If you like to hear from me you must remain a long time absent, that you may receive a great many letters.\'a0 It almost \ul provokes\ulnone  me that as soon as you leave home you should be thinking of \ul returning\ulnone , & \ul particularly\ulnone  when \ul returning \ulnone would be \ul detrimental\ulnone  to your \ul interest\ulnone .\'a0 I am really shocked at your childishness.\'a0 Why surely you would not run for Solicitor, & then come home before the election is decided, & give such an advantage to your opponents.\'a0 I hope your \ul good\ulnone  \ul judgment \ulnone will not allow you to act so foolishly.\'a0 If you \ul do\ulnone , your influence over me is \ul gone\ulnone , for I do not think of being guided by one who will act so strangely as \ul that\ulnone .\'a0 I will have no further confidence in your understanding.\'a0 I make home \ul too\ulnone  \ul pleasant\ulnone  for you.\'a0 I intend now to \ul grumble\ulnone  & \ul scold\ulnone  & \ul complain\ulnone , & make you so \ul unhappy\ulnone , that you will be \ul glad\ulnone  to get away, & \ul dread\ulnone  returning.\'a0 I regard your \ul interest\ulnone \'a0 so much, that if your writing to me, interfered in any way with your business I would not wish you to write, though I derive so much pleasure from your letters.\'a0 I am writing today merely to keep you \ul quiet\ulnone , for I write with the \ul greatest\ulnone  \ul inconvenience \ulnone to myself.\'a0 It is \ul washing\ulnone  day, so that \ul Lindy\ulnone  is Frank\'92s nurse, & of \ul course\ulnone  he is fretting, & I have to stop every now & then to quiet him, & also to interfere with Willy & Anna who are now quarreling on the floor.\'a0 If you are in Columbia Wednesday night & do not hear from I am afraid Thursday morning you would start home, even if you were in the \ul midst\ulnone  of an \ul important\ulnone  case, or the election for Solicitor had not come on.\'a0 For the sake of your \ul clients\ulnone , I must keep your mind easy, to enable you to do justice to their cases,\'a0 Perhaps the constant uneasiness you have been in, from hearing from home \ul only\ulnone  every \ul other\ulnone  Mail has been the cause of your losing so many cases. I am glad the Rail road stock has fallen, otherwise I might be disposed to \ul murmur\ulnone  at your selling your shares for so little.\'a0 You will now \ul just\ulnone  be able to pay your debts & feel \ul free\ulnone  again.\'a0 Aunt Eliza in her last letter to Mamma said, Mr. Hayne was not unmindful of her letter on the subject of giving \ul you\ulnone  \ul my\ulnone  portion of my Fathers estate, that he thought Mamma was \ul able\ulnone  to do it & much approved her intention; that her income is at this time \ul better\ulnone  by 200 dollars than it was some \ul years\ulnone  \ul ago\ulnone .\'a0 This resulted from the increased value of \ul Bank\ulnone  \ul Stock\ulnone , in some investments he made for her by your advice.\'a0 That Mr. Hayne will write soon a \ul full\ulnone  \ul statement\ulnone  of my claim upon my Father\'92s estate, & of Mamma\'92s affairs in general.\'a0 If I do get my portion how delighted I will be, for it will be something to depend on against a \ul rainy\ulnone  \ul day\ulnone , & you can improve it for the children. I went to see Ann yesterday after church.\'a0 She was seated, or rather \ul laying\ulnone  \ul down\ulnone  in her chair which she likes as much, as suffering as she does, she can like anything.\'a0 It supersedes the necessity of Ann being held, & is a great relief to Mamma & Susan.\'a0 It is a noble chair, well worth 20 dollars.\'a0 Ann liked the oranges & Pine Apple \ul very\ulnone  \ul much\ulnone , & said I must thank you for them.\'a0 We \ul all\ulnone  enjoyed them.\'a0 It was fortunate I wrote you that Ann had a chair.\'a0 If you had bought the other, you would have been obliged to have kept it for yourself. I have written a long letter to Pamela.\'a0 Mrs. Croft has heard lately from her, & she is \ul better\ulnone .\'a0 I wish you would pass a night with them on your return, & comfort them about John.\'a0 I wrote her you thought you would gain his case.\'a0 It would be very unfortunate for Mr. Yancey to be put in Jail when his wife is sick.\'a0 If all challenges were followed by such consequences, duelling would be put a stop to.\'a0 Yesterday was a beautiful day.\'a0 I went to church morning & afternoon.\'a0 Mr. Pinckney looks quite well & \ul rather\ulnone  fatter.\'a0 Old Mr. Pinckney & his wife & youngest daughter left for the lower country today. \'a0Mr. Pinckney inquired after you & offered to take \ul any\ulnone  \ul commands\ulnone  to you.\'a0 I would have written by him but feared he would be a long time on the road.\'a0 As he was so polite, if you see him in Columbia you must speak to him.\'a0 This morning the sun shone, but now it is raining hard, & Minerva & Delia are at the spring washing.\'a0 You could not have had worse weather than we have had.\'a0 I bought Saturday some delightful apples from your client Mr. Sherman.\'a0 He gave me the history of them the\'85he brought from New England & grafted.\'a0 His manners were like Mr. Burts, when he said he was well acquainted with you, which caused me to ask his name.\'a0 I thought he would say \ul Burt\ulnone .\'a0 He says they will keep all winter, until apple trees bloom. Aunt Eliza wrote about Fanny\'92s wedding.\'a0 She says she could \ul pronounce\ulnone  Capt. Beall an \ul estimable\ulnone  man from his \ul countenance\ulnone  & \ul deportment\ulnone , which is \ul marked\ulnone  by \ul modest\ulnone  \ul simplicity\ulnone  which seldom[page torn] to a trifling character.\'a0 He is certainly \ul well\ulnone  \ul looking\ulnone  & \ul prepossessing\ulnone , \ul modest\ulnone  & \ul manly\ulnone  in address &[page torn] & quite disposed to regard them in a friendly manner.\'a0 Uncle Arthur thinks very highly of him, but feels \ul much\ulnone  in parting with Fanny to such a \ul destiny\ulnone .\'a0 They are to pass this winter in \ul Washington \ulnone but his \ul station\ulnone  is \ul Louisiana\ulnone .\'a0 He has no \ul resource\ulnone  but his \ul profession\ulnone .\'a0 Fanny only won the \ul consent\ulnone  of her Father, though he very highly estimates Capt. Beall. Aunt Eliza says she heard I was going to town with my little ones; that she thinks it \ul very \ulnone desirable I should & truly \ul wishes\ulnone  she could \ul lead\ulnone  the \ul way\ulnone  in urging it as a visit to \ul herself\ulnone  but that Mamma knows her \ul situation\ulnone  which \ul hampers\ulnone  her wishes on subjects of this kind.\'a0 She thinks it greatly to be desired that I should make my children known to their friends, that \ul intercourse\ulnone  fosters \ul affection\ulnone .\'a0 Aunt Martha McCall she says expressed a \ul great\ulnone  \ul desire\ulnone  to see the children, & Aunt Anna Turnbull said she \ul wished\ulnone  I would come.\'a0 Aunt Martha often refers to their \ul broken\ulnone  \ul up\ulnone  condition as a \ul family\ulnone .\'a0 Aunt Eliza says she often thinks how much the sight of Mamma & hers would gratify all of her friends. Aunt Eliza says Mr. Rhett died a \ul Christian\ulnone , & that this was not the result of a \ul death\ulnone  \ul bed \ulnone repentance, for the last two years he had been very serious, & would have made an open profession of religion had Mr. Barnwell encouraged him to do so.\'a0 His illness was short but he was very sensible of his approaching end & perfectly calm & resigned.\'a0 He said to his brother Barnwell, \'93What \ul now\ulnone  is \ul ambition\ulnone ? & lamented that his life had been passed in pursuits which belong to this \ul world\ulnone  \ul only\ulnone .\'a0 His brother Edmund arrived after his death & clung to the \ul mournful\ulnone  \ul relics\ulnone  in the bitterness of grief, but thanked God that his brother died a Christian.\'a0 Mrs. Rhett is with her Mother.\'a0 She is resigned & submissive tho she can only lift her \ul hands & weep\ulnone . Only two letters have come for you, the one from Mr. Fabers agent & one last night from Wesley Robertson, & no one has enquired for you but Mr. Sherman, who said he would get some counsel from you on your return.\'a0 So you see you lose nothing by being absent.\'a0 As you have spent $900 this year in servants, we will visit town if nothing happens next \ul Spring\ulnone  \ul twelve\ulnone  \ul months\ulnone .\'a0 I must \ul see\ulnone  your Gold pen before I can judge if it was a wise purchase.\'a0 You will get tired of it before the half of fifty years, & I rather think it will not be a good pen then the fifth of that time.\'a0 I have just received a note from Susan.\'a0 She says Ann \ul appreciates\ulnone  your kindness in thinking of the chair for her.\'a0 If you see a pretty prayer book for about $1.25 bring it to me to give to Ann or if you chose you can give it as \ul your\ulnone  \ul present\ulnone .\'a0 I hope this letter will find you in Columbia.\'a0 Do not hurry home.\'a0 The longer you stay the more glad we will be to see you.\'a0 Do you think you will get Willy a horse or not?\'a0 Truly yours, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
