My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 You see I have \ul broken\ulnone  my promise, (not to write to you).\'a0 I am afraid you will be \ul very\ulnone  \ul angry\ulnone  as \ul you\ulnone  think, the mind \ul once\ulnone  made up, \ul right\ulnone  or \ul wrong\ulnone , it must \ul never\ulnone  be changed.\'a0 I \ul hope\ulnone  you will forgive me this \ul once\ulnone .\'a0 I\'92ll try & not offend \ul again\ulnone .\'a0 It is \ul charity\ulnone  to you that induces me to write, for I know how much at a loss you must feel now, having been \ul three\ulnone  days without receiving any \ul advice\ulnone .\'a0 I must write a \ul book\ulnone  for \ul your\ulnone  \ul especial\ulnone  benefit, containing advice on \ul every\ulnone  subject, which you can \ul constantly\ulnone  apply to when \ul absent\ulnone  from \ul me\ulnone .\'a0 I think perhaps it is the \ul want\ulnone  of this that has made you pursue such an \ul inconsistent\ulnone  course, partly a Union man, partly a Nullifier, partly a Whig, & partly a Democrat.\'a0 You think a \ul little\ulnone  with \ul each\ulnone  party, & belong to \ul no\ulnone  party whatever, & no party \ul owns\ulnone  you, or \ul supports\ulnone  you.\'a0 This is owing to your making up your mind on different subjects when away from \ul me\ulnone ,\'a0 After consulting \ul me\ulnone , you find you are \ul wrong\ulnone , but having \ul made\ulnone  up your \ul mind\ulnone , you can\'92t \ul change\ulnone  it, & therefore pursue a course which you know is \ul against\ulnone  \ul your\ulnone  \ul interest\ulnone , & \ul perfectly\ulnone  calculated to advance the interest of \ul others\ulnone .\'a0 However advice is to \ul end\ulnone  my letter not \ul commence \ulnone it, so I will now tell you all the incidents that have occurred since you left, & as what is \ul last\ulnone  said produces the \ul greatest\ulnone  impression, \ul close\ulnone  with the \ul advice\ulnone . When you requested me to write the \ul same\ulnone  day you left, I told you I would have \ul nothing\ulnone  to write about.\'a0 I \ul might\ulnone  have had something very \ul serious\ulnone , for you had been scarce gone \ul ten\ulnone  \ul minutes\ulnone  when the Market bell rung, & there was a cry of \ul fire\ulnone .\'a0 \ul Nothing\ulnone  alarms me so much \ul except\ulnone  an \ul election\ulnone  in which \ul you\ulnone  are concerned, as the cry of \ul fire\ulnone .\'a0 Everybody seemed rushing round \ul our\ulnone  \ul corner\ulnone , so I knew it was near \ul us\ulnone .\'a0 It was Mr. Murphy\'92s house.\'a0 A spark from the chimney set the roof on fire; fortunately it was put out \ul immediately\ulnone  (long before the Engine arrived), or there might have been an extensive conflagration for the wind was blowing high at the time in the direction of the village & everything as dry as tinder. As soon as the alarm of fire was over, I dressed & walked to see Mrs. Faber.\'a0 I thought she would \ul expect\ulnone  it.\'a0 Miss Lynah & herself were very glad to see me.\'a0 They said I looked \ul well\ulnone , & not like the Mother of \ul three\ulnone  children.\'a0 Of course to seem \ul still\ulnone  \ul younger\ulnone , I told them that I had had \ul four\ulnone .\'a0 Mrs. Faber said \ul you\ulnone  looked \ul quite\ulnone  \ul well\ulnone .\'a0 Miss Lynah will stay with her Aunt at Flat Rock until her Father\'92s family come up & then return here & pass the summer at Pattons.\'a0 Mrs. Faber has not \ul hired\ulnone  her house.\'a0 Mr. Lowndes changed his mind.\'a0 The afternoon I spent at home & sent Willy & Anna to Mamma.\'a0 They were very glad to see them; said they \ul looked\ulnone  & \ul behaved\ulnone  \ul sweetly\ulnone , assisted in fanning \ul Ann\ulnone , & Willy has commenced planting a little garden under the drawing room window, which every day he wishes to go to water.\'a0 Just before supper Mr. Barclay came to see me & spent the evening.\'a0 He told me Mr. B\'85 had sent for him to sketch his child, & as soon as he returns he is to paint what he sketched, so I am glad he has \ul another\ulnone  engagement.\'a0 He went Saturday on Plough boy.\'a0 A letter came for you Friday night from Mr. Leitner, though it must have been in the office \ul before\ulnone  you left.\'a0 On the back was the request, that if you had left, it might be \ul sent\ulnone  to you.\'a0 I sent it to Col. Townes.\'a0 He said it was too late \ul that\ulnone  night to put it in the Mail. But he would the next \ul day\ulnone .\'a0 A Hamburgh Journal also came, sent I suppose by Mr. Yancey, as it announces him as a candidate for the Legislature.\
\'a0\

\f1\b 37 \
Saturday morning
\f0\b0  \
	\
	I staid at home & worked in the afternoon.\'a0 I carried my jewelry to Mr. Pickerel, & went to see Mrs. Markley, Mrs. Elford & Mrs. Town[e]s.\'a0 At night I went early to bed.\'a0 Sunday morning Willy & myself went to church & heard a missionary sermon.\'a0 Miss Stuart & two of the children sat in the pew.\'a0 I would not be surprised if they had taken possession for the summer.\'a0 In the afternoon, I went with \ul all\ulnone  of the children to Mamma\'92s.\'a0 She was very glad to see us; Ann just the same.\'a0 They inquired after you.\'a0 We walked in the garden, & Mamma waked with me to the gate.\'a0 We got home just at dark.\'a0 After supper I told some Bible stories to Willy & then went to bed.\'a0 In the night it thundered and the wind blew.\'a0 I predicted a storm, but it passed over in a few minutes, & no rain yet. This morning just after breakfast, I went over to Mr. Watson to pay my respects to your \ul second\ulnone  \ul self\ulnone .\'a0 It is indeed an \ul admirable\ulnone  portrait.\'a0 If I only looked my \ul best\ulnone , I might be \ul persuaded\ulnone , to have \ul mine\ulnone  taken.\'a0 Butler Thompson came in to look at it.\'a0 He said it was the best Portrait he ever saw in his life.\'a0 It was \ul precisely\ulnone  you, \ul except\ulnone  a little \ul younger\ulnone .\'a0 Mr. Wells was looking at it.\'a0 His only objection was the \ul shadow\ulnone  of the \ul spectacles\ulnone , Which Mr. Watson says is the most \ul ridiculous\ulnone  criticism on a picture he has ever heard, & though he does not wish Mr. Wells to \ul have\ulnone  it, shows he is too ignorant on the subject to be a competent judge.\'a0 The picture looks so much better at a \ul distance\ulnone , than \ul near\ulnone .\'a0 When I \ul first\ulnone  went in the store, it was \ul directly\ulnone  behind the counter, I was hardly more pleased with it than I was in Mr. Barclay\'92s room.\'a0 I begged Mr. Watson to put it at the \ul end\ulnone  of his store, & at that \ul distance \ulnone & in the \ul shade\ulnone , I was \ul delighted\ulnone  with it.\'a0 I imagined you \ul standing\ulnone  in the store, & was surprised you did not \ul speak\ulnone  to me.\'a0 You must get a \ul very\ulnone  \ul handsome\ulnone  frame for it.\'a0 If you cannot get one in \ul Charleston\ulnone , send to the \ul North\ulnone .\'a0 That picture will remain in the family \ul always\ulnone , generation after generation,, perhaps \ul hundreds\ulnone  of years, & sure to show to your posterity, how the \ul founder\ulnone  of their family looked.\'a0 Do my dear husband render your name so \ul distinguished\ulnone  that it will be regarded with \ul pride\ulnone , by all your descendants.\'a0 Don\'92t let them say \'93My Grandfather was beaten by Dr. Sullivan.\'94 Mrs. Marion\'85lingers, but I believe she is very low.\'a0 I have no news at all to write about.\'a0 I heard Miss McBee was going to the North with Mrs. Dr. Butler, but I hardly believe that; I do not believe she would leave the Dt. to electioneer alone.\'a0 I heard Miss McLeod was engaged to Mr. Mood, but I do not believe that either.\'a0 I see in the paper the death of cousin Edward Finley who you recollect as a member of the Legislature.\'a0 Aunt Finley of our \ul five\ulnone  grown children has \ul one\ulnone  left. I have so much work to do, that I will not be able to write you again.\'a0 It takes up too much time.\'a0 I will now mention my commissions.\'a0 Do not forget to buy for Willy a \ul Leghorn\ulnone  \ul hat\ulnone  with a \ul wide\ulnone  \ul rime\ulnone .\'a0 Measure the \ul crown\ulnone  by the \ul string\ulnone  I gave you.\'a0 For Frank buy a \ul common\ulnone  \ul straw\ulnone \'85not costing more than 25 cts.\'a0 For Susan & Ann I would like you to bring a little \ul trifle\ulnone , not costing more than 50 cts.at the \ul utmost\ulnone .\'a0 The pincushions you brought them last winter 3 1/4 cts a peice showed them yesterday to me on the \ul Mantle\ulnone  \ul peice\ulnone , & seemed to value them \ul greatly\ulnone .\'a0 Any little \ul trifle\ulnone  would do, such for instance as those little glass figurines you brought me once.\'a0 It is merely to show that you have \ul thought\ulnone  of them.\'a0 Ann says she does not care for any \ul oranges\ulnone ,\ul  \ulnone but I think you had better bring her a \ul few\ulnone . And now my dear for the \ul advice\ulnone , which I know you are \ul anxiously\ulnone  expecting.\'a0 I do hope you are for \ul annexation\ulnone .\'a0 If you are not my misery will be \ul complete\ulnone , for \ul now\ulnone  I \ul doubt\ulnone  if you will be elected, \ul then\ulnone  I am \ul certain\ulnone  you will not be, for it seems \ul treason\ulnone  in a \ul southerner\ulnone  to be \ul against\ulnone  Texas. Unless he is a \ul Whig\ulnone , & \ul nobody\ulnone  will vote for you.\'a0 Dont be so foolish as to do everything to \ul injure\ulnone  \ul yourself\ulnone , & \ul benefit\ulnone  your \ul opponent\ulnone .\'a0 You \ul wont\ulnone  \ul electioneer\ulnone , when you know it is so particularly important for \ul you\ulnone , who have so \ul many\ulnone  things against you, & so many \ul persons\ulnone  doing all they \ul can\ulnone  against you.\'a0 I believe you \ul want\ulnone  to be defeated, though you know how \ul mortified\ulnone  I will be.\'a0 I am \ul certain\ulnone  that if you were to take an \ul interest\ulnone  in the matter & do \ul all\ulnone  you \ul could\ulnone  to \ul ensure\ulnone  \ul success\ulnone , you \ul would\ulnone  \ul be\ulnone  successful, but instead of that, you take \ul no\ulnone  \ul interest\ulnone  in the matter, & do \ul all\ulnone  you can to be defeated.\'a0 Your conduct \ul certainly\ulnone  indicates that, & I don\'92t know \ul why\ulnone  you are a Candidate, unless it is to be\'a0 the \ul death\ulnone  of \ul me\ulnone , for \ul uneasiness\ulnone  of \ul mind\ulnone  is \ul wearing\ulnone  out my \ul body\ulnone , & I cant \ul endure\ulnone  it \ul much\ulnone  \ul longer\ulnone .\'a0 All of the Candidates wives feel easy except \ul myself\ulnone , for they know\'a0 their husbands will \ul exert\ulnone  themselves to be elected, but I who am sensitive, know that my husband who has so many enemies working against him, will leave his election to \ul chance\ulnone , & \ul chance\ulnone  never elected anyone to the \ul Legislature\ulnone .\'a0 I have read the arguments for & against Texas & \ul I\ulnone  am for Texas, & you may as well be \ul apparently\ulnone  \ul for\ulnone  it, if in \ul reality\ulnone  you are against it, for I do not believe it will be admitted into the Union.\'a0 You must make haste & come back to electioneer.\'a0 In the meantime \ul all\ulnone  I can do for you.\'a0 Write me. If you are defeated I will tear up your picture.\'a0 Your descendants shant see it.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
