\'85.me by your inertness, laziness, obstinacy &c.\'a0 I do not intend to write to you again unless I have something very important to write about.\'a0 I will now tell you news that I know will \ul shock\ulnone  & \ul grieve\ulnone  you.\'a0 Judge [Baylis John] Earle is \ul dead\ulnone .\'a0 He died this morning.\'a0 He returned to Greenville a few days ago looking very badly, though his friends told him he looked \ul better\ulnone , as it \ul pleased\ulnone  him.\'a0 Yesterday after dinner, he went into Mrs. Colemans room to chat.\'a0 Suddenly he said his tongue felt thick, he could not speak well, & he would go in the drawing room & laid down, he got up to walk.\'a0 When he was taken insensible, he was laid on Mrs. Colemans bed & continued so until this morning when he died.\'a0 It was a fit I suppose.\'a0 He was perfectly unconscious. Just a few moments before he died, he was turned on his side.\'a0 When he was put again on his back. He opened his eyes for a moment & looked perfectly natural, but instantly a spasm convulsed his body & he died.\'a0 Mr. Sam Earle was sent for after he was taken sick & was the only one of his family with him.\'a0 Mr. Edward Earle had been here yesterday morning & left.\'a0 He was sent for & arrived 10 or 15 minutes after his brother had breathed his last.\'a0 Delia tells me she has just seem Mrs. Mays carri[a]ge come in from Pendleton.\'a0 After nursing her brother so long, she must regret not being with him at the last.\'a0 He is to be carried to Pendleton to be buried as soon as arrangements can be made.\'a0 He is now at the Mansion house.\'a0 There is to be\'a0 a meeting of the citizens this afternoon.\'a0 I suppose to[page torn]resolutions.\'a0 Da\'85[page torn]Judge Earle eat a plate of cherries which made him feel badly.\'a0 Yesterday he f[elt] better & eat a [hea]rty dinner.\'a0 Mr. Lester was at the door a few minutes ago.\'a0 He said Mr. Choice said when Judge Earle went to Florida (I do not know whether the last time or not) he left a \ul will\ulnone  with him, but it was not now in his possession, & he did not know whether it was destroyed or not, & Mr. Cloice said from an estimation they made not long ago his property was 60,000 dollars.\'a0 I had thought he was worth twice as much.\'a0 Mr. Edward Earle when he came this morning, Mr. Lester says, took on a great deal.\'a0 How I wish you had sent for those Busts when Judge Earle offered them to you, we would now have had them to remember him by.\'a0 Mrs. Marion was buried yesterday.\'a0 It was while her funeral was taking place, that it was reported Judge Earle was dying.\'a0 How strange another world must be.\'a0 I wonder if persons recognize each other.\'a0 What a mystery, and how gradually it is made known to all, one after another.\'a0 Judge Earle has often of course thought of what kind of existence he would enjoy after his soul separated from his body.\'a0 He was certain how it would be; well this morning the secret was revealed to him.\'a0 I hope it has been to him a happy change.\'a0 I will now change this sad subject for a happier one, at least to the parties concerned.\'a0 Mr. Elford & Miss Sloan are to be married next Thursday.\'a0 Mr. Barclay returned from Spartanburgh yesterday.\'a0 He brought you a gold pencil case from Mr. Seay.\'a0 The bill in NY mentions the Pencil case 14 dollars & cutting the Initials 3 dollars, 17 dollars altogether.\'a0 The initials are in German text, which I do not like as well as plain letters, as they are not so easily distinguished.\'a0 It is a beautiful pencil case very heavy.\'a0 I do not know the cost of them so cannot tell if it was dear.\'a0 I went with Susan one afternoon to look at your picture.\'a0 Both her & me think Mr. Barclay has not done you justice.\'a0 I do not think he has given you as noble a countenance as you deserve, & there is an unusual look about the mouth you have not, & we do not like.\'a0 Still it is very much like you & could be recognized anywhere.\'a0 You are a remarkable looking man, & so easily taken, that it would be hard not to take a likeness of you that would not be known, for your features are marked, but what I wished was your countenance & expression when you look most benevolent.\'a0 The mass of the people do not observe your countenance particularly & therefore do not miss in your picture & what I miss, as Susan says it certainly looks like you, but there is something in it that is \ul not\ulnone  you.\'a0 Justice has not been done you.\'a0 But the picture is so much like you, that someone standing at Mr. Watsons store, looked in & said \'93I thought Maj. Perry had gone to Columbia.\'a0 I am afraid for Mr. Barclay to take mine.\'a0 I know he would not succeed as well as he has with yours.\'a0 He could not have had a better subject than yourself.\'a0 I hope he may meet with success, for I am sorry for him, & he seems a worthy young man. These sheets of paper are not large enough for correspondence between husbands & wives, particularly when a husband acts so badly as to require half of the letter to be filled up with scolding.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

