\f1\b Wednesday morning, 27 November [1844]
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I am now to write my \ul second\ulnone  letter, before I have heard from you, & I write \ul without\ulnone  \ul delay\ulnone , because I am going to consult you\'a0 how I shall \ul act\ulnone , with regard to the letter \ul just\ulnone  received from Pamela.\'a0 I will now tell you what I was \ul afraid\ulnone  to mention, until I knew all had turned out \ul well\ulnone .\'a0 When I paid my visit to Mr. Yancey, Mr. Yancey said he would be obliged to \ul give\ulnone  \ul up\ulnone  going to see his Aunt, for he could procure no conveyance in the village.\'a0 I instantly offered your horse & buggy to him, & he accepted it with \ul great\ulnone  \ul pleasure\ulnone  & said Mr. McKay would go with him to bring it back.\'a0 After he had gone I was uneasy, lest the horse being skittish, some accident should happen, but Mr. McKay has just returned quite safely, & bringing me a most \ul grateful\ulnone  letter from Pamela, \ul thanking \ulnone me for enabling them to see Mr. Yancey, & giving me a most \ul pressing\ulnone  invitation to visit them.\'a0 She says I must go with the children & you must meet us there & \ul all\ulnone  partake of a Christmas dinner.\'a0 She says the first night I can go to Goldsmiths, & the second night reach their house.\'a0 She says I \ul must\ulnone  go, that I know they all love me\'a0 & consider me almost as a relation.\'a0 She says that she is not going to Columbia, that Mrs. Cunningham is prevented by sickness from going with her daughter.\'a0 You she says on your way up can stop at Laurens, & they will have a buggy there to meet you, or I you know send the carri[a]ge; or else you could get in the stage which passes through their plantation, & which meets the Greenville stage.\'a0 Pamela says she will not \ul hear\ulnone  of any \ul obstacles\ulnone  or \ul denials\ulnone ; & she knows \ul you\ulnone  will not object; says she regrets exceedingly you could not have stopped on your way down, but insists on your doing so on your return; says she will accept the offer of you as an escort, during one of the four winters you are certain of being in Columbia.\'a0 Now My dear husband what shall I do?\'a0 I would like to go \ul very\ulnone  \ul much\ulnone  & see no objection to it, & it would be so pleasant for you to meet me there & all return to Greenville together.\'a0 I would not go for two weeks at least, so that Jim could kill hogs before we went, & if you prefer it, Jim could return after carrying me to Mrs. Cunninghams, though I do not think that would be necessary.\'a0 I think it would be a pleasant way of passing the time during your absence, so you must write me immediately whether I shall go; for though so anxious to go myself; I will of course give up if \ul you\ulnone  object, but I rather think you will like me to go, & if I do go, I will arrange everything at home, so as to go on \ul well\ulnone  without me.\'a0 I will now drop this subject & tell of all that has occurred since I last wrote.\'a0 Sunday night a letter came from Mr. Bancroft, acknowledging the receipt of your check.\'a0 Monday I paid visits.\'a0 I went to see first Miss Pinckney, who I \ul always\ulnone  like & she gave me a p[ai]r of gloves for one of the children, which she had bought for Charley & were too small for him.\'a0 Mr. Pinckney says the Physicians have advised him to take 2 years rest; otherwise he will have Spinal complaint.\'a0 So I believe \ul certainly\ulnone  at the end of this year he will leave us, for which I am \ul very\ulnone  \ul sorry\ulnone , for I think a family like his, an acquisition to Greenville.\'a0 He says Mr. Sharpe was once in Greenville in Bevens store; then returned to Pendleton, & set up a \ul Confectioners\ulnone  shop, & afterwards entered into business with young Warley; that he has \ul no\ulnone  \ul education\ulnone , which you can perceive by \ul conversing\ulnone  with him; & that he is good looking, which I think must have caused Frances to have fancied him.\'a0 Mr. Croft was at Mr. Pinckney\'92s & asked me if I had seen the compliment paid you in the Charleston Courier, & then said to Mr. Pinckney, that you were now \ul Senator\ulnone , higher that you had ever been before, & elected by such a handsome majority.\'a0 I saw him (Mr. Croft) yesterday afternoon at Mamma\'92s & he said to me Well the Maj now is in all his glory, the next thing I expect to hear of him is, that he is President of the Senate.\'a0 I am thinking now, that I ought to have \ul advised\ulnone  you to appropriate that honour to yourself, & if you had signified your \ul wish\ulnone , perhaps you might have obtained it.\'a0 How delightful \ul that\ulnone  would be, to be a \ul Senators\ulnone  \ul wife\ulnone  is good, but Wife of \ul President\ulnone  of the \ul Senate\ulnone , \ul still\ulnone  \ul better\ulnone , & I am \ul sure\ulnone  if you had \ul tried\ulnone  for it, you \ul might\ulnone  have got it.\'a0 My next visit was to Mrs. Thompson.\'a0 I saw Genl Thompson for a moment.\'a0 He was about going for the \ul fourth\ulnone  time to Mr. Carsons to persuade him\'a0 to sell him his place.\'a0 Genl Thompsons miniature I do not think a good likeness, & Mrs. Thompsons can \ul never\ulnone  have looked like her.\'a0 Speaking of the Torchlight procession, Mrs. Thompson mentioned, that Butler, Mr. Holcombe, & some other gentlemen were standing by the Mansion house, & Butler said \'93how will this do?\'92 & Mr. Holcombe said, \'93very well for the occasion,\'94 & Mrs. Walker who was at one of the windows replied, \'93if we had our hands in the \ul public\ulnone  \ul treasury\ulnone  , we would do \ul better\ulnone ,\'94 meaning it of \ul course\ulnone  for \ul Genl\ulnone  \ul Thompson\ulnone .\'a0 Afterwards she went for Butler & apologized to \ul him\ulnone , saying if she had known \ul he\ulnone  was near, she would not have said what she did & she did not mean it for \ul him\ulnone , which made the matter \ul worse\ulnone 