Mr. Butlers election; he very kindly offered his services to me during your absence.\'a0 Mr. Bee stopped for a few moments yesterday on his way to Pendleton, & said he left you \ul well\ulnone .\'a0 The Pendleton stage had not come this evening before, & he was going in Genl Thompsons buggy.\'a0 He is so \ul kind\ulnone  \ul hearted\ulnone  & \ul affectionate\ulnone , & so is Col. Keith , who I knew would inquire after us,\'a0 & his wife is a sweet lady.\'a0 Mamma has received a letter from both Mr. & Mrs. Roper. Mrs. Coleman says the Shaefer family are connected with hers.\'a0 Genl Haynes \ul grandchildren\ulnone  will be connected with a good many families, who never dreamed of such an alliance.\'a0 If all his connections are as worthy & respectable as Mr. Elford & Mrs. Coleman, I will be glad.\'a0 Uncle Haynes death taking place at this time, has prevented our having an account of Mr. Sharpe from our friends.\'a0 I suppose they have not seen much of him , particularly about Aunt Eliza, whose opinion I would like to have heard.\'a0 She has such a good judgment.\'a0 Col. Bee says he is a fine young man.\'a0 I have just seen John.\'a0 He seemed pleased to hear of Thomas, says he was always a good boy.\'a0 I am quite well [and] so are the children.\'a0 Willy & Anna are remarkably well, & Frank begins to look better.\'a0 He is so affectionate.\'a0 He can say \ul Ma\ulnone , & is satisfied at night, if he is in my arms with his hand on my neck.\'a0 I must keep him as my bedfellow all winter.\'a0 Anna because she is in the bed with me, sleeps \ul soundly\ulnone  all night.\'a0 Willy will have to accommodate \ul you\ulnone  when you came back.\'a0 He says I must tell you he can read some stories without missing a \ul word\ulnone .\'a0 In their prayers, they beg that \ul Pa\ulnone  may come back \ul safe\ulnone \'a0 \ul home\ulnone ; sometimes Anna \ul forgets\ulnone  It & she comes back & says \'93I forgot to say , bring Pa safe home\'94, & then kneels down & says it.\'a0 Today Willy was pla\'85 her, & she said she was going to look for Pa\'92s horsewhip for me to whip him.\'a0 I think they are \ul all\ulnone  fine children, & if it were not for their playing so much with servants, I could easily manage them.\'a0 You must when you return have a fence made to separate the yards, so that the servants may play in one, & my children in the other.\'a0 So much associations with \ul servants\ulnone  only gives them \ul low\ulnone  \ul ideas\ulnone  & \ul habits\ulnone , which they will never be able to correct.\'a0 These early impressions are lasting, & having a small family & seeing no company, our children have not the advantage some others have. How disappointed Mr. Earle must be.\'a0 I am sorry for him, but he did not \ul need\ulnone  an office.\'a0 Mamma received a letter from Aunt Eliza Friday night, the \ul first\ulnone  she has received since Uncle Haynes death.\'a0 She says all of Mamma\'92s bonds are \ul separate\ulnone  in a little \ul tin\ulnone  \ul box\ulnone  made for the purpose last year, that Mr. Hayne seemed to think Mamma\'92s business very \ul simple\ulnone  to \ul manage\ulnone , & that \ul Alston\ulnone  \ul Hayne\ulnone , who has the \ul warm\ulnone  \ul heart\ulnone  & \ul noble\ulnone  \ul nature\ulnone  of his \ul father\ulnone , will do anything in the way of business for her, that [page torn] him in preference to her son Wm Ed[ward], who is a minor & has not a moment to spare.\'a0 She says Mamma must advise with \ul you\ulnone  & \ul you\ulnone  communicate with \ul Mr.\ulnone  \ul Martin\ulnone  in Columbia.\'a0 Mamma does not know anything that \ul she\ulnone  can do, & so leaves it to \ul you\ulnone , & if you find it not necessary\'a0 to go to town, you need not.\'a0 She mentions Uncle Haynes reason for going to Washington.\'a0 She says 2 years ago, Mr. Grayson the Collector, suggested to Mr. Hayne, that through the Southern delegation he should receive an appointment from the President in the Custom house; that Mr. Hayne would take no steps for the purpose, & therefore she herself wrote to Mr. Pickens who had always been a warm friend of the family, & to Mr. I[saac] E. Holmes, who had always been a particular friend of Uncle Wm & whose family she was intimate with.\'a0 Mr. Pickens made a personal application to the President, who said that the son of a Revolutionary Martyr, & the sister of one whose death had been a calamity to the common country, should \ul certainly\ulnone  be provided for, & that an office should be given him in the Custom house, but Uncle Hayne with his usual benevolence, was not so selfish as to deprive anyone of an office on his account, but thought a vacancy would soon occur as there were 3 \ul aged\ulnone  incumbents (one of them Uncle Perronneau).\'a0\'a0 In the simplicity of her heart, Aunt Eliza mentioned to Mr. Holmes the Presidents kindness.\'a0 She received a \ul glowing\ulnone  letter from him, promising to do \ul all\ulnone  he \ul could\ulnone  &c.\'a0 2 months ago, Mr. H\'85 died of Apoplexy, in the Custom house.\'a0 Mr. Hayne immediately walked round to Mr. Holmes, to know what measures to take & found he had gone to Washington.\'a0 The next day he heard for what purpose.\'a0 He was advised to go to Washington, & when he got there was overwhelmed with disappointment.\'a0 Mr. Tyler thought Mr. Hayne had been \ul provided\ulnone  \ul for\ulnone .\'a0 Mr. Holmes represented to him that his \ul brother\ulnone  had been deprived of office by Genl Jackson, & leaving it to be \ul understood\ulnone , that it was for \ul that\ulnone  brother he wished the office, when it was for another.\'a0 Mr. Holmes \ul knew\ulnone  Mr. Hayne was waiting to receive the \ul first\ulnone  \ul vacant\ulnone  \ul office\ulnone , & hurried on before even the letter announcing Mr. H\'85s death was written.\'a0 Mr. Barnwell as soon as he heard of the death of Mr. H\'85 rode over from Georgetown to Washington to ask the appointment for Mr. Hayne, but arrived 2 hours after it had been given to Mr. Holmes.\'a0 The excitement disappointment &c. brought on what followed.\'a0 So far from Mr. Hayne having \ul lost\ulnone  his \ul mind\ulnone  as Mr. Pinckney told you.\'a0 Aunt Eliza says during his \ul whole\ulnone  \ul sickness\ulnone , he was \ul sensible\ulnone , \ul resigned\ulnone  \ul affectionate\ulnone , & spoke of \ul us\ulnone  all, particularly Ann, & \ul returned\ulnone  the pressure of her hands \ul almost\ulnone  to the \ul last\ulnone .\'a0 Mr. Butler says Mr. Martin says he never witnessed such a death bed, that he was \ul perfectly\ulnone  \ul composed\ulnone , looked at his watch, & mentioned the hour when he would die, he \ul fainted\ulnone , & when he recovered, he regretted his time had not come.\'a0 He had a \ul good\ulnone  \ul conscience\ulnone  & could well die peacefully.\'a0 Aunt Eliza says they will continue housekeeping, at any rate this year. I tell you \ul again\ulnone , do not \ul think\ulnone  of \ul home\ulnone , be \ul sociable\ulnone  & \ul affable\ulnone , throw off your \ul reserved\ulnone  \ul familiarity\ulnone , & then you will be \ul happy\ulnone  in Columbia.\'a0 You must enjoy home when you have established a reputation for yourself, for while you are enjoying yourself at home, it will \ul add\ulnone  to the \ul enjoyment\ulnone  to think that your country thinks well of you.\'a0 You have the elements of greatness & must be a great man.\'a0 If your Wednesday night letter says you have no objection to my leaving home, I will go Thursday 12
