\f1\b Tuesday night, 10 December 1844
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Again do I write to you at night, because tomorrow I will not have a moment to spare.\'a0 I am now \ul prepared\ulnone  to go to Mrs. Cunninghams.\'a0 I know in tomorrow nights letter, you will express no unwillingness that I should go, & now I have gone so far, I do not think I can turn back.\'a0 I have written to Pamela, that she may expect me Friday evening, though not \ul certainly\ulnone .\'a0 I have purchased materials to work you a pair of shoes.\'a0 I have bought a beautiful pattern to work them by, so I will be able to work them now, whenever you wish them.\'a0 Jim yesterday killed the hogs, & today he has been setting them up & salting & making the Sausage meat.\'a0 Tomorrow he will stuff the Sausages.\'a0 He killed seven hogs, but one of the hogs does not seem good,\'a0 It has white round spots or pimples all over it.\'a0 Jim says you have some sous you can kill if you wish it.\'a0 Today & yesterday have been the \ul coldest\ulnone  days we have had.\'a0 Miss Earle is married tonight.\'a0 Susan & myself preferred not going to so large a party, so soon after Uncle Haynes death.\'a0 \ul Mrs.\ulnone  \ul Sam\ulnone  \ul Earle\ulnone  was not invited.\'a0 \ul Mr.\ulnone  \ul Earle\ulnone  & \ul Mrs.\ulnone  \ul Earles\ulnone  \ul sons\ulnone  have had some difference; & on that account she was not invited; \ul her\ulnone  \ul sisters\ulnone  \ul child\ulnone , what a quarrelsome family they seem to be.\'a0 Mr. Lester came to see me this afternoon, to mention that he had left you well.\'a0 Robert Foster paid me a visit the other day.\'a0 I thought he must have come to borrow something, perhaps your horse & buggy, but he only came to pay a visit.\'a0 He says he is going to move to Pickens.\'a0 He says his mother wrote word all were well at Toogaloo [Tougaloo],\'a0What do you think I did this morning?\'a0 Why I had my \ul tooth\ulnone  \ul drawn\ulnone ?\'a0 You know how long it has worried me, & last night I do not think I slept an hour; & \ul fortunately\ulnone  it continued to ache this morning.\'a0 I say \ul fortunately\ulnone , for it was only \ul excessive\ulnone  \ul pain\ulnone  that could have given me \ul courage\ulnone  to have it drawn.\'a0 I sent for Mr. Buice before breakfast, & after taking an hour to dress himself as neatly as possible, he came.\'a0 At first he \ul frightened\ulnone  me, by saying he must be \ul candid\ulnone , & tell me that it was a very bad tooth, & might break in pulling. But I must let him cut the gum \ul deep\ulnone , that he might get a good hold, & then he would try & draw it out safely.\'a0 I said if there was any danger in it I would wait until \ul you\ulnone  came back, but he said no.\'a0 If it did break, he would try & break it \ul low\ulnone  \ul down\ulnone , so that the gum would close over it, & when the air was excluded, it would no longer ache.\'a0 So I summoned up all my courage & sat down.\'a0 He then cut the gum low, & that he said I bore \ul well\ulnone .\'a0 He then drew the tooth, & I did not even make an \ul exclamation\ulnone .\'a0 He said I was the bravest soldier he had seen for a long time.\'a0 It gave me \ul great\ulnone  \ul pain\ulnone , but not as \ul much\ulnone  as \ul I expected\ulnone , & I am really \ul thankful\ulnone  it came out so \ul safely\ulnone .\'a0 I think Mr. Buice must draw teeth \ul well\ulnone .\'a0 He did not give a \ul sudden\ulnone  \ul pull\ulnone , as I thought he would, but he took a \ul firm\ulnone  \ul hold\ulnone , then seemed to \ul loosen\ulnone  the tooth,\'a0 & then \ul draw\ulnone  it out.\'a0 I feel \ul happy\ulnone  tonight.\'a0 I would not pass such \ul another\ulnone  \ul night\ulnone  as the \ul last\ulnone , on any \ul account\ulnone .\'a0 I have another tooth which Mr. Buice says ought to come out, & which I myself know ought to.\'a0 Some day I will summon up courage & have that out too.\'a0 It \ul has\ulnone  ached me dreadfully, but it does not now.\'a0 Such teeth Mr. Buice says\'a0 (& I believe all do) injure the stomach & cause Dyspepsia .\'a0 I have four which he says plugging will save & some that need scraping. I would not have the tooth that was drawn this morning back again, for a thousand dollars, indeed for no sum whatever. Mr. Pinckney came to see me yesterday afternoon.\'a0 Mrs. Coleman has been, Miss Crittenden & Miss Skinner, Miss Pinckney, Mrs. & Miss Jones & Mrs. Duncan, when I was from home.\'a0 We have had a good deal of warm, rainy weather.\'a0 Mamma has written to Aunt Eliza to say, her business may be put in the hands of Alston Hayne, & he must act for her, as for his Mother.\'a0 I do not think there will be any necessity for you to go to town.\'a0 Ann is still very poorly.\'a0 Susan & Mamma came in today.\'a0 They are very kind to me.\'a0 Mamma not long ago gave me $6.50 to buy a Mantle, & she has lately given me a Shawl 5 dollars & a tippet 2 dollars.\'a0 I would like you to bring Susan & Ann a present, something that will cost \ul very\ulnone  \ul little\ulnone , for it is not the \ul value\ulnone  of a present they care for, but the \ul remembrance\ulnone .\'a0 You are \ul wrong\ulnone  to think you must not make a present, unless you can make a valuable one.\'a0 I think the merest trifle from a \ul friend\ulnone  acceptable.\'a0 I would be vexed if you bought them \ul handsome\ulnone  presents, for that you \ul cannot\ulnone  \ul afford\ulnone , but a little trifle, ornament for the table, Mantle peice, or \ul anything\ulnone  that will cost \ul little\ulnone , will do, merely to show them you \ul thought\ulnone  of them. I saw Mr. Thomas Cox the other day.\'a0 He said he supposed you were gaining new Laurels in Columbia.\'a0 I have to remain \ul silent\ulnone  when I hear the Hoar case mentioned.\'a0 I hope you will be able to explain your conduct \ul satisfactorily\ulnone .\'a0 As I have no letter of yours to answer, I have less to write about, than I otherwise would have.\'a0 I never saw the village quieter.\'a0 I am glad you are in Columbia, with something important to occupy you.\'a0 I hope you will act your part well, & increase your reputation.\'a0 I wonder you complain of having \ul nothing\ulnone  to write me.\'a0 It seems to me, you might write a \ul good\ulnone  \ul deal\ulnone . The children are well.\'a0 They are all asleep upstairs.\'a0 The servants are doing well.\'a0 I have indeed \ul nothing\ulnone  to write about.\'a0 I will write you again on Thursday if \ul possible\ulnone  before I start.\'a0 There may be something in tomorrow nights Letter I may wish to answer.\'a0 I will write you as soon as I get to Mrs. Cunninghams, but as the Mails are irregular in that part of the country, you must not be uneasy.\'a0 I would like you to spend Christmas there.\'a0 Everybody seems to think it will be a pleasant trip for me.\'a0 I think the children will enjoy it, & it will improve them, & it will be so pleasant to come home again.\'a0 I was agreeably surprised that in your two last letters, you did not scold me, for expressing so much anxiety on the subject.\'a0 I opened them with \ul fear\ulnone  & \ul trembling\ulnone .\'a0 Your two sheet one, made me shed some tears, & lost me some sleep.\'a0 We will meet now in less than a fortnight, remain satisfied in Columbia, & do not \ul think\ulnone  of leaving until the Session is over.\'a0 When you return home you will be long enough there to get tired.\'a0 Joe Powell told Minerva one day at the kitchen window, that he had got a letter from you & you were quite well.\'a0 I hope you have had some friendly correspondence with him, such men it is better to be on good terms with.\'a0 They can injure you so much.\'a0 It was wrong in you at the first to make him your enemy, but I forget, I will not give you advice.\'a0 M\'85 Mauldin today brought Anna a little basket, & Oscar [Mauldin] brought Willy & Frank a tumbler.\'a0 Ever Yours, Liz\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\'a0\'a0\
