\f1\b 55
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Friday morning, 24 January 1845
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received your letter Wednesday night & was \ul delighted\ulnone  to hear from you.\'a0 Your account of Willie was \ul very\ulnone  \ul interesting\ulnone , & pleased me \ul extremely\ulnone .\'a0 I \ul laughed\ulnone  at his \ul sayings\ulnone .\'a0 I was so anxious to hear how he was doing, & am \ul gratified\ulnone  he has behaved so well.\'a0 Susan & Mamma say they have always thought him an uncommon child in every respect.\'a0 I hope tonight to hear again.\'a0 I wish to know how Willie behaves in the \ul city\ulnone , & what his \ul friends\ulnone  think of him.\'a0 I am afraid you have bad weather.\'a0 It rained here yesterday afternoon, & all last night.\'a0 It is not raining now, but is very cloudy, & I suppose will rain again.\'a0 I have just been reading the Mountaineer.\'a0 Gov.Briggs message about the Hoar case is published, & Mr. Wells speaks very indignantly of the Abolitionists as interfering with us first in [one] way, then in another.\'a0 As you did not disapprove of Mr. Hoars mission, it does seem as if you side with the abolitionists, & indeed my dear husband I do think your judgement there was wrong, & I will always regret the part you took.\'a0 I think the Legislature was right in the course it took.\'a0 It was an uncommon case, & called for uncommon action.\'a0 If Mr. Hoar had been allowed quietly to remain, the Northerners would have been encouraged to go further.\'a0 On this account, it was right to send him away.\'a0 I am not satisfied with the peice you have written.\'a0 I do not think it vindicates your course.\'a0 To have avoided the appearance of evil, you should have acted differently.\'a0 I am afraid you will see trouble on account of it yet.\'a0 Your enemies can take hold of it against you.\'a0 However as you got yourself into trouble, I hope you will be able to get out without my help. I yesterday wrote to Pamela, & mentioned you would execute the commission for her.\'a0 I suppose she wrote directions, how the dress was to be dyed.\'a0 If you return by Augusta, in passing through Abbeville, you could send the dress to John Cunningham, who would send it to her, or if you return by Columbia, you can leave it at Laurens for her, but perhaps she has told you how to get it to her. A letter received by the last Mail from Mr. Bailey, making inquiries when you would be in town, & very anxious you should go down, or get someone to attend to the case for you.\'a0 A letter also came from Mr. Elijah Webb thanking you for your able speech on the Presidential Election, says it breathes a true republican spirit, that he believes the people will do right if left to themselves, that the election which has just come off is a fair illustration of it, that if his election had been control[l]ed by the dominant party of the state, & a few aristocrats about Anderson & Pendleton, he would have been turned out of office after all the pains he had taken to make the people a faithful public officer.\'a0 He hopes your speech will find its way to every house in S. Carolina.\'a0 The letter you received from Mr. Gantt the night you left, I hope you have answered, as he seemed so anxious to have his difficulty solved immediately.\'a0 A Museum has arrived.\'a0 Another year I would like to take the \ul Lady\'92s\ulnone  \ul book\ulnone .\'a0 It has such beautiful pictures in it.\'a0 Mrs. Coleman has stopped taking it, so now I have no chance of seeing the pictures. I have not been out since you left.\'a0 The walking is very bad.\'a0 Susan has been in to see me.\'a0 Miss Goodlett & Miss Long have paid me a visit, & Miss Williford & Miss Service.\'a0 Mrs. Pemble lives only a few steps from the Charleston Hotel, in Hasell st, so you must carry Willie to see her, if only for a few minutes.\'a0 They would be pleased if you did.\'a0 Miss Margaret said you must.\'a0 Uncle Joseph lives so \ul out\ulnone  of \ul society\ulnone , that I am certain he will not call to see you, but through Aunt Anna Turnbull, Willie could see him.\'a0 Aunt Anna would carry Willie, or invite uncle Joseph to her house.\'a0 Though he has \ul thrown\ulnone  \ul himself\ulnone  \ul away\ulnone , he has \ul strong\ulnone  \ul feelings\ulnone , & would be gratified to see his little nephew. There are some things I am afraid you will forget, so will remind you again.\'a0 One is to inquire the prices of \ul carri[a]ges\ulnone  for Mamma, & put the prices on \ul paper\ulnone , so you will not forget.\'a0 I am under the impression that carri[a]ges are much cheaper in town, & handsomer than in Greenville, & there of course they have the \ul latest\ulnone  \ul fashions\ulnone .\'a0 Mr. Cox I think is exorbitant, & after all our carri[a]ge was not made so well, for it is now at the shop repairing.\'a0 Jim says the springs at first were too slender.\'a0 I am satisfied with our carri[a]ge, but I am willing Mamma should get a better bargain.\'a0 You must price different ones.\'a0 Another \ul important\ulnone  thing you must not forget is to look for a place for Minerva.\'a0 Mrs. Thompson & Coleman, had women with Mrs. Lee or Johnson, the latter I believe keeps Jones.\'a0 Lee it is said keeps the best table in town, so that would be a good place for Minerva to learn cooking.\'a0 I never could spare Minerva better than now.\'a0 Her children are old enough to do without her.\'a0 Delia can sleep in the room & take care of them.\'a0 She can wash & iron, & Eliza cook.\'a0 The terms are, that for the servants \ul services\ulnone , she is taught to cook.\'a0 Minerva is capable of being a good cook, if she was only taught.\'a0 A mistress can read the \ul receipts\ulnone  for making things, but cannot direct the baking, boiling, mixing &c which is the most important part.\'a0 Minerva could go down as soon as you return, & come back in the Spring.\'a0 The expense incurred would be well repaid by having a good cook. I have been planting orange seed.\'a0 I have planted a row on each side of the walk from the steps to the gate, & am not planting all round the fence.\'a0 James & Delia are doing it, directed by me.\'a0 Whenever I commence such improvements I am discouraged, from the difficulty I find in getting what I wish done.\'a0 Jim will \ul commence\ulnone , & suddenly when my back is turned, go off, & I can[not] get him again.\'a0 Then I call James, & while I am attending to something else he will disappear, & lastly I give up in despair.\'a0 \ul You\ulnone  will have to improve your \ul lot\ulnone , & I attend to the \ul house\ulnone .\'a0 I am anxious to have some orange trees, that I hope you will persevere, if I am obliged to give up.\'a0 Jim has been working at the farm.\'a0 It is only before he gets his breakfast, I ask him to help me.\'a0 I have been told the lower country orange seed, take better than the upper.\'a0 If you were to be in the way of getting any, now you are in town, you must bring me some.\'a0 You must buy some Mango seeds, which makes such nice Pickles. I have \ul no\ulnone  \ul news\ulnone  to tell you.\'a0 We are all well, at Mamma\'92s the same as when you left.\'a0 Corn has been brought several times.\'a0 I hope to hear tonight from you.\'a0 Tell Willie he must behave so well, that his friends will love him, & then he can go & see them again.\'a0 I may write to you once more, if you remain as long as you expected, but if you do not hear you may not be uneasy.\'a0 Kiss Willie for me, & tell him I long to see him.\'a0 Remember me to my friends, Lizzy\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Charleston\
\'a0\

\f1\b 56
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Monday morning, 27 January 1845
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I was so disappointed at not hearing from you last night.\'a0 I could hardly believe James, when he told me he had no letter.\'a0 However the disappointment was made up, by reading one from Aunt Eliza, Mamma received last night.\'a0 I was \ul perfectly\ulnone  \ul delighted\ulnone  at her account of Will.\'a0 She seems \ul enraptured\ulnone  with him.\'a0 She says \'93had not thought to \ul know \ulnone such \ul pure & lively\ulnone  joy again on Earth as she felt at the sight of him\'94, that he is indeed a \ul lovely\ulnone  boy, that Sue has carried him to see some of his friends, & \ul all\ulnone  received him most \ul affectionately\ulnone , that Aunt Brewton was \ul touched \ulnone even at the sight of him.\'a0 I suppose it recalled to her mind his Baptism, the last Sunday she was ever at church with Uncle Robert.\'a0 Sue says Aunt Anna & Martha were \ul overjoyed\ulnone .\'a0 She did not \ul know\ulnone  they would be so \ul glad\ulnone .\'a0 Mrs. Irvine Keith\'a0 met him, & was delighted to see him, & wanted to claim him too.\'a0 Mrs. Deas a friend of Mamma\'92s called to see Aunt Eliza; and when she told him Willie had been to deliver letters of \ul introduction\ulnone , she said. \'93\ul nature\ulnone  had furnished him with the \ul best\ulnone  in his \ul countenance\ulnone .[\'93]\'a0 Aunt Eliza says Sue\'a0 is perfectly happy playing with Willie.\'a0 She really seems to \ul love\ulnone  him, & I cannot tell you how \ul much\ulnone  \ul gratified \ulnone I am at his reception.\'a0 Aunt Eliza begs, that I will let him stay with her, until I make my visit in the Spring, that he will then have time to \ul know \ulnone & be \ul known \ulnone to his friends, & it would be quite a \ul charity \ulnone to \ul her\ulnone .\'a0 My dear husband, I would have \ul no\ulnone  \ul objection\ulnone  to let Willie remain.\'a0 Though I miss him \ul sadly\ulnone , I am willing to part with him for the sake of the benefit he would derive, from intercourse with his friends.\'a0 It may improve his character, his disposition, his manners; the good impression made on him would be lasting & of benefit to him for Life.\'a0 In Greenville, he is always at \ul home\ulnone , associating with \ul servants\ulnone , & no \ul social \ulnone intercourse at all.\'a0 Aunt Eliza brings up children \ul so\ulnone  \ul well\ulnone , I would commit Willie to her care with \ul perfect confidence\ulnone .\'a0 However this is just as you think.\'a0 In the Spring if I do not go down, you can carry him again to see his friends, when you go to Columbia, but I hope I will be able to go in the Spring. Aunt Eliza says you were kind & friendly.\'a0 You must go & see her the night before you leave, thank her for her kindness to Willie, & tell her if she goes to Edgefield she must come & see us, & offer your services if ever you can be of use to her.\'a0 She says she would like Wm Ed[ward] her son to make your \ul acquaintance\ulnone  & secure an \ul interest \ulnone in your \ul feelings\ulnone .\'a0 She says she would \ul gladly \ulnone have invited \ul you\ulnone  to \ul stay \ulnone with her, but they were in daily expectation of Dr. & Mrs. Thomas.\'a0 Mr. Martin was with them, & I believe Judge Butler also.\'a0 I hope you have been to see \ul all \ulnone the \ul family \ulnone & been kind & \ul sociable \ulnone in your manners, & made a \ul good\ulnone  \ul impression \ulnone on them.\'a0 I am anxious they should think \ul well \ulnone of \ul my\ulnone  \ul husband\ulnone .\'a0 If I can I will write to Aunt Eliza by the same Mail that carries your letter, but I may not have time.\'a0 This is the \ul last \ulnone letter I will write you if you leave Friday the 31
\fs24\fsmilli12222 \super st
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \nosupersub  as you intended.\'a0 I have \ul nothing \ulnone to write about.\'a0 The children & myself are quite well.\'a0 Mamma has been unwell.\'a0 Ann is the same as when you left. Aunt Eliza said she wishes I could have seen Willie as he was feeding the pigeons, & \ul gazing \ulnone in astonishment at the Chimney sweeper who was performing his office, that the Canary bird & everything delighted him so that his sense of bashfulness gave way to wonder & pleasure, & that he sallied forth as trustingly with Sue, to deliver his letters of introduction, as if he had always lived with her.\'a0 She says she was not prepared to see so \ul lively \ulnone a child, but she is \ul rejoiced \ulnone at it, that his motions are \ul lively\ulnone  & \ul free\ulnone , \'93best befits the \ul mountain\ulnone  boy.\'94\'a0 Aunt Eliza says Willie \ul knew \ulnone them \ul all\ulnone , & he asked to see the room where I was \ul born\ulnone .\'a0 You recollect I told you to see the \ul house \ulnone where I was born.\'a0 He said he would stay with them \ul every\ulnone  \ul day\ulnone , but must \ul go \ulnone to \ul sleep\ulnone  with \ul you\ulnone .\'a0 The whole letter is about \ul Willie\ulnone , & the most \ul interesting\ulnone  I ever read. Aunt McCall\'92s thought at first Willie looked like his \ul Grandfather\ulnone  \ul McCall\ulnone , but after a time, said he resembled \ul both\ulnone  \ul parents\ulnone  & several\'85on each side.\'a0 I knew my friends would be \ul glad \ulnone to see him, but they have expressed \ul even\ulnone  \ul more \ulnone pleasure than I expected.\'a0 From Aunt Eliza\'92s account they seem to have the \ul sincerest\ulnone  \ul love \ulnone for him already.\'a0 She says each kind Aunt he went to see wished to \ul keep \ulnone him.\'a0 She could hardly get leave to bring him back, & Anna Turnbull thought she had quite an advantage over them, in the opportunity of being acquainted with him.\'a0 Willie made his \ul mark \ulnone in the letter for \ul me\ulnone .\'a0 Tell him it was made \ul beautifully\ulnone  & \ul delighted\ulnone  me.\'a0 Delia & Edward say I must tell him Howdys, & Anna\'92s toy he must not forget.\'a0 Anna tells everyone, he has gone to town to buy her a toy.\'a0 I do indeed long to see my darling boy, & hear tell all the wonders he has seen.\'a0 Today is \ul clearing\ulnone .\'a0 You have had much better weather than I anticipated you would have.\'a0 I suppose you will be back Sunday night, but I certainly expect to hear from you before you return.\'a0\'a0\'a0 You must not forget to buy the carpet.\'a0 The present one is not decent.\'a0 Susan begged me yesterday to tell you to inquire about the carri[a]ges.\'a0 Mr. Cox you know said he would not build them one for less than \ul 350 \ulnone dollars.\'a0 Mrs. Stone says Tom Butlers brother bought a handsome one for \ul 275 \ulnone & Col. Lynah\'92s Mrs. Coleman says was only \ul 245 \ulnone & Mrs. Tom Lowndes was \ul 245\ulnone .\'a0 Mr. Cox I dare say was \ul exaggerated \ulnone when he said Mr. Lowndes was \ul 375\ulnone .\'a0 Your affectionate wife, Lizzy You must execute all my commissions.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Charleston\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 57
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Wednesday morning, 7 May 1845
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 As I \ul promised\ulnone , I must write, but I am so busy I can hardly spare the time.\'a0 The whole family are well, except Minerva who is today sick in bed, with cold & pain in her stomach.\'a0 I have given her castor oil & Ginger tea.\'a0 Yesterday afternoon we had a delightful rain, & this morning Jim & James planted out cabbages & Tomatoes, & replanted seeds.\'a0 They have now gone to the farm, to make the Potato hills.\'a0 I have rode out once only since you left, Sunday afternoon.\'a0 The afternoons are generally so doubtful, that I am afraid to venture the carri[a]ge, not myself.\'a0 I am well enough to do a good days work.\'a0 I yesterday made a frock for Minerva, & a pr of pantaloons for James.\'a0 You may know how much work I must have, to require me to work so steadily & imagine how inconvenient it must be to me to write.\'a0 Monday, Jim carried wood to the Saw Mill.\'a0 Tuesday he hauled rock from Mr. Pikes.\'a0 He would have hauled the remainder today\'a0 if he had not been obliged to stop to plant.\'a0 Mr. Pike sent word, the rock was finished, & was in his way, that he would like it sent for.\'a0 The Miss Willifords, & Mrs. Perry Duncan have been to see me.\'a0 The latter heard I had been sick, & came to inquire after me.\'a0 I miss you \ul greatly\ulnone .\'a0 I often go in the drawing room with the children & look at your picture, which as it bears \ul resemblance\ulnone  to \ul you\ulnone .\'a0 I regret it does not look \ul more\ulnone  like you.\'a0 I ask Frank where Papa is, he points to the picture & wishes to shake hands with it.\'a0 \ul When\ulnone  I go to town, if there is a \ul good\ulnone  artist there I \ul must\ulnone  have my likeness taken, for I am sure as long as it was in your possession, you could not forget me, even if I was \ul gone\ulnone , & you had so far forgotten me, as to have taken to yourself \ul another\ulnone  in my place.\'a0 I would like it to be hung up somewhere, to recall to your mind now & then some of the happy days we have passed together, particularly our first wedded ones, but most especially would I wish it for the children.\'a0 I am sure as long as I have your picture before me, I could not forget you, or love anyone in your place, , or even if I were (impossible)\'a0 to love another, I would still love that picture, imperfect as it is.\'a0 Willy, the morning after you left when he woke up & found you \ul gone\ulnone , said \ul bitterly\ulnone , I told him you kissed him & bid him good bye, he said, you did not.\'a0 He seems really attached to you, & I think it would improve him to be more with you.\'a0 I hope his \ul wish\ulnone  to \ul be\ulnone  like you, will \ul make\ulnone  him like you.\'a0 He last night took off his \'85coat & shirt in the way Pa took his off.\'a0 I think our children would be much better if they did not associate so much with \ul young\ulnone  \ul servants\ulnone .\'a0 Our servants are too young to know how to behave themselves, or care to teach their children how to behave.\'a0 Old servants would injure them much less.\'a0 They would not be so trifling, or teach them so many bad things, but on the contrary assist in making them behave properly.\'a0 However I do not complain, we are obliged to have servants, but I am sorry associating with them is so injurious, & I wish them to make companions of them as little as possible.\'a0 My worriments \ul now\ulnone , are not \ul servants\ulnone , but \ul War\ulnone  & my \ul box\ulnone .\'a0 I hope if Mr. Earle has gone to town you have requested him to bring it to Columbia.\'a0 If you can you must convey a message to Mr. Thompson\'85to beg him to send it to you by some opportunity, only one days journey from Charleston to Columbia.\'a0 It certainly could get there safely.\'a0 Last year you recollect writing to you at this time my theme was \ul Texas\ulnone  & the \ul election\ulnone .\'a0 I feel much happier now for I am in hopes we will have no War, & that you will bring my box & what I wished then for you, you have attained. I have bought no flour, all the \ul good\ulnone  flour like \ul ours\ulnone  was sold.\'a0 Mr. Roberts had some \ul not\ulnone  so \ul good\ulnone , but which I did not get, as Mamma could not have made eatable bread out of it, Hardly can with my good Flour.\'a0 It is so \ul scarce\ulnone  I have been obliged to lend Mamma half of my barrel.\'a0 When we send for Groceries,\'a0 I expect we will have to send for Flour.\'a0 Mamma\'92s Groceries a few she sent for arrived last week, were only 5 days on the road.\'a0 That is the quickest way of getting anything from town. You have my list of purchases, so I need not mention them again.\'a0 In all probability you will not see Sarah Taylor, but if you were to tell her I ask her to send me some patterns of her childrens clothes, that I may see the \ul fashions\ulnone .\'a0 She has sent me patterns before, & I know she would have pretty ones.\'a0 Willy has outgrown his last years clothes, & I will have to make him a \ul few\ulnone  for \ul dress\ulnone . No one has come to the house to inquire for you, & no letters came last Sundays mail.\'a0 Mr. Simpson sent you a large package of public documents.\'a0 My pen, paper, & ink are so bad I take no pleasure in writing.\'a0 I sent to your office for paper but there was none, & I thought it not worthwhile to buy for one letter, for I do not expect to write again.\'a0 Margaret will be here today & tomorrow.\'a0 I have a great deal of work on hand, particularly servants clothes, which I wish to do during your absence, that on your return I may have more time to devote to you, so if you do not hear again, you must not be uneasy.\'a0 You must if you get summer clothes, buy pretty ones.\'a0 Take care of yourself, & as the children say in their prayers, come back safe home. I have told Willy he may carry my letter to the office, and Frank who is near me, says in \ul his\ulnone  \ul language\ulnone , that he wishes to go too.\'a0 Anna is asleep.\'a0\'a0 She has called to me while writing to put her to sleep, & as I did not notice her, she lay down on the bed & went to sleep.\'a0 Willy went to the Sunday school last Sunday.\'a0 He was anxious to go, so I thought I would let him try it.\'a0 He was very much pleased.\'a0 Anna\'92s hand is almost well.\'a0 A poultice took out the inflammation.\'a0 Your affectionate Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 58
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Sunday night, 11 May 1845
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received a letter from you.\'a0 I am so glad you wrote, for it is such a disappointment when I do not hear, more so to me than to you, for \ul without\ulnone  \ul you\ulnone  I am \ul lonely\ulnone , & a letter from you, even a few lines is a treat.\'a0 If you were not so \ul very\ulnone  \ul busy\ulnone  I would write oftener, when you know how \ul much\ulnone  \ul work\ulnone  I have on hand, you will see I have not the time.\'a0 I write tonight, because I am more at leisure than I will be tomorrow.\'a0 I will tell you the work I have to do at once a dress for Minerva, Delia, Mary, Lindy & Clara each; Pantaloons for Jim & James; Shirts also & aprons for them; Night\'a0 dresses, Chemise, Petticoats, Nightcaps, Aprons & Collars for myself.\'a0 Shoes for you & clothes for the children, & more besides; now have I a \ul moment\ulnone  to \ul spare\ulnone . Mamma is very glad to hear Uncle Arthur will pay her a visit.\'a0 From Aunt Elizabeths letter, she was in hopes he would.\'a0 I dare say he will come during your absence.\'a0 I am \ul sorry\ulnone , as I would like you to have seen him, & he you.\'a0 It is a pity the arrangement of the Court was changed so as to bring the lower country Lawyers to Columbia.\'a0 You were not formerly \ul delayed\ulnone  in your business as you now are, & it is so \ul expensive\ulnone  to remain so long a time in Columbia, particularly when you are doing nothing.\'a0 You must in the Legislature next winter propose altering it, & having it as it formerly was. Mr. Butler went Friday night to Columbia.\'a0 He sent me word that he would take a letter but Margaret was with me, so I could not write.\'a0 I wonder why he goes down.\'a0 Mrs. Stone says on business connected with the Commissioners office.\'a0 You say you have engaged a suit of clothes.\'a0 I suppose they are a \ul dress\ulnone  \ul suit\ulnone .\'a0 If they are, you ought to get another suit for every day, as you so much need them.\'a0 Nice clothes are needed for the week, as much as on Sunday.\'a0 I hope you have bought us \ul pretty\ulnone  beads.\'a0 I suppose they are different from mine, as you got a set for me.\'a0 Willy says you must bring him something \ul pretty\ulnone , that he will not tell you \ul what\ulnone , because perhaps you will get something \ul prettier\ulnone  than he would tell you.\'a0 If there are any horses such as you saw in Charleston, & are suitable for a boy of \ul his\ulnone  \ul size\ulnone , & do not \ul cost\ulnone  \ul much\ulnone , you might think of one of those for him, but I expect there are none of the kind there, you mentioned seeing in Charleston, & if they are, now when we wish to \ul save\ulnone , it would be extravagant to get it.\'a0 The \ul Valocipedes\ulnone  I do not like \ul at\ulnone  \ul all\ulnone .\'a0 I wish Columbia was as good & economical a place for shopping as Charleston.\'a0 There are several things I would like you to get for me.\'a0 I am very glad when you do buy pretty things, that they should be such as will do to put in the Drawing room, & add to the beauty of the room. You must tell Mr. Barclay if he is coming to Greenville \ul only\ulnone  for the purpose of taking \ul my\ulnone  \ul likeness\ulnone , he may stay away, if he did not succeed to my satisfaction in \ul yours\ulnone , he will certainly not in \ul mine\ulnone .\'a0 I wish mine taken, but it shall be by one, who I am \ul confident\ulnone  will \ul not\ulnone  \ul fail\ulnone .\'a0 Yours to the generality of people would be a striking likeness, but \ul I\ulnone  see it is \ul far\ulnone  from being \ul correct\ulnone , though your features are large, they are \ul delicately\ulnone  formed, your nose is \ul thin\ulnone , your lips are thin,, & you have no double chin, & full cheeks which Mr. Barclay has given you along with a \ul Roman\ulnone  \ul nose\ulnone , & \ul puffed\ulnone  up \ul lips\ulnone .\'a0 It always looks to me like Mr. Henry & Col. Brockman than you.\'a0 If the Daguerreotype painter that Mr. Summer mentioned in his paper, is still in \ul Columbia\ulnone , do you have your likeness taken, in the \ul prettiest\ulnone  way that he takes them.\'a0 If you wish to bring me a \ul valuable\ulnone  present, & one that will please me above everything else, bring me your miniature.\'a0 I wish to \ul own\ulnone  an \ul exact\ulnone  likeness of yourself, & taken as Mr. Summer described, it was far superior to all Daguerreotypes we have ever seen & must certainly give an exact likeness, so if the Dr I think he was a Doctor is still in Columbia, \ul gratify\ulnone  me & bring me what I so much wish, a \ul faithful\ulnone  \ul likeness\ulnone  of yourself to comfort me during your many absences.\'a0 This is if the likenesses taken are \ul really\ulnone  \ul good\ulnone .\'a0 The paper mentioned the price was reasonable. Mrs. Chick is dead.\'a0 She & Dr. Chick have been at the Springs since last summer..\'a0 She was quite well & went into the garden after the rain & was walking about, & she fell down.\'a0 She cried for help. & when someone went to her, one side of her body was paralyzed.\'a0 When she was carried into the house, the other side became affected.\'a0 After that I think it was the last consciousness, & after remaining so for a time & suffering greatly, died. You say I must tell you how everything goes on.\'a0 I am sorry to tell you that \ul faithful\ulnone  \ul Bob\ulnone  is not well.\'a0 Yesterday morning Jim came in & said Mr. Longs Dudley said Bob & Buck were taking the Distemper.\'a0 I told him to go ask Mr. Hoke to come & see them.\'a0 Mr. Hoke came & said they had \ul not\ulnone  the Distemper, that they were injured by James riding them so \ul hard\ulnone  to water, their filling their stomachs with water, & then being rode \ul hard\ulnone  back again, that if \ul that\ulnone  was continued, you would never have horses, or they would be of no account if you had, that he had often spoken [page torn] about [page torn] he said also their food was \ul too\ulnone  \ul dry\ulnone , that their fodder must be [page torn] in salt & water, & they would then improve.\'a0 Today Buck who was the \ul least\ulnone  \ul sick\ulnone  seems quite well, & Bob is \ul better\ulnone , & will soon I suppose [be] watered & fed properly [&] be \ul quite\ulnone  \ul well\ulnone .\'a0 I suppose when James \ul kills\ulnone  a pr pf horses for you, you will think it time to part with him.\'a0 Mr. Westfield, Mr. Cauble, & I expect many others have spoken to him about his manner of riding.\'a0 If you cannot make him \ul obey\ulnone  \ul you\ulnone , it is high time to \ul sell\ulnone  him.\'a0 The other evening, a horse galloped by so \ul fast\ulnone  I thought & Will too that it was running away.\'a0 I looked & it was James on Skylark.\'a0 You need not be uneasy about them now, for this warning for the \ul present\ulnone  at \ul least\ulnone , will make him more careful. \ul Troubles\ulnone  I expect to have as long as the \ul Goddess\ulnone  of \ul Wisdom\ulnone  presides over my kitchen.\'a0 For several days she was sick, so I have not been troubled as much as usual.\'a0 This morning however she did something to provoke me, so when she came in to take out dinner, I told her not to do so again, & told her I hoped she would do better, that if she did not behave differently from what she had done, we would not keep her.\'a0 Instead of saying, she would \ul try\ulnone  & do \ul better\ulnone , she said she had done nothing wrong, \{&] if I was not pleased with her, she would \ul rather\ulnone  be sold, [&] if I would only let her have her two children, that she had never been so unhappy as since she had been in this yard, that she had \ul scars\ulnone  on her now, given her by \ul you\ulnone  &c. &c.\'a0 The other morning Charlotte was walking round the garden, & would stop & pull something.\'a0 I sent Edward to bring her out.\'a0 I was in the piazza , & Minerva came to the kitchen door, & before me called to Edward to leave Charlotte alone, that she had feet of her own to walk out of the garden with.\'a0 I do not tell you these things to worry you, for I have not been worried.\'a0 I am contented, as you say you will part with her, & get another if she does not do better.\'a0 I am going to \ul try\ulnone  & get along as \ul easy\ulnone  as possible, & not worry myself & scold the servants as little as possible.\'a0 Still I do not think everything should be put up with.\'a0 Margaret the other day observed the behaviour of some of them & said to me, if you let your servants go on so, they will soon walk over you.\'a0 I did not mean to say so much about them.\'a0 I went to church twice today.\'a0 The children & myself are well.\'a0 Ann says if Lemons are not \ul dear\ulnone , she would like you to bring her a few.\'a0 No letters came for you tonight.\'a0 If money is \ul scarce\ulnone  bring only a \ul trifling\ulnone  present for Will.\'a0 I am glad you bought perfumery.\'a0 Write me as often as you can.\'a0 I will write every other mail, if am not \ul busy\ulnone .\'a0 It is now past 9.\'a0 The children are asleep.\'a0 Mamma\'92s horse is dreadfully hurt, the hip either out of place, or fractured, can hardly walk.\'a0 Bob I think will soon be well.\'a0 Goodnight, E.F.P. I received a letter from Pamela last Mail, do not think I am worried about servants & hope Minerva will do better.\'a0 I am worried about \ul War\ulnone .\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

\f1\b 59
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Tuesday night, 17 June 1845
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I met Genl Thompson on the road yesterday as I was walking to Mamma\'92s, & he asked me what message he should give you at Pickens, if he should say we were all well.\'a0 I told him perhaps I would write a few lines, & he said he would call for them tomorrow.\'a0 The children are gone up to bed, & instead of passing the evening, reading or working, I will converse with you, & you must promise not to \ul scold\ulnone  me \ul once\ulnone .\'a0Sunday morning Susan & myself went to church.\'a0 Mr. Pinckney preached on the subject of building a new church.\'a0 He gave all the reasons why it was \ul necessary\ulnone , & answered \ul all\ulnone  \ul objections\ulnone  that \ul could\ulnone  be made against it.\'a0 The sermon was so satisfactory, that many who objected before are reconciled now.\'a0 He regretted you were not there to hear it.\'a0 The reasons in favour are too many for me to mention in a letter.\'a0 I will let you know them all when you return.\'a0 I will only inform you of a few now. It is a \ul fact\ulnone  that the sleepers under the floor are decaying, some have already given way, & that part of the church would have to be repaired at an expense of several hundred dollars,\'a0 The church would not be enlarged for cutting away the wall, would make it unsafe.\'a0 More pews are needed, for persons have applied for pews, & not been able to obtain them.\'a0 The Society in Charleston which has given one half of the salary to our Minister, been assisting for 20 years & in that time given 5000 dollars has informed the Vestry, that it must now withdraw its assistance, appropriate it to build up other churches.\'a0 This year they have decreased the sum one fourth, & will continue gradually to lessen it, until they stop entirely. The support of the Minister will then devolve on 30 pew holders, & they will consequently have to pay more than they do at present.\'a0 It is therefore important that there should be more pews, so that the support of the Minister, should fall upon many.\'a0 This last I think the strongest reason, but there are others too numerous to mention.\'a0 Yesterday Mr. Pinckney, Mr. Cox, Dr. Irvine went about obtaining subscriptions, & Mr. Sutter, Mr. Bee\'85himself among the young men.\'a0 Persons have been uncommonly liberal even those badly off have given.\'a0 1600 dollars have been subscribed.\'a0 The work goes on prosperously.\'a0 I have heard of but one person who objected to it, the bearer of this letter, but he does not know the motives for undertaking it, neither do \ul you\ulnone , so you must not say anything against it.\'a0 Mr. Pinckney came to me for your subscription, thinking you had told me how much you would give.\'a0 I told him you had not said what \ul sum\ulnone , but that you would give \ul something\ulnone , & if he thought it not proper in me, & not taking too great a liberty with you, I would put down for you what I thought you would be willing to give.\'a0 He said yes certainly I must put it down, so I \ul did\ulnone , & he said it was the sum all expected from you.\'a0 It was however on the condition that you were not \ul bound\ulnone  to \ul pay\ulnone  it, as it was done without your \ul knowledge\ulnone .\'a0 He said there was no danger of that, that you were a gentleman of \ul taste\ulnone , & would contribute towards raising a beautiful building, such an ornament to the village, even if you had no higher motive.\'a0 I am afraid you may be displeased at what I have done, & I have been rather uneasy at my boldness, but Mrs. Poinsett this afternoon said I was perfectly right, & she would have done the same.\'a0 The money is not to be paid for some time, & I intend to \ul save\ulnone  out of the 5 dollars you allow me every week, so when the time comes to pay the money I will be able to assist you.\'a0 You have no curiosity so you will not care to know, how much I subscribed for you until you come home.\'a0 I have dwelt so long on the church, I will not be able to tell you all I had to say on other matters.\'a0 Sunday morning stupid James sat down by one of the horses in the stable.\'a0 I rather think \ul under\ulnone  it, & had a finger mashed by the horses foot, so that the nail has or will come off.\'a0 I suppose he was asleep.\'a0 I almost thought he must have done it on purpose to keep from working.\'a0 I was afraid he would not be able to plough, but from Jims not asking for Mary today, who I told him he might have, I suppose he has been able to.\'a0 John drove the horses Sunday quite well.\'a0 Jim came home early Monday morning in a good humour.\'a0 Perhaps it will be better for his wife to live at the farm.\'a0 It will be a treat to him to go to see her, & he will be grateful to you for allowing him the privilege.\'a0 Yesterday I paid 6 visits.\'a0 Mrs. Irvine, Mrs. Jones, Mrs. Dubose, Mrs. Crawford, Mrs. Wm Roberts, & Miss Crittenden.\'a0 In the afternoon I walked to Mamma\'92s with the children, & Susan came back with me part of the way.\'a0 This morning I paid 6 more to Miss Lynah, Mrs. Mauldin, Mrs. Wells, Mrs. Theodore Thompson, Mrs. Bradshaw, & Mrs. Baker.\'a0 I was congratulating myself at the prospect of \ul getting\ulnone  \ul through\ulnone  & lo! 3 have been returned alteady.\'a0 One I paid yesterday was returned today, Miss Crawford.\'a0 Col. Lynah this morning inquired after you.\'a0 I told him you were away, & you would have gone over with me to see him.\'a0 I thought I might say so without \ul fibbing\ulnone , for of course after his coming to your house last summer, you would call to see him this.\'a0 They left Mr. Roper at the point of death with country fever, & Mrs. Andrew Turnbull with the inflammation of the Bowels.\'a0 You saw her at Aunt Turnbulls & was pleased with her.\'a0 Mr. & Mrs. Poinsett called this afternoon & were quite pleasant.\'a0 I like them so much.\'a0 Nobody knows there is Court at Anderson.\'a0 I don\'92t believe the Lawyers wives (with a few exceptions.)\'a0 Minerva I let go to Mamma\'92s today, to make another trial at cooking, & will continue to do so, until you return.\'a0 I suppose tonight you are at Pendleton.\'a0 I have scarcely room to inquire after my little Willie.\'a0 Tell him I hope he has been a good boy & given you no trouble; that Mrs. Mauldin thinks of naming her baby Willie or Frank, & little Mary says she must name it \ul Willie\ulnone  \ul Perry\ulnone .\'a0 Anna & Frank went to see it this afternoon.\'a0 I \ul kissed\ulnone  it this morning, & Mrs. Mauldin said I was the first person who had, that it was so ugly no one would.\'a0 It is a large child, weighed 11 pounds when it was born.\'a0 Tell Willie the kitten is very playful, that his chicken is well & takes care of Anna\'92s chicken.\'a0 They are always together & seem so fond of each other.\'a0 Frank begins to talk.\'a0 He is so smart & interesting.\'a0 Sunday he was at the window & John passed on horseback towards the stable.\'a0 Anna said there goes Uncle John.\'a0 I asked if he was on a horse, & Frank called out; Skylark, Skylark.\'a0 Today I was in the Library writing a note to Susan & Frank was playing with a half a dollar of hers.\'a0 When I had finished writing I left the Library & went to my room.\'a0 After a while I thought of the half a dollar.\'a0 I took Frank back into the Library & told him to find the money.\'a0 He instantly went to a book that was loose at the back where he had slipped the money down & showed it to me.\'a0 This morning his tea was hot, & he said to Lindy blow, blow.\'a0 As you rode off Sunday he said, \'93I want go.\'94\'a0 Anna & himself behave quite well, so I hope Willie will too when he comes back.\'a0 Mr. Hoke has returned.\'a0 Hooker this\'85 he might eventually\'a0 live in N.C. but he believed not at present.\'a0 Mrs. Stone last Sunday said Tom Butler was going to write to Richard Stone to come up to be a candidate for Sheriff, as it was thought Mr. Hoke would resign.\'a0 He had better not be so \ul quick\ulnone , but wait till he \ul actually\ulnone  \ul does\ulnone .\'a0 I would be sorry for Mr. Hoke to move away & hope he will not.\'a0 No more Balloons have been sent up.\'a0 Hooker said he heard it fell in our yard, & he believed the Council had talked about it, & determined to allow no more to ascend.\'a0 Good night.\'a0 I hope you will be pleased to hear from me.\'a0 Except salt, I have not bought anything since you left.\'a0 10 oclock, E.F.P. The church last Sunday was crowded, more so than I have ever seen it & Mr. D\'85mion preached the best sermon I have heard from him\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Pickens C.H.\
\'a0\

\f1\b 60
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Monday night, 13 October 1845
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Mrs. Palmer leaves tomorrow, & I will write a few lines by her.\'a0 I hope you will be glad to receive them.\'a0 Though only two days have elapsed since you left, I have a good deal to tell you.\'a0 I went to see Mrs. Palmer this morning.\'a0 She said to \ul me\ulnone , as she did to Susan that she was very sorry not to have made \ul your\ulnone  acquaintance, that she would like to have done so, for she heard you spoken of in such \ul high\ulnone  \ul terms\ulnone , but she would take it for granted that all she heard was \ul true\ulnone .\'a0 I told her you were at Laurens.\'a0 She said perhaps she would see you there, as she was to pass a night there, so if you come in contact with her, you must be very polite, & if needs be, you must give up your chamber as you once did to Mrs. Alston.\'a0 Mrs. Alston leaves tomorrow also but I believe she generally goes as far as Goldsmiths only, the first day.\'a0 I supplied both Mrs. Palmer & Alston with cake to eat on the road.\'a0 I saw Mrs. Alston yesterday for a little while after church at Mrs. Longs door.\'a0 She inquired after you [&] said she would never forget your kindness at Laurens in giving up your comfortable room to her.\'a0 I told her you would be happy to oblige her again, & perhaps she may need the room this time, so if she does you must let her have it.\'a0 The Middletons leave tonight, & the Lynahs tomorrow, so that this week everybody will be gone.\'a0 I went this morning to see Miss Crittenden, Mrs. Townes who was out, & Mrs. Hoke.\'a0 Mr. Hoke came in while I was there, & said he had just made a bargain for you & himself that he had sold your land in the Mountains for 95 dollars \ul Cash\ulnone , & received nine dollars for rent.\'a0 He thought he had done \ul well\ulnone , so I hope you\'a0 \ul will\ulnone  think the \ul same\ulnone ; so you will have 52 dollars waiting for you on your return.\'a0 You ought to be very grateful, whenever your purse is emptied it is filled again.\'a0 Mrs. Palmer told Susan that Mrs. Gibbes wishes to sell her place, that Mr. Gibes health is worse, & that after Mrs. Poinsett leaves there is no one she could depend upon for being with her in sickness, so she would rather go back to Columbia.\'a0 I think she is mistaken, for in Greenville persons are particularly kind in sickness. I saw Mr. Poinsett at the Mansion house this morning.\'a0 He said he had hoped to see you, about the Railroad business.\'a0 He had forgotten you would be at Laurens, but supposed you would be back Saturday.\'a0 He thinks there is no doubt but the stock will be taken.\'a0 Genl Thompson went to see Mamma Saturday in the \ul pouring\ulnone  \ul rain\ulnone , said he was on his way to see Mr. Poinsett & as it was raining, thought he would stop & see her, particularly as he expected to be absent a great deal during the \ul winter\ulnone .\'a0 Mamma asked him \ul where\ulnone  he was going.\'a0 He said he would be \ul attending\ulnone  \ul Courts\ulnone . I went to the Methodist church yesterday morning & afternoon.\'a0 Heard the presiding elder Mr. Walker in the morning, & Dr. Palmer in the afternoon.\'a0 Miss Ann Gadsden dined with Mamma.\'a0 She asked me if I knew the reason Miss Crawford did not take tea with me.\'a0 I told her I thought she was \ul rich\ulnone .\'a0 She said no, she was not, that she asked her if she was coming, & she said, \'93no indeed!\'a0 She would not accept a 3 oclock invitation\'94.\'a0 Mrs. Coleman says she is the most offensively\'85person she ever saw, & I hear, all the gentlemen at Longs are going to present a petition to Mr. Long to turn her away.\'a0 March Jim & James all worked at Mamma\'92s today.\'a0 James says they have got through.\'a0 Charles said yesterday he wants to finish their room now as his time was up & Jim told him he was anxious to have him, to help with the Cotton lands.\'a0 Jim drove the Cows home last night after I had gone to bed, & tonight long after supper.\'a0 In future he must be earlier. No one has inquired for you & no letters have come.\'a0 We are all pretty well.\'a0 Willie has written you a note which he says I must be sure & not forget to send you.\'a0 Miss Crittenden says Mr. Adam Summer has gone on to Portland, Maine, to be married, that the other one of whom Cornelier Crittenden has been joked, she Cornelier has seen very seldom & does not like, he has never been attentive to her, but has spoken well of her. And now my dear husband, you will think you are reading one of Aunt Harriets letters such a \ul medley\ulnone , but I thought all events I would fill my sheet.\'a0 I hope you will be grateful to me for passing the evening writing to you\'85be grateful instead of working on my Quilt, which I was strongly tempted to do.\'a0 I told Mrs. Poinsett today that Pamela was very glad to see that \ul she\ulnone  was a subscriber to her book.\'a0 She said she had \ul not\ulnone  \ul subscribed\ulnone  & that she would \ul not\ulnone .\'a0 Good night, Your affectionate Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Laurens Court House\
\'a0\

\f1\b 61
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Tuesday night, 28 October 1845
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 As I promised to write to you I \ul must\ulnone , & I write tonight, because \ul tomorrow\ulnone  I am going to Mamma\'92s to help Susan work.\'a0 I was there part of yesterday & today.\'a0 You are perhaps uneasy about Willie.\'a0 All Sunday he complained of pain in his stomach, said he felt weak, & as if he would throw up.\'a0 At night I went for Dr. Earle.\'a0 Just before he came, Willie threw up some acid stuff.\'a0 It seemed to relieve him.\'a0 The Doctor said I must give him a dose of Castor Oil, & 10 drops of Laudanum.\'a0 It operated, & Willie was well enough Monday to go to school.\'a0 I dare say he will be better for that dose of Medicine. Sunday morning I went to the Methodist church.\'a0 In the afternoon I rode with the children to Mrs. Gibbs to inquire how Mr. Gibbs was.\'a0 He is very poorly, eats principally Custard.\'a0 At the Methodist church door, I saw the servant Ben who wishes you to purchase him.\'a0 He is a \ul fine\ulnone , \ul pleasant\ulnone  looking servant.\'a0 I told him I wished to exchange James for him.\'a0 He said he would be very glad of it.\'a0 I mentioned to Mrs. Gibbs that I would like to change one boy for Ben.\'a0 She said James was good looking, but did not say whether she would like the exchange.\'a0 I asked Mr. Gibbs price for Ben.\'a0 She said 700, & I do not think that is high for so good a servant as he looks to be.\'a0 I should think he was under 20.\'a0 As for James I have no patience with him.\'a0 I will not rest until you have parted with him.\'a0 I have no comfort in his driving.\'a0 I intend to give up riding altogether.\'a0 He has not \ul sense\ulnone  enough to be a good driver.\'a0 This afternoon he almost upset us.\'a0 He turned the carri[a]ge short, & carried us up a high bank. You must thank Providence your Wife & children are spared you, for you might have returned & sought for them in vain.\'a0 When we are on a good road we go at a snails pace, with every now & then a jerk forward which nearly throws us off of our seats, then when we come to a hill either up or down, we go at a gallop, & we are always at the side of the road half way down in a gully, or up on the bank, with the tree brushing or scratching the carri[a]ge.\'a0 Our carri[a]ge which has always been thought so easy, is now the most jolting concern I know of, so do you think I will lose anything in giving up riding.\'a0 The Springs I think must be injured from driving fast over bridges, gullys & stumps.\'a0 Last Sunday the carri[a]ge would not have been ready in time, if Jim had not been here to fix the horses, while James was dressing, & I had to go to the stable myself to call him to come & dress, & when dressed he was not fit to be seen, his coat collar turned inside, his shirt collar standing up & a dirty Jacket.\'a0 This Afternoon he drove us to the show.\'a0 I let him unharness the horses & go in.\'a0 When the show was over he was nowhere to be found.\'a0 Fortunately March was near, & he drove us home.\'a0 When we passed near Dr. R\'85\'92s shop, there was James quietly standing up.\'a0 He is a \ul perfect\ulnone  \ul fool\ulnone , & if you will keep him, he must be in \ul your\ulnone  \ul service\ulnone  & not \ul mine\ulnone .\'a0 I would rather have March as my wa[t]chman than him.\'a0 The carri[a]ge & horses are both beginning to look shockingly & I expect will last one twentieth the time, that they would have done with a good servant. We went to the Menagerie.\'a0 It is the \ul poorest\ulnone  \ul collection\ulnone  of animals I have ever seen, but still worth seeing, as all animals are.\'a0 So I advise you to go if they are in Anderson.\'a0 The Hippopotamus is stuffed, the snakes are quite small, a Monkey rides round on a pony, a little boy & man perform feats of agility & strength & some men dressed as negroes sing.\'a0 They perform again [page torn]\'a0 night [page torn]\'a0 if you had been here I would like to have gone.\'a0 I like all shows.\'a0 I now hear the music & wish I was there.\'a0 Everybody I may say was there this afternoon. Mr. Pringle went last night, & Mrs. Pringle goes Saturday.\'a0 She was here this afternoon after the show.\'a0 I drove up while she was in the house.\'a0 I was going to shop with Susan.\'a0 She said I must not get out, that she had come for a book, & would come again to see me.\'a0 I told her to go up in the Library & choose one.\'a0 I can tell you nothing of your farm, but hope all is going on well.\'a0 Neither Jim or Maria came in to go to the show.\'a0 Charles I met on Mamma\'92s road.\'a0 I gave him the money but do not think he went.\'a0 I expect he preferred keeping the money.\'a0 3 letters have come for you, one acknowledging the receipt of T. Butlers money, another from \'85 Foster enclosing a note on a Richards, another from N. Carolina relating to Hodges.\'a0 I am ashamed of my shabby letter.\'a0 You must excuse it.\'a0 Your dear wife, Liz.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Anderson Court House\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 62
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b 24 November 1845
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I must write you a few lines to prevent your being uneasy, but I can promise you neither a long or interesting letter, for my material for composing one, is very scant indeed.\'a0 All Saturday I staid at home.\'a0 I had a visit from Mr. Luther McBee & Mr. Erwin his cousin.\'a0 Sunday morning we enjoyed a treat in going to the Episcopal church & hearing Mr. Pinckney.\'a0 He is to preach again next Sunday, & then the church will be shut up, until a new minister comes, which I fear will be for a long time.\'a0 After\'85Mamma, Susan & myself rode out to Mrs. Gibbs to bid her good bye.\'a0 She leaves this afternoon, & expect[s] to reach Columbia in five days.\'a0 The place is sold to Mr. Whitefoord Smith, father of the minister of that name\'a0 2500 dollars he gave for it; including I believe, a little of the furniture.\'a0 After returning from Mrs. Gibbs, I remained at Mamma\'92s & spent the day.\'a0 I sent for the children.\'a0 Mrs. McBee, Miss Malinda, & Miss Reinhardt were there.\'a0 The wedding takes place Thursday evening at church.\'a0 Only a few persons will be invited.\'a0 Miss Reinhardt only will return home with Susan, so that it will be to them like any other evening.\'a0 I will not have my party for a fortnight.\'a0 The McBee\'92s wish it put off until then, when they expect more friends from N. Carolina, & will themselves then give a party.\'a0 A great many persons are now absent, who we wish to invite, & will have returned by that time.\'a0 I am quite satisfied, & \ul prefer\ulnone  putting it off.\'a0 Mr. Pinckney in a visit to Mamma, spoke well of Mr. McBee, & seemed pleased at Susans marrying him.\'a0 I hope she will be happy, she \ul deserves\ulnone  to be. Today is quite cold, & Jim intends killing the hogs.\'a0 Mr. Hooker brought the oats Saturday, & I paid for them.\'a0 This morning the old free black male, your client, came to see you.\'a0 He is in trouble about the money you paid him some time ago; says Willis Robinson says; you paid him too much, & wants some of it, , that he had seen you about it, & you told him to go to him.\'a0 He reminds me of Durham.\'a0 He dreads advantages being taken of him.\'a0 Only a newspaper came last night.\'a0 I have no news to tell you, & as only two days have passed since you left home, of course nothing has occurred for me to relate.\'a0 We are quite well, Willie is at school, the other children playing in the yard.\'a0 This is a pleasant day.\'a0 I hope you have the same weather in Columbia.\'a0 I miss you very much, but am so unselfish, as to prefer your being where you will be of service to your District & State than with me.\'a0 It would be a pity that the best qualified man to represent the people, should remain in seclusion at home, recollect, write me nothing about \ul homesickness\ulnone .\'a0 In the first place I don\'92t believe it, & in the second place do not wish my husband to be so childish this time next year.\'a0 I hope I will be with you on my way to Charleston.\'a0 I am still busy helping Susans work.\'a0 Yesterday she had a bad headache, & I am afraid she has it today.\'a0 I look forward with pleasure to hearing from you Wednesday.\'a0 I must conclude with one peice of advice.\'a0 Do not forget to send Legislative documents to your friends.\'a0 Write me of everything, take care of yourself, & be happy.\'a0 The children all sleep with me.\'a0 I will keep you informed of all going on at home, but if I miss writing by one off the Mails, know that I have nothing to write about, & I do not wish you to pay postage for a letter\'a0 containing one sentence, \'93we are well\'94.\'a0 Your affectionate, Liz\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 63
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Tuesday night, 25 November 1845
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I wrote to you yesterday, & as you are so anxious to hear every Mail, I must write again tonight, for tomorrow I will be very busy working for Susan.\'a0 I was at Mamma\'92s today.\'a0 Some boxes arrived from town for her, among them one containing presents for Susan.\'a0 Aunt Brewton has sent her a handsome shawl; Aunt Elizabeth (Uncle Arthurs wife) a \ul beautiful\ulnone  \ul bracelet\ulnone ; Aunt Martha a Prayer book\'a0 Aunt Turnbull a pr of glass bottles; Aunt Harriet a China cup & saucer; Aunt Sarah Matthews a China candlestick; Aunt Eliza a China Lamp; Aunt Mary Hayne a Shawl & Gloves; Aunt a book; Elizabeth Jones a lace collar; Mrs. Lowndes a \ul beautiful\ulnone  Broach an Amethyst, which you know is a Red or rather Claret coloured stone, not in gold.\'a0 They are the kind worn & Mrs. Lowndes has sent Ann a handsome Silver cup.\'a0 I mention the presents, because as I have so little to write about, it helps to fill up the letter.\'a0 The wedding is to be very private.\'a0 Susan has invited only Dr. Crook, Mrs. Duboc & Maria Pinckney.\'a0 Mr. McBee has invited Mr. Croft & Mrs. Pearson who said they intended giving a party on the occasion.\'a0 Mrs. Thompson & Eliza, Mr. & Mrs. Bradshaw & his own family.\'a0 Mamma was having some cake made today, to send to her friends in town, & to some persons here.\'a0 She will send you a peice.\'a0 There will be a good many opportunities to Columbia.\'a0 Wm Rowland is going down Thursday, perhaps I will send this letter by him, if he goes in the Columbia stage.\'a0 Mr. Elford is going to Charleston, & I suppose goes by the way of Columbia.\'a0 Mamma got him to attend to the witnessing & signing the papers Alston sent.\'a0 He said he would send them up & send them back to Alston, & at the same time, write a peice & put it in . saying \ul he\ulnone  had attended to the business for her. The hogs are killed.\'a0 I hope now the weather will continue cold.\'a0 I am glad the corn will not diminish as rapidly as it has done.\'a0 You must not be uneasy about home.\'a0 I expect everything will go on as well as if you were here. Anna & Frank are in bed.\'a0 Willie has been staying downstairs with me.\'a0 They all speak of you, & Frank when offended with us, says \'93I\'92ll tell Pa\'94 & ask him where Pa is, he says, Pa gone to Lumbia.\'a0 Last night was very cold, & I am squeezed in bed.\'a0 I can scarcely move.\'a0 All of the children wish to sleep with me, & I do not know which to refuse, so have to let them all.\'a0 The contest now is, which shall be next to me. I hope Mr. Elias Earle will be elected.\'a0 You must do all you can for him.\'a0 Mr. Wigfall I think I would like also elected, & would like you to vote for him, if there is no other person who has a greater claim on you.\'a0 Mr. McBee says he met Col. Townes today, & he said to him, \'93you don\'92t go down to Columbia\'94, he said, \'93no, but I hope you will help to send me down \ul next\ulnone  \ul winter\ulnone !\'94  Mr. Gibbs left today.\'a0 I am sorry he has been obliged to leave, for I like Mrs. Gibbs, their boy Ben, I believe has been purchased by the gentleman who bought the place. After hearing from you, I will have more to write about.\'a0 At present I can scarcely make out a letter. Genl Thompson leaves tomorrow.\'a0 Mrs. Thompson & Eliza are not going as they intended to Edgefield.\'a0 I suppose you do not know yet, whether the Governor will pardon Mr. Wells. A Mr. Humphreys came yesterday to get some advice from you.\'a0 No letters have come, only the Charleston papers. Good night, my dear husband; act for the best interest of Greenville; gain all you can in the Appeals Court is the advice of Your affectionate Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

\f1\b 64
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Friday morning, 28 November 1845
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 The great event is over, & Susan is married.\'a0 We went to the church last night between 6 & 7.\'a0 Mamma invited a few more persons than at first she intended.\'a0 Mrs. Harrison, Mrs. Walker, Mrs. Dr. Earle.\'a0 Mr. McBee also invited more.\'a0 Mrs. Irvine, Mr. Swandale, Mr. Cline & some others.\'a0 Dr. Crook was there & Mr. Croft had to take your place & give away Susan after the ceremony was over.\'a0 Mrs. McBee\'92s family, Mr. Pinckney & his sister, Dr. Crook & myself returned to Mamma\'92s & spent the evening very pleasantly, in cutting up cake, wrapping it up, & directing it to our friends away, & also many in the village.\'a0 Susan has sent some by Mr. Elford this morning to Columbia to you, & also a peice to Mr. & Mrs. Martin, Mr. & Mrs. Taylor & Pinckney McBee which you must give to them.\'a0 You will not be able to eat the whole of your peice yourself, but you can divide it with your particular friends, particularly those from Greenville.\'a0 And oh! How I wish I could promise Susan so much happiness in the married state, as \ul I \ulnone have enjoyed.\'a0 I must say I have my \ul fear\ulnone , but I hope they will \ul never\ulnone  be \ul realized\ulnone .\'a0 I only wish she could be as happy as she deserves to be.\'a0 No one ever \ul deserved\ulnone  happiness more than she does. I read your letter in the Mountaineer this morning.\'a0 I liked it, except your comparison of Mr. Edwards manners to those of a womans.\'a0 I am sure women are not always \ul mild\ulnone  & \ul amiable\ulnone , but I suppose you judge of all, by your wife.\'a0 You must be careful & make no statement in your letter, but what is \ul perfectly\ulnone  \ul correct\ulnone .\'a0 You must write \ul good\ulnone  \ul letters\ulnone , & give all the information possible.\'a0 I am sure in Greenville, we would not know what was going on in Columbia, if it were not for you.\'a0 So you must do \ul well\ulnone  for your district this session.\'a0 The resolution of Mr. Henry\'92s about Seduction, is the one I have wished you to introduce.\'a0 Mr. Pinckney says he went to see Mr. Obed Wells yesterday, that he looks badly.\'a0 He had a relapse last Sunday.\'a0 Mr. Cleveland is very low, & it is thought cannot live very long.\'a0 I was very glad to hear from you Wednesday.\'a0 I hope to have that pleasure again tonight.\'a0 The Judges trunk had quite an amusing fate.\'a0 You may tell Mr. Martin that next winter certainly, I hope to visit Columbia & Charleston.\'a0 I am impatient to see my friends.\'a0 The hogs you will be glad to have heard are safely housed for the winter.\'a0 They were very small ones.\'a0 You may judge of their size by knowing, that their fat only made half a Can of good Lard & half a can of bad Lard.\'a0 Mr. Holcombe has not sent what you engaged from him.\'a0 I dare say he will soon.\'a0 Mrs. Griffin brought a few days ago, some Cider, which she said you engaged from her.\'a0 She had not enough apples to make the quantity you desired.\'a0 She brought only 15 gallons.\'a0 It seems good.\'a0 I have bought a \ul new\ulnone  spinning wheel for Maria at 1.50 & a pr of Cards 62 \'bd .\'a0 I begged Alexander McBee to send me a dollars worth of Cotton.\'a0 He says they are buying it at 7 cents a pound.\'a0 Jim says one of the worst bargains, you have lately made is March [&] that of the two he would rather have James, & that James is good for nothing.\'a0 He said if March works hard for 15 minutes, he complains of being sick, & seems overcome.\'a0 He says his sickness is \ul reality\ulnone  not \ul pretence\ulnone , that March says he has always been weakly.\'a0 Yesterday he was obliged to stay at home on account of pain in his stomach.\'a0 He told me this morning he was subject to it, since he was a child.\'a0 He looks weak, I am sorry for him, but still wish you to better yourself as soon as you can; exchange him if you can do no better for little negroes, as Mr. McNeely proposed.\'a0 I believe Rabe has \ul wilfully\ulnone  \ul cheated\ulnone  you, & if he was here you ought to see him.\'a0 After all the trouble you had about his case, you will have gained nothing.\'a0 I am provoked that you did not make him \ul pay\ulnone  you.\'a0 He has money, for he had sold property.\'a0 He is a \ul deceitful\ulnone  \ul creature\ulnone .\'a0 If you keep March he will be an expense to you, so you had better try & dispose of him & James as soon as possible.\'a0 I tell you this not to worry you, but as a peice of news, & you said I must tell you \ul everything\ulnone .\'a0 The children & myself are quite well.\'a0 Willie says he is learning fast so that he will be sure to have his knife.\'a0 I hope Mr. Elias Earle will be elected.\'a0 I am sorry for Mr. Ancrum too.\'a0 I do not think rich men ought to apply for office.\'a0 There should be a law against it.\'a0 I have no news to tell.\'a0 There is one peice of business which I would like you to attend to for me.\'a0 I would like you just to inquire the \ul price\ulnone  of some fruit, & let me know.\'a0 Perhaps I might like you\'a0 to send me up a little for my party, if it is \ul good\ulnone , & \ul cheap\ulnone , but if it was dear, I would not \ul think\ulnone  of getting it so don\'92t you get any, but in your next letter tell me the \ul price\ulnone , & also of Cocoa nuts.\'a0 I would be \ul provoked\ulnone  at your getting fruit at a high price.\'a0 What was sent Mamma from Charleston, was \ul cheap\ulnone , but is all decayed.\'a0 I thought perhaps in Columbia it might be cheap also.\'a0 I only wish for the present to know the \ul price\ulnone .\'a0 Mamma intends sending to Columbia perhaps tonight a box, containing cake for our friends, which you must send by the first opportunity to Charleston.\'a0 Your truly attached Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

\f1\b 65
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Sunday night, 30 November 1845
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received your letter by Mr. Cox, & it has given me great pleasure.\'a0 I am surprised at your not hearing from me last Friday.\'a0 I have written \ul every\ulnone  \ul Mail\ulnone  since your left.\'a0 The Post Master in Columbia must be careless, or there is carelessness somewhere.\'a0 You had better always go yourself.\'a0 If you do not receive my letters it is not worthwhile for me to write, & I do not like them to fall in any other hands, but the one for whom they were intended.\'a0 Though very busy, I did not \ul neglect\ulnone  \ul you\ulnone . I am glad you spent a pleasant day at Dr. Gibb[e]s.\'a0 You must accept all your invitations.\'a0 I wish I had given you the other pr of Shoes to carry down also to exhbibit.\'a0 The next time I will have something very [page smudged] to send.\'a0 I am going to work two beautiful patterns on velvet for Ottomans or stools.\'a0 Mr. Cox it is said is engaged, but not to be married for a year.\'a0 I suppose you have heard of the death of Mr. Wm Blassingame.\'a0 I \ul believe\ulnone  he died of Delirium Tremens.\'a0 Mr. Murphy told me, it was the \ul horrors\ulnone , or Tremens or some such thing he \ul heard\ulnone .\'a0 You did not think when you saw him Court week, he would die so soon.\'a0 I am sorry he is dead, for he was such a friend of yours.\'a0 I think persons acting as he did, are more to be pitied, than \ul blamed\ulnone , for he certainly could not control himself.\'a0 You say I must tell you everything, so I will mention every incident.\'a0 Maria has been sick with cold, fever & pain in her head & shoulders.\'a0 Jim came for Dr. Crook to go see her.\'a0 She is now better.\'a0 March still complains of pain in his stomach, & is not able to do anything.\'a0 I expect he needs medicine; He says he ought to take Calomel; so tomorrow I will send him to Dr. Earle or Crook to know what he ought to take.\'a0 James is as bad as ever.\'a0 Whenever I tell him to cut wood, he says March cuts it when he knows March has not been able to cut it.\'a0 James will be in the kitchen doing nothing, & I not able to have any wood.\'a0 It is best to have only one man in the yard, for when there are two, each leaves the work for the other to do. \'a0If you keep March he is so weakly, he will have to stay at home, to attend to the lot, drive the carri[a]ge & haul wood, & James must stay entirely at the farm.\'a0 I cannot bear him any longer.\'a0 If you keep him, he \ul shall\ulnone  \ul not\ulnone  be within my sight or call.\'a0 If he is, I will \ul sell\ulnone  him \ul without\ulnone  \ul your\ulnone  \ul leave\ulnone .\'a0 I hope you will meet with an opportunity in Columbia of disposing of him, but I rather think you will not, & it would be difficult getting him down, unless he went in the stage.\'a0 Jim & Charles have been cutting rails.\'a0 They will sow the Oats as soon as the ground can be ploughed.\'a0 It is now \ul frozen\ulnone .\'a0 We have had most \ul severe\ulnone  weather, & still have.\'a0 Yesterday Mr. Holcombe sent the hogs, 5 of them weighing altogether 983 pounds.\'a0 They are cut up, salted & put away.\'a0 There is no danger of their spoiling in this weather.\'a0 The Cider Mrs. Griffin brought is \ul very\ulnone  \ul nice\ulnone .\'a0 Mr. Pinckney preached today.\'a0 He leaves with his family tomorrow.\'a0 Susan & her \ul husband\ulnone  were at church.\'a0 As I looked at him at the foot of the pew, I could but contrast \ul his\ulnone  \ul appearance\ulnone  with \ul yours\ulnone , he looking like but I wont say it.\'a0 It is wrong to speak against my sisters husband.\'a0 I only hope \ul she\ulnone  will never think of him, as \ul I\ulnone  do, that she will remain blind to his failings, she \ul must\ulnone  think \ul well\ulnone  of him, or she would not have \ul married\ulnone  him, for she is an \ul upright\ulnone , \ul honorable\ulnone , \ul conscientious\ulnone  person, \ul confiding\ulnone , & \ul generous\ulnone , & \ul deserves\ulnone  as \ul good\ulnone  a \ul husband\ulnone  as \ul I\ulnone  \ul have\ulnone .\'a0 He has done well for himself, gained a comfortable home, & himself & his wife &\'85supported.\'a0 All he has to do is to pay his Tailors bill.\'a0 But do not my dear husband, ever \ul breathe\ulnone  a \ul word\ulnone  of what I say to you about him, & I wish \ul you\ulnone  \ul always\ulnone  to think \ul well\ulnone  of him.\'a0 Sometimes I am so unhappy when I think, that perhaps \ul Susan\ulnone  will be \ul unhappy\ulnone , but there is no appearance of unhappiness yet, & I \ul hope\ulnone  & \ul trust\ulnone  she will \ul never\ulnone  repent her choice, so do not mention ever what I have said.\'a0 Susan has been very liberal in distributing cake.\'a0 She has sent to a great many in Charleston, & all of her acquaintances here.\'a0 I hope you will receive your peice tonight.\'a0 I suppose Mr. Elford will have reached Columbia this evening.\'a0 Mr. Duncan is really obstinate.\'a0 Does \ul he\ulnone  wish Mr. Wells hung? Or think \ul public\ulnone  \ul opinion\ulnone  wishes it?\'a0 You ought to have introduced the resolution about the Chancelors decrees, for I have often heard you \ul express\ulnone  that opinion, so you ought to have had the credit of it.\'a0 Any law that you think would be of advantage, you should introduce \ul yourself\ulnone , & not wait for others to.\'a0 I see the Hoar question will be brought forward again, now my dear, I \ul beseech\ulnone  you not to take the part of \ul Massachuset[t]s\ulnone .\'a0 I have always been ashamed of the part you acted last winter, so do not do so again; rather agree with your state & give up your \ul one\ulnone  opinion to her, than wish to bring her round to you.\'a0 The minority should yield, & it seemed so strange for you to be differing from the whole Legislature.\'a0 Massachset[t]s has no good motive in sending her agents here, & she ought not to be encouraged in it, & if turning them away is \ul unconstitutional\ulnone , it ought to be \ul constitutional\ulnone .\'a0 I am sorry I did not know this question would be brought forward & advised you before you left, & so saved my paper.\'a0 However I hope the advice will not come \ul too\ulnone  \ul late\ulnone .\'a0 If you will act badly, do not \ul \'85ron\ulnone  in the \ul Mountaineer\ulnone , but keep it to yourself.\'a0 Your bad acts I wish concealed, not published to the world.\'a0 If you wish the reputation of being \ul independent\ulnone , you have acquired that already; so need not make yourself singular for that purpose.\'a0 Above all never do anything that has the \ul appearance\ulnone  of siding with the North against the South.\'a0 The people are so suspicious on that subject, & they judge from appearance, do not always understand the motive, therefore avoid the appearance of evil, acquiesce without any \ul fuss\ulnone  to what the legislature determines on.\'a0 If you \ul will\ulnone  object, object quietly & without any noise, but I hope you will agree with me.\'a0 I think I must have convinced you. if your good sense had not before.\'a0 You must take my advice in good part, for you know it is given for the purpose of making you act wisely & for the good of your constituents, & I being one of them, wish you to act for my good.\'a0 I do not wish for agents to be coming here from the North meddling with our concerns.\'a0 The children are well, & so am I.\'a0 Willie will write a postscript in my next letter; he is now asleep.\'a0 Frank speaks \ul constantly\ulnone  of you; they all love you \ul dearly\ulnone .\'a0 You ought to have told Mr. Henry his love for his wife, was not to be compared to yours for me, for that \ul I\ulnone  was a most \ul uncommon\ulnone  \ul wife\ulnone , very few to be compared to me.\'a0 I am glad you asked me about the Silk dress, before buying it, for it would have been useless.\'a0 I sent to town for it when Susan did.\'a0 It is beautiful, & only 1 dollar a yd.\'a0 I am to pay Mamma \ul gradually\ulnone  for it.\'a0 Instead of bringing me a dress, I would rather you give me the money to pay her at once.\'a0 I wrote to you to inquire about fruit.\'a0 I do not wish you to buy it.\'a0 I would be vexed if you did. I only wish to know the \ul price\ulnone , so if it is \ul cheap\ulnone ,\'a0 & I \ul wish\ulnone  it, I can send for it.\'a0 Last night I slept on a feather bed.\'a0 It is the first time I have been warm for a week.\'a0 I missed my stove, but with the feather bed I am very comfortable.\'a0 Good night, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

\f1\b 66
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Tuesday night, 2 December 1845
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have been waiting near two hours for Willie to copy the postscript which you will see at the end of this letter.\'a0 It is his own composition as you will perceive.\'a0 I write at night, because in the day, I meet with so many interruptions.\'a0 In all probability I would seldom\'a0 be able to finish a letter before the Mail closed.\'a0 I have very little to write about.\'a0 Maria is still sick, but is better.\'a0 Jim says it is cold; that at one time she will wear Shoes stockings; & another time go barefooted; & that she is so headstrong, she will not mind him.\'a0 He went for her Grandmother to come & nurse her.\'a0 She said she would come.\'a0 I sent Lindy out yesterday to stay with her.\'a0 In a few days I suppose she will be well.\'a0 I think colds are prevalent.\'a0 March is better.\'a0 He went to the farm today.\'a0 Jim thinks he is of \ul no\ulnone  \ul account\ulnone , even when well.\'a0 As long as he is so delicate, he had better stay at home & do the light work, & I will have more comfort in him as a Coachman than James.\'a0 James can stay at the farm; & under Charles & Jims superintendence he will do more work than he does here; & rid you of a great worriment.\'a0 It rained Sunday night & was thawing all yesterday; so Jim thought today he would be able to plant the oats.\'a0 He carried the seed to the farm, but the weather became so severely cold again, that the ground is frozen, & he has not been able to.\'a0 He will plant them as soon as the ground will admit of ploughing.\'a0 He & Charles say the wheat, rye & barley have come up beautifully.\'a0 The sows they turned out, & they went back with their pigs to Mr. Watson\'92s.\'a0 Jim went for them today.\'a0 He says he will make a pen for them outside the farm near Charles house, & let the pigs run about in the woods.\'a0 He & Charles both think when the Sows get fat they had better be killed.\'a0 For that they will continue going back to Mr. Watsons, & get lost or be stolen.\'a0 Charles says this was the case with some Mr. Rowland once bought, so you can think about it, & then determine.\'a0 This is the coldest weather I have almost ever felt.\'a0 I can do hardly anything but sit by the fire & warm myself.\'a0 Mr. Cleveland died this morning.\'a0 I have not been to Mamma\'92s since Friday.\'a0 I had the pleasure today of a visit from Mr. Luther.\'a0 Miss McBee sent Sunday night to know if I had heard from you, & how you & Pinckney were.\'a0 She thought of \ul course\ulnone  you had mentioned \ul him\ulnone ; so you had better in future say something about him; that I may be able to answer the inquiries of the family satisfactorily.\'a0Have you not the least idea whether the Governor will pardon Mr. Wells.\'a0 I hope all those who promised to speak to him on the subject will not forget it.\'a0 You must do what you can.\'a0 I think Dr. Gibb[e]s has been quite attentive to you.\'a0 I do not know what is going on in the Legislature at this particular time. So will not be able to give you my usual quota of advice.\'a0 I hope you are sensible of your great loss.\'a0 I did not understand what you alluded to, in, \'93Mr. Calhoun\'92s course at the Memphis Convention.\'94\'a0 I have not read the proceedings of that meeting, nor Mr. Calhoun\'92s speech, knowing it would be very uninteresting.\'a0 Does the Legislature disapprove of his course?\'a0 I believe there is no news at all in Greenville except Mr. Clevelands death which I have mentioned.\'a0 I think the village looks very dull.\'a0 You ought to be thankful to be away at this dull season & enjoying the society of \ul congenial\ulnone  \ul spirits\ulnone , a pleasure you so seldom have.\'a0 Yes my dear, I am \ul thankful\ulnone  that \ul sometimes\ulnone  you can associate with your \ul equals\ulnone .\'a0 Your letters give me great pleasure.\'a0 They are my \ul comfort\ulnone  in your absence.\'a0 It is well they are not so few & far between as Mrs. Henry\'92s.\'a0 Suisan has not sent the box of cake yet that I mentioned to you.\'a0 She must soon or it will be \ul stale\ulnone .\'a0 The Miss Andersons have gone to Alabama.\'a0 They have a brother and sister in law living there, both in very bad health.\'a0 The brother wrote word that he did not think either his Wife or himself would live long, & if they died, wished his sisters to take charge of their only child, so they have gone on, to take the child if the parents die, & I suppose stay with them in the meantime.\'a0 I hope you will receive my letters more regularly.\'a0 I have written every Mail, & intend to unless I am absolutely prevented by business.\'a0 Ann has borne Susans marriage well.\'a0 Caroline Reinhardt stays with her a great deal, & she finds her a great comfort.\'a0 The children are well.\'a0 Willie was at Mammas last Sunday.\'a0 Mr. Ervin was there.\'a0 He took Willie on his knee, & said he was the best boy in school.\'a0 Frank talks sweetly.\'a0 Edward says Mr. Town[e]s is having the holes dug for the fence between our lots.\'a0 I am afraid he will dig the holes a \ul little\ulnone  \ul too\ulnone  \ul near\ulnone  \ul this\ulnone  \ul way\ulnone  a few feet or so.\'a0 I expect that is the reason he is doing it while you are away.\'a0 A Museum & two English Reviews came last Mail, no letters, & no one has been to see you, but your black client & Mrs. Humphreys.\'a0 I have put down the old dining room carpet in my chamber, & it looks quite comfortable; at any rate \ul feels\ulnone  so.\'a0 It is\'85in about 50 places.\'a0 If chance throws you in his way, or you can make the chance, you must become acquainted with my cousin Wm H. Heyward.\'a0 Uncle Arthur thinks him a remarkably fine young man, & his Mother Mrs. Keith is such an affectionate relative.\'a0 Mr. McBee told me he heard the state would take stock in the rail road, one \ul third\ulnone  I \ul believe\ulnone .\'a0 You have doubtless seen many from Greenville before now.\'a0 Tom Butler, Wm Rowland, Mr. Elford , Genl Thompson & others, tell the two former & any other young men you see, to come back to attend the parties here.\'a0 Good night, Your \ul attached\ulnone  wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\

