\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Sunday night, 7 December 1845
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received a letter from you, & as usual it has given me great pleasure.\'a0 You ought to have attended the Governors ball.\'a0 If it was only for a little while, it would have given you so much to talk about to me.\'a0 If all the persons who promised to speak to the Governor \ul had\ulnone  done \ul so\ulnone , I am certain he would have \ul no\ulnone  \ul hesitation\ulnone  in pardoning Wells.\'a0 I am afraid they have not performed their promises.\'a0 If you would only get the Judge to say as he did to you, that he \ul ought\ulnone  to be pardoned, I am sure he would.\'a0 Do tell Mr. Duncan what the Judge said & ask him if he is not ashamed, & tell him if he thinks it will increase his popularity, the refusing to sign he is mistaken, & even if it did, would he for the sake of \ul popularity\ulnone , hang a \ul man\ulnone .\'a0 I am sorry he is one of the Delegation.\'a0 I hope the Governor will not be influenced by him.\'a0 Do bring back Mr. Wells pardon in your packet.\'a0 Margaret told me Col. Dawkins wife expected to increase her family.\'a0 If so how \ul pleased\ulnone  he must be.\'a0 He must feel as if he had just commenced life.\'a0 I thank you for your liberality in sending so much fruit.\'a0 I am anxious to receive it.\'a0 It will add greatly to my supper, in appearance, & value.\'a0 Miss McBee gives her party next Wednesday.\'a0 I intend giving mine the Friday following.\'a0 As the Legislature adjourns so soon, I am hesitating whether to put it off until Thursday the night after you return.\'a0 I think it would be respectful to you, & a proper welcome for you.\'a0 If I thought it would give you pleasure to be at it, I would not hesitate a moment.\'a0 My only motive for having it during your absence, is that you dislike parties, & would prefer being away.\'a0 Oh for a magnetic telegraph that I might this instant consult you & know which you prefer.\'a0 I would \ul rather \ulnone you should be present, & yet I am afraid that \ul you\ulnone  will \ul dislike\ulnone  it.\'a0 My only resource will be to consult Mamma & Susan.\'a0 When you left, I expected to have it \ul immediately\ulnone .\'a0 Miss McBee requested me to put it off, until her friend came, as it has been put off so long it will make no difference to put it off a little longer.\'a0 My only hesitation is whether you will like it or not. Willie is disappointed at not hearing from you.\'a0 I told him he would hear tonight.\'a0 Frank is so interesting.\'a0 Willie said to him the other day, Frank I am going to whip Lindy.\'a0 Frank replied, \'93 you shant ip my \'85.\'94\'a0 This morning in bed he pressed his arm hard on my face.\'a0 I called to him loudly to move his arm.\'a0 He commenced crying & said, \'93I tell Pa, Pa ip Ma.\'94\'a0 I would tell you many sweet sayings of his, but have not room.\'a0 They all look healthy.\'a0 Willie is a fine boy.\'a0 Anna is very affectionate.\'a0 If our children only turn out well, we will have great cause for thankfulness.\'a0 I dined at Mamma\'92s today.\'a0 Mr. McBee appeared quite well.\'a0 I hope marriage will improve him.\'a0 I liked him better than usual today.\'a0 Susan was sick in bed yesterday with a bad headache.\'a0 She was up today.\'a0 There was no preaching in any church, so I rode with the children to the farm after breakfast, to see Maria, who is still sick, but better than she was.\'a0 Dr. Crook is attending her.\'a0 March seems quite well again.\'a0 They have been planting Oats.\'a0 Lindy has returned home, & I have sent Mary to the farm to attend on Maria.\'a0 A drove of Negroes passed through today.\'a0 I wish you had been here to exchange James.\'a0 I saw the Drover in the road\'a0 & asked him what he would exchange him for.\'a0 He said a woman & two children, & you pay something to boot.\'a0 He will be back in the Spring.\'a0 I received a note from Pamela yesterday by Maj. Eddins.\'a0 She has given me no invitation this winter to visit her.\'a0 I am glad of it, for on account of my party being put off so long, I could not have accepted it, & now I will not be obliged to ask her to stay with me next summer.\'a0 What shall I say to your extravagance.\'a0 315 dollars in books.\'a0 I can only say it would have been wiser to have extinguished one debt, before you contracted another.\'a0 At this rate there is no hopes of my going to town next winter.\'a0 There ought to be a general rejoicing among the Lawyers in Greenville, as they all have access to your books.\'a0 However I am willing they should, I like to be obliging; only I am sorry after incurring so great an expense, you are not compensated for it by enjoying any superior advantage.\'a0As you are a member of the Legislature, you ought to become acquainted with all the members.\'a0 Mrs. Keith has spoken highly of you in all her letters, so I would like you to become acquainted with her son Mr. Heyward.\'a0 Be sociable.\'a0 It would much improve you.\'a0 Behave your \ul most\ulnone  \ul agreeable\ulnone , when you go to see Mrs. Martin & Mrs. Taylor.\'a0 Tell them I will go down next winter.\'a0 I am glad you are so busy.\'a0 From your being \ul homesick\ulnone , I was afraid you were \ul idle\ulnone , & had very little to employ you.\'a0 Do not forget to go to the person from whom you got the Candle[page torn] & get the Snuffers.\'a0 I expect it was Veal, Glaze or Mordecai, but I should think you would recollect.\'a0 Butler Thompson ought to be ashamed to go to Columbia, where he owes so much money.\'a0 I wonder they do not hold him to bail.\'a0 I am glad you were appointed to examine the Law students, for I think it quite a \ul compliment\ulnone .\'a0 Another English Review has come for you but no letters, & no one has come to see you.\'a0 Greenville looks very dull.\'a0 I know of no news.\'a0 Mrs. Jones sent for Mrs. Fabers keys.\'a0 I suppose they have bought the place.\'a0 Mr. Jones is in Georgia.\'a0 I would like to know if Mr. Earle is elected.\'a0 I see his brother in law has been.\'a0 Alston seems to manage Mamma\'92s business now, remarkably well.\'a0 Aunt Mary Hayne writes word, that she is in such bad health, that she would not be surprised at any moment that she died.\'a0 I hope you will be successful in your appeal cases.\'a0 You ought to make arrangements with Mr. Bauskett to pay you.\'a0 March drove me today, & did quite well.\'a0 If you keep him, he must be the coachman.\'a0 James had better work entirely at the farm, under Jim & Charles.\'a0 He will do more than any other way.\'a0 He wont do the work on the lot, & it is useless to have both March & him here.\'a0 The Cows are not driven off now, because there is no good pasture for them.\'a0 Yours, E.F.P. Do not come home until the Legislature adjourns, or I wont be glad to see you, after that I will.\
\'a0\

\f1\b 71\
Monday,
\f0\b0  \
\
	I wrote to Mamma & Susan this morning to consult them whether it were best to put off the party.\'a0 They & Mr. McBee think of course it ought to be.\'a0 As we pay you the compliment, I hope you will be pleased.\'a0 I believe no wife would give a party only a few days before her husband\'92s return instead of waiting for his arrival.\'a0 So we will welcome you home cheerfully.\'a0 All the preparations will be made during your absence.\'a0 You will not be troubled with them, & the night after your arrival it shall be.\'a0 You will have an opportunity of meeting many of your constituents & telling them the news.\'a0 So I hope my dear husband you will appreciate our motive & feel the compliment.\'a0 As so many gentleman have their wives with them in Columbia, it cannot be very troublesome attending to them, so next Winter you must have Willie with you.\'a0 He will be worth showing.\'a0 Susan wrote me such a kind note about you that I enclose it for you to read.\'a0 It will be worth the postage 5 cts.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 72
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Wednesday morning, 10 December [1845]
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I was not able to write you last night, & this morning I am so busy, I will be able to write you but a few lines.\'a0 Miss McBee\'92s party is this evening.\'a0 I am glad mine is put off, for it will take all this week to prepare for the cooking next week, & I think it would have been very strange to have had it \ul just\ulnone  \ul before\ulnone  your return.\'a0 I hope this evening to hear from you that Mr. Wells is \ul pardoned\ulnone , & to carry the good news with me to the party.\'a0 In the consultation with the Delegates last Saturday, I suppose the Governor decided what to do, & I can hardly think he has \ul refused\ulnone  to pardon him.\'a0 If he has we must get up some stronger petitions, & all of us \ul write\ulnone  to him, & even send a Committee to intercede with him.\'a0 Mr. Earle I should think would be here tonight.\'a0 I hope he has not had the fate of Mr. Wigfall, who I \ul regret\ulnone  \ul exceedingly\ulnone  to here [hear] has been beaten by Mr. Black.\'a0 I suppose it is dreadful to be opposed by a Black.\'a0 They get everything they wish. The fruit & nuts arrived last Monday, & in good order.\'a0 It will be quite an accession to my supper.\'a0 Mr. Luther McBee had promised me two pigs.\'a0 He finds he has none young enough, so instead has sent me\'85pounds of Flour.\'a0 I am going to fatten two of yours, & also two Turkeys.\'a0 Vardry McBee & Mrs. Alexander sister in law of Mrs. McBee\'92s arrived yesterday from N. Carolina.\'a0 Mrs. Alexander is a sister of Mr. Clark in Columbia, who is the step father of Miss Scott.\'a0 Vardry McBee & her son were at Mamma\'92s last night.\'a0 Alexander McBee has been there twice, which is something wonderful for him.\'a0\'a0 I think they seem a fine family, & I begin to like Mr. Luther very much.\'a0 Last Sunday afternoon Susan & myself rode by to Mrs. McBee\'92s & we did not get out.\'a0 We only went to ask a question.\'a0 Old Mr. McBee came to the carri[a]ge.\'a0 He looked smiling & pleased.\'a0 He said he must have an introduction, for he did not know us apart.\'a0 I told him \ul I\ulnone  was his daughter in law, so he shook hands with me & said \'94howdy do Susan\'94, I am glad to see you, & Miss Malinda said he would have kissed me, if I had been nearer.\'a0 Afterwards Susan told him, that she was the one. We are quite well.\'a0 Maria is a great deal better, getting well.\'a0 We will all be glad to see you, next Wednesday.\'a0 I believe I have told you all you are to get.\'a0 Two presents for Susan, for you & me to give her, a present for Ann, Knife for Willie, Drum & Whip for Frank.\'a0 He speaks often of his Drum & Ip, & anything you choose for Anna.\'a0 I will write but once more to you & hear three times more from you.\'a0 I must now close my letter.\'a0 There is no news to write about.\'a0 Your affectionate wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 73
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Thursday night, 11 December 1845
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have taken up my pen to write you my last letter.\'a0 I will hear twice more from you, & then I hope to see you, as the Legislature adjourns Monday.\'a0 I received a letter from you last night, just before I went to Miss McBee\'92s party.\'a0 Everybody who spoke to me, asked if I had heard from you lately.\'a0 I told them I had just heard, & then informed them of the news.\'a0 Dr. Crook said I was the \ul only\ulnone  one you let hear from you, for you had not written to him or anyone else, & that Mr. Wells was complaining of you.\'a0 How my dear husband have you been so neglectful.\'a0 I believe I told you before you went to write to persons, particularly when so interesting a subject as the Rail road, they wished to be informed on, for all the gentlemen last night seemed to take a deep interest in the Rail Road.\'a0 I you had written \ul long\ulnone  letters for the Mountaineer, there would have been some excuse for your not writing to others, but you have not done that.\'a0 You have not informed the people of all that was going on, for I have never known you to write such short & inferior letters as you have this time.\'a0 It is well you took my advice, & have written a longer one for tomorrows paper, & now \ul take\ulnone  \ul my\ulnone  \ul advice\ulnone  \ul again\ulnone , & as soon as you have read this letter, sit down & employ yourself Sunday night, & as much of Monday as you can spare, in writing another \ul long\ulnone  \ul letter\ulnone  for the Mountaineer.\'a0 Try & make up by the \ul two\ulnone  \ul last\ulnone  \ul letters\ulnone , for the inferiority of the two first.\'a0 Tell all that has been done in the Legislature that you think the people would like to know.\'a0 I am sure you can find enough to write about.\'a0 I bet you Mr. Henry has.\'a0 I have been extremely mortified on this subject.\'a0 You generally have written such good letters, so now take my advice, & write one more good letter, but do not say anything in favor of Mr. Hoar.\'a0 The Miss Harrisons were here this afternoon.\'a0 They said from what Mr. Reinhardt said, they did not think much Rail Road stock would be taken in Charleston, on account of some of the Greenville members not have taken an active part in it, that Mr. Walker & Mrs. Duncan had not, that they heard Mr. Duncan was afraid of his popularity.\'a0 I now think Mr. Duncan one of the \ul meanest\ulnone  men I know of.\'a0 What a pity he ever quitted the shades of private life, where his meanness he might have concealed.\'a0 He is on a footing with my next door neighbor.\'a0 If he only knew it he has injured himself more by refusing to sign Mr. Wells petition than he has gained.\'a0 Mr. McBee says he will never vote for him again, & I expect many others will not.\'a0 Dr. Crook spoke of him last night; said he told you he knew he would not sign it.\'a0 I am so sorry you have not written letters to Dr. Crook & others as I told you.\'a0 I wish I were near you constantly to give you advice.\'a0 You would do much better.\'a0 You need me, instead of being like Mr. Duncan, politic.\'a0 You are the most \ul impolitic\ulnone  person I ever knew.\'a0 Do in future do better.\'a0 The Governor has really taken \ul long\ulnone  to consider Mr. Wells case.\'a0 Of course he cannot refuse pardoning him.\'a0 You must bring the pardon home with you.\'a0 Ask him for it.\'a0 You said in your letter last night, you wish you could return with Mr. Earle, in time to be at my party.\'a0 I am doubly pleased at having put it off.\'a0 I do not think Mr. Earle has returned.\'a0 I have not heard from him or my bundle, which if he had come, I think he would have sent.\'a0 I am sorry for his disappointment.\'a0 Everybody is astonished, that a man so well off as Mr. Maxwell should have run.\'a0 Mrs. Thompson says she is \ul glad\ulnone  Mr. [Louis Trezevant] Wigfall is not elected, because he had no business to live so extravagantly.\'a0 I expect she is not glad on \ul that\ulnone  \ul account\ulnone , but because he killed Mr. [Thomas]\'a0 Bird.\'a0 I enjoyed my self very much at the party.\'a0 It was one of the pleasantest I have been at.\'a0 In the first place I was dressed very nicely, which made me feel \ul comfortable\ulnone .\'a0 I had on a beautiful silk which I told you I had sent to town for, also a \ul beautiful\ulnone  \ul sash\ulnone , which \ul Susan\ulnone  had sent to town for.\'a0 It was not becoming to her, & as it was to \ul me\ulnone , I took it from her.\'a0 It was the admiration of the room.\'a0 It is such an uncommon looking one, that it strikes attention.\'a0 When I first went in, I sat by Mrs. Pearson.\'a0 She is a \ul great\ulnone  \ul flatterer\ulnone .\'a0 She told me if you were to hear the compliments that were constantly paid me, you would be very jealous.\'a0 She told Susan last summer, that \ul I\ulnone  was the \ul belle\ulnone  of Greenville.\'a0 Certainly I am the most \ul unconscious\ulnone  belle.\'a0 I am the belle at any rate of the only one I care to be, my husband.\'a0 You will be astonished at the nice party I am going to give.\'a0 When it was first proposed, Mamma was to pay the expenses, & that will consist\'a0 in the purchase of Butter & Eggs, which I have paid for, & paying the servants who assist.\'a0 Almost everything I have in the house, the expenses we now incur will not be much.\'a0 20 or 30 dollars at least will cover them.\'a0 Willie wishes to add a postscript.\'a0 He was very much pleased with his letter.\'a0 We are all well, & I will be delighted to see you.\'a0 Do not forget the snuffers for the candle sticks, the presents for Susan & Ann.\'a0 I would like you to bring me one dozen Lemons to make Lemonade for my party.\'a0 It is so much better than Lemon Syrup, which I would have to buy.\'a0 I am obliged to you for the fruit you have sent me.\'a0 Pinckney McBee, Butler & Harriet did not arrive in time for the party, & I do not know whether they have yet.\'a0 Mr. Luther is very much provoked at Pinckneys not having come.\'a0 Pinckney thought they would have waited for him,\'a0 but as the preparations were made they did not.\'a0 I got a long letter from Pamela last night.\'a0 She does not invite me to see her.\'a0 Says she hopes I will go when she is better.\'a0 I expect she is in reality too sick for company.\'a0 She says children & talking disturb her.\'a0 I have no pencil to write Willies letter for him, so will write for him what he tells me.\'a0 E.F.P.\'a0 \
