\f1\b 75
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Thursday night, [26 March 1846]
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received your letter last night, & was very much pleased to hear from you.\'a0 I can scarcely afford the time to write you even a few lines.\'a0 I am in the midst of housecleaning, & you cannot imagine the confusion that reigns all over the house.\'a0 It is worse even than usual for generally I have had only \ul two\ulnone  rooms & the Entries whitewashed but this time I am having the whole house, but Mr. Wallace being obliged to go on & do one room immediately after the other, allowing me no time to fix, every part of the house is in the utmost confusion.\'a0 Tonight we sleep in the large chamber.\'a0 I am glad you are away, & if you are only careful, take care of yourself & come back safe, I will be thankful that your absence is prolonged longer than usual, for I believe in a fortnight, we will only have \ul commenced\ulnone  getting in order, & I have very little assistance, only Delia & Mary today.\'a0 When I told Minerva I wanted her to help, she said she could not leave her child in the kitchen.\'a0 Charlotte & John would kill it, & this evening when I told her, I could not have believed she would have sat in the kitchen all the afternoon doing nothing, when even her mistress was in the house working hard.\'a0 She said, cleaning the house was not her business.\'a0 Her place was in the kitchen.\'a0 Eliza I have been obliged to let iron, so that Delia might assist me.\'a0 March tonight helped move some of the Furniture.\'a0 He is most obliging.\'a0 I like him very much.\'a0 I much prefer him to Jim, because he has such a good temper, but Jim is a valuable servant, but is so often ill natured.\'a0 Monday morning Jim planted the Yam potatoes.\'a0 After that it rained so much & the next day they were not able to do anything.\'a0 It rained almost incessantly Monday & Tuesday.\'a0 Yesterday Jim & March ploughed the lot where your office is, & planted the Lucerne, & also ploughed the middle lot.\'a0 Today at the farm, they were building the fence.\'a0 March said it was too wet to plant the Corn.\'a0 I dare say they will do their duty, while you are away.\'a0 Mamma & myself hear constantly from Susan.\'a0 She seems satisfied & contented & Mr. McBee she thinks a great deal happier there, than he was at Mamma\'92s, & I do not wonder at I;, & his associates also she thinks much better than those here, for though plain, they are all worthy persons.\'a0 Alexander is almost constantly with him, & Pinckney very often.\'a0 Mr. Bigham is so kind & generous.\'a0 Susan wrote today, that he had made her a present of a gold pen.\'a0 He insisted upon her taking it.\'a0 Susan says the\'85with such good worthy persons, is preferable to the heartless intercourse of the village.\'a0 She seems to appreciate the quiet retreat she has found, so I hope she will remain.\'a0 In her letter to me today, she said she felt to you as she would to an own brother.\'a0 I think she & Mamma value you a great deal more than they did, since they have come in contact with \ul others\ulnone  of the\'a0 Male sex & seen how far superior \ul you\ulnone  were to them.\'a0 They now have more confidence in your judgement, & are more willing to be guided by you.\'a0 Perhaps it would be well if you were to write a letter to Susan, a \ul kind\ulnone  one, giving her all the advice you think she needs, encouraging her to perform the duties devolved on her to persevere in remaining where she is, speaking well of Mr. McBee, & I think she would consider it as a mark of friendship, take it kindly, & be benefitted by it.\'a0 Let \ul me\ulnone  have the reading of it \ul first\ulnone .\'a0 Mr. McBee thinks \ul me\ulnone  \ul perfection\ulnone , \ul looks\ulnone , \ul manners\ulnone  & everything, & that therefore I ought to like him.\'a0 Mamma in one of her notes to me, speaking of Susan & Mr. M said Susan did not expect to marry one like \ul you\ulnone , for \ul you\ulnone  were an \ul exception\ulnone , so for the \ul first\ulnone  time, I told her, (in answering the note) my \ul real\ulnone  \ul opinion\ulnone  of you.\'a0 I said you \ul were\ulnone  an \ul exception\ulnone , that we might look\'85in vain to find your equal, that I knew of no fault you had, & though by Christians, you would not be called a Christian, you were more perfect than any Christian I knew of.\'a0 So now what do you say to that,\'a0 The children are well, but are obliged to be rather neglected now.\'a0 As I look at them covered with dirt, I think the housecleaning is no advantage to them, they will require some cleaning & putting in order too.\'a0 Willie has been learning today a peice of poetry to speak tomorrow.\'a0 Frank today, said to me, \'93I want horse to go to Factory.\'94\'a0 I said, very well get me.\'a0 I thought he was joking.\'a0 He went out of the room, & after awhile, he came back & said \'93there\'92s no horse.\'94\'a0 I said where have you been.\'a0 He said, \'93to stable,\'94 & the little fellow had really been all the way to the stable to see if there was a hose there.\'a0 Do not be uneasy about us.\'a0 We are getting on quite well.\'a0 I hope you will be able to go & see your Mother before you return, for you are so much nearer to her now, than you are in Greenville, that you may not find it convenient to leave home to go see her, for a long time.\'a0 It has been very inconvenient to me to write tonight.\'a0 I do not think I will be able to write by anyone going to Pickens, unless someone goes Monday, & then I would write to you Sunday, so do not be disappointed if you do not hear.\'a0 I will have Tuesday, to get the house fixed somewhat in order before Sunday.\'a0 I have not a particle of news to tell you.\'a0 There is none in the Mountaineer which came this evening.\'a0 It is past 10 oclock, the children are all asleep.\'a0 Only one more letter has come for you, from Mr. Miller\'85candidate for Bursar, the Literary Messenger & the Union have come.\'a0 Mr. Luther gave me at the Factory \'bd a ream of Letter paper.\'a0 I\'a0 had no idea it was such an extensive establishment.\'a0 Old Mr. McBee is about building there a Woolen Factory.\'a0 Yours &c, Liz\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Anderson Court House\
\'a0\

\f1\b 76
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Wednesday morning, 6 May 1846
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have taken my seat in the library, to perform my promise of writing to you by tonights Mail.\'a0 You have left here so recently that of course I have nothing to tell you.\'a0 I have not been anywhere, & have seen no one.\'a0 We are all well.\'a0 Mary worked all day in the garden yesterday, & hoed all of the beds.\'a0 She made great havoc among the strawberries, Edward & herself, for in the morning, I observed a great many almost ripe, & in the evening, I could discover not one.\'a0 Today I have sent her to the farm, & will let her remain there the rest of the week, without coming home at night, so that she can commence working early in the morning.\'a0 Today Delia will finish ironing, & tomorrow go on with the garden.\'a0 Eliza is still at Mamma\'92s .\'a0 This is the third day she has been there.\'a0 March took the Mare to the farm yesterday, but left it at home today, said they had no use for it there.\'a0 I was downstairs this morning by half past 5 oclock.\'a0 I was in the garden, & worked an hour until 6, when we had breakfast.\'a0 The house was all fixed & dinner given out by 8 oclock.\'a0 So you see how industrious I am.\'a0 I think I will earn the use of the horses on Saturday\'a0 I sent the money to Mamma yesterday.\'a0 She wrote word she was very glad to have it.\'a0 Susan\'92s headache was better, & she says she will stay with me before she goes back to the Factory.\'a0 As I told you, I have nothing to write about, & I am very busy, have a whole basket of clothes to mend, besides other work.\'a0 I do not expect to write to you again until Monday, when I will answer the letter, I hope to receive from you Sunday night; so unless I have something in particular to write about, you will not hear from me again until Wednesday.\'a0 I hope & trust you will reach Columbia in safety this evening.\'a0 Take care of yourself, for the sake of your wife & children, to whom you are justly so dear, so important., gain as many cases as possible in the appeals Court, particularly try your best for Dr. Croft.\'a0 You have the measure of Willie\'92s head.\'a0 You know what kind of hat can be got for him in Greenville, so you can judge whether they are cheaper in Columbia.\'a0 I should think they would have a much better assortment there than here.\'a0 In general I like wide rims to keep off the wind, but I will leave it to your taste, to do as you think best.\'a0 The hat, the ball,\'85 & books for Willie, & the India rubber for me, is all that I wish you to purchase at present.\'a0 The India rubber may be elastic, so as to cut in strips, to stretch & put between the teeth.\'a0 If you can \ul afford\ulnone  it, perhaps you had better purchase a dozen small knives; our large ones are quite good, & we can do without a carving knife.\'a0 We have a good carving fork, so the dozen small knives is all that I care for, or that is necessary for you to get.\'a0 If you were to happen to see Mrs. Taylor, I really would be obliged to you if you would ask her to cut out for me & send me a picture of a suit of clothes such as boys of Willie\'92s age wear.\'a0 I believe I have told you all my wishes now.\'a0 I hope you may be able to get the money Mr. Chaplin owes you.\'a0 I wish you could pay your bookstore bill, but that I suppose is impossible.\'a0 I must now bid you adieu my dear husband, believe me as ever, Your truly attached wife, Liz\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 77
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Monday morning, 11 May 1846
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I do not know whether to be most provoked or uneasy at your silence.\'a0 How would you serve me so, as not to let me hear from you last night, unless you are sick, which I hope & trust you are not.\'a0 You have no excuse, for never mind how engaged; you would be spared a few moments to tell me you had arrived safely, & were quite well.\'a0 You do not deserve that I should write to you by this Mail, not having heard from you, & were it not, that I dread your feeling the same anxiety that I do now, I would not.\'a0 If I do not hear by Wednesday\'92s Mail, I will be miserable indeed.\'a0 It is \ul cruel\ulnone  in you to keep me in such suspense.\'a0 I did not think you would be so unkind.\'a0 I do not even know if you have reached Columbia in safety.\'a0 However I must hope for the best.\'a0 I will now tell you all that has occurred since I last wrote.\'a0 We have a great deal of rain, so that not much ploughing has been done at your farm, but they have been replanting & hoeing.\'a0 The Rye looks well, and the Corn better.\'a0 No Cattle have been jumping the fences.\'a0 Mary was at the farm the greater part of last week.\'a0 Today she is with Delia washing, but tomorrow I will send her out, to remain for the rest of the week.\'a0 Very little has been done in our garden on account of the rain, which keeps the ground constantly wet.\'a0 It has been weeded once.\'a0 The walks have not yet been cleaned.\'a0 As soon this week as Delia gets through her ironing, she shall work in it.\'a0 I am sorry to tell you that Jim & Maria are getting along very badly.\'a0 Yesterday afternoon Maria\'92s mother Winny came to me crying, & said she heard Jim had been abusing Maria, had beat her, broke her head, & her face, & the flies had blown it, & she said her Master would take Maria back any time.\'a0 I told her I did not believe all that, but I was going to the farm then, & would see about it.\'a0 So when I went I found Jims abuse of her had been exaggerated.\'a0 Maria was alone in the house, everything about her filthy, the floor not even swept, the\'85pails &c. all dirty.\'a0 She showed me a scar on her neck, where Jim had struck her.\'a0 I talked to her, & gave her some good advice, about doing better.\'a0 I then went on to Charles house & there saw Jim, & told him Maria\'92s mother had been to me.\'a0 He said he had struck Maria about 3 blows, that it was not half she deserved, that she was the worst creature that was & that her mother, father, Mr. Cauble & everybody knew it, that he knew Mr. Cauble would not take her back, for they were delighted to get rid of her, that Mrs. Cauble said she could not make her do anything at all, that people told him about her before he married her, that he felt when he married her, that he was doing wrong, but somehow was forced to do it, that she behaved so audaciously just after she was married, that her father stripped her & gave her 100 lashes so Maria told him, that she is obstinate & mulish, & lazy & dirty, that she wont clean the house, & wash his clothes or mend them, nor even wash hers, that their meals she would give them in dirty plates that they had eaten peas in days before, the peas all sticking to them, that often he had to neglect his work in the field, to clean the house & wash the dishes, that he was sorry when you bought Maria, that at that time he had taken all of his clothes away from her room & had them in the carri[a]ge house, & given or almost given her up, that as you wished to purchase her, he made no objection, & was in hopes when he got her to the farm away from her family she might do better, that she was worse than James, if you watched James he would work, but Maria you could not make work. & the more you coaxed & tried to please her the worse she was, she would not hoe or do anything.\'a0 Charles corroborated all he said.\'a0 I told Jim as Winny said Mr. Cauble would take Maria back, to ask Mr. Cauble to come & speak to me, for though I would not act in your absence, I would like to know if he would.\'a0 So Mr. Cauble came this morning, & to my great sorrow said, Winny has no authority for saying what she did, that nothing would induce him to take Maria back, not if he were given 5 negroes along with her, & he described her character \ul precisely\ulnone  as Jim had done, says Mrs. Cauble would not have her on any account, that she has\'85learn her \ul nothing\ulnone , that she is mulish, lazy obstinate & so on, that he would not have her in the yard, that he told you what she was when you bought her, that she could do \ul nothing\ulnone , not even spin.\'a0 If he did tell you all this I think it was \ul astonishing\ulnone  you should think of buying her, & such a high price for a worthless negro.\'a0 I want her sold to the first drover who passes.\'a0 Jim says through he loves & respects you & would rather belong to you than anyone else, rather than be with Maria he would like you to sell him.\'a0 He says Maria can work if she \ul chooses\ulnone , but she wont & that you are not strict enough with your servants.\'a0 You don\'92t make them work, & Mr. Cauble says you are not a good manager of servants, & \ul I\ulnone  have always said that.\'a0 Now I have done with Maria, hoping you will sell her as soon as possible.\'a0 I have \ul never\ulnone  \ul liked\ulnone  her.\'a0 Elias, Mr. Cauble says you would be pleased with, & if Col. Dunham is willing he will sell him for 600 dollars, but about this I will give no advice.\
\'a0\

\f1\b 78\
Saturday 
\f0\b0 \
\
	I had the horses & paid with Miss McBee & Reinhardt\'85visits.\'a0 Mrs. Smith we went to see & Mrs. Bradshaw, we went into the garden, which has the greatest variety of vegetables in it.\'a0 Some I have never heard of.\'a0 He gets his seed from Thorburn N. York, & they are the finest vegetables I have ever seen.\'a0 Susan went back to the Factory last Friday & returns today, to remain a few days & go on with her work.\'a0 She has not staid with me yet.\'a0 I stopped at Mamma\'92s yesterday & carried herself & Ann to ride a little way.\'a0 It was the first time I had seen them since you were away.\'a0 I am so busy I will not be able to write to you again.\'a0 In my last letter I told you what to get.\'a0 India rubber for me.\'a0 Hat, ball, picture books for Willie.\'a0 Anna says you must bring her a doll, & Frank says an ip (whip) but I don\'92t say so.\'a0 I would like you to bring some little trifle for him, if it were only a 25 cts present.\'a0 Do not forget to draw the pattern of a \ul fence\ulnone .\'a0 The Mountaineer mentions Col. Town[e]s is to be the editor for a year & perhaps longer.\'a0 I have no news to tell.\'a0 I long to see you, & long to hear from you.\'a0 The children are quite well, & often say, \'93I want my Pa\'94 & I reply I want him too.\'a0 Yours, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 79
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Friday morning, 3 July 1846
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 This is the first day I have sat up, & though \ul weak\ulnone , I will write you a few lines, so that you may certainly hear from me before you leave Washington.\'a0 I wish to reiterate again two peices of advice I gave you.\'a0 I have been uneasy about your \ul gold\ulnone  ever since you left.\'a0 Do take it out of your trunk, & carry it about your person.\'a0 It seems to me it \ul must\ulnone  be safer under your \ul immediate\ulnone  care.\'a0 In your trunk it will be impossible\'a0 for your eye to be \ul constantly\ulnone  upon it.\'a0 The other peice of advice is that you must \ul not\ulnone  go to \ul Columbia\ulnone  to attend the Court of Appeals.\'a0 Mrs. Thompson came to see me yesterday, & after what she said, I am more uneasy than before.\'a0 She says Judge Butler was very much provoked when he heard of the arrangement.\'a0 He knew nothing of it at the time, & thinks the Judges who wished to hold Court in \ul August\ulnone , ought at any rate to have held it at some \ul healthy\ulnone  \ul place\ulnone .\'a0 Columbia is the hottest place in the world Mrs. Thompson says, & that whoever does attend the Court, will have for safety to go to the Sand Hills \ul every\ulnone  \ul night\ulnone , & it would be particularly unsafe for one just from the North.\'a0 So I hope my dear husband you will consult my \ul feelings\ulnone , if not your own, & give up all idea of Columbia.\'a0 You have too many dependent on you at home,\'a0 Your life is too precious to run any risk.\'a0 As you have had but one day from home, of course I have little to write about.\'a0 Yesterday morning, Susan was so sick Mamma had to go to her, but she returned last night, is here now, & says she will take good care of me.\'a0 We had a shower yesterday afternoon which lasted about a quarter of an hour, & one at night of about 5 minutes.\'a0 Though so short, I hope they did a little good, & as a commencement has been made, that we will soon have more.\'a0 Willie came home delighted yesterday at having got \ul head\ulnone  of his class, & says I must tell you of it.\'a0 Frank the morning after you left, when breakfast was ready, put on his bonnet to go to your office to call you.\'a0 He cried when he was told you were not there.\'a0 He often says, \'93I want Pa to come now,\'94\'a0 The beds today have been taken down, you know for what purpose.\'a0 I feel my dear husband that I cannot write a letter important enough to send to \ul Washington\ulnone , where you are surrounded with such \ul great\ulnone  \ul men\ulnone , & have your mind occupied with such \ul great\ulnone  \ul subjects\ulnone , what I say must appear so trifling & unimportant, as my letter though will contain the intelligence that your \ul wife\ulnone  is \ul better\ulnone  & your \ul children\ulnone  \ul well\ulnone .\'a0 I hope that alone will be sufficient to gratify you.\'a0 Mrs. Butler spoilt my only good pen, so that I am not able to write as I would wish a letter going such a distance.\'a0 Do not forget to ask Mr. Yancey what he meant by I.W. Hayne being involved in Mr. Joyce\'92s law case, & the reason \ul he\ulnone  \ul thinks\ulnone  that induced him to leave Alabama.\'a0 Write me of everything that you know will interest me.\'a0 Tell me where to direct my next letter to.\'a0 You must see everything worth seeing, stay as long as you choose, & spend just as much money as you have it in your power to spend.\'a0 I would advise you to make your purchases at the close of your travels, just before you start for home, so as to allow yourself the \ul means\ulnone  of going anywhere your fancy dictates.\'a0 I will try & manage everything \ul well\ulnone  in your absence, so you must give yourself no uneasiness about home affairs.\'a0 When able I will ride to the farm, & read your written directions, & add some of my own, for I think of \ul farmer\ulnone  as well as \ul Lawyer\ulnone , that I would do \ul exceedingly well\ulnone , but of course