\cf0 I received your letter written at Columbia last night, & it gave me \ul unfeigned\ulnone  \ul pleasure\ulnone .\'a0 I was in hopes you would write, yet feared you might not have the time.\'a0 Do write to me whenever you can. But still do not let it interfere with your writing to \ul others\ulnone , or any other engagement you may have.\'a0 When I read to Willie & Anna what you said of them, the tears came into Willie\'92s eyes, & Anna cried & said, \'93I want Pa.\'94\'a0 Frank not long before, while laying by my side, had said, \'93I want Pa to come now.\'94\'a0 So you see they all cherish for you a \ul deep\ulnone  \ul affection\ulnone , & it would be long indeed before they would forget you.\'a0 You have told one peice of news I am sorry for, that is that Col. Fair, Mr. Caldwell, and Mr. Vance are going to the North.\'a0 Now though at one time I thought it would be pleasant for you to have a travelling companion, I now \ul decidedly\ulnone  think it would be pleasanter to be \ul without\ulnone  one.\'a0 You will interfere with each other, one will wish to go one way & one another, \ul alone\ulnone , you can do just as you please.\'a0 Besides you have so many letters of introduction, the others I suppose have \ul none\ulnone , & you being \ul with\ulnone  \ul them\ulnone , you may be induced \ul not\ulnone  to deliver them.\'a0 You say you wish to look at the country, more than to become acquainted with people.\'a0 Now I have sent you to the North to become \ul acquainted\ulnone  with \ul people\ulnone , as well as to \ul look\ulnone  at the \ul country\ulnone , & all of these \ul persons\ulnone  to whom you carry letters will assist you to see the country to better advantage.\'a0 Mamma expects you to deliver \ul all\ulnone  of hers. So does Mrs. Butler.\'a0 She will be gratified at your seeing her friends, who are even of the same name with yourself, & as soon as you do see them, you must write me word that I may have the pleasure of telling her.\'a0 At any rate some of them you must see.\'a0 You must be sure to deliver \ul all\ulnone  of Mr. Poinsetts.\'a0 It will not put you to inconvenience to do so, for you intend visiting all the places where his friends are.\'a0 This is perhaps the only time you will ever be able to go to the North it is just as important you should see the great \ul men\ulnone  as the \ul country\ulnone .\'a0 Therefore I wish you to become acquainted with them, & they with you.\'a0 In my opinion you are greater than any of them & I wish them to see you.\'a0 It will be a pleasure to you I know to see persons of whom you have heard of for so long a time , & I will be \ul mortified\ulnone , & \ul never\ulnone  \ul forgive\ulnone  you, & \ul scold\ulnone  you \ul well\ulnone , if you return home without availing yourself of the opportunity afforded you of becoming acquainted with persons.\'a0 Therefore, that you may have it in your power to go where, & do as you please, travel \ul alone\ulnone , & not bind yourself to the company of anyone.\'a0 You can see & be with Col. Fair as much as you wish next winter in Columbia.\'a0 Another thing I wish to tell you is, not to return home too soon, as you are not going to Columbia, there is no reason you should hurry, travel at your \ul leisure\ulnone , & see \ul everything\ulnone  worth seeing.\'a0 Be \ul sure\ulnone  to go as far as \ul Niagara\ulnone .\'a0 I must [page smudged] description of it from you.\'a0 The Catskill mountain house 3000 feet [page smudged].\'a0 Hudson, where there is one of the finest views in the world, must be worth visiting, in short go \ul everywhere\ulnone .\'a0 I am sure your money is enough.\'a0 If not \ul contract\ulnone  your \ul purchases\ulnone , & then you will certainly have enough.\'a0 I will not expect you home, till the middle of September.\'a0 Mamma says you need not be uneasy about me, she will take good care of me.\'a0 She has been with me constantly since you left.\'a0 She was gratified at your remembrance of Susan, Ann & herself.\'a0 You must \ul always\ulnone  \ul mention\ulnone  them.\'a0 They think so highly of you.\'a0 They value your remembrance.\'a0 Mamma desires the best love.\'a0 I must tell you John\'92s opinion of you.\'a0 He said as he drove from the door the last evening you were here , \'93Major Perry is the finest gentleman I ever knew, although he is not a Christian.\'94\'a0 I am happy to tell you we have had \ul rain\ulnone .\'a0 It commenced raining yesterday afternoon , & continued raining all night in a gentle manner, which must have done good, without washing the land.\'a0 March says they expected to finish ploughing today, but the ground is too wet.\'a0 He says a great deal of the corn is tasseling, & that it is \ul clean\ulnone , & free of grass.\'a0 As the horses are at leisure, I intend riding out this afternoon for the first time.\'a0 I will go to the farm & send your directions.\'a0 Today is a fortnight since I lay in bed sick & suffering, & at night met with such a disappointment.\'a0 You do not know how great it was.\'a0 I feel it still.\'a0 Yesterday I went down stairs for a little while, & I could not think how differently I had gone down from what I expected.\'a0 But I am thankful I am now almost well, & have no sufferings to look forward to.\'a0 I feel now for Susan, who can have no idea what she is to go through.\'a0 Willie this morning said, I must beg you to bring him some \ul books\ulnone  \ul particularly\ulnone  one called \'93\ul Mother\ulnone  \ul Goose\'92s\ulnone  \ul Melodies\ulnone ,\'94 which he once owned, but it is torn up, so bring that, & a few simple books with pictures.\'a0 Frank wants a whip [page torn] a doll, & other things innumerable.\'a0 I told her you will not have room to bring [page torn] said you must get someone else to bring them for you.\'a0 With regard to the Music box, I would like one if you can get it reasonable, a \ul large\ulnone  \ul one\ulnone , & it is not beyond your means.\'a0 It must play \ul beautiful\ulnone  \ul tunes\ulnone .\'a0 You must get a \ul better\ulnone  \ul judge\ulnone  of Music than \ul you\ulnone  \ul are\ulnone  to select it.\'a0 But if on enquiry you find they are \ul dear\ulnone , more than you can afford, you must not \ul think\ulnone  of bringing me one.\'a0 Another time when\'a0 you can \ul better\ulnone  \ul afford\ulnone  it, I would get one.\'a0 Now I wish you to spend as much money as you choose in \ul travelling\ulnone , & not deny yourself in that way at all.\'a0 The next thing I would like after a Musical box is a \ul Bracelet\ulnone  if they are \ul worn\ulnone  & I believe they still are.\'a0 Alex McBee brought Caroline Reinhardt one.\'a0 It was very showy with stones in it , & cost $6.50.\'a0 That is \ul not\ulnone  the kind \ul I\ulnone  wish.\'a0 I wish a plain \ul genteel\ulnone  one suitable to wear to \ul church\ulnone  & \ul visiting\ulnone .\'a0 Inquire of a Jeweller which kind are \ul fashionable\ulnone  & select a \ul plain\ulnone  \ul genteel\ulnone  but pretty one.\'a0 I suppose such a one would not at the utmost cost more than 5 dollars, & I would like you to buy me two \ul gold\ulnone  \ul pins\ulnone , to pin my Mantle on at each shoulder.\'a0 All of these things are only mentioned, supposing your money \ul holds\ulnone  \ul out\ulnone , a \ul Large\ulnone  \ul Music box\ulnone  in Charleston costs 20 dollars.\'a0 In New York I suppose they would be much less.\'a0\'a0 Mamma wishes you to buy for her Masselon\'92s sermons.\'a0 She thinks them the best she has ever read.\'a0 If they are not too dear, you might bring them to her as a present.\'a0 Bring also a present for Susan & Ann, however \ul trifling\ulnone .\'a0 They would value it as coming from \ul you\ulnone .\'a0 I will direct this letter to Washington, & hope it will reach there, before you leave.\'a0 4
