My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Again have I taken my seat at your desk in the Library to write to you.\'a0 I read yesterday evening your letter in the Mountaineer.\'a0 It gave me pleasure, but I think it was written in a more careless manner than you generally write.\'a0 I suppose it was written in a \ul hurry\ulnone , but when you write to be \ul published\ulnone , you ought to write with \ul great\ulnone  \ul care\ulnone .\'a0 You did not dwell \ul long\ulnone  \ul enough\ulnone  on the different subjects, & one thing I was surprised at, was your laying so much stress on \ul dress\ulnone .\'a0 It would make the impression that you thought \ul dress\ulnone  of so much \ul importance\ulnone , when \ul I\ulnone  know you \ul do\ulnone  not \ul value\ulnone  it in the \ul least\ulnone , & I am sorry an impression so much against you\'a0 should be made.\'a0 If the Members of Congress had \ul behaved\ulnone  \ul well\ulnone  & performed their \ul duty\ulnone , it would have been of no \ul consequence \ulnone if they had \ul dressed\ulnone  badly, though it would have showed more \ul refinement\ulnone , if their dress had been\'85.\'a0 Another thing I did not like was your \ul court\ulnone  to Genl T\'85..n.\'a0 His \ul character\ulnone  I do \ul not\ulnone  \ul admire\ulnone , & I do not like to see one so far above him\'a0 in everything that is worthy of praise as \ul you\ulnone  are, paying what \ul seems\ulnone  in the \ul eyes\ulnone  of \ul others\ulnone , \ul flattery\ulnone  & \ul court\ulnone .\'a0 Where one possesses \ul vanity\ulnone , it should be \ul pulled\ulnone  \ul down\ulnone , not \ul puffed\ulnone  \ul up\ulnone .\'a0 There was an ungrammatical expression in your letter also.\'a0 You see with how much \ul interest\ulnone  I must have read your letter to criticize it so, but I assure you it gave me \ul great\ulnone  \ul pleasure\ulnone , & the remarks I make, are for you to \ul proifit\ulnone  from in \ul future\ulnone  for I \ul love\ulnone  my husband \ul so\ulnone  \ul well\ulnone  that I wish his letters to be faultless, so as to escape criticism from \ul others\ulnone .\'a0 So continue to write, for all you tell is \ul so\ulnone  \ul interesting\ulnone , that I always wish you would \ul tell\ulnone  \ul more\ulnone .\'a0 Your letters to me are \ul very\ulnone  \ul interesting\ulnone , & I think might even do to be published.\'a0 Mrs. Butler was here yesterday & says she is coming again tomorrow as she thinks I may hear from you tonight.\'a0 She is so anxious to hear something of her family who she thinks you will of course see.\'a0 She says you \ul must\ulnone  go to N London if it is only for \ul two\ulnone  \ul hours\ulnone .\'a0 Her sister Mrs. Rogers is there, & her niece Miss Rogers wishes to come to Greenville, & she thinks it would be a good opportunity for her to come on with you.\'a0 You might arrange it when you return to N. York or Washington on your way home, she might meet you, & come on with you.\'a0 I hope you are willing to put yourself \ul even \ulnone out of the \ul way\ulnone  to oblige others, so that you will make some arrangements of this kind.\'a0 Mrs. Butler is very anxious for a \ul French\ulnone  \ul cap\ulnone .\'a0 She has written to her sister to get her one & send by you.\'a0 She says I ought to have told you to bring \ul me\ulnone  one so now she has put it in my head.\'a0 I \ul would\ulnone  like one.\'a0 You must bring me one.\'a0 I would like you also to bring me as a \ul present\ulnone  to Mrs. Butler, for in all probability she will not get the one she has written for, & she has been so long talking about a French cap, & you can get directed to a Milliner in N. York.\'a0 I wrote you in my last, that I wished you to buy a set of Coral beads for Susan.\'a0 She did not know I had written, & asked me the other day. if you would be a good person to get her a set, that she \ul wished\ulnone  one.\'a0 So you see it would be an \ul acceptable\ulnone  present to her.\'a0 Get a set of small coral beads for the neck, & two smaller strings for the arms, that is called a \ul set\ulnone , the Jeweller will tell you.\'a0 Mamma & Susan are with me washing, so I am not lonely, though nothing can make up for \ul your\ulnone  \ul absence\ulnone .\'a0 I think one reason we love each other so, must be that we are often separated.\'a0 When \ul apart\ulnone , we feel the loss of each other so much, that when we \ul meet\ulnone , we value each other \ul more\ulnone  than ever.\'a0 Mamma sends her affectionate love to you, & says she believes they love you as much as I do.\'a0 They have learnt to value you.\'a0 Willie has holiday now for 4 weeks, & enjoys it greatly.\'a0 Not a day passes but all the children speak of you.\'a0 Frank is a sweet boy, a universal favorite.\'a0 He greets everyone with such a smile, that he wins their hearts immediately.\'a0 My mantle was up yesterday, & I took my meals for the first time down stairs (since you left) & commenced keeping house again.\'a0 After dinner\'97We have just dined.\'a0 Mr. McBee dined with us.\'a0 Susan is here.\'a0 He sends his love & says you must do all you can for the Rail Road.\'a0 Very few persons have come to Greenville as yet.\'a0 Sunday I am going to church, & next week I wish to go by to see Mrs. Dickson & Mrs. Poinsett.\'a0 You must certainly go to N. Haven & deliver all the letters Mamma gave you.\'a0 You must not omit going to the Graveyard, that beautiful spot, where you will see in the plot owned by Mr. Ingersoll, the grave of my little sister.\'a0 You will then realize that we indeed lived in N. Haven.\'a0 Now that you are at the North, you ought to go everywhere, & I think it is such an advantage to have introductory letters.\'a0 It makes you acquainted with the people, & enables you to see the country better.\'a0 You must deliver them all.\'a0 I am sure in Washington you must have felt the benefit of them.\'a0 I am afraid from the Presidents overhearing your remarks on Oregon that it\'85him against you.\'a0 I am sorry, for I wished you to gain the favor of the President.\'a0 Your descrying of Mrs. Polks vanity was not at all \ul pleasing\ulnone .\'a0 The more elevated one is in the world, the more humble they ought to try to appeal.\'a0 Of course she must be pleased at the distinction of\'85& husband, but she ought to have sense enough to conceal it.\'a0 \ul I \ulnone value\'a0\'a0 \ul you\ulnone  \ul more\ulnone  as much as if you were \ul President\ulnone , & the reason I am pleased at any \ul honor\ulnone  paid you, is that it is a proof that \ul others\ulnone  value you, as well as myself, & for this reason I would be pleased if you were made President, if not Judge, at any rate Senator as you now are.\'a0 I am not \ul vain\ulnone  at being the \ul Senators\ulnone  \ul wife\ulnone , but \ul grateful\ulnone  to the \ul people\ulnone  who \ul appreciate\ulnone  you.\'a0 By the by, are you not afraid that the remarks you make about the \ul house\ulnone  may get you into \ul trouble\ulnone .\'a0 Every member may call you to account, thinking it a personal insult.\'a0 If they do, \ul apologize\ulnone .\'a0 I cannot consent to your settling it in any other way.\'a0 I am \ul serious\ulnone , & you must be more careful.\'a0 You must \ul continue\ulnone  to write for the Mountaineer, but write \ul well \ulnone as you know you \ul can\ulnone  \ul write\ulnone , for your letters are \ul always\ulnone  \ul interesting\ulnone , & your travels now afford such a good subject for your pen, & you see so many persons also.\'a0 Mrs. Butler said she hoped you would write about Genl Towson, that he distinguished himself in the last war, so I suppose you know all about him.\'a0 She mentioned someone who went from N. York to Boston for 50 cts in an opposition line.\'a0 I want you to buy \'93Walker on Beauty\'94, & if you cannot get all of Mrs. Sherwoods works, you might get the \'93Lady of the Manor\'94, if it is reasonable.\'a0 Would you not like to get for yourself, \'93Horace Walpoles last letters,\'94 that you could [write] a review of.\'a0 You must bring some clothes or articles of clothing for Willie. Frank & Anna ready made if you see them, so I may know the \ul fashion\ulnone .\'a0 Hat or Dress or something of the kind.\'a0 I have in my different letters given you various commissions, but you must consult your \ul purse\ulnone , & your \ul judgement\ulnone .\'a0 I long to see you, but at the same time wish you to remain away long enough to see everything worth seeing.\'a0 Perhaps on your return you can stop at Bordentown, Wilmington & Carlisle, & at Philadelphia be well to deliver your letters.\'a0 You must see Mr. Van Buren, & write an interesting description of him for the paper.\'a0 You had better remain some days in Washington on your return , for I am sure you did not stay long enough before.\'a0 You must certainly go to N. Port, & engage lodging there for me next \ul summer\ulnone , & go to Burton River [where] her brother lives.\'a0 She says you pass it, & it is a beautiful place.\'a0 Yours, E.F.P. I have written you 6 letters, two at Washington, two at N. York, two at Boston.\'a0 I have no news to tell.\'a0 Take care of yourself.\'a0 The weather here is now \ul hot\ulnone .\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Boston\'a0\'a0\'a0\
