\f1\b Monday afternoon, 12 October 1846
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 According to promise I write you how Frank is.\'a0 The Doctor this morning said he was \ul better\ulnone , & thinks if the medicine would only operate \ul freely\ulnone  he would soon be well.\'a0 The medicine operating so slowly is the reason he is so long sick.\'a0 His throat is better, & his tongue cleaner.\'a0 This morning as he awoke, he asked if I was going to make cake today.\'a0 He then asked if Pa had come back.\'a0 I told him no.\'a0 He said he was afraid somebody would steal Pa.\'a0 I told him Pa would not let them.\'a0 He said they would steal Skylock.\'a0 He then asked to see his cap, then he wished to put it on.\'a0 Your uneasiness about him\'a0 must not bring you back sooner than you ought to come.\'a0 If there is any prospect of business, remain for it.\'a0 In these hard times the least prospect of business you can get is of importance.\'a0 Frank is doing just as well as if you were here, & as he is getting better, you must feel easy.\'a0 I have just written a letter to Aunt Eliza for my Aunts to carry.\'a0 It is now raining, so I think it probable they will not be able to go tomorrow.\'a0 It will be a disappointment to them, that I would rather the rain should have put off a few days longer.\'a0 They are to pass the night here, so as to set off early tomorrow.\'a0 They were here yesterday after church.\'a0 They asked me when they would see me in town.\'a0 I told them I did not expect to go, that travelling was expensive & that your journey had taken all the money you could afford.\'a0 They both said that the only expence would be the journey down & up, for of course I must stay with them, that they would always be glad to see me; they really are in earnest. I hope you will made a bargain with Col. Irby for Maria & James.\'a0 They are perfectly useless servants, at any rate sell James to him, & try to get 550.\'a0 March is so good tempered I am loth to part with him.\'a0 He is a pleasant servant for a lady, more so than Jim.\'a0 I would be willing to hire out Mary this winter.\'a0 She is such a pleasant servant I never wish to sell her.\'a0 Eliza could very easily\'85us wages by taking in work.\'a0 All these means we must resort to if your business fails, & what a Providence it will be if you can make Chancellor.\'a0 If not you will have to go to Congress, as the last resort.\'a0 It was only your Law practice that prevented your thinking of that & now if you have no law business, that objection is removed.\'a0 What bad news we have from Mexico, so much for War.\'a0 The spirits of the Volunteers will be\'85.\'a0 Poor Capt. Williams, you know who used to be with us in the Mansion house, he has been killed.\'a0 It is well his wife is dead, for what an affliction she is saved, but the orphan children are to be pitied & I dare say he had a second wife.\'a0 You know I have a painting over the Dining room Mantle peice which he gave me.\'a0 I shall always value it for his sake.\'a0 I liked him so much, that I am grieved at his death.\'a0 I am writing with such a bad pen, that you must excuse this ill looking letter, & I have been writing all the morning so that I am quite tired, & have also been obliged to stop frequently to attend to Frank.\'a0 Willie has staid at home this afternoon on account of the rain.\'a0 I today bought him a pr of shoes with his money & have given the others to Edward, as they fit him exactly.\'a0 I have tried to get some news of the election, & send you Mr. McHays statement.\'a0 I sent to Mr. N\'85 & Mr. Watson who lives next the Court house, but would hear nothing satisfactory from them.\'a0 I then sent to Mr. Mc\'85 & send you what he wrote me.\'a0 I see Dr. Crook\'92s name is not even mentioned.\'a0 He must have come out too la[te].\'a0 He is in Greenville village today.\'a0 I have not heard of any of th[e] other candidates being here. \'a0Mr. Hoke I expect went to some other box to electioneer for I sent to know [fro]m him about the elections, but Mrs. Hoke said [he] would not be back until this evening.\'a0 I must now send my letter to the office.\'a0 Yours truly & sincerely & devotedly, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Laurens Court House\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 87
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Wednesday afternoon, 28 October 1846
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just done dinner, & I will write you a few lines merely to gratify you in case you are still at Anderson, as in all probability you will not be there, it is not worthwhile writing a long letter which you may not receive.\'a0 I scarcely have the time to write.\'a0 All of the morning I have been visiting my neighbors,\'a0 I paid 8 visits.\'a0 I owe now almost everyone a visit.\'a0 Yesterday I returned some visits at a distance, so rode, but this morning I walked.\'a0 March has been hauling lumber to the Mill.\'a0 I intend to let him haul for sometime.\'a0 This afternoon I am going over to the Mansion house to bid Mrs. Middleton good bye.\'a0 She goes tonight, & after that I going over to see Mamma, who is quite sick with Sore throat & fever.\'a0 Susan is not going to\'a0 Mrs. Thompsons or Mr. McBee either.\'a0 Neither of them wish to go.\'a0 I would like to go, & if I do go will go with Mr. & Mrs. Town[e]s.\'a0 Mrs. Town[e]s asked me to this morning.\'a0 You might very well have come back, & then gone to Josiahs afterwards.\'a0 Saturday night would have done just as well for you to attend to the business.\'a0 If you were going with me I would be certain of enjoying myself.\'a0 With regard to selling the servants, we will talk about it when you return, as to which shall be sold.\'a0 March is so pleasant a servant I would rather keep him.\'a0 His temper is so good, & as you must have a servant about the yard, he is a good one to have.\'a0 Your Farm ought to be attended to.\'a0 Therefore Charles & Jim will do for that.\'a0 James I would sell by all means, & Maria wish sold.\'a0 She is not good enough to regard her feelings, therefore sell her to Col. Irby or Mr. Cureton.\'a0 Mrs. Cauble I went to see this morning.\'a0 She said Maria\'92s mother has spoiled her, that she is only fit for a corn field, & at that will do well, that she can never be made a good house servant, that she is filthy, & that she has been more impertinent to her, than she imagined a servant would be, that the impertinence she gave me was just like her.\'a0 So unless you keep her at the farm, you will have to sell her, & at the farm she is of no use.\'a0 If it is necessary I can send Mary there to stay, let Eliza \'85 & Delia stay in the house.\'a0 All of this we can talk over together when you return.\'a0 I wish you to take the money James is sold for & pay what you owe.\'a0 Willie, Anna & myself are quite well.\'a0 Frank I hope will soon be so.\'a0 He wishes to eat all the time.\'a0 I am obliged to restrain him.\'a0 Mamma has a dreadful sore throat.\'a0 It is very much swol[l]en.\'a0 She told me she had sent for you to stop there, & that you were quite kind. A letter came to you last night from John Cunningham about Mr. Simms.\'a0 It is a good letter.\'a0 He says he has always thought that his ancestors & Bill Cunningham ought to be disconnected, that he disapproved of his sisters publications, but he thinks Mr. Simms language most insulting to her, & that he would notice it, but he hopes you or Judge O\'92Neal[l]\'a0 will this winter\'a0 write a peice about his ancestors, disconnected with William Cunningham, & if so he will not do anything, says he regards you as a personal & family friend, & wishes you & Judge O\'92Neal[l]\'a0 to give him your opinions, & talk together on the subject.\'a0 He begs you to interest yourself in the selection of Aldrich for Barnwell, & Cochran for Abbeville.\'a0 I wrote to Pamela last night.\'a0 I had nothing else to do, & thought she would like to hear from me.\'a0 I did not mention Johns letter, as perhaps he would think I ought not to have opened it, but there were no secrets in it.\'a0 I have now written you a long letter.\'a0 I will write or send a message by someone going to Pickens, & you must write me when you think you will be back.\'a0 Stay as long as it is necessary.\'a0 If you can you must go & see Frances.\'a0 I would like to hear of her & her children, & she would regard it as an attention.\'a0 A North American Review has come containing a Review of Mr. Simms works, in which he is spoken of most disparagingly.\'a0 I long to see you.\'a0 I met Mr. Perry Duncan yesterday going to Georgia after his Wife.\'a0 Susan asked Mrs. Spears if Mr. Spears had any thoughts of accepting the Academy.\'a0 She said, no indeed, that after taking so much pains to acquire the arduous profession of the Law he was not going to give it up\'a0 to keep school, & besides he had refused much better offers than this one &\'85said seemed almost offended\'a0 at the question., but don\'92t mention this.\'a0 I have written in a great hurry, so good bye my husband & believe me as ever, Yours, Liz\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Anderson Court House\
\'a0\

\f1\b 88
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Saturday night, 31 October 1846
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I will now write you a letter & send it by Mr. Elford who goes to Pickens tomorrow.\'a0 It is more convenient to send it to him than to Mr. Spears, being so much nearer.\'a0 We are all quite well.\'a0 Frank is now I think as well as ever.\'a0 He eats a good deal, but seems to experience no bad effect from it, & as he only eats wholesome things, I do not think it will injure him.\'a0 He talks a good deal of you, & is impatient for your return, as all of us are, but though missing you so much, I am glad you should be detained by \ul business\ulnone , so do not return one\'85before you ought to.\'a0 Never leave while there is the \ul least\ulnone  \ul probability\ulnone  of your getting business, as that is our support.\'a0 I am anxious you should have as much of it as possible.\'a0 Among some visits I paid yesterday, I went to see Mrs. Elford & I saw Mr. Elford.\'a0 I liked him very much. He says the lawyers here are very anxious you should be made Judge, as it would be to their interest, throwing your business into their hands.\'a0 My dear husband there is nothing that would please me more, than that you should be elevated to the bench, & if there is the least probability of your succeeding you must try for it, & a Chancellor would be the very thing for you.\'a0 There will be a good many vacancies on the bench soon.\'a0 Judge Johnson, Richardson & Harper, so I should think you stand as good a chance as any one else of succeeding one of them.\'a0 So you must let yourself be talked of in reference to it.\'a0 You are now as much from home as a Judge is, & have much more disagreeable duties to perform, & not so well paid, particularly now, when Law business is scarce, & a Judge is more respectable than anyone.\'a0 I prefer it to being a Member of Congress.\'a0 You must make exertions yourself to get the office.\'a0 You must not expect to have it given to you without your trying for it, but don\'92t mention any of this & we will talk about it when you come home.\'a0 I went to the wedding with Mr. & Mrs. Town[e]s.\'a0 Susan or Mr. McBee did not go.\'a0 They were neither of them well, & even otherwise, she could not have left the baby, Mamma being sick also.\'a0 The room was crowded, only one being opened to receive the company.\'a0 I could not see half the persons who were there, but it was not such a general invitation.\'a0 As to Butlers wedding party, you know the whole village were at that, but at this one only the persons I expect that Mrs. Thompson invited.\'a0 I spent a pleasant evening, but not as pleasant as if you had been with me.\'a0 I did not feel so independent as I would have felt with you.\'a0 I was near Mrs. Poinsett almost the whole evening, & Mr. Poinsett & Genl Thompson handed me in to supper,\'a0 Many inquiries were made after you.\'a0 I told them you were attending to your business, while they were pleasuring it.\'a0 Mrs. Thompson said you ought to have come.\'a0 I thought she looked\'85, & she looks badly very thin.\'a0 I think she has been sick.\'a0 I expect she felt sadly at giving up to another her only daughter.\'a0 Genl Thompson said his head felt turned the whole evening.\'a0 The bride looked pretty, but very thin.\'a0 Mr. Edward Earle & Miss Calhoun seem to like each other very much.\'a0 I dare say that will be a match.\'a0 Mr. Sam Earle was not there.\'a0 He was invited, but Mrs. Harrison did not send him his invitation, so he did not know he had received one.\'a0 If he had received it, he would have gone, for he wished to go.\'a0 Mrs. Mays & the Miss Maxwells who were staying at his house went; was it not strange in Mrs. Harrison.\'a0 There were 6 bridesmaids & Groomsmen.\'a0 Mrs. Butler Thompson does not look as if she intended to increase her family.\'a0 Some say it is a mistake, but I suppose not, as those who ought to know, say that she does.\'a0 You say Genl Thompson told you she did.\'a0 She has only taken a long time about it.\'a0 I have told you as much about the wedding as I have room to. Last night it commenced raining, & has been raining hard all day.\'a0\'a0 It has now stopped, so I hope tomorrow will be clear, to allow me to go to Church. & you to travel, for you cannot have travelled today.\'a0 I am glad you have taken some notes, but would much rather the money.\'a0 Perhaps if you had \ul urged\ulnone , you could have got the money.\'a0 The servants I suppose at the farm are doing what you told them.\'a0 Mine here are doing well.\'a0 Elizas John is much better.\'a0\'a0 She says she will\'a0 soon come home, \'85really I have no money, & now as I am economizing have so little work for her to do, that I will be sorry when she comes.\'a0 If it is any conven[ience] to you this winter, Mary can stay at the farm, Eliza iron & do what little work we have, & Delia attend to the house.\'a0\'a0 I am now really e[cono]mizing. The bill you left me would at the end of this week have been almost unbroken, if it had not been for paying Mr. Pickwell for mending Watch & Jewelry.\'a0 I did not spend the usual sum in Butter,\'a0 Mr. Roberts not having brought any.\'a0 When you are \ul Judge\ulnone , we will spend 1000 & put up 1000 every year, so that by the time our children grow up, we will be able to give them every advantage, I will not be left destitute.\'a0 Now it is always uncertain what you will make, & you have to beg the people to pay you, but then you will have a certain income, receive it without begging, & be independent of the people, but I need not urge the advantages to induce you to win the place, for you cant be so indifferent to your own interest & your family, as not to wish & try for it if you thought there was a possibility of your getting it.\'a0 Four letters came last night, & all electioneering letters, except one from Mr. Thompson of Washington about the Shirts.\'a0 He says he is mortified at his having received the money when you had not received the shirts, that he thought they reached you safely, that he will remit you the money, & asks in what manner he shall do it.\'a0 The postage on the letters were paid.\'a0 A\'85came & other papers.\'a0 The mail before a\'85letter came from Mr. Pettigru, begging you to interest yourself in Col. Keiths reappointment as City Register.\'a0 Col. Keith had requested him to write to you.\'a0 You can write him.\'a0 Col. Keith is connected with you, so of course you would interest yourself in him.\'a0 Mamma received a letter from Alston about her business.\'a0 He gave her some good advice such as you have often told me about her breaking in upon her Capital, but she did not like his advice at all, was hurt that he should not think her economical.\'a0 She will soon receive money enough from her income to pay Mr. Hoke.\'a0 Her house was invested in Mr. Tuppers bond, & she will receive that interest.\'a0 Poor Mamma has had a dreadful sore throat & fever with it.\'a0 She is now getting better.\'a0 Mrs. Duboc is staying with them to help nurse her.\'a0 Fam[ily] is quite well.\'a0 Mr. Luther has been there the greater part of the week.\'a0 I have no room to write more.\'a0 The children are asleep.\'a0Willie is still head. He makes no fuss now learning his lesson.\'a0 Mr. McNutt says he ought to miss & let the other boys get up & he skips all about to try to make him miss & tries to cheat him & tell him he has spelt the words wrong, but Willie says Mr.McNutt says he cant cheat him.\'a0 The Miss Ramseurs used to make me go\'85, said I allowed the girls no chance of getting up.\'a0 Take care of yourself.\'a0 Come back safe, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Pickens Court House\
\'a0\

