\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Sunday afternoon, 22 November 1846
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Charleston
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have but a few moments to write to you.\'a0 I have not heard from you yet, & would have been\'85hearing an accident had happened to the Rail Road Cars, Sunday, but this morning saw your name mentioned in the paper as having presented some petition in the Legislature, so I know you must have arrived safely.\'a0 I have no conveniences for writing, & have but this one blotted sheet, perhaps not for a week to come to write on, so you may expect to hear from me very seldom.\'a0 Monday I dined at Aunt Haynes, & spent a very pleasant day.\'a0 Last night I took tea at Mrs. Henry Pinckney\'92s.\'a0 There were about 30 persons there.\'a0 It was quite pleasant.\'a0 Mr. Pinckney said he saw you at the City Hall, & tried to speak to you but it was so crowded, he could not get near enough to shake hands.\'a0 I was also invited to Mrs. Ancrums, but I was engaged to Mrs. Pinckney\'92s.\'a0 Tonight I was invited to take tea at the Elliotts , but it is so cold & the wind blowing so high, that I have excused myself.\'a0 Tomorrow I am to dine at Aunt Brewtons.\'a0 My present plan is to stay here about 2 weeks, then go to Columbia & stay 2 days, & then return to Greenville unless E\'85 goes to her brother Isaac, & Aunt Eliza asks me to stay with her, & then I will stay longer in Charleston.\'a0 I sent a message to Miss Rodgers, & wished I could have gone to have seen her but it was out of my power, she stayed so far up.\'a0 She was to leave today.\'a0 I have been at a great deal more expense as regards clothing than I expected to.\'a0 Charleston is now so fashionable a place, that coming from the country, one has to brush up a good deal.\'a0 I will never come again except with a plenty of money, & as that perhaps will never be the case, I hardly think I will see Charleston again.\'a0 I am sure my dear husband you have been very liberal to me, when you were so straightened & I am much indebted to you.\'a0 The children are quite well.\'a0 Willie behaves the worst of all.\'a0 He is a boy that does not care what is thought of him, so he behaves just as badly among strangers as he does at home, but I hope he will improve.\'a0 The weather is now very disagreeable, cold & windy.\'a0 I have written to Mamma but once.\'a0 It is only when I am perfectly at leisure, that I can write with care, & I have been obliged to shop every day, which is very fatiguing.\'a0 Aunt Anna has made me comfortable, but I would have enjoyed myself much more at Aunt Eliza\'92s, for she possesses a spirit congenial with my own, & if ever I come again, I will stay with her.\'a0 Still Aunt Anna has been quite kind, & I do not feel as if I was imposing on her.\'a0 I am now writing in the same room with my Aunts, & the children running about shaking the table, so I hardly know what I am writing.\'a0 You must be careful how you express yourself in peices to be published.\'a0 Today I read your Rail Road speech, & you said in it, that the best part of the population emigrated & left behind the paupers & drones.\'a0 You ought to be very careful [page torn]\'85dieu now my dear husband.\'a0 It is getting [word obscured; page torn].\'a0 I have written in a great hurry [word obscured] not know when I can write again.\'a0 Your truly attached Wife, E.F.P. I told Willie what I had written about him.\'a0 He says I must rub it out.\'a0 I told him I would let it stay in, but tell you he was going to be a good boy.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\
\
\'a0\

