\f1\b Wednesday morning, 2 December 1846
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Charleston
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I wrote to you yesterday, but having a few moments to spare this morning, I will write again, for I expect you will not think you can hear too often.\'a0 It is before breakfast.\'a0 My Aunts have not come down yet.\'a0 Frank is upstairs with Delia, & Willie & Anna are playing about the room.\'a0 I have just been reading the Newspaper.\'a0 I see a bill has been introduced in the Senate by Mr. Manning appropriating 20000 dollars for the Volunteers.\'a0 You were one of that Committee.\'a0 I am certain your Clients will think you most extravagant, for 20,000 is too large a sum for that purpose; 5 or 10,000 would have been enough.\'a0 You must not be prodigal in spending the peoples money.\'a0 I see also a resolution has been introduced by Mr. Felder relating to the Bank.\'a0 I approve entirely of them, & recollect \ul you\ulnone  said the bank ought to be divided.\'a0 I do not undertake to advise you on the subject, but I can give you a little information regarding it.\'a0 I went to see Mrs. Colcock yesterday, & speaking of Banks, she said, that her husband, though a President of the bank used to say, that Banks were a \ul curse\ulnone  to the country.\'a0 I think Mr. Felder is right.\'a0 All the affairs of the Bank ought to be inquired into, who is indebted to it, & so on.\'a0 Mrs. Colcock says persons who borrow from the bank think they ought not to pay, because it is a \ul bank\ulnone , & if their property is sold to pay the debt, they get vexed.\'a0 You are Chairman of the Committee on Banks, so you must weigh well all these considerations & determine what to do.\'a0 I do not presume to advise you, but my \ul instinct\ulnone  tells me Mr. Felders resolutions on will, & as womans instinct is worth a good deal.\'a0 There is nothing[page torn]present I know of\'a0 to benefit you with my counsel, so I will co\'85.\'a0 My situation has changed.\'a0 The children are now around me pressing me & making so much noise I will soon have to stop writing.\'a0 My Aunts also have come down, & breakfast will soon be ready.\'a0 Just after breakfast, I am going out.\'a0 So this is the only time I will have today to write.\'a0 I dined yesterday at Aunt Susan Haynes & spent a pleasant day.\'a0 In the evening Aunt Eliza & Eloisa & Sue came up & took tea with her.\'a0 Eliza dined there.\'a0 Tomorrow or the next day I dine at Aunt Eliza\'92s.\'a0 I have not yet determined what day to leave, but in all probability one day next week.\'a0 Cousin Isaac ought to have been in Columbia yesterday, but his wife is sick, & he does not know when he can go.\'a0 She is within 2 months of her confinement, & has been taken prematurely sick, & perhaps she may be confined shortly, so in this situation he cannot leave here.\'a0 I am sorry your bust is an ugly one, but I hope before it is finished, it will improve.\'a0 If you bust is a correct likeness, I will be glad you have had it taken, for your portrait is a poor one, but I do not admire busts, & have no wish to have mine taken.\'a0 A portrait of myself I would like to have taken very much.\'a0 I hope to hear soon from you, & must now close this letter.\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P.\'a0\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\

