\f1\b Monday afternoon, 7 December [1846]
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Charleston
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I will write you a few lines, as I have some leisure moments.\'a0 All the morning I was shopping, & riding; rode over the city with Aunt Anna, tonight we take tea with Miss Seabrook & her sister Mrs. Legare.\'a0 We were invited also to Mrs. Capers, but were engaged to the other place first.\'a0 Saturday evening we took tea at Mrs. Andrew Turnbull\'92s.\'a0 I have determined to leave here next Saturday, stay in Columbia Sunday & Monday & set off for Greenville Tuesday, & arrive there Wednesday the 16
\fs24\fsmilli12222 \super th
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \nosupersub .\'a0 About that time the Legislature will adjourn, so I hope you will soon follow me.\'a0 I have written to Susan to tell her what time I will be at home, & to let the servants know.\'a0 I saw by the papers this morning that Judge Butler had been elected Senator, & I also saw your name mentioned as a candidate for Judge.\'a0 I hope you will ascertain beforehand whether you can be elected.\'a0\'a0\'a0 You are so good a judge of elections, I should think you would tell beforehand how it would be.\'a0 I will be delighted if you can be made Judge but I would prefer your not being beaten.\'a0 However you will act for the best I know.\'a0 I have not got through with my visiting yet every day someone comes to see me & yet being always out myself, I have seen not half of my friends.\'a0 I have been treated more kindly than I expected, & Charleston seems much pleasanter than it did, when I was complaining at the Hotel & thought myself neglected.\'a0 It is delightful to be among so many relations as I have here, relations I think must care for a person more than mere acquaintances.\'a0 Klinck has not yet sent in his bill.\'a0 He is waiting for a vessel to arrive that contains some of the articles that we wished.\'a0 I think he is a good Grocer.\'a0 I can write only these few lines, for I wish to send the letter to the office before it closes that you may get it tomorrow.\'a0 Today I bought a present for the Aunts with whom I am staying.\'a0 I feel under obligations to them & wished in some measure to return it.\'a0 For Aunt \'85 is so economical, she must think we have been an expense to her.\'a0 The children drink so much Tea, that it takes a good deal of Sugar to sweeten it.\'a0 She is as close a person as I ever saw.\'a0 She spends just as little as possible, but considering that failing, she has made us more welcome than I possibly thought she could.\'a0 Adieu.\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P. Meet me at the Cars Saturday evening.\'a0 If I change my mind I will write you.\
\'a0\
