\f1\b Wednesday night, 9 December 1846
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Charleston\'a0\'a0\'a0
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received a letter from you tonight, & though I wrote to you today, I will write again to tell you, that I will go up Friday.\'a0 Col. Isaac Hayne goes that day, & I will go under his protection, & it will then be optional with us whether to go on to Greenville Saturday morning, or remain in Columbia until Tuesday morning.\'a0 If I go Saturday I will be obliged to wait in Columbia until Tuesday, but going Friday will allow me to do as I choose, & if you think there is the least risk of the Scarlet fever, I will go on at once.\'a0 I am prepared to hear of your defeat.\'a0 I cannot but be provoked that you should have suffered your name to be used, & then done not the least thing to be elected.\'a0 I must say it was foolish conduct, & in future I hope you will never apply for an office, unless you intend to try to get it.\'a0 I think it is perfectly right to use honorable means to ensure success.\'a0 You suffered your name to be used, & yet acted in the very best way not to get votes.\'a0 Why whoever heard of such a thing. I could not help scolding, for indeed you deserve it.\'a0 The world will think we are mortified not knowing how you acted.\'a0 But you must not give up, another time I dare say you will succeed.\'a0 I spent today after shopping & visiting at Aunt Eliza\'92s.\'a0 My most pleasant days have been spent with her & Aunt Mary & Aunt Anna, & also a delightful day I spent with Aunt Emily & Aunt Sarah.\'a0 The other days I spent out were also quite pleasant.\'a0 Mamma\'92s Sisters are uncommonly fine ladies; they have noble qualities.\'a0 When I returned home tonight, I found that Aunt Mary McCall had been to see me & left me a beautiful China Ink stand.\'a0 E\'85 gave us some presents today.\'a0 I assure you I have been most kindly treated by my friends.\'a0 Aunt Eliza was regretting today that I would not have staid with her.\'a0 She is a cheering lady, & more congenial with me than those with whom I have been staying, but my Aunts have been\'85& considering the close disposition that one of them has, I have been made more welcome that I thought I would be, but still knowing that failing, it makes me feel badly as myself & family being here, must be a \ul little\ulnone  \ul extra\ulnone  expense & that little expense, I know must be regretted.\'a0 I have been glad whenever I had an invitation out, so as to be as little expense as possible.\'a0 If I had been at Aunt Eliza\'92s, I would have staid until the adjournment, & let you come down for me, but Aunt Anna is not prepared to entertain gentlemen, & you would not have found it pleasant.\'a0 I think I have now staid long enough with her, & I will be delighted to see you, & happy to be at \ul home\ulnone .\'a0 Though my visit has \ul exceeded\ulnone  my expectations, I have had real heartfelt pleasure in being with my friends, a feeling I have not had for years, for in Greenville there is nobody with the exception of Mamma\'92s family who \ul love\ulnone  me, but here there are many.\'a0 I assure you no body in Charleston has more sincere friends than \ul Mamma\ulnone , & loving her, makes them take an interest in me.\'a0 I am sorry Mamma ever left Charleston.\'a0 She would have been saved many troubles if she had not, & it is more respectable for persons to be among their relations.\'a0 Mrs. Whitefoord Smith who in Greenville seems to be thought nothing of, in Charleston would be respected if it was only [on] account of her son, who is said to be the most distinguished preacher in the city.\'a0 Persons \ul advanced\ulnone  in life at an age that you are not apt to contract friendships, ought to remain where they are brought up.\'a0 Aunt Mary really wishes me to leave Anna with her, but Anna will not consent, or I would do it.\'a0 Aunt Mary loves little girls.\'a0 Aunt Eliza says she would be a little treasure among [word obscured] all.\'a0 You must not be mortified\'a0 at your [two words obscured] , & I suppose you are not, for from the way you acted you must have wished to be mortified.\'a0 Good night.\'a0 Your affectionate & \ul wise\ulnone  \ul better\ulnone  \ul half\ulnone , E.F.P. P.S. I would like to stay at the Congaree House, & I should think you would prefer it, for otherwise you will have to leave your lodgings, or be away from me.\'a0 I am not mortified at your defeat, & I am sure it has done you no harm, & perhaps good, as you may be thought of in future for the bench.\'a0 Still I wish you had thought soon of coming forward & been on a footing with the others & tried as hard as they did, then you might have succeeded, & I am \ul certain\ulnone  you would have beat \'85.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 99
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Thursday night, [1846]
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I will write you, if it is only a few lines tonight to send by Mr. Town[e]s tomorrow\'85.\'a0 I know you will be disappointed if you do not hear again.\'a0 I expected certainly to hear from you last night, & would scarcely believe the mail had come, when March returned without a letter.\'a0 My disappointment is always mingled with uneasiness, for when from home, I am always anxious to know \ul certainly\ulnone  that you are well.\'a0 Your life is so important to your family, that you must be as careful as possible of it.\'a0 I am still busy housecleaning, even now.\'a0 March is in the room, putting a peice of Furniture in its place.\'a0 We have not half got through, the white washing is finished, & the room somewhat fixed, but next week the Entries, the Staircase, the Piazza\'85all to be cleaned, the Curtains washed & put up, & other things done too numerous to mention.\'a0 There are enough dirty things to occupy a week. \'a0Monday, Delia & Mary will have to stop to wash some of the clothes, the house, all over, was shockingly dirty, the dirt seemed to me several inches thick under the Carpets.\'a0 To show you in what confusion we have been, last night when Frank fell asleep in my lap, there was not a single bed ready for him, & we had to put him in the basket of dirty clothes, where he took a comfortable nap.\'a0 I am thankful, & you ought to be, that you have not been here.\'a0 You would not have stood it.\'a0 I feel tonight, tired.\'a0 I have to work, so will be able to write you but a short letter.\'a0 You must write to me by someone returning home, any directions about your farm you can give.\'a0 I expect they are all doing as you would wish them, for I believe Jim & Charles are good fa\'85.\'a0 I sent work to Jim, that you wished him to go on planting rapidly.\'a0 Susans letters now are quite satisfactory.\'a0 She mentioned in one of her notes to Mamma, that Pinckney McBee had paid them a pleasant visit, that he kissed her, which she certainly thought a proof of regard, & on going away, he said, if he was only certain of having such a wife as she was, he would be perfectly happy.\'a0 Mr. Luther said, he had never known propriety, until he married \ul her\ulnone , & they determined her to do all in her power\'a0 to make him happy.\'a0 So I hope everything will go on smoothly.\'a0 As soon after your return as is convenient, I wish all of us to go & spend a day at the Factory.\'a0 I have seen no one, been no where, & have no news to tell you.\'a0 The only new thing I have heard is, what Mr. Hooker told me when he came to fix up the bedstead (which March could not do).\'a0 He said there were to be several more stores set up here, one by Mr. R. Duncan & Charles Elford, another by Col. Irvine & Joe Elford, & another by Mr. McBee & Frank Cox, so I think they must be anticipating the Rail Road.\'a0 The children are quite well.\'a0 Today Frank said, I rode on horse.\'a0 I said when? He said, this morning.\'a0 I said, who let you ride?\'a0 He said Pa.\'a0 I said where is Pa?\'a0 He said, up street.\'a0 He is as sweet as ever.\'a0 Mr. Luther says they are the prettiest & finest children he has ever seen.\'a0 Unfortunately a looking glass has got broken, the one that was on my table & that you had before we were married.\'a0 It was put in the Portico yesterday along with the other chamber furniture.\'a0 The wind was very high & blew it down.\'a0 I am more superstitious about that than anything else.\'a0 It makes me uneasy about you while you are away, & after you return I will be uneasy about myself.\'a0 So do be careful of yourself my dear.\'a0 It is now past 9, so good night\'a0\'a0 Yours ever, Liz P.S. Mr. Luther sent me yesterday a present of some candle wick.\'a0 As I do not make Candles, I will put it into stockings for yourself & the children.\'a0 It seems very strong.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Pickens C.H.\
\'a0\

