\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Wednesday, 8 March 1847
\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Rosemonte
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I feel very anxious to write at once to you, to tell all that has passed \ul outwardly\ulnone  & in my \ul mind\ulnone  to you, since we parted.\'a0 We rode on after you left us, until today when we stopped near a well & eat our dinner.\'a0 Then we continued our journey & arrived at Mr. Conner\'92s at 4 oclock.\'a0 We stopped & a servant came to the gate, & on asking her if we could stay there that night, she replied, her master & mistress were both from home & she expected them back that evening, that the house was locked up, & that we would have to sit in the \ul kitchen\ulnone  until they came, so we got out & went into the \ul kitchen\ulnone , but I had not been there a \ul moment\ulnone , before I thought how \ul uncomfortable\ulnone  & \ul ridiculous\ulnone  for us to sit several hours in a kitchen, full of servants, & perhaps after all, the Master & Mistress might not return, & then what were we to do.\'a0 So before the Trunk was taken off, I asked the girl what was the next house we would stop at.\'a0 She said, either Mr. Boyd\'92s, which was 10 or 12 miles beyond, or Mr. Barksdale\'92s which was two miles from Laurens C.H.\'a0 So as the horses were tired, I determined to go to the \ul latter\ulnone  place, & right glad was I at my determination, for when we drove up to Mr. Barksdale\'92s, the house looked so comfortable, I was certain we would be well accommodated..\'a0 We asked a boy we saw, if we could stay there, & he called his Master.\'a0 As soon as I saw him, I thought of Mr. \ul Richardson\ulnone  & \ul your\ulnone  \ul cases\ulnone , but the old gentleman, a very \ul respectable\ulnone  looking person, handed us out, & carried us into the house, into a comfortable room where there were 3 ladies seated by the fire.\'a0 He said to the oldest one, a \ul motherly\ulnone  looking person, that he did not know by what \ul name\ulnone  to introduce the lady to her.\'a0 I told her my name, though I was almost afraid to.\'a0 After awhile, he said, there was a \ul Perrin\ulnone  that lived in Abbeville.\'a0 I told him I was from Greenville.\'a0 In a little while he went out of the room, & when he came back, he noticed the children, & looking at \ul Frank\ulnone , said he was the image of his \'85. & said Willie\'92s forehead was exactly like his \'85.\'a0 I expect he had found out from Jim who we were.\'a0 I sat with them, until a fire was made in another room; when they asked me to go into that room, where I staid until Supper was ready.\'a0 After supper I [word obscured] back into that room, thinking they preferred I should, but Mrs. Barksdale asked me to remain in the room with them, which I did & made myself as agreeable as I could.\'a0 We passed the most \ul comfortable\ulnone  night, I have ever passed on the \ul road\ulnone .\'a0 Everything was \ul clean\ulnone  & the cooking better than usual.\'a0 The next morning Mr. Barksdale sat with us before & after breakfast.\'a0 I thought all the time it was your \ul particular\ulnone  enemy.\'a0 I felt awkward to ask him if he was that gentleman, but on speaking of our return, & Laurens Court & soon, I took the opportunity to ask, if he was the gentleman that had the difficulty with Mr. Richardson.\'a0 He said \ul no\ulnone , it was his \ul brother\ulnone , who lived six miles above.\'a0 I said I was very sorry it had occurred.\'a0 He said he was very sorry Mr. Richardson applied to \ul you\ulnone  to defend him.\'a0 I did not say anything more, not knowing that I ought to.\'a0 After a most pleasant time spent with the family, we prepared to resume our journey.\'a0 I asked him what he charged; he said 2 dollars.\'a0 I told him that was too little; he said no, he only charged for the provisions we had used.\'a0 So after being treated kindly & behaving kindly myself we left.\'a0 We passed through Laurens village, & arrived at Mr. Cunningham\'92s Monday before dinner.\'a0 We were affectionately received, & this is the first opportunity I have had of writing to tell you so since I arrived.\'a0 Mr. McLees, the Presbyterian minister of the church in the neighborhood, was here.\'a0 He left yesterday morning.\'a0 Mrs. Beman & little Cara Yancey & Mrs. John Cunningham & children are here now.\'a0 Pamela seems as usual.\'a0 She came downstairs last evening & spent it in the dining room & today she is riding out.\'a0 I sit with her a great deal & the children run about & have not given me much trouble.\'a0 Fanny\'92s voice is hardly ever heard.\'a0 Willy sometimes seems at a loss what to do.\'a0 I have not heard them any lessons yet & intend to.\'a0 And now my dear I would be happy & contented, & pass my time pleasantly, if it were not for \ul one\ulnone  \ul thing\ulnone , &\'a0 that one thing \ul absorbs\ulnone  my \ul thoughts\ulnone  in the \ul day\ulnone , & keeps me \ul awake\ulnone  at \ul night\ulnone .\'a0 I will tell you what it is.\'a0 Soon after I got here, Mr. Cunningham asked me where I had passed the last night.\'a0 I told him at Mr. Barksdale\'92s.\'a0 He laughed & asked how I had happened to get in at the Barksdales, & then the difficulty with Mr. Richardson was mentioned.\'a0 He said he had forgotten the subject until a few days before, he was speaking with \ul Mr.\ulnone \'a0 \ul Coleman\ulnone  of this District, & he asked Mr. Coleman what he thought your prospects were in this District, & Mr. Coleman said you would have had no trouble at all, not met with \ul any\ulnone  \ul obstacle\ulnone  in the District, if it had not been for that \ul unfortunate\ulnone  \ul Richardson\ulnone  \ul affair\ulnone , but that \ul your\ulnone  appearing \ul against\ulnone  Mr. Barksdale, , had completely turned him against you & Mr. Barksdale & his family commanded \ul 500\ulnone  \ul votes\ulnone .\'a0 Mr. Cunningham said he was at first surprised when he heard their influence extend[ed] to 500 votes, but when he began to think of the \ul respectability\ulnone  of the family, the \ul number\ulnone  of the \ul influential\ulnone  families with whom they were connected, many of them having been members of the Legislature, the Allens & others, & the \ul popularity\ulnone  of \ul Mr. Barksdale\ulnone , Mr. Richardson insulted, he was not surprised at it.\'a0 \ul He\ulnone  & \ul all\ulnone  \ul here\ulnone  think that Mr. Barksdale has \ul justice\ulnone  on his side, that Mr. Richardson acted with the \ul greatest\ulnone  \ul impudence\ulnone , that striking his \ul negro\ulnone ; he ought to have \ul whipped\ulnone  his negro \ul himself\ulnone , & \ul apologized\ulnone  to Mr. Barksdale.\'a0 I cannot but be surprised that \ul you\ulnone  should bring a case of this kind, you might have been in honor bound to \ul defend\ulnone  Mr. Richardson in the case brought \ul against\ulnone  him, but it seems to me you ought not to have \ul indicted\ulnone  Mr. Barksdsale, you ought to have \ul declined\ulnone  this, & could have done it with perfect propriety.\'a0 I had not heard you say anything of the cases lately & had quite forgotten them.\'a0 I only hope they will be dropped, that you will drop the one you brought, & Mr. Barksdale will drop his.\'a0 But if they \ul are\ulnone  tried, I \ul pray\ulnone  & \ul beseech\ulnone  you to conduct the cases so as not to hurt Mr. Barksdale\'92s feelings.\'a0 You can be \ul just\ulnone  to your Client without being \ul unjust\ulnone  & \ul harsh\ulnone  to your \ul opponent\ulnone .\'a0 You have the \ul unjust\ulnone  side, & I am afraid your only recourse will be \ul abuse\ulnone  \ul lavished\ulnone  on the opposite party, for you deal in abuse I believe more than any other Lawyer.\'a0 You make more enemies than any Lawyer I ever heard of.\'a0 There seems to be no reason why a Lawyer should not conduct a case with zeal & ability for his \ul Client\ulnone , & yet so \ul honorably\ulnone  & \ul justly \ulnone as to satisfy even the other party.\'a0 Do my dear be on your guard in these cases, so important to your interests, the fate of the election perhaps depends on it.\'a0 I beg you not, just to show your \ul independence\ulnone \'a0 & \ul disregard\ulnone  of \ul votes\ulnone  to \ul abuse\ulnone  Mr. Barksdale & be \ul violent\ulnone  against him.\'a0 I regard it as most \ul unfortunate\ulnone  that Mr. Richardson should have applied to \ul you\ulnone .\'a0 If it had not been for this affair, Mr. John Cunningham says would have got but very few votes.\'a0 Now you have been the cause of giving him \ul 500\ulnone .\'a0 He is certainly most fortunate, electioneering \ul himself\ulnone  & \ul you\ulnone  electioneering for him.\'a0 I am so provoked with Mr. Richardson.\'a0 I wish he could be \ul well\ulnone \'a0 \ul punished\ulnone  for the trouble he has given me.\'a0 The Lower Country persons regard the Upper Country persons with contempt, & this is an instance of it.\'a0 He treated Mr. Barksdale with contempt, made his horses run away, & then ran after him with a pistol & long knife, & then indicted him .\'a0 You know Mrs. Span said their servants had been ruined at the Virginia Springs, & they behaved impudently at Mr. Simmons, & to think that all this impudent conduct, in which you had no success, & you yourself would have acted so differently, persons who had no interest in you, should have injured you in so vital a manner; you ought to have told Mr. Richardson that he had acted \ul impudently\ulnone , that he had not \ul justice\ulnone  on his side, & advised him to apologize to Mr. Barksdale. & make up the latter as well as he could.\'a0 If he had given you a fee of \ul 500\ulnone  \ul dollars\ulnone  to have the \ul unjust\ulnone  side, you may have been obliged to \ul defend\ulnone  Mr. Richardson, though you might as you were advised by others have declined it, but I cannot see that you were obliged to \ul bring\ulnone  an \ul unjust\ulnone  case \ul for\ulnone  him, as the indicting Mr. Barksdale for striking an impudent negro, certainly was.\'a0 Oh my dear I can only beg you for the \ul love\ulnone  you \ul bear\ulnone  your \ul Wife\ulnone , to be \ul prudent\ulnone , in the management of these cases, in which you are so \ul unfortunately \ulnone concerned, if they are \ul tried\ulnone , but I hope they will \ul never\ulnone  be tried.\'a0 My mind is relieved after expressing all these thoughts to you, but I cannot tell you how \ul provoked\ulnone  I feel with Mr. Richardson.\'a0 Little did I think, a person who I \ul never\ulnone  \ul saw\ulnone , was to become such an \ul injurious\ulnone  \ul influence\ulnone  on your fate in life, perhaps make your career in this world so entirely different, from what it otherwise would have been.\'a0 At any rate if he does not occasion your \ul defeat\ulnone , your election if it had not been for him would have been attended with so \ul little\ulnone  \ul difficulty\ulnone , the Barksdales with their 500 votes, would have gone for you.\'a0 They are connected with the Parks, Allens & I do not know who all.\'a0 The gentleman I passed the night with has 9 \ul children\ulnone  \ul gwown\ulnone , one a doctor at Laurens village, another living near him, a son in law named Parks, another named Bird.\'a0 I sincerely believe this Mr. Richardson will be the cause of your defeat, for otherwise the majority in Laurens would have elected you, for it is that District which will turn the Election.\'a0 Do write me \ul immediately\ulnone .\'a0 I long to see you, though I am vexed with you for all the trouble you cause me, for you ought to have followed the advice of your \ul friends\ulnone , & not taken the cases.\'a0 I envy Mr. Orr\'92s good fortune in having his opponent electioneering for him.\'a0 Do read this letter \ul over\ulnone , & think \ul deeply\ulnone  on it.\'a0 Write me when you will come here.\'a0 When you get to Laurens you will be able to tell how long you will be detained there.\'a0 If you can [word obscured] sooner than you thought, write to Mr. Hoke to tell Jim to come sooner than we told