My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I wrote you a long letter yesterday, & gave you a great deal of advice, all for you own good, which I hope you will follow the reason of my writing to you again is that Mr. Cunningham this evening, said he wanted me to give you a message.\'a0 That in the management of these cases against Mr.\'a0 Barksdale you must be very\'85that you can act \ul justly\ulnone  towards your Client, but at the same time not be \ul harsh\ulnone  & \ul severe\ulnone  to your opponent, that if you have any \ul severity\ulnone  in your manner towards Mr. Barksdale. It will excite his feelings against you, to your injury, while it will be of no advantage to your Clint.\'a0 You must be \ul fair\ulnone  & \ul just\ulnone , but not \ul severe\ulnone  & \ul harsh\ulnone , & if you set them, the cases in the end may not operate against you.\'a0 So perform your \ul duty\ulnone , but do not have any harshness or severity in your\'85.\'a0 Mr. Cunningham if he can, , will go to Laurens C.H. but does not feel well, & is not certain he can go.\'a0 I like Mr. Cunningham, & particularly because he is such a friend of yours, he is a man of honor, which is saying a great deal.\'a0 I wish I had some good news to tell you, but as I have none, I will tell you some bad.\'a0 Mr. Quin came here this afternoon, & told Mr. Cunningham that he met a son of the Genl Jones who has volunteered to raise a regiment, & he told him Mr. Orr would get \ul half \ulnone of the votes in the village of Laurens.\'a0 I know he is an enemy of yours, but I am sorry to hear that this Genl Jones is a man of \ul great\ulnone  \ul influence\ulnone , a dangerous man Mr. Cunningham says.\'a0 You will think I am Jobs comforter, but really this news, & the 500 votes you are to lose on account of taking Mr. Richardsons part has so depressed me, that I feel as if I must unburden myself to you.\'a0 Mr. Cunningham thinks Mr. Orr a most insinuating person in his \ul manners\ulnone  & knowing as I do, that he will exert himself to the utmost, & that all you do, is to give votes to him 500 at a time, I cannot but be very uneasy.\'a0 Do write to me.\'a0 I have written all my thoughts now, so I will not have much more to say to you when I see you.\'a0 I am passing my time very pleasantly, & if it were not for these unfortunate cases against Mr. Barksdale, who Mr. Cunningham says has \ul immense\ulnone  \ul influence\ulnone , connected with the most \ul respectable\ulnone  families, I would be very happy.\'a0 Fanny gives me \ul no\ulnone  \ul trouble\ulnone , the other children amuse themselves running about & playing.\'a0 It is late at night.\'a0 I will conclude with one more peice of bad news.\'a0 Mr. Cunningham asked me who Genl Thompson was for, I told him he professed to be for \ul you\ulnone .\'a0 He said the reason he asked me was, that he had lately seen a Mr. Ward from Greenville a Whig who was going to support Mr. Orr.\'a0 So he wanted to know if it was owing to Genl Thompsons influence or not,\'a0 He said when he argued with Mr. Ward & told him he was astounded he should support a man from \ul Anderson\ulnone  in preference to one from his own district whose character, talents, firmness & so on were so well known as \ul yourself\ulnone  that Mr. Ward seemed warped.\'a0 So my dear all this bad news is to make up for the good news we heard before we left Greenville.\'a0 I thought I was duty bound to tell you, so as to put you on the \ul alert\ulnone , & not let you \ul deceive\ulnone  yourself.\'a0 I will close by begging you once more, to be \ul prudent\ulnone  in the management of these cases, but I cannot tell you how \ul grieved\ulnone  & \ul provoked\ulnone  I am that you are engaged in them.\'a0 Drop Mr. Richardsons the one you bought, for there is no \ul justice\ulnone  in it, & I am surprised any Lawyer but Joe Powel should bring it.\'a0 Wishing that you may have better news to tell me than I have told you.\'a0 I remain Your devoted Wife, E.F.P. I hope Mr. Cunningham will go to Court.\'a0 He is your real friend.\'a0 You will think me warm & will be inclined to go just contrary to all I have said, but, assure you this letter is written so as to give you the message Mr. Cunningham sends you on the first page.\'a0 He begged me to delete it, for he may not be able to go to Court.\'a0 I believe you are often \ul unnecessarily\ulnone  \ul severe\ulnone  in your speeches in Court, but in these cases do not be so.\'a0 You must be\'85than it is the custom for any other Lawyer to be, for I know of any other Lawyer who makes enemies of the opposite party, in \ul every\ulnone  \ul case\ulnone  he has, as you do.\
