\f1\b 107\'a0\
Monday afternoon, 22 November 1847\
Greenville\

\f0\b0 \'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I wrote you a letter which I suppose your received last night, on your arrival in Columbia.\'a0 I received yours written at Newberry, last evening.\'a0 Willie answered it for me, & put his letter in the Post Office on his way to school today.\'a0 It is his \ul first\ulnone  letter so you must be \ul pleased\ulnone  with it, & answer it & \ul praise\ulnone  it.\'a0 He was not satisfied with it himself, wished to write it over again, but I told him it would do very well.\'a0 I wish you had carried him with you.\'a0 Excursions from home always do him good, & associating with grown persons.\'a0 He always appears well, having no excuse to quarrel, or be irritated as he is with children.\'a0 You can carry him with you next Spring, when you go to Columbia.\'a0 Though Willie has written, I cannot resist writing, to express some of the thoughts\'a0 that are passing through my brain now that I have been to Columbia, I can imagine your situation there, much better than I did formerly.\'a0 I know where your chamber is, & where your seat in the Senate is.\'a0 I used to imagine the Senate Chamber, at the other end of the State House.\'a0 I am sorry indeed the Convention acted with so little harmony.\'a0 If I may express my humble opinion I would say, that the only plan now to be adopted is, that each District should build the road for itself.\'a0 Newberry must build the Road from Columbia to Newberry C.H.\'a0 Then Laurens must continue it & build from Newberry to Laurens C.H. & Greenville must go on & build it from Laurens to Greenville.\'a0 In the same way Abbeville & Anderson will have to do, for no people will build a road for others, that is not to benefit them.\'a0 Selfishness is too deeply planted in\'85nature for that.\'a0 I hope Anderson does not feel to you, as Laurens you say does to Mr. Orr.\'a0 It was unfortunate the interest of the two places should clash together & that you should be situated as to have to offend one or the other.\'a0 I hope that your good judgement carried you skilfully through & that in the end it may be all the better for you, & that you have gained & not injured yourself with either party.\'a0 I have perfect confidence in you, though I often venture to suggest, some \ul new\ulnone  \ul ideas\ulnone  to you.\'a0 Your honor, prudence, & good judgement, I believe equal to anyone.\'a0 Now for a little advice, if you would obtain a Seat on the Bench \ul easily\ulnone , you hear so from our friends, you must by no means \ul decline\ulnone  it, it being in my opinion a situation preferable to any other, combining both \ul profit\ulnone  & \ul honour\ulnone , with permanency, but I rather think the office will be sought so earnestly\'a0 by so many, that your claims would have to be \ul pressed\ulnone  to be successful.\'a0 A Judge you are cut out for, your good judgement, would make you an invaluable one, but in my opinion there is no responsible situation you are not fitted for, even the Presidential Chair.\'a0 I am glad Mr. Choice & yourself are friendly, an \ul honorable\ulnone  \ul enemy\ulnone , could easily be changed into a \ul friend\ulnone .\'a0 I was uneasy about \ul you\ulnone , when I heard of his accident.\'a0 Mrs. Thurston I believe was hurt also.\'a0 Mrs. Butler told me she jumped out, & knocked out some of her Teeth.\'a0 Mrs. Butler stopped at the gate Saturday.\'a0 Miss Rogers says she will stay with me, so I expect her at any time.\'a0 No one can supply your place to me, therefore when you are away, I prefer no one staying with me, I am not \ul lonely\ulnone , but I \ul miss\ulnone  you.\'a0 But if Miss Rogers comes, I will try & make her pass her time pleasantly.\'a0 Jim has carried me to ride \ul twice\ulnone  since you left, one afternoon & one morning.\'a0 All the rest of the time, he has been digging Potatoes for Mr. Hoke.\'a0 He will finish I hope today.\'a0 He says Mr. Hoke has about 100 bushels of Potatoes.\'a0 Mr. Hoke Saturday sent me a peice of Pork & a peice of Beef.\'a0 Saturday & Sunday were so cold.\'a0 If such weather had continued, hogs would have been killed, but the weather today has moderated.\'a0 It is cloudy & drizzly, so unfavorable.\'a0 Mary & Delia have not washed as usual.\'a0 I went to see Mrs. Harrison one evening.\'a0 I think she seems more comfortable in her present home than in her old one.\'a0 I have received pleasant letters from Aunt Harriett & Mrs. Dubose.\'a0 Uncle Edward & his daughter has not yet arrived.\'a0 Mrs. Alston Hayne Aunt Harriett says has sent some of her Bridal Cake to us. Sarah Cunningham, Pamela\'92s cousin is engaged to Mr. Daniel of Georgia.\'a0 I suppose she saw him last summer.\'a0 You know she went to Clarksville.\'a0 Have you heard anything of Pamela?\'a0 I am surprised she has not answered my letter.\'a0 I directed it to Hamburgh to the care of Mr. Yancey.\'a0 Ask him if she received it.\'a0 Willie wrote you the compliment Genl Whitner paid your speech.\'a0 Mrs. Dubose says Mrs. Gordon & Mrs. B\'85 who have children named after you & to whom I sent a frock & book were delighted with the presents, particularly as coming from me.\'a0 Your brother Fosters children thanked me for what I sent them.\'a0 Her brother Mr. Lee had been elected Magistrate, but the friends of his opponent, are going to try to present a petition to the legislature about it.\'a0 The children are well.\'a0 I went to see Mamma yesterday morning after church.\'a0 The 3 oldest children dined with her.\'a0 I returned to my sweet little Fanny, who is as good as ever.\'a0 The cold days I could not keep her warm, so wrapped her up in a\'85blanket.\'a0 Mary Long is said to be engaged to Tom Crayton & to be married next month.\'a0 One of the Miss Bollins is to be married Thursday night, & the other the Thursday after.\'a0 Mrs. Town[e]s I believe is well.\'a0 Mrs. Roberts & Mrs. Burn came to see me Saturday.\'a0 As I have written twice already, I do not think I will write by the next mail, but will wait to hear from you.\'a0 I dare say the opponents of the R[ail] Road would constantly have said, the road would stop at Newberry, that the money would all be used to bring it as far as that & no further, so perhaps it is as well the company should be dissolved & each District made to build it for herself. \'a0Newberry must commence, & the other Districts follow.\'a0 Each one now will be obliged to build for itself, & Abbeville & Anderson do the same.\'a0 Adieu my dear husband.\'a0 Tell Edward I am glad to hear he is behaving well.\'a0 Your affectionate Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 108\
Friday morning, 26 November 1847\
Greenville\

\f0\b0 \'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received your second letter Wednesday night, & was \ul very\ulnone  \ul much\ulnone  pleased to hear from you.\'a0 It would have been a \ul great\ulnone  \ul disappointment\ulnone  if Mary had returned from the office \ul without\ulnone  a letter, for a \ul letter\ulnone  from \ul you\ulnone  \ul now\ulnone  is the principal incident in our lives.\'a0 You say I must write if it is only to say \ul we\ulnone  \ul are\ulnone  \ul all\ulnone  \ul well\ulnone .\'a0\'a0 I have not much more of interest now to tell you, so you must blame circumstances & not \ul me\ulnone , if you receive uninteresting letters.\'a0 I wrote you Monday.\'a0 I must now think of all that has happened since Tuesday & Wednesday.\'a0 It rained incessantly, so that Willie & Anna were obliged to stay from school, but they each said their lessons to me.\'a0 They are both \ul smart\ulnone  children, & learn with great ease.\'a0 Willie learns now a history lesson every day.\'a0\'a0 Wednesday Jim killed the smallest hog.\'a0 He said the other hogs would kill it, if \ul he\ulnone  did not.\'a0 They fought it constantly so I made no objection, & we now have some fresh meat to eat.\'a0 I sent a peice to Mamma .\'a0 It is very fat meat.\'a0 The weather has not continued long \ul enough\ulnone  to kill all of the hogs.\'a0 Mr. Phillips has not sent any hams yet.\'a0\'a0 Wednesday Mr. Croft sent me some Packages from Pamela.\'a0 He had just returned, & had passed one night at Mrs. Cunningham\'92s on his return.\'a0 Pamela sent your books \'93Moultrie\'92s American Revolution,\'94 \'93Drayton\'92s Memoir,\'94 \'94Hallam\'92s Literature\'94.\'a0 She sent you a \ul beautiful\ulnone \'85& Mrs. Cunningham sent me a small book, called \'93Woman\'92s Mission.\'94\'a0 Pamela wrote me a letter.\'a0 They had but recently arrived at Rosemonte, & she had been sick with Chill & Fever.\'a0 She had intended going to the Lower Country this month, but as she had just reached home, she did not know now when she would go; perhaps not until the Spring, when she expected again to go to the Island.\'a0 The purse, she said she finished the very day Mr. Croft arrived.\'a0 She intended writing a note with it, but Mr. Croft was\'85so short of time, she was not able to, so I must present her kind regards & beg you to accept this simple offering of her conviction of your \ul honesty\ulnone  & \ul purity\ulnone  of \ul purpose\ulnone  in public life, & whenever you looked at it in \ul Washington\ulnone  (that den of corruption) it must serve to remind you that your fiends look to \ul you\ulnone  on all occasions to display that love of Country, which disregards party interests & individual aggrandizement!\'a0 I wish I was as certain my dear husband that you will have the opportunity of so acting as she is.\'a0 I am afraid this Rail Road business will injure you greatly in Anderson, but even if it has injured you there, I know your \ul first\ulnone  duty was to Greenville, therefore it cannot be.\'a0 I only hope Mr. Orr is as much injured in Laurens as you are in his District & that you are at any rate \ul even\ulnone , (but here comes the suggestion).\'a0 \ul Mr.\ulnone  \ul Orr\ulnone  has been \ul successful\ulnone  in his efforts for the Road, & \ul you\ulnone  have \ul not\ulnone  \ul been\ulnone .\'a0 Mr. Orr\'92s friends will be so grateful they will do all they can to elect him, however I will not \ul worry\ulnone .\'a0 I \ul know\ulnone  \ul you\ulnone  \ul act\ulnone  as \ul duty\ulnone  \ul inculcates\ulnone  & I hope in the end you will be \ul rewarded\ulnone .\'a0 I hope you have not estranged Genl Thompson & Mr. Read from you.\'a0 It is well if you \ul can\ulnone , to retain them as your friends, as they are the leading Whigs in this Congressional District.\'a0 The Canvas in which you are now engaged is so extensive & so important, that great circumspection is required to ensure success.\'a0 You know I always wish you to \ul act\ulnone  \ul honorably\ulnone  & \ul independently\ulnone .\'a0 All I ever fear is, that when there is no \ul reason\ulnone  for it, you will act independently, & without cause injure yourself, \ul just\ulnone  to show your \ul independence\ulnone .\'a0 I think you are justified in \ul honorably\ulnone  doing all you can to \ul retain\ulnone  & make friends, but ! will go on to other subjects, that I know you think more within \ul my\ulnone  \ul sphere\ulnone .\'a0 The Book Mrs. Cunningham has sent me, Pamela says they had read & were very much pleased with, that they knew I would like it, it would give me many ideas as to governing children.\'a0 I was interrupted in my letter by a visit from Mr. & Mrs. Rowland.\'a0 Mr. Rowland said as the Greenville & Laurens Stockholders withdrew , from the Convention, those who were left, applauded them, that they were treated with no respect.\'a0 I am very sorry the Convention should so have ended & that Greenville should have lost the road.\'a0 What do you think now will be done. Will Greenville do anything again toward having a Road?\'a0 Yesterday morning Jim cleaned out the Stable yard & in the afternoon I rode with the children to Mr. Buists\'92s to know when he was going to Bachelors Retreat.\'a0 Mrs. Doloc wishes me to send something by him.\'a0 He is going there to assist in the ordination of Mr. Hillhouse.\'a0 They are to have a 3 days meeting.\'a0 I had not been on the Spartanburgh road since I paid a visit to Mr. Buist with you years ago.\'a0 This morning Jim is hauling wood\'a0 & this afternoon, I intend going to see Mrs. Pearson.\'a0 Fanny is sweeter than ever & gets more interesting the older she grows.\'a0 She knows \ul me\ulnone  now, & I love her so, when she cries to come to me.\'a0 She also knows Delia, & sometimes likes to go to her from me.\'a0 She is my little comfort at night.\'a0 A father is necessary to a child, when she is looking & behaving so sweetly.\'a0 I always wish \ul you\ulnone  were here to see her.\'a0 Frank is shaking my desk, & saying he wishes Pa would come.\'a0 Almost every morning & in the middle of the night, when he wakes, his first exclamatiion is \'93has Pa come\'94?\'a0 I say no, he says, \'93well then I dreamt he had come\'94.\'a0 One morning he said,\'a0 \'93I dreamt Pa was baptized\'94.\'a0 I asked him who baptized him, he said, \'93he baptized himself\'94.\'a0 When the children behave badly, I tell them I will write & tell you, & it distresses them very much, & they beg me not to.\'a0 I think they have behaved pretty well, since you left.\'a0 The servants do as usual.\'a0 Minerva ought to be satisfied.\'a0 I have as little cooking as possible, so as to allow her plenty of time to make her clothes.\'a0 I have been very busy making Delia Mary & Lindy\'92s clothes.\'a0 I have not touched the Worsted work.\'a0 Except going behind the Carri[a]ge, I do not miss Edward in the least.\'a0 Lindy with ease does what he did.\'a0 I would like when he returns, to put Lindy with Mary McLeod to learn to wash iron & cook, so that she may be a useful servant.\'a0 She has a good temper & I want to make her a valuable servant.\'a0 At Mamma\'92s they are as usual.\'a0 Susan has had headache lately.\'a0 Mamma says she would like you to get a chair like ours, even if you had to give more.\'a0 I must now close & will only say if I have given more advice than you care for.\'a0 You must\'a0 consider it only as a vent to my thoughts, that I have no one to listen to me as you do, & that I have perfect confidence in my dear husband that he always acts as \ul duty\ulnone  & \ul honor\ulnone  dictates, & that his \ul good\ulnone  \ul judgement\ulnone  will carry him \ul safely\ulnone  through life.\'a0 I hope even to a better world , in spite of his wifes interference.\'a0 E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 109\
Monday morning, 29 November 1847\
Greenville\

\f0\b0 \'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 If Fanny will permit me I wish to write to you this morning.\'a0 I have the charge of her, Delia & Mary having gone to the Spring to wash.\'a0 She is now lying on the floor, but does not seem satisfied with her position.\'a0 I received a letter from you last night, & Willie also received one.\'a0 He answered his immediately, so you will get two letters again the next Mail, but I know it will not be too much of a good thing for you.\'a0 I must give you a \ul scold\ulnone , for breaking your word & being \ul extravagant\ulnone  when you promised you \ul would\ulnone  \ul not\ulnone .\'a0 It is well for you to say, you got the books to \ul send\ulnone  to \ul me\ulnone  this winter.\'a0 Your \ul conscience\ulnone  told you, you must give me some excuse, for doing \ul exactly\ulnone  what you told me you were \ul not\ulnone  going to do.\'a0 There are more books in the Library now, than I can expect to read, & until we have read those, there is no necessity to buy any more.\'a0 There is no room in the Library even to \ul place\ulnone  them.\'a0 Those that Pamela sent back, I cannot find a place for.\'a0 If you buy books to \ul please\ulnone  \ul me\ulnone , I would like Mrs. Opie\'92s, Mrs. Sherwood\'92s, Miss R\'85\'92s works , & others of the like kind.\'a0 \ul Novels\ulnone , I do not care for, but such works as I have mentioned, are improving & interesting & light, serve to wile away an hour agreeably.\'a0 Your books, almost all of them are too deep & solid, for the general reader.\'a0 Yesterday Mamma & Susan stopped on their way from church to see me, & they went in the Library to choose a book for Ann, & except two or three little books \ul I\ulnone  had bought there was scarcely one suitable for her, who was sick & wished something amusing & interesting.\'a0 There are so many things we need for the \ul house\ulnone , \ul necessities\ulnone  that we will be \ul obliged\ulnone  soon to supply, that we ought both to deny ourselves of whatever we can do without, that we may have money to supply those wants.\'a0 We now need many things, Staircase Carpet, Waiters, Face Towels, Cups & Saucers, Dinner set &c&c, but even these things we must try & do without as long as we can.\'a0 It must be a\'85tation to you, when in Columbia, & particularly in a Book store, to forget all of your economical resolutions.\'a0 I cannot \ul blame\ulnone  you, in Charleston last winter I saw so many things I wished to get, & it was such a good opportunity to supply all my wants that I could not but regret that my means did not allow me to, & I did spend to the very last cent almost, all that you gave me.\'a0 I would never go to town again, unless I had plenty of money, as I know that will never be the case.\'a0 I for my part need not regret the Rail Road failure.\'a0 It would have been no immediate benefit to me.\'a0 It would have brought crowds of friends to see us, but not carried us to see them in return.\'a0 It would not have cheapened the price of board in Charleston, & would have made things dearer here.\'a0 I am not so selfish as to begrudge to others the benefit they would have received, so if the failure of the Road is an injury to my State,\'a0 I do regret it, but I do not regret it for myself.\'a0 Genl Whitner is really anxious to be elected Judge, & I am sure he has no \ul claims\ulnone  to it, for he is not I believe, even a good Lawyer.\'a0 He would make a \ul poor\ulnone  \ul Judge\ulnone .\'a0 \ul Honour\ulnone  has certainly something more fascinating in it, than money, for Col. Memminger I suppose makes a great deal more as a Lawyer, than he will as Judge, but he wishes the \ul honour \ulnone of being a Judge.\'a0 I have always felt so.\'a0 I would not wish the honour with \ul no\ulnone  money, but I am satisfied\'a0 with \ul less\ulnone  \ul money\ulnone  & \ul some\ulnone  \ul honour\ulnone .\'a0 You \ul tantalize\ulnone  when you say, Col. Martin says if you continued in the Senate, you would be elected President of it.\'a0 If I were \ul certain\ulnone  of that I would wish you to continue, for you would then still practice Law, & the position would be just as honorable & even more so than if you were in Congress.\'a0 I suppose though it is entirely uncertain if you would be elected President, & at any rate it is too late to change for Col. Brockman considers perhaps himself as in the field.\'a0 I believe if you are \ul confident\ulnone  you can be elected to Congress, & at the same time practice Law, & support your family, though you have to give up half you make to a partner, I am satisfied I would have liked you to have been a Judge above all things, but there are so many aspirants for that office, & would be also for the President of the Senate that I need worry myself, that you will lose all chance of ever being elected to those offices.\'a0 In a few years as our young servants grow up, we must\'85or sell some of the older ones & make something in that way.\'a0 When Edward can drive, we can sell Jim, & when Lindy is older we can sell Mary & Minerva & Lindy herself or hire them out.\'a0 I would like now to hire out some of them. \'a0I am glad you have heard good news from Stephens, & that Genl Thompson is interested in your election.\'a0 As you \ul are\ulnone  a \ul Candidate\ulnone , I wish you elected.\'a0 Mrs. Duloc wrote me word you had a great many warm friends in Pickens.\'a0 Willie was very much pleased with your letter.\'a0 As I read it to him, the tears came into his eyes.\'a0 Every evening I hear him his lessons, & after that he reads to me or asks questions.\'a0 We sit up till 9 oclock, & I am so busy working I am sorry then to go to bed.\'a0 I have\'85now for all of my learning.\'a0 Woman\'92s Mission, which Mrs. Cunningham sent me, I find I have read.\'a0 Aunt Eliza sent it to Susan; in it, I recollect reading to you, that Mothers must recollect they were to be the Mothers of grown up men, as well as children, & must improve their minds, to keep pace with them respect them.\'a0 Saturday Jim & Charles killed the Steer.\'a0 It is not very nice meat, tastes poor, however it is some help; the hog also that was killed, was\'85by the other hogs so I do not eat the meat with much pleasure, but it makes no difference with the servants.\'a0 As regards the presents you are to bring us, I wish you to be \ul economical\ulnone  & bring \ul trifles\ulnone .\'a0 I assure you we do not care for valuable presents.\'a0 Bring Susan & myself a string of Black beads, such as you got us before.\'a0 I think the price was 621/2 cts.\'a0 Bring Ann a basket if you see a pretty one to put her knitting in, if not some little trifle.\'a0 Bring Anna a Match to her China Doll, bring Willie a Knife, bring Frank some Marbles he says & a knife.\'a0 He needs a cap for the Winter, but I expect I could get a cheaper & prettier one in Charleston.\'a0 I could send for one, but do as you think about the Cap.\'a0 Bring Fanny a Straw Rattle; in Charleston they cost\'85so I can send for one, if there are none cheap in Columbia, & bring her an Ivory ring if you see them cheap.\'a0 I mention these things, but you can bring whatever you think best, provided they \ul cost\ulnone  \ul little\ulnone .\'a0 We are counting the days until you return.\'a0 You must write \ul every\ulnone  Mail, if it is only a line.\'a0 Willie says I must tell you to be \ul sure\ulnone , and ask Mr. Summer for his dog.\'a0 Since I began writing, I have held Fanny repeatedly, & have now put her to sleep.\'a0 She is more & more interesting.\'a0 Your affectionate Wife, E.F. Perry P.S. I do not\'85to scold you for buying books.\'a0 You must get whatever you wish, but I like lighter works\'85.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

\f1\b 110\
Wednesday morning, 1 December 1847\
Greenville\

\f0\b0 \'a0\
My dear Husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Again am I seated at the desk to write to you, with literally nothing to write about, but that you may hear Friday night.\'a0 I must even make a letter out of \ul nothing\ulnone .\'a0 This first winter day is a bad one.\'a0 This morning early it was sleeting, & mow it is raining. So that Willie & Anna have been obliged to stay at home from School.\'a0 They have each said their lessons to me, , & Willie has been reading to me one of Miss Edgeworth\'92s good stories.\'a0 He has now stopped to eat with Anna & Frank Molasses & ice & bread\'a0 & I wish Until I have done writing, that they would be at School.\'a0 Lindy is holding Fanny, who is sucking a peice of Biscuit.\'a0 She looks so eagerly at the children when they are eating, that I give her a peice of biscuit , to make her think she is eating too.\'a0 Jim says Mr. Hoke says\'a0 he will kill hogs the first of next week.\'a0 This week would have been cold enough, but Jim says Charles & himself\'a0 would not have killed ours alone.\'a0 They would have been obliged to hire two hands, that it was best to wait for Mr. Hoke, & that the Hogs are so fat, they do not eat much corn.\'a0 He sold the skin of the steer at the Tan Yard for $1.05 he brought me the money.\'a0 Mr. Phillips has not brought the Meat to Mr. Goodlett\'92s that he intended to.\'a0 I sent to the Jail to inquire, & they sold it without bringing it here.\'a0 Our Beef will last a long time.\'a0 As Minerva wishes to make her clothes, I have Soup principally every day.\'a0 I have spent money in ways I did not expect when you left.\'a0 Some \ul very\ulnone  \ul nice\ulnone  Rice was brought, & as ours was just giving out, I bought between 3 & 4 bushels, more than enough to fill a barrel.\'a0 It was 2 dollars a bushel.\'a0 I let Mamma have a bushel, so that it left me not quite a barrel full.\'a0 The Servants needed more unbleached Homespun to make up underclothes so I was obliged to buy a peice of it.\'a0 Lindy needed shoes.\'a0 She had not had new ones this winter, & Minerva asked for another Homespun frock, having but one thick one, & she wished another for a change, so I gave her one.\'a0 When you went I put aside the greater part of the money you gave me, determining to spend very little, & what I saved reserve[d] for \ul myself\ulnone , with your permission, but these expenses, without my wishing it, have obliged me to draw on the Sum put aside.\'a0 I have been busy ever since you left, & still am, working for Lindy, Mary, Delia & the Children.\'a0 I make the Servants clothes much better than they do, that when I give them good clothes, it is a pity to have them spoiled by their\'85so I generally, even if I commence showing them how to do it, end by doing it myself.\'a0 They must learn to work from mending their clothes.\'a0 Yesterday morning I wrote to Mrs. Duloc, & in the afternoon, carried the letter, along with a package of articles she desired me to purchase, & some plants to Mr. Buist, to carry to her.\'a0 He is to go Friday, but if the weather continues as it is now, I should not think he could go.\'a0 There is to be a three days meeting of the Presbyterians at Bachelors Retreat.\'a0 Mr. Hillhouse is to be ordained.\'a0 I called for Mrs. Arthur to go with me.\'a0 When the weather is pleasant Mr. Arthur & herself to spend the day with me, & Mamma, Susan, & Ann.\'a0 Mamma & Susan Sunday stopped to see me.\'a0 Mamma said I must give her love to you.\'a0 I sent the letter you wrote to Willie, to her to read, & she said, it was a very pretty letter.\'a0 I have not seen Ann to tell her of Mr. Simms\'92 interest in her.\'a0 I wish Mr. Simms was a single man, but I expect Ann would be shocked at my saying so, for conscientiously, I believe marrying never enters her thoughts, & it is only one who is respected by \ul all\ulnone , as ,well as \ul herself\ulnone , that she would every have thought of.\'a0 She has been particularly unwell lately, has had a Blister on, which has been very painful.\'a0 In one of your letters you mention.\'a0 In one of your letters you mention you had just seen Mr. the name that follows, I cannot make out, that he enquired after Mamma & myself, talked a great deal about Congress, & said Orr was a particular friend of his, & he had told him he ought not to have opposed you.\'a0 It is so provoking that you should have written the \ul name\ulnone  so \ul indistinctly\ulnone .\'a0 I cannot tell who it is you are talking about.\'a0 In you next letter tell me who is was, & write the name, so I can read it. I merely looked over the Governor\'92s message, & I see he recommends taking a boundary line & defending it.\'a0 As from the character of the Mexicans, they will never make peace on our terms.\'a0 I should think this was the only plan to be adopted.\'a0 It seems useless to go on fighting them, for they do not mind defeat.\'a0 As useless as to punish Mary for stealing, she has no feeling whatever.\'a0 I believe if her hand were cut off she would not feel it, , so she must just be taken as she is, & not mind her faults, but overlook them.\'a0 So the same with the Mexicans, you must treat them differently from other nations.\'a0 Butler Thompson I expect is nearing home, I see a wagon going to Mr. Montgomery\'92s every now & then lately for furniture,\'a0 I went to see Mrs. Elias Earle after she had left not knowing she had gone.\'a0 Lately I have been glad to stay at home.\'a0 I have been expecting Miss [page torn] constantly, but am glad she has not come, for I have been (that Minerva may\'85) living plainly, & when you are away, I attend to the children, hear their lessons &c & company\'85\'a0 She borrowed when here last, \'93Washington & His Generals.\'94\'a0 She has not returned yet a book she borrowed when she staid with me when Mrs. Duloc was here, & has some she borrowed last summer.\'a0 I have even forgotten what they were except one \'93the Hungarian Tales,\'94 Mrs. Gibbs gave me.\'a0 The others I believe were of the same nature.\'a0 I have heard of several engagements.\'a0 I believe I have not mentioned them, Eliza Earle to Mr. Breaker, & the Miss Juan who stays at Mr. Buists to Mr. Hearn Fountain Irvine, Emma Juan to Col. Irvine, Mary Long to Tom Crayton I have told you.\'a0 I do not know that any are true.\'a0 Take care of yourself my dear husband.\'a0 Frank still dreams of you.\'a0 I am so crowded between Frank & Fanny, I hardly sleep enough to dream.\'a0 Frank throws off the covering so & takes cold, that I am obliged to have him with me, to cover him,\'a0 Anna can\'85very prettily in different books.\'a0 I hope the Legislature with adjourn soon.\'a0 I hope also to hear from you tonight, & that today you are writing to me, so that I may hear Friday night.\'a0 I have written Pameta to thank her for your purse & the book.\'a0 E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
