\f1\b 111\
Friday morning, 3 December 1847\
Greenville\

\f0\b0 \'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Again has the day come around for me to write to you.\'a0 I assure you it is a great interruption to your work, but I am willing to be interrupted if it is any satisfaction to you to hear.\'a0 I judge of you by myself, & I am not willing a\'85Mail should come without bringing me a letter.\'a0 I have just been reading the Mountaineer.\'a0 I miss your letters, they were more interesting to me than any others.\'a0 You are Chairman of Finance & Banks.\'a0 You must recollect what Mrs. Colcock told me last winter in town, that her husband though \ul President\ulnone  of the Bank, \ul disapproved\ulnone  of it, & said it was of \ul no\ulnone  \ul advantage\ulnone  to the \ul State\ulnone .\'a0 I read Mr. Sullivans letter about the Rail Road meeting, & he clearly shows, that it was from \ul manuvering\ulnone  \ul beforehand\ulnone , that the Convention terminated so unfavorably for Laurens & Greenville.\'a0 If there are to be as many R[ail] Roads through the State as are \ul now\ulnone  \ul projected\ulnone , after they are all built, they will not be able to pay their own expenses, for there is not freight or passengers enough for all.\'a0 It was the patronage of the greater part of the State, that was to make the Greenville Road profitable.\'a0 She was to get help from \ul all\ulnone , but now that help is to be \ul divided\ulnone .\'a0 One thing I am glad of that you are released from the payment of your Stock, & when you submit again, you must only subscribe \ul one\ulnone  \ul thousand\ulnone  \ul dollars\ulnone , the sum that so many richer than yourself subscribed.\'a0 I received your letter Wednesday night.\'a0 I am sorry that you spent Sunday writing letters.\'a0\'a0 I know that \ul going\ulnone  \ul to\ulnone  \ul church\ulnone  \ul alone\ulnone  will not carry us to heaven, but I think it shows our hearts are not in a right state, when we think it of no consequence to say Gods\'85.\'a0 \'93Remember the Sabbath Day to keep it \ul holy\ulnone .\'94\'a0 It certainly was not \ul holy\ulnone , to be writing Electioneering letters.\'a0 I wish you to write the letters, but not take the \ul Sabbath\ulnone  \ul Day\ulnone  for it.\'a0 Abridge time from your sleep. business or pleasure, but not from that day.\'a0 You have been peculiarly prosperous, & you above all others, ought one day in reserve to return thanks to God in his house for all his mercies to you.\'a0 I like to go to church on Sunday, not that I think performing that duty, & leaving others undone, will benefit me, but keeping the Sabbath holy is one of Gods commands, & I can keep it more holy at \ul church\ulnone  than anywhere else, & it is a respect we owe to a time honored custom, but I did not mean to say so much.\'a0 You are as Judge Butler said of Cousin Harriett his second wife, you are \ul near\ulnone  \ul perfection\ulnone .\'a0 I wish you to be \ul perfection\ulnone  \ul itself\ulnone .\'a0 If Col. Benjamin Perry opens my letters, he will think his wife has grown very sensible, that he was not aware how superior she was before.\'a0 You ought to have learnt by this time always to look at the back of your letters, & open them very carefully, & look at the signature.\'a0 I am sorry you refused lending Mr. Jones the money.\'a0 I would not have lent 50 but 25 dollars to show my good will, & it would have put him under obligations to you, which would have been to your advantage.\'a0 You must consider it a compliment as I do to be requested to lend.\'a0 My neighbours have much better opinion of my obliging disposition than I have of \ul theirs\ulnone , for I scrupulously avoid borrowing from them, knowing their \ul closeness\ulnone  & \ul illiberallity\ulnone , but they constantly let me know that they think me just the reverse of themselves.\'a0 Unless you have been very extravagant, you certainly have money to spare, so you must repent of your unkindness, & go to Mr. Jones immediately as soon as you receive this, & say Mr. Jones here are 20 dollars, I find I can lend you, you are welcome to it, if it can be of any service to you, I am sorry I have not more to spare.\'a0 He will be grateful to you, & he will then be able to bring his Wife & children a present, & even if he never returns it, I would rather lose it, than be \ul disobliging\ulnone .\'a0 It gives me great delight to oblige others.\'a0 I find it hard to refuse.\'a0 I expect that is the reason you are blessed with your dear Wife.\'a0 I knew it would break your heart, hard as it is, if I refused you.\'a0 I am certain Mr. Jones will return the money, so lend him some, & not be disobliging.\'a0 He must have been \ul hurt\ulnone  at your refusing, & you had more than usual in your purse, & ought to have been glad to have it in your power to assist.\'a0 Yesterday it was cloudy all day but did not rain.\'a0 Last night it rained, but stopped before breakfast.\'a0 It continues cloudy, & is wet & damp.\'a0 Perhaps it is well we have not killed the hogs yet, as it is rather warm, & they are so fat, they might have spoiled.\'a0 Jim is today putting the cabbage under a shelter.\'a0 Mr. Hoke he said intended killing hogs next week, I suppose if the weather is cold.\'a0 Jim said Mr. Hoke intended sending me 10 or 15 bushels of Potatoes, & when I had used those he would send \ul more\ulnone .\'a0 Instead of that he has sent me about 1 bushel.\'a0 I think Jim worked for him 7 or 8 days.\'a0 Willie & Anna are at school.\'a0 I told Willie I was going to write to you.\'a0 He asked if I was going to say they had been good children.\'a0 I told him I would say, \ul pretty\ulnone  \ul good\ulnone , which meant not \ul very\ulnone  \ul good\ulnone  & not \ul very\ulnone  \ul bad\ulnone .\'a0 He said I must not say, \ul pretty\ulnone  \ul good\ulnone  then.\'a0 I think they are as children go \ul good\ulnone , just as \ul good\ulnone , if not \ul better\ulnone  than \ul most\ulnone , & they have \ul honourable\ulnone  \ul feelings\ulnone .\'a0 Anna this morning got up before the fire was made, dressed, came down & got her book, & went upstairs, & commenced reading.\'a0 She is very \ul quick\ulnone , in all she does.\'a0 I feel very much interested in teaching them, & I am glad to bring the little knowledge I have into use.\'a0 I do all of Willie\'92s sums for him.\'a0 He is now even with Frank Hoke who is 15 & Willie is 8.\'a0 His last letter was written in a hurry.\'a0 Dilia Derbeck came home with Anna, & she distracted his attention.\'a0 He will write soon again.\'a0 Fanny is very sweet & good.\'a0 In the evening when she wont go to sleep, I lay her on the pillow on the floor, & she is happy kicking up her feet.\'a0 She can put her foot in her mouth.\'a0 She is so quick & active & lively & strong & sweet & good.\'a0 She loves Delia & me.\'a0 I expect she will not go to you.\'a0 She knows strangers & does not like them\'a0 & she will think her Papa a stranger.\'a0 I dare say my dear husband you would like to take a peep at home, but when you are homesick, recollect if you were at home, you would be worried by \ul Wife\ulnone , \ul children\ulnone , & \ul servants\ulnone , which worriment you have not now.\'a0 You have no one to scold you.\'a0 At Washington you will find it much pleasanter than Columbia.\'a0 There will be so much there to interest & improve you, & come \ul May\ulnone , \ul I\ulnone  may go on to see \ul you\ulnone .\'a0 Instead of six months you will have to go six years, but that circumstances\'a0 will determine, when you see how your business goes on.\'a0 I will make any sacrifices for your happiness, & I think it will be happiness to you associating\'a0 with the great & learned, & seeing men & things.\'a0 No happiness is without\'85, but perhaps ,you can even make arrangements, sometimes to have your family with you, hire out all our servants, & give up housekeeping in the winter, but I am calculating too surely.\'a0 I hope to hear from you tonight.\'a0 Yours truly & sincerely, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

\f1\b 112\
Monday morning, 6 December 1847\
Greenville\

\f0\b0 \'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I must write you again.\'a0 Willie just put a letter of his in the Post Office this morning for you as he went to school.\'a0 He was interrupted \ul twice\ulnone , while writing it, so at last has to finish it in a hurry.\'a0 I received one from you last night.\'a0 I thank you for the present you have bought me.\'a0 Tell Genl Martin I will wear it with more pleasure knowing that Eloisa has one like it.\'a0 I am sorry for Judge Richardson, but his family if he did not, ought to have perceived he was too old to be a Judge.\'a0 Mr. Hoke says he ought to be impeached, or at \ul least\ulnone  he seemed to think it was right, but I cannot say whether it was right or not.\'a0 If he heard he was to be impeached, it seemed\'85he did not resign.\'a0 Perhaps he thinks the resolution will not pass.\'a0 It seems such a \ul dishonorable\ulnone  ending, for an \ul honorable\ulnone  life.\'a0 As regards the Mexican War, you must have told me all your doing on that subject, to make me \ul uneasy\ulnone , for you know I have always thought you too \ul zealous\ulnone  about it, particularly as you are a \ul Candidate\ulnone , & it is such an \ul unpopular\ulnone  \ul War\ulnone , say what you will about it.\'a0 Mr. Orr perhaps is in favor of it, but he has the good sense & prudence, not to express his opinion \ul constantly\ulnone .\'a0 By the means you have taken to spread abroad yours, you will lose the Whig votes, the Calhoun men votes, & many of the Democratic votes, for even the \ul Democrats\ulnone  are opposed to the War.\'a0 You & Col. Town[e]s are almost the only persons & Mr. Ritchie & Mr. Polk in favor of it.\'a0 As for me I think this country ought not to have considered the Mexicans worth fighting, & though an inferior people, like \ul fools\ulnone , they are the hardest to deal with, & in the end we will have to give way to them.\'a0 Everybody is tired of the War, & I wish we had peace on any terms.\'a0 We have more territory now than we can manage.\'a0 Disunion is even now threatened.\'a0 Therefore we are better without more Territory, & I do not see how \ul that\ulnone  is to pay back the money spent in carrying on the War, & it cannot make up for the blood spilt which is worth more than the whole of Mexico.\'a0 \ul Candidly\ulnone  I have read the speeches made on \ul both\ulnone  sides of the questions, & I \ul sincerely\ulnone  decide \ul against\ulnone  the \ul War\ulnone , & I think it most \ul unfortunate\ulnone  it was ever commenced.\'a0 It would have been best not to have noticed them, like some quarrels that persons get into, which are hard to settle & could so easily have been avoided at first. It is well you say, you are happy independent of being elected or not, for I think your prospects now, if you inquire, you will find very bad.\'a0 Mr. Orr ought to be happy electioneering himself, & \ul you\ulnone  electioneering for him.\'a0 If you are \ul indifferent\ulnone  as to mind \ul being\ulnone  \ul beaten\ulnone , you ought \ul not\ulnone  to be a Candidate, for a Candidate should \ul strive\ulnone  to be elected.\'a0 I will consider it a \ul great\ulnone  \ul disgrace\ulnone  for you to be beaten by a man like Mr. Orr.\'a0 If you had acted \ul judiciously \ulnone I am certain you would have been elected.\'a0 Mr Orr I see attends to the \ul interests\ulnone  of his \ul District\ulnone .\'a0 He does not meddle with the Mexican War.\'a0 Mr. Polk who originated it, must terminate it.\'a0 I have said more than I expected, but you must recollect, in \ul your\ulnone  \ul absence\ulnone , I have no one to sympathize with me, or express my thoughts & feelings to, so when I write to you, I embrace the opportunity to express them to you.\'a0 You know I \ul love\ulnone , \ul respect\ulnone  & have the \ul greatest\ulnone  \ul admiration\ulnone  for you, but I think \ul sometimes\ulnone  you try to be \ul too\ulnone  \ul independent\ulnone , just to \ul show\ulnone  you are independent, & I feel certain by your course on the subject I have been writing, you have \ul weaned\ulnone  many from you, who would have supported you.\'a0 Tomorrow Jim & Charles will kill \ul half\ulnone  of the hogs.\'a0 We can attend to half at a time much better, & have fresh meat twice.\'a0 Mr. Hoke says some of yours would do better to fatten a little longer.\'a0 He only kills half of his.\'a0 He came over this morning to see me about it.\'a0 Mamma & Susan were here this morning.\'a0 Mr. Croft also made me a visit this morning.\'a0 I was engaged talking with him very interestingly about the Cunninghams &c. when Mamma came in.\'a0 Mr. Croft says Lawyers do not make as much as they did, that the Law is getting into disrepute, so you had better when Law declines, try & secure some other way of making money for your family, so you had better in future be more prudent how you act, for I think a seat in Congress now will be very eligible.\'a0I have been interrupted by Mr. Hooker who came to say he would go on putting up the fence on Wednesday, & would like Charles & Jim to help him.\'a0 It will be a great pleasure to me to see the fence continued.\'a0 I forgot to tell Mamma about Mr. Choice\'92s carri[a]ge, but I am certain Mr. Choice will not exchange, & his carri[a]ge I think smaller than Mamma\'92s.\'a0 It can hold only 2 in the\'85.Mamma\'92s though crowded can hold 4, his is the prettiest looking.\'a0 Vardry has been here.\'a0 As you are his \ul Godfather\ulnone , I would like you to bring him a present, a Toy of some kind.\'a0 Bring \ul him\ulnone  a present, instead of bringing one to \ul Susan\ulnone .\'a0 I told Mr. Croft you had seen Mr. Gliddon, & that you had a book written by him, so he borrowed the book to read.\'a0 Mr. Hooker said Judge Richardson ought to be made to resign, the general impression is that he should be made.\'a0 His last Circuit I suppose showed he was incapable of performing his duties.\'a0 A certain\'a0 age \ul 65\ulnone \'a0 will have to be fixed for the Judges to continue in office.\'a0 You once before introduced some such bill.\'a0 Suppose you introduce it this Session.\'a0 I know of no news whatever to tell you.\'a0 I have had a cold, but am now quite well.\'a0 I have written in a great hurry, & often been interrupted.\'a0 Aunt Eliza wrote word that Susan on her return from Columbia lost her Trunk.\'a0 The Omnibus in which it was placed went first to the Wilmington boat, & it must have been placed on board the boat by mistake.\'a0 It contained \ul all\ulnone  of Susan\'92s clothes, all of them new.\'a0 She had fitted herself up \ul completely\ulnone , all of their Jewels, & a valuable package for Miss Elmore, & presents made Susan in Columbia.\'a0 The loss she says is not much less than 300 dollars.\'a0 Every effort has been made to recover it but without success.\'a0 Alston\'92s wife she says, is a lovely gentle being, intelligent & pious.\'a0 They are all very much pleased with her.\'a0 She sent Mamma a Slice of Wedding cake.\'a0 You will be glad to hear from me, I know, though I reason with you on some of your acts.\'a0 It is all for your good.\'a0 Fanny is crying for me.\'a0 Yours truly, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\

