\cf0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just put Fanny asleep, & will embrace the opportunity while she is in the cradle to write to you.\'a0 Yesterday was the great Hog killing day.\'a0 I changed my mind about killing only \ul half\ulnone , & had \ul all\ulnone  killed \ul except\ulnone  \ul one\ulnone  that is \ul crippled\ulnone  & that Jim thought ought \ul not\ulnone  to be killed.\'a0 He has turned it into the Stable yard; one we killed after you went, so that left \ul 12\ulnone  to be killed yesterday.\'a0 Today Charles is cutting them up & salting them & Delia & Minerva are drying the Lard.\'a0 Unfortunately, it is a delightful \ul mild\ulnone  day, but Charles thinks it will turn cold again, & that there is no danger of the meat spoiling.\'a0 I was glad to have the hogs killed so as to save your Corn.\'a0 This morning was cloudy, & looked like rain.\'a0 It was the day Mr. Hooker was to have continued putting up the Fence, but as the weather seemed unfavorable, but he told Jim, he disliked throwing down the fence in such weather, so he had better haul wood, that he might not be interrupted.\'a0 When he \ul did\ulnone  commence, since then, the weather has improved, but I hope it will continue so, & that he will begin tomorrow.\'a0 Mr. Elford sent yesterday to let me know he was going to Columbia, & would take anything to you, so I sent you your purse, that you might have an opportunity of showing it, it is so pretty, but recollect that you are not to \ul use\ulnone  it.\'a0 It is to be reserved for \ul Washington\ulnone , & to hold the first money that you receive \ul there\ulnone .\'a0 I wrote to Pamela, to thank her, & to tell her she must still write the note she intended to have sent with it.\'a0 Mr. Croft says Mrs. B\'85 was at Mrs. Cunninghams.\'a0 Mr. Croft soon goes to town, to wile away he says the \ul loneliness\ulnone  of the Winter.\'a0 I told him he ought to bring a companion back with him, to wile away the Winter \ul here\ulnone .\'a0 He said he was afraid his case was \ul hopeless\ulnone .\'a0 So you see he regards children & grandchildren as nothing, for he could have his daughter & her children to pass the whole Winter here with him, but he is not satisfied, he wants a \ul Wife\ulnone ; no one like a \ul Wife\ulnone .\'a0 Mrs. Pearsons children are sick at present, so she cannot go when Mr. Croft does.\'a0 In January one of her brothers will come for her.\'a0 She must have found it \ul unpleasant\ulnone  with her husband in Florida, or I think she would have remained, where she would have a \ul settled\ulnone  \ul home\ulnone .\'a0 In the last letter I wrote you, I gave you a good deal of advice on the Mexican War.\'a0 I have since come to the conclusion not to meddle with Politics, but leave you to act as you choose, though of course hearing as much of politics as I do, I must form an opinion, but I believe my opinion is as Judge Colcocks used to be of the roads; if you take \ul one\ulnone  side I am always afraid you have taken the \ul wrong\ulnone  side, & that the \ul other\ulnone  \ul side\ulnone  is the \ul right\ulnone  one so I do not like you to be too obstinate on the side you have taken, & you must promise me to think of your own \ul interest\ulnone , even while you are \ul acting\ulnone  \ul conscientiously\ulnone , & I will not advise you.\'a0 Aunt Eliza said in her last letter said Cousin Isaac was in Columbia, with what \ul prospect\ulnone  she hardly knew.\'a0 Is he a Candidate for Attorney General, & does it come on in this Session.\'a0 If it does, & he \ul is\ulnone  a Candidate, without \ul wishing\ulnone  to advise you, you must vote for him on account of \ul Aunt\ulnone  \ul Eliza\ulnone , who I esteem as one of the \ul best\ulnone  of my \ul friends\ulnone  & know she would be \ul hurt\ulnone , if you did not vote for Cousin Isaac.\'a0 I am anxious what has been done with Judge Richardson.\'a0 I\'a0 have nothing interesting \ul at\ulnone  \ul all\ulnone  to write 