\f0\b0 \'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I hope I am going to write, now, one of my \ul last\ulnone  letters to you, that you will \ul very\ulnone  \ul soon\ulnone  be at \ul home\ulnone .\'a0 The remainder of my letters I promise you shall be \ul pleasant\ulnone  ones, for I do not intend to give you any more \ul advice\ulnone , & only wonder that I should have ever set up \ul my\ulnone  \ul will\ulnone  & \ul judgement\ulnone , in opposition to \ul yours\ulnone , you know you are in my opinion \ul incomparable\ulnone .\'a0 I received two \ul delightful\ulnone  letters from you Wednesday night.\'a0\'a0 I wish you had written me two \ul every\ulnone  \ul Mail\ulnone .\'a0 Your letters have been my \ul chief\ulnone  \ul pleasure \ulnone since you left.\'a0 They compensate me a \ul little\ulnone  for your absence.\'a0 I thank you for \ul all\ulnone  you have got for us.\'a0 You are so \ul generous\ulnone , that when away from me, I believe there is no wish of mine you would not gratify.\'a0 I am always afraid to express a wish, knowing you will go \ul beyond\ulnone  it.\'a0 You deserve a \ul good\ulnone  \ul Wife\ulnone , & I will be a \ul kind\ulnone  \ul sweet \ulnone wife to you.\'a0 I wish you to love your \ul Home\ulnone  & those \ul in\ulnone  it \ul above\ulnone  \ul every\ulnone  thing.\'a0 They ought to constitute your \ul chief\ulnone  \ul happiness\ulnone , but your duty to your \ul country \ulnone also, must not be forgotten, & you are so well fitted to be of service to your Country, that you must be willing even at a sacrifice to your \ul feelings\ulnone , to devote your talents & all the gifts you possess for your Countrys interest.\'a0 My only fear has been, whether in going to Congress, you can still \ul support\ulnone  your family, but I have thought what you made by \ul going \ulnone would compensate for what you lose in \ul practice\ulnone , & as Law business is \ul declining\ulnone , perhaps you would do just as well, as you will not make as much in future at the Law.\'a0 Except in Equity & that business, you can still carry on almost as well as if you were here all the time.\'a0 I think perhaps you can even carry your \ul family\ulnone  to Washington \ul sometimes \ulnone if you are elected.\'a0 Mr. Barnwell Rhett who is very economical did.\'a0 Housekeeping is expensive, & if we give up Housekeeping a \ul whole\ulnone  \ul Winter\ulnone , & hire out \ul all\ulnone  our servants, \ul except one\ulnone  who will stay at home to take care of the negro children & the animals, this will enable us to pay the board of our family at Washington.\'a0 However after you go on one Winter & see how matters are, you can make some pleasant arrangement I know.\'a0 One thing I am \ul determined\ulnone  on, & that is not to have as many servants about us as we now have.\'a0 It is a useless expense, the feeding & clothing so many\'a0 & losing the interest on the money they cost.\'a0 I have done so well without Edward, that I will be sorry when he comes back, & I think then we must hire out Lindy, or put her out to Mary McLeod; but I must not fill up my letter with all these plans.\'a0 I only mention them, that you may know we \ul can\ulnone  live more economically, if there is a \ul necessity\ulnone  for it. & to beg you not to have any \ul misgivings\ulnone  on your \ul future\ulnone  \ul course\ulnone .\'a0 Your judgement is so \ul good\ulnone  that I do not think you would have \ul formed\ulnone  such plans for yourself if they have been \ul wrong\ulnone , & I am not going to \ul worry\ulnone  about the election, but leave you to manage it as you think best.\'a0 \ul Hoping \ulnone that you will manage us to be \ul successful\ulnone .\'a0 You do not write a \ul scrawl\ulnone , your writing is as plain to me as \ul print\ulnone , only \ul sometimes\ulnone  the name of an \ul individual \ulnone I cannot make out, but the name I asked you about I \ul told \ulnone Willie looked like \ul Symms\ulnone , you spelt it with a y , but I did not think it was \ul Simms\ulnone , because I did not know \ul he \ulnone knew much about \ul Congress\ulnone , or even \ul knew\ulnone  Mr. Orr.\'a0 I had forgotten he was once a member of the Legislature himself.\'a0 Since our Hogs were killed, the weather has become \ul warm\ulnone , but many have killed, even since it became warm, so I suppose there is no danger of our Meat spoiling, & that it will turn\'85soon again.\'a0 Yesterday it rained, today it is cloudy & looks like rain, so our fence has not been commenced yet.\'a0 Margaret this week sent to beg me to let Eliza go & help her work.\'a0 I asked the servant who she was working for, & among others she mentioned, she was making a \ul Wedding\ulnone  \ul dress\ulnone  for \ul Miss\ulnone  \ul Foster\ulnone .\'a0 I asked when she was to be married.\'a0 She said Christmas.\'a0 So Harriet Foster must have been accepted.\'a0 Dr. Hillhouse, so much for owning a few negroes, it makes up even for lameness.\'a0 I am \ul glad\ulnone  she is to be married, for I would be sorry that a \ul misfortune\ulnone  debar her of happiness in this life,\'a0 but certainly it is owing to what she \ul has\ulnone , not what she \ul is\ulnone , that she should be chosen, & it does not say much for the young man.\'a0 I have been reading the Mountaineer, but I do not take the interest in \ul Col.\ulnone  \ul Townes\ulnone  letters, as I did in \ul yours\ulnone  for I principally wish to hear about \ul you\ulnone , & of course when you wrote, you mentioned all you did.\'a0 I see Col. Townes is going to introduce the bill I told \ul you\ulnone  to, limiting the Judge to 65.\'a0 It will\'85the Judges feelings, & they will retire from the Bench\'a0 with \ul honor\ulnone , except, they will be apt to \ul conceal\ulnone  their age & \ul never\ulnone  \ul reach\ulnone  \ul 65\ulnone .\'a0 Willie & Anna are at school.\'a0 Anna often lays the supper table.\'a0 The other evening after laying it, she ran in the kitchen & brought in the supper.\'a0 She said, you must write & tell papa I brought in \ul every\ulnone  \ul thing\'a0 \ulnone except the \ul Tea\ulnone .\'a0 I said yes, & \ul every\ulnone  \ul thing\ulnone  was the \ul hot\ulnone  \ul water\ulnone  & \ul bread\ulnone , she said the \ul Molasses\ulnone  too.\'a0 Frank repeats constantly, \'93why don\'92t Pa come.\'94\'a0 I told him of the pretty knife you have bought him.\'a0 He wants to know how many \ul blades\ulnone  it has, is very much afraid it has \ul not\ulnone  \ul two\ulnone .\'a0 He must have \ul two\ulnone  \ul blades\ulnone , he says like\'85. as he calls Willie.\'a0 Fanny has had a cold, but it is almost well now.\'a0 She wets her clothes so from \ul drivelling\ulnone .\'a0 It is impossible to keep her from catching cold.\'a0 She presses her gums together, as if they hurt her.\'a0 I hope before long she will have some Teeth.\'a0 We were not able to go to Mrs. Perry Duncan\'92s Thursday, as I expected.\'a0 I do not know if we can go at all, but if possible we will go one day next week.\'a0 I want to ask Mr. & Mrs. Arthur to pass one day with me, before you return, if not after you come back.\'a0 I told her I was going to.\'a0 Cousin Isaac\'92s Wife is not \ul amiable\ulnone , but \ul selfish\ulnone  in the \ul extreme\ulnone  & so \ul fussy\ulnone .\'a0 She had a child after I left last Winter.\'a0 She did not nurse it, & now expects to have another, & Aunt Eliza says, she will not \ul leave\ulnone  the \ul house \ulnone except to \ul ride\ulnone , & if she had kept her own counsel, she would have gone out some time longer, without anyone knowing even, she was in that way.\'a0 I dare say she is not an \ul amiable\ulnone  \ul wife\ulnone .\'a0 She is too selfish \ul even\ulnone  for \ul that\ulnone .\'a0 I expect \ul she\ulnone  \ul made\ulnone  cousin Isaac leave Alabama.\'a0 For Aunt Eliza\'92s sake, I would like him elected, his own too, as I am sorry for him.\'a0 Although you have never been a particular friend of his, you must do what you \ul consistently\ulnone  can for him, but I expect \ul no\ulnone  \ul election\ulnone  comes on now.\'a0 I have heard of none, & I forgot I must not \ul advise\ulnone  \ul you\ulnone .\'a0 I will be \ul disappointed\ulnone  if I do not hear from you tonight.\'a0 Mamma is not well, the rest as usual.\'a0 Yours, E.F.P.\
