\f1\b 127\
Saturday night, 1 April 1848\
Greenville\

\f0\b0 \'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I will write you a few lines tonight, to send by Mr. Elford tomorrow.\'a0 I wrote you a long letter by Mail, a few days ago, directed it to Anderson, thinking you would be there Thursday, to receive it, but in your letter to me, you mentioned you expected to leave Anderson, Wednesday morning.\'a0 If you did, you cannot have received my letter, & I am very sorry for it.\'a0 I would be sorry for it never to be read by \ul you\ulnone , for whom it was intended, & very sorry it should be read by anyone else.\'a0 It contained all that occurred Sunday Monday & Tuesday after you left.\'a0 It mentioned a visit Mr. Croft paid me, & his conversation, & had some \ul advice\ulnone  in it, that I think might be of benefit to you for \ul life\ulnone .\'a0 I do not like to repeat over again in this letter, what I said in that, for you may perchance have received it, but if you have \ul not\ulnone , you must write to the Post Master to forward it to you immediately.\'a0 Perhaps some are going to Pickens might carry it to you.\'a0 If not, have it sent by Mail.\'a0 I received your letter by Mr. Elford, & it gave me great pleasure, particularly as it contained \ul good\ulnone  \ul news\ulnone .\'a0 I only hope you are not \ul deceiving\ulnone \'a0 yourself, as you think Mr. Orr is \ul himself\ulnone , but it seems to me so impossible that Mr. Orr should be preferred to \ul you\ulnone , that I cannot but think you will be elected.\'a0 Mr. Orr I expect is like one of the Candidates for Sheriff at the last Election here.\'a0 He you know was confident of being elected, until Mr. Goodlett came out. He had such a high opinion of his own merits, he thought the people must have the same. But he was greatly mistaken, & I hope in this instance someone will [page torn]\'a0 themselves \ul greatly\ulnone  \ul mistaken\ulnone  too.\'a0 It would \ul rejoice\ulnone  me so to have this\'85person \ul beaten\ulnone  & \ul badly\ulnone  beaten, for daring to oppose \ul you\ulnone , who is so much better fitted than he is, to assist in the councils of the nation, & so much better \ul entitled\ulnone  to it.\'a0 You must my dear try your \ul best\ulnone , do not deceive yourself, & if unsure, you must as Mr. Croft said, make \ul assurance\ulnone  \ul doubly\ulnone  \ul sure\ulnone .\'a0 Papers have come for you, & only two letters which I send to you.\'a0 Mrs. Thompson continues the same.\'a0 I hear the Doctors say, though so low, she may linger yet several weeks.\'a0 Mrs. Hay is very ill with \ul Consumption\ulnone , so of course she cannot get well..\'a0 Mrs. James Williams (Ann D\'92Oyley) has a \ul son\ulnone , & Mrs. Barnard Cleveland an infant.\'a0 I first hear it was a daughter, then a son, so I do not know which it is.\'a0\'a0 Mrs. Bryan & Henrietta D\'92Oyley came to see me yesterday.\'a0 I sent Mrs. D\'92Oyley this week, \ul four\ulnone  of the \ul largest \ulnone of Mrs. Griffins Hams.\'a0 They weighed 62 \'bd pounds.\'a0 Miss Williford & Emma Service came to see me day before yesterday.\'a0 They asked if you would take a bundle to Pickens for Mrs. Duloc.\'a0 I said you were not here, but I intended writing by Mr. Elford, & expected he would take the bundle, so I sent to him to know & he said yes, anything he would take.\'a0 So I send the bundle, & you must give it to someone to carry to Mrs. Duloc.\'a0 They are things she wrote to Miss Wiliford to buy for her.\'a0 I have been busy in the garden all this week, & have almost got it into order.\'a0 Mary only has been working in it.\'a0 Delia has pain in her chest & neck, so does not seem to be of much use there.\'a0 Mary is a first rate hand.\'a0 I have let Lindy go to the farm to\'85Corn.\'a0 Mary shall go next week, but she ought not to work too hard now.\'a0 Minerva says she herself expects to be confined in June, so Mary I expect I should think expected much sooner.\'a0 The garden looks very nicely.\'a0 I have planted some of all the seeds.\'a0 Miss Williford said they were planting their \ul second\ulnone  crop of Squashes, Cucumbers, Okra &c. so I thought it high time our \ul first\ulnone  crop should be planted.\'a0 I looked at the plants today Mrs. Cunningham gave me, & they are most of them putting out leaves already.\'a0 The Mountain Ash,\'85&c. so I hope all will live.\'a0 The incident you mention of Esquire Long, his saying I asked him if I was not as good looking as Susan, is quite a \ul mistake\ulnone .\'a0 I have such a \ul good\ulnone  \ul memory\ulnone , that such a thing I would not have forgotten, & besides it does not sound like me.\'a0 It seems to ne I recollect Susan\'92s saying someone praised me, & added by way of complement, so that she might not be offended, that she was almost as good looking.\'a0 Something of this kind I think occurred.\'a0 I walked to Mamma\'92s this afternoon with all the children.\'a0 In my other letter I mentioned going there last Monday afternoon.\'a0 They inquired after you.\'a0 Mrs. Butler stopped one day & left Headleys \'93Washington & His Generals\'94, & asked for the second vol.\'a0 She expected to meet Behethland here, but Behethland had not come.\'a0 She did not come in.\'a0 She said I must go & see her.\'a0 She was going to be ceremonious.\'a0 I have been out only 3 times since you left, once to church & twice to Mamma\'92s.\'a0 Willie is still head.\'a0 He will soon finish his History book, & then he wishes to commence Geography.\'a0 Anna is full of May day.\'a0 Monday they are to elect their Queen.\'a0 Frank & Fanny are well.\'a0 I know of no \ul news\ulnone  to tell you.\'a0 I long to hear from you again.\'a0 After Pickens Court is over, you had better employ the remainder of the week, in travelling over the District, going to places you may not be able to go to when Musters, or other gatherings take place, when perhaps you will be attending meetings in the other Districts, & you cannot like Mr. Orr divide yourself in half, & be in both places at once.\'a0 Make sociable calls at as many houses As you can, before you come home again.\'a0 Mrs. Bowen the person I bought Eggs & onions from once & made such bad bargains, was here today.\'a0 She says her husband is Robert Bowen & lives in Anderson.\'a0 Miss Williford says Dr. Alston left 60000 dollars to be divided among his 3 grandsons, & Mrs. Alston\'92s property is larger than his, so when she dies they will have more.\'a0 Mrs. Walker sent me word, she would have been to have seen me, but she had to walk now.\'a0 They had sold their horses.\'a0 I asked the servant why they sold them.\'a0 She said they were old, & her Master wanted to buy a better pair.\'a0 This is Saturday night.\'a0\'a0 The children are asleep, & I must now go upstairs.\'a0 Adieu, my dearest.\'a0 Ever Your obedient. faithful, & loving Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Pickens Court House\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 128\
Sunday night, 21 April 1848\
Greenville\

\f0\b0 \'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 As you have not returned home today, I will write you a few lines, which perhaps may reach you, & inform you how matters stand with your family.\'a0 I am \ul happy\ulnone  to tell you that Mary is a great deal better, Dr. Crook finding that it was not the \ul Morphine\ulnone , that excited her, & that she needed \ul sleep\ulnone , gave her a large dose Friday night, & in the morning she awoke in her \ul right\ulnone  \ul mind\ulnone .\'a0 She asked Delia about herself.\'a0 She thought from her feelings, she was about to be confined & was astonished when she heard she had been sick a\'85had her baby, had had convulsions, bruised herself &c.\'a0 Her sight is not perfectly restored yet, but that is improving, & Dr. Crook tonight said all she needed now, was a good nursing.\'a0 He yesterday said Mary would soon be able to take charge of the baby.\'a0 If she is not, when Mom Charlotte leaves, we must hire a woman with a child, to attend to Mary, & nurse the baby.\'a0 I have become attached to the little thing, but I must reserve my strength that may await me hereafter.\'a0 From the moment you left, things took a better turn.\'a0 The baby seemed to give less trouble & Mary seemed better.\'a0 I was sorry you could not know of the favorable change, as it would have been such a relief to your mind.\'a0 I hope you are this evening at Mrs. Cunninghams; at any rate I imagine you there.\'a0 You must do the best for yourself.\'a0 You know it is the universal opinion you have a cunning adroit opponent. The Carolinian & Charleston papers have come tonight, & Judge O\'92Nealls report on Col. Dunhams call.\'a0 I did not go to church today.\'a0 The children went with Susan & Mamma.\'a0 Tomorrow Jim says, both Charles & himself will work in the garden.\'a0 I am sorry I have so bad a pen to write with.\'a0 This is the 9
\fs24\fsmilli12222 \super th
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \nosupersub  day of Mary\'92s sickness, when if a change for the worse is to take place, it would have taken place.\'a0 As it has not, we have every reason to think she is getting well.\'a0 I asked Mom Affy today, if what Mrs. Horton said about Caroline\'92s asking certain questions was so, & she says there is not a \ul word\ulnone  of \ul truth\ulnone  in it.\'a0 I miss two silver teaspoons, & four yards of unbleached Homespun I had given Mary is gone, & a spool of thread of Mom Charlottes was actually seen in the hands of \ul some\ulnone  \ul one\ulnone .\'a0 Mamma & Susan paid me a visit going to, & coming from church this morning.\'a0 Mrs. Arthur is going to Virginia in a few weeks.\'a0 Mrs. Hoke came to see me this afternoon.\'a0 Frank will commence going to school tomorrow; he \ul wants\ulnone  to go.\'a0 I must now conclude, & go to bed, before my little charge\'85the children are all in bed.\'a0 I hope you will soon receive this, & that it will relieve your mind.\'a0 We have great cause to be thankful for Mary\'92s recovery, & that her child also is doing well.\'a0 Now if your prospects in Laurens are good, & you do not become inert, & let your adversary get the advantage of you, I will have no cause of complaint.\'a0 Take care of yourself, my dear husband, adieu, Your attached Wife, E.F.P.\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Laurens Court House\
\'a0\

\f1\b 129\
Friday afternoon, 5 May 1848\
Greenville\

\f0\b0 \'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I will according to promise, write you a few lines, though I have \ul nothing\ulnone  to write about.\'a0 I have just written a letter to Eliza Hayne to send by Mr. Wells.\'a0 I have sent her money to buy me, \'93the \ul Carolina\ulnone  \ul Housewife\ulnone ,\'94 so \ul you\ulnone  \ul need\ulnone  \ul not\ulnone  buy it for me, nor \ul either\ulnone  of the \ul other\ulnone  books I gave you the list of.\'a0 Keep the list, as I do not wish to forget the Titles of the Books.\'a0 At some other time, I may get them, but not now.\'a0 I thought it best for Eliza to get \'93the \ul Carolina\ulnone  \ul Housewife\ulnone ,\'94 because I was certain it could be got in Charleston, & in Columbia they may not have it.\'a0 Yesterday afternoon Mrs. Town[e]s & Mrs. Elford came to see me.\'a0 In the evening I got a note from Mamma saying Susan & Ann were both sick, Susan with dreadful headache, & she was very sorry, she had been unable to see you before you left.\'a0 This morning Jim came over & hoed a little in the garden, but I expect he could not do much.\'a0 He is not there now, perhaps he may have gone to the farm.\'a0 Today I let Lindy go with Charles to dross Corn.\'a0 She can go when it is necessary instead of hiring boys.\'a0 I have told Charles that any boy Jim hires, to send away.\'a0 We are not going to pay anything for hiring.\'a0 I sent the Peacocks & the Pigeons to the Farm. They are a good riddance, & if they cannot stay there, will have to\'85their exit out of this world.\'a0 This morning Mr. Littlejohn made his appearance.\'a0 He says he got here yesterday, two hours after you left.\'a0 He wished to know certainly when you would return, & to tell you what his business was, which ought to be commenced before the Equity Court sat, so I advised him to write to you, & gave him pen, ink, & paper, & he sat down in the Drawing room & wrote you a letter, & I sent it to the office for him.\'a0 The wind is now very high.\'a0 I hope you are making good use of your time, & wiping out the \ul tracks\ulnone  very fast.\'a0 You are a person, that can accomplish anything you choose, & in this instance I believe it depends \ul entirely\ulnone  upon \ul yourself\ulnone , whether you will be successful or not.\'a0 My opinion of you is such that I believe you cannot be \ul seen\ulnone  & \ul known\ulnone , & then the vote cast in favor of one \ul far\ulnone  your \ul inferior\ulnone .\'a0 The unfortunate reputation you have of being \ul aristocratical\ulnone , renders it absolutely necessary, that you should go among the people, & show them by your kindness & familiarity, that if you are \ul aristocratical \ulnone in \ul appearance\ulnone , you are not so in character.\'a0 It is\'85they should judge from appearance, for you know appearance indicates character.\'a0The truth is you are \ul reserved\ulnone , & reserved persons always appear proud.\'a0 Do not waste time in Columbia, but if you find your cases will not come on soon, return to Laurens & spend your time there to some purpose, or if your cases do come on next week & you will also be detained in Columbia part of the week following, arrange it, so you can return to Laurens to the Muster tomorrow week, & then return to Columbia.\'a0 You must not depend on your \ul friends \ulnone exertions for you.\'a0 There is no friend that you can depend on as you can on \ul yourself\ulnone .\'a0 Believe me it is \ul yourself\ulnone  alone that will elect you.\'a0 Do all \ul you\ulnone  can, & be \ul thankful\ulnone  for what aid your friends give you.\'a0 I have no objection to their \ul helping\ulnone , but it is on you the chief burden rests.\'a0 Fanny is crawling over the floor.\'a0 Charlotte is now my principal servant in the house & to take care of Fanny Lindy helped Delia wash yesterday.\'a0 We have done without Mary pretty well, so if ever we need it, we can dispose of some of our servants, particularly as the young ones grow up.\'a0 So if your property increases in no other way, it does in the value of your servants.\'a0 I have no news or anything interesting to write you.\'a0 It is only a little more than a day since you [page torn].\'a0 Last night was our hottest night.\'a0 Today for the first time I think, we have had no fire built.\'a0 This is a bad season for providing, no vegetables, so you would not be from home at a better time.\'a0 If I do not write by the next Mail, it will be that I do not know whether you are in Columbia.\'a0 Mr. Wells leaves tonight in the stage.\'a0 Write me as often as you can, though I would not have writing to me, interfere with your other duties.\'a0 I have written fast without stopping once, & I have managed to fill up a letter with \ul nothing\ulnone .\'a0 I cannot think of any advice to give you except to try your best, for your Clients, & try to make the Laurens people your Constituents.\'a0 With best wishes for your success believe me.\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 130\
Monday morning, 8 May 1848\
Greenville\

\f0\b0 \'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Again like a good wife do I take up my pen to write to you.\'a0 I wish to prevent your being at all uneasy about \ul home\ulnone .\'a0 I almost hope you will not be in Columbia to receive this, that you are in \ul Laurens\ulnone , where you ought to be, until your cases come on.\'a0 I will now think of all that has occurred since I wrote you on Friday.\'a0 Mary is getting quite well, & in a week when her baby will be a month old, she will go about her ordinary duties.\'a0 Jim is well now.\'a0 He drove me to church yesterday morning, & has gone to the Farm today.\'a0 Mrs. Butler was seated, it was early, & I had a long talk with her.\'a0 She asked where you were, & said I must soon go & see her.\'a0 She sent me Saturday a \ul very\ulnone  \ul pretty\ulnone  \ul note\ulnone , Miss Rodgers wrote me, & enclosed in a letter to her.\'a0 Miss Rodgers thanks us for our kindness to her & you for the beautiful breast pin & says she hopes to see us both at the North.\'a0 She has been sick she says & would have written before.\'a0 After church Mr. Arthur requested the Members to remain in, as he wished to say something to them, & the business was, that the pews should henceforth be \ul free\ulnone , persons still occupy the same pews they did, but instead of paying \ul pew\ulnone  \ul rent\ulnone , \ul call\ulnone  it a \ul subscription\ulnone .\'a0 He thinks adopting this plan persons will go to the church, as the pews are \ul free\ulnone , the congregation will\'85, the subscription will amount to more, than the pew rent does, but I think he is entirely mistaken, that many who now pay pew rent will pay less when the subscription is [final two lines on this sheet obscured] will now pay much less.\'a0 It would make no difference with me, for 20 dollars is little enough to give to Mr. Arthur for his preaching to us for a whole year. But I am certain also, money loving persons will pay as little as possible.\'a0 I carried Mrs. Rowland home.\'a0 She seems to be without horses at present.\'a0 She asked how Mary was, said a general interest had been felt in her on account of her suffering so much.\'a0 In the afternoon I walked with all of the children to Mamma\'92s.\'a0 Before I went a violent storm of wind & rain had occurred.\'a0 It was a whirlwind, but did not last very long.\'a0 At Mamma\'92s, I found \ul two\ulnone  \ul Oak\ulnone  \ul Trees\ulnone  had been uprooted, \ul one\ulnone , a \ul monstrous \ulnone one, larger than our Oaks.\'a0 Susan has had headaches all the week, but was up.\'a0 Mamma & Ann have both been particularly unwell.\'a0 I told Mamma that Mr. Luther McBee thought Mr. Orr would be elected.\'a0 She said that was different from what he told Susan, & she supposed he judged from what he had heard, that he told Susan he was standing with a circle of gentlemen, who were talking of the Election, & Mr. \ul Elford\ulnone  said he thought Mr. Orr would be elected, but Mr. Beattie said he thought \ul you\ulnone  would be.\'a0 Now Mr. Elford is your \ul friend\ulnone  I \ul believe\ulnone , & his opinion at that time was that Mr. Orr would be elected, so when your \ul friends\ulnone  think so, it ought to \ul alarm\ulnone  you, & make you determine to do \ul all\ulnone , that can be done to ensure success.\'a0 These \ul four\ulnone  \ul weeks\ulnone  Mr. Orr has spent in Laurens I am afraid will do \ul wonders\ulnone  for him, so on your return from Columbia, \ul you\ulnone  must spend a few weeks in Laurens & \ul rub\ulnone  out all the \ul tracks\ulnone  he has made.\'a0 You must not be too secure for yourself.\'a0 It is that feeling of security, that makes me fear for you.\'a0 I am afraid that Mr. Orr & his friends not feeling secure, will try so much \ul harder\ulnone  than you & your friends do, then they will in the end distance you.\'a0\'a0This morning at daybreak a storm of thunder & rain came on but it cleared up soon, & since I commenced writing, the thunder has commenced, & it is raining also & is very cloudy, except for Delia & Lindy who will have to come from the Spring.\'a0 I would be glad of the rain, for we need it greatly.\'a0 I put down my pen to go upstairs to shut the windows, & in the big room I found the rain pouring down into the Wardrobe, so I opened the Wardrobe & found my dresses wet, Boston\'85almost\'85& all the things in a fair way to be \ul washed\ulnone .\'a0 I will have the Wardrobe moved from behind the door, for it is too much trouble every rain, to remove the things out of it.\'a0 You must have the Leaks stopped.\'a0 I had to mount the Step Ladder & put three basins on top of the Wardrobe, & I am afraid more of the plastering will fall down.\'a0 It is raining \ul very\ulnone  \ul hard\ulnone .\'a0 Mrs. Earle went to see Mamma last week.\'a0 She said she had intended having a large wedding for her daughter & inviting all her friends, but now on account of Mrs. Thompsons situation, she would have a private one.\'a0 She said Mrs. Harrison was so envious of her daughters, & said such horrible things about them, that her daughters now would not speak to them, that Anne Harrison had not been to her house since her daughter Emily married Mr. Williams, that Anna said, Mr. Williams intended addressing \ul her\ulnone , but \ul Emily\ulnone  \ul supplanted\ulnone  her.\'a0 Anna Harrison also went to Mamma\'92s, & she asked her if she had heard of the great match her cousin was going to make, that she was going to marry a man nearly as old as Maj. Turpin, & who has illegitimate children in every direction, & that Elias Earle\'92s assurance was really great to think he was running for \ul Congress\ulnone .\'a0 It was presumption in him to offer for the Legislature.\'a0 My dear there is \ul one\ulnone  \ul book\ulnone  I wish you to buy me.\'a0 I enclose the advertisement that you may see it.\'a0 Mrs. \ul Cunningham told me no female should be without it\ulnone , so buy it for me.\'a0 My dear husband, I will send to town for it, if you do not, so save me that trouble, & buy it in Columbia \ul now\ulnone .\'a0 I am sorry to write on such coarse paper, but I have no other in the house.\'a0 Willie & Anna are at school, Frank & Charlotte are together upstairs & Fanny in the cradle asleep.\'a0 Miss Rodgers calls her the Rosebud, & it is an appropriate name for her.\'a0 No letters have come for you, only newspapers, the Cultivator & Southern Review.\'a0 Mr. Edward Earle has gone to Augusta & from there goes to Pendleton to address Miss Calhoun.\'a0 Susan says she has given him a hint to return & she will \ul accept\ulnone  him.\'a0 If this is so, Mr. Burt is mistaken in thinking she will only marry one who fills a large space in the world.\'a0 Mrs. Thompson is dying.\'a0 Mrs. Butler says it was a mistake in thinking she was better.\'a0 A Catholic Minister preached here last night.\'a0 A Catholic congregation I believe is to be formed.\'a0 I long to hear from you.\'a0 I will\'85on one letter until I receive another.\'a0 I will conclude by saying you must fulfil[l] the expression, \ul running\ulnone  for Congress, & not let Mr. Orr do the \ul running\ulnone , & you the \ul walking,\ulnone  for if so, you will be left far behind\'85, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

