\f1\b 132\
Friday morning, 30 June 1848\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I will write you a few lines to inform you of all that has happened since you left, to prevent your being uneasy & hurrying back sooner than you ought, & when you hear \ul all\ulnone , you will find you could not be from home at a better time than \ul now\ulnone .\'a0 Frances left yesterday, & she had scarcely gone, when Minerva was taken sick, & in a short time was delivered of a girl, & both doing well.\'a0 She will now be up when Frances returns in a month.\'a0 Mamma Susan & Mr. Arthur dined with us Wednesday & with\'85assistance I was able to prepare a nice dinner.\'a0 Delia was sick all day.\'a0 What with her sickness, the company, the ironing has been so retarded, that scarce any is done, & now Minerva confined.\'a0 I expect to live comfortably for a long time, as I have been living ever since Mary\'92s sickness.\'a0 So I advise you to take this opportunity & do all the Electioneering that is to be done between this & October.\'a0 You will fare better anywhere than at\ul  home\ulnone , for with Delia sick & at the same time our cook we will necessarily live economically, & it will be a convenient necessity.\'a0 Money is universally scarce.\'a0 Mr. Sharpe said he heard a merchant say, he did not believe there was 50 dollars in Greenville.\'a0 You had better bring back some money from Laurens.\'a0 I dare say if you try you will get interest money, or from someone that owes you.\'a0 If you can pay the money you have to without borrowing I will be so glad.\'a0 I never wish to go into \ul debt\ulnone .\'a0 You saw Mrs. H\'85 with me.\'a0 She\'a0 came to beg a great favor, that I would lend her four dollars, to pay a debt, but I had neither inclination or power to\'85her going \ul into\ulnone  \ul debt\ulnone , for the purpose of getting out of debt.\'a0 Before she left, Mrs. Walker came, with a subscription for the organ headed with her name 5 dollars, & she wished mine placed next.\'a0 I told her I had put down 100 for the church which I ought not to have done in your absence, & I was not going to contract any more debts.\'a0 She said if anyone gave for the church, \ul you\ulnone  ought to,\'a0 for you were the first Lawyer here, & had a most \ul extreme\ulnone \'85.\'a0 She forgot that she once said, no Lawyer made enough here to clothe his Wife.\'a0 She was quite vexed, & said she had done so much for the church, her \ul work\ulnone  would amount to 100 dollars, but that everyone must do as they chose, & I told her I thought so too.\'a0 The next time I will ask her how much she has\'85for the church.\'a0 Little did I think we would have so much cause to regret her joining our church.\'a0 If it was not for her, the church would remain just as it is, which it ought to until they have enough money to build a new one.\'a0 After she left Mrs. Tom Lowndes stopped to leave a bundle for Mamma, & begged me to go to the Working Society where she was bound, & said I must go & see her.\'a0 I told her I would go to the Society when I could, but that time will be very far off.\'a0 Yesterday Susan & her children dined here.\'a0 In the afternoon we set off to go to Mrs. Stones, but it rained, & we had to turn back.\'a0 It poured, & today Jim says the ground is too wet to plough, so this afternoon if it does not rain we will go, & then I will not take the carri[a]ge until the\'85is finished.\'a0 Willie went to the Methodist Fair, but he said he wished himself at home.\'a0 He was obliged to stay until after 11 until Frank Hoke came away.\'a0 I was uneasy & sent for him, but he was then on his way home.\'a0 I expect very little was made, but I have not heard.\'a0 I write to you my dear husband, though you did not request it, but I think if you hear that all at home are well, you will stay away with more comfort.\'a0 Otherwise you might come home sooner than you ought, merely to see how things are going on.\'a0 I wish your mine to be at ease respecting home.\'a0 I hope to hear from you this evening.\'a0 You must do all you can for yourself.\'a0 The time is approaching, & I tremble at the result.\'a0 I hope & trust that you will be successful;\'a0 you deserve it, but merit does not always bring its reward.\'a0 Art, intrigue, vanity & deceit, often triumph. Therefore it behooves you to do all that is \ul honorable\ulnone  to ensure success, & I think as yet you have done but little, & but little time remains.\'a0 New questions have been started.\'a0 You must try & see your way clear before you.\'a0 If you can you must see my friend Mr. Barksdale & the other brothers that you have not been to see yet.\'a0 I see all the communications you wrote for the Herald about Burnley & Johnson, in this mornings Mountaineer.\'a0 I hear Mr. Croft is to be married tonight.\'a0 I hardly think he would choose Friday, & Caroline Earle next month to Mr. Mills.\'a0 You ought to be thankful that your property is gradually increasing as you have now an additional negro.\'a0 Minerva[\'91s] children do not interfere with her work, as Mary\'92s baby did.\'a0 Frances came just at the right time,\'a0 She will stay one night when she returns.\'a0 I would like very much to go to Pendleton this summer, stay at Mrs. Heywards.\'a0 I always prefer boarding to a private house, (except Mrs. Cunninghams), but Frances pressed me to stay with her & said you may but the persons I like most Mrs. M\'85 for instance, she seems to have little to do with, never seen Mrs. Burt even.\'a0 The village is very quiet.\'a0 Susan said she heard Mr. N\'85 was going to stay six months in Stewarts store N. York.\'a0\'a0\'a0 You affectionate wife in haste, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Laurens Court House\'a0\
.\

\f1\b 133\
Monday morning, 3 July 1848\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received your letter last night, in which you say, you may not be at home till Wednesday.\'a0 On the strength of that, I will write you a few lines to \ul comfort\ulnone  you , & make you \ul happy\ulnone , as I know you \ul cannot\ulnone  be, unless you are informed \ul every\ulnone  \ul day\ulnone  or \ul two\ulnone , of the \ul health\ulnone  of your family.\'a0 We are accustomed to hear frequently from each other, that we are more uneasy from a \ul short\ulnone  \ul silence\ulnone  than others are from \ul months\ulnone .\'a0 You do not mention having received a letter from me Saturday, which you must have got, but in your haste forgot mentioning.\'a0 \ul This\ulnone  letter you may not receive, as you may leave Laurens before it reaches there, this being the case & not knowing in whose hands it may fall, I must be particular & not write with as much freedom as I generally do.\'a0 I only write because it may be to your interest to stay in Laurens some time longer, & if you hear that all at home are well, you will be induced to stay when otherwise you will hurry home to see how matters are going on.\'a0 I was very glad to hear from you last night.\'a0 I would have been uneasy if I had not heard, for I had been looking anxiously for you.\'a0 I am sorry \ul business\ulnone  should detain you, & I hope you will come home, with a \ul fee\ulnone  in your pocket.\'a0 I am certain some one of your Clients can pay you, so I hope you will induce some of them to.\'a0 I am sorry it did not suit you to accept the invitations you received.\'a0 I suppose \ul business\ulnone  prevented you, or you would have done so.\'a0 I have heard less about your Election than usual.\'a0 Mrs. Butler has paid me no visit lately.\'a0 I suppose she is waiting to have her budget full, before she comes.\'a0 Mamma asked Mr. Sharpe, what your prospects & he said, in Pendleton, they thought you would be elected by a majority of 1200.\'a0 Friday afternoon I went to see Mrs. Stone & Mrs. Sam Townes.\'a0 Mrs. Townes said she had recently been to Pendleton & heard very encouraging accounts, & all along the road they inquired, & they saw but \ul one\ulnone  \ul man\ulnone  who said Mr. Orr would be elected, & he was a barefooted ignorant person, & would give no reason for his\'85.\'a0 I do not like to tell you this news, for fear it may lessen your exertions which have never been great.\'a0 I would rather tell what your\'85friends, such as \ul Mr.\ulnone  \ul Jones\ulnone , \ul Mr.\ulnone  \ul Norton\ulnone  & \ul Genl\ulnone  \ul Thompson\ulnone  say.\'a0 I am glad for your sake that you have been making friends, & yet at the same time I am \ul vexed\ulnone  that your Election should be doubted, for it seems injustice to you, for a moment to think you can be beaten, by one your inferior in every respect.\'a0 I think this remark is rather free, considering my letter may be opened by those for whom it was not intended, but it is the \ul truth\ulnone , & even your enemies will allow it.\'a0 This is Sale day, but it seems very quiet, & I see no one coming in.\'a0 I am glad you are in Laurens, where there is more to be done than in Greenville.\'a0 Tomorrow is the 4
\fs24\fsmilli12222 \super th
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \nosupersub  of July. But I have heard of no preparations to celebrate it.\'a0 The Sunday school children are not going to march as usual, & have a Picnic, for which I am very glad.\'a0 It was all trouble for nothing.\'a0 Only one letter has come for you, from Walker & Bradford, wishing to know what had become of their case.\'a0 I paid a very short visit to Mrs. Sam Townes.\'a0 Jim thought it was going to rain, & hurried me off, but it did not rain after all.\'a0 When you come back, you must drive me out, unless I can have the carri[a]ge & take Mamma with me.\'a0 She seems very anxious to see Mamma.\'a0 Said her sister Mrs. Burt asked her, if she had seen Mamma.\'a0 Frances\'85her bag fully of medicines.\'a0 I see they are medicines such as she can easily\'85so I have made no exertion to send them after her.\'a0 The visit passed off very pleasantly, but it was just long enough, for after she left Minerva was taken sick, in a short time her child was born of which I have written you, a girl it is.\'a0 Eliza was last week at Mamma\'92s.\'a0 She has now come home to assist in working, but she seems very unwell.\'a0 She begged to go to Dr. Earle.\'a0 I let her go, & he has written me a note, saying her womb is affected & unless she is examined he can do nothing.\'a0 He sent some medicine for the nettle thrash which she has.\'a0 Delia is better again.\'a0 She & Mary have gone to the Spring to wash.\'a0 John drove us to church yesterday morning, & Jim in the afternoon.\'a0 Susan is still at the Parsonage, but I expect she will be obliged to go to the house Mr. Dupree lived in.\'a0 It is a very mean one & I am afraid she will never have a better.\'a0 I tell her she is the rich man\'92s wife without a comfort, & I am the poor man\'92s wife, with every comfort.\'a0 Caroline Earle is engaged to\'85.\'a0 I expect when Mamma saw her, she was considering.\'a0 Mamma sent her a message by her Mother, advising her to accept him, & Mrs. Earle seemed pleased, & said she would be sure & deliver it.\'a0 Mr. McBee heard that Caroline Earle was engaged to a gentleman \ul richer\ulnone  than \ul all\ulnone .\'a0 I saw Col. Dunham seated in the\'85of his Tin Shop yesterday.\'a0 He looked pale.\'a0 Ann heard that \'85 Dubose was to be married.\'a0 Clara was the authority.\'a0 She may have heard it from Margaret, who generally knows of the engagements.\'a0 Aunt Anna Turnbull sent Fanny a dress by Mrs. Tom Laurens.\'a0 I expect it was 6 \'bc a yd., but for \ul her\ulnone  it was a valuable present.\'a0 I now take the Shower bath every day, & find it very pleasant.\'a0 The first day the water was so cold, it took away my breath, & I could not stand it.\'a0 I now use water brought the day before.\'a0 Willie loves to take it, but neither of the other children.\'a0 I wonder Mrs. Cunningham & Pamela have not written me.\'a0 Stop & see Mrs. Barksdale on your way back & Capt. Conner, & others.\'a0 I hope you will receive this letter safe.\'a0 It is a medley like Aunt Harriett.\'a0 I am going to write to her now.\'a0 Stay as long as you ought in Laurens.\'a0 I wish you to be elected by an \ul overwhelming\ulnone  majority not by \ul hundreds\ulnone , but \ul thousands\ulnone .\'a0 When you return you must go to Pickens & Anderson, & if you wish it I will accompany you, though I had better stay at home, & attend to your interests in Greenville.\'a0 Your ever attached Wife, E.F.P. Mr. Croft will soon be home with his Bride, his 3d bride.\
