\f0\b0 \

\f1\b Tuesday morning, 10 October 1848\
Greenville\
\'a0
\f0\b0 \
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I feel as if I must write you a few lines by Genl Thompson, who leaves for laurens about 10 oclock today.\'a0 He will carry later news than mine, but I will tell of little incidents, that he will not mention.\'a0 He voted for you, but that is \ul all\ulnone  he did.\'a0 He has not \ul gained\ulnone  you \ul one\ulnone  vote besides, but on the contrary like some other of your \ul professed\ulnone  friends, has \ul tried\ulnone  to injure you by telling how many more votes Mr. Orr\'a0 would get at certain places than yourself.\'a0 For instance he said, at Pickensville, Mr. Orr would beat you 200 votes, & he only beat you 71.\'a0 Mr. Jones told a man from Pickens, that Mr. Orr would beat you at \ul this\ulnone  \ul box\ulnone .\'a0 I think in future Mr. Orr, Genl Thompson, & Mr. Jones must put very little confidence in their calculations.\'a0 So far the news from Greenville is \ul better\ulnone  than you expected, for all the boxes \ul I\ulnone  have heard from, you have got more than you expected & Mr. Orr only as much, or less than you calculated, except \ul Dickeys\ulnone  where not as many votes were given in as you thought, but of those you got all but \ul 2\ulnone .\'a0 Of the other candidates, Mr. Edward Earle is ahead, Smith next, Col. Town[e]s \ul perhaps\ulnone  next, though Mr. Hoke says he has fallen off wonderfully, for which I am \ul very\ulnone  \ul sorry\ulnone , for next to \ul you\ulnone  I wish him elected.\'a0 The fourth man will most probably be Elias Earle.\'a0 I will not tell you who voted against you.\'a0 Mr. Hoke says generally the most trifling worthless people from the country, some from Pickens & Anderson voted here against you, & I heard of one from the Sullivan neighborhood, two of the Paris\'92\'a0 voted against you, , the Fergusons, a Richard, a Kemp, from the country , of the villagers, \ul Old\ulnone  \ul Maj.\ulnone  \ul Turpin\ulnone , who is an \ul intimate\ulnone  friend of Genl Thompson, Tom Turpin, Charles Stone, Gaines, Isaac Hennings, & he did all he could \ul against\ulnone  you, boasts of having turned 4 men from \ul you\ulnone , to \ul Orr\ulnone  yesterday.\'a0 Mr. Wm Choice is \ul against\ulnone  you & doing all he can against you, & Tandy Walker is \ul against\ulnone  you.\'a0 He saw a man passing & asked who he was going to votes for, the man replied \ul Perry\ulnone .\'a0 Mr. Walker said, \'93Oh no! that wont do.\'94\'a0 The man in reply said, \'93I will vote as I please Sir.\'94\'a0 Choice & Walker are both electioneering \ul against\ulnone  Col. Town[e]s, \ul because\ulnone  Col. Town[e]s is for \ul you\ulnone .\'a0 They take men into a corner & electioneer in a sneaking underhanded way.\'a0 Mr. Nicol made Lark vote \ul for\ulnone  youwho was going to vote against you, because he said, because you tried to make his wife a free dealer.\'a0 The old man Lark & Palman were going to vote against you, but Mr. Hoke changed them.\'a0 Mr. Taft at the Mill, was going to vote against you, but Mr. Hoke made him vote for you.\'a0 He saw him put in your ticket, & afterwards heard him saying, he had voted for \ul Orr\ulnone .\'a0 Lewis Thurston voted for \ul you\ulnone , Dr. Turpin voted for \ul you\ulnone , S\'85thiel Martin voted for \ul you\ulnone , Smith who works at Mr. Cox\'92s voted for \ul you\ulnone , & Mr. Luther McBee says he is certain Mr. Peter Cauble will.\'a0 Maj. Earle voted for you Mr. Hoke thinks.\'a0 Mr. Orr said, if \ul Hoke\ulnone  could be kept away from the Dark Corner, he would get \ul 100\ulnone  votes there.\'a0 Hoke \ul did\ulnone  stay away, & he got \ul 30\ulnone .\'a0 So mention this circumstance to him and ask him to account for it.\'a0 I received a message last night from Mr. Durbec, saying he had heard from you at Laurens, & you begged him to tell me not to be uneasy foryou were getting a great many more votes in Laurens than Col. Orr.\'a0 It seems to me that there is some mistake in this, that time did not allow for a message to arrive so quickly.\'a0 I feel very anxious, for though the news from Greenville, so far is \ul good\ulnone . There are still other boxes to hear from, & \ul three\ulnone  other Districts, in two of which Mr. Orr is certainly to beat.\'a0 Yesterday, it was so quiet, that I would hardly have known that an election was going on, except from my feelings, it was a clear but windy day rather.\'a0 Today it is cloudy, & unfortunately has commenced drizzling, but it only makes me more thankful that \ul yesterday\ulnone  was a good day.\'a0 The vote in Greenville is larger than you expected.\'a0 You have been unlucky in having your friends absent & sick.\'a0 Mr. Croft intended if able to come out today & vote for you, but the rain will of course prevent him.\'a0 Mr. Spears is sick & cannot leave his room.\'a0 Mamma stopped yesterday to inquire after him, & Mr. Spears said, it made him more sick the disappointment, at not being able to come out to vote for you.\'a0 He has diarrhea, passes blood.\'a0 Dr. Earle, Mr. Poinsett, Mr. Arthur & others are absent.\'a0 Dr. Crittenden & his sons voted for you.\'a0 John Crittenden wrote the tickets for Mr. Hoke.\'a0 I feel grateful to your friends here, Mr. Hoke, Taylor, Dill & Others I will be always obligated to, but those who voted \ul against\ulnone  such as Maj. Turpin &c. I will \ul never\ulnone  forgive; for Orr\'92s being a Taylor man is \ul no\ulnone  \ul excuse\ulnone .\'a0 It ought to have made him contemptible in their opinion, knowing he only went for Taylor, to gain their \ul votes\ulnone ; & the men who \ul voted\ulnone  for you, but were not in their \ul hearts\ulnone  for you, & tried to \ul injure\ulnone  you by saying you would not be elected\'a0 & would hardly get any votes at such & such places, are the worst of all, & they have sunk in my \ul esteem\ulnone .\'a0 If they had been your \ul friends\ulnone , & such was \ul their\ulnone  \ul real \ulnone opinion, they would have kept it to themselves, but they expressed this opinion with a view to injure you.\'a0 It is raining now quite hard.\'a0 A great many people have come in already, but I am afraid many of your friends, will be prevented by the rain, from going in to vote for you, , & today the strong pull, the long pull, & the pull altogether is to be given, that is to make you successful, today the great event\'a0 is to be decided.\'a0 I am so sorry it is raining.\'a0 How I wish\'a0 there was a Telegraphic line to Laurens, & I could ask you, how you are coming on?\'a0 I do hope in Laurens you will get the majority you expected.\'a0 The paper I send you was furnished by Mr. Taylor.\'a0 At the Dark Corner Mr. Nicol gave you 5 more votes than he does, 175 instead of 170.\'a0 Mr. Orr\'92s minority are so small, that you will be able to tall to a man who voted for him.\'a0 Some of the boxes are not mentioned on the list you gave me, or they have different names.\'a0 Groces I cannot find, or Brushy Creek.\'a0 At Pickensville Mr. Orr got about what you expected, & you less.\'a0 Perhaps some of your friends went to other places to vote.\'a0 Mr. Hoke does not think Mr. Jones will be elected, but somehow it seems to me he will; his friends will try so hard today.\'a0 Do write me by Wednesdays Mail.\'a0 Last night I hardly slept at all.\'a0 Just before bedtime I heard the news, & it excited me.\'a0 Either \ul good\ulnone  or \ul bad \ulnone news keeps me awake, but the \ul former\ulnone  makes my thoughts much pleasanter when I am awake.\'a0 I do not see McDaniels mentioned on your list either.\'a0 While I have been writing I suppose more news has arrived.\'a0 I am seated at the window in my chamber with the blind hooked.\'a0 Little while ago I saw two buggy\'92s pass with gentleman in them.\'a0 It seemed to me they were friends of Mr. Orr\'92s come over from Anderson to electioneer for him.\'a0 They looked at the house so much, as if they had never seen it before, was what made me think so.\'a0 Mrs. Lowndes came to see me yesterday.\'a0 I told her she must make Mr. Lowndes & Mr. Wm Lowndes come in & vote for you.\'a0 She said she wished she had a vote she would give it to you; that Mr. Lowndes was then in the village & she expected would vote for you.\'a0 Mr. Shermans little son brought some apples, & I took 2 \'bd bushels, & told him his father must vote for you, & he said he \ul was\ulnone  going to, but I do not know if it was true.\'a0 I bought some Irish Potatoes from a person Molineaux. Who said he had just voted for you.\'a0 The rain has now stopped so I hope your friends will not be kept away.\'a0 You ought to be proud of the vote at Dickeys, all but \ul two\ulnone .\'a0 You certainly must inquire who those two are.\'a0 If you are elected, & Edward Earle, Col. Town, Smith & McKay all will be as I wish.\'a0 Mr. Jones has acted too treacherously for me to wish well to.\'a0 Perhaps he may lose by it, as Genl Garvin did.\'a0 At Burtons you did so well, all but 7.\'a0 Smith at Cox\'92s shop, voted for you of his own accord, because you were best qualified.\'a0 Charles Stone voted against you, because you voted he says against Richard Stone.\'a0 Mrs. Earles son in law\'92s have not acted I [word obscured] suppose as she wished.\'a0 If you are only elected my dear husband I will be so gratified, I must have my likeness taken again.\'a0 It will look so much happier than the last, & the reason I wish you elected is that you \ul deserve\ulnone  it, & I will feel for \ul once\ulnone , that \ul merit\ulnone  has met with its \ul reward\ulnone , that envy & \ul malice\ulnone  have been \ul defeated\ulnone .\'a0\'a0 We are all \ul well\ulnone .\'a0 I hope to see you safe & well next Tuesday as the representative of your State, but if it is ordered otherwise, I must be resigned, but I wish Col. Orr to be made to feel his \ul presumption\ulnone , & the Pendleton junto to know, as things do not happen as they \ul dictate\ulnone . & [word obscured] believe in prosperity or adversity.\'a0 Ever your attached, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Laurens C.H.\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 136\
Wednesday afternoon, 11 October 1848\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Mr. Taylor has just sent me the list of boxes showing how many votes you received.\'a0 You got altogether 23 less than you expected, & Mr. Orr 18 more than you expected, so that your calculation in that way was pretty correct, but at the separate boxes in some of them you were so much mistaken, that it makes me more anxious than ever. For the Sullivans were so successful in their exertions as to cause you to be beat at two boxes.\'a0 Therefore in Laurens, they may be equally successful, & occasion your defeat.\'a0 It is all decided now, though I am in the dark.\'a0 Last night, Mr. Hoke read me a letter from Mr. Sitton to Joe Powel.\'a0 He said it was thought Mr. Orr would beat you in Pendleton District 800 or 1000 votes.\'a0 Your vote in Greenville will makeup for that, but unless you get a large majority in Laurens you may be defeated.\'a0 I know of 10 men in this village who voted \ul against\ulnone  you, so I have \ul heard\ulnone , it may be a mistake, some of them & \ul others\ulnone  no doubt voted against you that I have not heard of yet.\'a0 Old Maj. Turpin \ul did\ulnone  vote for you.\'a0 He had said he would not, but he \ul did\ulnone .\'a0 Butler Thompson, Charles Stone, Isaac Henning, Joe Hayden, Tom Turpin, Gaines, Mr. Penible, Mr. Douglas, Mr. Walker & Mr. Choice voted against you.\'a0 Mrs. Wallace was here this morning, & she said Mr. Jacobs said at her house, that Mrs. Walker said to him, if \ul you\ulnone  were elected, she supposed you would call your dogs & feed them.\'a0 Mr. Lester said Dr. Sullivan was electioneering against you, saying you called the people vagabonds.\'a0 Col. Town[e]s, Mr. Smith & the two Earles are elected to the Legislature.\'a0 Mr. Lester says he knows of a dozen men at least, at Shockley, who if they had voted, would have voted for you, & yet did not leave their work to go to the Polls.\'a0 Mr. Dill did wonders for you at the dark corner.\'a0 Mr. Hoke worked well here & if he had had more like himself, says he would have saved you many more votes, but there are very few electioneerers, like Mr. Hoke & now I understand how much can be done on the day of election.\'a0 I am more uneasy than ever, for good electioneerers are in the class of Mr. Orr\'92s friends.\'a0 Your friends are generally those who do not pull & drag people to the polls, & force a ticket into their hands.\'a0 At Pickensville you got 73 votes, Mr. Orr 144.\'a0 Perhaps it was only guess work.\'a0 I do not know that the votes were counted out.\'a0 At Brushy creek you 35, Mr. Orr 60.\'a0 At Pickens C.H. Mr. Sitton said you were running ahead, at Bachelors Retreat Col. Orr, but he thought that a mistake.\'a0 At Gantts & the Trap you beat; at Stantonville & McElroy Mr. Orr.\'a0 I suppose tonight we will hear certainly from Laurens.\'a0 That news will decide the election.\'a0 Mrs. Butler was here this morning.\'a0 She says Butler Thompson told Dr. Butler he was going to vote for you.\'a0 I hear he voted against you, but it may be a mistake, as it was with Maj. Turpin.\'a0 The two Dr. Crofts came to see me yesterday.\'a0 Their father sent for the managers to come & take his vote.\'a0 They went, but afterwards said they would not take it, it was illegal.\'a0 A young Guinn would have voted for you, but because \ul more\ulnone  \ul than\ulnone  a \ul year\ulnone  ago he went to Texas for the purpose of settling, but did not like the country & returned.\'a0 Mr. Kilgore told him he must not vote because he had not been here 2 years; he had been more than a year.\'a0 Your friends are too scrupulous.\'a0 If Mr. Orr had such, he would get no votes at all.\'a0 I hope & pray Laurens may have done you \ul justice\ulnone , but Mr. Orr has powerful friends there.\'a0 I have seen no gentleman today.\'a0 I hope some of them will write, & tell you more than I know.\'a0 Mr. Thirlkill did a great deal for you.\'a0 At Doiuthits Mr. Orr beat you 11 votes; at McCulloughs 11.\'a0 Elias Earles brother voted \ul against\ulnone  you.\'a0 Mr. Hoke says if they had known that, the first day of the election, they would have paid it off on Elias.\'a0 I am so sorry Mr. McKay was not elected.\'a0 Col. Town[e]s saw a narrow escape.\'a0 Mrs. Wallace says she heard people saying Col. Orr was the poor mans friend; that you never bowed to anyone except when you were a candidate. She contradicted it.\'a0 Your Law cases have made you so many enemies.\'a0 Genl Thompson was electioneering for Mr. Jones, & said he did not know of four other men, who were so disinterested as he was, that he always acted from\'a0 \ul principle\ulnone , he disregarded his interest.\'a0 Genl Thompson says he gained you 500 votes by voting for you.\'a0 I rather think he lost you 500, by telling, how many places you would be beaten at.\'a0 He might have gained you thousands, by writing & speaking to his Whig friends throughout the Congressional District.\'a0 I am afraid no one comes to tell me news today, because they have heard \ul bad\ulnone  news.\'a0 I am sorry to close without hav[ing] something more definite to tell.\'a0 Mr. Sitton said at Pendleton you were getting one third.\'a0 Col. Irby Mamma heard , pretended to be for you, but was electioneering against you. I hope this is [fal]se.\'a0 The village has seemed to me very quiet.\'a0 I can [word obscured] imagine such important events have been going.\'a0 [Word obscured] hope you received my letter safe by Genl Tompson [word obscured] message Mr. Durbec sent me, saying you were doing well in Laurens, was a mistake of the servants.\'a0 I was sorry it turned out so.\'a0 If Genl Thompson influenced 500 votes, it was strange he did not influence his son.\'a0 My dear husband, your character for pride, & your abusing the opposite party in Law cases, has injured you to an immense degree, so I hope in future you will pursue a different course, look & be more sociable, & not be so abusive in your speeches.\'a0 Your course has been of great advantage to Mr. Orr.\'a0 If you had gone about more, you would have convinced the people it was not pride you had.\'a0 There is nothing they dislike as much as that.\'a0 I have heard more chicken stories.\'a0 A Mrs. Gunter, said she would not come to this house to be degraded, that persons who came here to sell things, were made to stand \ul out\ulnone  of the house, said she heard it from good authority.\'a0 In Laurens I am afraid all that stuff will have injured you a great deal.\'a0 I am really sorry I have not some \ul very\ulnone  \ul good\ulnone  \ul news\ulnone  to tell.\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Laurens C.H.\'a0\'a0\'a0\
