\f1\b 137\
Sunday evening, 22 October 1848\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Mrs. Du\'85\'a0\'a0 has just paid me a visit, & I am so sorry you did not see her.\'a0 She came about half an hour after you left, & she told me a \ul great\ulnone  \ul deal\ulnone  about the Election, & gave me \ul great\ulnone  \ul comfort\ulnone , for she explained how much \ul chicanery\ulnone  & \ul cheating\ulnone  went on in the election, & which when you are aware of, you might another time counteract.\'a0 She says your friends are \ul indignant\ulnone  at the way things were managed & say Col. Orr shall never get as many votes again, & indeed they think that he did not in reality get all the votes counted him.\'a0 At Bachelors Retreat Ebenezer Verner voted for you, but did \ul nothing\ulnone  \ul more\ulnone  for you.\'a0 Sam Verner certainly voted \ul against\ulnone  you.\'a0 Old Mr. Verner said he did not care for either you or Col. Orr.\'a0 Old Whitfield she says acted a \ul double\ulnone  party at Bachelors Retreat pretended to be for you, so that your family even voted for him, & elsewhere abused you, & tickets that were written for \ul you\ulnone  & given to voters, he withdrew & gave others with \ul Orr\'92s\ulnone  name on it.\'a0 She says he acted most deceitfully.\'a0\'a0 Mr. Taylor Mrs. Du\'85 says turned against you two weeks before the election & electioneered against you all he could.\'a0 Says\'85were attributed to you, as being in favor of, which you never\'85that something I think Genl Cass said about poor people being sold, it was said was a measure of yours.\'a0 In short such \ul cheating\ulnone , \ul stealing\ulnone  & \ul corruption\ulnone  as went on at this Election, was never known before.\'a0 Mr. Lee says Orr is a disgrace to the country, & you ought to hold your head higher than ever, but he thinks \ul he\ulnone  could never be elected again.\'a0 Mr. Humphries the minister electioneered against you.\'a0 He is Wm Lee\'92s brother, told Mr.M\'85 Judge [page torn] was a great friend of yours.\'a0 Mr. Orr\'92s friends thought \ul you\ulnone  would be elected, & that is the reason they made such exertions.\'a0 Mr. Orr, your friend, I suppose, thought you would be, & did not exert themselves as they ought to have done.\'a0 Mr. Ben Hillhouse the gentleman who dined here, was a good friend of yours.\'a0 I hope you will hear a great deal from your friends about the election, & write me about it, & if they think so you ought to, & run again & beat the \ul drunken\ulnone  \ul demagogue\ulnone .\'a0 It is a disgrace to send such a creature to represent the State, & I hardly think the people would do so another \ul time\ulnone .\'a0 You have pursued such an honorable\'a0 & manly course, that I must believe you will be rewarded.\'a0 Your intellectual countenance. & fine commanding person\'a0 were not given you for nothing.\'a0 It is meant that you shall take a stand among the highest of Creation, & then you\'a0 will be appreciated.\'a0 Mrs. D\'85 says\'a0 all that was said against you was your \ul pride\ulnone , but the idle lies, about Brandy &c. were circulated.\'a0 They may have injured you this time, but another time, I think they will lose their effect.\'a0 If you are ever a Candidate again, I will put in the newspaper an especial advertisement for myself, saying all the idle reports of my \ul sayings\ulnone  are \ul false\ulnone , that I love the poor people, & have always been particularly kind to them.\'a0 Mrs. D\'85 threw a new light upon Mrs. Choice\'92s dislike to you.\'a0 She says Mrs. Choice\'a0 once thought you were going to marry her, & I believe it firmly, even if you do not.\'a0 You never have suspicions of that kind, but I dare say she would like very much to have married you, for when she was young, among her acquaintances in Greenville, there would have been none superior to you, or who a young lady would have been more likely to wish to make a conquest of than \ul yourself\ulnone .\'a0 So my dear husband, I feel very gratified & quite complimented that you should have chosen \ul me\ulnone , when I know there were others, who would have been glad to have bestowed themselves [page torn] & who also at the same time would have bestowed a \ul fortune\ulnone  likewise.\'a0 I must try & make you a good wife, & I assure you I would not change you now, for anyone else in the universe & as for \ul Col.\ulnone  \ul Orr\ulnone , he is not fit to black your boots.\'a0 I am too worrying a person, should have triumphed over you.\'a0 It would have been quite natural for you to beat him, but I think it must have been a most unexpected surprise to himself & his friends, when they found he was the successful one, but you must hold your head above him & hold it higher than ever, & he ought to put his in the dust when he knows how many tricks he had to resort to, to accomplish his ends.\'a0 Yes he triumphed, but he ought often to pass in rev\'85 all he means he used.\'a0 I wish you would mention to him or his friends, that they must have really determined to use all means, when he even tried to injure \ul you\ulnone  through your wife.\'a0 Tell them you heard what he said of me.\'a0 It was a \ul mean\ulnone  \ul thing\ulnone , & I wish him to \ul know\ulnone  it.\'a0 He ought to know that we heard it.\'a0 Mr, Pickens Mrs. D\'85 does not like, says he thinks only of himself.\'a0 I expect among all the Candidates in Pendleton District you had (except Mr. Lee) not one friend.\'a0 Tell Mr. Burt from me, that I always knew he was a false friend.\'a0 Mrs. D\'85 says Josiah is confined to the house.\'a0 Wilbern is staying with him.\'a0 Perhaps you had better return home from Anderson, & go to see Josiah from Pickens Court, for I\'85say he is in immediate danger.\'a0 Mrs. D\'85 did not know anything more of him than this.\'a0 She told me a great deal about the Election which I would like you to have heard, before you went to Anderson.\'a0 Col. Orr\'92s brother, though he was treating so for him, did not expect him to be elected.\'a0 I do not suppose anybody did.\'a0 Mrs. D\'85 will come & see me tomorrow again, & I expect pass the night.\'a0 I expect she will stay with me off & on while she is here.\'a0 You must certainly write to me by Tuesday\'92s Mail & I think you had better return home, & go to see Josiah from Pickens Court,\'a0 I wish you would go to Pendleton Village before you re[turn] next week on your way to Josiah, & see what the people there say. I think there will be a reaction in your favor, at least I hope so.\'a0 Mrs. D\'85 thinks Mr. Taylor acted shamefully, but W\'85field the worst of all.\'a0 I hope you will hear all she told me, & I suppose you will, when you see Foster, & Mr. Keith & others.\'a0 I have nothing to write about, which is the reason I dwell so long on one thing.\'a0 Willie is downstairs.\'a0 I have spent the morning in writing to you, & this afternoon I must read.\'a0 Mrs. D\'85 says Col. Orr can never again get the same number of votes, as he got this time, that the eyes of the people are opened, & they are disgusted at his electioneering, & this is the last thing I will say.\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P. Write to me Tuesday, whether you will come back, or go on to Pickens & see Mr. Lee if you go to Pickens, & he will tell how things were managed at Bachelors Retreat.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Anderson]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 138\
Monday morning, 27 November 1848\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 According to promise I have taken my seat at the desk to write to you, & I must commence with the business part first.\'a0 Mrs. Harrison has just left here.\'a0 She came to ask if I knew if you would buy Reuben, that Reuben was anxious you should buy him, & though she would get a higher price for him, from others, she would be willing to sell him to you\'a0 for 500.\'a0 She says her son James saw you, as you were starting to Columbia, & asked you if you would buy Reuben, & you said \ul yes\ulnone , you would give \ul 500\ulnone  for him.\'a0 She begs you to write to me \ul immediately\ulnone , so that I may hear by this Friday\'92s Mail, for next week she is to leave for Florida, so you must be certain & let me hear Friday night, & immediately as I get the letter, I am to let her know.\'a0 She seems exceedingly anxious you should buy Reuben.\'a0 I know not what to advise you.\'a0 She speaks in the highest terms of Reuben, says she does not know his age exactly, that he is 30 certainly, how much more she does not know, that Dr. Harrison bought him when her daughter Mrs. Earle was a baby, to go to the Mill, & Mrs. Earle is nearly 26, that he was a little boy, that he is sober & industrious\'a0 & made her last summer 10 dollars a week, that Mr. Cox speaks highly of him &c. &c. &c.\'a0 Write me an answer by Fridays Mail.\'a0 I will now speak of other matters.\'a0 Fanny is a great deal better.\'a0 I have not given her any medicine.\'a0 I hope she will be quite well when you return.\'a0 The rest of the family are well except John who now has the Measles, & Delia who though complaining, is better.\'a0 She is able to hold Fanny & today is cooking while Mary & Minerva are at the Spring washing.\'a0 The weather cleared up so soon, I expect you are almost sorry you did not go down in your Buggy, but perhaps the first day you might have taken cold, so it is all for the best.\'a0 I hope you & Mr. Keith had a pleasant journey down.\'a0 I expect to hear from you by Jim.\'a0 Mrs. D\'85 slept here Friday night, & \'85 slept here last night & this morning went to Mrs. Service\'92s to prepare to start.\'a0 They were to stop to bid me goodbye, but they have not come yet, so I expect they will not leave today.\'a0 Mrs. D\'85 had a pain in her face, which perhaps prevents her going.\'a0 The children & myself went to church yesterday morning, & Mr. Arthur preached a sermon on temperance, alluding to the Law lately passed by the Town Council, & said the community ought to sustain them.\'a0 Mrs. Tom Jones was at church.\'a0 As well as I could see, she was not remarkably pretty, looked very pale.\'a0 In the afternoon there was no service.\'a0 Mr. Arthur had a bad cold. \'a0\'85 the children & myself walked over to Susans house.\'a0 It is a very plain looking house, & seems built in the most economical manner, & ought to have had a chamber downstairs, which I think is essential in winter.\'a0 Mr. Hoke had a load of wood hauled Saturday for us.\'a0 It has all gone already, so Charles today has got one of Mamma\'92s horses & is hauling wood.\'a0 Jim cut up so little Sausage meat, that with the greatest economy, it has only lasted for 7 meals. & then we each had only two little ones, not enough to satisfy us.\'a0 I should think one hog, the trimmings from, would have furnished more meat than that.\'a0 A letter came last night from Walker & Bradford, saying they had forwarded a box to you.\'a0 It weighs a hundred pounds, the freight is 50 cts a hundred.\'a0 It is the box I suppose Aunt Eliza sent.\'a0 It will be here Friday.\'a0 A letter has come for you from Mr. Barclay who is now in Canada, patronized he says by the nobility & gentry & standing at the head of his profession.\'a0 He wrote to you for a friend who is writing a book on Indian traditions, & who wanted to know something of the Carri\'85, who lived in Georgia, & as you had interested yourself in Revolutionary Incidents, he thought you might be in possession of information relating\'a0 to the Indians, which might be of service to his friend.\'a0 His name is J.A. VanHeuvel, Ogdensberg, N.Y.\'a0 He was a classmate of Mr. Calhouns.\'a0 Another letter came from Mr. Berry & wished to know. If you would wish the Lumber that was at the Mill for Josiah, that Josiah had hauled off 88 cts worth more than he had paid for, & that if you needed the lumber he had, he would like for you to pay for it immediately, as he was closing his business & was going to Mississippi & that if it was not convenient to pay immediately for the lumber, he would rather keep it, that Josiah would have preferred getting it at Sh\'85s Mill which was in sight, but engaged it from him, thinking he would have finished it sooner.\'a0 I have no news to tell you.\'a0 The village seems very dull.\'a0 The weather is very cold.\'a0 I suppose you will wish the other hogs killed now.\'a0 You must write me by every Mail.\'a0 Your letters will be my chief pleasure in your absence.\'a0 I hope you will be able to get a new trial for Dr. Anderson.\'a0 You must speak to your friends in the Legislature for Cousin Isaac, Mr. Cannon, Col. Ware, Mr. Earle & others I am sure might be influenced by you, & do what you can for Wm Ed to retain the office of Inspector.\'a0 I am sure your speaking only to enemy would cause them to vote for Cousin Isaac, & you may with very little exertion do him good, for many would give their votes to the one who has first asked them for it, so you ought to have spoken long ago.\'a0 I am anxious Cousin Isaac should be elected, particularly for Aunt Eliza\'92s sake.\'a0 I have a bad pen to write with, & nothing to write about, which must be the excuse for this uninteresting letter.\'a0 When I hear from you, I will have\'85to write you, & I will try & get a better pen.\'a0 Anna went to school today.\'a0 I was reading a peice in the Spartan last night, which says children should not commence to learn until 7.\'a0 That those children who know the \ul least\ulnone  at \ul 12\ulnone , prove in after life the smartest men, that Dr. Adam Clarke when a child was thought rather stupid, that it injures the brain to exercise it too much.\'a0 I intend Willie to write to you sometimes instead of me.\'a0 I have so much work to do, writing takes up too much time, particularly when I have nothing to write about.\'a0I hope to hear certainly Friday your answer about Reuben.\'a0 Mrs. Harrison says until then, she will make no exertion to sell him.\'a0 She says Mr. Mooney offered her 6 dollars a month for him which would be 72 a year, but she does not wish to hire him out.\'a0 She seems very anxious you should buy him, says Col. Irvine would buy him\'a0 & give more than 500 but she prefers you having him, says she heard you were willing to give 550 but was advised by someone not to do it.\'a0 She says you told James before you started, that you would give 600 for Reuben.\'a0 I told her I had not heard you say anything before you left, that not hearing from her, I thought she had made other arrangements.\'a0 So my dear husband, in this instance I leave you to \ul act\ulnone  as \ul you\ulnone  \ul think\ulnone  \ul best\ulnone , for fear that I might influence you, & then be blamed by you.\'a0 If she is correct, Reuben would be an invaluable servant, but you know we must make allowances for her representations.\'a0 She says she knows you would not sell him, you would be so much pleased with him.\'a0 I wish you could see Fanny now playing about the floor.\'a0 Our carpet is getting so old.\'a0 I am trying to save to buy one.\'a0 If I show you the 10 dollars when you return, you must let me get one either send town or get one at Mr. Nicols.\'a0 Now adieu my dear husband, recollect when I give advice, I always\'85you to consider it, but \ul do\ulnone  \ul as\ulnone  \ul you\ulnone  \ul think\ulnone  \ul best\ulnone .\'a0 Late events have made me lose some confidence in your judgment, & place more in mine.\'a0 Yours truly, E.F.P.\'a0\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 139\
Friday morning, 1 December 1848\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received your letter Wednesday night, & am glad in writing this time to have a letter to answer.\'a0 Your letter as usual gave me great pleasure.\'a0 You know they are my chief source of pleasure, in your absence.\'a0 I regret, as well as the \ul Members\ulnone , that you are not in the Legislature.\'a0 It is a place suited for you, & I feel now that your talents have no field for their usefulness.\'a0 You ought to have remained there at any rate, until the Electoral Bill was passed, for you have been its great Champion, & others will take the credit from you.\'a0 As regards the Presidency of the Bank, it is a subject too important for me, to give any advice on.\'a0 Your comprehensive mind, can judge better of that, than I can.\'a0 I never could like some wives try to influence my husband \ul against\ulnone  \ul his\ulnone  \ul judgment\ulnone , what will effect his whole life.\'a0 You know what your prospects are in Greenville.\'a0 I have often wished you could be, where there was more congenial society for you, minds on a footing with your own, & with whom you would have pleasant intercourse.\'a0 I regret this more than you do, but such an important step , as changing your residence & your business, I cannot say one word either way.\'a0 Mr. Hooker was here today.\'a0 He says, he heard a Charleston gentleman, say at the Mansion House, last night, that Mr. Elmore wished to be Judge, when Judge Richardson resigned.\'a0 I wish you could be Judge.\'a0 I have always wished it, & when there is a chance of your succeeding, you must try for it.\'a0 The upper country Members are in the majority, & they generally would vote for you, so I think your chance would be good.\'a0 If you had thought of it in time, I would like you to have been a Candidate for Attorney General.\'a0 Being from the Upper Country, you would have beat both of the other Candidates, & that would be an eligible office, worth removing to Charleston for I wish you to get some office or other, & I hope there is still a chance at any rate of your being a Member of Congress.\'a0 You were \ul foully\ulnone  \ul treated\ulnone  this time.\'a0 As you say it is \ul doubtful \ulnone who will be elected Attorney, it behooves the friends of each party to use their influence, so I hope for \ul my\ulnone  sake, you will speak to your friends in behalf of Cousin Isaac.\'a0 I do not wish you to make strenuous exertions, but such friends as you can influence, speak quietly to.\'a0 He will lose all the Taylor Democrats & Whig votes I expect, having taken an active part on the other side.\'a0 I am sorry to hear Sarah Taylor is sick, but hope she is better now.\'a0 The box containing the Shrimps has arrived.\'a0 Aunt Brewton sent Willie a little Gold pencil case.\'a0 A few of our other friends sent presents to the children, & Shrimps to me.\'a0 I am glad to tell you, that my Gold Thimble is found.\'a0 Night before last, Lindy took the Candle out of the Candle Stick, to grease her face, & when she was putting the candle back, in the socket of the Candle Stick she found the thimble, almost concealed by grease.\'a0 I instantly conjectured, that Frank while at the stand, the night I missed it must have put it there, & that it was the spool that dropped & you picked it up the next morning.\'a0 So in the morning I asked Frank about it, & he says yes, he put the Thimble there.\'a0 Yesterday on removing the Fender to clean it, my large scissors was found.\'a0 So Mary is no longer implicated in those supposed thefts.\'a0 I hope now, my Che\'85, & other lost articles will come to light.\'a0 It was natural I should suspect her, when the morning after the Thimble was lost she stole an apple & a few days after a quarter of a dollar.\'a0 I believe none of us were glad to see Jim on his return.\'a0 We had got along so comfortably without him.\'a0 He is a worthless servant.\'a0 A plank has been off the carri[a]ge house a long time, & instead of mending it he let it remain, & in his absence someone got through\'a0\'a0 & took out a peice of leather.\'a0 The person knocked off another plank.\'a0 He yesterday was wearing the nice pantaloons you gave him, instead of keeping them for his dress pantaloons all winter.\'a0 I told him to take them off.\'a0 He said he had no others to put on.\'a0 I told him he must, & he then went & put on others, & I made Elizer make him a pair.\'a0 He seems to like to destroy his clothes, & every thing about him.\'a0 He has a bad temper & is at war with the whole world.\'a0 In contrast to him stands Reuben, who though I know is not perfection, yet he cant be worse than Jim, & must be better.\'a0 The day I wrote you he hauled two loads of wood for us.\'a0 He also hauled three loads for his mistress from beyond Mr. Brooks.\'a0 That was five loads in one day, & Jim scarcely hauls 3.\'a0 Jim took all day yesterday to clean the carri[a]ge & did not do the harness.\'a0 Today I told him to do that, but he is always so mysterious, he is never to be found.\'a0 Charles this morning cut wood, got his breakfast, & went to the farm before I was dressed.\'a0 He is so different from Jim.\'a0 Indeed there is no servant as bad as Jim & I would rather be \ul without\ulnone  \ul him\ulnone  even if you do not \ul purchase\ulnone  \ul Reuben\ulnone .\'a0 I feel happier when he is away, even if I have to give up riding but I hope tonight, to get a letter saying you will buy Reuben.\'a0 His mistress & himself today I know are very anxious, for I think Mrs. Harrison is a kind mistress, & wishes for him to get a good owner, for she sells him to you for very little 500 dollars, the interest of which is 35.\'a0 I am sorry I did not beg you to buy him, but I was afraid to, for fear you might blame me.\'a0 As soon as Jim returned as\'85& worthless as ever, I was sorry I did not beg you.\'a0 If what Mrs. Harrison says is so, that you told her son James, you would give 500, I suppose there is no doubt, but what your answer will be in the affirmative.\'a0 Otherwise I believe on my own responsibility I will get him, for I am so much without you, I need a good man servant.\'a0 Your first large fees you must pay for him & secure it, so he will not be taken for Mrs. Harrisons debts, & this I suppose you can do, as you did the farm.\'a0 If you will not buy him, then Charles must stay here, & Jim sold or hired out, & Charles learn to drive, or you get a buggy & drive me.\'a0 Jim knows you have thoughts of selling him & yet he does not do any better for it.\'a0 I hope my dear you will look at low Buggy\'92s with\'85, & let Jim carry your Buggy down for you, & see what you can get for it.\'a0 I am anxious you should have a nice Buggy with a cover.\'a0 You travel so much, you need a nice one, that will protect you from the rain.\'a0 I knew you would buy knives.\'a0 We would have done without large ones; small ones only we needed.\'a0 They could have been got cheaper in Charleston.\'a0 I am glad you bought clothes for you needed them.\'a0 The young\'85you do not need.\'a0 After being \ul 11\ulnone  \ul years\ulnone  \ul married\ulnone , it is too late for that now, your habits cannot be changed, so change it for another book.\'a0 I wish \'93to the Married, & those contemplating marriage.\'94\'a0 Mrs. Cunningham wishes all females only to have it.\'a0 I am afraid the Brooches\'a0 are not very pretty, as they are as cheap.\'a0 I wished one as pretty as you got before.\'a0 If they are as pretty I will be satisfied, & as they are so reasonable would like you to get me another, to give to Ann & one of those you have got I will give to Susan.\'a0 Willie says get him a \ul glass\ulnone  \ul slate\ulnone .\'a0 He is fond of drawing; bring Vardry a little present, as you are his Godfather, a \ul trifle\ulnone  will do, just to show you think of him.\'a0 Thank you for the fruit.\'a0 I sent some to Susan, Ann, Mrs. Irvine & Miss Payne.\'a0 It rained yesterday all day, & is wet today.\'a0 Yours, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\'a0\'a0\
