\f1\b 140\
Greenville, 3 December 1848\
Sunday night
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received your letter by Mr. Keith.\'a0 Mr. Long\'92s son brought it.\'a0 I told him to ask Mr. Keith to come & see me, but I dare say he will not.\'a0 I write to you tonight, because tomorrow I expect to be engaged visiting.\'a0 Jim arrived safely, as you have heard.\'a0 The two next days it rained, so he only cleaned the carri[a]ge & put up Elisa\'92s Stove.\'a0 Yesterday he hauled one load of wood, & some leaves.\'a0 All next week I am going to use the carri[a]ge, so I expect he will do very little work, but Charles will work & Jim as much as I can spare him. Since writing the above, Mr. Keith has paid me a visit.\'a0 He has just left, so I will continue.\'a0 You will be surprised to hear, that I have \ul not\ulnone  \ul purchased\ulnone  Reuben.\'a0 You merely said, if \ul I\ulnone  desired it, you would purchase him.\'a0 This permission, I do not consider authority enough.\'a0 I will tell you all that has passed.\'a0 After receiving your letter, I went to tell Mrs. Harrison, what you said, & that I would not decide unless I knew your wish, to purchase Reuben.\'a0 She said I must decide at once, for Mr. Beattie & Mr. McBee both wanted him, so I sent for Mr. Hoke, to get advice from him. He said he had never thought much of Reuben, but admitted he knew nothing against him, except that he drove Mrs. Harrisons horses hard, that he knew he would suit \ul me\ulnone  better than Jim, for he was obedient, sober, & industrious, that Jim was a worthless creature, drank, traded with poor people, was idler, careless, &c. that he saw him constantly at Pecks stable & numerous other things that he mentioned, & yet said he would rather have Jim than Reuben, for he would whip him & make him know his place, but with you he would never be of any account, because you were too indulgent.\'a0 After this account of Jim, I was determined to buy Reuben, so I sent to Mrs. Harrison that he should come for me to look at.\'a0 He came, & I liked his looks, & what he said, but still not give a decided answer.\'a0 At night when Jim came in with the keys, I felt sorry for him, so I thought I would say something to him, so I said \'93Jim you know if we buy Reuben,\'a0 & are pleased with him, we will sell you, but I do not suppose you will care, for you never have seemed happy here,[\'93], he said, \'93 if my owners are not satisfied with me, I am perfectly willing to be sold, I do my work, & if I cant please them\'a0 I am willing to leave them\'94.\'a0 I said, \'93you have told me you would rather belong to a strict owner, than your master\'94.\'a0 He said, \'93I would rather belong to an owner who treats his servants alike some of them here are treated well, the other have to poke about,\'94 insinuating that he, the most indulged of \ul all\ulnone , was treated the worst.\'a0 I now lost all pity for him, & determined to buy Reuben.\'a0 I was in this frame of mind, when Mr. Hoke came in, & brought with him Dr. Crook, who he said knew more about Reuben, than he did.\'a0 Dr. Crook said he had always seemed to him slow motioned, & if you sent him on an errand, he would stop if he met anyone & laugh & talk with them, that he thought compared with Jim. It was 6 of one & a half a dozen of the other.\'a0 Mr. Hoke said he had worked for him & worked faithfully, & what Dr. Crook knew against him was literally nothing, yet they both advised me not to buy him, & said if he ever acted badly, I would blame myself.\'a0 Of course advised in this way. I would not make the purchase, so I went to tell Mrs. Harrison, that in your absence I could do nothing.\'a0 This morning Reuben came again & said his mistress said, that she would let him remain so, until you returned, that she would send me the bill of Sale, & then if you did not wish him, you could give it to Mr. Beattie, & Mr. Beattie would buy him.\'a0 She said you would fix all right.\'a0 She had perfect confidence in you.\'a0 Matters rested so until this evening after church.\'a0 I saw Mr. Beattie, & asked him if Mr. Harrison left Reuben & you did not buy him, if he would, & he said he had sent word to Mrs. Harrison he would take Reuben, but had not received an answer so he thought if Mrs. Harrison would agree to it, he would take Reuben at once, & when you return if you wish him, he will sell him to you at the 500 dollars.\'a0 If you do not wish him, he can easily sell him to someone else.\'a0 So here the matter rests, & I think I am a perfect Metternich to arrange things so well.\'a0 Dr. Croft after church this morning, said he wished to see you, to consult you on some business.\'a0 I told him, I could advise him, I knew a great deal about Law.\'a0 He said I was indeed, the smartest lady he ever knew.\'a0 He invited us to visit him at Newberry this winter.\'a0\'a0And now for your letter.\'a0 I must my dear husband say that I am vexed at the \ul foolish\ulnone  \ul purchases\ulnone  you make.\'a0 You show no judgement at all, \ul knives\ulnone , \ul forks\ulnone , \ul spoons\ulnone , when we have not a decent cup or plate to use with either, the spoons, but particularly the forks we could have done without & as the forks are not \ul real\ulnone  \ul silver\ulnone , it was foolish to get them, for our\'85ones answer perfectly well, & one set of \ul imitation \ulnone is quite enough.\'a0 What we need is a \ul dinner\ulnone  \ul set\ulnone  of \ul Crockery\ulnone , a nice set of \ul cups\ulnone  & \ul saucers\ulnone , some \ul Table\ulnone  \ul Mats\ulnone , a carpet for the Dining room, which we will be \ul obliged\ulnone  to get, for our present one is in \ul rags\ulnone , a chamber downstairs, our house painted, an oil cloth for the Stair case.\'a0 These things are \ul necessaries\ulnone .\'a0 The 36 dollars thrown away in the spoons & forks, would have bought the carpet, & then our chamber would have been made comfortable with the old carpet, & the dining room with the new.\'a0 Every thing of this kind is yet so much cheaper in Charleston, & comes up so much more conveniently, that I prefer getting them there.\'a0 Things are so dear in Columbia, that when you go down, I do not even mention what we want, for fear you may buy it, but as you will throw away your money so \ul foolishly\ulnone  I will not be so scrupulous another time.\'a0 If you knew how self denying I was, how I deny myself of every comfort in clothing, because you cannot afford it, you would reflect more before you spend your money.\'a0 If you were to see my \ul petticoats\ulnone , my \ul drawers\ulnone , my \ul stockings\ulnone  you would be \ul shocked\ulnone .\'a0 Of the money that passes through my hands. \ul Precious\ulnone  little is spent on myself.\'a0 It is all expended on the house, children & servants; a few handsome dresses I have & those \ul you\ulnone  bought me.\'a0 I have taste, & make my things look well but nothing more than I possibly can help, do I buy.\'a0 Aunt Eliza who thinks herself so straitened, would be astonished if she examined my Wardrobe.\'a0 You preach economy, & in your \ul dress\ulnone  you are economical, but at one blow you spoil it all; 36 dollars or at least 18 thrown away, for forks we had no earthly use for.\'a0 What we have are good enough for our circumstances, & they are not even \ul silver\ulnone .\'a0 What you have bought therefore I must say it was very foolish to buy a \ul second\ulnone  \ul set\ulnone  of \ul imitation\ulnone  silver.\'a0 I would like you if you would\'a0 to get back your money & keep it for some of the necessaries mentioned above.\'a0 The first 20 dollars you can spare me, I am going to send to Charleston or the North for a Musical box.\'a0 If you had\'85the money you\'85to, I would long ago have got one.\'a0 I do not wish it now, but next year some time I hope to git one.\'a0 Now I wish the house painted, and a Chamber downstairs, & a Carpet, & an Oil Cloth, & a Dinner Set, & a Tea Set, & Table Mats, & more Table Cloths, Towels, Pillow cases &c., but these things I intend getting in Charleston, everything now is cheap there.\'a0 Columbia particularly during the Session is extravagant,\'a0 Therefore I do not care for them to be got there.\'a0 I\'a0 have spoken long on this subject for I really \ul feel\ulnone  it.\'a0 I know that we have no money to spend uselessly.\'a0 I never have a fourpence to give away.\'a0 As \ul you\ulnone  have I want you to bring a present for \ul Vardry\ulnone .\'a0 You are his Godfather, & have never given him a present yet so get something for \ul him\ulnone , & the three pictures for 50 cts for Ann, & the glass slate for Willie, & engage the \ul Lady\'92s\ulnone  \ul book\ulnone  \ul for\ulnone  \ul me\ulnone , & if Graham & that together can be got for 5.00 engage Graham for Mamma.\'a0 Willie has \ul 15\ulnone  cts I owed him for Chickens.\'a0 He says you must buy something pretty for him at that \ul price\ulnone  besides the slate & he will pay you the money when you come home.\'a0 You must buy what books you can afford, but I expect that will not be many.\'a0 I expect the Women of the Bible, is too costly, so you can get that another time.\'a0 Per[s]ons here seem to think Mr. Edward Earle is sick, but as you do not mention it, I suppose he is not.\'a0 Mr. & Mrs. Perry Duncan were here this evening a few minutes to see how Fanny was.\'a0 They had heard she was sick, & did not know she was better.\'a0 I went to church today, both morning & afternoon.\'a0 Mr. Hoke says Genl Thompsons family say he has been offered a seat in the Cabinet.\'a0 I wonder he does not accept it.\'a0 He boasts enough.\'a0 He loves nothing from his humility.\'a0 I cant bear him or his \ul family\ulnone .\'a0 They are too conceited, but conceit & vanity helps a person in this world.\'a0 It has \ul made\ulnone  Genl Thompson.\'a0 I am pleased at the compliments paid you, but nothing can make up for my mortification at your late defeat, until you have \ul triumphed\ulnone  over your \ul base\ulnone  \ul enemies\ulnone .\'a0 Until then I can not feel as happy as I once did.\'a0 I took\'85pride in you, & it has been humbled, & so many are pleased at your defeat in this Congressional District.\'a0 The Lower County appreciates you much more than the Upper.\'a0 I wish Judge Butler could be beaten.\'a0 He never ought to have been elected.\'a0 I do not wish Col. Manning elected Governor.\'a0 He has no claims to it.\'a0 I hope Cousin Isaac will be elected.\'a0 You must do what you can, without injuring yourself.\'a0 I am sure you can influence many.\'a0 I feel great interest in his election, not only for Cousin Eliza\'92s sake, but for the sake of the name he bears.\'a0 He is the only one at present, to preserve it with distinction., & I am sorry for him.\'a0 Gloria has not much manner.\'a0 She is like her father, & she is very cold.\'a0 She always was.\'a0 I hope Col. Orr heard the speech made by Genl Brisbane, & I hope Col. Edwards with be elected Solicitor.\'a0 I wish you would be elected Solicitor when Genl Whitner is elected Judge, which Mr. Keith says he will be when Judge Richardson resigns.\'a0 Do you not think your chance is better than Mr. Youngs.\'a0 You must watch your chance, & be elected to something to cover the disgrace of your late defeat.\'a0 You must certainly price Buggy\'92s & Carri[a]ge\'92s, but a\'85Buggy you most need, & if you can make a good bargain, buy one.\'a0 See how much they would give for your old one.\'a0 Describe it to them, & then let Jim carry it down to you, or if you can get a reasonable one, perhaps you might\'85your old buggy here.\'a0 At any rate see what kind of bargain you can make.\'a0 If you cannot make a \ul good\ulnone  one, then get one from Mr. Cox here.\'a0 You might price Carri[a]ges & at one time or other change ones.\'a0 I dare say you would sell ours here, to someone in the country at a good price, when you wish to get another.\'a0 I have had a long chat with you, & if you were not tired would go on much longer.\'a0 I am not as silent as Gloria.\'a0 It is going on 10 oclock.\'a0 I am sending Willie upstairs.\'a0 I am glad you thought his letter did pretty well.\'a0 You might have told Col. Dawkins, if he meant it as a disparagement\'a0 [of] the four children only that you had had 6, & asked him how many he had.\'a0\'a0 They having married \ul twice\ulnone , you supposed\'a0 he had a house full, & tell him we were going on quite as rapidly as we desired, but if\'85would leave some of his property to one, we would try & have another & name after him.\'a0 Mr. Henry Thompson will be disappointed in not being Bursar.\'a0 I am going to write to Aunt Eliza now , & will tell her you think Cousin Isaac will be elected, & that the Greenville delegation will go for him.\'a0 The village is dull.\'a0 I have only been out to church, since you left.\'a0 I have been working for the servants all the time.\'a0 Eliza has worked two days for Margaret Croft, which will come to 75 cts.\'a0 Adieu I may add something tomorrow.\'a0 I am going to see Mrs. Town[e]s tomorrow.\'a0 Several messages have passed between us.\'a0 I am going to see Mrs. Tom Jones,\'a0 & Mrs. \'85.\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P. I have a shocking pen to write with & no way of getting another.\'a0 I am ashamed of my letter but cant help it.\
\'a0\

\f1\b 141\
Monday morning, 9 oclock.
\f0\b0 \'a0 \
\
	Mrs. Harrison has just paid me a visit.\'a0 She is very anxious, that I should take Reuben, with the bill of Sale, & on your return if you do not wish him, let Mr. Beattie have him, or she says, or perhaps she may let Mr. McBee have him at once.\'a0 I told her I proposed that to Mr. Beattie but he said the other was the best plan.\'a0 I suppose Mr. Beattie in taking him now & selling him to you would have his debt paid, but otherwise he would not.\'a0 I cannot buy Reuben on my own responsibility, for I do not know whether you wish to buy him or not, so I will not take any step.\'a0 You write me word so I can hear Friday, whether you prefer \ul buying\ulnone  him. Or prefer not.\'a0 Just tell me what \ul you\ulnone  \ul wish\ulnone , & I will do \ul exactly\ulnone  as you \ul say\ulnone .\'a0 Mrs. Harrison will be here I expect then, & then I can give her the answer.\'a0 I preferred waiting until you returned, that we might have a long talk on the matter, but I expect it will have to be settled now.\'a0 Mrs. Harrison asked who was elected Messenger to carry votes.\'a0 I told her I expected Mr. Black would be & told his motive for going.\'a0 She said \ul he\ulnone  ought to be \ul elected\ulnone .\'a0 She says Mr. Jones is a candidate for Treasurer of upper division.\'a0 I hope he will \ul not\ulnone  \ul be\ulnone  \ul elected\ulnone .\'a0 You \ul need\ulnone  not \ul do\ulnone  \ul anything\ulnone  \ul for\ulnone  \ul him\ulnone .\'a0 I am going to his house today, but I am sorry to have to.\'a0 Mrs. Harrison has just paid me a second visit to say Mr. Nichols says he \ul knows\ulnone  you will be willing to buy Reuben.\'a0 You write me word \ul distinctly\ulnone  what to do, whether to \ul buy\ulnone  him or \ul not\ulnone .\'a0 I will do just as you say.\'a0 Mr. Cox says he \ul likes\ulnone  him.\'a0 Mr. Hoke & Dr. Crook say they do not.\'a0 You know what Jim is, & I expect you have some idea of what Reuben is, so just do as you think best.\'a0 Mrs. Kerrison is so anxious you should take him.\'a0 She seems averse to Mr. Beatties taking him, but you must do as you think best.\'a0 Do write me exactly what your wish is, so that I may not have to act on my responsibility, but \ul yours\ulnone . I have not said all I wished, so will write a little more.\'a0 If you have good news for Mr. Henry Thompson, you must write & tell him.\'a0 I am going soon to see his Wife.\'a0 Mrs. Tom Jones sees company, so Susan & myself are going to see her.\'a0 I suppose Genl Thompson has gone on to Washington to get an office.\'a0 He is well situated now, for his disposition, able to go wherever he pleases.\'a0 I do not think he is suited for domestic life.\'a0 As Mrs. Pattersons expectations were so large, I hope she got something, at any rate enough to make her lead a virtuous life, & not be the means of leading many a young man astray, as I expect she now does.\'a0 I wish my dear husband you would be elected Senator.\'a0 I have such aspirations for you.\'a0 I believe I would be happier, if you were a stupid ignorant man, for then I would expect nothing for you, & would be satisfied, but as it is, my opinion of you is so \ul exalted\ulnone ,\'a0 my expectations for you are \ul great\ulnone , & as they are not realized, I am unhappy.\'a0 I am not \ul envious\ulnone  of others, but I am provoked, when those, so far your inferior, triumph over you.\'a0 I never can forgive the people of Pickens, Anderson, & Laurens for letting Mr. Orr beat you, when they knew what low means, he was using, & should have made them feel a contempt for him, instead of that to put him in such an honorable position, as he now holds.\'a0 Mr. Burt acted \ul basely\ulnone , & I hope he may \ul never \ulnone succeed in obtaining an office again, but he is so \ul mean\ulnone  I dare say he will.\'a0 Col. Irby, Mr. Sullivan the Pendleton people & others, I think are contemptible, & yet such a man as Sullivan, can get forward better than you, & I dare say will be a Member of Congress some day.\'a0 If you can do nothing better, you must go back in the Legislature, which I am sorry you quitted, for another time you might have been elected to Congress.\'a0 It was most unfortunate you should have come out when you did.\'a0 I wish you had staid 4 years more in the Senate, & then run for Congress.\'a0 When I think of these things I am so unhappy.\'a0 I cannot feel as happy as I once did.\'a0 I have a bitter, mortified feeling, which I will never get over, until you have triumphed over your enemies, & made them see, that they cannot always pull \ul you\ulnone  \ul down\ulnone .\'a0 Then again I will be happy, & I hope that time will come.\'a0 It is too bad to think that such men as Garvin, Reid, Whi\'85, headed by Calhoun, just as mean as they are, should succeed in preventing your obtaining the place, that Providence by giving you the proper qualifications for, meant you to have.\'a0 I hope they will yet be mortified, by seeing you successful.\'a0 I hope experience will teach you in future to manage better, for you are greatly to blame yourself.\'a0 Your publishing your peice, your \ul controversy \ulnone with \ul Sullivan \ulnone occasioned your defeat, & now that it is over, the speeches we can see helped to it, but I know\'a0 you acted for the best, though unwisely, so now I will stop.\'a0 Fanny is better & looks better & prettier than I ever saw her.\'a0 Write me every Mail.\'a0 The rest of us are well.\'a0 It has been a \ul relief\ulnone  to me to write what I have done.\'a0 You know I must express my thoughts to you, & it is my high opinion of you that makes me feel you have been so illy treated.\'a0 Your defeat is \ul astonishing\ulnone .\'a0 I cant understand how you could have been except there are too many Mr. Burts.\'a0 I hope Mr. Burt will be defeated.\'a0 He is one of your worst enemies, & pretending to be a friend.\'a0 Mrs. B\'85. who you & Mr. Beattie & other denominations have to support, immediately after Mr. Beattie had paid 5 dollars on Mr. Elfords subscription, went into Mr. Beatties store & bought 16 dollars worth of velvet to make herself a V\'85, supported by C\'85, & then to be so extravagant, more so than the wives of those who support me.\'a0 Tell Col. Evans & Mr. Elford of this.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 142\
Greenville, 6[5] December 1848\
Tuesday night
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just written a long letter to Aunt Eliza, & you will see by the date, that it is now very late, but I cannot go to bed, without writing to you, because tomorrow I may not be able to.\'a0 I expect to spend the morning in writing.\'a0 This morning I went to see Mrs. Kingsland, & then Susan, Mamma & myself, to see Mrs. Bryan, Mrs. Cox, Mrs. Robert Smith, & Mrs. Coleman.\'a0 Mr. Bryan is trying to sell his place.\'a0 He asks 2500 dollars for it, & he is selling his furniture at private Sale now, & afterwards what is left, will sell at Auction.\'a0 They will go to town whether the house is sold or not.\'a0 Mrs. Bryan was very anxious to go & says she does not wish to return.\'a0 Says Mr. Bryan says, perhaps he may return & buy a farm.\'a0 Dr. Simmons must have a very bad judgement before he has tried Greenville, & known whether he will like it, & known whether he will succeed.\'a0 He has bought a poor farm of Dr. Atwoods near Piney Mountain, given 800 dollars for it, & engaged board for himself Wife & children & 2 servants at Dr. Atwoods for 650 dollars a year.\'a0 \'85at the Mansion House he would have boarded the same family for 450 dollars.\'a0 Mrs. Bryan says, he said the Trustees had thrown out\'85inducements to him (which he would not\ul  mention\ulnone ) that he would not decline settling here, that she knows next year, he will get the Female Academy, & that she is sorry for Mr. Bradshaws family, they are such a fine family.\'a0 I myself am sorry for them, & as Mr. Bradshaw seems a good Teacher, I think for their sakes even, he ought to be continued.\'a0 Anna learns well, & of the two I prefer Mr. Bradshaw to Dr. Simmons,\'85looks too young, & too weak, & simple, & I dislike hurting Mr. Bradshaws feelings, & sending him & his family adrift into the world.\'a0 Mr. Mc\'85 Mrs. Bryan says is going to remain, & has the promise of 30 scholars.\'a0 I must tell you the final settlement about Reuben.\'a0 Mr. Beattie is to take him, & you buy him, or not, just as you please, on your return.\'a0 So we can have a long talk about it, when you come back.\'a0 I have no letter to answer of yours, so have no more to scold you about at present.\'a0 Mrs. Coleman today, showed us over her house, & told the price of the furniture, for Susan\'92s benefit, who will have to get furniture for her new house.\'a0 She had in her Dining room a beautiful Carpet, Red & Black, colours suited for this Soil.\'a0 It was only \ul 80\ulnone  \ul cts\ulnone  a yd.\'a0 I intend to write to town for just such a one.\'a0 She bought it at Lambert & Brothers.\'a0 She had a set of the handsomest Waiters I ever saw. Which she gave only 5 dollars for, & a beautiful Sideboard with a Marble top, which she gave only 50 dollars for.\'a0 I wish you to buy as few things as possible in Columbia.\'a0 Everything is too dear their.\'a0 I expect you could have got Knives much cheaper in Charleston.\'a0 Mrs. Colemans chamber looked so comfortable opening into her Dining room.\'a0 As soon as you come back I want you to have one made for me back of my Dining room, so much of it being made already, it will not cost much, & I wish the house painted.\'a0 The paint is so dirty now, I cannot make it look cleaner, so save all your money for this.\'a0 You need not buy any Books, except engage the Lady\'92s book.\'a0 The Croft family left today, all except Mr. Croft & Mrs. Pearson\'92s family.\'a0 Jim this morning drove me out.\'a0 This afternoon he shelled Corn for Meal & Hominy.\'a0 We are all well.\'a0 Mrs. Town[e]s is better.\'a0 I hope Cousin Isaac\'92s prospects are brightening.\'a0 I take no interest in the Legislative proceedings, as you are not a member.\'a0 I hope you will be, this time 2 years, if nothing better offers.\'a0 I cannot let you remain as \ul useless\ulnone  as you now are.\'a0 You are too well fitted for the duties of a Legislator, not to be one.\'a0 All the bills you introduced about giving the voting for President to the people, the Penitentiary &c. will be passed, & you gain no credit for it.\'a0 I will stop now & add some more tomorrow.\
\'a0\

\f1\b 143\
Wednesday morning.
\f0\b0 \'a0 \
\
	I have just done breakfast.\'a0 Mrs. Town[e]s sent me a few Oysters, & some bread, & says she is quite smart, & that Maj. Earle returned last night & says Col. Townes is better.\'a0 The Oysters as usual were \ul shocking\ulnone .\'a0 I sent them into the kitchen.\'a0 The pickled Oysters brought to Greenville, are not fit to eat.\'a0 You know the Cornfield at one side of Joe P\'85s house, between his house & Mr. Luther McBee\'92s .\'a0 He has sold \ul half\ulnone  of it, a narrow strip to Mr. Rowand for 500 dollars, which I think was enormous.\'a0 Today it is very cloudy & warm.\'a0 I expect it will rain.\'a0 If you get a Buggy, & can have yours taken in exchange, you must write for Jim to carry it down.\'a0 If you do not get one, & wish to come back in the carri[a]ge, write for that, & I will let Willie go down in it.\'a0 The horses seemed not at all injured by the journey, or the Carri[a]ge either.\'a0 If you get a Buggy, it must be a fashionable kind, but if they are too \ul expensive\ulnone , you can wait until next Spring.\'a0 Columbia is so dear, perhaps Buggy\'92s & Carri[a]ges may be dear too.\'a0 So I do not tell you to get \ul either\ulnone .\
\'a0\

\f1\b 144\
2 oclock.
\f0\b0 \'a0 \
\
	I have just returned from paying visits.\'a0 In the course of them I heard the Governor was dead, that Maj. Earle brought the news.\'a0 I heard also that young Elias Earle, intended next winter to be a Candidate for Comptroller General, & Mr. Jones also, that Mr. Jones had declined running for Treasurer.\'a0 I went to Mrs. Arthur\'92s where I saw Mr. Rosemond who is building a nice piazza in front of Mr. Arthur\'92s house, for only 27 dollars.\'a0 Mr. Arthur furnishes Lumber & Nails.\'a0 I asked him how much he would ask for putting a room in our Piazza & described it to him.\'a0 He said he would not exactly say, but he supposed 10 or 12 dollars.\'a0 I told him to come down tonight & look at the Piazza & tell us exactly.\'a0 He is going to build the house for Mrs. Pearson, & is said to be the cheapest workman here.\'a0 He has been working for Mr. Pinckney at Flat Rock, & was recommended by him.\'a0 So I wish you as soon as you return, to get the Lumber, & have the room commenced by Mr. Rosemond.\'a0 I hope to hear tonight from you.\'a0 Susan is going to Housekeeping, & I will wish you to make her a valuable present.\'a0 So a dozen large & small forks, such as you have got, I will wish you to get for her.\'a0 If you could afford it \ul now\ulnone , I would like it, if not in the Spring when you go to Columbia, perhaps what you have got for me I may give to her.\'a0 I will see about it.\'a0 This week I expect to get through with my visiting.\'a0 Every afternoon Jim has leisure.\'a0 Yesterday he shelled Corn; this afternoon he is going to haul wood.\'a0 Tomorrow I am going to see Mr. Henry Thompson.\'a0 This afternoon I am going to pay visits in the neighbourhood, so when you return, I will be able to stay at home, & entertain you, & ride with you.\'a0 Fanny is at this moment seated on the table sucking a bone.\'a0 Charles stays entirely at the farm, so I hope he is doing well.\'a0 It has cleared off now, & the sun is shining, but it is so warm I expect it will rain soon.\'a0 I must now close to send the letter to the office.\'a0 Yours truly, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 145\
Greenville, 8 December 1848\
Friday night
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I did not intend writing to you by this Mail because I thought you would leave Columbia tomorrow, but as in your letter tonight you do not say when you will be at home.\'a0 I write, for fear if you do not hear, you will be uneasy, & hurry home.\'a0 Today I have been visiting.\'a0 Mamma & myself went to Dr. Butlers this morning, & Mrs. Henry Thompsons this afternoon.\'a0 Mr. Thompson said he would always recollect the interest you had taken in his election as Bursar.\'a0 I am surprised you should have voted for Thompson Earle as Messenger, when you were under no obligation to his family, but rather the reverse.\'a0 I thought you would have voted for Mr. Black.\'a0 I am glad Cousin Isaac is elected Attorney General.\'a0 Mrs. Butler said there were such reports about Dr. Griffin when he left Abbeville.\'a0 He was the \ul last\ulnone  man she thought would have got an office, particularly that of \ul Treasurer\ulnone .\'a0 I hope you did not have to pay for the printing of Dr. Anderson\'92s briefs, & I also hope you will do your best, & get him a new trial.\'a0 I wish you had mentioned the Decisions in your cases.\'a0 Mrs. H\'85 seemed to me a pleasant lady.\'a0 I hear Mr. Eddings your friend has taken Dr. Austin\'92s house.\'a0 I suppose hired it.\'a0 It is uncertain whether Mr. Bryan will leave or not.\'a0 I rather expect Greenville suits him too well, that he will remain.\'a0 I am glad you purchased Candlesticks for we need them.\'a0 We need some for the Drawing room.\'a0 China ones are used, & when we can afford it, I will get a pr.\'a0 I wish you to buy for me, \'93the Carolina Receipt Book,\'94 by Miss Rutledge of Charleston.\'a0 The price in Charleston is 1 dollar, Mamma wishes it also, but as we are not certain\'a0 how we will like it, only one is enough to get.\'a0 You have not mentioned whether you have engaged the Lady\'92s Book. & whether Graham & that taken together would be got for 5[.]00.\'a0 Mamma wished Graham, if it would be got on those terms.\'a0 Cork Soles are worn in Shoes now.\'a0 Mrs. Arthur got a pr from Charleston.\'a0 I wish you would inquire in Columbia, & if they can be got, buy me 1 pair, & if \ul very\ulnone  \ul reasonable\ulnone  \ul 2\ulnone  \ul pair\ulnone .\'a0 You must bring something for the children, something that will be useful & last, not broken up immediately.\'a0 I will send this letter by Mr. Smith who leaves tonight, & get him to put it in the Post Office at Columbia.\'a0 Tomorrow I expect to finish my visiting,\'858 next week.\'a0 Jim will work steadily.\'a0 I will not take him off.\'a0 I thought it best to visit while you are away, as Jim will work more steadily when you are here.\'a0 He has not given me so much trouble in getting the carri[a]ge as usual.\'a0 Franks dog is quite well.\'a0 The Baptist Convention commenced today, but I do not think many persons have come yet.\'a0 The Village looks as quiet as ever.\'a0 We will all be happy to see you, but do not come sooner than\'a0 your business permits.\'a0 I must now conclude so as to send the letter before the bell rings.\'a0 Do you not think it would be a good plan to buy you[r] seed in Columbia of Russell, that they are better than those got here, but this is, as you think.\'a0 Willie is now studying his lesson.\'a0 Fanny is asleep in the Cradle.\'a0 Anna & Frank are gone to bed.\'a0 I believe I have nothing more to write.\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P. Recollect the pictures for Ann 3 for half a dollar, such as you got before, & something for Vardry, an Ornament such as you have sometimes got for Anna, or some little thing, I do not care what.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
