My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Mr Elford\'a0 has just been here to say he will take this letter to you from me tomorrow, & that he believed he was the only Lawyer going.\'a0 I intended of course writing, even before he came.\'a0 It seems an age since I saw you.\'a0 If you stay away much longer, I will forget I have a husband.\'a0 Mrs. Dub\'85 has ben with me a great deal, but still I have missed you.\'a0 You are the only one, to whom I tell all my thoughts.\'a0 Much as I miss you, I am \ul thankful\ulnone  that you have \ul business\ulnone  to detain you.\'a0 You cannot have \ul too\ulnone  \ul much\ulnone  of that, & love must be \ul secondary\ulnone  to \ul business\ulnone .\'a0 We are all well.\'a0 Willie & Anna have been going steadily to school.\'a0 Frank I have kept at home a few days to rest from his studies &\'85, but I will send him again on Monday.\'a0 Dr. Simons moved to his Farm yesterday & gave the boys holiday, so Willie & Frank went to the Farm to dig Potatoes & earned 5 cts a peice.\'a0 The Potatoes now have all been dug.\'a0 Amounting to 1 bushel, & Ground nuts about a \'bd bushels.\'a0 The Corn hauled, 12 loads \ul altogether\ulnone  from that field, \ul good\ulnone  \ul loads\ulnone , Charles says, & the hogs today were turned in.\'a0 The rainy spell made it later, than it otherwise would have been.\'a0 I must now tell you all I have seen & done since you left.\'a0 Last Saturday Mrs. Henry L. Pinckney sent me a newspaper from the Mansion House.\'a0 It rained until Monday so I could not go to see her, but Monday afternoon I sent word I would call for herself & Mr. Pinckney to take a ride (it is the only time I\'85the carri[a]ge).\'a0 I did so & found them very [page torn] they enjoyed the ride \ul extremely\ulnone , were delighted [page torn] \'85tain scenery, the variety in the foliage &c.\'a0 The next morning they paid me a visit.\'a0 I showed them your Library, busts, pictures &c.\'a0 They admired them, & Mr. Pinckney said I had an \ul Earthly\ulnone  \ul Paradise\ulnone , & asked if I did not think so.\'a0 I told him \ul no\ulnone .\'a0 He said he thought so, no one was contented.\'a0 On going away he shook me warmly by the hand, & said I must tell \ul you\ulnone , when he determined to come to Greenville.\'a0 The \ul chief\ulnone  \ul pleasure\ulnone  he promised himself was the \ul seeing\ulnone  & \ul conversing\ulnone  with \ul you\ulnone .\'a0 Mamma carried them to ride Tuesday, & to see Susan & also Ann who was with Susan.\'a0 Mr. Pinckney was quite overcome at the meeting.\'a0 They all observed it, & Mrs. Pinckney afterwards in Mamma\'92s presence what had affected him so.\'a0 He said \'93really when he thought to himself, that there before him was \ul Susan\ulnone  \ul Hayne\ulnone  & her \ul children\ulnone .\'a0 It brought the \ul past\ulnone  so \ul vividly\ulnone  to his \ul mind\ulnone , that it wholly overcame him.\'94\'a0 Mamma used to be intimate with him & his family, & she says the seeing her, no doubt brought his \ul first\ulnone  \ul Wife\ulnone , to whom he was \ul passionately\ulnone  attached to her through & \ul that\ulnone  affected him.\'a0 He seems to have an affectionate heart & this visit of himself & Mrs. Pinckney was a very pleasant one & different from anything we anticipated.\'a0 They left Wednesday.\'a0 Tuesday morning I sent for Mrs. Dr. Simons to come & go with me to the Mansion House to see some of her relations who were there, some of whom we used to know, Mrs. Keating Simons & Mr. G\'85 Simons daughters.\'a0 They returned the visit yesterday.\'a0 Mamma met Mr. G\'85 Simon & he told her his Wife who was an old friend of hers had given him express orders to see her, when he came here.\'a0 Mrs. Dr. Simons came with the others to see me.\'a0 She seems good & I wish for her sake Dr. Simons would do well.\'a0 They intend staying at the farm the remainder of this year.\'a0 They have no equipage , so she [page torn] expect to come in at all.\'a0 Next year if they do not get the [page torn] \'85tend hiring Mrs. Seviers house,\'a0\'a0 She only asks\'85a year.\'a0 Mr. Bradshaw had engaged Dr. Austins house & had 60 Scholars pledged to him but lo! Good luck has come to him, he has had an offer from Pickensville Alabama of a school with several hundred scholars & some thousands dollars of Salary, & of course he has accepted.\'a0 Mrs. Dub\'85 heard this.\'a0 It is well if he goes, for he would have\'85with the Academy & returned to stay here he said, as long as he chose.\'a0 He leaves the 1
