Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I ought not to write to you today, for I have now written you \ul three\ulnone  letters, & received \ul not\ulnone  \ul one\ulnone  from you.\'a0 I have always said if I was \ul neglected\ulnone  by my husband, I would not bear it calmly & submissively, as some poor, weak spirited Wives do.\'a0 You will think now I am not putting my Theory into practice.\'a0 I assure you I only write because I am \ul certain\ulnone  \ul tonight\ulnone  I will hear, a most \ul justifiable\ulnone  excuse.\'a0 You are always so attentive in writing, that when I do not hear, I am sure it is \ul business \ulnone prevents you, & I am always pleased you should have just as much \ul business\ulnone  as \ul possible\ulnone  to occupy you.\'a0 I mentioned in my last that Mamma, Susan, Ann & the children were to dine with me that day.\'a0 Mr. McBee I invited but he was busy assisting in the Hog killing at his fathers, so did not come.\'a0 We spent a pleasant day.\'a0 Yesterday after breakfast, I was surprised by a visit from Clarke & Harriet Perry.\'a0 They came to Eveline Fosters wedding.\'a0 They dined here.\'a0 I asked them to pass the night, but they said they had promised to return to Mr. Fosters, & were to leave for home this morning by the way of Mr. Hunts, where they would sleep tonight.\'a0 Clarke regretted you were not at home.\'a0 He walked to the Mill, & the Village & Harriet walked over the house, & I entertained her as well as I could.\'a0 I thought they were going to pass the night & ordered the carri[a]ge to carry her to ride, but they said they could not stay.\'a0 So I carried Mrs. Forbes to Mr. Colemans place.\'a0 Mr. Powell is painting the house Straw colour, & it looks much prettier than ours.\'a0 The colour of our house is entirely too \ul deep\ulnone .\'a0 I am longing for it to fade.\'a0 Eveline left for Abbeville yesterday.\'a0 She had a small wedding. Principally the family, & the persons Dr. Cox brought with him from Abbeville.\'a0 She is just 15, he about 21.\'a0 Miss Vance was married last night; only the connexions of the parties were invited.\'a0 Mrs. Dr. Williams says Mr. Dubose came here last summer in search of a Wife; at Mrs. Brooks he saw Miss Vance.\'a0 Miss Ann Anderson came to see me yesterday.\'a0 She says Mrs. Stuart the Wife of the Teacher of the Academy, is a very plane lady in \ul appearance \ulnone quite a contrast to her husband, & \ul quiet\ulnone  in manners, that they have been married
\fs24\fsmilli12222 \super  
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \nosupersub several years, & lost one child, that Mr. Stuart has taught in her brothers family. & was once private Tutor in the Rutledge family in Statesburg, & gave private lessons to young ladies, at the same time that he kept a school for boys.\'a0 Dr. Simons has five borders engaged to him & some scholars I am afraid his\'85will take, particularly from his saying he would be cheaper than any other. I gave you wrong information about your Hogs.\'a0 First I said they had killed only 5, & afterwards said they had killed \ul all\ulnone .\'a0 I misunderstood, Reuben says they killed 9, & left 4 which had been injured by fighting &c to be killed at a future time.\'a0 The weather still continues cold enough to be safe.\'a0 They are going on with the ploughing today.\'a0 It does seem a pity to put such fine horses in the plough.\'a0 You must get a Mule.\'a0 I have heard Mrs. Sam Earle was coming on with Mr. Earle to be with Dr. T\'85 in her confinement.\'a0Mamma paid a visit to Mrs. Rowland lately & heard the other side of the quarrel, & it really seems from Mrs. Rowlands representation that she is not at all to blame.\'a0 She says she is not as well off as persons think, & her son John left his property to her on that account, & on his death bed wished he had more to leave her; that at her death, she intended leaving it to his Sisters, but that Mr. Beattie & themselves made so much fuss about it,\'a0 that her son Tom & Mrs. Henry Earle begged her to give it up at once to them, & they would return her what she had given them; that she had given it up now, & was so straightened, she intended to sell her place, & move to another place she owned 20 miles in the Country, that she had worked hard to give her children a good education & a start in life, & this was her return, that\'85Speers she always liked, but Mrs. Speers would not let her give anything.\'a0 What she gave Mrs. Speers had settled on herself.\'a0 She said a good deal more, & cried bitterly, & said the ungrateful conduct of her children was the greatest affliction she had ever met with. Ann received by the last Mail a pleasant letter from Paul.\'a0 In it he says that he had that morning seen Alston Hayne, who had lately returned from Philadelphia, that Alston inquired particularly about us all, & had a \ul high\ulnone  \ul opinion\ulnone  of \ul your\ulnone  \ul abilities\ulnone , & \ul regretted\ulnone  your non election to Congress, (& which I will never cease to regret)[.] We are all well.\'a0 Anna & Frank are at school.\'a0 I think Frank finds it much pleasanter at Mr. Beads\'85, than he did at Dr. Simons school.\'a0 He had no dread of\'85now.\'a0 Fanny is playing about, & still talks about you, & Billy in Lumbia.\'a0 She is as\'85as ever & as interesting.\'a0 Since sleeping at Fanny Town[e]s & bringing her home to sleep with her, the very next day when she came from school, said Fanny Town[e]s had quarreled with her.\'a0 Anna had taken a tuck out of her dress, which made it quite long , & Fanny Town[e]s told her, her dress was too long.\'a0 Anna replied, that she dressed as her Mamma wished her, & so Fanny got miffed & left her seat at the desk with Anna, & would not speak to her, & Mary Croft who had quarreled with her companion, left her desk & came & sat with Anna.\'a0 I have not asked whether the quarrel was made up yet.\'a0Yesterday as I was riding, I saw Judge Moore walking with a lady.\'a0 I could not see the ladys face well as she had on a sun bonnet. Our dining room now looks very comfortable.\'a0 I have shut up one of the doors by the Sideboard & removed the Table in that direction, & a little in \ul front\ulnone  of where the Table was, put the Sofa, the one Jim made.\'a0 Mamma & my Sisters think it the sweetest little Sofa they ever saw, & now that E\'85 has altered the Cover, & made it right, it does look very comfortable.\'a0 Mr. Rosemond came here yesterday. He measured the distance for the Fence, & will send a bill of what it will cost.\'a0 I believe I have nothing more to tell you.\'a0 Mamma desired their love to you when I wrote.\'a0 Mrs. Hokes family are to take tea with me this evening.\'a0 Tell Willie he does not know how anxious I am to know how he is getting on.\'a0 I hope to hear a good account of him, & that he will return quite a man, & never quarrel with his brother & sisters again.\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P. P.S. I have a shocking pen, & do not want to trouble Mr. N\'85 very often to mend it.\
