\f1\b 156\
Monday afternoon. 3 December [1849]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Willie\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I wrote to Papa last night, & have sent the letter to the Post office, along with the one Dr. Irvine ought to have carried & also one Anna wrote yesterday.\'a0 As so many letters were going by this Mail, I thought I would write to you by the \ul next\ulnone , but today I find I have so much to say, I feel I must write.\'a0 I am so much alone, I get thinking, & having no one to express my thoughts to. I am obliged to write.\'a0 I was very glad to receive your letter.\'a0 You must write often & tell me everything you see & what persons you see, & how you enjoy yourself.\'a0 I think you must be passing your time quite pleasantly.\'a0 You have set the fashion for little boys going with their Fathers to Columbia.\'a0 It will be followed.\'a0 Ann\'85 says Mr. Jones perhaps will take his son & Col. Town[e]s Alex the next time.\'a0 I would not send a son younger than you are.\'a0 You are just old enough to take care of yourself, & notice things & improve from associating with gentlemen.\'a0 I am glad you have new clothes.\'a0 I have always preferred a round Jacket to a Frock coat.\'a0 I have never seen you in a Coat, so cannot imagine how you look.\'a0 You must be a good boy.\'a0 Papa has done so much for you to make you happy.\'a0 Anna says she wishes to read your books.\'a0 Papa must not\'a0 bring many presents to the Children, for he will need all his money to pay your board, & to give you to spend in other ways.\'a0 12 numbers of the Lady\'92s book for 1849 have come.\'a0 Mr. Godey wrote word those were all he had, that he would get two bound volumes of the years previous at a high price 5 dollars a peice, & if Papa wanted them, he would have to send 5 dollars more.\'a0 Frank & Anna carried their dinner today.\'a0 It is so wet, so I have only Fanny at home.\'a0 Frank dreams of you every night; says he dreamt last night you had grown so big.\'a0 I expect he saw you in your new suit.\'a0 Have you new pantaloons & waistcoat? as well as Coat.\'a0 I hope you read in your little Testament every day, & say your prayers, & that you clean your teeth. & have your face & hands washed very nicely.\'a0 I am glad you behave like a little man.\'a0 Today I suppose you are at the College Commencement.\'a0 When you are graduating, I will go to Columbia to hear you speak.\'a0 Perhaps Papa will carry Frank next Spring.\'a0 I sent word to Poinsett Wells that you had bought him a knife.\'a0 I send in this letter a 2 dollar bill, which Papa must keep, & out of it pay 1 dollar or 1.25 for my shoes.\'a0 I send it because as Papa has not much money I would rather pay for the Shoes out of what he left me.\'a0 Mr. Leary I believe\'a0 gives holiday next week.\'a0 I am so sorry Mr. Stuart is not coming.\'a0 I am certain Dr. Simons having set up an opposition school is the cause of his resigning.\'a0 Mr. Arthur has moved back to the Parsonage.\'a0 I have no news to tell you.\'a0 Grandma says she can never love any grandchild as well as you, for she helped to take care of you, when you were a baby.\'a0 I wish you would pay a visit to Charleston.\'a0 You would stay with Aunt Eliza, but I expect Papa would hardly have the money now to let you go.\'a0 You have travelled a good deal for a little fellow like you.\'a0 Fanny talks often of \ul Billy\ulnone , & thought your letter was written to her.\'a0 She has put it away in a corner, & will not let me have it.\'a0 Your affectionate Mama, E.F.P.\
