My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 You will think I am in a writing humour, but really having no one to talk to, it is a relief to write, having written so much by this Mail.\'a0 Unless I have any particular thing to relate, I may not write by the next Mail.\'a0 I sent your letter this morning to Mr. Wells.\'a0 If you continue to write, be careful in all you say, & not get into any trouble, & write good letters.\'a0 I am quite worried about the Bank question.\'a0 You say it is such an important question.\'a0 I hope you understand it well & are on the right side.\'a0 I am staggered when I hear of Col. Irby, Mr. Henry, & so many intelligent upcountry gentlemen going for it, & am surprised that 3 members from Greenville should.\'a0 I had thought the very name of B\'85 was odious to the Upper Country, but it seems so many of them are in favour of it, as in the Lower.\'a0 So examine the subject & be sure you are \ul right\ulnone .\'a0 You cannot think how sorry I am at Mr. Stuarts resignation, & am particularly provoked\'a0 with Dr. Simons, who I feel certain is the cause, & to think such an Organist we have lost.\'a0 I wish you would write to him & tell him his Wifes health would improve in Greenville.\'a0 I am very sorry you did not carry my pencil case down, & exchange it instead of yours.\'a0 I suppose you could have exchanged it on the same terms, & yours was a superior English one, which I would like to have had.\'a0 You blame others for fickleness, & liking to change, but you are very fond of changing all you have yourself.\'a0 Some of the servants say, they hear Mr. & Mrs. Sam Earle are here.\'a0 I do not know but as tomorrow is the \ul Sale\ulnone , suppose he at least is.\'a0 Mr. Moore was here, not his Wife, the lady with him was Miss Thurston. Send your letters to me to read, if you write any to Mr. Wells, I have not looked at the last Mountaineer yet.\'a0 I would rather read your letters in manuscript.\'a0 They give me more pleasure there.\'a0\'a0\'a0 The B\'85 Office Reports, & a book on Mexico & California with a map.\'a0 I have written Willie about the Lady\'92s books.\'a0 There are two or three pretty pictures in each number.\'a0 The rest are woodcuts.\'a0 I believe I have said all I had to say.\'a0 I only feel\'85that the majority of the people are for the Bank, & I am sorry if you are on the unpopular side, & as Mr. Elmore thinks it is so important that you should go for the Bank so\'85to us, you ought to examine the subject well.\'a0 I do not mean to interfere.\'a0 I only tell\'a0 my \ul thoughts\ulnone .\'a0 You must speak well & distinguish yourself as you have hitherto done.\'a0 I wish I could be seated in the Gallery by Willie listening to you.\'a0 Before next winter we will perhaps get a new carri[a]ge, & I can go down for part of the Session, & hear you, if you are still in the Legislature, but I believe it is so cold now, I will prefer going in the Spring, if ever I do go.\'a0 I will go to see \ul you\ulnone  \ul inaugurated\ulnone .\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P. Col. Ware is so politic.\'a0 What makes him go \ul for\ulnone  the \ul bank\ulnone .\'a0 He keeps very quiet.\'a0 He does not distinguish himself, but he gets along easily with all parties, & so finds no difficulty in being elected.\'a0 If nothing better offers, in two years, you must have your place back again, that he now has.\
\'a0\
Bejamin Perry\
[Columbia]\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 158\
Wednesday 1 o\'92clock, 5 December 1849\
Greenville\'a0
\f0\b0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 \'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Though I have nothing very particular to write about, as you may be disappointed if you do not hear, I will write you again.\'a0 I expect you were \ul surprised\ulnone  by the last Mail.\'a0 I have just returned from carrying Mrs. Forbes to ride to Mr. Lowndes.\'a0 The view is prettier than I ever saw it.\'a0 The whole village & all the settlements about can be seen.\'a0 I told Mrs. Forbes Mr. Stuart had resigned, & she said; so Mrs. Durb\'85 said, & with what spirit he had acted; that she understood when he went home. & began to consider the manner in which he had been elected, & how \ul badly\ulnone  Dr. Simons had been treated by the Trustees, particularly how a \ul Committee\ulnone  had acted, he determined to resign.\'a0 Did you ever hear such a story, & yet there may be truth in it.\'a0 You may depend on it.\'a0 Dr. Simons has had some understanding with him.\'a0 He has written to him & given him a Statement of his treatment.\'a0 Mrs. Forbes said she heard Mr. Stuart was elected on account of his being rich, that he had plenty of negroes to bring along with him.\'a0 All this I suppose has come from Dr. Simons, & if he has not written to Mr. Stuart, at any rate these are the reasons he gives for Mr. Stuarts resignation.\'a0 I begin to think it strange in Mr. Stuart to have resigned.\'a0 He had no right to, & it was no reason to give; his Wifes ill health, for I always understood he came here on account of health, that where he had been living was sickly.\'a0 Perhaps it will all be for the best; though on account of the Organ I will also regret his not coming.\'a0 Mr. Davis has been elected.\'a0 I hope he will be a good Teacher, for the children have been sadly neglected.\'a0 Dr. Simons acted outrageously.\'a0 I think Willie learned nothing with him.\'a0 Charlotte Smith told Miss Stuart; in Charleston he is thought \ul half\ulnone  \ul cracked\ulnone .\'a0 Yesterday was a gloomy day;\'a0 I sat down quite easy, though I would see no one all day.\'a0 Minerva & Mary had gone to the Spring to wash. Eliza was sick in bed, & Lindy was to be our Cook.\'a0 At 11 I heard a wrap at the door & to my surprise Miss Stuart & little Henry Thompson were there.\'a0 Miss Stuart said she was obliged to shop, & had come to my home as being more convenient to shop from, than Genl Thompsons.\'a0 I told her I was glad to have her, but she never would have found me more unprepared to entertain her well.\'a0 So she went to shop & I laid the table nicely & Lindy killed a fowl & fixed it, & we had a Fist, & with the help of raisons, Almonds, & sweetmeats, we did quite well. Poor Mr. Kinloch died this morning.\'a0 He has been ill a long time.\'a0 His Mother & his sister Mrs. Singleton, passed down some time ago from Flat Rock.\'a0 His cousin Mr. Middleton, Mrs. William Lowndes both staid with him to nurse him.\'a0 It seems so strange his mother did not come up to him.\'a0 He is an only son.\'a0 His parents have been separated for a long time.\'a0 When he was a little boy we used to see him in New Haven where he was going to school.\'a0 Mrs, Forbes says she has heard he was sent there to be away from his Father & as soon as he had finished school, was put in the Navy, & when he found out how his Father had been treated, & that he had been purposely kept away from him, he had a difference with his Mother on account of it.\'a0 So I suppose this is the reason his Mother has not been with him.\'a0 I expect he had great feeling.\'a0 He died of an affection of the heart.\'a0 The funeral takes place tomorrow morning at the Mansion House.\'a0 The father I believe is in the Asylum at Columbia.\'a0 His Mother is a sister of Mrs. Aiken.\'a0 I sent to Mrs. Hoke to know who bought Mr. Ed Earles place, thinking you would wish to know, & she sent word Mr. Sam Earle, & that he gave 12,100 dollars for it.\'a0 I believe it is a \ul mistake\ulnone , Mrs. Sam Earle being here.\'a0 I have not heard anything about him except that he was here.\'a0 We have cold weather, so the hogs were killed at a very good time.\'a0 We are all well except Eliza, who has been in bed for 3 days with pain in her side,\'a0 She is better & thinks she will be up tomorrow. I hope to hear tonight from you.\'a0 It is a great disappointment when I do not hear. Tomorrow night there is to be a Cotillion party given as a farewell compliment to Mary Bradshaw & her sister.\'a0 Frank goes cheerfully to school, & is learning to read.\'a0 Fanny is my little companion, & all I can say of her is, she is as sweet & amusing as ever. I paid Mr. Miller for the Potatoes & bought some more.\'a0 Reuben & Charles ploughed yesterday, & are to plough this afternoon.\'a0 I hope soon to get a long letter from Willie, & to hear good accounts of him.\'a0 He attended Commencement I suppose, & perhaps Commencement Ball.\'a0 I will now bid you adieu with love to Willie.\'a0 Yours affectionately, E.F.P. P.S. Willie said Aunt Eliza wrote a note to you asking you to send him to town.\'a0 Did you answer it.\'a0 I wish he could go.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 159\
Friday morning, 6[7] December 1849\
Greenville\'a0
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received a letter from you the last Mail & it gave me great pleasure.\'a0 I am glad cousin Isaac Hayne is more cordial.\'a0 I expect his coldness at first was owing to your manner, & as I wish you to be on good terms, you must return his visit & take Willie with you.\'a0 Mr. Heyward, is Nat Heyward, who we were intimate with at New Haven, & who liked \ul me\ulnone  particularly.\'a0 He is a cousin of ours.\'a0 His Mother was a Miss Barnwell.\'a0 You must be very polite to him, for our sake.\'a0 I am gratified to hear how well Willie behaves.\'a0 Mamma is afraid he looks too much like a man with his frock coat & cravat.\'a0 I hope his coat is a \ul Sack\ulnone .\'a0 I am glad you have fitted up yourself well in Clothes, for you \ul needed\ulnone  them, & it gives me pleasure\'a0 to see you well dressed.\'a0 I think married persons ought to dress better after marriage than they did before,\'a0 They ought to appear as comely as possible to each other.\'a0 They have then \ul one\ulnone  \ul person\ulnone  at \ul least\ulnone  to please, before they had \ul no\ulnone  \ul one\ulnone  in particular.\'a0 Susan now tells me that Mr. Jones mentioned she thinks in his correspondence to Mr. McBee, that probably in \ul two\ulnone  \ul years\ulnone  he will be Candidate for Solicitor, that Genl Whitner perhaps will not wish to be reelected & Mr. McBee mentioned it to her, as showing how conceited he was.\'a0 I heard it in t\ul his\ulnone  \ul manner\ulnone .\'a0 I said to Ann, Mr. Jones is going to Columbia, & she said yes.\'a0 He is a Candidate for Solicitor the office Genl Whitner has.\'a0 I felt certain Genl Whitner was going to resign so in two years, if you have been elected to nothing more lucrative or honorable \ul you\ulnone  must think of it, but in earnest I hope someone will bring you forward as Mr. Seabrook\'92s successor.\'a0 All have to convince themselves & do for themselves & if you give a hint to some friend, to propose you, you will be elected, for the Legislature can appreciate you more\'a0 than the people did, & of course give you whatever you asked for, & the Upper Country ought to share the honours equally with the Lower, & Greenville has not yet had that honour bestowed on her. Dr. Tiddyman has written word that the Rail Road \ul shall\ulnone  \ul not\ulnone  pass through his land, but that he wil sell them his place at \ul 10,000\ulnone  \ul dollars\ulnone , & you know he thought he was \ul cheated\ulnone  when he gave \ul 7000\ulnone  for it.\'a0 What is the Law on the subject; cannot they have the right of way, whether he gives it or not?\'a0 How \ul illiberal\ulnone  he is.\'a0 I think he is a \ul mean\ulnone  old man.\'a0 Mr. Cox who gave a \ul high\ulnone  price for his place, I think it was 25,000 dollars, says he will sell his place for a Depot, for \ul 8000\ulnone  \ul dollars\ulnone . We attended Mr. Kinloch\'92s funeral yesterday at the Episcopal Church.\'a0 It was a \ul sad\ulnone  funeral, only 20 persons at it, & his cousin & \ul servant\ulnone  chef mourners.\'a0 I should think his Mother would never forgive herself, for not having been with her \ul only\ulnone  \ul son\ulnone , the \ul best\ulnone  of his name in his dying moments.\'a0 I hear he was a handsome, accomplished young man.\'a0 Every vehicle that stopped at the door, he would ask if his friends had come.\'a0 They were written for.\'a0 He afterwards felt better & came down into the Bar room, & so countermanded the order.\'a0 He rode out to try his strength, to see if he would bear the journey down, but found he could not, & became so much worse, that his friends were written for again, the\'85weeks he\'85down stairs, he was brought down a\'85; if he was sick enough to remain up here & his cousin obliged to remain with him, it shows that he needed his Mother, & if she had loved \ul him\ulnone  she would have been with him.\'a0 Mrs. Forbes says she has \ul heard\ulnone , he was \ul indignant\ulnone  at the treatment of his \ul Father\ulnone .\'a0 Mr. Croft says his Father is not in the Asylum.\'a0 He saw him in Charleston when he was last there.\'a0 It is singular that at New Haven, we should meet with the little boy he was then, every day going to school. & here in Greenville, we should be brought in contact with him again but in so sad a way, Mrs. Sam Jones is in the Village today, so I invited her & Mrs. Town[e]s to come & take tea with me this evening, & invited Mrs. Elford also.\'a0 They are coming,\'a0 Mrs. Forbes & Mrs. Gibbon are going to spend the \ul afternoon\ulnone  with me.\'a0 They are afraid to be out after dark, on account of the cold.\'a0 I have made some nice Jelly, & some Custard for them, & have sent to ask Mamma & Susan, family to come.\'a0 Anna last night took tea\'a0 with Fanny Town[e]s next door.\'a0 They are good friends again.\'a0 Miss McBee told Susan the other day, she was anxious to see her to tell what Mr. Bradshaw said of Anna.\'a0 He says, \ul Anna \ulnone is the \ul brightest\ulnone  \ul genius\ulnone  in his school.\'a0 She ought to be smart, if she takes after you, as you daughters do after Fathers.\'a0 I am willing \ul all\ulnone  should be like you.\'a0 Miss Stuart says Fannys face from her nose down is the express image of \ul yours\ulnone . Ann begs me to request you, to buy for her, a large box representing an \ul Apple\ulnone  such as you bought for her before.\'a0 You recollect it I suppose.\'a0 She will return the money.\'a0 As you are \ul Vardry\'92s\ulnone  \ul Godfather\ulnone  you must bring \ul him\ulnone  some \ul little\ulnone  \ul present\ulnone  to show you \ul think\ulnone  of him.\'a0 If you see nothing suitable or pretty or reasonable to buy for me, to wear this winter, I will \ul wait\ulnone  until you come back, & what money you can spare, send to town\'a0 & buy something there.\'a0 In Charleston they have a great variety & you can get an article for almost any price you choose.\'a0 In Columbia everything is dear & not such a variety as in Charleston.\'a0 So if you can get nothing for me you \ul like \ulnone I prefer waiting & sending to Charleston, when I am certain I can get something \ul pretty\ulnone  & \ul reasonable\ulnone . I wish you to do one thing in the Legislature, & that is make an alteration in the Court of Appeals.\'a0 Introduce a law to make the \ul lower\ulnone  country Lawyers try their Appeal cases in \ul Charleston\ulnone , when the Court sits \ul there\ulnone , & the Upper country Lawyers try \ul their\ulnone  \ul cases\ulnone  only in \ul Columbia\ulnone .\'a0 As it is \ul now\ulnone , the Lower Country has \ul more\ulnone  than she is entitled to, & the Upper Country \ul entirely\ulnone  \ul overlooked\ulnone  & \ul unjustly\ulnone  \ul treated\ulnone , The weather continues cold, so our meat is safe.\'a0 I see Dr. Irvine has returned.\'a0 What 3 votes did Mr. Walker get?\'a0 Perhaps it would have been best for \ul you\ulnone  to have voted for him, to have gained his \ul kind\ulnone  \ul feelings\ulnone .\'a0 You had best be \ul polite\ulnone  to Mr. Jones\'a0 Though he is so vain, how much \ul happier\ulnone  he is, than if he was \ul conscious\ulnone  of his \ul real\ulnone  \ul value\ulnone .\'a0 I have no news to tell you.\'a0 Mrs. Turpin came to see me yesterday.\'a0 Miss Vance is married & gone.\'a0 We are all well.\'a0 Reuben & Charles are ploughing.\'a0 I paid Mr. Slatton yesterday for Flour.\'a0 He says they marked it at the Mill, \ul Superior\ulnone .\'a0 Send pamphlets home to your constituents, such as Dr. Crook who once said you did not.\'a0 You must answer Aunt Eliza\'92s letter, & thank her for inviting Willie.\'a0 I wish he would go down & see his friends.\'a0 Has Judge Dunkin given you the money for Mrs. D\'92Oyley.\'a0\'a0 Col. Irv\'85 has gone to the West to sell a Drove of negroes, & while he is absent his Wife has gone home.\'a0 Caroline Earle went with her.\'a0 What an uninteresting employment he has.\'a0 Examine all subjects brought before the Legislature well, always be sure you are on the right side, & I hope it will happen aways to be on the popular side.\'a0 Give our love to Willie.\'a0 Grandma & all send love.\'a0 I hope to hear from you tonight.\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
