Sunday night, 9 December 1849\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 It is just 8 oclock, so I will spend one hour in writing to you.\'a0 I have read your letters to Anna & myself, & Willies letter to me, all of which have given me \ul great\ulnone  \ul pleasure\ulnone .\'a0 This has been a rainy day, so we have not been to church.\'a0 I finished reading Lectures on the Pilgrims Progress lent me by Mrs. Pearson, & it is so interesting.\'a0 I wish \ul you \ulnone \'a0to read it when you return.\'a0 I read this morning in the Bible to Mary, Lindy, Charlotte, Sarah & the children,\'a0 & tonight until the Mail came I began the Pilgrims Progress to Mary & Lindy, explaining it as I read.\'a0 I am surprised you did not send a letter to Mr. Wells, for you would have had more to write about now, than at first, & the people like \ul news\ulnone  & \ul business\ulnone  matters, more than sketches of character, which you[r] first letter consisted of.\'a0 I received the first letter you wrote to come by Mr. Keith Friday night.\'a0 \ul He\ulnone  paid me a visit last night, said that he had just arrived, that he was not able to leave Columbia the day he expected, & put your letter in the Post Office.\'a0 He went on today to Pickens.\'a0 Unless your \ul compliments\ulnone  amount to something in \ul reality\ulnone , it only \ul provokes\ulnone  me.\'a0 What makes me unhappy, is my \ul aspirations\ulnone  for you, & that they are not \ul realized\ulnone .\'a0 It is only your being elected to something \ul honorable\ulnone  that can make me forget your \ul late\ulnone  \ul defeat\ulnone , so you must embrace the \ul first\ulnone  \ul chance\ulnone  that offers.\'a0 I am \ul vexed\ulnone  that you should have \ul declined \ulnone Genl Adams \ul suggestion\ulnone  , for it is an \ul honour\ulnone  to be a \ul Candidate\ulnone  for \ul Governor\ulnone .\'a0 Even if not elected, you must consent to any proposal made you, & whatever it is, do not think it will interfere with your private interests.\'a0 I can attend to them, & I am willing to stay in Greenville, & live economically, so \ul you\ulnone  are \ul honoured\ulnone , & if you wish to remove to any place, you can sell your property here to advantage, now, property has risen so.\'a0 To have a good chance for Governor\'a0 you must be \'85get out \ul soon\ulnone , so if anything \ul more \ulnone is said to you, do you \ul consent\ulnone , for the Salary is good, & for only 2 years will not interfere with your other business, for you have partners, & can have more during that time.\'a0 As regards being President of the Bank, I was \ul willing\ulnone  for it, if you are.\'a0 It is from the \ul State\ulnone  that with Mr. Elmore, & ever since has been a flaming Bank man.\'a0 I was glad to find Mr. Keith was against the Bank, & he says the majority of the people of Pickens & Greenville are.\'a0 I had begun to be uneasy about \ul you\ulnone , fearing you were as usual in a small minority.\'a0 I hope you will make an \ul able\ulnone  speech on the \ul subject\ulnone .\'a0 You ought certainly to have dined with the Governor.\'a0 I hope you will be appointed Trustee of the College again, that is such a dignified office.\'a0 I am glad you are one of the Board of Visitors, & that you think you will be appointed a delegate to the Southern Convention.\'a0 Mr. Keith says some alteration ought to be made in the Court of Appeals that the\'a0 Charleston Lawyers shall not try their cases there in Columbia so you must attend to this as I wrote you.\'a0 \ul Commissioner\ulnone  of \ul Equity\ulnone  ought to be given to the \ul people\ulnone , but not Attorney General, Controller &c. to the \ul Governor\ulnone  or people.\'a0 It would be giving him too much power.\'a0 He would favour his friends.\'a0 I see you introduced a bill of that kind.\'a0 Tom Butler knew not whether we were sick or well.\'a0 I heard he arrived one evening, & left that very night again for Columbia.\'a0 Now that I think of it, you must get the \ul Sum\ulnone  allowed last Session for the \ul Electors\ulnone , & which you have \ul never\ulnone  got.\'a0 There is one book which I wish you to buy \ul me\ulnone , & that is, \'93the \ul Lady\ulnone  \ul Alice\ulnone  or the \ul new\ulnone  \ul Una\ulnone .\'94\'a0 Mr. Brown said it was one of the best books he had read for a long time, so do not forget it, & if you have money enough buy Ernest Maltravers, by Bulwer.\'a0 You have the second part called Alice, so ought to have the \ul first\ulnone .\'a0 In Anna\'92s letter you Say you have bought my Shawl.\'a0 I \ul thank\ulnone  you.\'a0 I was going to quarrel with you for getting \ul White\ulnone , which was expressly what I told you not to get, but as the Shawl is so \ul reasonable\ulnone  I cannot object.\'a0 I am afraid it will not suit my other clothes.\'a0 I ought now to have a\'a0 \ul Winter\ulnone  \'85.\'a0 If you see a \ul reasonable\ulnone  one you might get me one, a dark Silk or velvet.\'a0 About the Canary birds, I do not know what to say.\'a0 Anna is asleep & has not read your letter.\'a0 If you could afford it I would like them; perhaps it is the only chance we may ever have of getting them & four dollars for a p[ai]r \ul including\ulnone  the \ul Cage\ulnone  is reasonable, & you can have the Cage fixed in some part of your Buggy, & must bring up seed, & we can raise the birds.\'a0 Aunt Mary Hayne\'85them, &\'a0 can give me directions, so my advice is, if you have the \ul money\ulnone  \ul to\ulnone  \ul get\ulnone  \ul them\ulnone .\'a0 I am glad you are so much pleased with Anna\'92s letter.\'a0 You do injustice to Frank.\'a0 Dr. Simons taught him \ul nothing\ulnone .\'a0 The short time he \ul \'a0\ulnone has been going to Mr. Bradshaws, Mr. Burnham the \ul assistant\ulnone  has taught him to \ul read\ulnone .\'a0 Today he has been reading in a religious Primer, Aunt Eliza sent him some time ago.\'a0 When you come back, he will be able to read it \ul through\ulnone  to you, & he loves to read, as soon as a child can \ul read\ulnone  he takes great interest in it.\'a0 He said yesterday he wished to write to you, that he would \ul hold\ulnone  the pen, & I must \ul move\ulnone  it for him, & you would think he wrote it.\'a0 Frank has too \ul fine\ulnone  a \ul face\ulnone  not to be \ul more\ulnone  than \ul ordinary\ulnone .\'a0 Aunt Eliza was \ul selfish\ulnone  in her kindness to Willie.\'a0 \ul Self interest governs her\ulnone .\'a0 Mrs. Isaac Hayne used to be \ul very\ulnone  \ul pretty\ulnone , though with some defects, a long chin, & bad figure & walk.\'a0 I had heard she was faded, but have not seen her for years.\'a0 I am glad Col. Hayne & yourself are better friends.\'a0 Fanny yesterday morning when she woke up, said, \'93Ma, Pa sleep here.\'94\'a0 I said \'93no, Pa is in Lumbia.\'94\'a0 She said, \'93I want Pa to come soon, I want Pa to come now.\'94\'a0 We all would be very glad to see Willie & yourself, but all I think of is \ul your\ulnone  \ul happiness\ulnone , & Greenville is so dull now, I am glad you are in Columbia among congenial spirits.\'a0 I am surprised you did not write to Mr. Wells.\'a0 I sent to him just now to know if he had received a letter from you, & he sends word no.\'a0 When you write again, enclose the letter to me, as I like to read it in manuscript.\'a0 I have not seen the last Mountaineer.\'a0 I put them when I send for them in the Library, without opening them.\'a0 The two Mrs. Town[e]s & Mrs. Elford took tea with me Friday evening, & we had a \ul pleasant\ulnone  \ul sociable\ulnone  time.\'a0 Mrs. Sam Town[e]s makes any place pleasant. She seems so free from envy, & bad feelings towards others.\'a0 Mr. Mauldin says Dr. Simons rejoices now he was not elected, says he was disappointed at \ul first\ulnone , but he would not be in the power of such a \ul set\ulnone  of \ul men\ulnone  as the \ul Trustees\ulnone  on any account.\'a0 He has published a Circular, in which he says, his table will be furnished with the \ul best\ulnone  of the \ul Land\ulnone , \ul fresh\ulnone  & \ul good\ulnone  from his \ul Farm\ulnone .\'a0 He is looking out for some white man to live on his Farm, & cultivate it on \ul shares\ulnone  with him.\'a0 He dined at the Mansion House lately, & Mrs. Forbes says made his story out quite clear, that says the Board of Trustees consists of 10, that 7 form a quorum, that he got \ul 4\ulnone  \ul votes\ulnone , & besides Mr. B\'85 wrote a note, saying he must get \ul his\ulnone  & Mr. Roberts who was absent wished him to have \ul his\ulnone , & yet the Trustees say Mr. Stuart was elected unanimously, that he heard Mr. Stuart\'92s resignation was attributed to \ul him\ulnone , but he had no doubt, Mr. Stuart staid here long enough to see what \ul kind\ulnone  of \ul men\ulnone  the \ul Trustees\ulnone  were.\'a0 Said you troubled yourself very little about who was elected.\'a0 He considers Mr. Stuarts resignation quite a feather in his cap.\'a0 Susan Hoke says she heard that a lady who went down in the Stage with Mr. Stuart says, he said he had \ul amused\ulnone  himself with the people of Greenville, but I think this must be \ul false\ulnone .\'a0 He has however acted I think dishonourably & unjustifiably, accepting the place\'a0 & then resigning it,when it was not of the power of the Trustees to elect those they might have chosen\'a0 & had in their power, if he had not accepted, for Mr. D\'85 who I hear was the second choice, & has been written to, has had a situation now offered him in Columbia, & therefore may decline this.\'a0 Mr. Smith also has a place, so Mr. Stuart has prevented the Academy having a good teacher.\'a0 His Wifes ill health is foolishness, for it must be the same now, as a few weeks ago, when he \ul accepted\ulnone .\'a0 I would \ul like\ulnone  you to have voted for Arthus Simkins, on account of old associations.\'a0 Mr. Keith says Mr. Jones is a candidate for two Offices, neither of which are vacant, Solicitor & Brigadier General.\'a0 Genl G\'85 it is thought, may resign.\'a0 He is\'85to be in \ul time\ulnone . Yesterday was very cold, today it has been raining & is warmer, but if it is cold tomorrow, Reuben & Charles will kill the 4 remaining hogs, & so save the Corn.\'a0 I have had the Gutters cleaned out.\'a0 You had better vote Richard Stone for a Director of the Bank, on account of Tom Butler who has generally been \ul your\ulnone  \ul friend\ulnone , & Mrs. Stone who is \ul mine\ulnone . Mr. Keith says he thinks there are more members \ul against\ulnone  the Bank than for it, that the vote that was taken on the subject of the special Committee in which there was a \ul tie\ulnone , some who were \ul against\ulnone  the Bank, voted on that question with the friends of the Bank.\'a0 It is now getting late.\'a0 I will finish my letter tomorrow.\'a0 When I go to bed tonight, before I go to sleep, many things will occur to my mind, that I wish to mention to you, one sheet will not hold half I have to say,\
\'a0\

\f1\b 161\
Monday morning.
\f0\b0 \'a0 \
\
	I have a good pen & will now my dear finish my letter.\'a0 Anna the first thing this morning when she woke looked under her pillow to feel for your letter.\'a0 I told her when she went to bed, if one came, I would put it there, but I had forgot to.\'a0 She dressed & came downstairs & I read it to her & it pleased her very much.\'a0 She sat down & answered it, but only had a short time before School, so hurried & did not write it as well as the last.\'a0 She is quite pleased at the idea of the \ul Birds\ulnone .\'a0 Frank is surprised you do not say what you will bring \ul him\ulnone , & while we were talking about your letter, Fanny said you must write to her.\'a0 She had a book a little while ago, & said she was going to play school.\'a0 She was to be little Sis, \'85(Sarah) big Sis, & C\'85 was to be \ul Mother\ulnone .\'a0 Frank is now sitting down reading his book.\'a0 He wont let me tell him the words, says \ul he\ulnone  knows, so it is amusing to hear him, but he manages to find out a great many.\'a0 Tell Willie I will soon write to him, & Anna says she will write after he has written to her.\'a0 I think his letters do quite well, when you think he has never written\'a0 but one or two before in his life.\'a0 I hope this visit will be of lasting benefit to him.\'a0 The other parents had better leave their children at home.\'a0 They are not equal to Willie.\'a0 It is a damp drizzly day, so the hogs are not to be killed, but as soon as it becomes cold again, they will be.\'a0 Anna has gone to school.\'a0 She will have holiday the middle of this week.\'a0 Wha Office is Dr.St\'85 a Candidate for?\'a0 I hope Mr. Burt will not be elected Secretary of State.\'a0 He is a malignant creature.\'a0 Mr. Keith says you have often \ul nonsuited\ulnone  him in court which is one reason of his dislike to you. You seem to make no complaint of want of money, & say you would have given even 15 dollars for my Shawl.\'a0 As the Shawl is so pretty & yet reasonable, you must spend the remainder of the 10 dollars which is what you were to give for the Shawl, in a bonnet for me 6 dollars or less could buy a pretty winter bonnet,\'85Silks or any kind that is fashionable.\'a0 I will need one now to wear with my Shawl.\'a0 I had intended wearing a Straw bonnet trimmed with Blue, that I wore in the summer, for a bonnet cannot even be trimmed well here.\'a0 But as the Shawl has cost so little, you must spend the remainder of the money allowed for it, in a bonnet whatever kind is fashionable.\'a0 I think you can get one for \ul less\ulnone  than 6 dollars, & buy me the books I have mentioned \'93The lady Alice, or the new Una.\'94\'a0 Mr. Brown said it was a superior work, & if you have money enough buy Ernest Maltravers by Bulwer.\'a0 It is the first part of Alice which you bought at Mr. Earles sale.\'a0 If you have still money enough, buy Miss Pardoe\'92s [\'93] Francis the First.\'94\'a0 Of course if you have not the money you must not think of getting these things.\'a0 You must get your money due you as an Elector.\'a0 I wish you would send me the Telegraph, that contains all the news I believe.\'a0 I should think you might give up the Banner edited by Mr. Morgan, the Carolinian is sufficient.\'a0 I suppose you are beginning to have gloomy weather in Columbia as we have here.\'a0 Stay until the very \ul end\ulnone  of the Session.\'a0 I will be delighted if you are elected President of the Bank, or Governor or any honourable Office.\'a0 Genl Adams seems a good sincere friend.\'a0 I have just asked Fanny what I shall tell you.\'a0 She says you must bring her Cocoa nut cakes & she wants you to come home.\'a0 She laughed aloud at Willie\'92s message that he longed to see her.\
\'a0\

\f1\b 162\
Monday afternoon
\f0\b0 .\'a0 \
\
	I will not conclude my \ul journal\ulnone .\'a0 Anna came home early this moprning, said Mr. Bradshaw had dismissed the School, that \ul he\ulnone  cried, & the scholars cried. That he is to go away next week.\'a0 Mr. Erwin is to live where Mrs. S\'85don did.\'a0 Old Mrs. McBee has bought the house from Mr. Waddil.\'a0 If there are not prettier ladies in Columbia, than Miss Pickens & Miss Thompson, the attention of the members will not often be diverted from the members of the house.\'a0 If you get the birds, you must have the cage fastened on top of your trunk behind the Buggy, & if you get me a bonnet, you must have it put in a small box, & fastened alongside of the Cage on the trunk.\'a0 It is giving so little for the Shawl & its being so pretty has made me think of the bonnet, & I really need one.\'a0 Ann says you must get her the box in the shape of the Apple so do not forget it.\'a0 I wish you could get \ul her\ulnone  some \ul birds\ulnone , but of course you have not the money.\'a0 You must buy Vardry a little present.\'a0 Willie is well supplied with books.\'a0 You ought to borrow from the Bookseller for him.\'a0 The weather continues gloomy.\'a0 Reuben is cleaning the Carri[a]ge today.\'a0 Eliza has gone to Mamma\'92s to work.\'a0 There is no news to tell.\'a0 I wish you to write Mr. \'85 so the people may hear of your deeds, otherwise they will hear nothing of you, for I expect Col. Town[e]s does not mention you but enclose the letters to me.\'a0 I suppose your being\'85prevented your writing & you must write or not as you wish.\'a0 If you have money enough bring Ann some birds, & some gentleman coming up can bring them for you, but only [if] you have more than the 40 dollars you mentioned.\'a0 I am sure you will not be able to.\'a0 You must be tired of this letter.\'a0 You must send it attentively\'85&\'85all I say.\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P. If you are made President you can afterwards practice Law in Charleston.\'a0 If you are not you must be Gov. I hope you will be appointed a Delegate to Nashville.\'a0 It will be a pleasant experience.\'a0 You must get yourself appointed.\'a0 If you are elected President of the Bank I will like it, or Gov.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\'a0\
