My dear husband, \
	As I had nothing particular to write to you today, I thought it best to answer Willie\'92s letter.\'a0 I will now however express a few thoughts to you.\'a0 I saw the Courier last night.\'a0 I approve of your recommendation about the Penitentiary.\'a0 The other motion you made partly I approve.\'a0 The election of Commissioner in Equity ought to be given to the people, but the Attorney General, Solicitor, Controller &c ought to be left as it is.\'a0 I suppose by this time you have spoken on the Bank.\'a0 I hope you did \ul credit\ulnone  to \ul yourself\ulnone , acquitted yourself better than Mr. Reed.\'a0 Have you done anything for Mr. Markley\'92s son?\'a0 You must not forget him.\'a0 I hope your prospects as regards the Executive & the Bank are progressing, now that \ul Law\ulnone  is\'85, you ought to think of something else.\'a0 You must do something in advancing your own interests, not\'85leave it to friends, & I hope you will tell me your prospects are good, for one or the other of these offices.\'a0 I think if your name was only suggested for the future Governor, it would take immediately, for you are \ul respected \ulnone throughout the State.\'a0 So if you are not elected to the Bank. You must think of the other.\'a0 You can have a partner here to attend to your business for [word obscured].\'a0 My directions about getting me a bonnet are not a joke.\'a0 10 dollars was what I allowed you for the Shawl, & as you only gave 4 dollars, the remaining 6 spend for me in a suitable winter bonnet.\'a0 You have much good taste.\'a0 Whatever you get will be pretty, & it gives me pleasure to wear anything \ul you\ulnone  \ul buy\ulnone .\'a0 These are the only things I care to buy this winter.\'a0 I do not expect to buy a dress.\'a0 What I have I will make do.\'a0 When I tell you to buy me anything, it is always of course meaning if you have the money.\'a0 If you had the \ul money \ulnone I would like a dress too but I know you have not.\'a0 From your being able to do all you have done, you mst have been supplied from some source I know not of. We are all well.\'a0 The weather is very cold.\'a0 We have fine weather for our meat.\'a0 I wrote Willie all I could think of, having received no letter since I last wrote.\'a0 I have less than usual to write about.\'a0 Your letters give me great pleasure.\'a0 If it were not for the cold I would like to be with you.\'a0 I am really glad Willie does so well.\'a0 Yours affectionately, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\'a0\
