\fs29\fsmilli14667 \nosupersub  as you think, this will be my last letter to you.\'a0 So I will mention all I wish you to get, promising that you must only get what I mention in case you have money.\'a0 Dr. Teague I believe was to pay you some & as you do not mention a scarcity, I think you must have been supplied.\'a0 If you are in funds, get for Anna the birds, if there is no risk of cold weather killing them, for Frank a trumpet or ball or some toy for Fanny & all included Cocoanut cakes; for Ann the box resembling an \ul apple\ulnone , for Vardry a little present of some kind, for \ul me\ulnone  to wear with my Shawl, a bonnet costing not more than 5 or 6 dollars, if you see a \ul pretty\ulnone  one, but if not, [do] \ul not\ulnone  \ul get\ulnone  \ul any\ulnone , & also if you see a pretty dress, worsted, at 25 or 37 1/2 cts a yd, get me enough to make dress & cape, & fringe & buttons, or any other\'85used.\'a0 A dress can be got here at the prices mentioned, but I would rather have one from Columbia, but not on any account with a price higher than this, at 25 or 37 \'bd.\'a0 All my dresses are light coloured\'85& thin Silks, so I used a new one to wear with my Shawl, though if you are \ul straightened\ulnone , I will do without it.\'a0 I got no new one last year.\'a0 All of my present ones except the light Cashmere, suitable only for Spring, are \ul very\ulnone  \ul shabby\ulnone .\'a0 In the way of books get me \'93The Lady Alice or the new Una,\'94 [\'93] Ernest Maltreves,\'94 & \'93the Carolina Receipt book\'94 by a Charleston lady, the \ul price\ulnone \'85\ul dollars\ulnone , & if you have it not to spend, I will wait for the books another time.\'a0 I expect you think I have written demands enough.\'a0 I will now close.\'a0\'a0 If tomorrow I have anything more to write I will inflict another sheet on you.\'a0 On the reception of our letters our exclamations are reversed.\'a0 I of yours, \'93how short,\'94 yours\'a0 of mine, \'93how long\'94!\'a0 We are all well.\'a0 Frank says he has almost forgotten how Willie looks.\'a0 Fanny today when she was troubling me, & I said I was busy said \'93is Pa busy.\'94\'a0 She takes up a book & reads, \'93B.F. Perry turn into Court.\'94\'a0 She has not forgotten Mr. Montgomery\'92s call.\'a0 You must be \ul patient\ulnone , & not feel too anxious to come home.\'a0 You will have a long time to stay, & will get tired before the Circuit commences again.\'a0 So enjoy yourself now among congenial spirits.\'a0 The children are all asleep.\'a0 Good night, E.F.P.\
