\f1\b 166\
Friday morning. [1849]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I will write\'a0 you a few lines, as it may be a comfort to hear from home tomorrow if you are\'85that long at Laurens perhaps I ought not to write,\'a0 You may not care to hear so often, but I judge of you by myself, & when absent from you, my only comfort is your letters.\'a0 Mary I am sorry to say is sick, but I expect not seriously.\'a0 She complained yesterday of pain in her stomach, so could do not any work.\'a0 I gave her castor oil, & pepper tea & put on mustard plasters.\'a0 Today she said she felt no better, so I sent for Dr. Crook.\'a0 Think it safer a Doctor should see her, & he says she has cold & must take Parsley root tea with Nitre in it, & iron herself with a warm iron, so I hope & suppose she will soon be well.\'a0 It puts me to great inconvenience having her sick, & Minerva on finding she had to do some of her work, was most \ul impertinent\ulnone , but I need not dwell on this subject, for you know I have never had your sympathy or aid in helping me in these domestic things & I always look to others for sympathy. Mrs. Kingsland & her youngest sister came to see me yesterday.\'a0 These are all I have seen since I wrote, & I have not been out. I am almost sorry Dr. Teague paid you.\'a0 I so prefer your having a note, drawing Interest, & if associates children\'a0 take part of your Rail Road Stock, you will not have so very much to pay.\'a0 You had better keep only one thousand or 1500 yourself, & they take the rest, even if Mr. Foster takes some. The children & myself are well.\'a0 Fanny sweeter than ever.\'a0 Last night at support Anna said something about your drinking hot water tea when you were a little boy.\'a0 Fanny got quite offended, & said to me almost crying \'93Tanner calls Pa a boy, Pa aint a boy,\'94 I said \'93what is he, is he not a \ul gentleman\ulnone ,\'94 she said, \'93\'92no. Pa is Pappy.\'a0 Pa is Pappy.\'94\'a0 She is always saying something sweet & affectionate.\'a0 The children go regularly to school.\'a0\'a0 Dr. Simons seems kinder since his disappointment, than he was before.\'a0 I hear that Mr. Leary has asked Mr. Erwin, who teaches at Spartanburg to assist him, perhaps Mr. Stevens declined coming. I hope Mr. Farleys business will be profitable to you.\'a0 The woman who murdered her husbands mistress, sa\'85ied her revenge \ul for\ulnone , she ought to have shown her contempt for her & him by \ul leaving\ulnone  him, to the enjoyment of one he preferred to her. I hope to hear from you tonight.\'a0 You need not be uneasy about Mary.\'a0 When you return Sunday, I dare say she will be up, at her work.\'a0 Dr. Crook said he wished to see you about his Turnpike road, that he expected he would not be able to go to Columbia himself.\'a0 Mrs. Durbec sent me word a few days ago, that she had received a letter from Mrs. Blake, who sent her love to me, & said she had written to me, & wished to know if I had received the letter. Mr. Sam Town[e]s left for Florida a day or two ago.\'a0 We have still pleasant weather.\'a0 I am glad negroes are rising though perhaps it is no advantage to us, who have, except Jim, none to dispose of, & I expect you have not determined to dispose of him.\'a0 If ordinary men servants sell for one thousand, he with his \ul trade\ulnone , ought to sell for 1500.\'a0 I will be willing to sell him when you can get that.\'a0 You know Sheriff a common negro & a rogue into the bargain sold for 1200.\'a0 Betsy, Jims wife has returned from the Limestone Springs.\'a0 I expect Jim has forgotten her. We will all be very glad to see you Sunday & you no doubt glad to see us.\'a0 I have nothing of interest to write about.\'a0 I am sorry Miss Dillard cannot have her case tried.\'a0 She is quite unfortunate.\'a0 I expect she will often be inconvenienced in the same way.\'a0 If her mother is \ul good\ulnone  for the note, no matter if she does not pay it now, though I would rather have her money & Dr. Teagues note. Believe me my dear husband as I ever have & ever will be your attached, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 167\
Saturday night, 30 March 1850\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 As you will be disappointed if you do not have a letter from me tomorrow I will write you a few lines, but I have a shocking pen, & am very tired.\'a0 I invited some company for the children here today, Mrs. Pearson & a few others.\'a0 I have been on my feet all day, as I always have so much to do myself when I have company, & as usual it has fatigued me.\'a0 I have written a few lines to Mrs. Sharpe to send along with the shoes., & if I have time I wish to write to Mrs. Duboc.\'a0 I received your letter last night & was very glad to hear from you, but I am sorry you made no mention of having received money from Mr. Norris, & nothing of Mr. Dickey\'92s case.\'a0 I expect as you have left it to Mr. Norris\'92 generosity to give you what he thinks right, he will give you nothing more.\'a0 I am afraid there is no chance of your being appointed a Delegate to the Nashville Convention.\'a0 I would have like that\'a0 you should even if you had declined going in case the first nominated declined going, would have gone in your stead, but you have no ambition.\'a0 That is your failing & in that lies your bad success.\'a0 When a man wishes, & is determined to gain what he wishes, he is certain to succeed but you are too lazy sometimes for exertion, but I will not dwell on your faults.\'a0 Reuben & Charles have ploughed every day since you left, & will finish the Oats sometime next week.\'a0 The fence is you mention being down is up now & Reuben does not know who would have taken it down.\'a0 He did not see it down.\'a0 Charles has finished the Stable & has been cleaning the yard.\'a0 Jim has made the Arbor in front of the house in the garden, has finished the Chicken pen, & made the fence by the Stable.\'a0 Next week if there is Lumber enough he will make the pig pen & Cow Stalls.\'a0 He says Mr. Hooker has hired two hands, & said nothing more to him, but I hope when he has finished here, Mr. Hooker\'a0 or someone will hire him, but when you can, you had better sell him, for it is very troublesome to keep servants to hire.\'a0 In your travels you ought to look out for a purchase for him.\'a0 900 I should think you would get, at any rate 850.\'a0 I would be glad for you to have a note for that amount.\'a0 Jim has made a step to Anna\'92s house & a fence would\'85separating it from the servants yard.. Eliza is sick in bed today with pain in her back & side.\'a0 Monday I will go in the garden & direct Charles what to do there.\'a0 The garden needs some attention now.\'a0 Wednesday night we had a heavy Snow, & I am afraid the fruit is all killed.\'a0 One of my large wild oranges was broken down.\'a0 We have cold weather & cold nights now; it is unfortunate, our winters are mild, & our Springs cold.\'a0\'a0\'a0Yesterday was Good Friday, & Mamma & myself Willie & Frank went to church.\'a0 Mr. Leary gave Holiday.\'a0 There was service again today, but I did not go.\'a0 Mr. Arthur for several mornings has had Sunrise meetings, to stir up his congregation, but I believe he has not stirred up many out of their beds.\'a0 Even Mr. Leary said he would not go, & Mrs. Pearson said she went with the greatest exertion.\'a0 I am sure if I was to go, my household would be put in entire confusion. The Ware\'92s dined here today, & Sally Crook.\'a0 Sally says Mr. Davis says, he has enough to support him without teaching that he teaches because he likes it.\'a0 I am glad to hear that Susan has given Anna a pretty doll, which has made her very happy.\'a0 I have been dressing it for her, & it will teach her to work.\'a0 Ann has been suffering from Calomel.\'a0 She took rather too much & not enough medicine after it, & is salivated & Mamma says her head feels as yours did.\'a0 Her mouth is sore & bleeds. Edward says Mrs. Mooney sold his home because he is in debt, that himself & Mr. Dyer get very little work to do, are sometimes weeks without any, but they manage to keep him employed, but Edward is not infallible authority, so I would not mention what he says.\'a0Mr. Cox & Mr. Griffin are exchanging homes.\'a0 I know of no news to tell you, except to church I have not been & at home have only\'85.\'a0 The children are well.\'a0 Willie rode on his colt today & it did pretty well, did not throw him.\'a0 Fanny talks about you, & what she will buy with the money you will bring her.\'a0 Anna has gone regularly to school.\'a0 Willie & Frank Wednesday staid at home because it rained & they have colds.\'a0 I hope Mamma will dine with me tomorrow.\'a0 I thought I would have had things left today, but all was eaten.\'a0 I am glad you sleep well, for that contributes a great deal to ones feeling well.\'a0 I hope your face when you return will be of its\'85.\'a0 At Pendleton last summer I saw some Smiths related to Mrs. North.\'a0 One of them lives with her.\'a0 Perhaps it was one of them that inquired about me of you.\'a0 Judge Withers I think must be quite trifling.\'a0 He seems to be a great talker & I thought\'85in his remarks the evening he spent here.\'a0 Susan told me Mary Creyton was trying for Mr. Campbell. I will send your letters & papers along with this letter, such papers as you have not seen, only one letter has come.\'a0 I hope you will come back with plenty of money, at any rate enough of the Tugaloo\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 estate to pay you what it owes you, & you to pay all the Rail Road then after that.\'a0 I wish you to send for Groceries, which we now greatly need, then get a new carri[a]ge for me\'a0 to ride more comfortably in, & then get a Piano, & furnish me with a generous supply for\'85, so you have a good deal to do.\'a0 Write by someone coming back before you leave.\'a0 I knew Mr. Calhoun was not going to leave this world yet, but be spared to trouble it longer.\'a0 I expect he now has been as ill as said in the papers.\'a0 I was never uneasy about him.\'a0 I can\'85letter up.\'a0 It wont do to be bound.\'a0 It is written too badly for Mrs. P\'85 & Mrs. Williams to read.\'a0 Hetty D\'92Oyley has gone to Aiken to Mrs. Theodore Crofts who has been very ill.\'a0 Your\'85, E.F.P. Though I forget to tell you, you must not leave Pickens until all your business is finished.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Pickens]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 168\
14 April 1850\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have time to write only a few lines.\'a0 We are all well.\'a0 I send a Carolinian.\'a0 You will see Col. [Franklin Harper] Elmore is appointed Senator.\'a0 The Governor has been cunning.\'a0 He says he need not serve more than this Session.\'a0 Next winter he can return to the Bank, & I suppose he himself take his place.\'a0 I send a receipt for money Mr. Dill begged me to give you, to collect money for Mr. Farr. Mr. Arthur has a daughter, born only 2 hours after Mrs. Thomas arrived Saturday evening. I went to church morning & afternoon yesterday.\'a0 Mr. Arthur preached on the love of the world, going to Theaters Balls &c.\'a0 I am sure in Greenville, there is no theater to go to, & so few Balls, one is not tempted to show their love of the world in that way.\'a0 I think Mr. Arthur loves the world as well as anyone. I called in Edward & told him about the flower.\'a0 His behavior I will tell you of when you return.\'a0 I hope you will gain Dr. Andersons case.\'a0 Miss Greens was certainly the most unjust decision I ever heard of. You must think of what I said about offering for the Legislature.\'a0 You certainly ought to be there next winter when the important Banks question will be discussed.\'a0 Do not wait to be asked; come forward yourself.\'a0 People are too selfish to think of you, if you do not yourself.\'a0 I promise you not to worry you on the subject.\'a0 I think you will if in the Legislature be elected Speaker, & then I will be gratified.\'a0Jim is building the low\'85.\'a0 I long to see you.\'a0 I was prevented writing this morning, & now the Mail is about closing.\'a0 I will\'a0 have to stop.\'a0Only one letter came last night from Mr. Squier, asking you to collect Tom Butlers & Butler Thompsons money due him. I will write a longer letter next time.\'a0 Adieu.\'a0 Your affectionate Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
\'a0\

\f1\b 169\
[Wednesday], 17 April [1850]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 To prevent your being disappointed I must write, but I really have nothing interesting to write about, but I must try & think of something.\'a0 Today it is raining so not much can be done at the Farm.\'a0 They intended planting Corn today, but the weather being bad, Reuben is hauling Manure.\'a0 I told Charles to cut\'85for the Peas, but I do not know whether he will. Jim has been working at the pig pen & cow stalls ever since you left.\'a0 He has not finished them, says he has not enough to cover them with. I do not like to dictate to you, but it seems to me when you can get what you think his value & a good price it would be well to sell him.\'a0 I think he is worth a great deal, for he is so smart & capable that will a strict owner, he would be invaluable, though to you he has been of little service, but I am willing to take 800 though would be glad to get more.\'a0 The interest of the money added to the principal would be more than he makes for you, deducting his expenses, risk of losing him, & his unsteady way, but I wish you to act for yourself Monday I dined at Mamma\'92s.\'a0 She walked in to see me.\'a0 Fanny & myself walked back with her.\'a0 I spent a pleasant day.\'a0 Yesterday we all dined at Susans.\'a0 Willie & Frank came out after morning school.\'a0 I spent a very pleasant day.\'a0 Speaking of Mr. Erwin Jones, Mr. McBee said if he ran for the Legislature, he would not \ul run\ulnone  \ul far\ulnone , & as for being Solicitor he stood no chance for the Greenville Delegation even would not vote for him, that \ul you\ulnone  he knew would not, nor Col. Town[e]s &c; said if you ran for the Legislature, which he seemed to think was a thing of course, you would be elected.\'a0 I expect it is thought such a settled matter that no one has thought it worthwhile to ask you.\'a0 Frank is still head.\'a0 Fanny talks as usual of you, & we all long to see you.\'a0 I hope \ul gain\ulnone  or \ul not\ulnone , Dr. Anderson will pay you some of the fee you charge that you will come home with a purse full.\'a0 I know of no news to tell you.\'a0 The rain will I hope make our seed come up, & perhaps tomorrow it will clear, & the Corn can be planted.\'a0 I wish a good deal planted as you will have 3 hands & 3 horses all summer. I hope to hear from you tonight, & now having said all I possibly can say except that one letter came for you last night, from a Mr. Fisher or some such name from Augusta which does not seem of much importance.\'a0 I remain your attached, dutiful wife. E.F.P. P.S. If Dr. Anderson does not pay you, be sure & make him give you his note, which will be as well, perhaps better. I do not wish Col. Irby to pay you, so if he offers to, decline.\'a0 I wish his note to accumulate for years as it is such a good Compound Interest\'85him keep it as long as he will.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Laurens C.H.]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 170\
Sunday night, 5 May [1850]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I hope you are now safe in Columbia, & resting after your journey.\'a0 According to promise I must write & tell you all that has occurred\'a0 since the moment you left, but very little of importance have I to tell you.\'a0 Friday afternoon Mr. Richardson called & said he was just from the Mill, & Mr. Taft said your wheat only turned out 183 pounds, that I must send a bag to the Mill & get 17 pounds more.\'a0 I told him you said he was celebrated for good wheat.\'a0 He said what he had just brought was good.\'a0 That wheat you got, Mr. Taft said was not secured enough, that the wet weather had given him no chance of securing it, so from this I expect the Flour is not very good, & I observe the Biscuits look black & do not rise well.\'a0 I sent the bag & got the 17 pounds. Friday Charles came in & planted the ground nuts, & prepared the ground for potatoes.\'a0 The slips we will have to buy.\'a0 Yesterday he planted his\'85, & we had in the afternoon a good rain, & last night it rained hard & with this morning, vegetation looks revived. Jim came home a little while last evening I expect for his tolls.\'a0 He thought he would do some mischief, so he set in the Cows to the Calves, so we got very little Milk. Yesterday afternoon I walked to see Mrs. Tom Gower.\'a0 She was out, then to see Mrs. Norton, who has been sick a long time, & then on to Mamma\'92s.\'a0 White at Mamma\'92s it rained hard so she had to send me home in the carri[a]ge.\'a0 This morning the children & myself went to church.\'a0 As it was damp, I called for Mrs. Walker.\'a0 Mr. Arthur gave us an old sermon on regeneration, to a very small congregation.\'a0 This afternoon there was no service.\'a0 The children were catechized.\'a0 Willie & Anna went, & afterwards we all went out to Mamma\'92s & took tea. At church Mr. Croft asked me if I would be home tomorrow at 9 oclock.\'a0 He wished to see me on a little business.\'a0 I told him yes, so I am quite anxious to know what it is about.\'a0 This afternoon I intended going to see Mr. Sam Town[e]s, but Reuben said Scott was lame.\'a0 At the church door when I was getting in the carri[a]ge he said the horse was so lame it could hardly walk, but I thought it only seemed a little lame, & that Reuben was afraid I was going to employ him this afternoon.\'a0 He said , it either sprained its awful kicking against the stable or had run a nail into its foot, in walking over the old planks in the stable yard, & said if I needed it this afternoon it might be lamed for life, so I told him to attend to Scott, & see that he got well soon.\'a0 Reuben loves to exaggerate.\'a0 It is raining now.\'a0 The servants have gone to church.\'a0 The children are upstairs in bed.\'a0 I am downstairs.\'a0 Charlotte told\'85little while ago, that today Mary joined the Methodist church.\'a0 It is no wonder they are turned out so soon, if they join with so little thought as I am sure she has\'85the dreadful accident happened on Mr. Arthurs R[ail] Road\'85yesterday while digging the earth & rocks fell on a servant of Mr. Arthur\'92s named Bob, & Mr. Walkers \ul Joe\ulnone , & \ul killed\ulnone  \ul them\ulnone .\'a0 Mr. Walker says an easy way of digging is, to dig the earth [word obscured] the bottom far under & then the earth on the top falls down, that the men were digging in this way, & after digging far under the earth did not fall, so Joe & Bob were told to dig a little more.\'a0 They began, & in a few moments, the earth & rocks came tumbling down on them & killed them.\'a0 She seems to bear it well, but it must be a great trial.\'a0 Mr. Arthur seemed the same as usual today, but I am sure he must be distressed at it. \'a0It was owing to carelessness of the Overseer I believe.\'a0 Mr. Arthur seems to have been unfortunate with negroes.\'a0 Your different papers have come, & 3 letters, one from Dr. Holland about a bill the Tugaloo estate owes him, one from Mr. Christie from Edgefield a few lines\'85Mr. Deans paper, & one from Peirce Earle to his Wife.\'a0 It is directed to you.\'a0 Ann says you must not forget to buy her the apple box.\'a0 Mrs. Arthur gave her a cap, & she thought she ought to make a return, & told her she would give her\'a0 one of those Apple boxes.\'a0 With regard to going to town my dear you must do just as you please.\'a0 I objected because I thought the expense was great, & the pleasure would not equal it, & if I was with you, it would be pleasant visiting my relations, but alone, you might not find it so, & that next year I hoped to go with you, & introduce you to them all, for some of the pleasantest, such as Aunt Mary McCall & Mrs. Susan Hayne, you have never even seen, & do everything you think proper as regards bank Stock.\'a0 If there is any risk, you might sell only half of the Stock.\'a0 Aunt Turnbull you saw in Greenville, so if you did not object, I would like you to call on her.\'a0 The Hayne family, most of them have treated us so\'a0 \'85\ul gently\ulnone , they have no claims on your politeness so I do not tell you to call on \ul them\ulnone , but Aunt Ann Turnbull & my Aunts there I would like you to see.\'a0 I feel \ul nearer\ulnone  to them, & they have always been kinder to us, than my \ul mothers\ulnone  \ul sisters\ulnone .\'a0 Tomorrow the Whitewashing will be commenced which is the reason I write tonight.\'a0 The home will be in confusion.\'a0 This is the only sheet of letter paper in the\'85.\'a0 It is blotted, but you must excuse it, you left me badly off.\'a0 I will leave room to add a few lines tomorrow, telling what Mr. Croft wishes to see me for.\'a0 Mamma says Mr. McBee told Susan Anna was the admiration of all at Mrs. Cannons Mayday.\'a0 Frank is still head.\'a0 Willie\'92s colt is doing quite well.\'a0 Fanny talks about Papa, & wished you home the day you left.\'a0 I hope your horse held out, & that you did not get wet.\'a0 My pen is so bad, I am afraid you cannot make out my letter.\'a0 Mr. Croft says he has not sent down yet for his groceries, that it will be a month at least before they are here.\'a0 The\'85will be out of seed, so if you can buy them in Columbia, you must buy some & send by Mr. Elford or the first person coming.\'a0 If you can get a cage, you must buy one.\'a0 The female has lately had some more feathers plucked out, & the male does not sing at all, so they ought to be separated before they kill each other.\
