\f1\b 172\
Wednesday morning, 8 May 1850\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have stopped in the midst of my housecleaning to write to you. but I am in such confusion, I cannot collect my ideas sufficiently to write an interesting letter.\'a0 I have had the whole house whitewashed.\'a0 When the carpet & furniture was moved out of the Dining room, the walls looked so dirty, I thought it best as I was obliged to buy yellow wash for the little dining room, to have another coat given to the big one, so it has been done.\'a0 Mr. Smith is here with his brother & will finish today.\'a0 They commenced the house yesterday & having to dismantle the whole of it\'a0 you cannot conceive the disorder it is in, but I am willing for it, for the sake of cleanliness that follows & when you see the quantity of dirt swept under the Carpet, Furniture & corners you would wonder how we could have existed.\'a0 It is well you are away.\'a0 You would have to leave on three occasions, whether business called you away or not.\'a0 Last night Anna, Fanny & myself slept in Anna\'92s bed. It is now raining a little.\'a0 Reuben & Lindy have gone regularly to the Farm.\'a0 Scott\'92s lameness is better.\'a0 Hochelago, yesterday laid down a good deal, & I was afraid was sick.\'a0 Charles brought Mr. Longs Dudley down who said nothing seemed the matter with him.\'a0 He expected he was suffering from the operation he had gone through.\'a0 I do not think he will ever get over that.\'a0 He seems so sad & dispirited.\'a0 It has certainly lamed him.\'a0 I\'a0 hope to hear from you tonight.\'a0 Mr. D\'85\'92s came here yesterday afternoon to say a Piano had arrived, & you should have the refusal of it;\'a0 that it was a very fine instrument & Anna\'92s mind was capable of learning more than she did at present, & he was anxious she should commence with a class now forming.\'a0 The price of the Piano frieght\'a0 included 300 & you pay at your convenience.\'a0 Mama, Susan & myself went up to hear the Piano.\'a0 As well as we could judge it seemed a fine one.\'a0 Mr. D\'85 sent me yesterday a letter to you, which he requested I enclose to you at Columbia, speaking of the Piano & advising Anna to learn.\'a0 I do not send it, because you will be at home so soon, you can then decide on the matter.\'a0 If you could pay for the Piano, I would like to get one, but I cannot say I wish you to go in debt for it, so we will speak on the subject when you return.\'a0 That is time enough.\'a0 He expects other Pianos which will be more reasonable, though perhaps not as good, so it is no\'85to determine at once.\'a0 If anyone wishes this Piano that has arrived I will call Mr. D\'85 to let them have it.\'a0 When you return we can decide whether it is best Anna should commence at once, whether this year we can afford it. Mrs. Tom Rowland has a Son, & Mrs. Charles Rabb has lost hers.\'a0 You know she brought one with her from Louisiana.\'a0 It died yesterday.\'a0 Miss Markley is not expected to live long.\'a0 Mr. Choice is going soon to send the boys, under his charge to Princeton, so Mrs. Blake will lose them as scholars.\'a0 Mr. Beattie says he knows she will have a good school, but several think her terms too high.\'a0 Do you not think Mr. Croft\'92s plan a cunning one.\'a0 The Dr. Crofts can afford better than most to pay for their children dancing.\'a0 Old Mr. Croft can pay for Mrs. Pearsons, & yet he would wish Mrs. Blake to stay with him, save her about 30 dollars, & give his grandchildren 80 dollars worth of dancing, & speaks as if he was quite kind in making the proposal; says he would be the means of putting hundreds in her pocket, that if she makes it she shall have her glass of wine every day, as if that was really extraordinary. Mamma saw Mr. Arthur lately in the streets.\'a0 He seems to bear his loss well, as I said, only the week before he bought the boy for 600 dollars.\'a0 Mrs. Arthur has had headaches lately, but has not yet been in the state she usually is after her confinements.\'a0 Mrs. Thomas I believe is still suffering with her knee.\'a0 Saturday I went to see her, & she was then not able to put it to the ground. We are all well.\'a0 I would write more to you, if I had received a letter from you.\'a0 I hope you will get a new trial in Miss Green\'92s case.\'a0 Aunt Eliza wrote to Mamma that E\'85 had received my letter about the bonnet, & would purchase it, that if I had written the age of the young lady it would have been a guide but as it was she would try & do her best.\'a0 I am certain it will be a pretty bonnet, at any rate prettier than could be got here.\'a0 I will never get a bonnet in Greenville.\'a0 They are always old fashioned. The Drawing room is fixed, & Minerva & Mary are now fixing the Entry.\'a0 Upstairs is whitewashed but nothing else done yet.\'a0 The little dining room now is to be yellow washed.\'a0 I wish every part of the establishment just in order, but it will take a long time.\'a0 Charles is working in the garden, but is called off very often to move furniture.\'a0 I must now stop.\'a0 I went to your Office yesterday to look for writing paper but could find only this coarse kind & saw no ink.\'a0 I am badly off for all materials for writing, so you must make excuses.\'a0 I would not write today I am so busy, but you may be uneasy if you do not hear. So I write. I long to see you.\'a0 I forgot to send last night to the Post office, so do not know if any letters have come.\'a0 Adieu, Your attached Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 173\
Tuesday afternoon, 18 June 1850\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I will this afternoon write you a few lines as you told me to though I am very busy.\'a0 After the Mail comes in tonight, if any letter comes for you, I will add a few lines & tell you.\'a0 I intended writing tonight instead of this afternoon, but Anna tells me Susan Hoke is coming over to sleep.\'a0 Her father is away.\'a0 If so I will be engaged with her & would only write a line or so. Willie & Anna commenced Dancing yesterday afternoon.\'a0 They have gone again this afternoon.\'a0 I expect Mrs. Blake will give lessons every afternoon, so she will make a good deal in a short time.\'a0 She had yesterday 19 scholars, but many who intend learning, either did not know of it, or were not prepared, so her school will encrease.\'a0 I have not seen her since Sunday.\'a0 Then she said she would be willing to stay at Mr. Crofts & teach for nothing as many children as paid her board.\'a0 All over Mr. Croft ought to pay for.\'a0 I sent a message to her today, & she was there at Mr. Crofts.\'a0 He has sent down his carriage for her, so I would not be surprised if an agreement is made between them.\'a0 Mrs. Pearson is so anxious her children should learn.\'a0 I carried Mrs. Blake to church Sunday morning & afternoon.\'a0 Mr. Arthur gave us long sermons, in the afternoon an old one.\'a0 Susans Alexander was baptized, & Mrs. Arthurs baby.\'a0 Alexander behaved well, but Mrs. Arthur\'92s baby screamed from beginning to end & seemed to agitate her. \'a0Miss Lewis came this morning before we had done breakfast to practice.\'a0 She says they have heard from Mrs. Thomas lately & she still is obliged to use a crutch.\'a0 Mr. & Mrs. Poinsett paid me a visit this morning, said they would come again, when you were at home.\'a0 They say they have not half read the House of Orleans, & asked if we were in a hurry for it.\'a0 I told them no, they could keep it as long as they pleased.\'a0 Mrs. Poinsett had been to Mr. Arthurs, & she says his negroes have again run away, that 3 of them are in the Charleston Jail.\'a0 I suppose they are from the Contract in Newberry, but I do not know.\'a0 He has trouble enough with his negroes.\'a0 He today has gone to his contract in Anderson.\'a0 I wonder he has time to write such long sermons.\'a0 I carried Fanny to church Sunday afternoon, but she behaved very badly.\'a0 I hope Frank is behaving well.\'a0 Tomorrow the 19
\fs24\fsmilli12222 \super th
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \nosupersub  is his Birth Day.\'a0 He will be 7 years old.\'a0 Willie says that he misses him, & the house is so much quieter. As I have so much less trouble that I miss him in a very agreeable way.\'a0 \'85I hope travelling will so much improve him, that he will behave well when he comes back. Two letters came for you Sunday night, one from Mr. Jamison saying he had received the half of the bills you had sent & begging you to send on the other half.\'a0 The other letter from Eutaw from Mr. Coleman saying the Court had allowed Washington Foster until October to settle his accounts with the Estate, the reason given, that the money was loaned out & had to be sued for & would not be collected until that time. We have had no rain.\'a0 Charles came in last night, & said they were getting the Farm in good order.\'a0 On Sunday while cutting wood, Reuben hurt his knee with the axe, & told Willie he could hardly walk.\'a0 I saw he walked lame, but he said nothing to me about it.\'a0 This afternoon he has returned early from the farm, & Charlotte told me he said he had come because his knee hurt him.\'a0 He left Lindy to hoe I suppose.\'a0 I have not seen him to ask about it, but will this evening when he brings me the keys. I have no news to tell you.\'a0 I have not been out except to church, & have seen only those who I told you came today & Susan Hoke & Mrs. Blake.\'a0 The walking in this dirty weather is so disagreeable I do not like to go out.\'a0 I have been busy working hardly had time to practice.\'a0 Anna says Mrs. Davis is sick in bed with Rheumatism\'a0\'a0 The pianos Mrs. Davids said were on there way, some of them actually in Hamburg, have taken so long to come, that I rather think he deceived us, & that he never wrote on for any more, until we took the one that came, for if the others had been on the way as he said\'a0 they would have been here before this.\'a0 I think ours a fine Piano.\'a0 I played for Mr. & Mrs. Poinsett, & they both thought it a very fine one, & not expensive.\'a0 I like it too, but still as some others might come I would prefer, I do not intend to decide yet until I see them, & whether you pay or not will make no difference.\'a0 I will still be at liberty to exchange this if I see proper.\'a0 I wish to feel perfectly satisfied with my bargain.\'a0 If I prefer this to any that come I will keep it, & if I do not I will exchange it for the one I like better. The household are well, including horses hogs &c except Reuben\'92s knee being hurt, which I suppose will not prevent his working tomorrow.\'a0 We are well.\'a0 Charles last night said when he went to bed at night\'a0 he was in pain all over.\'a0 I suppose old age & infirmities.\'a0 I am afraid he will not be able to work much longer.\'a0 I will stop & add something tonight.\
