\f1\b 175\
Saturday night, 24 November [1850]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 You only left this morning, & yet you see I am already writing to you.\'a0 I intended writing tomorrow evening but as it will be Sunday, I will wish to send to Mary & Lindy.\'a0 I thought it best to write some this evening.\'a0 I will as usual tell all that has occurred since you left.\'a0 Fanny did not cry very long. & was quieted by sitting in my lap & eating an apple, & tonight is made happy by being put in my bed to sleep. Mr. Moore came this morning to sell Eggs, & I told him of your paper & that he must take it.\'a0 I did not give him a Prospectus, because I was afraid he would not understand it, & I would rather give them when I have the peice you wrote afterwards, to give along with it, for the Prospectus needs an explanation.\'a0 It has been so unrepresented.\'a0 I sent all of the letters you left to the Post office.\'a0 The boy sent word that the postage would amount to $1.35, & you can charge it to the Printing office.\'a0 The Columbia mail brought your newspapers, & a letter from Mr. Pettigru in answer to the one you wrote him, when Mr. Elford was in the desponding humour.\'a0 He said he hopes you will go on with the paper; that one established now on Constitutional principles he knows will succeed, & will deserve the gratitude of the rising generation; that he thinks the Disunion spirit is already lessening , but it would be better if the State did commit some folly & get into a scrape such as separate State action, for it would bring her to sense of her ill conduct, though it would be mortifying to be laughed at by everybody; that it is vanity more than any other feeling that influences South Carolina, so he think it will soon pass away. He says he will see you in Columbia, so as this is the case it will not be worthwhile to send you his letter, & I can make good use of it here.\'a0 Mr. Pickerell came this afternoon to fix the Clock, & we had a political talk.\'a0 He agrees with you, & I told him of Mr. O\'92Hanlon\'92s & Mr. Petttigru\'92s opinions, & he said he knew them both by reputation, so I offered to loan him the letters to read, at which he seemed pleased, so I lent them.\'a0 He said he went to the Mansion House the other evening to see the Phrenologist, who is a very intelligent person, & Dr. Simons came in & turned the conversation on politics, & said he went for Disunion, & they ought to ask Congress for something\'a0 she \ul could\ulnone  \ul not\ulnone  \ul grant\ulnone , & then we would have Disunion.\'a0 Mr. Pickerell said someone went to his shop the other day, & asked him if as a Chemist he could explain how it was that you & Genl Thompson had got together; that he told him \ul you \ulnone were where you had always been, & could not help it if Genl Thompson came over to you.\'a0 All who wish to know ought to ask Genl Thompson to explain it. I see by the Courier the Nashville Convention has adjourned & propose a Southern Congress, & see the death of Mr. Daniel Webster who died suddenly in church. This afternoon I went to see the Miss Anderson\'92s & I explained the State of the country to them.\'a0 They say if you go for the Union they will certainly take your paper.\'a0 They agree entirely with you in Politics.\'a0 They say they had heard nothing of the Meeting & Mr. Memminger until Mr. Cox paid them a visit, & they asked him what he thought of matters, & he said it was generally thought now the time had come to Secede & judging from the Demonstrations in honor of Mr. Memminger that was the popular feeling here & begged him to let him request Mr.\'a0 Cam[p]bell to send his paper to them, so you were either mistaken in thinking Mr. Cox agreed with you; or he has changed; or he is on both sides; but the people are so deceived; it is no wonder they think as they do.\'a0 I look for your paper to enlighten them.\'a0 Until that comes out they will remain in ignorance.\'a0 Miss Anderson says you will\'85with justice, if not now, in years to come; when the children of those now who are opposed to you, will be disgraced on account of the conduct of their fathers.\'a0 So my dear husband, act as your Duty dictates; bring forward a resolution for a Southern Convention; make a noble speech on the subject; that will be handed down to posterity; be sure that you say everything that is true & right & consistent with a Patriot & have it published in the Carolinian.\'a0\'a0 You have been\'85now as much as you can be.\'a0 I think the Editors are tired now they have vented their spleen & cannot find any words stronger to express it.\'a0 Do not vote for \ul Mr.\ulnone  \ul Memminger\ulnone , \ul Mr.\ulnone  \ul Burt\ulnone . \ul Mr.\ulnone  \ul Rion\ulnone , & you know who. I hope you had a pleasant journey down, that the horses did not give out, & Willie & Frank are behaving well.\'a0 As you went off Charles said Scott would give out; that he had a strain in his back; that he was injured before you bought him; that you were cheated by the Drover.\'a0 I hope he is not correct in his opinion.\'a0 Tomorrow night I will finish my letter & tell you of everything else that occurs.\'a0 If it were not for want of space, I would write all\'85longer, but I must leave room for what may occur tomorrow.\'a0 Do not forget Susan Hokes Music, \'93Roll on Silver Moon.\'94\'a0 Miss Anderson tells me she heard Dr. Simons & Mrs. Temple had quarreled.\'a0 I do not know if true or not\'85.Sunday night.\'a0 My dear husband, I will now finish my letter.\'a0 I went to church this morning, & heard an \ul old\ulnone  sermon from Mr. Arthur in praise of the Liturgy, which I expect was not interesting to Col Town[e]s & some other Baptists that were there.\'a0 Mr. Arthur attends to his worldly business all the week, & then Sunday gives us an old sermon.\'a0 This afternoon Mamma sent for me to go & see Susan\'92s baby which was not well, but it is better than it was this morning, & after paying Susan a visit, Mamma & myself rode up the Anderson road\'a0 & stopped at Mr. Tom Butlers house & went over it, & then stopped at Mr. Saxons house where Mr. M\'85 staid & went into that.\'a0 Mrs. Carson is to live there, & they are now preparing to plaster it. so Mr. Carson & Mr. Butler will be near neighbors.\'a0 The day has been so cold.\'a0 I thought tomorrow Charles with Marys assistance had better kill some of the smallest hogs, but he says he has to haul more wood first, & tomorrow he will borrow Mr. Goodletts horse, & put with Selim, & haul a load of wood, & if the next day is cold he will kill some of the hogs.\'a0 A good many persons have killed. I see in the Chronicle & Sentinel Mr. Kings & Mr. Clemens Senators from Alabama expressing the same views you do.\'a0 You must while in Columbia do all you can for the paper.\'a0 Get Mr. Pettigru, Mr. O\'92Hanlon, Mr. Yeadon & all your friends who agree with you to interest themselves in sustaining it.\'a0 They ought all to get subscribers for it, for never has a paper been more traduced or have more to encounter than yours has.\'a0 The State is so provoked that after buying up the Mountaineer & get that in the proper training, another should be started in the very place, that they know is above a\'85& may spoil their game.\'a0Write me every Mail, tell me everything, & tell Willie to write.\'a0 I hope Frank & himself are doing well, & will return improved & do credit to you.\'a0 Tell them from me, they must be \ul good\ulnone  \ul boys\ulnone .\'a0 They must keep themselves neat & clean, & they must read in the prayer book every morning & night.\'a0 And my dear husband you must act judiciously & wisely.\'a0 I do wish you could have been elected Judge or some honorable Office that the world might see you had at least met with your reward for people are apt to think until persons are rewarded, that they do not deserve i, & my ambition is you should be appreciated by others, & you seem further from it now than ever, but I must be resigned & hope that even you will meet with your reward & I believe if you were more anxious for it, you would.\'a0 Adieu, your attached Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

