\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Reuben returned this evening, but brought no letter from you, for which I was very sorry; but\'a0 I hope you were so busy talking to Col. Brockman enlightening him & others that it left you no time to write to me.\'a0 I am glad you reached Mr. Felkes in safety, & that the horses did not give out as Charles predicted.\'a0 Reuben says they are well, only tired, so they shall rest awhile. You are now in Columbia in the midst of the excitement.\'a0 The papers that came today, I see are full of Judge Cheves speech, but I do not intend to read it, as I have not you to do away any impression it might make on me.\'a0 I thought I would try & enlighten someone, so I sent some papers last night to Mr. Nicol to read, the Chronicle & Sentinel containing Mr. King & Mr. Clemens\'92 speeches, & another with Judge Nes\'85 letter, & he said he would read anything I sent him.\'a0 A letter today came from Mr. Thomas McLure of Chester C.H. begging you to send him the first number of your paper & mentioning a gentleman\'a0 to whom you must also send it, as he thought they would like to subscribe for it.\'a0 The names of the gentlemen were John Rosborough Esqr, Chester C.H.; Peter Wylie, Do; Dr. A.P. Wylie, Do; James Drennan Esqr., Chesnut Grove; Danl. G. Stenson Esqr, Cedar Shoal; William Heath, [Do]; William Moffat, Lewisville, Chester District; William A. Rosborough, [Do]; James Hemphill, Esqr, Chester C.H. I went to see the Miss Andersons yesterday afternoon to carry them some books & papers.\'a0 Miss Anderson told me Mr. Cox told her, that Slavery was \ul abolished\ulnone  in the District of Columbia, so either he is very ignorant, or he says, what he knows is not so.\'a0 I almost wish the State would secede this winter, get into a scrape as Mr. Pettigru says, & then perhaps she would be brought to her senses.\'a0Mr. Arthur came to see me yesterday.\'a0 I did not say anything wrong that you would have disapproved, but I expressed the state of matters to him & how the paper originated &c, & he was very mild, & agreed with me in all I said about Politics &c; said Mr. Watson presented the Southern Association paper to him to sign it.\'a0 He told him before he was a Minister he was a Democrat, but now he had done with Politics.\'a0 So now I have seen Mr. Arthur & talked to him.\'a0 I have better feelings towards him than I had.\'a0 I think I gave him a great deal of information.\'a0 But I think the Episcopal Church on account of the \ul Members\ulnone , it is composed of, it is really high time now for me to leave.\'a0 Who do you think has joined it?\'a0 Why \ul Mrs.\ulnone  \ul Choice\ulnone  that vindictive ill tempered woman.\'a0 She is still a Baptist in heart. So she was not satisfied with sprinkling, or she thought that not sufficient to wash away her sins, so yesterday she was \ul emersed\ulnone  by Mr. Arthur, & next Sunday is Communion Sunday, so I suppose she will commune.\'a0 Mrs. Joe Powel who I met at the Miss Andersons told me that when she was ill, she heard Mr. Arthur administered the Sacrament to her; so if so, it was after taking that solemn ordinance, she went to Mr. Nicol so infuriated because she had voted for you so it had certainly not changed her heart, or improved her temper.\'a0 The Lords Supper is a feast of \ul Love\ulnone , & when I think of Mrs. Jones who said she \ul hated\ulnone  \ul me\ulnone ; Mrs. Choice & Mrs. Walker who \ul hate\ulnone  \ul you\ulnone , Mrs. Rowland who has always seemed so unfriendly to us \ul both\ulnone , Dr. Crittenden who is so violent against you; Dr. Irvine who is ready now to see his count[r]y in war & bloodshed; I cannot but think it is sacrilegious\'a0 to unite with such; so next Sunday I do not think I can feel it my duty to go to the Episcopal church.\'a0 I am afraid I will commit a greater sin in going than staying away. Tonight a letter has come from Mr. W.M.D. Crowder, Due West, asking for a place in the office of the Southern Patriot.\'a0 He says he can work either at the Case or Press, & the terms whatever is usually paid to Journeymen in the upcountry offices; says he can give you references as to attention to Duty.\'a0 Two Chronicles & Sentinels have come, & that is all. Last Saturday night a Mr. Campbell from Anderson came to see you on business, but he said the business was not important. The children & myself are well.\'a0 When Fanny was saying her prayers, I told her to pray that Papa, Willie & Frank might come safe home, & she said \'93bring Papa, Mr. Duncan Willie & Frank safe home.\'94 Eliza & Minerva as usual are complaining.\'a0 I never knew so much cramp in the stomach as they have.\'a0 Minerva sent in this morning for some Brandy, because she had cramp in the stomach, & then sent word to say she could not work, & she has been in her room all day.\'a0 When she sends for Brandy again, I will send her pepper or pepper tea, for as the spirits do not cure her, it is no use to waste it.\'a0 If all persons made as much fuss as she & Eliza do, in their situations, it would really be dreadful.\'a0 Theye not delicate creatures indeed.\'a0 I hope Willie & Frank have behaved well, & given you no trouble.\'a0 I long to hear from you.\'a0 I have very little to write about.\'a0 I hope though in the \ul minority\ulnone , you will have a pleasant time in Columbia. Dr. Simons scholars are to \ul speak\ulnone  in the Methodist church next Friday morning, & receive Diplomas; young ladies, mind Susan Hoke says in his advertisement he says his school has been most flourishing, consisting of a \ul majority\ulnone  of the respectable families in Greenville, that it is entirely a Southern Institution; & he hopes that parents will send to him, instead of sending to Philadelphia & New York, that he will assist in establishing that \ul non\ulnone  \ul intercourse\ulnone  with the North, so desirable at the present time. Mrs. Temple is going away, so I dare say, she & Dr. Simons did have a quarrel.\'a0 He has angered\'a0 another teacher an English lady I heard, & yet he says his institution is all \ul Southern\ulnone .\'a0 Any humbug can succeed, after him.\'a0 I was at Susan\'92s this afternoon, her baby is well now.\'a0 Send Susan Hoke\'92s Music by Mail.\'a0 It is \'93Roll on Silver Moon.\'94\'a0 It is now time to stop.\'a0 I will have more to write about when I hear from you.\'a0 As soon as the weather gets cold, the hogs shall be killed.\'a0 Charles killed the smallest one\'a0 yesterday, was to give us some fresh meat.\'a0 Good night, your attached Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 177\
Thursday night, 28 November 1850\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received your letter this morning, & was very glad to hear from you.\'a0 You must write me \ul every\ulnone  \ul Mail\ulnone .\'a0 I live on your letters & think on the contents of one, until I get another.\'a0 Your news as regards Politics is cheering, but I am afraid you are mistaken.\'a0 It is a bad idea for Judge Cheves to be thought of as Governor, & I think would be unpropitious\'a0 for the State.\'a0 Mr. Memminger with his usual hypocrisy, begins with appealing to the Most High, & re commencing a \ul Fast\ulnone .\'a0 He thinks after \ul this\ulnone , his sincerity cannot be doubted & he will certainly be made Chancellor.\'a0 Do you \ul vote\ulnone  against him, & do all you \ul can\ulnone  \ul against\ulnone  him.\'a0 He has done more to cause the excitement, at any rate in Greenville, than any other man.\'a0 He has \ul deceived\ulnone  the people, & told absolute falsehoods to gain his worldly ends, & then at the same time, pretends he is such a Christian.\'a0 He uses both worlds. As for Mr. Jones, he is as contemptible & mean a man as ever lived.\'a0 He occasions me more vexation than anyone else, for he is constantly doing something so mean.\'a0 He gets what he can from the Anti Bank men, & then what he can from the Bank men.\'a0 It seems as if he pursues the course to get along, for instead of being treated with the \ul contempt\ulnone  he deserves, he is \ul rewarded\ulnone .\'a0 By treachery he gats into the Legislature, & now by Treachery, he will be elected Solicitor, for it only requires electioneering to succeed.\'a0 Court both parties, & he will get what he wishes.\'a0 If he is elected Solicitor, I will never get over it.\'a0 It will be too provoking to think of, & I have no doubt he will, for he is a better Electioneerer\'a0 than Mr. Young.\'a0 He is a Member which is an advantage, & he will by his vanity & conceit make the impression that he is a very important man at home.\'a0 He is no better than Joe P\'85.\'a0 It is strange he should ever have been tolerated in Greenville, but it seems as if he can act just as mean as he chooses, & yet he is thought not the less of.\'a0 I hope Mr. Duncan is now convinced of his \ul true\ulnone  character. Mr. Burt\'92s deceit equals his malice. He has injured you as much as he possibly could\'a0 killed your paper in Pendleton as Mr. Keith said, & now to gain your \ul vote\ulnone , tells a falsehood, & says he ordered your peice to be published.\'a0 He did no such thing, & he must think you a Simpleton, to try to deceive you so\'85.\'a0 I hope you have more sense & spirit than to be taken in by him.\'a0 Tell him from \ul me\ulnone , that you have \ul my\ulnone  \ul orders\ulnone  \ul not\ulnone  to \ul vote\ulnone  for him, that if you vote for him, I will \ul never\ulnone  \ul forgive\ulnone  \ul you\ulnone .\'a0 I look upon him, as having helped, more than anyone else, to defeat you for Congress, & you are not to turn round & \ul help\ulnone  \ul him\ulnone  to what he wishes.\'a0 With the exception of Mr. Jones, he is one of your greatest enemies, insignificant men, those even you have a \ul contempt\ulnone  for can injure & ruin you.\'a0 The\ul \'85\ulnone in Cuba can undermine & destroy the strongest foundations.\'a0 Mr. Burt need not trouble himself about amusing Willie & Frank.\'a0 He shows his interested motive too plainly. I am glad Willie & Frank have behaved well.\'a0 You must be particular in making them keep themselves clean, have their boots cleaned, their hair parted nicely & smooth, & combed every night with a fine tooth comb.\'a0 They must clean their teeth, wear their gloves when they go out, & keep their clothes brushed, & then behave like little gentlemen.\'a0 Tell them I hope to hear constantly good accounts of them.\'a0 You must get a good supply of clothes for yourself, everything you need. I am glad Col. Brockman is right in Politics.\'a0 I was fearful not seeing the \ul right\ulnone  side of the question he might go wrong.\'a0 I am pleased also that the prospects for your paper are encouraging.\'a0 Mr. Elford ought to act for awhile as agent in Charleston.\'a0 Miss Anderson told me she wished she had thousands to assist in sustaining the paper, that she would take it of course, & you would find persons springing up in every direction\'a0 who would take it.\'a0 Now you are in Columbia & see persons from every part of the State.\'a0 You must not be backwards in asking them to subscribe & do all they can for it.\'a0 Do not forget to stop the Palmetto Banner.\'a0 I saw Mr. S\'85ham the other evening & gave him Mr. O\'92Hanlon, Mr. Pettigrus, & Mr. McLures letters to read to encourage him.\'a0 Mr. Nicol today sent to ask me\'a0 if I had heard any interesting new[s] from Columbia to let him know the items.\'a0 You must tell me all the news, so I may tell others.\'a0 I wish the Mountaineer would let you write for it.\'a0 You can tell the people in that way so much, & influence them right.\'a0 Anything written for that paper now, by the other party will be entirely false.\'a0 Mr. Jones\'92 treachery ought to be known.\'a0 He\'92ll not tell it, but I dare say he will gain by it. In future,\'a0 instead of being treated with the contempt he deserves, he will get \ul both\ulnone  Bank & Anti Bank votes.\'a0 I always knew he was for the bank, for I dare say he is indebted to it in some way. Either borrowed, or other borrowed for him. Minerva has now been 3 days in her room doing nothing, says she cant come out to lift pots & pans.\'a0 I tell her she can have Charotte to help her, but she is not satisfied with that.\'a0 She wishes Mary & Lindy, & with the small family I now have, & so little cooking, it is not necessary to have a grown woman & herself to cook, so she stays in her room.\'a0 I try Bakers bread, & have tea & toast & Eggs & Charlotte looks after the servants.\'a0 She makes more fuss than Mrs. Sharpe with her delicate health.\'a0 Eliza is up now & sewing.\'a0 Reuben instead of wearing his own hat to travel, borrowed a new one of Charles & returned\'a0 a different one to Charles from the one he sent him.\'a0 Reuben says it must have got changed.\'a0 Charles says he knows he sold it, & pocketed the money.\'a0 He was in a great passion, when he found it out, but now he is calm & says you will make Reuben pay him.\'a0 The horses have rested now, & today Reuben hauled Mr. D\'85 a load of wood\'a0 & brought me 50 cts.\'a0 It has been raining all day, so he hauled only 1 load.\'a0 Mr. Davis went somewhere today on business, so Anna has holiday until Monday.\'a0 Tomorrow Dr. Simons scholars speak in the Methodist church.\'a0 He has but 2 boarders, but his school breaks up for the holidays this week, Miss Anderson was here this morning to borrow books.\'a0 She says she hopes you will buy the 3d vol of McCaulay\'92s history of England in Columbia.\'a0 She is anxious to see it.\'a0 If you can get the continuation of \'93Laneton Parsonage,\'94 I would like it.\'a0 I have the first one & a second & a third I think have been published.\'a0 Also the\'85Daughter by the same author, & there is a Book called \'93the lady Alice or the new Una,\'94 which Mr. Brown mentioned as being very fine, I would like, but I only mention in case you have a Book mania\'a0 as usual.\'a0 Whatever you get, must be something pretty.\'a0 Mamma wrote today to know if I had heard from you.\'a0 She is as much interested in your interests as I am.\'a0 The Chronicle & Sentinel has two speeches by Mr. King & Clemens of Alabama, which are very good.\'a0 You must get the paper & read them.\'a0 If you make a speech, you will find them of service.\'a0 I would send you the paper, but I make great use of them.\'a0 Mr. Arthur has them now.\'a0 Mr. Clemens says from Maryland, N. Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky & Texas & Delaware some of their men have voted for the admission of California, so we must secede from them too.\'a0 Mr. Jones goes to Columbia tomorrow, no letters but what I have mentioned have come.\'a0 Good night, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 178\
Saturday night, 30 November [1850]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received Willie\'92s & your letters today & was very much pleased with them.\'a0 
\f2\i \'a0
\f0\i0 I wish you would write me two or three letters every Mail in your absence.\'a0 They are my only comfort.\'a0 Mail days I watch for the hour hand to point to 12.\'a0 Tell Willie his was a pretty letter, & he must write me a longer one.\'a0 If you buy him so many books, you must buy such as I would like, any works by Mrs. Howitt is good, buy Mrs. Sherwoods works, Mrs. O\'85\'92s, Miss Sewel\'92s.\'a0 There was a work called Evenings at Donaldson Manor, mentioned lately in the Carolinian, if it is not too expensive get, but it was mentioned as being nicely bound & handsomely illustrated, so I expect it is too expensive, & you will have plenty of use for your money, in other ways.\'a0 I do wish you could be elected Chancellor.\'a0 The very thought thrills me.\'a0 You might have let Col. Dudley nominate you & felt your prospects, even if you did not run.\'a0 It is well to be thought of for it, if not now, it will do you good for the future.\'a0 I see Col. B.G. Alston nominated for Governor, & yet I am sure he is not going to run, but it is a compliment for him to be spoken of. Do my dear husband if you think there is a chance of you being elected Judge or Chancellor, or running tolerably well, now, it may be of service to you.\'a0 Genl Whitner who has been beaten so often, perhaps now will be elected.\'a0 Her seems now to have a claim to it, from having been a Candidate so long, but You must not vote for Genl Whitner.\'a0 He has beaten you too badly.\'a0 I hope he will be obliged to continue Solicitor & then that aspirant for Solicitor will be disappointed and otherwise he may not be.\'a0 Mr. Memminger I suppose is conscious how interested his motive was in changing in Politics so he feels compelled to give up the Chancellorship.\'a0 I wish you could be elected.\'a0 It would be wise to let your friends find out for you, how many votes you would be likely to get.\'a0 You could ascertain I should think, beforehand\'a0 how many votes you would get.\'a0 When you ran for President of the Bank, you knew at first you would be beaten, & therefore you ought not to have run.\'a0 You always decline too soon.\'a0 You ought to let your friends find out, before you decline, what your prospects are, & if they find out they are not good, then it is time to decline.\'a0 I am glad Col. Hayne met you kindly.\'a0 I heard he was \'85lent in Politics, so I thought he would look on you as a Traitor & not speak to you.\'a0 I dare say you will see nothing of Mr. Taylor & Mr. Martin\'92s family.\'a0 They are very selfish, & even now to have no regard for us, whose house was once offered to them when they were in reduced circumstances\'a0 & had no home.\'a0 Mamma was like a Mother to Mrs. Taylor & Mrs. Martin, & we were intimate with them\'85of our own cousins, but I now look upon them as less than strangers,\'a0 Eloisa & Sarah are now as cold & selfish as possible.\'a0 I am pleased at you fitting out yourself with new clothes.\'a0 If sack dress coats had been worn, I would have preferred one to a Frock Coat.\'a0 You must get Susan Hokes Music at once, \'93Roll on Silver Moon,[\'93] & send it by Mail, that is if it can be got.\'a0 I am sorry to tell you that Eliza\'92s child did not live a day.\'a0 It was 5 weeks or more too soon, & owing to her falls I suppose. was outwardly bruised & inwardly hurt, & also Mom Phillis not being here in time, might have been bad for it.\'a0 From the fact of its being born alive, I wrote to you in good spirits, thinking it would live, for Mary\'92s that was so delicate lived 5 or 6 weeks, & perhaps longer if she had been careful, but N\'85 came to see Eliza a few hours after, & as soon as she saw it, said she did not think it would live.\'a0 Minerva came out of her room today but has done very little, & I will not give her more to do; let her do as she pleases, but I expect it will\'85with her as it did before; for I have never known two persons complain as she & Eliza have done. Mrs.. Arthur & Miss Lewis paid me a visit this morning. Miss Lewis had on a white Straw bonnet, & did not look near as well as in black.\'a0 She talks very little, if no more to Mr. Campbell she will not trouble him much, but I am glad they continue friendly.\'a0 I feared the paper & Mr. Campbell to be connected with them might have cooled them. Mary has just brought from the office a letter from Mr. George Gordon of Savannah.\'a0 He says he has a Mortgage on the Property lately occupied by Mr. Service, that he contemplated foreclosing & you will be so good as to inform him what time is necessary for the Legal proceedings in this State, & how long a Sale may be postponed after obtaining a decree.\'a0 He says he does not contemplate a public Sale until September, & not then at any\'85& positive sacrifice, rather than this he would desire you at the proper time to bid it in for him, & for your general services in the matter, please state the probable cost of proceedings &c.\'a0 This is all that is in the letter, so perhaps you had better answer it at once. It was suggested to Dr. Simons that it would not be proper for young ladies to speak in a public church, so he is to read the Essays himself.\'a0 It rained so yesterday, he postponed his exhibition as he calls it until Monday.\'a0 He is to \ul confer\ulnone  \ul Degrees\ulnone .\'a0 He is certainly a \ul great\ulnone  \ul Humbug\ulnone .\'a0 I am glad Mr. Fuller found him out, but there are many here, who would patronize him, just to show opposition to the Academy.\'a0 Mr. Brooks children now have left Mr. Davis .\'a0 Two of them go to Mr. Burnham. It would be bad for the State for Judge Cheves to be elected Governor, as he goes for Disunion, so you had better try & get a more reasonable man than he is.\'a0 I dare say his address will have a great effect, in making the State go for Disunion.\'a0 I have no news to tell you.\'a0 If tomorrow I can think of anything more I will begin another sheet.\'a0 I have a shocking pen.\'a0 Tell Willie I will write to him & Anna will too.\'a0 If you can buy a Male Canary bird bring it to me as my present.\'a0 It will be company for me when I am alone, & the cage ought to be used.\'a0 The Male bird sings. Mr. Rion I suppose was disappointed.\'a0 Because he was a prot\'e9g\'e9 of Mr. Calhoun he thought he would be elected I expect.\'a0 Mr. Calhoun really is to cost the State a good deal.\'a0 He would be satisfied if he knew how he was remembered.\'a0 You must write to Mr. S\'85 & others here & inform him & them of Politics &c as you have no other way of informing.\'a0 I am glad Frank is behaving pretty well.\'a0 Tell Willie he must not read books so fast.\'a0 He must borrow them from the Book\'85.\'a0 Good night, E.F.P.\'a0 Mamma is glad to hear all the news.\
