Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received your letter today, in which you mentioned you had spoken, but only an hour, & had not said half you wished, that you had astounded the Legislature, & your speech been poorly quoted, misrepresented &c.\'a0 All this is so different from what I had expected, that I feel disappointed.\'a0 As you have said the majority of the Members \ul agreed \ulnone with you.\'a0 I did not know your opinions would astonish them so, but the truth is you only agree in wishing a Southern Convention, but \ul they \ulnone wish it for the purpose of \ul dissolving\ulnone  the Union; \ul you\ulnone  to \ul preserve\ulnone  it, & that is a great difference.\'a0 I knew I would not like the notes of your speech in the papers, as they have not done you \ul justice\ulnone . So I thought it best today, not to look at the papers.\'a0 All the speeches on the other side, never mind how poor they all are \ul praised\ulnone .\'a0 Mrs. Pickerell told me. The correspondent of the Mountaineer spoke highly of Mr. Leitner\'92s speech.\'a0 I hope you will have yours published just as soon as possible; that justice may be done you, but I am thinking in what paper you can get it published; that perhaps none will publish it.\'a0 If all \ul refuse\ulnone , you must have it published in pamphlet form, even if you have to send it to Augusta. My greatest comfort during you absence has been to go every Saturday afternoon to the Miss Andersons & tell them the news from Columbia.\'a0 They are so few now with whom I can converse freely, & meet sympathy.\'a0 They are the finest ladies I know of.\'a0 They are so conscientious & act so on principle.\'a0 They are \ul poor\ulnone , & yet live respectably.\'a0 At one time they were afraid they would have to give up their house, & if they would get no other board out, & if so, they would be obliged to apply to their brothers for aid, which they were very reluctant to do, but for the present they can keep the house. Mr. & Mrs. Campbell left the morning after the wedding.\'a0 I believe for Augusta, but I am not certain.\'a0 They did not wait for the sister to return from Virginia, though she is expected every day.\'a0 Mr. Luther went to the wedding, & says though many were invited, there were only a few there.\'a0 Mrs. Arthur today sent each of us some cake. I am sorry you make no mention of a bundle having been sent to you from Charleston.\'a0 I wrote to Aunt Mary McCall to get me a Sashe, & send it by someone to you, or if no private opportunity occurred to send it on the Rail Road directed to the Columbia Depository to your care, & I have \ul repeatedly\ulnone  written to you to send to the Depository & see about it, but you give me no answer on the subject, & now the time approaches for you to leave Columbia.\'a0 I feel very uneasy, for fear you will leave without seeing about it.\'a0 Though a little matter to \ul you\ulnone , it is a \ul great\ulnone  matter to me, for I have nothing warm to wear to church.\'a0 My cloak is too old.\'a0 I have had it now 15 years, & my shawl is too \ul thin\ulnone , so I beg you to interest yourself & send the children down to the Depository every day to see if the bundle has come.\'a0 It will be a pleasant walk for them, & keep them from annoying you with their company, which I am afraid they do, as you say they are constantly with you.\'a0 I thought Willie having Frank as his companion would have been independent of you, that they would have spent the greater part of their time in walking about the town.\'a0 Today a letter came from Mr. Spartan Goodlett, inclosing a list of 10 subscribers, & wishing you success, & his best wishes.\'a0 The names are Wm J. Pennington, James K. Dickson, W.J. Gilreath, W.D. Berry, John Groce, Asa Cunningham, Lewis Cockrell, William Dickson, John Mosteller, Spartan Goodlett.\'a0 If all you send Prospectus to, will send you 10 subscribers, I will be glad.\'a0 Except Mr. O\'92Hanlon, all wish the weekly numbers, so I do not think there will be any use for a triweekly.\'a0 If so, the expenses of the printing establishment, I hope will be less.\'a0 I see pretty plainly, the paper will not be issued the 1
