\fs29\fsmilli14667 \nosupersub  January, for that is only two weeks from now, & the type is not even here.\'a0 Mr. Elford ought to hurry.\'a0 How times are changed.\'a0 The Mountaineer that seemed to \ul belong\ulnone  to \ul you\ulnone , now your \ul greatest\ulnone  \ul enemy \ulnone & governed by such a \ul little\ulnone  \ul mean\ulnone  of \ul set\ulnone  of \ul men\ulnone , who have been hitherto of so little importance, & edited by a simple schoolmaster of Chester, & a drunken sot from Alabama, they dictating to your friends, & reeling with a rod of iron, & carrying everything before them.\'a0 Papers have such influence & they misrepresent so, & in this \ul State\ulnone  at present, there is no chance of vindicating oneself.\'a0 I am sorry Mr. Young was defeated, but on the first ballot Mr. Reed ran so well, I thought he would be elected, & his being a Member of the Legislature was an advantage.\'a0 So Mr. Young though he got himself elected to the Nashville Convention, did not gain his end as Genl Whitner did.\'a0Scott is about the same,\'a0 He is very weak & stays down a great deal, but Reuben says he eats & drinks a good deal.\'a0 Dr. Earle told Mamma , he noticed him last summer & thought him S\'85, & if I sent him to his stable, he would try & cure him, but it is now Sw\'85 you know, it is the reverse, his \ul under\ulnone  \ul parts\ulnone  seem affected.\'a0 Reuben says, it may be worms in the Kidneys.\'a0 I think it is \ul Spinal\ulnone  \ul affection\ulnone . This is the last letter but one, I am to write.\'a0 You must write so I can hear from you \ul three\ulnone  times:\'a0 Tuesday, Thursday, & Saturday.\'a0 If I hear nothing to the reverse, I will send Reuben Thursday, perhaps Wednesday & let him rest a day at Fulkes.\'a0 Will Mr. Duncan return with you, or come in the Stage.\'a0 If you set off at 8 oclock I do not think you will come all the way to Laurens that day. Tomorrow is Sunday.\'a0 I will let the horses rest, & walk to church if I go.\'a0