My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 \ul As\ulnone  I \ul thought\ulnone , I have many things to write about.\'a0 I did not go to church this morning, but I did this afternoon.\'a0 Next Sunday Mr. Arthur gave out, he would handle preaching morning & afternoon on the subject of \ul Slavery\ulnone .\'a0 As I have no doubts on the subject, & think it a very \ul inappropriate\ulnone  subject for a \ul Sermon\ulnone , I am not going to church to hear him.\'a0 I dare say it will have a political bearing.\'a0 It is hard that those in the \ul minority\ulnone  who dare to express their opinion are branded as Traitors, & it is \ul impertinent\ulnone  for persons to be writing to Mamma in that strain, when they know you think as the minority does.\'a0 Today Mamma showed me a letter from Miss Drayton, & of course she must allude to Politics, & she expresses herself as follows.\'a0 \'93I suppose you are as much interested in the state of public affairs as I am; things are coming to a crisis, which might all have been prevented by fairness & unanimity in ourselves a few years back & even now unanimity would not only save us, but place us on a better understanding & finer position than we have possessed for years, but alas! Traitors within the camp are often exhibiting their satanic\'85some bought with Texan lands, with Northern dinners & flattery, or the hope of preferment.\'a0 They do not feel, \'93this is my own, my native land.\'94\'a0 I will say the reward attendant on their course.\'94\'a0 I suppose she alludes to Genl Hamilton & Mr. Poinsett.\'a0 I have not seen the letter of the former, but the latter I am sure, if he had not felt \'93this is my own my native land.\'94\'a0 Would have kept quiet, & not exposed himself to be assailed & persecuted as all who express their opinion on that side are.\'a0 Mamma says in the Mountaineer Mr. Poinsetts peice is answered & he is made out to be certainly wrong.\'a0 It is signed Tyger & Mr. McBee says Dr. Crook wrote it, & Mamma says Genl Hamiltons letter is ridiculed & spoken of as showing so little sense, that the writer does not believe Genl Hamilton wrote it.\'a0 I suppose you will also be scored.\'a0 If it were not for the Southern Patriot I believe the Mountaineer governed as it is now & nothing to counteract it, would not leave you a friend in Greenville.\'a0 Mr. Pickerell says it is an \ul incendiary\ulnone  paper.\'a0 I am more provoked with Dr. Crook than anyone.\'a0 He priding himself on his \ul patriotism \ulnone when he is a \ul selfish\ulnone  \ul designing\ulnone  \ul deceitful\ulnone  \ul hypocrite\ulnone , nothing but \ul self\ulnone  \ul interest\ulnone  has changed him.\'a0 I am sorry I spoke to him the other day.\'a0 I never will again, & as for being our Physician, he never enters this house again in that capacity, if I can help it.\'a0 He is a Traitor. Mr. Croft leaves tomorrow.\'a0 I saw him after church.\'a0 I forgot to tell him why you had not written to him.\'a0 He will be in Charleston before long.\'a0 If you choose you can write to him there.\'a0\'a0 I have given him some Prospectus\'92 to distribute.\'a0 I rode with Mr. Croft over to Mamma\'92s in his carri[a]ge.\'a0 He was at Miss Lewis wedding.\'a0 He says only about 30 were at it.\'a0 Mr. Campbell has rented his house, so he says.\'a0 Genl Thompsons wife he told me was neither rich or handsome, that he married her because he wants a family, that his children are outrageous, that Genl Thompson is coming here in January, that he chooses to he can be happy, & if he is not loyal & faithful, her family will take it up.\'a0 I hope it is not true that Genl Thompson is to be here in January.\'a0 He will ruin the paper.\'a0 There never was a man so disliked & thought so dishonourable, & I am truly sorry he is not your enemy as he used to be.\'a0 You then flourished, but leagued with him, you will fall with him.\'a0Miss Drayton says Jenny Lind is to be in Charleston about the 19
