\f1\b 194\
Monday 1/2 past 1, 23[24] November 1851\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear Husband\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Again I have to write to you, & have nothing of importance to tell you, except that I received a letter from Aunt Mary McCall last night, & she says she received the Check for 70 dollars safely presented it to the bank & obtained the money.\'a0 Last night Willie went to the Post Office & brought the papers & two letters for the Southern Patriot, but I thought I ought not to open them, so do not know what they contained.\'a0 I sent them this morning to Mr. Elford with your Editorial. The weather is still gloomy & cold, no sunshine today.\'a0I hope you have before this reached Columbia safely & have pleasanter weather than we have here.\'a0 Reuben went to Mr. Suddeth\'92s, but did not see him.\'a0 The servant he saw seemed to think Mr. Suddeth did not intend to take the Cows.\'a0 If he does not come & look at them, I will send them to Mr. Fosters. Willie & Frank are at school.\'a0 Anna has just come home to get her dinner. I have to write to Aunt Mary for Susan, so can write you but a short letter. Hext is asleep.\'a0 The colds generally are better.\'a0 I have told the children, whichever behaves the best I will tell you to bring a present to. I have not as much to write about as I will have when I hear from you, so I will now close by assuring you, we speak & think of you \ul constantly\ulnone .\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 195\
Tuesday morning, 25 November 1851\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 It is raining today.\'a0 We indeed have unpleasant weather,\'a0 I hope it is more cheerful where you are. Mr. Suddeth has not been to look at the Cows, so the first good day Reuben will carry them off. The Carpet came yesterday.\'a0 I think it a \ul beautiful\ulnone  one, & the Rug very pretty, & matches the Carpet exactly.\'a0 I will make up the carpets as soon as I can, but the days are so short, by the time the house is fixed, the day is gone.\'a0 It will take me a long time to do it.\'a0 I never had so much to do as I have now.\'a0 Your Shirts have taken so long to make, that all the other work has been neglected, & I now feel as if I never can get through particularly as Elisa helps so little, but I will not fill up my letters with complaints.\'a0 I will only add that yesterday I got warm dresses for Anna, Hext & myself, & though very reasonable only 20 cts a yd still they amounted to nearly 8 dollars & have made such an inroad in my purse.\'a0 I would not be surprised if my funds failed too soon.\'a0 If so, I will have to \ul draw\ulnone  on \ul you \ulnone & hope you will not be displeased.\'a0 You have no idea how expensive the clothes a Lady & 5 children amount to, dressed in the most economical manner & without many necessary comforts for \ul Flannel\ulnone I have not known for years.\'a0 I have bought myself two cheap dresses to wear at home the whole winter & part of the Spring.\'a0 My other dresses are not suitable for home as they are Silk or too light, & would get ruined immediately.\'a0 Anna wrote a long letter to Aunt Mary Hayne last night.\'a0 She has just come home from school, & is practicing on the Piano.\'a0 Only 3 girls at school, so she came home early.\'a0 Willie & Frank have not come yet.\'a0 The umbrella\'92s are so broken, Willie was to stop at Mr. Nicols & buy a new one.\'a0 Mr. Irwin told Frank he thought he had gone to Columbia.\'a0 Perhaps he sent in his bill from that thought, that he might get his money before Frank left, & not seem so unreasonable as to send in an account afterwards for schooling which he had not given. Mary seems pretty well now, & I am thankful for we live in confusion when she is sick.\'a0 Minerva & herself are our most useful servants, & we miss more when they are sick.\'a0 All of our colds are better.\'a0 I hope yours is.\'a0 I long to hear from you.\'a0 I am glad you will not be here in the confusion of taking up & putting down Carpets.\'a0 You will enjoy only the comfort of them. Mary says the Bull that has come back, is ours.\'a0 I have not been out since you left & have seen no one, so have no news to tell you.\'a0 I hope to see the Southern Patriot tonight.\'a0 I think I am its youngest admirer, perhaps because \ul I\ulnone  was the originator of it.\'a0I have now to write two letters to Aunt Mary McCall & Aunt Harriet McCall.\'a0 I am glad the 73 dollars for the carpet she received safely. Minerva is out of bed now & better.\'a0 John came in yesterday.\'a0 Charles is still there.\'a0 Reuben hauled Mrs. Cauble two loads of wood yesterday.\'a0 Today he burned the chimneys.\'a0 Minerva is making some Cake & Lindy helping her.\'a0 Elisa is making Willie a Jacket.\'a0 Sarah is cleaning the knives, & Fanny helping her.\'a0 Charlotte is holding Hext & trying to get him to sleep.\'a0 Anna is practicing, & I have just finished my letter to my dear husband.\'a0 E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 196\
Wednesday, 1/4 past 2, 26 November [1851]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I am very busy making up the Carpet, & intended Willie should write to you today, but he had not returned from school yet, & I am afraid would not write in time for the Mail, so I am writing in a great hurry you may be sure. I was glad to see by the Southern Patriot last night that you had arrived \ul safely\ulnone , Rail road accidents occurring so frequently made me uneasy until I heard.\'a0 In your letters to me mention all the compliments paid you.\'a0 You are my hero, & I wish to hear a great deal about yourself. A letter came to you from old Mr. Reese last night.\'a0 He was at Anderson C.H. on his way to Georgia, leaving this State forever, & wrote you a kind gratifying letter.\'a0 I sent it to Mr. Elford to \ul Publish\ulnone .\'a0 Mr. Elford sent word he would leave Monday morning.\'a0I see in the paper a notice that Judge Wardlaw should be appointed President of the College.\'a0 If he is, I hope you will receive your reward by \ul taking\ulnone  his place on the \ul Bench\ulnone .\'a0 I am waiting anxiously for you to be rewarded in some form or other.\'a0 You have saved the State [&] are entitled to the highest honors in the gift of the State. Mrs. Collins came here Monday to know if her husband could rent your farm.\'a0 Says Mr. Canon & Mr. Luther McBee know them well.\'a0 She has a large family of children the eldest a daughter of 13 years old so only the Father would work on the Farm.\'a0 They have a child born \ul without\ulnone  legs & only one arm, which would be a dreadful sight to look at when we went to the Farm.\'a0 She said she would raise chickens attend Cows & do anything in that way.\'a0 She was so anxious. I promised to write to you, & she was to come next week to hear your answer, so you must write me something in answer, but you had better not engage to anyone until you come back & consider well whether you will rent at all. We are all better of our colds.\'a0 Hext is now crying to be nursed so I will stop to attend to him & then go on with the Carpet.\'a0I hope to hear from you tonight\'a0 & \ul every\ulnone  \ul night\ulnone  but you must write only when perfectly \ul convenient\ulnone .\'a0 Do not put aside \ul business\ulnone  to write to me.\'a0 Willie Has bought himself a \ul knife\ulnone , so says you need not buy him any.\'a0 Believe me as Ever, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 197\
Thursday 2 oclock, 27 November [1851]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I was really disappointed I did not hear from you last night, & uneasy as I cannot conceive why you did not write, for Monday night you would have spared a few moments to me.\'a0 This is the fifth day since you left, & I have not received one letter, & this is the fifth I have written to you.\'a0 Mr. Elford did not hear either, which makes me more uneasy.\'a0 I hope I will hear tonight. An extra of the Southern Patriot was issued today, containing the Governor\'92s Message.\'a0 I see he still thinks Secession the \ul rightful\ulnone  remedy.\'a0 I hope there\'85a division still, will make your independence conspicuous.\'a0 I was afraid you would be lost sight of in the mingling of parties, but I hope you will in the end be rewarded, though I am afraid the ambitious & aspiring will outstrip you. I have just finished putting down the carpet.\'a0 It looks quite handsome.\'a0 I am afraid it will be injured before you return.\'a0 It makes the rest of the house look shabby.\'a0 I have not made the carpet for the little room yet.\'a0 Aunt Mary sent 2 peices of binding more than was necessary, & the thread we paid 50 cts for never came, so 2 dollars we might have \ul saved\ulnone , was spent. Charles has staid at home today for the first time.\'a0 Mamma no longer needs him.\'a0 He is now spading the garden, Reuben is hauling wood.\'a0 Tomorrow I will tell him to drive off the Cows.\'a0 He ought to have done it today.\'a0\'a0 The weather is now good, & much warmer & pleasanter than it has been.\'a0 Today Willie & Frank go to school the last time for 4 weeks.\'a0 Anna will not have holiday yet for 2 weeks to come. Mamma is better, but we are all so busy we have not been able to see each other.\'a0 I have no news to tell you, as I have not been out, & have seen no one.\'a0We are all pretty well.\'a0 Willie will write to you now [that] he has holiday. Charles says Burrill Ferguson who has only a Wife & two children would like to rent your Farm & that he would make a good crop for you [&] would cultivate your swamp land, that he would do better than Mr. Collins, who has so many children.\'a0 I think the dreadful sight of the unfortunate child would be objection enough to them. I must now close, & you scarcely deserve this letter but I return you\'85for evil.\'a0 Your affectionate Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 198\
Saturday, 12 oclock, 29 November 1851\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Anna wrote to you yesterday.\'a0 I was very busy making up the little room carpet, & I am happy to say, little Carpets are made, & put down, & the two rooms look very neat, but I am afraid, before you see them, the dirty feet of so many servants & children will have ruined them.\'a0 The old Carpet is put down in my room, & I have moved the set of Drawers & Basin stand from the large room into ours, & the Curtains, for we are entitled to the best in the house, you especially, who works hard & makes all the money, so I thought I would have a very nice room ready for you on your return, & I assure you it looks so nice & comfortable, you will be very much pleased with it, & the carpet makes it so much warmer. I was disappointed again last night in not hearing from you.\'a0 I hope you were busy, or the Postmaster as usual careless.\'a0 Mr. Elford did not hear either.\'a0 I thought you were to write to the Patriot every Mail.\'a0 You ought to write \ul longer\ulnone  letters for the paper, & I am disappointed at their being so short.\'a0 Perhaps you have not had much to write about yet. I hope you interceded for Mrs. Hughes, after all the trouble she has taken to go so far.\'a0 She deserves to succeed in getting her son pardoned, so for her sake at least I hope the Governor will show mercy to him, & hope he will be merciful to all for whom you carried petitions. I am glad Mr. Isaac Hayne & yourself have met & spoken; nothing more is necessary.\'a0 He & his sisters are very disagreeable, I think, & though Mrs. Martin & Mrs. Taylor lived with us, & we were brought up in intimacy, I now regard them as \ul Strangers\ulnone .\'a0 They seem cold hearted & selfish.\'a0 I am glad your cold is better.\'a0 You must give yourself no uneasiness about us.\'a0 I write to you \ul daily\ulnone , in order to make you \ul easy\ulnone  & \ul satisfied\ulnone .\'a0 I wish you to enjoy yourself & attend to your duties as a Legislator & Patriot.\'a0 I will attend to home & everything is going on well. Mr. Elford paid me a visit this morning.\'a0 He goes Monday morning in the Stage.\'a0 I will write by him.\'a0 He says Mr. Duncan & yourself are going to Charleston with him.\'a0 You must do as you please, but I think you had better go some other time, & not leave your Legislative duties now.\'a0 It will be an unnecessary expense, & when you go, there are many things I wish you to purchase which I cannot tell you now.\'a0 You had better go down in February during the Races.\'a0 You will then have been at home & wish for a change again. Aunt Mary McCall has sent 2 yds of Carpeting less than the room needs.\'a0 Mr. Elford looked at the Carpet & says he will buy it for me.\'a0 I will get him to buy a Straw carri[a]ge & chair for Hext, which I am very anxious for, & wrote to Aunt Mary to inquire the price., but I will get Mr. Elford who is so good a judge & has offered to buy anything.\'a0 To buy them for him the carri[a]ge will be 3 or 4 dollars, the chair 1 or 2.\'a0 I mention it to you, so that if Mr. Elford tells you, you need not be surprised.\'a0 I suppose you will have no objection to his getting them.\'a0 Hext needs both careri[a]ge & chair now.\'a0 Lindy hardly ever has time to hold him, & it is so much better for him to be drawn about, than held by \'85 & Charlotte. You would stay so short a time in Charleston now only a day or two, that I think it is not worth the expense going down.\'a0 Some other time you can stay longer, & carry Willie & Frank with you.\'a0 If you were to stay any time now, you would be neglecting your duties.\'a0 Mr. Elford says someone asked him if you did not feel more at home in Columbia \ul this\ulnone  winter than the last, & he said yes & that next winter you would still be more at home for the Legislature would be a new one, scarce one of the Members in it, that is now he says the Secessionists in their \ul hearts\ulnone  \ul thank\ulnone  you for getting them out of the scrape.\'a0 I think the Cooperationists are a cowardly set.\'a0 They have not the boldness to come out as Union men.\'a0 They cannot bear what you did.\'a0 I am sure you deserve to be rewarded., but not being ambitious. I am afraid you never will be.\'a0 You ought to try to advance yourself for the sake of your children. Young \ul Powell\ulnone  brought Col. Picket\'92s history of Alabama, that he gave Uncle Arthur for Mamma, & Uncle Arthur gave Aunt Eliza to send, & a bundle of Shoes, Susan sent for, & a little worsted bonnet apeice for Hext & Susan.\'a0 I wrote to Aunt Martha to buy Hext one. & she sent it as a present, but it is not pretty, & does not fit him, is too small. I have been interrupted so that the dinner hour has arrived, & dinner is coming in, so I must soon close. I sat with Anna while she practiced today, the first time for a month or more.\'a0 I am too busy to go out.\'a0I bought Reuben a pr of shoes yesterday.\'a0 He asked for them.\'a0 Mary & himself are quite well now, & Elisa as well as she ever is. The children are behaving pretty well.\'a0 Willie drove to the Farm today & Reuben brought home\'a0 a load of wood.\'a0 Willies cold is well; so is Franks.\'a0 We are all pretty well & hope you are too.\'a0 Yours as Ever, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

\f1\b 199\
Sunday morning, 30 November [1851]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Today is just such a day as last Sunday, except it is raining more, so none of us have gone to church.\'a0 We are all seated in the little dining room, & Willie & Anna are also writing to you, but I do not know that their letters will be worth reading.\'a0 They seem at a loss what to write about, & appeal to me every moment.\'a0 We have had some good weather, but as usual it has not continued long.\'a0 Hext is in Charlottes arms, & Fanny & Frank are plaguing us all. I received \ul two \ulnone letters from you last night.\'a0 I suppose as usual the Postmaster was careless about Mailing one of them the day before.\'a0 So in future I will not be uneasy when I do not hear from you.\'a0 I am glad everyone is so kind to you.\'a0 I hope you are spending today pleasantly at Mr. Latta\'92s.\'a0 You must accept all your invitations. I wonder what Col. Brockman wishes with 200 dollars, for he does not bring 15 dollar bibles to his Wife.\'a0 I thank you for your remembrance, but I must say I would rather you show your love by saving your money for our future support, for though it is very pleasant to spend it, you ought to recollect that you are our sole support, & now when you make, you ought to try & lay up something for the time when you will not be able to make, so you ought to deny your generous inclinations, so do not be extravagant, buy only what is necessary, & only buy such books as are really interesting.\'a0 The Bible is the best book, but the pictorial bible I have seen, the pictures are small, & not very interesting.\'a0 If you see any pretty present that Ann would like I would be pleased at your getting it, but only\'a0 something \ul reasonable\ulnone , & in buying for the children get a little present for Vardry.\'a0 You are his Godfather, & never give him anything.\'a0 Susan is grateful at your merely \ul remembering\ulnone  him, not the value of the present does she care for. I have had to buy Reuben Shoes, & an Umbrella, & sent some money to town I owed, so if you would send me 10 dollars I would be obliged to you.\'a0 My money has not given out, but it may, so I would be obliged to you to replenish my purse.\'a0 I read your letter in the Southern Patriot today.\'a0 You provoked me by mentioning Mr. Jones name.\'a0 You ought to treat him as you do the \ul Mountaineer\ulnone , & not deign to let his name appear in your paper.\'a0 The little he does in the Legislature is not worth recording.\'a0 Only in one instance ought you to have named him. & that is you ought to have mentioned \ul Mr.\ulnone  \ul Jones \ulnone said there were not 300 Union men in Greenville District.\'a0 His conceit & vanity provoke me beyond endurance.\'a0 He cannot forget that he stood at the head of the ticket & is still saying I suppose that \ul he\ulnone  represents the District not \ul you\ulnone .\'a0 I suppose he says, \ul he\ulnone  governs it, that you have no influence at all, & then at the next election he will wan\'85 & get the votes of your friends again.\'a0 Col. Brockman & Mr. Duncan & yourself ought to keep aloof from him, & not condescend to notice him & except to mention his \ul folly\ulnone  & \ul conceit\ulnone  which should be known to the people of Greenville, I wish you to mention him in no other way.\'a0 You ought to mention how he tried to put down the 4
\fs24\fsmilli12222 \super th
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \nosupersub  of July meeting.\'a0 Mr. Jones self conceit, & a toothache I now have, have put me in a bad humour for the present & Hext is crying, so I will stop & nurse him & begin again in a better mood. Margaret H\'85 left the Jail this morning.\'a0 Mr. Elford will take this letter.\'a0 I think you had much better not go to Charleston until the Spring when you go down to the Court of Appeals.\'a0 Now if you go, you will be neglecting your duties, & you would not stay long enough to warrant the expense of going down & coming up on the Rail Road.\'a0 In the Spring you can buy Groceries & other things we need, & take one or two of the children. I hope you will be appointed a Delegate to the Baltimore Convention.\'a0 It will be a pleasant trip for you.\'a0 So that you enjoy yourself, I am wil[l]ing to remain at home \ul quietly\ulnone , & think only of you, & wish you advanced, because you have always acted so disinterestedly & nobly you deserve it & unless one is rewarded by \ul office\ulnone  & \ul honor\ulnone , they are not appreciated for their conduct by the world, they are the same men, but they are not esteemed\'a0 as they are, when they meet with reward. I see Mr. Hopkins is going to keep a school, so there will be 3 schools, besides the Academies & Mr. Arthurs.\'a0 Mr. Elford says Mr. Arthur takes the Patriot.\'a0 I felt vexed when I thought he did not; for as you go to his church, & pay him so much, I thought he was in duty bound to take your paper, but it does not seem to have enlightened him. Dr. Koch was here yesterday a little while.\'a0 He begged me to ask you to attend to the business he asked you about, says he could pay some of the money required to board Mrs. \'85 at the Asylum, that he wishes to know how much they would charge for boarding her \ul 3\ulnone  \ul months\ulnone , so attend to it for him, do not think it too little a matter.\'a0 It is important to him.\'a0 I am glad you have introduced a bill for giving the Election of President to the people.\'a0 All the Anderson petitions were good.\'a0 You must introduce their petitions as bills, give election of Governor to the people, have basis of representation altered, the free school fund more equally distributed, & taxes more justly levied, & in short\'85South Carolina a free State, & the Upper country equal to the Lower. I like to read your letters in the Patriot, & always wish they were longer & contained more.\'a0 I have written to you every day now since you left but one, when Anna wrote.\'a0I have told Mr. Elford to buy Hext a Straw carri[a]ge & chair & 2 yds of Carpeting that is needed.\'a0 He is to buy a Carpet for Mamma.\'a0 He is obliging & a good judgement, & I would rather him shop for me than anyone, so let him make the purchases I have mentioned.\'a0 They are necessary & will be very useful, & I would rather buy these things for Hext than you should buy anything for me.\'a0 Hext needs both carri[a]ge & chair now.\'a0 I intended writing to Aunt Mary to buy them, but I much prefer Mr. Elford should.\'a0 He knows exactly the kind & will send them up quickly.\'a0 I will pay for them out of the next money you make for me, rather than he should not have them.\'a0 I hope to hear tonight from you.\'a0\'a0 I hope you will mention all Mr. Jones falsehoods in your letters.\'a0 They ought to be known.\'a0 Yours truly. E.F.P. I thought you were going to vote for Mr. Ashmore as Commissioner.\'a0\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 200\
Sunday, 2 oclock, [ca. November 1851]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 According to promise I have taken up my pen to write to you, but with literally \ul nothing\ulnone  to write about.\'a0 The clock struck 4 as the stage drove off, so you really got up unnecessarily early.\'a0 Another time I will not arouse you as I did.\'a0 I slept soundly until morning, when I awoke feeling very much fatigued from my disturbance in the night.\'a0 The children slept late, & as it proved to be a very unpleasant day, we resolved not to go to church, to hear one of Mr. Arthurs old sermons, so we read the services at home, & got through only a little while ago. Mr. Tindall left an advertisement about his writing in the walk, with a bird drawn on paper with a pen.\'a0 I told the children whichever of them behaved the best should have the bird so I put their names on paper & whenever they misbehaved gave them a mark.\'a0 Thus far Willie & Fanny have behaved the best, & bid fair one of them to get the bird. I received a note from Susan [a] little while ago.\'a0 She asked if you had left, & said you had gloomy weather.\'a0 It has been cloudy all day, gloomy & dull.\'a0 I hope you are wrapped up warm, & getting along comfortably.\'a0 I told Reuben to go to Mr. Suddeths & ask him to come tomorrow to look at the Cows, that if he went this morning, this afternoon he would go to church.\'a0 He said he would, but I have not seen him since, & do not know if he went or not. I have had the dining table moved into the small dining room, & we will take our meals there now.\'a0 It makes it so pleasant to have the table in a different room from the one we sit in.\'a0 When you come back I hope the rooms will both be fixed nicely carpeted & cleaned, & our chamber also looks more comfortable with a carpet which it has needed so long.\
\'a0\

\f1\b 201\
After dinner
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 We have eat[en] dinner, & it is now raining a little.\'a0 The winter has continued gloomily.\'a0 I hope the end will be pleasanter than the beginning.\'a0 If you would like Willie & Anna or one of them to commence writing under Mr. Tindall let me know & I will let them begin.\'a0 I see from his advertisement\'a0 that he does not charge unless you \ul improve\ulnone .\'a0 Hext is doing pretty well, seems not have experienced any bad effects from the Magnesia. My eyes hurt me in consequence of my loss of sleep last night.\'a0 I can hardly keep them open, & as soon as I have done writing, I will lay down on the sofa & take a nap. Take care of yourself & come back quite well.\'a0 I have read the Patriot through, your Editorial twice.\'a0 Bill Smith\'92s letter is an amusing one, & the peice on the Union from the Louisville Journal very good.\'a0 I hope Mr. Duncan, Col. Brockman & yourself are getting along in friendship & harmony.\'a0 You have stood by each other too long, to be separated easily. The children are talking, Anna is writing to you, but I do not know that she will send her letter.\'a0 I will finish before her. I believe I have nothing more to write, having parted so recently.\'a0 I will conclude as usual with a little advice.\'a0 Distinguish yourself this Session, as I think you generally do, introduce all the improvements you mentioned in your Editorial last night.\'a0 I think the road tax for the poor man is unjust.\'a0 The Election of the Commissioner ought to be given to the people, as well as President & Governor, & indeed all the changes you named ought to be adopted by the State.\'a0 Do all you can for the best interests of the State & your District Greenville, get money to build a new Court House, & in short prove yourself to be as hitherto the best member ever sent from Greenville, & I hope you may yet meet the reward you deserve, & which you have not got yet.\'a0 Adieu.\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P.\
\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\
