\f1\b 202\
Monday morning, 11 oclock, 1 December 1851\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I am sorry I have not better pens to write with, but as they are very bad, you must make many excuses.\'a0 Mr. Elford I suppose left this morning.\'a0 He will take you a letter from Anna & myself.\'a0 Willie thought his not worth sending.\'a0 He will write to you soon. I received a letter from you last night.\'a0 I was very glad to hear, & wish you would write every Mail.\'a0 I am pleased you are treated so well by the Secessionists.\'a0 I suppose, as Mr. Elford says, they thank you in their \ul heart\ulnone , & look upon you as one who has saved them from disgrace, though for their own credit, they feel compelled to \ul abuse\ulnone  you.\'a0 I hope they will reward you, for the good you have done them.\'a0 Mr. Memminger is a \ul mean\ulnone  man, & you have not been \ul half\ulnone  \ul hard\ulnone  enough upon him.\'a0 You ought in your paper to bring all inconsistent, selfish people to the view of the people.\'a0 I hope all such speeches as the \ul Representative\ulnone  from \ul Greenville\ulnone  lately made about their being so few Union men in Greenville, you will make known to the people, who are so \ul misrepresented\ulnone , through your paper.\'a0 I cannot bear for deceitfulness & falsehoods to pass unnoticed, & not injure the person who acts so\'85but\'85get him along prosperously & favorably.\'a0 Such people ought to be disgraced at once.\'a0 It is a wonder how such should have been honored by the people.\'a0 I hope the \ul days\ulnone  of such are \ul numbered\ulnone . The servants tell me Mr. Walker & family have left for Georgia this morning.\'a0 I hope you will not be grieved to hear the sad news.\'a0 I wish others of the same description would follow.\'a0 Yesterday was a damp, rainy, disagreeable Day.\'a0 I had toothache almost all day, & the cold penetrated me, & I have to wear a large shawl & flannel over my face; but today I feel \ul quite\ulnone  \ul well\ulnone , & this first day of winter has made its appearance \ul bright\ulnone  & \ul cheerful\ulnone , & most \ul charming\ulnone  for the washing of clothes, that most necessary business every Monday.\'a0 Anna is at school, & will have holiday in a week.\'a0 Willie has driven the horse & wagon to the Farm to help Reuben bring home a load of wood.\'a0 Charles is spading the garden.\'a0 Frank cut some wood, & then went in the streets to see some playmates.\'a0 Fanny makes herself very useful helping lay the table & put away the dishes.\'a0 I told her I would write you word \ul she\ulnone  was the best & you must bring her a doll, or some pretty present. I believe Green Hughes is just passing now to receive his sentence.\'a0 I suppose the Governor has not pardoned him.\'a0 I am glad you are getting along very well.\'a0 I wish you to be \ul happy\ulnone  & \ul contented\ulnone , as it is possible for you to be, without your wife by your side. Hext is well, & as sweet as ever, & waiting patiently for his Carri[a]ge & chair to arrive. Our colds are quite well.\'a0 That is the childrens & mine.\'a0 Lindy is a little hoarse; the rest of the servants are pretty well.  I have not been out once since you left, & am so busy, I do not know when I will go out.\'a0 The winter clothes for the children, are not hardly commenced making yet.\'a0 The rooms at present look very neat.\'a0 The Piano [is] in the dining room, where the Sideboard stood. The Sideboard looked so shabby, & got broke a little in moving.\'a0 I sent it to Mr. Waddil to do up, & when it returns will put it in the little dining room, as that is the place for it, when we eat, & it will save a great deal of dirt, from the servants not coming in & out constantly to it. Willie looks quite well & hearty.\'a0 Next Spring you can carry Frank & himself down with you.\'a0 You recollect in a few years Willie ought to be at college, so your expenses will then increase, so you must save your money now, for those times.\'a0 Col. Brockman must give you his note bearing interest, & then he may keep the 200 dollars as long as he wishes.\'a0Your review of Mr. Calhoun\'92s works has not been published yet in the Patriot,\'a0 I hope they will soon print Mr. F\'85\'92s peice of poetry addressed to you.\'a0 You must write & tell them to.\'a0 The paper will do badly with neither of its Editors here.\'a0 Old Mr. Reese\'92s letter has not been published either. I hope you are feeling well & looking well.\'a0 Tomorrow you must make a good speech on giving the Election of President to the people, & after that introduce some more important bills.\'a0 The basis of representation ought also to be given to the people, & you know all that ought to be done, to put South Carolina on a footing with the other States. I do not think the College will flourish under Mr. Manly as it has done under Col. Preston.\'a0 I am sorry Col. Preston has to resign.\'a0 I thought Mr. Thornwell or Mr. Henry would be elected President. I know of nothing new to tell you.\'a0 I hope you will put off your visit to Charleston till the Spring, & then Willie & Anna can go down with you.\'a0 You are sent to the Legislature by the people to attend to their business, & ought not to leave it, even for a day.\'a0 If you will go to town, go after the Session.\'a0 You can then stay longer, & will not be neglecting your duty.\'a0 The expense of going on the Railroad up & down is not worth incurring for the short time you will stay now. I write so often, I have nothing to write about & am sure you think so too, & will not be sorry I have come to the end of my sheet. Yours truly & affectionately, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 203\
Wednesday, 1/2 past 10, 3 December 1851\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\'a0\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 As I heard from you last night, & consequently have more than usual to say to you, I will write before I commence my work.\'a0 Willie, Anna, Frank & myself all received your letters last night, & were very much pleased to get them.\'a0 In all your letters you ask what you must bring me, so now I will tell you.\'a0 I love to make presents, as much as you do, so do bring me, a pair of \ul Indian\ulnone  \ul Shoes\ulnone , such as you have bought for \ul Hext\ulnone .\'a0 I wish to give them to \ul little\ulnone  \ul Susan\ulnone .\'a0 I have never made her a present yet, & would like to give her a pr of Shoes just like \ul Hexts\ulnone , & buy me also another \ul Indian\ulnone  \ul pocket\ulnone  book, that I may give it to Ann.\'a0 She is at present very poorly, & would be pleased to be noticed kindly by me in some way.\'a0 I would like \ul one\ulnone  or something else for Susan also.\'a0 If they are not very expensive, buy one of the \ul pocket\ulnone  \ul books\ulnone  for \ul Susan\ulnone , or I will instead give it to Vardry as a present.\'a0 So remember these are the things I wish you to bring me, \ul two\ulnone  \ul Indian\ulnone  \ul pocket\ulnone  books, & a pr of Indian Shoes, anything made by Indians is a curiosity, & even if not useful, is interesting to keep.\'a0 My bag is of no use.\'a0 It is too large, & the beads come out constantly.\'a0 I hope Anna\'92s is prettier than mine, & a \ul smaller\ulnone  \ul size\ulnone .\'a0 Now do not forget to bring me three things if the Indian has not gone.\'a0 These are all the presents I wish, & you must not bring many things to the children, save your money to clothe & feed us this winter, & to pay your Doctors bill, Blacksmith\'92s, Saddler\'92s &c &c to buy a new carri[a]ge & horses next Spring, & to take me to Columbia with you.\'a0 The children if you gave them a Carte blanche, would very easily fill it up, but you cannot think of gratifying all their desires.\'a0 They will each write to you, & you can select out of them what you choose to bring them.\'a0\'a0I am sorry you could not dine at Mr. Latta\'92s, & particularly the cause that prevented you.\'a0 If you see him, Mamma says you may tell him, she has not forgotten his kindness, to her on board the vessel as she was going to Philadelphia, & if he has a pretty place, & any suitable seeds to plant on a Lawn & improve \ul her\ulnone  place, she would be much obliged to him.\'a0 I read your letter in the Patriot.\'a0 I am afraid you are too kind to the Secessionists,\'a0 When you mention a Secessionist, you praise them up too much.\'a0 A Secessionist who has the heart to ruin his State & principally for his own selfish views, or the bad judgment to think he is right in wishing the State to Secede does not deserve \ul praise\ulnone .\'a0 The Cooperationists are the safest of the \ul two\ulnone  \ul parties\ulnone , as they can do no injury, have to wait for the other States to join them, but the Secessionists would ruin the State now at once.\'a0 I like Mr. Owens bill, that the people have resolved \ul against\ulnone  \ul Secession\ulnone .\'a0 I hope you will make an able speech on his side.\'a0 If the Convention does meet, arrange it, that it will not meet when the Baltimore Convention meets to nominate President, as you\'85to go to that, & will have to go to the Columbia Convention.\'a0 I do not understand how it is that Mississippi has no Governor, as the Patriot says, & I suppose she has not, as I see Mr. Footes name mentioned in Washington. If Mr. Burt wishes you Governor, I am sorry he does not edit a newspaper now, for if he did, he would make known his wishes to the people.\'a0 He commenced editing at the wrong time, when he \ul injured\ulnone  you, & stops when he would \ul benefit\ulnone  you.\'a0 If you tried for Office, I expect you would get it, but I hope you may still get it one day. I am sorry a Baptist will be elected President of the College.\'a0 My idea of that Sect is always associated with ignorance & cont\'85[word faded], & a Minister, the young men will feel a \ul prejudice\ulnone  against.\'a0 They are generally so sanctimonious, & put on the appearance of religion, where very often it is wanting.\'a0 Willie is again hauling wood.\'a0 He drives the wagon.\'a0 The children all talk constantly of you.\'a0 Your letters pleased them very much.\'a0 Fanny & Hext the next time you must write to.\'a0 Mamma has a bad cold & Ann poorly.\'a0 I rode in the Buggy yesterday for the first time to see them.\'a0 Mamma has made an arrangement with Mr. Saterfield who has been overseeing for Mr. McBee to cultivate her place next year, & make everything for her, & attend to the \ul whole\ulnone  place.\'a0 He has a wife but no children.\'a0 I wish you would get such a person.\'a0 I do not wish ever to rent your place to a large family.\'a0 They will burn too much wood.\'a0 Mr. Saterfield says your place well attended to, would yield so well you would have to buy very little provision, or none at all.\'a0 He is a friend of yours, says it is not easy to find another like \ul you\ulnone  & he takes the \ul Patriot\ulnone , so of course he will have me for a friend.\'a0 He will cut wood, raise hogs, work in the garden.\'a0 His wife [word faded] Chickens & Eggs, attend[s] to the Cow, & do[es] just Mr. P\'85 white overseers & family do.\'a0 So I hope Mamma will be more comfortably fixed than heretofore.\'a0 Negroes hire is so dear now 105 dollars a year for a man.\'a0 She is obliged to take Mr. John Townes woman, who has just been confined, so will have a young infant along with her.\'a0 She can get no other.\'a0 She will go in a few weeks. We have bright cheerful weather now, & even Commencement day turned out better than you supposed.\'a0 At least it was a charming day here. I have read the Patriot through.\'a0 It is the only paper I see.\'a0 I hope you will get some subscribers to it, while in Columbia. You made your speech yesterday I suppose, on the Election of President.\'a0 You can improve it, & write it out, & publish it in the Patriot, or publish the one you made before.\'a0 You occupy an independent position.\'a0 You are between the two parties Cooperation & Secession, can see the faults & virtues of each, & write of them accordingly. I am glad you are to dine\'a0 with old Mr. \'85.\'a0 Tell him \ul I\ulnone  am the \ul Originator\ulnone  of the \ul Southern\ulnone  \ul Patriot\ulnone , & even the Editors themselves were about to give up, I \ul encouraged\ulnone  & \ul made\ulnone  them \ul go\ulnone  \ul on\ulnone .\'a0 He ought to hand down \ul my\ulnone  \ul name\ulnone  to posterity in \ul poetry\ulnone . Do not be extravagant, my dear husband, bring me a present in \ul money \ulnone when you come home if you wish it.\'a0 So instead of buying so many things now, come home with a pocket full of money, but buy the Shoes & pocket books I have told you.\'a0 E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

