My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received a short letter from you last night.\'a0 You mentioned your Bill for giving the Election of the President to the people was \ul lost\ulnone  you did not say; you made a \ul good\ulnone  speech, but I hope you were \ul satisfied\ulnone  with your effort, & not \ul mortified\ulnone  at your ill \ul success\ulnone .\'a0 You know \ul nothing\ulnone  is to be expected from the \ul present\ulnone  \ul Legislature\ulnone .\'a0 They were elected before the people were \ul enlightened\ulnone  & go against \ul all\ulnone  \ul reform\ulnone .\'a0 The \ul next\ulnone  \ul Legislature\ulnone  will be \ul different\ulnone .\'a0 You can then introduce all the reforms you wish, & be \ul supported\ulnone .\'a0 You are now rowing \ul against\ulnone  the \ul current\ulnone .\'a0 Next Session the current will \ul go\ulnone  \ul along\ulnone  with you. I read your letter in the Patriot.\'a0 I am glad Dr. Thornwell was elected President of the College.\'a0 I am sorry a \ul Baptist\ulnone  for Dr. Thornwell\'92s place was elected, for I should think \ul he\ulnone  would interpret the Bible according to the \ul Baptist\ulnone  creed, which of all creeds is the most \ul illiberal\ulnone , & he will pervert the minds of the Students.\'a0 It is too small a denomination to be represented in College.\'a0 The students are generally of other denominations.\'a0 Mr. Wilkes\'92 bill to \ul repeal\ulnone  the \ul Convention\ulnone  I like, & Mr. Owen\'92s bill \'93that the people have declared against Secession &c.\'94\'a0 They are just such bills as I suppose \ul you\ulnone  would have introduced.\'a0 The Secessionists had better do all they wish \ul now\ulnone  before another Session.\'a0 I hope their power will have departed, & all their acts repealed.\'a0 \ul Then\ulnone  I hope \ul you\ulnone  will be the Leader, & for \ul once\ulnone  in a \ul majority\ulnone , & I hope you will be rewarded so do not be discouraged, if \ul now\ulnone  you fail in your endeavors to free the \ul Upper\ulnone  \ul Country\ulnone  from the bondage of the \ul lower\ulnone .\'a0 All Reformers you know have to \ul persevere\ulnone , meet with \ul opposition\ulnone  at \ul first\ulnone , but in the \ul end\ulnone  are \ul appreciated\ulnone .\'a0 Next winter I \ul must\ulnone  go down with you.\'a0 I love to hear public speaking, but above all else my \ul husband\ulnone  \ul speaking\ulnone .\'a0 I would like to have been among the ladies in the Gallery listening to you.\'a0 Hext will be a fine boy to introduce next winter.\'a0 He will surpass Willie & Frank.\'a0 I kissed him for you, & delivered your messages to the children. Willie all day is so busy hauling wood.\'a0 He has very little time left for reading, & the exercise seems to agree with him.\'a0 He looks \ul healthy\ulnone  & \ul well\ulnone .\'a0 When you return he can sit in your Office & read, & resume his studies, & the 1
