\fs29\fsmilli14667 \nosupersub  of January he will again go to school, & Mr. Leary will have I suppose so few scholars he can attend \ul well\ulnone  to \ul him\ulnone .\'a0 Anna\'92s school breaks up today.\'a0 Mr. Capers sent her bill yesterday for 6 weeks, 3 dollars.\'a0 My money had not given out, but except for your timely assistance last night of 10 dollars, I would not have ventured to have paid it, but this morning as my fund was replenished, I did pay it, sent 3 dollars by Anna, & felt quite \ul independent\ulnone .\'a0 There will be so many schools to choose from, when Anna begins again, I am as uncertain who she will go to, as who will be next President. Mr. Chalmers being a \ul Secessionist\ulnone , I would not have listened with pleasure to his speech; the \ul Union\ulnone  \ul man\ulnone  only would have pleased me.\'a0 \ul They\ulnone  are to be admired for their \ul independence\ulnone  if nothing else.\'a0 I love the \ul Union\ulnone  \ul men\ulnone , those who come out \ul openly\ulnone  for the \ul Union\ulnone .\'a0 The \ul Cooperationists\ulnone  & \ul Secessionists\ulnone  I have no sympathy for, they are \ul both\ulnone  \ul equally\ulnone  \ul bad\ulnone , but the \ul latter\ulnone  more dangerous.\'a0 They both act from \ul selfish\ulnone  \ul motives\ulnone , for their own \ul aggrandizement\ulnone , where they do not, they are ignorant & under a delusion that amounts to derangement. I would be glad for you to do something for Dr. Koch\'92s \ul wife\ulnone , but when you return, do not let him annoy you.\'a0 He is a perfect \ul bore\ulnone .\'a0 He has been here repeatedly after wood, which he has no idea of paying for, or he would go somewhere else, tells all manner of stories about his not being able to get anyone to haul it, & came yesterday to borrow \ul Meal\ulnone .\'a0 I sent him a little sausage, said I \ul gave\ulnone  it , but would spare no more, & I do not \ul see\ulnone  him now when he comes.\'a0 One or two loads of wood does not satisfy him.\'a0 He wishes us to supply him altogether.\'a0 Our horses are not equal to such a task, & I am not going to send him any more.\'a0 I do not believe he has a single scholar now, & he loses them by his own misconduct.\'a0 I think him so poor a Teacher, that I would hardly consent he should teach Anna for \ul nothing\ulnone .\'a0 He has disgusted her with Music, from the really \ul hard\ulnone  peices he has given her which she \ul plays\ulnone , but more as a \ul task\ulnone  than anything else.\'a0 Today is very pleasant, bright & cheerful.\'a0 I hope you have the same weather. \'a0We sit altogether in the little Dining room, which is very comfortable.\'a0 The larger room we are keeping clean for \ul you\ulnone , but I have a fire made in it every day, in case anyone calls.\'a0 Mr. Elford seemed to admire the Carpet very much.\'a0 If he writes from Charleston, & you from Columbia, the Patriot will be interesting.\'a0 Mr. Reese\'92s letter & Mr. F\'85\'92s poetry are published in this mornings paper.\'a0 I am afraid they will be published in the Weekly if next week, too late for the Session.\'a0 They put off publishing it so long, I was afraid they were not going to publish it, so I wrote yesterday to ask them to, & accordingly they did.\'a0 I wished you to see C\'85 Reese\'92s letter at once, as I knew it would gratify you.\'a0 I am still staying at home, busy all the time, not one moment to spare.\'a0 The afternoons are generally windy,, or I would go over to see Mamma.\'a0 I must soon make one desperate effort, & return all my visits, & then stay at home with a \ul clear\ulnone  \ul conscience\ulnone .\'a0 I have written to you every Mail but one or two when I got Anna to write, so you have heard every Mail.\'a0 It is a great comfort, & I begrudge the not hearing Monday night. The children have not commenced under Mr. Tisdale.\'a0 They seem disinclined to.\'a0 When you return if he is here, they can commence.\'a0 As I have not much to write about I will conclude with some \ul advice\ulnone .\'a0 You know I am very generous to you in furnishing a constant supply \ul free\ulnone  of \ul charge\ulnone .\'a0 I do not wish you to be in debt to me, as you certainly would, if I charged.\'a0 So this is it.\'a0 Do your duty as a \ul Legislator\ulnone & a \ul Patriot\ulnone  a \ul Member\ulnone  from the \ul Upper\ulnone  \ul Country\ulnone .\'a0 Do all your \ul Constituents\ulnone  \ul expect\ulnone  of \ul you\ulnone , & which you are so well able to do.\'a0 Satisfy your conscience, do not be disheartened at ill success.\'a0 Expect it now, sow the seed & after awhile it will appear & yield abundantly & though I am \ul much\ulnone  \ul afraid\ulnone  you will \ul never\ulnone  be rewarded\'a0 in a \ul tangible\ulnone  \ul form\ulnone , yet I will \ul hope\ulnone  even \ul against\ulnone  \ul hope\ulnone , & try to think you \ul will\ulnone  \ul be\ulnone .\'a0 I appreciate you, but that does not \ul satisfy\ulnone  \ul me\ulnone .\'a0 I wish you to be appreciated by \ul others\ulnone , & you will never be, unless you meet with honor & Office. In Greenville Village particularly, I wish you to be held in the consideration you \ul deserve\ulnone .\'a0 I cannot bear that \ul all\ulnone  should not \ul see \ulnone & be \ul made to feel\ulnone  how \ul much\ulnone  you are their \ul Superior\ulnone , I hope you will one day occupy a \ul position\ulnone  that will \ul make\ulnone  them feel it.\'a0 Then I will be \ul satisfied\ulnone , for \ul you\ulnone  will then be \ul appreciated\ulnone  & your \ul children after you\ulnone .\'a0 This winter you are treated better in Columbia than you were last winter, & next winter as Mr. Elford says, you will be treated still better, for those who are making themselves so important now, I hope will be at home, & an entirely different set, more of your own views will surround you, so good bye, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
