Wednesday, 20 minutes of 2, 10 December 1851\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just returned from Mrs. John Jones funeral & will write to you.\'a0 Genl Thompson it was thought would have returned last night, but he did not.\'a0 The funeral was at the Baptist church.\'a0 Mr. Hopkins preached a strange sermon for a funeral one.\'a0 It was on St. Paul, his belief in the gospel.\'a0 If you had not seen the \ul Coffin\ulnone , you would not have known it was over a corpse he was preaching.\'a0 It was a \ul long\ulnone  \ul sermon\ulnone , & when he had finished it, for it was \ul written\ulnone , he closed the Bible, & made a few remarks on the character of the deceased, said she was perfectly resigned to die, & in her last moments said she was not \ul afraid\ulnone , only that she might not have \ul patience\ulnone  to bear the \ul lingering\ulnone  approach\'a0 of the dread monster, & begged her friends to improve her death, & prepare to follow her.\'a0 Mr. Tom Butler\'92s son William is dead, died last night, so Mrs. Whiteford Smith told me today.\'a0 Only one son is left & 3 daughters, & Mrs. Butler expects before long to be confined.\'a0 Mrs. Stone & some of her daughters were packed & ready to start to town when a servant being sick detained them.\'a0 Then the little boy was taken sick.\'a0 The servant got well, & the little boy died.\'a0 I know of no other sickness at present. Now that I think of it, do my dear husband when you return, take your seat in the \ul safest\ulnone  Car.\'a0 So many Rail Road accidents are happening.\'a0 I think it dangerous traveling on the Road, & be careful also not to have your pocket picked of the little money you will have left.\'a0 I see in the last Patriot someone on taking his seat in the Cars leaving Charleston, had his pocket robbed containing 500 dollars. The children & myself received your letters last night & thank you for them.\'a0 They are very much pleased at the presents you have bought them, but \ul I\ulnone  am \ul not\ulnone .\'a0 You must mean to make them \ul sick\ulnone  with sugar plums.\'a0 I wish you would keep your money to buy necessaries we need, & to support your family, & pay your yearly bills.\'a0 So do not buy anything more for the children or myself.\'a0 I you really wish me to go to Columbia with you in the Spring, keep your money to pay any expenses, for I am afraid you will not have enough to carry me. Only one commission I will give you, & that is to buy me a Receipt book called \'93\ul Miss Leslie\'92s 75 receipt book\ulnone .\'94\'a0 By me \ul two\ulnone  of them.\'a0 They are \ul small\ulnone  books & do not \ul cost\ulnone  much.\'a0 One of them I wish for Susan.\'a0 They are the best receipts published, so if you can get them, bring me \ul two\ulnone .\'a0 The hogs were killed yesterday.\'a0 It was so warm, we had no fire & windows up, & I disapproved entirely of having them killed, but today is rather cooler, & Charles says there is no danger of the Meat spoiling. Mr. Foster sent a load of Corn today 8 barrels, so Willie says.\'a0 It came when I was away. You have before this received the letter in which I told you of Mr. Campbell\'92s impertinence, in sitting exactly in front of \ul you\ulnone .\'a0 I now \ul seriously\ulnone  tell you, that unless you change your pew & take Mr. Poinsetts, I will give up the Episcopal church, for when I go to church I wish to feel pleased & composed, no disagreeable thoughts intruding themselves on my mind, & to have a person who I look upon as one of your greatest enemies, sitting exactly in front of me, so I cannot move my head, without having my thoughts disturbed by him, is out of the question, & I do not intend to put up with.\'a0 It is a peice of insolence we can render ineffective by outwitting.\'a0 He wishes to be just in front of you, that you may \ul see\ulnone  him, & \ul think\ulnone  of him, but he will find he is mistaken.\'a0 That your dignity is not\'a0 [to] be treated in that way by a vain, \ul conceited\ulnone  creature.\'a0 Our pew is too near the Stove, which will be a good excuse for changing it, but I now say \ul distinctly\ulnone , that I give up our pew.\'a0 I am not going to occupy it again.\'a0 I read the peice of Newspaper you enclosed in your letter.\'a0 I was not pleased with it.\'a0 What it said in your favor, was so short of what you \ul deserve\ulnone , that I set no value on it, & I did not know there was such a bitter feeling against you, as the Writer states.\'a0 I thought Secession being dead, that you were looked upon with kindness, & did not know anything you proposed, would be opposed.\'a0 I hope this is not so. You ought to have spoken on the Convention bill, as it was of so much importance, you ought to have been able to say, that you did all you could to prevent its passing.\'a0 The older members ought to have spoken, &\'85left it to the younger. Mr. Hutson, as a boy, was a bragger & boaster & self conceited & insignificant.\'a0 My relations have been your enemies as well as ours, & my relations are the last persons I would apply to if in want. My relations I look upon as enemies, & it is \ul they \ulnone alone, that prevent my having any wish to visit Charleston.\'a0 I wish to go to \ul New\ulnone  \ul Haven\ulnone , but I do not care to see \ul Charleston\ulnone .\'a0 Hext, Wilie & myself can go to Columbia with you next Spring, Willie to escort me about\'a0 when you are engaged.\'a0 Hext of necessity has to go with me.\'a0I am glad you thought of Susan\'92s children in buying Sugar plumbs.\'a0 I am sorry for those children, & wish to give them something to show my regard.\'a0 Susan will be pleased at your remembering them. Frank cannot read your letter to him, but he knows what presents you have bought him, so he takes up the letter & begins, \'93my dear Frank, I have bought you some crackers, & a gold pen & some sugar plumbs,\'94 & then he comes to a pause, then begins again.\'a0 Fanny is very much pleased with the Mouse, & her stomach full of sugar plumbs. I am going over this afternoon to help Mamma do some work.\'a0 We all long to see you.\'a0 Do not leave until the Legislature adjourns. I hope you do all you ought to do, & do not remain inactive, when you ought to be active.\'a0 You may tell Mr. Ashmore the Upper country is my home.\'a0 I go for it \ul entirely\ulnone  & for the Upper country Candidates on all occasions.\'a0 I wish he had told you, the compliments the ladies paid you.\'a0 I hope Mr. Richards & the pupil are married now.\'a0 In haste, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 209\
Thursday morning, 11 December 1851\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I did not hear from you last night, which disappointed me greatly.\'a0 I hope it is the Postmaster in Columbia\'92s fault, & that tonight I will get \ul two\ulnone  letters, at any rate \ul one\ulnone .\'a0 When I receive no letter, I have not much to write about, as I write so often. Yesterday the children & myself all went over to Mamma\'92s & spent the afternoon.\'a0 Susan was there with a bad headache.\'a0 She suffers with them almost all the time.\'a0 Ann also feels poorly. Mamma says Mr. Hutson is so \ul distantly\ulnone  related to us, she does not look upon him as a relatiall.\'a0 His con\'85 is so \ul remote\ulnone , I do not even know what degree it is. Mamma has at present a girl of Mrs. Pearsons, who she likes very much.\'a0 The girl says her wages are 6 dollars a month, but if she cannot get that, she is to take 5 dollars, & that she has tried all over the village, & cannot get a place.\'a0 When Mamma heard of her she was working for Dr. Koch for nothing.\'a0 She told Anna yesterday that Dr. Koch had got wood from so many persons, & not paid for it.\'a0 Now, no one would carry him any, & some \ul cold\ulnone  days had been \ul without\ulnone  \ul fire\ulnone , that he had but one mattress for his whole family, & \ul two\ulnone  blankets.\'a0 She told Mary at the Spring, that Dr. Koch bought a Possum, & one day he would cut off \ul one\ulnone  \ul leg\ulnone , & give it to cooked, & the next day another, & so on, until it was all gone, that his Wife sits down & cries.\'a0 The law is that if a man is strong enough to support his Wife & family they are to look to him alone for support.\'a0 But there ought to be a law for families situated like Dr. Koch where the father \ul will\ulnone  not work to support them.\'a0 The son & daughter ought to be taken from him, & put to trades, & the Wife & young children sent to the poor house.\'a0 Dr. Koch is a \ul worthless\ulnone  \ul creature\ulnone  .\'a0 He sets up for a \ul gentleman\ulnone , so he is \ul above\ulnone  working.\'a0 It was presumptuous in him to charge 1 dollar a lesson for Music when he is as \ul poor\ulnone  a \ul teacher\ulnone  as can be.\'a0 Anna[\'91s] improvement is owing only to me.\'a0 If \ul I\ulnone  had not attended to her she would have learnt \ul nothing\ulnone . Fanny came running in just now to say Anna said I must tell you, she was teaching her, her lesson.\'a0 Fanny got her spelling book out of the Library, & carried it to Anna to teach her.\'a0 Willie was seated in the room looking over a little book.\'a0 I told him he had better read Baker\'92s\'85, so I might give a good account of him.\'a0 He went in the Library to get it, & I have been rattling some bones, & I sent to tell him, I would write you word he was shaking bones, instead of reading, so he stopped, & I hope now he is reading.\'a0Mrs. Walker I believe goes today.\'a0 Her negroes have already passed\'a0 I have heard so often she was going.\'a0 I won\'92t believe it until she is actually gone. I wish you would ask Col. Ashmore what the ladies said about you.\'a0 I love to hear you complimented. Mary says Mrs. Barnard Cleveland\'92s father, old Mr. Jim Cleveland is dead.\'a0The weather now & for several days past, is like Spring.\'a0 I hope you will have such to come home in.\'a0 The nights are as light almost as day.\'a0 I wish you would consult the best Physician in Columbia about your cold, & ask if your \ul tooth\ulnone  has anything to do with the flowing from your nose, & if you had better have it drawn, & you can have the gold to be artificial tooth fixed in a way to do without the decayed tooth.\'a0 No one is better off for a decayed tooth in their mouth.\'a0 It is best to get rid of it.\'a0 Do attend to this matter now while you are in Columbia, & can ask advice of a good Physician.\'a0 For \ul my\ulnone  \ul sake\ulnone  do it, for if your cold is not put a stop to at once, you will go into Consumption. We are all well.\'a0 I see Miss Cornelia Crittenden & Dr. Blackman walking together every now & then.\'a0 I once heard Mr. Walker tell her, she would be satisfied only as a \ul Princess\ulnone , but I think she has lowered her pride, instead of a Prince to take an unknown Dentist.\'a0I hope to hear tonight from you.\'a0 I suppose no Election has been made to the Female Academy.\'a0 Mr. Erwin I believe is the only Candidate, so I hope he will be elected.\'a0 Frank can then get rid of him, & there are so many Female schools, we are not obliged to send Anna to him  must now close after writing a letter literally about nothing.\'a0 When I commenced I did not know I would fill a page. Do your duty. The next Legislature I suppose will be composed of Members of entirely different politics from the present.\'a0 Since the people have been enlightened by the Patriot, & you can then carry your measures \ul triumphantly\ulnone , without any difficulty, so do not be \ul discouraged\ulnone .\'a0 Your affectionate Wife, E.F.P.\
