\f1\b 211\
Friday night \'bd past 7, 12 December 1851\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received two letters from you. & though I wrote to you [to]day, I was so hurried, I wrote but a few lines, & as I have more leisure at night, than in the day, I will write to you now, instead of tomorrow.\'a0 If anything occurs tomorrow worth relating, I can write again.\'a0 I am truly sorry to hear you have been sick.\'a0\'a0 I will be very anxious until tomorrow night, when I hope to hear from you, that you are \ul getting\ulnone  \ul well\ulnone .\'a0 If I do \ul not\ulnone  hear, I will be \ul very\ulnone  \ul uneasy\ulnone .\'a0 You ought to have attended to yourself \ul long ago\ulnone .\'a0 You have been so long threatened with sickness, you are too careless about you health when you know how important you are to your wife & children, sickness can often be kept off with a little care.\'a0 I had a headache day before yesterday.\'a0 I took a dose of Salts & Cream of Tartar, & it carried off my headache & did me good, & I feel now quite well.\'a0 If you had had the headache, I would have induced you to take medicine.\'a0 You would have left it to nature , & perhaps been \ul sick\ulnone  in \ul consequence\ulnone .\'a0 Do write me every Mail, & keep me informed of your health.\'a0 I will be very anxious to hear every night of your welfare.\'a0 Sunday I was able to write you but a line, but I knew \ul that\ulnone  \ul line\ulnone  would be a comfort to you, so wrote it.\'a0 Mr. Elford has not written very lately to his family as they are uneasy about him.\'a0 If you have heard anything of him, write me that I may tell Mrs. Elford.\'a0 I sent tonight to the Printing office to tell them you received no papers now, & beg them to send you one of all hereafter published.\'a0 They sent word they thought you were receiving them.\'a0 They often send me 4 Tri weeklys.\'a0 I would easily have sent you one every Mail.\'a0 I have kept \ul two\ulnone  of every paper.\'a0 I will send you the papers, whie you remain away, though I am thankful it will be only a few days now.\'a0 If the Legislature adjourns Tuesday, I will write you but once more.\'a0 You will get this letter Monday, & I will write on Sunday so you can hear Tuesday.\'a0 I hope & trust my next letter from you. will say you are \ul quite\ulnone  \ul well\ulnone .\'a0 Do consult a Physician about your cold.\'a0 It ought to be cured at \ul once\ulnone .\'a0 You have trifled with it too long. This morning I went to see Mrs. Arthur, Mrs. Beattie, Mrs. Turpin, Mrs. Wm Roberts, Mrs. Crooks, & Mrs. Dr. Irvine, Mrs. Beattie was out, Mrs. Wm Roberts at Union, Mrs. Dr. Irvine sick, so I only saw her sister Miss McMahon.\'a0 This afternoon I went to see Mrs. Henry Thompson.\'a0 Yesterday I went to see Mrs. Dr. Williams.\'a0 Mrs. Brooks I was going to see, but met her in the road.\'a0 I went to see Mrs. Westfield.\'a0 So I am making now an effort to get through with my visits.\'a0 Everywhere I am greeted with a scold, for not having gone sooner. I met Mrs. Hopkins the Minister\'92s mother & Miss Hopkins the sister, at Mrs. Thompsons.\'a0 I have owed them a visit for years, & Mrs. Farr I also met there, & owe her a visit of long standing.\'a0 I like Mrs. Hopkins & her daughter much.\'a0 Miss Hopkins will make a good teacher for children.\'a0 Mr. Capers they say, lets the children play too much.\'a0 Mr. Gailliard is to have both boys & girls, which I disapprove of, so perhaps we had better send Anna to Mr. Hopkins.\'a0 It makes girls \ul bold\ulnone  to go to a school with boys.\'a0 I think they should be kept at a respectful distance from each other.\'a0 None of us now have colds.\'a0 We are all well, & if you only are well, I will be thankful.\'a0 Going out at night does not agree with you.\'a0 When you return you must not go out at night.\'a0 The papers must be brought to you here.\'a0 It is the night air perhaps that has kept up your cold. Mr. Wardell brought home the Sideboard today, done up beautifully, looks like new.\'a0 He was to ask $3.50 if I was not entirely pleased, 4 if I was, , so I gave him a Table to varnish, & said he must do that, & then I would give him 4, at least that \ul you \ulnone would give it, for I had not the money to give.\'a0 I had no idea I would need so much money when you left, , but the necessaries of a family amount to so much,\'a0 If the money spent was not put down, it would be impossible to believe that it was all gone. Mamma is very much pleased with Mrs. Pearsons servant.\'a0 She sent to ask Mr. Elford about her, before you left, but Mrs. Elford never sent an answer.\'a0 The servant was staying at Dr. Koch\'92s working for \ul nothing\ulnone .\'a0 When Mamma heard of her & took her at \ul once\ulnone , & strange to say, Mrs. Buice sent word today that \ul she\ulnone  had engaged her, Maria says \ul she\ulnone  never heard of it, & that she had looked all about for a place, & when she was at Dr. Koch\'92s so near Mrs. Buice, it is strange Mrs. Buice did not send for her.\'a0 I hope Mamma will be able to keep her.\'a0 Mrs. Williams says Dr. Koch beats his Wife & children, that the neighbors have to go in to prevent him.\'a0 Mrs. Turpin says he taught a young lady who staid there. & he begged her to pay in advance, which she did.\'a0 The whole 36 dollars she paid him.\'a0\'a0 He told me he taught Mrs. Turpin, but I expect it was a story.\'a0\'a0 He told me he\'85nothing at Dr. Turpins which surprised me.\'a0 Mrs. Turpin says, he wished Dr. Turpin to give him supper before anyone else, & that he was intoxicated. Anna says I must tell you, she is making a quilt for Hext, for his cradle, as a Christmas present.\'a0 How glad you will be to kiss little Hext again.\'a0 He eats bread & biscuits & sucks chicken bones & spareribs, & likes all these things better than nursing, except when he is sleepy. & at night, then nothing satisfies him but nursing. Miss Crittenden & Dr. Blackman are engaged I expect.\'a0 Anna told me she saw them pass yesterday locking arms, & she was looking up in his face & talking to him.\'a0 Genl Thompson is expected, but has not returned yet.\'a0 Mr. Jones I hear will keep the children, as I should suppose he would, for he has the best right to them.\'a0 Mrs. Genl Thompson is sick in bed.\'a0 Her sister is still with her.\'a0 One of Genl Thompsons fine horses, Willie says, he heard was dead.\'a0 Mr. Latta must be a kind old man.\'a0 Miss McMahan today, told me he was very kind.\'a0 Mrs. Latta she says passed through Greenville not long ago, on her way to Pendleton to see her son.\'a0 Mr. Latta has been married twice she says.\'a0 I wish the son had purchased here.\'a0 He would have been an acquisition.\'a0 Miss Lucy Brockman is engaged to Mr. Julius Earle.\'a0 Mrs. Young her sister, told Mrs. Henry Thompson so, & she is to be married soon.\'a0 The weather is now cooler, so I think there is no danger of the meat spoiling now.\'a0I long to see you, & when you get safe home, you can remain here for four months, & when you leave I will go with you.\'a0 I believe though, the Circuit commences again in the Spring.\'a0 Take care of yourself for my \ul sake\ulnone .\'a0 Your dear Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 212\
Saturday night, 8 oclock, 13 December [1851]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received a short letter from you.\'a0 I was in hopes to hear you were quite well, & am uneasy at your saying, your cold & feverish symptoms were not much better.\'a0 I hope Lee\'92s pills which you say you were to take again, will do you good.\'a0 I write tonight because tomorrow I go to church.\'a0 I may not have time.\'a0 I hope & trust this is my last letter to you for a long time.\'a0 If we had arranged it beforehand, I would have written a letter to you at Newberry Wednesday evening or wherever you will be that evening, but it is now too late for that.\'a0 I am glad your speech had effect & was listened to with attention.\'a0 I hope the exertion will not injure you.\'a0 Tomorrow you can have a quiet day, free from fatigue & excitement. I am glad you think you will gain your Rail Road cases.\'a0 Mrs. Elford was uneasy at not hearing from Mr. Elford, but tonight she has heard, & he is well.\'a0 At 9 oclock I will send to the Patriot office for the paper, & read your letters which give me great pleasure.\'a0 No one enjoys the Patriot more than I do.\'a0 Mr. N\'85 tonight sent me a Jury ticket to send to you, & get you to bring him up the money.\'a0 I enclose it in this letter, & hope you will receive it in time to get the money for him. This morning I went to see Mrs. Elford, Mrs. Harvey Cleveland, & Mrs. Col. Irvine.\'a0 The latter lady was out.\'a0 Mrs. Elford says Mrs. Bruce had engaged Mrs. Pearsons servant Maria, so Mamma will be obliged to give her up & hire Mrs. Town[e]s\'92 who has children. A great trial has been going on today in Mr. Stokes Office, of negroes for gambling.\'a0 Mr. Erwin Jones watchman Lem, Mr. Douglas man, Mr. Washington Green\'92s, Mr. McBee\'92s & others.\'a0 Some were found innocent, some whipped & dismissed, others sent to jail.\'a0 Mr. Elias Alexander had his man Adam tried, & it was said, if he was whipped Mr. Alexander would have gone \ul crazy\ulnone .\'a0 I believe he was cleared.\'a0 Cass with the wooden leg was also cleared.\'a0 Maj. Earle Mamma tells me is ill, perhaps near his end.\'a0 How he has destroyed himself. I rode in the Buggy this afternoon to see Mrs. Brooks & afterwards to Mamma\'92s, so I am visiting in earnest.\'a0 I long to get through, & be able to stay at home as much as I please.\'a0 I hope to finish almost before you return & then devote myself to you. Hext tomorrow is six months old.\'a0 He is now seated in Lindy\'92s lap by the fire.\'a0 I am writing upstairs in my chamber.\'a0 The children are all asleep.\'a0 Fanny has not progressed much in her book.\'a0 Anna gave her two almonds in advance to learn a lesson, which she has not learnt yet.\'a0 She would be a good little girl, if it were not for the teasing of the servants & children, which ruins her temper.\'a0 Anna has been busy making a quilt, so stays satisfied at home.\'a0 Willie has been hauling wood again today.\'a0 Frank knows all the hogs that have been killed, the negroes whipped &c.\'a0 It is worth leaving home to have the pleasure of returning to it as you will have.\'a0 You leave it often enough to value it.\'a0 I stay at it too much, to value it.\'a0 In future you will have to carry me to Columbia with you, then you will be satisfied.\'a0 Next winter the Rail Road will be so far advanced, the journey will be nothing. The weather tonight is quite cold.\'a0 The meat is safe.\'a0 Several persons killed today.\'a0 Mr. Foster has sent 3 loads of Corn, 8 barrels in each load, the servant says.\'a0 Mr. Brooks told me Mr. Furman would most likely be elected to the Baptist church as Preacher, & that he is a hot \ul Secessionist\ulnone .\'a0 Last summer, went about making stump speeches.\'a0 How weak minded ministers are. Mary has not brought the Patriot yet.\'a0 I will stop writing & go to bed, & finish tomorrow.\'a0 I slept very little last night.\'a0 Was kept awake thinking of you, so I am very sleepy now.\'a0 I hope tomorrow night to hear \ul better\ulnone  news.\
\'a0\

\f1\b 213\
Sunday, 2 oclock
\f0\b0 .\'a0 \
\
My dear husband, I have just done dinner, & will finish my letter to you.\'a0 I went to church this morning, all of us.\'a0 I took possession of Mr. Poinsetts pew, & like it very much.\'a0 It is more private than ours.\'a0 We will keep it until Mr. Poinsett comes up, but I rather expect he will \ul never\ulnone  come.\'a0 If he does, we will take some other vacant pew in church.\'a0 There are several unoccupied.\'a0 Mr. Arthur preached.\'a0 He did not go to Spartanburg as he expected.\'a0 A horse fell with him & lamed him which prevented him.\'a0 Mr. Cox read the prayers.\'a0 Mr. Arthur\'92s was extempore, & as poor a one, as I ever heard, tedious & laboured, & really teaches us one virtue \ul patience\ulnone .\'a0 Mrs. Westfield says Mr. Ioor has addressed several young ladies on the Grove, & they all refused him, but Miss Lewis with her little property, thinks him good enough for her.\'a0 Mamma says he looks quite sad.\'a0 He must know that his object in choosing such a lady is wid\'85.\'a0 She is very unloveable, with her one eye.\'a0 Mrs. Ioor has taken the house Mr. Walker the merchant has been living in, so we will have her for a neighbor.\'a0It was a house of Butler Thompson\'92s I believe that is\'85not Genl Thompsons.\'a0 Edward told Mamma a tale of Butler Thompson\'92s being thrown out of a Buggy, his horse killed & himself hurt, but I do not know how \ul true\ulnone  it is.\'a0 Reports are so false I am afraid to mention them.\'a0The weather today is very cold.\'a0 Do be \ul careful\ulnone  of yourself as you come home, wrap up warm, & do not \ul increase\ulnone  your cold.\'a0 I hope & pray you may be \ul well\ulnone  when I hear from you tonight.\'a0\'a0 I am miserable when I hear you are feverish.\'a0 If you are sick you must be at home, where every moment, I can know how you are. I do not know whether you will be here Wednesday or Thursday.\'a0 Mr. Goodlet says the Legislature adjourns Tuesday 12 oclock & that you will set off in the Cars the same day.\'a0 Be careful to get a \ul safe\ulnone  seat in the Cars, & take care of your pocket book.\'a0 What a strange law to pass for a man when in debt to have so much of his own property secured to him.\'a0 Business will have to be stopped for no one will give him credit. This afternoon Willie is to drive us out in the carri[a]ge.\'a0 There is no service at church.\'a0 It is so cold I can hardly write.\'a0 My hands are cold.\'a0 I have not time to read over my letter,\'a0 Your must excusae mistakes.\'a0 Yours truly, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 214\
Thursday morning, [1851]\
[Greenville]
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Willie wrote to you last night, & I cannot seal up his letter, without adding a few lines.\'a0 I always have so much to say.\'a0 Anna is very much pleased at your praises.\'a0 Frank is anxious to write to you, but does not yet write legibly.\'a0 Fanny is very busy & industrious & often asks if she is not the best.\'a0 Hext is well & sweet, & will be very much pleased with his Indian Shoes.\'a0 He wears Shoes & Stockings now, , & the Indian Shoes if he does not wear much, he can keep in remembrance of you.\'a0\'a0 You must be \ul sure\ulnone  & buy me another pr to give to Susans baby, & the \ul two\ulnone  \ul pocket\ulnone  \ul books\ulnone .\'a0 These are all I wish you to bring me.\'a0 For the children anything you bring will please them.\'a0 Toys & candy is so dear in Columbia, you cannot bring much of either.\'a0It seems to me the State is getting in a more dangerous position than ever, for after the people have declared against Secession, the leaders are determined to go on with their designs.\'a0 The Patriot has yet an \ul important \ulnone part to act.\'a0 The danger is not over, as Judge O\'92Neal[l] said.\'a0 You have still to open the eyes of the people, & save them from disgrace & ruin.\'a0 What a pity we cannot have peace like the other States.\'a0 I am sure we would not know we were ill treated & dishonoured, if the Politiciasns did not tell us so.\'a0 Well after they have Seceded, I hope they will be satisfied.\'a0 \ul You\ulnone  will do your \ul duty\ulnone , & that is \ul all\ulnone  you \ul can do\ulnone .\'a0 But what is most provoking is that \ul all\ulnone  will be taxed, even those who are opposed to contemplated action, so I hope you will try & exempt those who are \ul opposed\ulnone , from taxation.\'a0 They should not bear the burden.\'a0 Even Mamma, whose income is only sufficient for her necessary expenses.\'a0 Mr. Barnwell, Mr. Rhett, & such should hear it. I hope to hear tonight from you, & to see the Patriot.\'a0 It is the only paper I have seen since you left. I am sorry you did not dine with Professor Brumby.\'a0 Whether busy or not you ought to have gone. The weather is charming today.\'a0 We are all well.\'a0 I have now a particle of news to tell you.\'a0 I have been out but once to Mamma\'92s, & owe everybody a visit, so nobody comes to see me.\'a0 I am very busy seeing for the children. If you saw a suitable present for Mamma, I would love you to bring it.\
\'a0\
[Benjamin Perry]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 215\
Wednesday morning, 10 March [1852]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received your letter this morning, & was very glad to hear from you.\'a0 Soon after receiving it, I set off & came to Mamma\'92s, where I am spending the day but fearing you may be disappointed if you do not hear from me.\'a0 I have begged writing materials of Mamma.\'a0 I wrote a note to Mr. Elford, requesting him to send you the Patriot tonight, as I will return home too late to send it.\'a0 I hope he will not forget it. I hope Mr. Dyson will offer you a fee large enough to induce you to go to Newberry.\'a0 I would like very much for you to return with your pocket book filled with 100 dollar bills.\'a0 You might go to Newberry, attend to the case, & return here the middle of the week, & be in time to receive business here.\'a0 I could have your Office opened, so that everyone that went in, would come down to the house, & I would tell them to keep their business until you returned, that you would be here the end of the week.\'a0 I am glad Mr. Jones is somewhat humbled, though I am afraid, it is not really so.\'a0 I am delighted at what has occurred, as now you will never let him be on the footing he was before.\'a0 You will never again condescend\'a0 to speak to him.\'a0 Have you heard that Mrs. Eliza Dawkins is married to Mr. Poole of Spartanburg a clerk in a store there.\'a0 He was \ul 20\ulnone  the night he was married & she is about 40 I suppose.\'a0 Mrs. Choice I hear was very angry when she heard of it.\'a0 I suppose the family objected, as I believe none were at the wedding. You will be surprised to hear that Fanny commenced going to school yesterday afternoon.\'a0 In the morning Vardry & Annie went, & Fanny felt that she was debarred of a \ul great\ulnone  \ul pleasure\ulnone  & fretted so, that I let her go in the afternoon, & she came home perfectly delighted, & has gone today.\'a0 I am glad for her to be kept from servants, for often she was seated on the ground playing with John & behaving & speaking badly.\'a0 This morning she dressed with pleasure at the thought of going to school, & took up her bucket & walked about the house delighted, her sweet face glowing with pleasure.\'a0 Hext is well & crawls over the floor.\'a0 All are well.\'a0Reuben & Charles are ploughing Oats.\'a0 No one has been to see you, that I know of.\'a0 Gov. Cobb\'92s Secretary wrote a letter last night saying he had received neither receipt for the money he sent, or the Patriot either, & begging you to inquire into the matter, & to acknowledge his letter & send the Patriot regularly.\'a0 I sent the letter to Mr. Elford.\'a0\'a0 Write again to me, & I hope that you will write that Mr. Dyson offered you the large fee you said you would accept.\'a0 Attend to the case the beginning of the weeks.\'a0 They can try it Monday or Tuesday or Wednesday at least.\'a0 Return quickly in the Stage & attend to your business here also.\'a0 I will make Willie sit in the office if you wish it. I must now stop.\'a0 If you do not get a Patriot, borrow one, & feast on it.\'a0 Yours truly & affectionately, E.F.P. P.S. Mr. Carson talks of carrying all his family to California, but I expect it will all end in toil\'85.\'a0 A Pension for Mrs. Paris has come & an Eclectic. [page torn]\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
Laurens C.H. canceled\
Greenville\
\'a0\

\f1\b 216\
Saturday night, 29 March [1852]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Mr. Elford does not go until Monday but for fear tomorrow I may not have time to write, I will tonight write as much as I can. I will begin by telling you the news that Lindy this morning after breakfast was taken sick, & after dinner gave birth to an infant a girl.\'a0 She suffered I expect a great deal, but I am glad the event is safely over, & hope she & her child will do well.\'a0 It is a good\'85baby.\'a0 Fanny wishes upon having it as her maid instead of Sarah.\'a0 I think we will name it Caroline or Emily after one of Lindy\'92s sisters.\'a0 I sent first for Mom Phillis, & Mom Phillis afterwards begged me to send for Dr. Crooks so he was with her. I received your letter this afternoon by Mr. B\'85.\'a0 I sent your Editorial to the Printing office.\'a0\'a0 I am very sorry you fixed upon this time to have the sale at Tugaloo, instead of coming home.\'a0 I told you it was unwise.\'a0 A Mr. Cunningham came today to see you.\'a0 He thought a case had been brought against him which he wished you to defend, but looking at the records, thinks the case has \ul not\ulnone  been brought. You have heard I suppose of the death of Mrs. Washington Earle.\'a0 She was sick only 2 or 3 days I believe with Cholic & I heard was speechless.\'a0 These are all [the] particulars I know. Mamma Ann Susan & the children [page torn]were with me.\'a0 Lucinda is sick\'85& the servant Mamma hires from Dr. Williams is sick.\'a0 My family are all well.\'a0 Fanny still goes to school.\'a0 She knows all her letters, says she is the smartest girl in school.\'a0 Anna & Willie took tea at Mrs. Hopkins last night & enjoyed themselves so much, they staid until after 11.\'a0 Frank went to the Court House to hear a blind girl play on the piano & sing.\'a0 He had no invitation to the party. Mamma Susan & myself called to see Mrs. Hoyt the other day, on account of her coming from Charleston, & knowing Aunt Hayne\'92s well.\'a0 She calls Mr. Hoyt & herself & the \ul young\ulnone  couple.\'a0 They stay at Mr. Randolph\'92s. I hear Mr. Tom Lowndes & family are not coming up next summer.\'a0 They are going to \ul France\ulnone .\'a0 Dr. Dickson it is said wishes to purchase again in Greenville \ul near\ulnone  the village or \ul in\ulnone  the village. Mr. Carson has postponed his trip to California for some months.\'a0 He cannot get a passage I believe.\'a0 Old Mrs. McBee says she does not know where he will get the money from to carry them.\'a0 I hear Chandler has returned.\'a0 Got as far as the isthmus where he found too many \ul waiting\ulnone  to get across. I am glad to hear of your professional good luck in these hard times.\'a0 A large fee is very acceptable.\'a0 I heard Mr. Wynn was going to bring suit for his daughter, so when you mentioned you\'a0 were employed I felt glad, but that feeling has passed away, & I wish it were on the \ul other\ulnone  side you were employed.\'a0 I have no patience with a bold impudent girl encouraging a young man, or at any rate yielding to his wishes, & then [page torn] round & seeing him for what she is as much to blame [page torn] girl would never be in the situation of Miss Wynn.\'a0 Her father may be good, but I expect she inherits \ul badness\ulnone  from her mother.\'a0 The whole family I believe are a worthless set.\'a0 Kelly while at Mamma\'92s spoke of this same Miss Wynn & said her \ul husband\ulnone  a \ul Mulatto\ulnone  man had connexion with her, & her master had a daughter who lived with a man without marrying, had a child & the man afterwards left her & she herself she said had children by her master & her masters son.\'a0 Someone told Mamma at the time that the servants & overseers are all alike.\'a0 I expect Miss Wynns character will be proved to be so bad (for so many were named as the father of her child) that you will \ul lose\ulnone  the case.\'a0 So if you bring such a case, so \ul demoralizing\ulnone \'a0 to the community, & one that makes you so \ul many\ulnone  \ul enemies\ulnone , you need to make up\'a0 for all you will suffer, secure to yourself a \ul large\ulnone  \ul fee\ulnone , whether you [word botted] or \ul not\ulnone , 1000 dollars if you lose, 2000 if you gain.\'a0 I think you laid the damages \ul too\ulnone  \ul high\ulnone .\'a0 She is not worth paying \ul one\ulnone  \ul cent\ulnone  to get rid of.\'a0 Make Mr. Wynn beforehand give his note.\'a0 I hope you will gain Mrs. \'85 case & get well paid by Mr. Brown.\'a0\'a0 Now you are an old Lawyer & of some reputation\'a0 you ought to charge high fees where you have rich clients.\'a0 Write me about Miss Wynns case whether it is for breach of marriage promise you are suing? Or what? & whether it is to be tried this Court?\'a0 Mr. Barnwell Rhett has sent you Espy\'92s report on Meteorology, the Smithsonian report & Patent office reports on Agriculture.\'a0 No letters have come.\'a0 You have two of Espy just alike.\'a0\'a0\'a0 You can give one away. Have you heard Mr. Jones is a candidate for Con[gress].\'a0 I hardly like to make him of so [page torn] to mention it, but wish to know \ul your\ulnone  \ul opinion\ulnone  as to whether \ul he\ulnone  \ul will\ulnone  be elected.\'a0 I am sure I hope not, do not you think perhaps he may, those opposed to Mr. Orr & not knowing what a contemptible character Mr. Jones is, may take him up.\'a0 This does not look as if he was \ul humbled\ulnone  by \ul your\ulnone  \ul exposure\ulnone  of him, or his \ul bankruptcy\ulnone ; but as if he would show to the world at least, that he thought \ul more\ulnone  of \ul himself\ulnone  than ever.\'a0 Write me your opinion on the subject, what you think his motives are in offering, if he really thinks he will be elected or thinks it will give him importance even if defeated.\'a0 Mr. Luther says at Mrs. Earles funeral he was figuring about, giving himself \ul great\ulnone  a[page torn] \ul not\ulnone  looking like a \ul broken\ulnone  \ul man\ulnone .\'a0 Tomorrow we will go to church for the last time in the building we have been going to for so many years.\'a0 It is to be pulled down & Mr. Arthur will preach in the Academy or McBee\'92s Hall.\'a0 I am sure he is not worth building a new church for.\'a0 I am sorry you have to give one cent for a person who I do not even regard as your friend. Susan says Mr. Campbell & Ioor are going to Florida to speculate in lands, \ul not\ulnone  to \ul live\ulnone .\'a0 I wish they were going there to \ul live\ulnone .  If I have anything new to write you tomorrow I will write again.\'a0 The children are all asleep, & I will now follow their example.\'a0 [page torn] I expect is coming on well.\'a0 Reuben & Charles [page torn] [E.F.P.]\'a0\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
\'a0\

\f1\b 217\
Monday morning, 26 April 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Except to let you know we are well my letters can afford you very little interest, for I have nothing to write you about.\'a0 Today the Convention meets.\'a0 I hope you will have a pleasant time, that no unpleasant excitement or difficulty of any kind will occur.\'a0 Write me how long you will remain in Columbia, for I have a box in Charleston which I will wish sent to you, if it is ready in time.\'a0 I do not wish it sent after you leave, so as soon as you can ascertain let me know. Tell Willie I am glad he is with you, & hope he will return improved, & behave like a gentleman & set a good example to his brothers & sisters & not quarrel with them Yesterday was a fine day; today it is cloudy & looks like rain. I get along pleasantly in my household now cleaning is away, & it is a satisfaction as each week passes away to know that a few dollars have been added to your little income, & that the increase has been added without our denying ourselves, so it is a clean gain.\'a0 I do not think you will ever know what I suffered while under Minervas dominion.\'a0 If ever I wish[ed] you punished I will wish you in that situation.\'a0 Frank has just come from the Office & brought a pardon from the Governor for Mr. Nash for as much as relates to the imprisonment.\'a0 I have sent him to the Goal with Mr. Beaufort Watts letter, & will send the Pardon to Mr. McDaniel or Mr. Hoke.\'a0 Mr. Nash has just sent to know if he can come [word faded] of Goal just as soon as he wants to, & I have sent word just as soon as I have sent him the pardon.\'a0 I suppose he will go immediately to his family & surprise them. A letter came from Mr. Willis Brown asking your influence in electing him Treasurer of the Upper Division.\'a0 He says he is encouraged to ask your aid on account of your friendship for his deceased brother John G. Brown, together with himself, that it is only necessity\'a0 [that] induces him to apply for the Office.\'a0 The letter is dated Spring Grove, Laurens.\'a0 Says in his old age he is left with a helpless family to provide for, & except the assistance he receives from his son M.L. Brown of Columbia, they are dependant upon his individual exertions.\'a0 He writes early, before other applications are made to you.\'a0 A letter came desiring the Patriot to be sent to a different Post office.\'a0 I will send it to Mr. Elford.\'a0 The Metropolitan the newspaper sent to me came.\'a0 This is all. It is now raining.\'a0 I have no news to tell.\'a0 We are all well.\'a0 When I hear from you I will have more to write about. Mr. McDaniel has just come & taken the pardon so you see since I commenced writing a good deal has taken place. I hope to hear tomorrow this time from you.\'a0 Give my love to Willie.\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 218\
27 April 1852, 20 minutes past 11 oclock in the morning\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received a letter a few hours ago & for fear of being prevented answering if I postpone to later in the day, will answer it now.\'a0 I was very glad to hear from you, to know you had arrived safely, & met with no disagreeable incident.\'a0 The Patriot I am gratified to hear is noticed, & its Editorials made of importance.\'a0 If I were a member of the Convention, I would propose the State should \ul leave\ulnone  the Union, & remain out of the Union \ul forever\ulnone , the Secessionists remain in her, & henceforth remain devoted to \ul her\ulnone , & \ul her\ulnone  \ul only\ulnone .\'a0 The Union men remove to some other State where they can have \ul peace\ulnone  & quiet, their principle be appreciated, & themselves have an equal share of honors & office with their fellow citizens.\'a0 South Carolina will be no \ul loss\ulnone  to the Union, but a \ul good\ulnone  \ul riddance\ulnone , & she & her \ul selfish\ulnone  & \ul vainglorious\ulnone  sons.\'a0 The Union can go on prosperously without her, & she has abused it so long, it is time now she should leave it.\'a0 I am glad Willie is satisfied & hope he is enjoying himself.\'a0 Tell him though he will not be here May day to participate in its pleasures.\'a0 He will be represented by his \ul second\ulnone  \ul self\ulnone  \ul Hocky\ulnone .\'a0 Frank Hoke has asked Frank to let Rudd have Hocky to ride on May day, as he is one of the \ul Marshall[s]\ulnone , & I have given my consent, that if he is \ul alive\ulnone  then, for being now under the \ul sole\ulnone  \ul care\ulnone  of \ul Reuben\ulnone  the \ul Horse\ulnone  \ul killer\ulnone , I am under daily apprehension of some morning hearing the news, \'93Hocky is in the stable lying down & cannot get up.\'94\'a0 Reuben has a mysterious way of getting rid of all our horses.\'a0 Charles says he killed 7 pair of Mrs. Harrisons.\'a0 So I am forgetting next Spring, new carri[a]ge, new horses, a new Coachman , all at the same time. Yesterday I wrote you word that we were all well.\'a0 A few hours later, I would have written, there are \ul three\ulnone  of your family sick, for at night Mary came from the Spring complaining of pain in her \ul chest\ulnone , Charlotte pain in her \ul stomach\ulnone , & this morning Minerva came from the Mansion house with pain in her \ul head\ulnone .\'a0 Charlotte I gave a dose of oil to, & she is now well.\'a0 Mary is so useful, I dread her being sick, & for fear of Pneumonia which is so fatal, I sent her at once to Dr. Dean\'92s & he gave her some pills, & said he thought the pain proceeded from her liver.\'a0 This morning I gave her Castor oil, & when the medicine has effect she will I think be better.\'a0 She is at her work, says the\'a0 pain is not as bad as it was.\'a0 Her habits being so irregular, & she so careless about herself, I expect is what makes her so often unwell.\'a0 Minerva had taken medicine from Mrs. Irwin before she came over, & is now in her room.\'a0 I am sorry whenever I see her come in the yard.\'a0 I never intend to have her as my servant again, if I can help it.\'a0 I went in to see her & found her the same \ul impudent\ulnone  \ul creature\ulnone  still.\'a0 I left her room in \ul thankfulness\ulnone  that she was sewing \ul others\ulnone  & not \ul myself\ulnone .\'a0 Your wife & children are at any rate well, & I hope will continue so.\'a0 Frank commences school tomorrow. Mr. Ward came yesterday to see you.\'a0 Mr. Hoke came over Saturday morning, thought you were not to leave until Saturday night.\'a0 He had Mrs. Blassingame\'92s marriage settlement, which had been sent him from Columbia, & he did not know what to do with it.\'a0 This morning your letter, the Lady\'92s book, & the Southern Review were all that came from the Post office.\'a0 I wish at Newberry you had seen \ul Mr. Williams\ulnone , & he had performed his promise.\'a0 Be economical, recollect this time next Spring, I will be with you on my way to Charleston, to buy new Carri[a]ge, & many necessaries we need, & you must save now for that purpose, & some summer before I get old, I do wish to go to New Haven, & look once again at places I will never forget.\'a0 If I were rich, I would wish for us all to go & end our days there.\'a0 I have no love for Carolina, where you will never meet with your reward.\'a0 You labour you save the State, others know it in their hearts, & are ever glad of it, but they give you publicly no credit for, & as for \ul honoring\ulnone  you with Office & Distinction, they never \ul dream\ulnone  of it, but to the end of your days, will heap abuse on you, & stigmatize you as a Submissionist, a \ul term\ulnone  that at once \ul excludes\ulnone  you from \ul honor\ulnone , & this is their \ul object\ulnone  in \ul applying \ulnone \'a0it.\'a0 They are thankful to you for \ul being\ulnone  a \ul Submissionist\ulnone , & yet try to \ul disgrace\ulnone  you\'a0 by the Epithet. You must not forget to see old Mr. Hearn.\'a0 Dr. Irvine must indeed have been anxious to be elected as he had determined to go to Columbia.\'a0 He would like to have been honored as a Delegate, & had his expenses paid.\'a0 I suppose he will expect great attention from the Governor, in return for his hospitality, selfish hospitality truly.\'a0 Hext looks well, & I believe does not miss you at all, & yet will be delighted to see you.\'a0 If it were not for him I would have been in Columbia with you,\'a0 Old Mr. Miller was here this morning, inquired about the Convention that the Leaders who boasted of \ul State\ulnone  \ul Right\ulnone  were \ul State\ulnone  \ul Wrong\ulnone , that Mr. Hunter had not gone to the Convention when now was the time for him to benefit the people.\'a0 He was electioneering for Clerk, & he hoped he would be beaten.\'a0 He mentioned your\'85about Genl Wallace.\'a0 He is a sensible old man.\'a0 Yours truly, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 219\
Wednesday morning, 20 minutes of 10 oclock, 28 April 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just read your letter to Anna.\'a0 She is at school, & will be pleased when she comes home to hear from you.\'a0 I write only because later in the day, I am generally interrupted. I am glad to tell you that the \ul blacks\ulnone  portion of your household are almost well.\'a0 Minerva yesterday after dinner, returned to the Mansion House where I hope she will remain.\'a0 Charlotte recovered entirely of her pain.\'a0 Mary while I was writing I believe stopped ironing. & lay down, & looked so stupid\'85& complained of the pain in her chest. & the medicine not acting much, I sent for Dr. Crooks.\'a0 He was at Laurens so I sent for Dr. Dean, & he said the pain proceeded from improper eating, that it was not Pneumonia, & he gave her Blue pills, prescribed Mustard plaster & Sage tea, & this morning she is up, & says she feels well.\'a0 I always like Dr. Deans prescriptions.\'a0 He says he would rather treat any disease than Pneumonia, that the lungs are effected (or affected) a vital part, & before you are aware the Patient is in danger, he dies. This morning Frank while dressing came into the room crying, with his face swollen, & said his cheeks being\'85, I expect he has the Measles which are all about.\'a0 So I have not sent him to school, but he is playing now, & seems in no pain.\'a0 He was afraid at first, they would kill him.\'a0 If the children will only wait & take them after May day I will not be sorry, as it is as well to have them now, as any other time, but I have fitted them in clothes for May day, so do not wish to lose my trouble.\'a0 Frank I expect will be well by then, so I am not troubled on that account.\'a0 He is grieving over the loss of his \ul last\ulnone  \ul pigeon\ulnone  which Charlotte with delight told him Minervas cat had eaten. Fanny complained of costiveness last Saturday, & I gave her a dose of Oil & last night again, & I gave her Rhubarb.\'a0 I am afraid at school she does not go out as often as she wishes, which will be very bad for her, so I dare say I will keep her at home, if she complains often in this way; otherwise she is well.\'a0 I have kept her at home today. Hext is quite well & steps about holding to something.\'a0 He crawled upstairs yesterday.\'a0 I followed after him.\'a0 He had a flower he wished to put in his mouth, & was going upstairs where I would not see him, & when he got to the top of the stairs, he dropped the flower, a fit emblem of what comes often in life.\'a0 I believe I have no news at all to tell you.\'a0 Except to church I have not been out.\'a0 Mrs. Col. Irvine & Susan Hoke are the only persons who have been to see me.\'a0 I owe almost everyone visits, so I expect few visitors until I visit myself.\'a0 I am glad everything in the Convention goes on well, that the Members are cordial to you, & you are passing your time agreeably.\'a0 If you are enjoying yourself & treated with the respect you deserve, it is all I wish, I am happy.\'a0 I would be willing to be shut up in the Penitentiary you wish to build, if at the same time, you were receiving some deserts from your fellow men; but what makes me unhappy, is, that \ul you\ulnone  should be \ul unrewarded\ulnone , & \ul others \ulnone so far your inferiors, in merit & ability should receive the prize you have won.\'a0 My. Orr so much your inferior in every respect, beat you for Congress & so it will be to the end of your life.\'a0 I must see you rewarded with some high Office or Honour before I leave this world.\'a0 I am thankful however for my many blessings, & first of all for my \ul dear\ulnone  \ul kind\ulnone  \ul husband\ulnone .\'a0 You have not mentioned Judge O\'92Neal[l] & your Daguerreotype.\'a0 How is your life & likeness progressing.\'a0 I hope you will have a \ul good\ulnone  \ul Daguerreotype\ulnone  taken\'a0 to transmit your intellectual features to posterity & that Judge O\'92Neal[l] will do your \ul character\ulnone  justice & write with more \ul warmth\ulnone  & \ul spirit\ulnone  than you did of yourself & as regards one incident of your life, explains it in such a way as to \ul exonerate\ulnone  you from \ul blame\ulnone , more than \ul you\ulnone  did \ul yourself\ulnone . From what you say yourself & the Greenville Delegates except old Mr. McBee must be rooming together.\'a0 Is it so.\'a0 Mr. C\'85 ought not to be unwell.\'a0 I suppose the life he now leads is so new to him, it does not agree with him.The poem you mention ought not to class you with Mr. Memminger Butler Orr & such who are influenced only by personal feelings, to keep themselves in power & gain Office & honor.\'a0 You stand apart, one the only one of prominence, who have acted from \ul disinterested\ulnone  \ul motives\ulnone .\'a0 You lose everything, gain nothing, & have the independence to be stigmatized as a Submissionist, which deprives you of all hope of advancement & which str\'85 prevents the others coming out as Union men.\'a0 I do hope though such nobleness will be rewarded.\'a0I saw Genl Thompson\'92s carri[a]ge pass out of the village this morning, I suppose going to bring up himself & family.\'a0 I am sorry, wish he would always remain away, particularly now he courts you, & you are so foolish as to unite your prospects with his.\'a0 No one likes him, & it is his going over to your side that caused all the excitement at the Memminger meeting, & your predicted downfall.\'a0 He will never be of any good to you.\'a0 In his\'85he would not advance you if he could. I am glad Willie is enjoying himself.\'a0 It is a great pleasure to hear from you, but if you are too busy to write, let Willie write one line, to say you are \ul well\ulnone .\'a0 Truly, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 220\
Thursday morning 10 min[utes] of 9, 29 April 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received your letter, & am very glad to hear from you.\'a0 I will write at once, because Susan is coming in to try on a dress Eliza is making, & she may stay the remainder of the day.\'a0 At any rate something will occur to interrupt me.\'a0 I believe as I read the other day in a newspaper, that \ul one\ulnone  \ul hour\ulnone  in the \ul morning\ulnone  is worth \ul two\ulnone  in the \ul afternoon\ulnone  & whatever I wish done well, I do in the morning, when I feel most capable of exertion.\'a0 I am glad you are passing your time pleasantly, & Willie is behaving well.\'a0 I hope your dinner at Col. Williams will end with the \ul fee\ulnone  being \ul paid\ulnone  you. but as he is not \ul obliged\ulnone  to pay, \ul I\ulnone  know he \ul will\ulnone  \ul not\ulnone , \ul you\ulnone  say he \ul will\ulnone , if he does, I will give you credit, for a better judgment than \ul I\ulnone  have. As for my relations, no neglect from them surprises me.\'a0 Mr. Taylor has never asked you to his house, since you have been going to Columbia, & if he were ever to ask you, I hope you would not accept the invitation.\'a0 I know when I go to Columbia, \ul I\ulnone  will not enter his house, & I would like you to go to Columbia, if it were only for the purpose of refusing any attention from Mrs. Taylor to show her my feelings.\'a0 It was giving vent to my true feelings that made me write so literally to Aunt Eliza, & she either deceitfully, or certainly knowing very little of the matter said \ul everyone\ulnone  connected with \ul her\ulnone , had always without any exception entertained the \ul kindest\ulnone  feelings to \ul you\ulnone .\'a0 She could with truth have said \ul exactly\ulnone  the \ul reverse\ulnone ,\'a0 I have learnt to expect nothing but \ul unkindness\ulnone  from my relations, & unkindness from those who you ought to receive kindness from, can neither be \ul forgiven\ulnone  or \ul forgotten\ulnone , & make your feelings more bitter, than towards strangers who you have no claim on.\'a0 In a political view my relations have always, before you entered the family I suppose & will always dislike you, for they being contracted & selfish in their views, of course will be on an opposite side from you & they look upon you as the chief cause of preventing Harmony in the State, the one who has opened the eyes of the people, & prevented them from carrying out their selfish views, prevented their aggrandizing themselves on the peoples ruin.\'a0 Of course you will be the object of dislike to such persons.\'a0 Mrs. Taylor never paid Willie any attention in Columbia, & then deceitfully turned the tables on \ul me\ulnone , & told Mrs. Thomas she was very much \ul hurt\ulnone  that \ul I \ulnone had not sent Willie immediately to her house to \ul stay\ulnone , that it was what \ul she\ulnone  would have done if \ul her\ulnone  \ul son\ulnone  had come to Greenville; but enough of them we are not dependent on them.\'a0 Your friends are certainly a distinct set from\'85.\'a0 Mr. Pettigru, Judge Huger &c.\'a0 They have not heretofore assimilated with.\'a0 I am delighted to hear of the\'85as regards your being United States Senator.\'a0 I will live on that \ul hope\ulnone , & will be\ul  satisfied\ulnone , when \ul that\ulnone  is realized. Frank when I told him of your pleasure at Hext\'92s improvement asked what you said about \ul him\ulnone . He has the Mumps.\'a0 Dr. Dean looked at his face this morning, but said nothing need be done for it.\'a0 He must not run in the yard when it was cold.\'a0 Fanny is well.\'a0 Mary looks ailing, but goes about.\'a0 Dr. Dean said she must take Blue pills again tonight.\'a0 She still has the pain in her chest, which shows disordered stomach.\'a0 The rest of the household are well, & I do assure you I keep house delightfully with my former illtempered cook away.\'a0 Lindy makes good bread, rolls, tea, cake, & above all she does whatever I tell her.\'a0 Whoever will give 1000 dollars for Minerva may have her.\'a0 Bad temper does not lessen her value to those who have the power (which I never had) of\ul  \ulnone governing her & she is as capable a servant as ever was.\'a0I am glad you are honoured in the Convention.\'a0 You I hoped would be one of the Committee.\'a0 I am afraid you will not remain in Columbia long enough to receive my box.\'a0 You must have my \ul thimble\ulnone  \ul mended\ulnone \'a0 & \ul after\ulnone  the Convention attend to your \ul tooth\ulnone .\'a0 Yesterday a letter from Mr. Verner came, one from Mr. Cochran about his Law case against Charles, one from Mr. Sawyer of Asheville about a suit he wished you to bring for some land near Union left to a family named F\'85, but who have never had it in possession.\'a0 He wishes the suit brought if you think they can gain it.\'a0 The land is worth 10,000 & you would get he says a good fee if recovered.\'a0 You would have to use the very \ul opposite\ulnone  \ul arguments\ulnone  you used for the Paris\'92s. Susan is now here, & I am writing while talking to her.\'a0 The children all have holiday until Tuesday.\'a0 Now to prepare for May day, & Monday to clean up.\'a0 I will be glad to hear from Willie.\'a0 I will write an account of May day, & how Hochy performs his part.\'a0 I have not a particle of news to tell you.\'a0 Charles & Reuben go every day to the Farm, & I hope are doing well.\'a0 In the morning Charles hoes in the garden. Though I expect no attention from our family, I am still glad that Isaac Hayne & yourself are friendly, & in the first instance he wrote you an apologetic letter, & what vexed him was that he had done it, & we did not accept it, so I think he at first was disposed to conciliate.\'a0 Mr. Perroneau I hardly know.\'a0 Politics now makes him treat you coldly, for he used to call on you in town & seemed to like you. Always write the \ul hour\ulnone  in which you are writing.\'a0 Then I can understand better at what time all you write about occurs.\'a0 The Duncans being with Willie must make him enjoy himself more than if he was alone.\'a0 Let him do as he pleases about returning with them.\'a0 I read your Editorials in the Patriot.\'a0 Dr. M\'85 I thought [word faded] Senator from Newberry, you said he had never before represented the people.\'a0 I am sorry your feet hurt you.\'a0 You must have your \ul likeness\ulnone  taken, & send me the doggerel poem. [E.F.P.]\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 221\
Friday morning, \'bd past 8 oclock, 30 April 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Willie\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received your letter & your Papa\'92s last night, & this time will write to you.\'a0 I am sorry you did not write a longer letter, but thank you for the short one.\'a0 Your Papa is so busy I make allowance for his short letters. Mary is still sick.\'a0 As she did not get better I sent for Dr. Crooks , who I always feel has a right to be our Physician & who was out, when I first sent, which made me send for Dr. Dean.\'a0 He is now prescribing for Mary, & she says she feels better today.\'a0 Mary being sick, & Minerva hired out, & Lindy taken up with her baby, has made us all depend on ourselves for fixing the house almost entirely.\'a0 I am glad to tell you Anna has excited herself, & with Charlottes help, has fixed the \ul whole\ulnone  \ul house\ulnone  \ul already\ulnone , & now gone up to the Academy to help dress it with flowers.\'a0 Lindy has to finish ironing, & Charlotte has gone to the Spring to wash, & Sarah is minding Hext.\'a0 John has gone to Mama\'92s to carry some chickens to Susan, to bring in two Chairs to send to the Academy to dress with flowers for Fanny & Anna to sit in at Flora\'92s.\'a0 A Ham that was boiled yesterday will serve us for dinner, so you see even when in a straight like the present, if the children perform their duty we can get along.\'a0 The House cleaning has not commenced yet.\'a0 John Smith was engaged this week & cannot come to Whitewash until Monday, so we will have very little time to clean up before you return.\'a0 It will have to go on slowly, even after you come back. Frank still has the Mumps, & is very much afraid he will not be able to march tomorrow.\'a0 He plays about as usual, & this morning when I told him he must not go out, he cried & said he promised to meet Alex Hunter at some corner of the street, & he must go.\'a0 He has escaped & gone.\'a0 This morning Dr. Crooks was examining his cheeks, & Frank resisted, & Dr. Crooks said, \'93you must not do so, don\'92t you know when your Papa is gone, I am a kind of papa to you all.\'94\'a0 Frank says if he does not participate in the May day pleasures, he may get back his 15 cts.\'a0 If you were here, after all you might have had the Mumps, & been obliged to stay at home, for you would have been for \ul concealing\ulnone  your swollen cheeks, not \ul displaying\ulnone  them like Frank.I have not had a glimpse of Hochy since you left, but I make frequent inquiries after him, & give cautions concerning his good treatment.\'a0 I hope tomorrow he will behave himself well.\'a0 My interest will be divided between Hochy & the Flora\'92s.\'a0 Next year you can ride on him as a Marshall. Hext looks well.\'a0 He does not walk yet alone, but walks about with very little assistance.\'a0 He gets more interesting every day.\'a0 This morning I taught him how to kiss.\'a0 There came from the Mail this morning a long communication from Asheville, contradicting the assertion Mr. Wh\'85 made in his Temperance lecture about the Scripture use of wine, that in some parts of the Bible it was \ul unfermented\ulnone  Wine, in others fermented.\'a0 It proved from the original Hebrew, that \ul Wine\ulnone  is \ul always\ulnone  \ul fermented\ulnone , that there is no such thing as \ul unfermented\ulnone  Wine, & where it is \ul denounced\ulnone , it is the immoderate use of it.\'a0 He says \ul temperance\ulnone  is a \ul Christian\ulnone  \ul virtue\ulnone , which can never be \ul too\ulnone  sedulously inculcated, but the lame attempt to wrest the scriptures will injure not benefit the cause.\'a0 He says he admires St. Paul who \ul voluntarily\ulnone  would abstain from anything on his brothers account, but when it was sought to ensnare his conscience, & to tamper with his Christian liberty & discretion on \ul false\ulnone  \ul grounds\ulnone , he would submit, \ul no\ulnone , not for an hour.\'a0 This is my opinion, I will not take wine, on account of my childrens sake, I will \ul voluntarily\ulnone  abstain from it, that \ul they\ulnone  may follow my example.\'a0 I will follow the dictates of my \ul conscience\ulnone , which is more noble, than promising a few individuals, who in all probability you care not for, & whose opinion you do not respect, promise \ul them\ulnone  not to do \ul wrong\ulnone .\'a0 I do not desire you should ever drink a drop of wine, & particularly until you are of your Papas age, & there is no danger of your indulging too freely.\'a0 I wish you to follow your Papas example & be actuated by a good conscience, & a sense of \ul morality\ulnone , \ul virtue\ulnone  & \ul religion\ulnone .\'a0 These must govern you.\'a0 These are \ul noble\ulnone  motives, & I have confidence in you, that your character is one to be influenced by such motives, & not by the far less noble of one. Of a promise to a few boys trifling ones for the most part, but I have said more than I intended & will tell you of something amusing.\'a0 Last Sunday at the Hall, I forgot to carry my prayer book so when I went in church, I took \ul Annas\ulnone  from her.\'a0 While the Prayers were being read, Willie Earle who was in \ul front\ulnone  of Anna, took the opportunity \ul very\ulnone  \ul slyly\ulnone  as he thought, to hand Anna \ul his\ulnone  Prayer book, which she had the \ul ill\ulnone  \ul manners\ulnone  to \ul refuse\ulnone .\'a0 A short time after, she removed her seat to \ul another\ulnone  desk.\'a0 I noticed Anna moved her [word faded] & wondered why, & noticed that Willie Earle looked rather vexed.\'a0 I had not seen the offer of the prayer book.\'a0 Susan saw it & told me afterwards.\'a0 Is it not amusing to see a little girl, \ul vexed\ulnone  at attentions, that in a few years \ul later\ulnone , she will \ul covet\ulnone , & displaying \ul rudeness\ulnone , which before long, she will be \ul surprised \ulnone at.\'a0 I mention this little incident to \ul amuse\ulnone  you.\'a0 Do not \ul mention\ulnone  it, as Anna will be vexed if you do. Tell your Papa I am glad his resolutions were approved of.\'a0 I have seen no paper mentioning the Convention, except the Patriot.\'a0 I am sorry the Duncans have left you.\'a0 Your Papa forgot to carry down the Tea nuts for Dr. Blanding & the other gentlemen. I have come to the end of my sheet, so must stop.\'a0 E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Willie Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 222\
Sunday morning, \'bd past 10, 2 May 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just sent off Anna, Fanny, & Frank to Church, & before I read to myself, will perform my duty to you.\'a0 Yesterday was May day, & getting ready so many children, Mary being still sick, & having to do it principally myself, fatigued me & gave me a headache, which though I partly slept off last night, I still have a little left & preferred staying at home this morning & resting, & go to church this afternoon. Dr. Crooks went to his farm Friday morning & said he might not return soon as he might find more of his servants sick.\'a0 I think he must have done so, as last night he had not come back.\'a0 Mary is getting better, & comes down into the kitchen. But she has not come into the house yet.\'a0 This put me to great inconvenience, so I live in great discomfort & make me reconciled & even pleased \ul you\ulnone  are not here & I would rather live as I do than [to] have Minerva back again.\'a0 Since she is away, the \ul other\ulnone  servants do better.\'a0 This morning while Lindy was fixing the house, Edward made some biscuits, & Eliza washed the dishes.\'a0 A general happiness has been diffused throughout the household since Minerva\'92s departure. Yesterday I received no letter from you, which disappointed me greatly.\'a0 This morning before I was up, Mr. Duncan sent you packages, & after breakfast when I sent to the Office a letter of yours came, which I expect I ought to have received yesterday, as it was written \ul before\ulnone  the one Mr. Duncan brought.\'a0 I suppose there was some carelessness in the Columbia Post office. I will have scarcely room to tell of May day.\'a0 Frank was at the School House all day, until 10 oclock at night, looking at the Tableaux & eating.\'a0 Very different from last May was this, for everybody I hear had \ul plenty\ulnone  to eat.\'a0 Frank asked this morning how long it would be before May day would come \ul again\ulnone , so he must have enjoyed it.\'a0 Anna also did.\'a0 She returned home in the afternoon. Dressed anew, went back again, & staid until 10 oclock at night.\'a0 The little H\'85 I think had very little pleasure, their poor little feet had to paddle along so fast, they were quite worn out.\'a0 Fanny dwells on the \'85ness of the \ul Queen\ulnone , who said she wished she had a \ul stick\ulnone  to make them go \ul faster\ulnone .\'a0 The Queen if she noticed \ul us\ulnone , must have been mortified at observing our attention was entirely on the H\'85, not on her.\'a0 Her iron rule it is well bestowed only for a day, & her subjects were rebellious, for they would have the Tableaux, which \ul she\ulnone  objected to.\'a0 I looked at them from the carri[a]ge, did not go into the schoolyard.\'a0 All of the Marshalls \ul walked\ulnone , so Hocky was not used,\'a0 Rudd strutted about in a \ul cocked\ulnone  hat.\'a0 The sun was so hot, it was enough to give them all fevers.\'a0 Hext was out, & looked \ul sweetly\ulnone .\'a0 I am glad the Convention adjourned in \ul harmony\ulnone .\'a0 I wish your resolutions had been adopted by the \ul whole\ulnone , but they paid you more respect that Mr. Memminger.\'a0 I long to read the account of the Convention in the next Patriot.\'a0 I read your Editorial this morning, & sent it to Mr. Elford with your printed Resolution & Mr. Greggs. You must be \ul sure\ulnone  & have your likeness taken, for without these the \ul life\ulnone  is far less interesting.\'a0 You must stay in Columbia for the purpose if necessary. I recollect in Columbia the servant at Maybins saying Mrs. Hemming a widow kept a boarding house opposite.\'a0 I suppose it is her son Miss Walker married.\'a0 I thought when she kept school she would meet with someone, as schoolteachers always manage to make a match.\'a0 As she is so unpleasantly situated at home with a stepmother. It is a \ul providential\ulnone  thing for her to get a husband. Mr. Burketts business being of less interest to me, than your\'a0 own,\'a0 I did not mention it. as I had not room for all, but I have opened the letter now, & will tell you what is in it.\'a0 Mr. Verner says he obtained a note on Mr. Hunnicut for 4 dollars, at a Muster, which he agreed to have paid in the fall; that Mr. Burkett says all are well & progressing at the Farm.\'a0\'a0 The Corn short 40 bushels, Lard 50 lbs.\'a0 Shucks one load which he paid for himself, which amount can lie, until he has some settlement about the notes in his hand for collection.\'a0 The country generally healthy.\'a0 One of the Mares at Burkett has a fine mule, & something about R\'85 Susan Perry was here.\'a0 Friday, her Grandmother had toothache\'85\'a0 A letter came this morning about some change in Post office & one from John C. Sullivan about some Law business.\'a0 You must try your best for the Paris\'92 \ul not\ulnone  to get a new trial.\'a0 Mr. Luther I am afraid & Susan never can be happy.\'a0 An un\'85 wife wife perhaps might be able to resign herself, but no other.\'a0 What do you think of his sitting down almost \ul naked\ulnone  to breakfast \ul only\ulnone  in his \ul shirt\ulnone , & going over the house before children & servants, & strange servants in that condition.\'a0 Vardry even asked if it was \ul right\ulnone  for Pa to come down naked.\'a0 He is still harping on the Joyce estate.\'a0 Mr. Hoke told him the estate was 160000 dollars, & he had given security only for 20 .\'a0 Mr. Luther told him he \ul could\ulnone  \ul give\ulnone  security for 500000 dollars.\'a0 Soon after Mr. Joyce died, old Mr. McBee sent for Mr. Luther to go to see him, & when he refused to go, sent again, & Mr. Luther went, & on his return home Susan asked him for what he was sent, & he said to talk about Mr. \ul Joyne\'92s\ulnone  \ul will\ulnone , so Susan thinks \ul his\ulnone  \ul father\ulnone  put it into his head to try & get it.\'a0 You know he persuaded him to run for Ordinary, an Office he was \ul entirely\ulnone  unfitted for.\'a0 So if this is so. You make old \ul Mr. McBee\ulnone  give security to \ul you\ulnone , that \ul you\ulnone  may not lose.\'a0 Pinckney is not as bad as Mr. Luther & is better off.\'a0 He has \ul carri[a]ge\ulnone , \ul buggy\ulnone  & 3 horses.\'a0 Tell Willie when he returns I am going to have a May day in the orchard, so he must bring me a pound of cocoa nut & one dozen nice oranges.\'a0 This will do instead of any presents for the children.\'a0 Anna will be Queen & he must deliver an address.\'a0 It will be pleasanter than the Academy May day.\'a0 I have come to a close.\'a0 Hext is now playing on the floor. E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 223\
Tuesday morning, 9 oclock, 4 May [1852]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received your letter & Wilie\'92s & am obliged to you for them.\'a0 I was holding Hext while reading them, & gave him the envelopes to play with.\'a0 Mary was taken sick two days after you left, & though almost well now, does nothing in the house, & very little of anything in the kitchen.\'a0 Lindy works, Milks, minds her child[,] helps wash & iron, so of course can do nothing in the house.\'a0 Eliza works for Mamma, Susan, Ann as well as my family, so I can take her as seldom as possible from her sewing.\'a0 Sarah or Charlotte have to mind Hext, so it leaves you perceive almost \ul nobody\ulnone  to clean the house.\'a0 So I have lived in greater discomfort than I have known at housekeeping, & the house is dirtier than I have \ul ever\ulnone  seen it, but I am \ul far\ulnone  \ul happier\ulnone  than if Minerva were here with her insolent tongue & things were cleaner.\'a0 John Smith disappointed me & did not come yesterday to whitewash. & says he cannot come until Thursday.\'a0 If so the house will be confusion the night you return, but I have sent to ask him to come tomorrow, & allow me one day to clean up before you come back.\'a0 If he cannot come tomorrow, I will have to put off the whitewashing until next week.\'a0 I like it done every year, because we are obliged to clean every corner, & cleanliness promotes wealth.\'a0 But when I tell you it was fever Dr. Crooks thought Mary had, you will be thankful that she is soon getting well, & that all the rest of us have continued well.\'a0 All of Dr. Crooks negroes are getting well, & Mary is almost well.\'a0 She only takes Bitters to strengthen her.\'a0 She is so careless I expect her to be sick as long as we have her.\'a0 Frank is well, & none of the others have as yet taken the Mumps.\'a0 You tantalize me when you tell me of Mr. Rhett\'92s resignation.\'a0 He is right, for as a Secessionist, he \ul misrepresents\ulnone  the State, but no other Secessionist ought to be elected his \ul Sucessor\ulnone .\'a0 \ul You\ulnone  of course ought to be, but as you do not try for yourself, & have no friends so disinterested as to try for you, your claim will \ul always \ulnone be passed over.\'a0 If you had only got some friends to bring you to the Governors notice, I am certain you would have received the appointment, & what a triumph after being defeated for the other house, but of course you will be overlooked, so I am provoked as I am always with you, for doing \ul nothing\ulnone  to promote your interest, but as usual letting others get ahead of you.\'a0 Some honor of this kind would be the \ul making\ulnone  of your family in \ul this\ulnone \'a0 \ul world\ulnone , so you ought to make every honorable exertion for your advancement.\'a0 Persons like Mr. Martin of Abbeville always express what you \ul ought\ulnone  to have & what is \ul due\ulnone  you, but no one \ul tries\ulnone  to \ul get\ulnone  you your \ul due\ulnone . I am glad your Daguerreotype is taken & so fine a one.\'a0 \ul Copys\ulnone  are always cheaper after taking \ul one\ulnone , so I wish as \ul my\ulnone  \ul present\ulnone , you would have a Daguerreotype taken like the one you are to send to Mr. Livingston, only \ul finished\ulnone , & \ul bring\ulnone  \ul me\ulnone .\'a0 A \ul second\ulnone  one should be taken for far less than the \ul first\ulnone .\'a0 I hope Judge O\'92Neal[l]\'a0 will write your life \ul better\ulnone  than you did.\'a0 Altogether I was not satisfied with it, & look to \ul him\ulnone  to do you \ul justice\ulnone .\'a0 I am glad Mr. Finley spoke cordially to you.\'a0 I know our family in their \ul hearts\ulnone  \ul respect\ulnone  you, but in politics having been always on opposite sides, gives them a reserved feeling to you, & you yourself are reserved to them, for your manners, as I very often tell you are \ul repulsive\ulnone  & you think \ul others\ulnone  cold to you, when it is only a reflection of \ul your\ulnone  \ul unintentional\ulnone  coldness to them, you need \ul me\ulnone  by to \ul soften\ulnone  things.\'a0 Politics creates bitter feelings as \ul I\ulnone  know by experience.\'a0 Think of the Cunningham family who formerly were your \ul best\ulnone  friends, have now changed into enemies.\'a0 You say you did not \ul recognize\ulnone  Mr. Finley, so \ul he\ulnone  might have thought \ul you\ulnone  rude, when you did not mean to be rude at all. You must not forget to have my \ul thimble\ulnone  mended.\'a0 I hope Willie will come back very much improved.\'a0 Yesterday afternoon we had a fine rain, which was \ul greatly\ulnone  needed, & today Charles & Reuben are ploughing the bottom land & planting it, as it is in good condition to be done.\'a0 Charles attends to the garden every now & then. Mrs. Poinsett is now at her place.\'a0 I believe her son is with her.\'a0 Last Sunday afternoon Mr. Arthur had no service, & we went to the Baptist church to hear Mr. Furman, but he is away. & there was a Prayer meeting held instead of preaching.\'a0 Mr. Elford made a prayer a \ul very\ulnone  \ul good\ulnone  one.\'a0 After service he called to me as I came out of church, & said he had an Editorial sent him that morning of yours, which he would send to \ul me\ulnone  to read.\'a0 I told him \ul I\ulnone  had \ul read\ulnone  it, & \ul sent\ulnone  it to \ul him\ulnone .\'a0 He said he thought it had been sent by mistake to him.\'a0 You know Mr. Duncan brought it & sent to me, & I sent to Mr. Elford, & he was \ul not\ulnone  up, & seeing the Envelope directed to me, & not knowing who sent it to him, thought there was some mistake .\'a0 I have not sent him the \ul Temperance\ulnone  communication yet.\'a0 It is directed to \ul you\ulnone , & he I expect will not publish it, & I want you to read it. \ul I\ulnone  like \ul you\ulnone , wish Anna to be \ul modesty\ulnone  itself, but at the same time \ul polite\ulnone , & I think it was \ul rude\ulnone  to refuse the prayer book.\'a0 If a fan is offered me & I do not wish it, for fear if I refuse I will hurt the persons feelings.\'a0 Little attentions ought to be accepted with \ul politeness\ulnone  & at the same time \ul modestly\ulnone .\'a0 A little girl who is afraid it shows her to be \ul bold\ulnone .\'a0 If she \ul looks\ulnone  at a \ul boy\ulnone , perhaps is \ul bolder\ulnone  than one who \ul looks\ulnone  at him with \ul perfect\ulnone  \ul indifference\ulnone .\'a0 I wish our children to be \ul modest\ulnone , \ul easy\ulnone  & \ul polite\ulnone , but not \ul forward\ulnone  & \ul bold\ulnone  & \ul rude\ulnone .\'a0 I think with \ul our\ulnone  \ul training\ulnone  they will pursue the \ul right\ulnone  \ul course\ulnone , as \ul we\ulnone  \ul ourselves\ulnone  have.\'a0 If I have time I will write to Willie.\'a0 We will all be very glad to see you.\'a0 Yours truly, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 224\
Tuesday morning, 11 oclock, [4 May 1852]\
[Greenville]
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Willie\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have written to your Papa, & as you are now at leisure, & not much to occupy you, it may give you pleasure to read a letter from me. So I will write to you.\'a0 I will first tell you of Hochy, who you are \ul most\ulnone  interested in.\'a0 He was not used May day, as I have informed you.\'a0 I saw Rudd strutting about with a cocked hat on, & though he would not have graced Hochy much.\'a0 Aunt Anne inquired what plain looking person he was.\'a0 I dare say he is \ul good\ulnone , which is far better than good \ul looks\ulnone , but he is not as \ul handsome\ulnone  as \ul Hochy\ulnone .\'a0 Sunday afternoon Reuben put Hochy & Selim in the carri[a]ge & drove us a little way.\'a0 It seemed to me both horses looked \ul thin\ulnone .\'a0 It may be I only \ul imagined\ulnone  it, for I expect no horse under Reuben\'92s care\'a0 to do \ul well\ulnone , & I am aways expecting to see them looking thinner & thinner.\'a0 Reuben said Hochy was quite well, & had been used very little to haul wood.\'a0 He is so young, it gives no pleasure to use him, for fear it hurts him, so I determined not to use him often in the carri[a]ge.\'a0 Anna wrote you a letter Sunday.\'a0 She would not let me read it, so you must make allowances for mistakes, as she composed & wrote it entirely herself.\'a0 Yesterday she wrote to her Papa, & I read that.\'a0 I was amused at her arrangements for the May day she is to have; at everyone having a part assigned them, & when it came to Alex\'92s carrying the May pole, I laughed aloud.\'a0 Hext will be an odd little H\'85, unless he walks alone before that time.\'a0 There will have to be a third H\'85 to lead him & the Procession will have to make a very short circuit, in consideration of his little feet.\'a0 I hope you will acquit yourself well on the occasion, & that your first \ul effort\ulnone  as a \ul public\ulnone  \ul speaker\ulnone , will foreshadow who you are to be in after life. The boys gave a party last night to the girls.\'a0 Anna wished to go, but as \ul you\ulnone  were not here to go with her, I was very glad it rained so \ul hard\ulnone , that she \ul could\ulnone \'a0 \ul not\ulnone  go.\'a0 I hardly think any girl could have gone, & it was not in the favor of any who did go.\'a0 Until girls grow up, they should show themselves very little in public, & even then only occasionally.\'a0 They should be retired & modest, though at the same time polite. Franks mumps have troubled him very little.\'a0 He has gone about as usual except the first day he stayed from school.\'a0 He has gone to school this week. Mr. Wallace Thompson\'92s judgment I think very bad, to tell you, you ran about too much & neglected your school.\'a0 Judge Butler would have told you \ul differently\ulnone .\'a0 The foundation you lay out at school is very important, but the knowledge you gain in the occasional trips you make from home, are of great benefit to you, & will be through life, & give you information, that probably you never would have. If you staid all the time at home, went to school, & devoted yourself to Grammar, Geography Arithmetic &c.\'a0 Perfection in these studies, would make you a good schoolmaster, enabling you to impart\'a0 the same knowledge to others, but as you are to be a Lawyer or Statesman or something of this kind, you must have a \ul knowledge\ulnone  of \ul mankind\ulnone , in \ul general\ulnone  \ul information\ulnone  matters & things which you can never gain at school only.\'a0 Your occasional association with the \ul good\ulnone  & great has already done I hope much for you; for you know Hugh Thompson told his mother you \ul knew\ulnone  \ul something\ulnone  on \ul every\ulnone  \ul subject\ulnone  mentioned.\'a0 Your character it seems to me is different from the other little Willie[s], who stay at home, & whose Papas are not like yours, who have not the advantages you have.\'a0 You are more enlightened, & ought to be better than they are, when you think of the trouble & expense your Papa puts himself to, to improve you, so you must come back a \ul man\ulnone  in \ul behaviour\ulnone , & such a thing as quarreling with Frank, & being rude & unkind to Anna & Fanny you must be above, & be respectful to your Mama & not scold the servants.\'a0 I would have sent your letter to your Grandmama to read, but as you forgot to send your \ul love\ulnone  to her, I thought she would be hurt at the neglect, so did not send it.\'a0 She takes great pride in you, as you are her oldest grandchild. The \ul Temperance\ulnone  Cadets turned out May day, & were very \ul intemperate \ulnone in eating.\'a0 I believe if it were not for the \ul marching\ulnone  \ul occasionally\ulnone , & the \ul scarfs\ulnone  & \ul banners\ulnone  the company would not be near as large as it is.\'a0 I hope \ul nobler\ulnone  motives than these will influence you to be \ul good\ulnone , \ul virtuous\ulnone  & \ul temperate\ulnone .\'a0 Read your \ul bible\ulnone  & be governed by the \ul principles\ulnone  there inculcated.\'a0 We are all born sinful creatures, but some certainly even by nature more virtuous than others.\'a0 Your Papa is \ul innately\ulnone  \ul virtuous\ulnone , & I hope his children may be like him. If you come home Thursday night, tomorrow I will write my last letter to Columbia.\'a0 When you return you must devote yourself with increased application to your studies. I hope Paul Hayne\'92s \ul talents\ulnone  will be of some \ul use\ulnone , & not like some of his cousins, but what was his end.\'a0 He had no energy & was wanting in many things, but he was sensitive & many allowances must be made for him.\'a0 I am glad your Papa dresses so well, as to be observed.\'a0 He loves you\'85, [E.F.P.]\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 225\
7 October [1852]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I will write you a few lines, though with a shocking pen, to prevent your being more anxious than is necessary.\'a0 Dr. Crooks this morning said Edward was doing \ul reasonably\ulnone  \ul well\ulnone , that with the fever he has, the patient one day is better, the next day perhaps worse, & sometimes so for 12 or 15 days, sometimes longer before they begin actually to get better.\'a0 He also says that there is not so much danger of the fever spreading in the yard, as if one of the servants about us had it, for then it would have originated on our premises, & the same cause would give it to others, but that Edward was not living here, his sickness originated elsewhere.\'a0 You know Mr. Dyer said he had 3 servants sick like him.\'a0 All the rest of the family are well, & I hear of no new sickness anywhere.\'a0 I expect certainly to see you Saturday night & wish you would come back sooner, as you are to leave Sunday.\'a0 You ought to give me one day at least.\'a0\'a0 Take care of yourself.\'a0 I hope Frank is behaving well.\'a0 You must not be uneasy about us.\'a0 Yours truly, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
\'a0\

\f1\b 226\
Tuesday, quarter past 1, 23 November [1852]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear daughter\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 You only left yesterday, but I am certain your Paper will be gratified to hear from home as soon as he reaches Columbia, so I will write now, that you may hear the very moment you get there.\'a0 This letter will be travelling along the Rail Road the \ul same\ulnone  \ul time\ulnone  with yourself.\'a0 Little will you know of it, that there is a letter travelling along with you telling how we all are.\'a0 I am sorry you had such a bad day yesterday but am glad that today the weather is so fine.\'a0 I hope you are well & behaving well, & that your Papa feels better than when he left.\'a0 We are all the same, as we were yesterday morning.\'a0 I have been busy today helping Mary fix upstairs, which has been in great disorder for several weeks past.\'a0 I am now tired so thought I would rest & write to you.\'a0 You must tell me everything in your letters, who you see, what they say to you, how you enjoy yourself &c. &c.\'a0 I was gratified to see you display some feeling on leaving home, for though I wish you to enjoy yourself when you \ul leave\ulnone  home, I wish you to be attached to home & prefer it to every place.\'a0 I hope & believe you will spend your time pleasantly.\'a0 Everything will be new to you.\'a0 If you can get a very pretty Silver comb in Columbia at a reasonable price, get it, but if not, \ul wait\ulnone  until you get to \ul Charleston\ulnone .\'a0 After you have made all the purchases you \ul need\ulnone , write me word how much money you have \ul left\ulnone .\'a0 Your Papa had better give you \ul 30\ulnone  \ul dollars\ulnone .\'a0 Buy some \ul Castile\ulnone  \ul Soap\ulnone  to clean your \ul teeth\ulnone  with the morning after you get to Columbia. I forgot to give you any; 6 cts worth is enough, & you will find it very useful.\'a0 It \ul whitens\ulnone  the teeth, & cleans them easier in this cold weather, than the water alone.\'a0 I forgot to put up your Barege Sack,, & one nice pr of\'a0 fine tucked pantalets, I saw in your drawer today, which I ought to have packed up.\'a0 Do not forget the Castile Soap.\'a0 I am going to buy 3 peices this evening for each of the childrens room. \ul Nothing\ulnone  more from the Post office this morning.\'a0 Fanny missed you yesterday & wished you were here.\'a0 Willie little while ago came from school with your bucket in his hand, grumbling that he had to bring it\'85Mrs. Hopkins called him in as he passed & begged him to bring it home.\'a0 I am glad it has been found.\'a0 Fannys shoes were broken, & as it was so wet I let her stay at home today.\'a0 Frank has gone to school.\'a0 Willie is now learning his lessons.\'a0 Fanny is seated on the floor putting on her stockings which\'a0 she had taken off.\'a0 Hext is in the little dining room playing with the\'85to the stove.\'a0 Charlotte has gone to Mrs. Mauldins to carry Mary Mauldins book mark & pocket handkerchief you left for her; the other book marks for Mr. & Mrs. Hopkins Fanny will carry tomorrow.\'a0 I have no news to tell.\'a0 Charles has gone to the Farm to get wood.\'a0 I have been busy cutting out clothes for the servants & helping make them, but I go to bed regularly at 9 oclock. I hope you will not have to stay long in Columbia.\'a0 As you have gone down so late, you will have but a short time to stay in Charleston.\'a0I will write perhaps again tomorrow, but if I do not you may know I have nothing to write about.\'a0 Write to me & behave like a lady, & tell your Papa to write.\'a0 Your affectionate Mother, E.F.P. P.S. This is the first letter I believe I have ever written to you.\
\'a0\
Anna Perry\
Columbia\
\'a0\

\f1\b 227\
Wednesday, 1/2 past 12, 24 November 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I take up my pen to write to you, with very little to write about.\'a0 We are all well.\'a0 Nothing more from the Post office this morning for you, a letter from Aunt Mary McCall to me, & letters from Aunt Eliza & Alston to Mamma is all that came.\'a0 Aunt Eliza is expecting Anna down, & says Mr. Taylor & Sarah requested her, to ask you to carry her to stay with them.\'a0 If they ask her in Columbia, let her stay with them.\'a0 Mrs. Martin & Mrs. Isaac Hayne are to be in Columbia & if they are at Sarahs, Anna will find it pleasant having companions among their children, & less lonely than at the boarding house, where she will be \ul alone\ulnone , while you are away all day. Col. Town[e]s came this morning for your office key.\'a0 He has brought it back again.\'a0 He says he sets off for Columbia tomorrow with his brother Augustus in a private conveyance, so he will not get as quickly as the Mail, or I would write by him. The Spotted Cow has a Calf, a few days old.\'a0 Charles says he will let it remain at the Farm until we can use the Milk.\'a0 Charles is today hauling wood with Mamma\'92s horse.\'a0 I suppose Reuben will be back tomorrow.\'a0 I hope you have arrived safely in Columbia & feel better than when you left.\'a0 I am glad you now have fine weather.\'a0 Today I hope you are going on safely to the end of your journey. Write me how Anna behaves, & if she enjoys herself.\'a0 Willie\'92s school breaks up tomorrow.\'a0 I will ride to Mr. McClanahans & pay him as soon as the horses have rested on their return.\'a0I have no news to tell you.\'a0 Write me everything you know I am interested in all that goes on.\'a0 I will have more to write about when I hear from you.\'a0\'a0\'a0 I will then give you advice, which I know you are longing for. We are getting on quite well.\'a0 I hope Anna & yourself are also.\'a0 I write only to keep you from being uneasy, for I have literally nothing to write about.\'a0 I hope tomorrow or the next day to hear from you or Anna.\'a0 My love to her.\'a0 Your affectionate wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 228\
1 oclock, 25 November1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 This is a bad day.\'a0 It commenced raining all day.\'a0 Reuben got home last night about Supper time.\'a0 The horses are quite well.\'a0 He says you set off before he left & you were quite well.\'a0 I hope to hear from you tomorrow morning.\'a0 Anna\'92s first day in Columbia has been a gloomy one.\'a0 But I hope she will pass her time pleasantly.\'a0 She can commence her quilt if she remains long in Columbia.\'a0 I hope she may stay with Sarah Taylor, but she may not like your not carrying her to her house at once, & therefore may not ask her again.\'a0 Your first appearance in the Legislature has been in bad weather.\'a0 I hope you are comfortably situated at your Hotel & able to get along with convenience though with a broken arm. Willie has come from school.\'a0 He has now done with Mr. Leary.\'a0 He brought his bill 10.25 which I will pay.\'a0 Frank is the only one who will be going to school.\'a0 Fanny\'92s breaks up tomorrow.\'a0 She staid at home today on account of the rain.\'a0 \ul Nothing\ulnone  came from the Post office this morning.\'a0 I have no news to tell you.\'a0 Mamma & Susan came in yesterday.\'a0 They are well.\'a0 Reuben is cleaning carriage & harness, Charles shelling corn.\'a0 As soon as Reuben returned, Charles accused him of carrying off one night last week a load of Potatoes. But it turned out to be a load of\'85he was carrying over to Minerva to fix up a Stove in her room.\'a0 Mr. Lasly is cutting down the timber at the Farm to build the house. I will stop now & write a few lines to Anna.\'a0 Yours truly, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 229\
Friday, 1/2 past 12, 26 November 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I was disappointed not to hear from you this morning, but I know you had not time to write the evening of your arrival in Columbia.\'a0 I hope to hear from you tomorrow morning. This is a bad day again.\'a0 Charles says it will rain until the \ul moon\ulnone  changes.\'a0 Willie says a man in N. Carolina (so Mr. Leary told him) has predicted another freshet before Christmas worse than the late one.\'a0 It seems as if this prediction may come to pass. I am glad to tell you the missing Heifer came up yesterday, little aware of its fate, & at this moment the rain having ceased awhile Charles, Reuben & Willie are all engaged dispatching it.\'a0 Our last Ham gave out at breakfast so we were absolutely in need of meat.\'a0 This now will last us a long time.\'a0 We will with the different Beeves we can kill, have a supply for a long time.\'a0 \ul Nothing\ulnone  came from the Post office this morning.\'a0 As Willie will have holiday for some time, I have told him he ought to improve his time systematically, read something improving first, then something interesting & afterwards making himself useful in cutting wood, hauling it &c., so he has commenced Bancrofts History of the United States, & read a good way in it.\'a0 John wets himself going to the Spring. & takes off his Shoes constantly, so he has taken cold, & Minerva makes such a fuss about him.\'a0 Came over late last night & early this morning, that I sent for Dr. Crooks.\'a0 He said he only had bad cold, must take Castor oil & Toddy & that was all that was necessary.\'a0 So he is in the cellar today.\'a0 But when the weather is good, he will come out.\'a0 The shoes you gave him, have shrunk so he cannot get them on.\'a0 I gave him a pr of Franks, & when they go will have to buy him a pr. I sent for Mr. Chandler to look at the leak in the floor of the balcony.\'a0 He says he will put a peice of tin against the house where the floor of the balcony joins & that will stop the leaking. I know of nothing new to tell you.\'a0 I have not been out since you left, & seen no one but Mamma & Susan once, & Col. Town[e]s for a few moments. I am afraid Anna has not enjoyed herself yet. As the weather if it is as bad in Columbia as here must prevent her going out. Fanny would not go to school today on account of the rain.\'a0 Frank has just returned.\'a0 He says Mr. Hillhouse the boys say is to be married to a Lady in Union.\'a0 I believe I have nothing more to write about.\'a0 This is the fourth letter I have written & have not heard once yet.\'a0 I hope you are well, & getting along comfortably.\'a0 I have put by two Patriots.\'a0 There was not as much Editorial as usual.\'a0 I will now close with love for Anna.\'a0 Your affectionate Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 230\
Sunday morning, 28 November 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 This is a bright pleasant day, but as I am not altogether prepared to go to church, I will stay at home, write to you, take care of Hext, as Charlotte is going to church, & read the services to Fanny.\'a0 Willie & Frank are going to church. I have not received a line from you yet.\'a0 Yesterday I expected certainly to hear but did not.\'a0 Today I supposed I would but no Mail came from beyond Newberry.\'a0 Tomorrow no Mail comes at all, so until Tuesday, the ninth day since you left, I will not hear, but I bear it patiently, hoping it is your business, that has prevented your writing, or the irregularity of the Mail that has prevented my receiving what you \ul have\ulnone  written.\'a0 It will be a great satisfaction when I do hear that you have arrived safely in Columbia & are well & Anna enjoying herself.\'a0 This is the fifth letter that I have written, so you have heard every day since you reached Columbia. The weather cleared Friday evening & is now very fine.\'a0 Charles is anxious for you to buy some Kentucky hogs before you come back, says those that pass by now are better & cheaper than they will be later.\'a0 Shall I tell Mr. Hoke to buy some? or wait until you return.\'a0 He has not bought the Hog yet.\'a0 We do not need it for immediate use, as we have a supply of Beef.\'a0 It would only be to put away for future use,\'a0 John is better of his cold, & was out yesterday, but complaining of Earache, which he sometimes has.\'a0 He is going to church this morning, so must feel well.\'a0 The rest of us are well.  Fanny amuses herself as well as she can, but often wishes someone to play with, but is better alone, as she then cannot quarrel.\'a0 Yesterday she & Hext went up to Mrs. Hopkins to carry two little presents to Miss Eliza & Rosa.\'a0 She returned with two presents for herself, a pincushion & little tiger, & is anxious to give more presents, that she may get a return.\'a0 She wishes Anna had gone long ago & come back so as to show her all the pretties.\'a0 \ul Nothing\ulnone  \ul at\ulnone  \ul all\ulnone  has come from the Post office for you since you left. I have nothing new to tell you, have not been out once, & seen no one but those I told you of before.\'a0 I am busy working all the time for the servants.\'a0 Baylis & Becky have Prayer meetings every night in their room, except Friday night, when they have it in Eliza\'92s room.\'a0 I hope they will cause a reformation in the yard. You must write me everything, whether you think Jones will be elected Treasurer.\'a0 I wont feel easy until he is beaten, for he is too unprincipled to be rewarded, & if he is, I will think it only requires a person to be \ul vain\ulnone , \ul presumptuous\ulnone , a \ul fool\ulnone  & \ul unprincipled\ulnone  to succeed in this world, for never has a man been more undeserving of success than him.\'a0 Merit & deserts do not meet with their reward & are not appreciated; that I know & feel from \ul your\ulnone  experience, but I trust & hope, you will \ul even\ulnone  \ul yet\ulnone  be \ul rewarded\ulnone  not by you \ul own\ulnone  conscience \ul alone\ulnone , but that the consciences of others will make them honor you, in some \ul tangible\ulnone  \ul shape\ulnone , give you an office or Honor that will show the \ul whole\ulnone  \ul world\ulnone  you have been \ul appreciated\ulnone . Give my love to Anna.\'a0 She forgot her \ul Veil\ulnone .\'a0 She must buy one.\'a0 I hope she is pleased, not disappointed in her anticipations, & able to get along alone, & been a good girl. Hext is now pulling me, & crying for me to take him, so I must stop.\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 231\
Monday morning, 29 November [1852]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have nothing to write about except to say we are all well.\'a0 Tomorrow I hope to hear certainly from you.\'a0 I have not heard yet.\'a0 When I do hear I will have more to write about than now. I am going to ride to Mr. McClanahan\'92s this afternoon to pay him.\'a0 Today Willie carried Mr. Leary his money. Yesterday I read Robert Halls life.\'a0 He thought Grey\'92s Elegy the finest thing ever written.\'a0 He recommends Jeremy Benthams writings to all Legislators.\'a0Mr. Hoke bought some hogs today.\'a0 I don\'92t know whether he bought the one for us you told him to. I hope you are well, & Anna also.\'a0 I am in hopes Anna is by this time in Charleston.\'a0 I know of nothing new, have seen no one, & except the Patriot, seen no newspaper.\'a0 I must now close.\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F.P.\'a0\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 232\
Tuesday. \'bd past 9 oclock in the morning, 30 November [1852]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received your letter & Anna\'92s & am very glad to hear from you.\'a0 I am glad you arrived safely, for I think there is great danger in the \ul boat\ulnone  conveyance.\'a0 I am sorry you have so little time for writing to me, but that is only of secondary importance, & I wish you to neglect nothing else to write.\'a0 I am sorry you should have to make your own fires.\'a0 Another time you had better take a servant with you, Reuben to wait on you.\'a0 You ought to attend to your comfort when you leave home.\'a0 Charles can attend to us here. Tell Anna I am glad to hear from her.\'a0 I dare say she will receive no message from Mrs. Taylor.\'a0 She is sick in bed, has recently for the \ul fifth\ulnone  time lost an infant at its birth.\'a0 Aunt Eliza said both Mr. Taylor & herself requested \ul you\ulnone  to take Anna to their house & not doing so, they may not think it necessary to send to ask her, particularly if it is true as Mrs. Thomas told me that Sarah was hurt at Willie\'92s not going to stay with her, when he \ul first\ulnone  went to Columbia.\'a0 We are all well.\'a0 John is well again.\'a0 The horses are quite well. & the stock generally I believe.\'a0 I will give particular directions about Genl Thompsons Heifer.\'a0 I rode yesterday to Mr. McClanahan\'92s & paid the money.\'a0 He was not at home & his daughter said, her Mother instead of receipting the bill, which I asked her to do, would send a receipt today, Yesterday old Mrs. John Stokes brought me some Butter 15 cts a pound, & the servant said, she would engage it to me all winter at that price, & I said I would be glad to.\'a0 Mrs. McClanahan asks 20 cts, , & does not send it.\'a0 So I will take from Mrs. Stokes. If Judge Evans is elected Senator, a judge will be elected in his place.\'a0 I wish \ul you\ulnone  would be a Candidate.\'a0 My ambition is to be a \ul Judges\ulnone  \ul wife\ulnone .\'a0 It will be easier for you to be elected to that office, than\'a0 to any political one, as a Judge has not much to do with politics, & then I can go to Charleston with you every year, so get some friends to interest themselves for you. The ride I took yesterday was quite pleasant. Susan, Ann & Fanny went with me.\'a0 This evening I intend to take another.\'a0 Reuben drives us.\'a0 I am sorry to mortify Willie, but I am afraid to trust him with the two horses.\'a0 Bill starts constantly, & it requires a a strong hand to keep him in.\'a0 You will have to buy a horse for Willie\'92s especial use. I will be very glad for you to pay Dr. Irvine for Becky.\'a0 It will save interest, & like you I like to pay my bills immediately, & if possible never go in debt.\'a0 He soon goes to Florida.\'a0 You had better send the Check at once.\'a0 Dr. Irvine I can beg to leave your note with someone, so it will be paid even in his absence.\'a0 I dare say he would like the money before he goes to Florida, as he is going there to purchase land.\'a0 When Mr. Hamilton pays you. you must pay all your debts, & then invest the rest profitably.\'a0 You see \ul I\ulnone  was right.\'a0 Mr. Williams has not paid you what he promised. Willie says the Mountaineer office is removed to that small house by Rutledge Stables, that Mr. Long had built over his Ice House.\'a0 I cannot say I am sorry for Mr. Sam Town[e]s sickness.\'a0 I instinctively dislike him.\'a0 He & Mr. Burt, both make a \ul tool\ulnone \'a0 of you for their \ul own\ulnone  \ul interest\ulnone , but whenever an opportunity offers they injure you.\'a0 For 100 dollars a year Mr. Town[e]s would abuse you as much as your enemies would wish, but when he wishes \ul you\ulnone  to \ul write\ulnone  his \ul book\ulnone  for him his abuse then stops for the time.\'a0 Mamma says she hears he is going to purchase the house Mr. Lynn Watson is building near her. Luther lately wrote a note to Susan begging her to return, but she declined.\'a0 He told her not to mention to anyone, particularly to Mamma, that he had written.\'a0 She told it to me in \ul confidence\ulnone , & I tell it to \ul you\ulnone  as we are one.\'a0 I know of nothing new to tell you.\'a0 An Eclectic is all that has come for you.\'a0 Tell Anna I will write soon to her.\'a0 I hope she will go to Charleston before long.\'a0 Yours, E.F.P.\'a0\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 233\
Wednesday morning, 1 December [1852]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received two letters from you this morning, & one from Anna.\'a0 I was very glad to hear from you.\'a0 Your letters are the only comfort I have while you are away.\'a0 I was really \ul provoked\ulnone  to hear that \ul Jones \ulnone was elected by the Legislature, Treasurer.\'a0 If anyone deserved defeat it was \ul him\ulnone .\'a0 It has given me a bad opinion of mankind, for I see now that \ul duplicity\ulnone , want of \ul principle\ulnone , \ul meanness\ulnone , \ul vanity\ulnone , \ul presumption\ulnone , & \ul being a fool\ulnone , is all that is needed now to succeed in this world; that \ul merit\ulnone  & \ul good\ulnone  \ul conduct\ulnone  & \ul sense\ulnone  stand \ul no\ulnone  \ul chance\ulnone .\'a0 I would have given a \ul large\ulnone  sum to have defeated Jones.\'a0 I believe how he will appropriate the money he receives in his Office to his own \ul use\ulnone , pay his debts, live in style, & never breaks, & even if he does this, I suppose he will be elected again.\'a0 He is now made for life, & will hold his head higher than ever.\'a0 I am sorry too, your \ul enemy\ulnone  should have succeeded.\'a0 It seems as if your exposure of him failed of its \ul effect\ulnone .\'a0 I thought he was \ul put\ulnone  \ul down\ulnone  forever, instead of which he has risen \ul higher\ulnone  than ever, & your \ul judgement\ulnone  too is out, for you thought he stood no chance of success.\'a0 What a pity Mr. Ashmore or some prominent man had not been a Candidate.\'a0What a dreadful Rail Road accident.\'a0 I am afraid for you to come back on it.\'a0 You must hire a hack or have the carri[a]ge sent down for you.\'a0 The Rail Road will never be safe.\'a0 It will be constantly under \'85ing.\'a0 All the rains will injure it.\'a0 At the South they cannot manage as at the North. Isaac Hayne\'92s election was really close.\'a0 You were obliged on account of my relation to Aunt Eliza to vote for him, but I would not have been sorry if he had been defeated.\'a0 You are the only magnanimous\'a0 person I know of, & the only one that meets with no reward.\'a0 It makes me heartsick to think of Jones election.\'a0 He \ul deserved\ulnone  \ul defeat\ulnone  \ul so\ulnone .\'a0 Dr. Crooks says he borrowed one thousand dollars to pay for his Piano & Carriage, that he cannot hold up much longer, & that John Jones will break along with him, for he is security for all his debts, but I do not believe either will break.\'a0 Mr. Hopkins has just brought me a letter from you.\'a0 I will stop & read it. I have read your letter & am very glad to hear again from you.\'a0 I hope Anna has gone to Charleston by this time, as she will have so short a time to stay, if she remains longer in Columbia. The white faced Cow has a calf also.\'a0 Reuben says they had better all remain in the field, that there is plenty there for them to eat.\'a0 They were brought home yesterday & Charles has carried them back today.\'a0 In two weeks the oldest Calf & Cow will be brought home & milked.\'a0 John is quite well now, Edward goes to his work, Mary is well, & Lindy seems pretty well, hobbles a little.\'a0 I would be thankful if I could get rid of Eliza.\'a0 She calls Joe Powel her husband, says she has been living with him five years, sends her children on messages to him, abuses me, wont let her children work for us, & she is an \ul abominable\ulnone  \ul creature\ulnone , a \ul pollution\ulnone  to any yard, & Mary could & would have married, if it had not been for Eliza\'92s abusing her, to those who wished to marry her, but these things we will speak of on your return. I am glad Anna is behaving well & enjoying herself.\'a0 I will write to her when she gets to Charleston, & she must write to me often, & do you write whenever you can.\'a0 I have written by \ul every\ulnone  Mail.\'a0 I know of nothing new at all.\'a0 The village seems very quiet.\'a0 When you are away, I hear nothing.\'a0 I have nothing at all to write about.\'a0 Becky is ding well.\'a0 If I can get rid of Eliza, & take home Clara as the seamstress, I think then our yard will be purified. I am sorry the Mails are so irregular.\'a0 I will be very uneasy when you are coming home\'a0 I would rather send the carriage for you all the way to Columbia.\'a0 The road curves so.\'a0 I think the Cars will constantly run off.\'a0 How sad for Col. Singleton & his Grandson to be killed.\'a0 The road must be badly managed, & I suppose the freshet undermined it so, that many parts will yet give way.\'a0 Next winter I will go with you. Hext will be weaned, & I would like to stay in Mrs. Janney\'92s room as Anna does, not go to the public table.\'a0 I am glad she does not.\'a0 She is too young to go much into public.\'a0 Mrs. Janneys family have been kind.\'a0 I rode yesterday to Mrs. Dr. Williams to carry home her Can she had sent for.\'a0 She has had 30 cases of sickness.\'a0 She expects to be confined.\'a0 What a pity.\'a0 She is having her house plastered, & going to add an addition in front.\'a0 We rode also to the College Hill, & saw the building more than 3 stories high.\'a0 I do not hear of any sickness now in Greenville.\'a0 I hope it will be healthier. I am glad you are treated with \ul respect\ulnone .\'a0 That is all the reward \ul you\ulnone  will meet with.\'a0 I wish you would be Judge.\'a0 If you think you can be elected you must try for it.\'a0 The Legislature would be inclined perhaps to bestow the honor on you, for your disinterested conduct, through life, but you have no \ul ambition\ulnone .\'a0 I wish you honored for your \ul childrens\ulnone  sake.\'a0 It will be an advantage to \ul them\ulnone . Write me long letters, & tell me everything.\'a0 All the letters I received today were dated 27
