\f1\b 234\
Thursday morning, 10 oclock, 2 December 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received a letter from you.\'a0 I am pleased at your being thought of as Governor, & provoked that you should \ul decline\ulnone  the honor.\'a0 If you ran & were not elected \ul this\ulnone  \ul time\ulnone , you might be \ul another\ulnone , & it would then seem as if you had at last been so rewarded & appreciated by your State.\'a0 Your position in the State for yourself & family would be established forever.\'a0 You would then be ranked among the \ul highest\ulnone .\'a0 Why do you \ul act\ulnone  so \ul strangely\ulnone , & not avail yourself of the offers made to honor you.\'a0 You are always holding back, & let others take, what you could easily have.\'a0 Why do you not think of your \ul own\ulnone  & your \ul wife\ulnone  & \ul childrens\ulnone  \ul interest\ulnone .\'a0 It has provoked me ever since I have been married, this disposition of yours, to do for \ul others\ulnone , what you wont do for yourself.\'a0 As your honors all end in nothing, it is tantalizing to me, only to have suggestions made & not carried out, that it gives me no satisfaction.\'a0 I would be much happier if you had some ambition.\'a0 \ul I\ulnone  \ul have\ulnone , & your not having any, is a constant source of annoyance to me.\'a0 You had better for \ul my\ulnone  \ul sake\ulnone  be elected to some Office.\'a0 Until you are I will give you no peace.\'a0 I will then get over my disappointment at your Congressional defeat.\'a0 You ought to have said \ul yes\ulnone  you would run for \ul Governor\ulnone .\'a0 You know you \ul deserve\ulnone  it, & would discharge the duties \ul better\ulnone  than \ul anybody\ulnone  & in Greenville where so many look \ul down\ulnone  on you & \ul dislike\ulnone  you, I would be so pleased to make them henceforward feel differently.\'a0 I hope you will be elected; for my sake \ul do\ulnone , it will make me \ul so\ulnone  \ul happy\ulnone .\'a0 I will never worry at anything again, & I will feel so pleased at your being appreciated, & after the term is over you can practice law again.\'a0 It will cause you to have higher honors & make your children stand so \ul high in the world\ulnone ; for their sakes, consent to run. I am glad Anna is enjoying herself, & that Mrs. Martin asked her to stay with her.\'a0 I suppose she is today in Charleston.\'a0 I am sorry you bought her so useless & extravagant\'a0 a present as a medallion.\'a0 A Silver comb which is ornamental & \ul useful\ulnone  I wished her to get.\'a0 She has no chain to wear the Medallion with.\'a0 Do not spend your money so uselessly.\'a0 All of mine here goes for servants clothes.\'a0 In winter it costs a great deal to clothe them & I only give them what is absolutely necessary but try to provide for one a great many.\'a0 I try to save but it is no use, what \ul I\ulnone  \ul save\ulnone , \ul you\ulnone  \ul throw\ulnone  \ul away\ulnone .\'a0 \ul We are all well\ulnone .\'a0 Mrs. Stuart was here yesterday, came to borrow books.\'a0 She said she wished Mr. Thompson would get an Office; that he wished to be Superintendent of roads, that the present incumbent did not wish the Office.\'a0 I told her you were going to try & get it for Mr. Thompson.\'a0 You must not forget it.\'a0 When you are \ul Governor\ulnone  you can \ul give\ulnone  him an Office.\'a0 How delightful to have it in the power to help others.\'a0 Susan Hoke says Mrs. Trimmier was a run away match; says the family are so small in size, \ul dwarfs\ulnone  I should think.\'a0 I am sorry Anna witnessed such \ul boldness\ulnone .\'a0 I hope to hear every day from you.\'a0 It is my only comfort.\'a0 I have nothing new to write about.\'a0I would be very sorry if the Commons in College is dispensed with.\'a0 I think the young men should eat & sleep in the College.\'a0 If the Fare is bad, make them pay more, & have better. Isaac Hayne\'92s was really a close vote.\'a0 If the Greenville Delegation had not voted for him, he would have been defeated.\'a0 I am really sorry Jones was elected, but if you are elected Governor, I will be able to get over Jones undeserved reward.\'a0 It worries me so, the fear that you will not run, that I am almost sorry you mentioned the subject to me.\'a0 From Mr. DeTrevilles vote there must be a great many Secessionists in the Legislature.\'a0 You will get also the Union & some of the Cooperationists, so if you will only run, you will \ul certainly\ulnone  be elected, so I will live on hope & do you run I never will again repine at you not hav[ing] been rewarded as you deserve if you Are Elected Governor.\'a0 It seems to me if you are only a Candidate, the Legislature will be glad to show their esteem by electing you.\'a0 So I new certainly look forward to my dear husband being a Governor, not that it will make him higher in \ul my\ulnone  \ul esteem\ulnone , but in the \ul World\ulnone  it will, & will be a mark of esteem he \ul deserves\ulnone  & \ul merits\ulnone , & through the whole United States he will be honored, but \ul alas\ulnone  I fear my wishes will not be \ul realized\ulnone .\'a0 If not, a Seat on the bench is what next I wish. I will write soon to Anna.\'a0 I hope she will pass her time pleasantly in Charleston.\'a0 I am glad she behaves well.\'a0 Willie reads, & hauls wood.\'a0 He misses the driving the carri[a]ge, & wont drive \ul one\ulnone  \ul horse\ulnone  unless he can drive both.\'a0 Frank goes to school.\'a0 Fanny & Hext\'85amuse themselves at home.\'a0 Fanny also goes to Mamma\'92s. & Annie comes here.\'a0 I am too busy to visit, have rode out twice only.\'a0 I am glad you are employed, but wish you had a little more time to write.\'a0 Write every day.\'a0 I miss your letters if you do not.\'a0 Ever yours, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 235\
Friday morning, 10 oclock, 3 December 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received your letter mentioning Anna had left, & I am very glad to hear from you.\'a0 I hope the Mail will continue to come regularly, & you to write every day.\'a0 If you do not, I will miss the letters so much.\'a0 It gives me something to think of each day, but you must not again mention honors offered you, & \ul declined\ulnone  by you.\'a0 You must if it is only for my \ul sake\ulnone , accept them, for you know I expect to be unhappy, until you are elected to some \ul Office\ulnone , that will make me feel, you are appreciated by your \ul fellow\ulnone  \ul men\ulnone , that your noble independence & disinterestedness, has been rewarded.\'a0 So I hope you will be run for Governor, even if you are defeated, it will be of benefit to you at some \ul future\ulnone  time.\'a0 Your name will be brought forward, & the next time you will be elected to that or some other office.\'a0 But I hope you will \ul now\ulnone  be elected, & if \ul you\ulnone  \ul consent\ulnone  that your friends\'a0 should interest themselves for you, you will,\'a0 you must not be so \ul indifferent\ulnone  to these worldly honors.\'a0 For the sake of your childrens \ul future\ulnone  \ul benefit\ulnone , you should exert yourself more to advance your name & reputation.\'a0 If you had been married to a Lady like Mrs. Brockman you might remain satisfied as you are.\'a0 She would have had no aspirations\'a0 for you, & would have been contented & happy, but I am different.\'a0 My desire is to have you \ul exalted\ulnone  in \ul Station\ulnone , for you are of a \ul superior\ulnone  \ul order\ulnone  of \ul being\ulnone , & deserve the \ul highest\ulnone  honors in the gift of the people, & until you get \ul one\ulnone  \ul Honor\ulnone  that will show to the \ul world\ulnone , that your fellow men have appreciated you as you deserve, I cannot be satisfied.\'a0 It is not for myself that I wish it but for \ul you\ulnone .\'a0 I am contented to remain in \ul obscurity\ulnone  so \ul you\ulnone  meet your \ul reward\ulnone .\'a0 But I cannot be satisfied until you are rewarded in the way I wish, not as you say a good conscience, is all you look for.\'a0 I look for something more.\'a0\'a0\'a0 So I hope you will be elected Governor.\'a0 If you are not, as you have elected Judge Evans a Senator, you ought to be elected Judge in his place.\'a0 So you must return either Governor or Judge. In one other thing also you have acted as you usually do, giving place to others,\'a0 the bill giving the Presidential Election to the people, \ul you\ulnone  first introduced, & have made the people \ul determine\ulnone  to have this Session when the bill \ul can\ulnone  pass, & \ul you\ulnone  ought to have the \ul credit\ulnone  of, you have let Mr. \ul Poppenheim\ulnone  \ul take\ulnone  from you, so instead of \ul your\ulnone  \ul name\ulnone  going down to posterity as the Author of this great reformation, you quietly give it to another, when \ul you\ulnone  are the one who deserve it.  I will write to Anna today.\'a0 I am glad she enjoyed herself in Charleston, & received so much kindness.\'a0 I am willing for her to remain several weeks in Charleston & even the whole winter if her friends wish it.\'a0 Two weeks is too short a time for her to stay.\'a0 You can come home, & she come up with someone who will be coming.\'a0 Mrs. Elford goes down Monday & will stay 3 weeks.\'a0 Anna can come back with her or someone else, after the trouble & expense\'a0 of getting ready & sending her down she ought to stay 3, 4, or 5 weeks at least.\'a0 I do not know when she will go again.\'a0 But I dare say Aunt Eliza will write to me about her staying, & I can then determine how long she had best stay.\'a0 I know there will be plenty of opportunities for her to return. I will speak to Mr. Hoke about the Hogs, & the first cold weather get him to buy some.\'a0 At present it is too warm.\'a0 It is today raining, but I dare say it will clear up cold.\'a0 We are all well, & coming on quite well.\'a0 I keep house in more comfort than I did, & when you return, hope to live systematically, & have everything in order. Frank goes to school.\'a0 He seems a favorite with everybody.\'a0 Willie reads & cuts & hauls wood.\'a0 I would much rather him be with you.\'a0 He would improve in character & manners more than here.\'a0 In future you had better carry him.\'a0 I dare say Mr. Janney would not charge for Willie, if he occupied the same room with you.\'a0You must have been pleased at Gov. Swains remembering you so kindly.\'a0 It is a pity you had not both met as \ul Governors\ulnone .\'a0 It would have been an interesting incident.\'a0 Two school mates being elevated to the same office, & meeting after 30 years had elapsed.\'a0I never know of any news to tell you.\'a0 A letter came from Mr. Hamilton today enclosing a second check for 300 dollars, In place of the one that you wrote word you had not received.\'a0 I suppose this second one will be of no use to you now.\'a0 But I will keep it carefully until you return.\'a0 If you have 400 dollars in your pocket book, & Mr. Gladden pays you 100, you can pay for Becky.\'a0 What next you receive pay your other debts with, & I hope next year being the\'85of debt, & even have some to invest profitably for future use. I am afraid the Railroad will constantly be injured by these rains.\'a0 It passes over so many water courses.\'a0 I should think it was not built well, or managed well.\'a0 You had better have the carri[a]ge sent for you to Columbia or hire a conveyance.\'a0 The horses are quite well & the animals generally.\'a0 Charles until the rain was digging ground nuts, & Reuben hauling wood.\'a0 Mr. Lasly is cutting down trees for the Log house.\'a0\'a0I write to you every day.\'a0 As you were so extravagant in buying Anna a Medallion, I was induced to buy something for the house which we much need, an Entry carpet 21 yds at 1 dollar a yd.\'a0 The Oil Cloth is completely worn out, & I have bought a beautiful Carpet, only two thirds more than the Medallion cost, & will be much more useful, & add to the beauty & comfort of the house.\'a0 It would take all of my money to pay for it, so I will not pay until you return.\'a0 I have only bought what servants clothes was necessary, but it costs a great deal, & to keep the house for so large a family.\'a0I am glad you are spending your time pleasantly with congenial spirits.\'a0 It is what I wish you would \ul always\ulnone  enjoy.\'a0 Greenville is too little & contracted & narrow a sphere for you.\'a0 I must now conclude.\'a0 Ever Truly Yours, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 236\
3 December 1852\
Charleston
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Mama\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I wrote yo Papa yesterday and so will write to you today.\'a0 I have not written to you in a long time, because I have enjoyed myself so much that I have not had time to write to you.\'a0 I arrived here Wednesday evening safely.\'a0 I came down with Mr. & Mrs. Trimmier.\'a0 They were staying at the same Hotel with us & perhaps I will go up with them, for they will be going up about the same time that I will.\'a0 I spent Tuesday with cousin Elise Martin in Columbia.\'a0 She had just arrived two days before & came for me to go to her house.\'a0 I did not see Cousin Sarah Taylor because she was too unwell.\'a0 Yesterday I went to see Aunt Annie, aunt Mary Hayne, and aunt Anna Turnbull, and aunt Martha, but I did not see aunt Harriet.\'a0 I suppose that she had gone in the country with aunt Sarah Matthew\'92s.\'a0 Cousin Susan took me to see them.\'a0 I would have gone to see my other aunts if it had been a good day.\'a0 It was cloudy all day and rained some.\'a0 I also went up S\'85 street, and I had my ear\'92s bored, and bought me a pair of gaiter boot\'92s, and a pair of gloves.\'a0 I just have finis[h]ed practicing.\'a0 I thought I would have forgotten my Tune\'92s, but I still knew them, and I am going to practice regularly every day.\'a0 I enjoy myself very much.\'a0 All of my aunts seemed glad to see me, and wished Fanny had come too.\'a0 They say that they would not have known me.\'a0 They do not think that I look at all like you, but the image of Papa.\'a0 I will have to write Papa sometimes too, and so you must not expect a letter every day.\'a0 You must write to me soon.\'a0 Tell Grandmama aunt Susy, aunt Annie Frank Fanny Willie all howdye for me and give Hext a kiss for me.\'a0 Tell Willie he must write to me.\'a0 Your affectionate Daughter, Anna\
\'a0\
Elizabeth McCall Perry\
[Greenville]\
\'a0\
