\f1\b 237\
Friday afternoon, 3 December 1852\
Greenville\
\'a0
\f0\b0 \
Dear Anna\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received a letter from your Papa today, in which he mentions your having left that morning for Charleston.\'a0 That you went off in good spirits, & had enjoyed yourself very much in Columbia.\'a0 I have time now to write you only a short letter, my next one will be longer.\'a0 I was gratified to hear you had been a good girl & given your Papa no trouble.\'a0 He wrote word, you were as good a girl as he knew of.\'a0 I was sorry he bought you so useless & extravagant a present as a Medallion.\'a0 You have no chain to wear it with.\'a0 I will send you by Mr. Elford who goes down on Monday, some of my hair, that I have had a long time.\'a0 I kept it at a time when it came out very fast, to make a chain with.\'a0 You can use what is necessary to make a chain to go round your throat to wear your Medallion to, sometime.\'a0 I will have my likeness & your Papa\'92s taken & put it in the medallion, so it will then be valuable, more so than it is now.\'a0 Your Papa\'92s heart overflows so with love for his wife & children, that he would spend his last cent in gratifying even an extravagant wish of theirs particularly when he is absent from them.\'a0 He then loses his prudence, & his generosity gets the better of him.\'a0 Whatever you need in the way of clothes to make yourself neat & comfortable you must get it.\'a0 Cloak of some kind I wish you to have, a bonnet either of drab stram, or any pretty kind children of your age wear, perhaps another dress.\'a0 Shoes, gloves &c.\'a0 A Silver Comb will be useful not only to you, but also to Fanny when you are done with it. And your Earrings you can have bored & buy Earrings.\'a0 Your money I expect will not be enough.\'a0 Your Papa wrote that it was all the change he had, & you could draw on him for more.\'a0 When you have made your purchases, write me word, & then I will write for a few things for myself & the children. I would like to know the price of a hat for Fanny either beaver or a bonnet.\'a0 Inquire the price of a dinner set of China for children.\'a0 Let me know how much a bracelet of hair could be made for, & a long chain & a short chain for the neck.\'a0 Your cousin Eliza beg[s] to let me know. I hope you will be a good girl, & return improved & benefitted, & pass your time pleasantly among friends.\'a0 Give my love to all of my Aunts, & particularly Aunt Eli\'85, Eliza & Susan.\'a0 Tell Aunt Eliza I am wondering why she has not written to me.\'a0 I expect she does not think my letters worth answering.\'a0 I write in such a hurry generally, that I am really ashamed to send my letters.\'a0 After writing to your Papa as I do every day, I am tired & hurried, for I am very busy now making clothes for the servants.\'a0 Your Aunt Susan is with me today, Annie & Fanny are playing about the room, & Hext as usual making a noise, & trying to break the window glass with a yd stick.\'a0 Poor little fellow.\'a0 I have not told your Papa because I knew it would make him so unhappy, more than he ought to be, but I will tell you that the other day I had a great fright about him.\'a0 He was at the wood pile, & Frank was cutting wood, & not seeing him behind him, raised his axe & struck him above his Eye, exactly across his Eyebrow.\'a0 He was brought in moaning, with his eye covered with blood, & I was afraid to look to see what injury was done, but the eye was not at all injured & Dr. Dean put Court plaster on the cut, & it is almost well.\'a0 I would have told your Papa, but he is so anxious about us all when he is away, that he would be needlessly made unhappy even miserable, & imagine the accident worse than it was, & perhaps even hasten home to see about it. I have written you a long letter.\'a0 Your Aunt is kind to have asked you to visit her, & you must behave yourself so as to not make her regret it.\'a0 If you can in any way make yourself useful to her you must Perform all of your duties.\'a0 Begin the day by praying to be kept from evil, & directed in the right way & reading in your Prayer book if it is only a few verses.\'a0 Give all of my messages to your Aunt & cousins, but I have written so hurriedly, I prefer their not \ul reading\ulnone  my letter.\'a0 Write me of everything that interests you, & of all of my friends. Your Grandmama stays constantly with your Aunt Annie who is very poorly.\'a0 Mr. Hopkins has returned.\'a0 Fanny speaks constantly of you, & wishes you would return with her Sugar dogs.\'a0 Annie & herself wish you to buy them a doll.\'a0 They have a great many wishes.\'a0 I must now close, in great haste.\'a0 Your attached Mother, E.F. Perry\
\'a0\
Anna Perry\
[Charleston]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 238\
Sunday, 2 oclock, 5 December 1852\
Greenville\'a0\'a0\'a0
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have come from church, eaten dinner & will now write to you.\'a0 I received a letter from you this morning dated Dec. 3rd.\'a0 Yesterday I did not hear, which disappointed me greatly.\'a0 But your todays letter pleases me, with the exception that you ought to \ul express\ulnone  a \ul wish\ulnone  to \ul be\ulnone  Governor, for if you \ul wished\ulnone  for \ul success,\ulnone  you would be apt to be successful, though personally you should do nothing, you should get some \ul friends\ulnone  to do for you.\'a0 I am certain if you let your \ul friends\ulnone  interest themselves for you you will be elected.\'a0 Either this, or if you fail here, an office from the President you \ul must\ulnone  have.\'a0 Judge I suppose you are not going to try for, though I would like that too. The letter you mention Mr. Keith would bring, Mr. Hopkins brought to the door.\'a0 I did not see him, but suppose Mr. Keith & himself had come in the Stage together, & Mr. Keith was hurried & begged Mr. Hopkins to deliver the letter.\'a0 Perhaps he did the same with your letter to the Patriot.\'a0 Mr. & Mrs. Elford leave tomorrow evening in the Stage.\'a0 I will write by them again to Anna.\'a0 They remain from one to three weeks in Charleston.\'a0 It will be a good opportunity for Anna to come back, but if she enjoys herself I am willing she should stay longer.\'a0 Mamma got a letter from Aunt Eliza yesterday.\'a0 In the beginning she expresses a wish that Anna may arrive that day with Judge Butler who was expected, says Sarah Taylor intended sending for Anna as soon as she heard of her arrival in Columbia, though very feeble, that Mr. Taylor was not in Columbia, & that Eloisa also intended to take charge of her.\'a0 Aunt Eliza said they were thankful Isaac Hayne was reelected , but were still anxious about the office that they were more immediately interested in.\'a0 At the close of the letter, Aunt Eliza says Anna has just arrived looking well & pretty, & she makes Anna sign her \ul name\ulnone  that \ul I\ulnone  may see it.\'a0 I am not worrying about servants.\'a0 When I wrote Eliza had been very impertinent, seated in the kitchen all the time cursing & swearing & abusing me to Becky, refusing to work for Reuben & Charles, & if she did making the clothes so that they \ul ripped \ulnone immediately, not letting Edward work for them & preventing Johnny doing anything for us.\'a0 I called in Becky & told her, Eliza she must not let sit in the kitchen & behave so, for it would make \ul her\ulnone  even disrespectful to me.\'a0 I told Eliza to go up & stay in her room, called Johnny in to wait, & my noticing her conduct has done good.\'a0 Johnny now comes in every day without being called, & I do not hear of Eliza\'92s speaking so impertinently.\'a0 I do think it is\'85to have a character like her in the yd.\'a0 She ruined Lindy, & will her children, but I hope so pious a person as Baylis & as I hope Becky is will soon counteract Eliza\'92s example.\'a0 Becky says she thinks Lindy & Edward are trying to be good.\'a0 Charles is delighted with her, says he does not hear himself cursed & abused as formerly, & gets plenty to eat, even say for to go to his supper.\'a0 I hope our yard will be happier & better now.\'a0 I dare say Becky has faults, & that I will find them out, but I think to be at the head of the servants, she will do much better than Minerva or Lindy.\'a0 I am not \ul worrying\ulnone , except about \ul honors\ulnone  for \ul you\ulnone , & your not \ul warmly\ulnone  \ul interesting\ulnone  yourself to get them, or getting your \ul friends\ulnone  to. I am glad you have become acquainted with Mr. Ravenel.\'a0 He is a \ul good\ulnone  man, an old friend of Mamma\'92s.\'a0 He is a \ul widower\ulnone  who has not \ul forgotten\ulnone  his \ul Wife\ulnone .\'a0 They were attached to each other as children, & she said if she died, she knew he would have to marry again, because he was so \ul domestic\ulnone  but he has not married.\'a0 He has no daughter, only sons.\'a0 His daughter in law keeps house for him.\'a0 One of his sons was engaged to Uncle Arthur\'92s daughter but died. I am pleased at Mr. Thompsons making you a present of boots.\'a0 Keep your money to pay your debts.\'a0 Dr. Irvine has not gone to Florida yet.\'a0 You must get the Black Dye for your Whiskers.\'a0 I think Mr. Cox\'92s at church this morning looked dyed. I am glad you made a good speech.\'a0 When published you must send it to me to read, & you must publish it in the Patriot.\'a0 I would like to have heard you deliver it.\'a0 How does Pinckney McBee come on.\'a0 How sad for Mr. Mauldin to be as he is.\'a0 How afflicted his family must be if true. As you were the originator of the Electoral bill, you ought to make a speech on it.\'a0 You ought to have introduced the bill this Session.\'a0 You must make Mr. Gladden pay you, & you ought to get Mr. Watts to \ul tell\ulnone  Mr. Williams that he ought to pay you the 500 & am surprised he has not paid it. The weather is so warm Mr. Hoke had better not buy any Hogs until it becomes colder.\'a0 We are eating the Beef still.\'a0 I will have one Cow & Calf brought home tomorrow & begin to use the Milk. Mrs. Genl Thompson I believe is not confined yet.\'a0 Mamma thinks she never will be, that it is a mistake, which sometimes happens.\'a0 I know of nothing new at all to tell you, except an Eclectic & the letter from Mr. Hamilton containing the second Check, nothing has come from the Mail for you. Mr. Elford will be in Columbia Tuesday night.\'a0 He told me he heard from you yesterday.\'a0 He came to let me know he was going & would take anything.\'a0 The bells for church are now ringing, & I must stop & get ready to go.\'a0Willie & Frank are going to ride on horseback.\'a0 Willie must in future go with you.\'a0 It improved & benefits him. Do my dear husband if it is only for \ul my\ulnone  \ul sake\ulnone , accept any honor that is offered you.\'a0 Do not decline beforehand as you always do.\'a0 Think what gratification it would give me to see \ul you\ulnone  who so well deserve it when no one deserves it so well as you.\'a0 Your Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 239\
5 December 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Anna\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Mamma received a letter from Aunt Eliza yesterday, in which at the close\'a0 she mentions your having just arrived, & to prove it she made you sign your name.\'a0 I was much gratified to see it, & to hear you had reached Charleston \ul safely\ulnone , for the late R. Road accidents made me uneasy.\'a0 I appreciate the kindness of your friends in Columbia, & also those in Charleston.\'a0 This visit will be long remembered by you, & afford an interesting subject of conversation for a long time.\'a0 We were all pleased with Aunt Eliza\'92s letter & grateful for the kindness of herself & others near to us. I was in hopes to have received a letter from you by the mornings Mail, but suppose you have not had time to write.\'a0 Mr. & Mrs. Elford leave tomorrow evening in the Stage for Charleston.\'a0 I will write by them, & send you a pr of pantalets & a veil you left & which you may find useful.\'a0 I will also send a bundle of my hair.\'a0 If your Medallion will be wo\'85 to a hair chain, you can have a chain made for yourself suitable for the purpose of getting your cousin Eliza to have it done.\'a0 With the hair that is left I wish a pretty chain made for \ul Willie \ulnone to wear with my watch.\'a0 I intend lending it to Willie.\'a0 If any is left have a chain made for Frank; if not enough for that, a bracelet to give to Fanny hereafter have as many things made out of the hair as it will admit, but I wish them all \ul pretty\ulnone , so if the hair will not allow of it, make only one or two of what I have mentioned.\'a0 These are presents for you to keep always in remembrance of me, & I leave it to your cousin Eliza\'92s taste & judgment to have the hair made in chains & bracelets as far as it will go.\'a0 \ul Read\ulnone  \ul this\ulnone  to \ul her\ulnone .\'a0 You can write to your Papa for what money is necessary.\'a0 Before you return I will write for several things.\'a0Mrs. Elford will be in town one, two or three weeks.\'a0 It will be a very good opportunity for you to return with her.\'a0 Mr. Elford will call & see you, & you may go & see Mrs. Elford.\'a0 Anything Aunt Eliza wishes sent up Mrs. Elford will bring.\'a0 In packing up again, you can put your clothes except your dresses & thick Sashes in the carpet bag & fill your trunk with what you buy.\'a0 I leave to your judgement to get what you need.\'a0 I hope you practice on the Piano, so as not to forget what you have learnt. Give my love to Aunt Mary & tell her she can now perform her promise & give you the Canary birds.\'a0 I would like very much you should have a pair.\'a0 I will help take care of them, & it would delight Fanny & Hext.\'a0 Give my love also to Aunt Anna. Give my love to my Aunts in Logan st.\'a0 Tell my Aunt Har\'85 she must answer my letter & beg my other Aunts also to write.\'a0 I am sorry you missed seeing Aunt Sarah Matthews. Each Aunt remember me kindly to & my friends generally.\'a0 Mrs. O\'92Driscoll you must not forget. When I told Fanny what Aunt Eliza wished she had gone down with you, she said, \'93I would be so glad, I would \ul scream \ulnone not to come back.\'94\'a0 She thinks her dollars you have will buy everything, a doll, & 7 Sugar dogs, a baby house furniture &c. Susan has been almost [every] day, & spent with me.\'a0 We work together, & Annie sometimes stays for the night, but she cries when bedtime comes.\'a0 Vardry & Alex come to the gate, but on account of the prohibitions they come no further. Luther has written to your Aunt Susy to return & says he will be willing to lose if she will return, & sends repeated messages.\'a0 Miss McBee wrote a note saying he was overwhelmed, & she did all she could to comfort him.\'a0 I got a letter from your Papa this morning.\'a0 He says he misses you a great deal, that you were a \ul great\ulnone  comfort to him that he likes always when from home, to have someone near to him he loves.\'a0 I am always better satisfied too to have one of the children with him, to contribute to his happiness, & to their improvement.\'a0 Another time Willie must go, as he used to.\'a0 I think he\'85a great deal, & is one reason why he has such general information; that it has been remarked, there was no subject mentioned, that he was not informed on.\'a0 I am sorry he did not go this time. Frank still goes to school.\'a0 All have holiday but him.\'a0 I am very busy making servants clothes & sewing up\'85for comfortables, which I find are more\'a0 reasonable than blankets.\'a0 I have been out very little since you left. Becky & her husband have prayer meeting every night in their room, which the servants with the exception of Eliza attend.\'a0 I hope there will be a reform in the yard.\'a0 It seems purer already.\'a0 Becky I hope by her example benefit them, more than precept alone can do. Mr. McKay has been prevented by a lame foot from going to town, & does not know when he can go.\'a0 Susan Hoke desired her love to you.\'a0 Said Augustus would go & see you.\'a0 Frank says you must write to him & he will write to you.\'a0 Fanny says you must bring her a head for her large doll.\'a0 The present head is broken.\'a0 She says you must bring her a set of furniture & a Cloak & hat.\'a0 I would like you to get a Worsted Cloak for both Fannie & Annie if they can be got of their sizes, & a hat & bonnet for Fanny.\'a0 If the Drab Beavers are not \ul very\ulnone  \ul dear\ulnone  & are worn, & you like them, perhaps one would be pretty, but I leave it to your taste & Eliza\'92s.\'a0 I wish a worsted Cloak & a hat for Hext.\'a0 Perhaps a Beaver would be pretty for him.\'a0I hope you are behaving well, & performing all of your duties, & never forget that hereafter an account is to be given of all our thoughts, words, & deeds, & that we must pray for help & strength to act\'85, & to\'85even as we ought to, for our hearts by nature are sinful & need a thorough change.\'a0 Give my kindest love to Aunt Eliza, El\'85 & Sue & W. Ed.\'a0 Write to me & believe me your attached Mother, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Anna Perry\
[Charleston]\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 240\
Monday morning, 11 oclock, 6 December 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have written to Eliza Hayne & Anna by Mr. Elford who goes this evening & I will now write to you.\'a0 My whole time now almost is taken up in writing. You said I might send you a bill of Groceries, so I have made out one which I think you had better give to Mr. Elford to get for us\'a0 at the same time he does for himself.\'a0 It is much better for someone to select them than to leave it to the Grocer.\'a0 I have lost a bill I intended to make it out by.\'a0 I have put down the necessaries, & only a few of the luxuries, not as many if it were summer.\'a0 In the Spring we can get more luxuries.\'a0 We have so many servants we use a great deal of Sugar, so what I have put down is not too much but you can make \ul any\ulnone  \ul alteration\ulnone  you wish.\'a0 We need a pr of fine dogs, a Fender Shovel & Tongs.\'a0 Perhaps Mr. Elford had better get them.\'a0 A \ul neat\ulnone  \ul set \ulnone will do, not the \ul handsomest\ulnone  do I care for.\'a0 Aunt Mary McCall has a box for Susan & myself.\'a0 Mr. Elford will either send it to you to bring, or send it by someone coming \ul before\ulnone  you do or bring it up himself, whichever is the \ul quickest\ulnone  way for we need the box now.\'a0 It contains the only dress I intend to buy for myself this winter, & a bonnet, & a few other things, which I stand in immediate use of.\'a0 I have written to Anna that if she wishes it, she can return with Mr. & Mrs. Elford, & save you going down for her, for you will be anxious to get home as soon as the Session is over, & \ul I\ulnone  would like to go down with you in the Spring.\'a0 I would like Anna to be in town a few weeks longer & not return as soon as you do.\'a0 Mr. Elford may return he says in 10 days, or may stay 3 weeks.\'a0 He will go & see Anna, & she will go & see Mrs. Elford.\'a0 Aunt Eliza wrote word that she had wished that Fanny was with Anna.\'a0 It was a pity Anna could not have been with Mrs. Martin sooner in Columbia, & not only the last day; Mrs. Martin intended to have her the whole time, or she & Sarah together have her.\'a0 Mrs. Martin borrowed a house ready furnished. No Mail came today, so of course would not hear from you, but I hope you wrote me a long letter yesterday & that I will get it tomorrow.\'a0 I think of the contents of one letter until I get another.\'a0 The letter yesterday I liked.\'a0 I do hope either the State or the Presidency will give you some Office.\'a0 If you \ul try\ulnone  you will get an Office, but you have to feel an \ul interest\ulnone  in it \ul yourself\ulnone , & get others also to interest themselves also. Edward mentioned at Mamma\'92s that Mr. Sam Mauldin was deranged & had taken Laudanum, because he thought his family all wished to get rid of him.\'a0 So I dare say there is some truth in the rumour you heard. I have not heard from Anna since you mentioned you had seen her off.\'a0 I hope to hear soon from her & also about her from Aunt Eliza, who I am sure will write.\'a0 I dare say she will need more money. This is Sale Day.\'a0 I do not know if many persons are in.\'a0 Mr. Hoke has not bought the Hogs yet.\'a0 The weather is mild & cheerful now.\'a0\'a0\'a0 We are all well.\'a0 Lindy\'92s baby is improving.\'a0 She has more time to attend to it, than she used to have.\'a0 When the child gets older we will not need both Charlotte & Lindy.\'a0 I wish Johnny would be put to some trade at once. But I suppose if Eliza\'92s child lives, he will have to mind that.\'a0In these holidays Willie has so little to improve him I wish he was with you.\'a0 In future he always shall go down with you.\'a0 It improved him to associate with gentlemen. I believe I have nothing new to write you.\'a0 I wrote yesterday except the Patriot I have not seen a single paper since you left.\'a0 I have rode out 3 times, & paid not a single visit.\'a0 I am busy all the time at home.\'a0 I will write again tomorrow.\'a0 After hearing from you I have more to write about. I hope the Secessionists will run you for Governor, vote for you & elect you.\'a0 If I were with you, to have urged your acceptance when they first proposed it to you there would have been no difficulty.\'a0 Your attached Wife, E.F. Perry I enclose the Grocery bill & added a few things I wish Mr. Elford to get, but you can leave out anything you think best, & make any alterations.\'a0 The Calico is for comfortable.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 241\
6 December 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Anna\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I wrote a long letter to you yesterday, & have just written to Eliza, so can write you only a few lines.\'a0 I send you a veil & a pr of pantalets that I forgot to put up for you, & which you may even now find useful.\'a0 I am anxious to hear how you are, & how you feel, in the \ul City\ulnone , away from those you have always been with from your birth.\'a0 While in Columbia with your Papa, were not seeing him, you knew he was not far off, & did not feel lonely, but now you are even without him.\'a0 I am afraid you feel strangely.\'a0 I dare say by this time however you begin to feel at home, & are passing your time quite pleasantly, & surrounded by so many to whom you can claim relationship, gives you a home feeling.\'a0 I hope to hear a good account of you.\'a0 I would like to know what you have bought for yourself, that I may then determine what other things to get.\'a0 The silver comb if not too dear you must get.\'a0 I suppose one would be got for 3 or 4 dollars & it will last always, will be useful to Fanny after you are done with it.\'a0 Just before you leave I will write for a few presents for Christmas.\'a0 It will be cheaper buying them in town than here, particularly the Candy.\'a0 Mr. & Mrs. Elford will remain in town one two or three weeks.\'a0 That will be only a little longer than you & Papa will be in Columbia.\'a0 He will be anxious to get home as soon as the Legislature adjourns, & I would be glad for him to be saved the trip to Charleston, so you can if you like it return with Mr. Elford.\'a0 I am certain there will be opportunities constantly offering.\'a0 The Gradys I believe go down with him. It is reported that Mr. Sam Mauldin is quite melancholy & took Laudanum to destroy himself under the idea that his family wished to get rid of him.\'a0 How sad for his wife & children to have him in that state. You must go & see Mrs. Elford if you can & Mary Crayton if she is in town.\'a0 Be a good girl. I am going to have some Ginger nuts made for you, to remind you of home, & send by Mr. Elford if they are nice.\'a0 If you do not receive them, you will know they were not made well enough to send.\'a0 Mr. Elford will send or bring anything.\'a0 Buy the\'85for Becky, & some little present for each servant.\'a0 Inquire the price of dolls ready dressed for Fanny & Annie, & also dolls not dressed.\'a0Be a good girl.\'a0 Mr. Wardel is today fixing the peice to the Piano, Mr. Bacon spoke of.\'a0 Your affectionate Mother, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Anna Perry\
[Charleston]\
\'a0\

