\fs29\fsmilli14667 \nosupersub  so it must have had delay by the rail road accidents.\'a0 My [letter] ought to have got to you sooner than it did.\'a0 There are a great many accidents occurring at the present time, on the railroad.\'a0 I am very glad that I got down safely, & hope to get back safely also.\'a0 I am sorry that you were kept so anxious about me.\'a0 I do not think that I am worthy of so much love, but will try to be so.\'a0 If I had thought that you would be so anxious, I would have written the very evening that I arrived.\'a0 It was very late when I arrived, though no accident occurred.\'a0 I forgot to ask you for the carpetbag key before I left although I was thinking about it all of the time.\'a0 If you have an opportunity of sending it down, I would be very glad.\'a0 I hope your arm is better and that will be perfectly well when we return to Greenville.\'a0 I think those young ladies that you spoke about in your letter did not have much manners to be so noisy as that but I hope they will not annoy you so again.\'a0\'a0 When I was in Columbia I enjoyed myself quite well, but you and Mama both seem to think that I did not.\'a0 I enjoyed myself exceedingly well, and hope that I did not give you much trouble.\'a0 I enjoy myself here exceedingly well also and hope that you are enjoying yourself also.\'a0 I do not think that yours is much enjoyment for you have to attend to your business.\'a0 I am sorry that you feel lonely but I suppose as you are at the Statehouse all day you will not find much time to feel lonely.\'a0 You must write to me if you can find time\'a0 but I expect that all the time you have to spare you will write to Mama.\'a0 I think I would rather you come down after me if it would suit you.\'a0 I do not think that Mr. Trimmier will go up for two weeks to come but I will go to see him and see when he is going up, but I would rather you come down for me.\'a0 I am sorry to ask you for a little more money but if you have not got it do not worry yourself about it.\'a0 Though I have not spent all that you gave me yet I expect it will go, but if it does not go I will\'a0 give you back what is over.\'a0 I have not bought all of my clothes yet 10 dol[lars] would be enough.\'a0 I think I have been visiting my aunts almost every day.\'a0 I have been to see all but one.\'a0 I would write you a longer letter but I am going to dine at Anna Turnbull\'92s today and will have to stop to get ready.\'a0 This is a very long letter.\'a0 If you have time to write me only six lines I would be glad but if you have not time I will not mind it.\'a0 I hope you will continue well.\'a0 Tell all of Mr. Janney\'92s little girls howdye for me.\'a0 Your affectionate Daughter, Anna P.S. All of aunt Eliza\'92s family are well.\'a0 Aunt Eliza thanks you & mama for letting me come down and begs to be remembered.\
