9 oclock, Tuesday morning, 7 December 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received two letters from you this morning. & one from Anna which I will enclose to you.\'a0 I was glad to see the one Anna wrote you.\'a0 I was reading your letter aloud to Willie but when I got in the \ul midst\ulnone  of the \ul scold\ulnone , I stopped \ul horror\ulnone  \ul struck\ulnone , merely glanced at it, went into the rest of the letter, & have not read the scold yet.\'a0 When you know it is my \ul love\ulnone  for \ul you\ulnone , my \ul exalted\ulnone  \ul opinion\ulnone  of your \ul character\ulnone  that is my opinion you surpass even the \'93Father of his Country\'94 that is \ul this\ulnone  \ul feeling\ulnone  that makes me dissatisfied . that you who are so far \ul above\ulnone  others have not received the rewards & honors, that your \ul inferiors\ulnone  have.\'a0 You ought not to \ul scold\ulnone  me, but \ul sympathize\ulnone  with & try & \ul gratify\ulnone  me.\'a0 I must say with the exception of \ul scolding\ulnone  you \ul wife\ulnone  now & then, you are the best \ul husband\ulnone  that ever was.\'a0 You have retained more of the spirit of a \ul Lover\ulnone , than husbands generally do.\'a0 I feel that I am \ul first\ulnone  in your \ul heart\ulnone , & perhaps if I were not quite so confident, it would be better for you, for if I were not, I would be more careful to retain your heart & perhaps would never dare to resort\'a0 to scolding, but now I am so well satisfied of your love, that I try it as I please. My dear husband if you had been in Congress, you would have been the admiration of the United States, & I believe you would then have aspired even to the Presidential Chair, but now what can you attain to nothing at all, & will be never more than a Member of the Legislature, & a Village Lawyer toiling for meat & clothes for his family.\'a0 This is beneath your deserts, your fellow men know it, & therefore they \ul talk\ulnone  of elevating you, but never do, & I cannot help being provoked, but I \ul wont\ulnone  be \ul again\ulnone .\'a0 I will \ul live\ulnone  on \ul hope\ulnone .\'a0 I like Mr. Morgans feeling, & wish the people of Greenville would have heard you.\'a0 You are so well fitted to serve & benefit them, which is the reason I feel grieved when you hint at abandoning your present position.\'a0 You are by nature meant to serve your fellow\'85, Frank Pierces\'92s destiny was meant to be yours, somehow a mistake has been made, & you have not fulfilled your destiny, & I am afraid it is marrying that has prevented it.\'a0 It is the single men that are advanced most easily,\'a0 Mr. King for instance the Vice President.  Last Sunday in church I looked at some of the Wives, & I thought to myself, none have such a husband as I have.\'a0 Mrs. Choice looked so cross & unhappy.\'a0 Mrs. Arthur looked vexed & strange.\'a0 Mrs. Butler Thompson they say has trouble with her husband; Susan at my side had so little to make her happy.\'a0 Mrs. Car\'85 husband & indeed all so different from you.\'a0 It is your \ul superiority\ulnone  that has made me repine.\'a0 I wish you in an enlarged sphere, known & appreciated.\'a0 If you would have been in a City & constantly associated with minds on an equality with your own, you would be \ul happier\ulnone .\'a0 You will call this scolding, but you have brought it forth by \ul scolding\ulnone  \ul me\ulnone .\'a0 Mr. Sam Mauldins condition is truly sad.\'a0 I do not think he ought to have been left in the Asylum against his wishes.\'a0 If he is so miserable, even as to destroy himself, he would not be accountable for the act.\'a0 He could be guarded & go at large.\'a0 It seems so sad, to have him in the Asylum, when he is as \ul conscious\ulnone  as he is now.\'a0 He ought to be confined in a room in his own house.\'a0 If he recovers it will make him miserable to think where he has been.\'a0 I am sorry for his Wife & children.\'a0 Mrs. Bollings daughter (Mrs. Childs) Mrs. Westfield told Ann was perfectly derange