\f1\b 245\
Thursday, 1 oclock, 9 December 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received a letter from you today, for which I am very thankful, for yesterday I did not hear & was getting uneasy.\'a0 I am pleased at your being made the heroe of the Poem at College Commencement.\'a0 You must get a copy of it for me to read, & publish it in the Patriot. I am sorry for poor Mr. Mauldin.\'a0 Is he really deranged or miserable from taking opium.\'a0 He seems too conscious to be altogether deranged & to be out in the Asylum. But I may be mistaken.\'a0 An old lady named Mrs. Wiliams who sells Butter was here yesterday & seemed to think that the whole family drank, says the Father was a dreadful man, & never drew a sober breath, & at last shot himself, that several brothers killed themselves drinking, & insinuating that all the brothers living drank, but I think this latter suspicion is not true, so only mention it to you.\'a0 Mr. Easley was to have been married last night to Miss Sloan of Pendleton.\'a0 I hope he will now have trouble enough at home to keep him from troubling others.\'a0 Mr. Joab Mauldin is to be married tonight. The Collegiates must have acted very badly at the Commencement ball.\'a0 The Ladies were not rewarded for going so far to attend a Ball. Mrs. Barclay was rather forward I think.\'a0 I heard Mr. Barclay had left her, & she had to take in work.\'a0 I did not know he was dead.\'a0 She is a northern lady.\'a0I received a letter from Anna today.\'a0 She is well & enjoying herself very much she says.\'a0 I wrote to Aunt Eliza that Mr. Elford would be a good opportunity for her to come up, that she would be long enough in town to see all her friends, & not too long to inconvenience her.\'a0 Aunt Eliza\'92s letter about her was gratifying.\'a0 Aunt Anna Turnbull wrote word that Anna was so much altered & improved since her former visit, that if she had entered the room alone, she would not have recognized her, that she thought her quite pretty, & she was sociable. Last night it commenced raining, & today is gloomy & drizzling.\'a0 I rode to Mrs. Stokes yesterday to know if she had engaged her Butter to me, as her servant had said, & Mrs. Stokes said yes.\'a0 The road was so bad.\'a0 I thought of your journey home, & I am afraid you will find the roads after so much rain dreadful.\'a0 You must consider whether it will be best for you to come in the Stage or have the carri[a]ge sent for you.\'a0 If you come in the carri[a]ge you had best if you have heavy baggage send it in the Stage to make the load lighter for the horses.\'a0 If you feel \ul quite\ulnone  \ul well\ulnone , the Stage journey perhaps will be best.\'a0 You will come \ul quicker\ulnone  & save your horses, which the bad roads may injure, as they have heretofore.\'a0My dear husband I think with you that our happiness depends a good deal on ourselves, but some persons have much more to make them happy than others.\'a0 I don\'92t think Mrs. Mauldin now can be happy.\'a0 We who are so blessed in each other, may talk of happiness, but I can mention numbers who I should think were only miserable.  Frank at last has holiday.\'a0 His school broke up yesterday.\'a0 Willie & himself cut wood, not a very \ul elevating\ulnone  employment, but very useful.\'a0 Fanny & Hext are quite well.\'a0 Mr. Lasly paid me a visit yesterday to consult about his house, says he will finish planting Wheat, cut logs, & commence raising the house when you return.\'a0 Dinner is now ready, so I will have to stop. I was very busy, so could not write as soon as usual.\'a0 I will write again tomorrow, & hope to hear from you again.\'a0 I want if possible to write to Anna after dinner. I know of no news to tell you.\'a0 I read the Patriot yesterday, was sorry you had not written on to a later date, later than you had written to me.\'a0 I think the last anecdote might have been left out, but perhaps it would please some tastes.\'a0I have now done dinner.\'a0 Becky this far does well, works well, & makes the servants happy.\'a0 I hope we will find her a comfort.\'a0 The prayer meetings I hope will have a good influence on the servants.\'a0 I have not time to read over my letter.\'a0 I am so anxious to send it to the Post office in time.\'a0 Yours truly, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 246\
Thursday afternoon, 9 December 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Anna\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received your letter this morning, & was very much pleased to hear from you.\'a0 I would like to write you a long letter, but I have not time now.\'a0 I have been writing to your Papa, & your Grandmama,\'a0 Aunt Susy, Aunt Annie, Fanny & Annie are all in the room, & I cannot collect my ideas well.\'a0 Your Aunt Susy & Annie have .been spending several days & nights with me, & your Grandmama & Aunt Ann come in for the day.\'a0 They as well as myself are gratified to hear that you are behaving well, enjoying yourself, & kindly received by your friends.\'a0 Opportunities are constantly offering up, I expect, so exercise your own wishes about coming back.\'a0 If it is more convenient for you to return \ul before\ulnone  Mr. Elford does, you must. I leave it to you & to Aunt Eliza whose hospitality you must not impose upon.\'a0 Your Papa in his letter today says you must suit your pleasure about returning, & your friends, that it will make no difference to him, if Mr. Elford does not stay longer than he told me he would.\'a0 He seems a good person for you to come back with, but I wish you to do as you & your Aunt think best. I wish you had written me a list of what you had bought, & the prices.\'a0 I was waiting for that to decide what to get myself.\'a0 A small pair of Cuff pins perhaps you had best get, two pr of Gaiters for yourself.\'a0 Have you bought a bonnet? & what kind?\'a0 A dress & the Silver Comb, what is the price of the Comb.\'a0 I wish particularly to know.\'a0 Buy a Cornelian ring for Fanny & Annie such as Fanny had & Mary lost.\'a0 Tell me the price of a bonnet such as little girls of her age wear & a cloak of some kind & a hat & Cloak for Hext such as the old one he wears of Franks, or any other kind.\'a0 I wish some Stockings for Hext & Fanny, two pr of \'85for me to wear in the house, two pr of undersleeves for me to wear to church, two aprons for myself, a pr of Gaiter boots for Fanny, & gloves, but these things I would rather know the price first, before I decide to get them.\'a0 A dress for Fanny to wear to church also I wish, & if you can bring any pretty patterns of Aprons & Sashes for Fanny & Hext you must, & any pretty apron you see for yourself, or Sashe or Sun bonnet & either buy & have made for yourself or bring the patterns; a waist apron if you wish it get.\'a0 When you return home for a long time now, you will need to buy nothing more.\'a0 You will be well supplied for an age to come.\'a0 I am thankful that your Aunt is pleased with your deportment.\'a0 Continue to act as you have done, & when you return set a good example to your brothers & sister. Give my love to Aunt Eliza, El\'85 & Wm Ed.\'a0 Write to me & beg Aunt Eliza & El\'85 also to.\'a0 Your Grandmama & Aunts send their love, & say you will have a great deal to tell on your return.\'a0 I write in great haste.\'a0 Excuse all mistakes & bad writing, & write better than I do.\'a0 Do not follow my example.\'a0 I write every day to your Papa which fatigues me &\'85is talking in the room now, which confuses me.\'a0 Give my love to all of my Aunts & friends, & beg Aunt Mary for the Canary birds. Be a good girl.\'a0 You have a great deal to be thankful for.\'a0 Not many little girls have had such an enjoyment as you have at present.\'a0 It was kind in your Aunt to invite you to stay with her.\'a0 Do not forget to get a present of some kind for your Aunt, to remember you by; one according to your means, & something for Eliza & Sue.\'a0 Your affectionate Mother, E.F.P. P.S. Give Mamma Susan & Anna love to all.\'a0 I will write you about the Candy & Cocoa next week, & also all I wish got.\'a0 I would like to hear the price of what I have mentioned first, but if I if I do not hear soon, will not wait. Your Aunt Susan wishes two aprons of plaid Alpaca or such as your cousin Susan says are worn & a peice of black silk braid to sew round a skirt.\'a0 She wishes strings for the apron.\
\'a0\
Anna Perry\
[Charleston]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 247\
Friday, 1 oclock. 10 December 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have received \ul no\ulnone  letter from you today.\'a0 Nothing has come from the Post office today.\'a0 So I will write you only a few lines.\'a0 I am disappointed at not hearing, but hope you were too busy to write, that you are quite well.\'a0 Mr. Hoke today is to buy the Hogs.\'a0 There is a fine drove in the village, & he says not many more fine ones will come.\'a0 You must write now whether the carri[a]ge must be sent for you, or whether you will come in the Stage.\'a0 If it were not for bad \ul roads\ulnone , the carri]a]ge would be the pleasantest, but you will know best.\'a0 I hope to hear tomorrow.\'a0 I am very busy working.\'a0 All are well except Charles who in bad weather has Asthma.\'a0 The weather is still bad, cloudy & drizzly.\'a0 I have no news to tell you.\'a0 I write so often I have not missed a single Mail. I wrote to Anna yesterday, & will again tomorrow.\'a0 We get along quite well, & am glad you are at a pleasant Hotel. The Legislature adjourns too soon to get through with the business.\'a0 You ought to postpone it, so as to pass all your important bills.\'a0 A few days longer, so much could be done.\'a0 Those who are in such a hurry should stay at home. I hope we will have good weather so as to clean the house before you return.\'a0 I must now conclude.\'a0 I think of you constantly.\'a0 Your affectionate Wife, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Benjamin Perry\
[Columbia]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 248\
Saturday night, 11 December 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received a letter about an hour ago from you.\'a0 A Servant brought it to the door & said, \'93Mr. Jones sends his respects, & sends you this letter.\'94\'a0 I took it & said nothing.\'a0 I knew \ul he\ulnone  had not brought it from \ul you\ulnone  that someone else had brought it, & begged him perhaps to send it to me.\'a0 In your letter you say \ul Dr.\ulnone  \ul Pasley\ulnone  will bring it.\'a0 I did not hear from you yesterday, nor today.\'a0 I mean this morning, no Mail it was said came from beyond Newberry, so I was glad to get the letter this evening.\'a0 I wish you had enclosed Anna\'92s to me.\'a0 She writes such short letters.\'a0 I would like to see all she writes to you.\'a0 Not being accustomed to writing, she finds it difficult to express herself & tell all I wish to hear, but what she does write, she writes well.\'a0 Aunt Eliza\'92s letter was very satisfactory, & she is fastidious & particular. & expects a good deal even from children.\'a0 So approbation from \ul her\ulnone  is worth something.\'a0 This has been a fine day.\'a0 It is getting cold, & by Monday I hope will be good weather to kill hogs.\'a0 Mr. Hoke yesterday bought 10 for you weighing 2306 pounds, some of them about 200 weight, & some a good deal more, but on an average 230 pounds.\'a0 All say it is the cheapest way of getting meat, & everybody seems to have bought.\'a0 Mr. Lasly came today to offer to help kill.\'a0 He & his sons, & offered his daughter to help clean & attend to stuffing Sausages, so we will get assistance from him.\'a0 He says he will be here Monday at daylight.\'a0 We are out of lard so I am very glad to have some soon.\'a0 Lard is selling 15 cts a pd.\'a0Charles has been suffering with Asthma, but is getting better & expects to be well Monday.\'a0 I told Becky to attend to him.\'a0 She said, \'93it was her duty to attend to Charles, for he was a good old man.\'94\'a0 So this shows her to be better disposed than some of our other servants.\'a0 The servants all seem happy now, & they respect Becky. & do not quarrel & abuse each other as they did.\'a0 Even Lindy\'92s child is beginning to thrive.\'a0 There is no complaint of not having enough to eat.\'a0 I dare say in consequence, that the eating will \ul cost\ulnone  a great deal more than heretofore, but I know you will not object.\'a0 Susan this week spent several days & nights with me.\'a0 It was quite unexpected.\'a0 She came in to pass the day, & I felt so sorry for her, & knew it would be a relief to Ann to have her away, that I told her to stay for the night.\'a0 She, Annie, & Susy, so she staid three or four nights, & went back to Mamma\'92s this morning to see Vardry & Alex.\'a0 Mamma & Ann have dined with me three days so I have not been lonely this week.\'a0 I feel so sorry for Susan.\'a0 She has had a hard fate.\'a0 She is sensitive & ill fitted to endure the trials she had.\'a0 If she had been differently constituted perhaps she might, but as it is, I know of no one more to be pitied.\'a0 She said she enjoyed being with me, that I had everything to make me happy, that if it were not sinful, one might almost be envious of me.\'a0 When I think that it was just something in my person & manners that struck \ul an\ulnone  old \ul Bachelors\ulnone  \ul fancy\ulnone , I realize how accidental our fates in life are. Susan has helped me a great deal in my work.\'a0 I have been trying to make the house look more comfortable, particularly the two rooms where we sit for the winter.\'a0 I have had them whitewashed & new curtains put up.\'a0 The Sofa Mr. Wardell has finished looks very comfortable.\'a0 It will suit you exactly to lounge on these winter evenings.\'a0 The new Carpet on the Staircase & Entry looks very pretty.\'a0 These improvements were so unexpected.\'a0 My money has not held out, but as Minerva\'92s wages this year I have spent for you.\'a0 I know you will not begrudge returning as much of that money as I need.\'a0 Another year Minerva\'92s wages will appropriate expressly for my clothes & to buy things for the house I wish, & you do not care for.\'a0 This year I have spent it for every purpose but myself.\'a0 In Jan[uar]y you will receive Bank Interest which will help you to pay your debts.  Mr. Arthur came to see me yesterday.\'a0 He inquired after you.\'a0 He says he went down on the R[ail] Road with Col. Dawkins last summer I think, & he was drunk the whole time.\'a0 His bold, vain aspiring Northern Wife I dare say has made him miserable.\'a0 She does not love him for himself, & therefore she wishes to gratify his vanity, that he should have honors & distinctions.\'a0 She has met with \ul more\ulnone  than her \ul deserts\ulnone  in marrying him & therefore she ought to be satisfied.\'a0 She ought to think that she was once a Music Teacher working for her bread, & now she has an independent fortune.\'a0 The bench must have been little in demand, so \ul few\ulnone  Candidates, & such \ul inferior\ulnone  ones.\'a0 I believe truly \ul you\ulnone  would have been elected.\'a0 The State is beginning to \ul appreciate\ulnone  you; if it does not, I hope the \ul President\ulnone  will.  Genl Thompson today sent for your office key to look at a\'85this afternoon.\'a0 I went to the office to shut it, & I saw Rices Digest open at a page relating to property given to children.\'a0 Mrs. Thompson is not confined yet.\'a0 I hope she will not be disappointed.\'a0 Perhaps the Legislature will not adjourn the 15
