\fs29\fsmilli14667 \nosupersub .\'a0 I almost wish you were coming in the Stage.\'a0 I am afraid the roads are so bad you will find the travelling in the carri[a]ge tedious, & the horses will get injured.\'a0 Mr. Elford would have gone down in his carri[a]ge but for the roads.\'a0 I do not wish you to follow my advice, \ul contrary\ulnone  to your judgement, but I wish you to inquire on the subject, & find out whether the Stage with the night traveling, or the carri[a]ge & horses with the risk of injuring horses is best, or whether the road from Cokesbury or from Laurens is best.\'a0 Mr. Arthur says the road from Cokesbury \ul generally\ulnone  travelled is \ul very\ulnone  \ul bad\ulnone , that there is a more private one that is better.\'a0 The Mails are so irregular.\'a0 I hope the letter in which you \ul tell\ulnone  me, how you have determined to come, will come directly to hand without any delay.\'a0 If it does not, it will be bad.\'a0 Only twice however the Mails have failed, though several times I have received no letter, but I suppose you did not write.  Except to hear \ul you\ulnone  \ul speak\ulnone , I would not care to be in Columbia during the Session.\'a0 The weather is so unpleasant, & the house so filled with ladies all seeking pleasure, but I think I will go next winter to hear you speak.\'a0 This Spring I would like to go to Charleston, when you go to Columbia, & if we are out of debt & have plenty of money, this summer we can go to the North.\'a0 You must send me a copy of your speech, \'93the Speech of the Session.\'94\'a0 I will read it with more interest now in your absence than when you are with me.\'a0 I hope you will soon have it published in the Patriot. I thought Anna would have to send for more money.\'a0 She will not have to buy anything again for a long time.\'a0 Going away from home, the softer sex require so many things to make them neat & comfortable, that they can at home do without, that it makes it quite expensive, but she is well fitted up & will need nothing more for some time.\'a0 I thought she would send for more than 10 dollars. Fanny says she longs for you to come back, but after you come back she will be sorry.\'a0 I asked her why.\'a0 She said because she would have to go \ul out\ulnone  of \ul my\ulnone  room, & sleep in the big room.\'a0 She already says Anna when she comes back must go up to bed with her after supper.\'a0Hext is well, & when I ask where Papa is, holds up his hand as if to say \ul gone\ulnone .\'a0 Willie & frank are well.\'a0 I have rode out three times, & been to church each Sunday, the rest of the time busy at home. I hope to hear tomorrow, if so I will write more.\'a0 You ought to have told me what you thought of the Grocery bill.\'a0 At this moment I hear the singing in Becky\'92s room.\'a0 Mr. Arthur says he does not approve of it.\'a0 I am sure I do, & hope it will bring religion near to the servants, make them feel its importance, & lead them in the way they should go.\
