My dear husband.\'a0 The Mail this morning came very late, owing I suppose to the bad roads, to my \ul great\ulnone  \ul disappointment\ulnone  \ul no\ulnone  \ul letter\ulnone  has come from \ul you\ulnone .\'a0 One from Anna, & one from Aunt Mary McCall I received.\'a0 I think you must have written, but the Post master in Columbia has neglected sending it.\'a0 Tomorrow no Stage comes, so I cannot hear until Tuesday, & if you then write for the carri[a]ge, it may be too late for it to meet you.\'a0 Mr. Hoke says he thinks\'a0 the roads are too bad for a carri[a]ge to get along at all.\'a0 I wish you to come the way you prefer, but I hope you will come in the Stage.\'a0 It seems to me that will be the best way on account of the roads both for you & the horses, but if you write for the carri[a]ge I will send it, if the letter comes in time.\'a0 I am going after church to dine at Mamma\'92s so have to write to you now.\'a0 I am so sorry I did not hear from you.\'a0 I am afraid you were spending your evening so pleasantly with some of those bold ladies, it made you forget your Wife; perhaps Becky Sharpe you got introduced to. I have written to Mr. Elford to buy us a set of common knives for every day use.\'a0 Our old knives are lost & worn out, & the new set is too handsome for every day, & would soon get ruined, a common Butter knife I also begged him to get.\'a0 You\'a0 must bring us \ul nothing\ulnone  \ul at\ulnone  \ul all\ulnone .\'a0 Anna will bring us something.\'a0 Charleston is a cheaper place than Columbia.\'a0 The little things you get for the childrenare expensive & useless, so bring back nothing but \ul yourself\ulnone .\'a0 I must write to Anna now.\'a0 She says she enjoys herself \ul more\ulnone  than she expected, & that she will come up with Mr. & Mrs. Elford, & that \ul I\ulnone  must write & tell \ul you\ulnone  so that I can make you understand better than she can, that she is not to go to Columbia & meet you, & come up with you, but she will come \ul all\ulnone  the \ul way\ulnone  \ul up\ulnone  with Mr. & Mrs. Elford. I hope you will be careful on the R Road & take a safe scarf & wrap yourself up warm. I will now conclude.\'a0 I remain Your affectionate Wife, E.F. Perry I am glad you now like my letters.\'a0 \ul I\ulnone  like \ul you\ulnone  cannot bear to be \ul scolded\ulnone , especially by a husband.\'a0 The next time you begin, I will call in one of the servants & let you finish on one who \ul deserves \ulnone it.\'a0 But you think you are so certain of my \ul heart\ulnone , you can \ul impose\ulnone  on it, but you must not venture too far. If I had heard from you this morning I could have written you another sheet.\'a0 Now I have nothing more to write about, except to add I love you.\'a0 E.F.P. Anna\'92s letter today was a long one, a whole sheet.\
