\'a0\
My dear husband\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I had written a long letter & sent it to the Post office & wrote I had \ul not\ulnone  heard from you, when Mr. Beattie sent me \ul two\ulnone  letters.\'a0 I can now only acknowledge them, for I expect Susan every moment to come from church & carry me to Mamma\'92s\'85I now hear the carri[a]ge. I know the sugar was more than we use, but it is economy to get a large quantity at \ul one\ulnone  \ul time\ulnone .\'a0 The barrels & commissions cost as much if they are \ul small\ulnone , as if they are large.\'a0 I thought & knew the Sugar would not last more than a year.\'a0 We have 14 servants.\'a0 We use more than a pound of Brown Sugar every day for them, more than a pound of white for ourTea & Coffee each day.\'a0 The loaf Sugar was for company, the Clarified for cake, the powdered for icing.\'a0 This was the reason there was such a variety. Susan has come & gone, & I must now get ready, for when the carri[a]ge comes back.\'a0 I will write again tomorrow.\'a0Mr. Brown was not the Soul of Honour as I had thought.\'a0 I am glad you are coming up with Mr. Duncan, but think you would find it pleasanter on account of the bad roads to come in the Stage.\'a0 Yours truly, E.F.P.\
