\f1\b 255\
Wednesday, 11 oclock, 16 December 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Anna\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received a letter from you this morning, & also one from Eliza.\'a0 I received one from your Papa.\'a0 He leaves Columbia tomorrow morning, so I am not to write to him again & will be able now to write longer letters to you.\'a0 I am glad you are still enjoying yourself.\'a0 If you do not come home by Christmas, you will lose \ul nothing\ulnone , for you know at that time the servants having \ul holiday\ulnone , we live in \ul less\ulnone  \ul comfort\ulnone  than any other part of the year.\'a0 It reminds me of the way we are living at \ul present\ulnone .\'a0 This week Mr. Hoke bought some hogs for us, which have been killed, & instead of living in \ul abundance\ulnone  as one would think, we almost starve, & have our meals \ul irregular\ulnone , all the servants being engaged drying Lard, cutting up Sausage meat, cleaning feet, stuffing sausages &c, that they have no time to attend to us, so busy preparing for our \ul future\ulnone  comfort.\'a0 Susan Hoke said she would write to Augustus to call & see you, but as you have not mentioned him, I suppose you have not seen him.\'a0 She sends over to know if you mention him in your letters, for they were uneasy not having heard from him.\'a0 Fanny Hoke is quite sick with Measles & Scarletina. Perhaps you heard that Mr. Sam Mauldin was carried down to Columbia & put in the Lunatic Asylum.\'a0 He attempted several times to kill himself.\'a0 He took Laudanum in Greenville, going down he attempted to jump out of the Cars & when left in the Asylum, tried to beat his brains out.\'a0 He eats Opium which is worse than drink.\'a0 How sad for his Wife & family.\'a0 James Benson is married to a Lady in Abbeville. Mr. Wm Easely is married to Miss Sloan of Pendleton\'a0\'a0 Mr. Joab Mauldin is married to Miss McIver.\'a0 Mrs. Mims Sister Mrs. Genl Hampton has a Son.\'a0 This is all the Greenville news I know of to tell you.\'a0Frank commenced a letter to you, but I saw it would take so long to finish it, I told him he might stop.\'a0 Willie is generally busy reading, cutting & hauling wood, & as I write so often, he thinks he would have nothing to tell you.\'a0 Hext is quite well & when I ask where Anna is, holds up his hand, as if to say \ul gone\ulnone .\'a0 Fanny speaks often of you & calls you \ul my\ulnone  \ul sister\ulnone .\'a0 She longs for Papa & Sister to come back, & then adds, I will be \ul sorry\ulnone  too, & when I ask why says because I will have to go out of Mamma\'92s room & sleep with Anna.\'a0 Now I go upstairs & sit with her at night.\'a0 Then she thinks \ul that\ulnone  will be put a stop to, so she feels quite divided.\'a0 She wishes though she had gone to town with you, & says I ought to have let her.\'a0 I did not think of it, but the weather has been so bad ever since you left, that I think this is the very worst time to leave home for \ul enjoyment\ulnone .\'a0 The \ul Spring\ulnone  is much pleasanter & is always the time \ul I\ulnone  will choose.\'a0I am glad Uncle Arthur & all of your friends are so affectionate & enquire after us all so kindly.\'a0 They are kind to you not only for \ul your\ulnone  \ul sake\ulnone  & \ul mine\ulnone , but for your \ul Grandmama\ulnone  whom they all love.\'a0 You must go to see all of her \ul old\ulnone  \ul friends\ulnone .\'a0 I often wish \ul she \ulnone would see them once more.\'a0 I know she must miss their friendship & society.\'a0 You must buy a present for each servant.\'a0 I wish this Christmas to give each of the grown servants a Bible.\'a0 Reuben, Eliza & Becky I think can read.\'a0\'a0 Charles, Lindy, Mary, Edward & Clara can bring theirs to me or you at any time to read to them.\'a0 8 Bibles plain ones I will have to get.\'a0 If Eliza could get reasonable ones in Charleston, & have them packed in the box she is to send, I would like it, but if she thinks it will take up too much room, I will get them here from Mr. Elfords book store.\'a0 A prayer book get for yourself & one for Willie, a \ul neat\ulnone  \ul plain\ulnone  \ul one\ulnone  for him, of a convenient size to put in his pocket. Becky\'92s comb you must not forget & some little present for Ninny, Lucinda, John & each of our servants, either a handkerchief, apron, or something pretty if you prefer it, not the \ul value\ulnone  of the\'a0 \ul present,\ulnone  will they regard but \ul your\ulnone  \ul remembering\ulnone  them, & anything from \ul Charleston\ulnone  will seem to them \ul great\ulnone .\'a0 A little present for Mary Mauldin also get.\'a0 Little China ornaments can be got for 15 cts.\'a0 Those little baskets, cups & saucers &c. that we have had, were of that price.\'a0 Get a \ul little\ulnone  \ul present\ulnone  for your Grandmama, Aunt Susy & Aunt Annie, also for Vardry Alex Annie & Susy, a doll for the two latter & some toy or book for the former, a dress for Lindy\'92s baby of cheap calico, a knife for Willie & Frank, the dolls & sugar toys for Fanny, & with the \ul 2 dollars\ulnone  she gave you buy her a large \ul box\ulnone  of \ul Furniture\ulnone .\'a0 I wish her to begin having a \ul baby\ulnone  \ul house\ulnone , so as to keep all her things in order.\'a0 At some future time I wish you to get a \ul dinner\ulnone  \ul set\ulnone  of \ul China\ulnone  for yourself so inquire \ul now\ulnone  the price.\'a0 It will be useful when your young friends come to see you.\'a0 You can have a table set to yourselves.\'a0 I expect \ul now \ulnone you cannot afford it.\'a0 Some time hence you might get it.\'a0 If you need \'85rilla before you get back, you must buy some & take.\'a0 Mrs. Elford went down first, & I expect sent you the gingernuts.\'a0 Mr. Elford went down afterwards, I expect had the hair & a letter for Eliza.\'a0 You must get Eliza to buy two bottles of \'93preparation of Castor oil,\'94 one for Aunt Susy [&] one for me.\'a0 I am glad you got a new bonnet.\'a0 I would like one for Fanny, if it is as pretty as any others worn by little girls of her age.\'a0 I have bought a Worsted bonnet here for Hext, & given him Fanny\'92s cloak, so he can do without anything.\'a0 Buy a Cornelian ring for Annie & Fanny, & one for yourself.\'a0 I wish you to buy a dress, & have any \ul new\ulnone  \ul fashioned apron\ulnone ; \ul Sack\ulnone  \ul or\ulnone  \ul new\ulnone  \ul bonnet\ulnone , or anything else \ul pretty\ulnone  you see made up for yourself.\'a0 All the \ul pretty\ulnone  \ul patterns\ulnone  you\ul  \ulnone can get, \ul bring\ulnone .\'a0 I am sorry you will not see Aunt Harriet & Sarah, & that you have not seen either Aunt Emily or Aunt Susan, & that sickness is the cause of not seeing the two later.\'a0 This visit is an event in your life which you will never forget, & you are grateful I am sure to your friends for being so kind, & will always do what you can in your power to return it.\'a0 I hope you will see Eloisa\'92s family before you leave.\'a0 The Legislature adjourns today.\'a0 Your Papa sets off tomorrow, & will return in Mr. Duncan\'92s carri[a]ge, for one of the sons went down in it.\'a0 The roads must be very bad.\'a0 It is raining now, & has been for several days.\'a0 Give my love to my friends.\'a0 Go & see Mrs. Elford & write when she will return; also go & see Mary Crayton.\'a0 Your attached Mother, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Anna Parry\
[Charleston]\
\'a0\

