Friday morning \'bd past 9, 17 December 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\
Dear Anna\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I wrote you a long letter yesterday & did not expect to write to you today, but as tomorrow no Mail goes, I will write now.\'a0 I have just received a letter from your Papa.\'a0 He is to leave Columbia today, & hopes to be at home tomorrow evening.\'a0 He comes up on the R[ail] Road & from there in Mr. Duncans carri[a]ge.\'a0 As neither of us now have to write to him, we can write oftener to each other.\'a0 I would be glad if every morning you would write to me, & tell me everything that interests you.\'a0 You will in this way tell me more than I will otherwise hear, for you will write of what may escape your mind when you get home.\'a0\'a0\'a0 As soon as you know from Mr. Elford what \ul time\ulnone  he is to return, let me know. Four days in this week it has rained.\'a0 Today it seems as if the weather may clear.\'a0 I hope it will.\'a0 For your Papa\'92s sake who is coming home, for your sake, that you may be able to go about, & for my sake that I may have the house cleaned.\'a0 It is very dirty, so much mud is brought into the house by the servants. The carpets I have had turned, & whitewashed the two Dining rooms, & bought some \ul reasonable \ulnone furniture Calico at Crittendens & made new curtains for the dining room windows.\'a0 The Calico is beautiful & was only 9 1/4 cts a yd & everything looked \ul neat\ulnone , but the rainy weather has caused so much dirt to be brought into the house, that I now have to clean it all again.\'a0 The soil here is very bad, different from the City, & there the yards & streets are generally paved, which is so neat.\'a0 We are all well except Eliza.\'a0 She is sick in bed, & has been unwell a long time.\'a0 Dr. Crooks had to come & see her today.\'a0 Becky gets along well with all the servants.\'a0 They like her, & respect her, so I hear no more abuse & quarreling among them as I used to.\'a0 Baylies has Prayer meetings every evening in his room at\'85it is more of \ul family\ulnone  \ul prayers\ulnone  for the servants in the \ul yard\ulnone .\'a0 He thinks \ul Lindy\ulnone  is feeling an interest in religion.\'a0 I hope so, & that it will make her a \ul good\ulnone  \ul servant\ulnone .\'a0 Next Wednesday the 22
\fs24\fsmilli12222 \super nd
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \nosupersub  Rutters time is up, & as your Grandmama does not like to hire Rutter with her \ul two\ulnone  children, & have to pay 1 dollar month for Catherine who does \ul nothing \ulnone for her, only minds Rutters child & cannot even \ul talk\ulnone  or go on a message, she intends to let Rutter & her children go home, & try Lindy instead.\'a0 If she does \ul well\ulnone , she will keep her.\'a0 If she does \ul not\ulnone , she will look for another servant.\'a0 Priscilla is there now, & I expect will stay there for her food & clothing.\'a0 She will help mind Lindy\'92s child.\'a0 Aunt Annie is very poorly.\'a0 Your Grandmama is not well today.\'a0 Alex & Vardry have been there since Saturday, on account of Alex being sick with Measles.\'a0 He has worms also.\'a0 The weather has been so bad, that since you left I have been out very little, once to your Grandmama\'92s, three times to ride on business, & twice to church.\'a0 Susan, Annie & Susy staid with me awhile.\'a0 Becky sent in word last night to say, I must write you word not to forget \ul her\ulnone  \ul comb\ulnone .\'a0 Your Aunt Susy says you must be \ul sure \ulnone & bring 4 Sugar dogs for her children, & if the 25 cts she gave you to buy them with is not \ul enough\ulnone , to get more money from Aunt Eliza, who has some of your Grandmama\'92s money.\'a0 She wishes \ul pretty\ulnone  dogs, & the children will be very much disappointed if you do not bring them, so you must not forget it.\'a0 Your Silver comb cost so much less than I expected, that I wish you to get one for Annie \ul just\ulnone  like yours.\'a0 I suppose your size she can wear \ul now\ulnone , & when she gets older too, she needs a comb always to keep back her hair.\'a0 The horn one she breaks, & one of the plated kind her Mamma got her, but it hurts her head & she cannot wear it, so as I intended to get her a \ul cloak\ulnone  but now she does not \ul need\ulnone  one.\'a0 I will instead get her a silver comb, which will be a lasting \ul useful\ulnone  present for her.\'a0 You I expect will not have money enough to buy it, so if your cousin Eliza will add it to the list I have already sent her, I will pay for it, when I pay for the other things.\'a0 Willie & Frank have bought have bought two pigs from me.\'a0 As soon as they can get at their Bank & \ul pay\ulnone  me, I will send you the money to invest in something for them, books perhaps.\'a0 The Candy & Cocoa & ground nut cakes you must not forget.\'a0 50 cts worth of Sugar ground nut cake, 50 cts worth of Cocoa nut cake, 50 cts worth of Candy of different kinds, & 50 cts worth of \ul Cakes\ulnone  of different kinds.\'a0 These things are instead of buying anything here for Christmas, & if \ul you are\ulnone  not here Christmas, we will put off the celebration till \ul you\ulnone  \ul return\ulnone , & it will be better, for at Christmas the servants have holiday, & cannot do much for \ul us\ulnone . After their holiday is over, they can wait on us, & Becky will make us something nice.\'a0 So do not regret if you are not here Christmas, we will wait for you.\'a0 I want you to buy a nice little bible for yourself, a larger size I wish for Willie & Frank.\'a0 If you choose you can buy the three Bibles in town. Beg Eliza to have a \ul Cloak\ulnone  made for Fanny & buy a \ul pretty\ulnone  bonnet & all I have written for.\'a0 Fanny has no cloak to wear to church.\'a0 I wish it \ul made\ulnone  up, for Eliza is sick, & cannot work, & I have no pattern to make it by.\'a0 Some little girl of Fanny\'92s age you will know of to fit by.\'a0 Be sure to bring the cloak \ul made\ulnone , & try & get patterns for yourself. Beg Aunt Anna Hayne to carry you to see \ul her\ulnone  friend, & \ul our\ulnone  friend \ul Elizabeth\ulnone  \ul Jones\ulnone .\'a0 I did not know until you mentioned it, that the Canaries were dead.\'a0 Gine my love to your Aunts & cousins.\'a0 Your affectionate Mother, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Anna Perry\
[Charleston]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 257\
Saturday morning, 18 December 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Anna\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received a letter from you, & one from your Papa, the \ul last\ulnone  one I will get from him for a long time, for he will reach home today.\'a0 Mr. Hoke has just sent me word, that he heard of his just having left the head of the R[ail] Road, which I was thankful to hear, as so many accidents now happen.\'a0 He comes home through Abbeville, passes Cokesbury where Mrs. Holmes lives, & was to sleep at Col. Wares last night. I must begin & tell you of the \ul increases\ulnone  in the family which will surprise you.\'a0 Yesterday afternoon I rode over to Mamma\'92s, & as soon as I got back, the children came running to me, crying out, \'93Eliza has a baby, it is to be Hext\'92s maid,\'94 & so it was.\'a0 Eliza has a girl, the baby is well, but Eliza last night was \ul very\ulnone  \ul ill\ulnone .\'a0 She fainted, & was out of her head.\'a0 I went up to see her.\'a0 This morning she is better. Before I was out of bed this morning, Frank came running up saying \'93the Sow has five pigs.\'94\'a0 So I told him I would give each of you a pig, which you must each attend to, & when they grow up, you would sell them to your Papa.\'a0Since you left \ul two\ulnone  Cows have had Calves, so you see what an \ul increase\ulnone  there has been in the family.\'a0 Willie & Frank will soon have to help your Papa support them.\'a0 We now have plenty of Milk & Cream.\'a0 Willie & Frank enjoy it, & have given up Tea & Coffee which I am glad of.\'a0 Your not coming back with your Papa will give us \ul two\ulnone  pleasures.\'a0 We are now with pleasure expecting him, & afterwards we will have the pleasure of looking forward to your return.\'a0 Your Papa writes, he has directed you to get money from Mr. Elford if you need it.\'a0 Mr. Elford has money of his.\'a0 You can also tell your Cousin Eliza, that \ul she\ulnone  can get \ul money\ulnone  from \ul Mr. Elford\ulnone  to pay for the things she buys for me. I know I will like your Cloak, & all you have bought.\'a0 I may before you leave write for a few more things.\'a0 I hope Eliza will have a pretty cloak made for Fanny.\'a0 I would like you to get the \ul largest\ulnone  size box of \ul Furniture\ulnone \'a0 for Fanny.\'a0 I want her to have a baby house.\'a0 She gave you 2 dollars of hers.\'a0 If 150 the Furniture costs, with the 50 cts left, buy some other toy for the baby house.\'a0 I would like you to get a Bedstead for it, &\'a0\'a0 several other peices of Furniture also bring her that will be suitable for the baby house.\'a0 She is so fond of arranging things it will delight her to fix the house, & give her occupation, which we have to find for children to make them happy. I am glad you are making so pretty a quilt.\'a0 I wish you always to have one on hand.\'a0 Eliza said \ul Worsted\ulnone  Quilts were pretty, & they must be very warm for winter & suit Greenville.\'a0 I wish you would get her to make \ul one\ulnone  \ul patch\ulnone , buy \ul several\ulnone  \ul kinds\ulnone  of Worsted cloth, & you bring it up with you & make a quilt.\'a0 I am glad your Aunts think you behave well, & feel \ul young\ulnone  again.\'a0 In being with you, interest in the\ul  young\ulnone  is what prevents persons feeling their age as they grow older, & it is \ul wisely\ulnone  \ul ordered\ulnone .\'a0 So old age is not as sad as it otherwise would be.\'a0 We live over again in the \ul young\ulnone .\'a0 We are interested for \ul them\ulnone , as we once were for \ul ourselves\ulnone .\'a0 You must bring us any present you think proper.\'a0 I wish \ul two\ulnone  pair of \ul Mits\ulnone  to wear in the house & a \ul neck\ulnone  \ul ribbon\ulnone  to wear to church.\'a0 You may bring \ul me\ulnone  \ul these\ulnone  as presents.\'a0 For your Aunt Eliza\'92s present, ask your cousin Eliza what to get for her mother, & then ask Eliza what to get for Eliza & Sue. Mrs. Barnwell Rhett\'92s is a sad death, & she will be a great loss to her children.\'a0 Children require so the care of a Mother, that her loss is even greater than the Father.\'a0Tell your Aunts Willie is not quite so ungallant as he was.\'a0 As he grows older he feels the value of the Fair Sex & pays them more respect. Tell Aunt Eliza, no change for the \ul better\ulnone  takes place at your Grandmama, that Mammas situation is one of \ul constant\ulnone  trial, & I wonder her mind & body have been able to bear it.\'a0 A \ul living\ulnone  \ul trouble\ulnone  like hers is worse than death.\'a0 She tries to be cheerful & to bear up, but it is hard not to despond.\'a0 Aunt Eliza must write to her & try & comfort her.\'a0 Her letters are consoling.\'a0 She must also send messages to Susan to tell her to bear up. & to Ann to acquiesce in what has happened.\'a0 You must bring your Grandmama & Aunts whatever present you choose, either something useful or pretty.\'a0 Buy for yourself a few peices of Music, easy enough for you to learn. I wish you could learn to Crochet. Since I commenced writing Aunt Mary McCall\'92s box has arrived. It stopped in Columbia & your Papa sent it on by the Stage.\'a0 Tell your cousin Eliza the bonnet is prettier & fancier than I expected.\'a0 It is a \ul dark\ulnone  \ul Straw\ulnone  with a feather, so I will be able to wear it to \ul church\ulnone , but it is not suitable for \ul common\ulnone  occasions, so the one I wrote her to get, I will still be glad of, as I need one to wear on occasions that the other I would not wear the feather would look unsuitable, & it is \ul very\ulnone  \ul small\ulnone .\'a0 Tell her the \ul Cloak\ulnone  Aunt Mary has sent me is beautiful to \ul look\ulnone  at, but not useful.\'a0 It is the \ul lightest\ulnone  grey colour & so \ul small\ulnone , it cannot meet across the chest. So instead of the \ul bonnet\ulnone , the \ul Cloak\ulnone  I must try & dispose of.\'a0 Ask her what a Cloak like the kind she is now making for herself would \ul cost\ulnone  for \ul me\ulnone , the materials & the making it.\'a0 I like a \ul dark\ulnone  \ul Cloak\ulnone  that will not \ul soil\ulnone  easily, for even our carri[a]ges here are not always clean.\'a0 I will get \ul her\ulnone  to have a cloak made for me.\'a0 I am as \ul tall\ulnone  as Eloisa, but \ul much\ulnone  \ul stouter\ulnone  across the chest particularly & back.\'a0 [E.F.P.]\
\'a0\
Anna Perry\
[Charleston]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 258\
Tuesday evening , 21 December 1852\
Charleston
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Mama\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 We were all out this morning shopping, & that is the reason why I did not write to you.\'a0 I will not have time to write but a few lines.\'a0 Aunt Emily has invited us to drink tea this evening with her.\'a0 It has been raining & thundering today but this morning was beautiful.\'a0 Aunt Eliza says that she knows that Aunt Emily is going to send for us, if it pours down.\'a0 It\'a0 has stopped raining now.\'a0 Aunt Anna & aunt Martha are going in the country,,,that is Thursday.\'a0 They are to take tea with aunt Eliza tomorrow evening.\'a0 All of my relations are kind to me & they all send their love to you all.\'a0 Cousin Sarah Gibbes invited me to tea yesterday.\'a0 I went.\'a0 I spent a very pleasant evening.\'a0 She has three daughters & four sons.\'a0 Two of her sons are grown & one of her daughters.\'a0 The next daughter is fifteen & her next just eleven.\'a0 She sends her love to you all & says she is very sorry for Aunt Annie, & aunt Susy.\'a0 Cousin Eliza says she will try to have a cloak made for Fanny.\'a0 I saw Miss Mary Drayton in the streets this morning & she said that Mr. & Mrs. Elford\'a0 were going next Tuesday or the end of next week.\'a0 I expect that I will go up with them.\'a0 I am enjoying myself exceedingly well.\'a0 I have bought six bibles for the servants. Cousin Eliza says she will get the other two for the servants if you wish her to do so and the two for Willie & Frank.\'a0 I have just received a letter from you but have not time to answer it.\'a0 Give my love to all, especially to Papa.\'a0 Your affectionate daughter, Anna. P.S. Aunt Eliza, Cousin Eliza, & cousin Susan send their best love to you all.\
\'a0\
Elizabeth Perry\
[Greenville]\
\'a0\

