21 December [1852]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
My dear Anna\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received two letters from you, and one from Aunt Eliza.\'a0 I write to say as there is such a difficulty in having work done, I will \ul give\ulnone  \ul up\ulnone  having Fanny\'92s cloak made.\'a0 If the \ul materials\ulnone  are \ul bought\ulnone  & a \ul pattern\ulnone  \ul sent\ulnone , I will have the Cloak made \ul here\ulnone .\'a0 I will make it \ul myself\ulnone .\'a0 If a \ul ready\ulnone  \ul made\ulnone  \ul Worsted\ulnone  Cloak would have been got, it would have saved the trouble of making one.\'a0 If cloak patterns cannot be got, perhaps a S\'85 a large one will do.\'a0 If so get [page torn] materials for a S\'85 & a pattern. I wrote to Eliza to have a Cloak made for me; at least that I would wish one, but as there is such a delay, it will be best to inquire the prices of \ul ready\ulnone  \ul made\ulnone  \ul Cloaks\ulnone , black silk & other \ul dark\ulnone  \ul kinds\ulnone .\'a0 It will be better to give \ul more\ulnone , & be saved the trouble of buying materials & \ul waiting\ulnone  to have the Cloak ma[de].\'a0 There is such a delay in fitting oneself with suitable winter clothes, so that this winter I am \ul obliged\ulnone  to have some things.\'a0 Last Sunday I wore a hat with a feather, & an old black Silk dress, & felt very shabby indeed.\'a0 As Eliza wil[l] be confined to her room for a month I got Margaret [to] let Clara come & make a dress for me, the \ul first\ulnone  she has ever made \ul alone\ulnone .\'a0 She is now in the room with me making the dress. Tell Aunt Eliza Aunt Mary McCall sent me two beautiful dresses.\'a0 The blue one was got at Browning & Semans 25 cts a yd.\'a0 The whole peice looks \ul beautiful\ulnone , much prettier than yours at the same \ul price\ulnone .\'a0 The Cashmere is 75 [page torn] & is \ul embroidered\ulnone .\'a0 I send a pattern, but not of the part \ul embroidered\ulnone .\'a0 Mary said \ul belts\ulnone  were \ul not\ulnone  \ul worn\ulnone , the dresses were \ul peaked\ulnone , but I intend to have my dresses made my same favorite way & so need a belt for each dress.\'a0 Ask Eliza to buy me a belt for each.\'a0 They can come up in [page torn] \ul large\ulnone  \ul envelope\ulnone , if no opportunity occurs. There are a great many stores here, but the shopping is very \ul limited\ulnone .\'a0 If we get a dress, we cannot get \ul trimmings\ulnone  for it.\'a0 \ul You\ulnone  would not price a pr of Gaiter boots to fit, & some simple things we cannot get, & the Stores are so frequented by \ul Greenville\ulnone  \ul Loungers\ulnone , it is disagreeable\'a0 to go in them & the merchants are \ul acquaintances \ulnone , & they \ul talk\ulnone  & \ul press\ulnone  their goods on us, so it is very awkward to refuse.\'a0 The shopping [l]ine is more like disagreeable visiting in the City.\'a0 It is a business matter\{&\} I am surprised Mr. Elford did not deliver my packages\ul  immediately\ulnone .\'a0 He is more careless than I thought.\'a0 He is not as \ul punctual\ulnone  & \ul exact\ulnone  in \ul business\ulnone  as your \ul Papa\ulnone  is.\'a0 Mr. Elford\'92s little daughter is not expected to live.\'a0 He has been written for & may come back before he has time to let you know, before you can get ready to come.\'a0 If so I will let you know of the \ul first\ulnone  opportunity I hear of.\'a0 It may be \ul inconvenient\ulnone  for your Aunt to have you longer, & I do not wish you to \ul impose\ulnone  on her \ul hospitality\ulnone , so you must consult \ul her\ulnone  wishes about lengthening your visit.\'a0 She has been \ul very\ulnone  \ul kind\ulnone  indeed to you, & has afforded you a \ul great\ulnone  \ul pleasure\ulnone  by introducing you to your relations.\'a0 You cannot return her kindness [page torn] it \ul deserves\ulnone , but you must show your \ul value\ulnone  of it, by making her some useful present.\'a0 You must get money from Mr. Elford & pay for what \ul I\ulnone  wrote for, & also if you \ul need\ulnone  \ul any.\ulnone  [G]et at Klinckes a Jar of \ul preserved\ulnone  \ul Ginger \ulnone & give to your\'85in \ul my\ulnone  \ul name\ulnone  & get a present for \ul her\ulnone  \ul Eloisa\ulnone  & \ul Susan\ulnone .\'a0 If you buy the \ul dress\ulnone  & t\ul rimmings\ulnone  & bring it home, Eliza can make it when she gets well.\'a0 A dress for 25 cts a yd as pretty as the blue Aunt Mary has got me at that price, & which [pagetorn]\'a0 send a \ul pattern\ulnone  of will do.\'a0 Beg Eliza to get me two belts to suit [page torn] patterns I send.\'a0 I will write to Aunt Eliza soon.\'a0 Tell her I [w]ould be gratified if she would write to your Papa about you.\'a0 Your Mama, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Anna Perry\
[Charleston]\'a0\'a0\
\'a0\

\f1\b 260\
Friday morning, 24 December [1852]\
Greenville\
\'a0
\f0\b0 \
Dear Anna\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just written to your cousin Eliza & will now write to you.\'a0 I expected you home this morning.\'a0 I heard Mr. Elford would be here.\'a0 Last night I heard a Stage as I thought stop at the gate.\'a0 The driver called out very loud, & then blew his horn.\'a0 I thought \ul you\ulnone  had come, & woke your Papa & he woke Charlotte.\'a0 By that time the horn sounded at a distance, & I discovered it was the Augusta Stage that had passed.\'a0 This morning Mr. Hoke told your Papa, Mr. & Mrs. Elford had arrived at 6 oclock.\'a0 Little Mary Elford died only a short time before.\'a0 She was at Mr. Perry Duncans.\'a0 Mr. Duncan sent in a servant to prepare Mr. & Mrs. Elford for the sad event.\'a0 The servant passed them on the road, but they were afraid to inquire of him about the child, so rode on, & knew not whether the child was alive or not until they got to Mr. Duncan\'92s & found it dead.\'a0 It was something like Scarlet fever, for yesterday an irruption broke out.\'a0 Fanny Hoke has also been sick in the same way, but is getting better.\'a0 How many little children have died lately in Greenville.\'a0 It must be a warning to those who are left.\'a0 Mrs. Harvey has moved into the County.\'a0 Her two oldest children will stay in the village & go to school.\'a0 Susan Hoke I see very often.\'a0 She sends her love.\'a0 She says she wrote to Augustus to go & see you, but as you have not mentioned his visit, I suppose he has not been.  I am sorry Mr. Elford was hurried home so much sooner than he expected, & that you did not come back with him.\'a0 Do inquire of Mary C\'85ton & anyone else from Greenville who may be in town of some opportunity, & let you know that you may return.\'a0 If you hear of none, in a little more than a week your Papa will go down for you.\'a0 He would set off at once, if it were not for some business that detains him at home.\'a0 I proposed that Willie should immediately go down for you, but your Papa said somebody would have to go to take care of Willie.\'a0 The\'a0 children are very much disappointed at not having their Christmas presents.\'a0 I have nothing to give them.\'a0 They will have to hang their Stockings after you come back.\'a0 I am sorry you are not here.\'a0 I put off making the Hogs feet into Jelly until you returned but now it is so warm I can wait no longer & am making the Jelly today.\'a0 I am sorry also you have been obliged to stay so much longer than we intended you should, & as your aunts house will soon be full, I feel uneasy at your putting her to inconvenience.\'a0 You must write to me every day until you return.\'a0 Do not forget the Candy & Cocoa nut cake for the children.\'a0 I am getting nothing of the kind for their Christmas here.\'a0 I have sent Eliza 20 dollars, & I have troubled her so much in shopping for me that except a\'85for Fanny, & something for a S\'85 or Cloak for her, & a pair of Gaiter boots for me, & a Prayer book for yourself, there is nothing more I wish at this time.\'a0 You know we pay our bills.\'a0 We have to contract during the year, at the Blacksmiths, Sadlers. Doctors &c, buy meat Corn &c, so I am more straightened than at any other time, or I would send for a great many things I need, & I have also a large bill to pay Aunt Mary McCall \ul 21\ulnone  dollars for the \ul Cloak\ulnone , which is almost \ul white\ulnone , & I never expect to wear, but I know she did the best for me, as she thought, & therefore I do not wish to hurt her feelings, & she has been kind to you, but it would have been better not to have got me my cloak.\'a0 The bonnet is \ul too\ulnone  \ul fashionable\ulnone  for Greenville, but I cannot dispose of it, so wear it.\'a0 If I had known there was so much difficulty in getting work done I would not have written to you to get a dress.\'a0 I am sorry I troubled your cousin so about work. Your friends have been kind to you, & I am sure you will never forget it.  I hope to see you soon, & to hear from you every day.\'a0 Frank says bring him some crackers, & Willie & himself a knife.\'a0 In haste.\'a0 Your affectionate mother  Mr. Hopkins & his family have just passed on their way to Florida.\'a0 Fanny is regretting she did not see them, & says she wishes Rosa had staid.\'a0 I think Fanny is almost crying.\'a0 She is now saying, \'93I want Anna.\'a0 I wish Anna would come.\'94 The Silver Comb I want for Annie like yours.\
\'a0\
Anna Perry\
[Charleston]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 261\
Saturday afternoon. 25 December [1852]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Anna\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 This is Christmas day, & a very dull day it has been.\'a0 The weather continues very bad.\'a0 I never knew so long a spell of rainy warm weather in winter.\'a0 The streets & yards are very muddy, & the house looks as if it never could recover.\'a0 The Carpets I am afraid are ruined.\'a0 The roads must be dreadful.\'a0 Your Grandmama & family were not able on account of the weather to come in & spend the day with me.\'a0 I sent them some of our desert, as they could not come.\'a0 I let Becky have holiday, & Lindy cooked.\'a0 Tomorrow Lindy will have holiday.\'a0 The pleasure seems to be all among the servants.\'a0 Last night some of them went to a party; today they have dined out, & their having holiday seems to make them happy.\'a0 The children hung up their Stockings, so I was obliged to put something in.\'a0 I bought 5 cts worth of Candy apiece, a mug, a 5 cts doll, a cake, an apple, a \ul switch \ulnone & 10 cts apiece.\'a0 So St Nicholas they think has not forgotten them.\'a0 Fanny regrets very much that you are not here.\'a0 I hope when you return we will have pleasant cheerful weather or you will think Greenville very dull.\'a0 Your Papa will go down for you.\'a0 He may not have time to go & return before New Years day.\'a0 If he does not, he will go immediately after New Years Day & that will be as soon as Mr. Springer thinks of coming.\'a0 So by New Years day have everything ready.\'a0 I dare say he will spend a few days in town though, so you will have time to get ready after he gets down.\'a0 I expect he will take Willie with him. Mary Elford was buried this morning.\'a0 I hope she has spent her Christmas in a happy world with Laura McKay, who was so afflicted, that I think it was a blessing she was taken, as her life would certainly have been one of suffering. Fanny Hoke is getting better.\'a0 Fanny sent her a doll & she sent Fanny a box.\'a0 Susan Hoke told me she wrote to Augustus to go & see you.\'a0 I suppose he feels awkward about visiting.\'a0 Butler Tompson told your Papa his Fathers wifes son, weighed 13 \'bd pounds, & his father was very proud of it.\'a0I am always writing you something to get, & I expect as long as you remain in town it will be the case.\'a0 I wish you to get me a little \ul key\ulnone  \ul basket\ulnone , & 1 dozen \ul black\ulnone  \ul lacets\ulnone  for Gaiter boots.\'a0 The tines come off so soon, & then ties cannot be laced.\'a0 Mr. Westfield puts such large tines on they will not go through the holes, & then they cannot be laced, so buy one dozen black lacets for Gaiter boots. Some neat \ul dark\ulnone  Calico about 12 \'bd\'a0 cts a yd such as will \ul wash\ulnone  I also wish, & will write for before you leave.\'a0 A good many yds I would like, but I will wait until I get Eliza\'92s \ul next\ulnone  \ul list\ulnone .\'a0 Beg her to send me a list of the other things she has bought.\'a0 I know I will like the bonnet she has got, & will wear it constantly.\'a0 I see in my list Calico is mentioned for A\'85 the 1.37 \'bd for the Calico if Eliza \ul chooses\ulnone  & the 1.12 \'bd for Reedy House might be added to your money, & pay for some of the things you have got. I am obliged to your Aunts for making you such acceptable presents as the Bible & Prayer book, the very things you were going to buy.\'a0 Also to Aunt Eliza for the boxes & Aunt Emily.\'a0 Your friends are very kind & I am thankful for the good opinion they have of you.\'a0 I am greatly indebted to your cousin Eliza for all the trouble she has taken to shop for me.\'a0 I will never forget their kindness to you.\'a0 Aunt Mary McCall has been kind.\'a0 I hoped to have heard today from her about the Cloak but have not.\'a0 If the man will take it back, your Papa can carry it down, but I suppose he will not change it.\'a0Give my love to your Aunt & cousins, Aunt Mary, Aunt Anna, Aunt Emily & my other Aunts.\'a0 I wish you would see about Sarah Matthews & Aunt Harriett but suppose you will not.\'a0 Give my love to cousin Sarah Gibbes, Mrs. Irvine Keith, Mrs. O\'92Driscoll, & my other family.\'a0 Have you seen Elizabeth Jones? It is 10 oclock.\'a0 I can hardly see to write.\'a0 Hext is well & fat & lively & good, better than he used to be.\'a0 Minerva is sick, over at the Mansion House, with cold & headache.\'a0 The rest are well.\'a0 Lindy is still lame from Rheumatism, & is not going at present to your Grandmama\'92s.\'a0 She has engaged Nancy Greens daughter.\'a0 While Lindy\'92s baby is young, I know she would not do well hired out.\'a0 She can hardly work but next summer, after her child can run about she will do better.\'a0 She is now only able to help the other servants.\'a0 I will stop now & finish my letter after the candles are lit. Dear Anna,
\f1\b  
\f0\b0 You had better buy the dolls not dressed & dress them yourself.\'a0 I hope Aunt Harriett will come down from Mrs. Wilkes to see you if you are in town when she is there.\'a0 I am sorry you have not dined with your Aunts in Meeting St. but hope you will now.\'a0 We used to spend pleasant days with them when we were children.\'a0 I hope Alston will name his son after his f\ul ather\ulnone .\'a0 He lost one named Robert, but I think he ought to name another after his father, & that it would please his Mother.\'a0 I am sorry Aunt Anna Turnbull & Aunt Martha have gone in the country.\'a0 I hope you will see them again, & that they will be in town when your Papa & Willie go down.\'a0 Tuesday week I expect your Papa will go down for you.\'a0 Wednesday the day after he will stop at Newberry to attend a R[ail] Road meeting, Thursday he will go to Columbia, & Friday reach Charleston.\'a0 He will remain there a few days.\'a0 It is very \ul unexpected\ulnone  he is going down, but now he has determined to go, he is pleased with the trip, he is obliged to be back before the 15
