\f1\b 264\
Friday, 1 oclock, 31 December 1852\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Anna\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just written to Aunt Eliza to say, you may remain longer in town, that my only fear was, you would put her to inconvenience. & be in the way, when the family became larger, but as she says this is not the case, & you are passing your time so pleasantly, & are anxious to remain longer, we have no objection at all to your remaining, & coming up with Mary Crayton, if she does not stay longer in town, than you think you \ul ought\ulnone  to stay.\'a0 Your Papa is better today, but will not be able at present to fix upon any time to go for you, & if you come up with Mary Crayton, or any other lady coming, he will not go down, as the traveling is too unpleasant at this season to visit town for pleasure.\'a0 We leave it to \ul you\ulnone  now & your \ul Aunt\ulnone  to return, at a suitable time.\'a0 Of course I would not object to your lengthening your visit, except that I thought you were trespassing on your Aunt\'92s hospitality, which she says is not the case.\'a0 I am very much pleased with the accounts Aunt Eliza & your cousin Eliza give of you, they say you have pleased \ul all\ulnone  your friends, behaved exceedingly well, & have all the virtues that adorn the female character.\'a0 I hope you will improve as you grow older, & not disappoint your friends, & be a comfort to all those kind friends, who are interested in you, & set a good example to Fanny.\'a0 The character of the oldest sister has great influence over the others, & therefore a great responsibility rests on you.\'a0 I am glad you perform all of your duties so regularly & do not forget the most important, the \ul religious\ulnone  one, you must keep yourself very \ul neat\ulnone , clean your teeth regularly, wash your hands, face, ears clean your nails, & be very nice in person, you know cleanliness is a virtue placed very high in the bible.\'a0 I see in the paper Charcoal recommended as the best \ul tooth\ulnone  powder, buy a box & use it every morning.\'a0 If I cannot get any here, I will get you to buy some for me.\'a0 I do not need the \ul key\ulnone  \ul basket\ulnone  now.\'a0 Mr. Elford has bought a \ul nest\ulnone , which I suppose includes the\'85for keys, so if you have not got it already, you need not. I much prefer Fanny\'92s cloak being made.\'a0 I countermanded the order thinking it could not be done conveniently, but Eliza has engaged the mantua maker, & says it can be done.\'a0 I will be very glad to have it made, & of a \ul large\ulnone  size, as the winter is so far advanced it will be more useful \ul next\ulnone  winter than \ul this\ulnone . Tell Eliza by Butler Thompson I will send down a Gaiter boot, so she can know exactly the kind I wish, & I may write for a pr of India rubber shoes, & she can put them over the Gaiter. Mamma asks Eliza with the money she has of hers to spend 2.25 or about that, for a Silver spoon for Sarah Taft\'92s child.\'a0 It is named after Mamma, Susan Hayne McCall Taft.\'a0 She wishes the four Initials marked on the spoon S.H.M.T.\'a0 Eliza will know what kind of spoon will be suitable. I am glad you spend Christmas so pleasantly, & am sorry as you were, that you could not have been at Mr. Wm Ravenel\'92s where I suppose the \ul tree\ulnone  was beautiful. But it was kind in Mrs. Drayton to ask you. I am pleased you remembered your Aunt & cousins with a little present.\'a0 If I had not a \ul large\ulnone  \ul debt\ulnone  to pay to Aunt Mary McCall, I would send you money to make them \ul handsome\ulnone  presents.\'a0 Minerva\'92s wages are due in two weeks & the \ul whole\ulnone  of it I have to send to Aunt Mary & more besides, & what is mortifying, the Cloak is useless, & the bonnet almost so.\'a0 I have worn it \ul once\ulnone  only, & am sorry I wore it then, as Eliza has got me one I know I will like better, & Aunt Mary\'92s, perhaps I might have disposed of it at a low price, or kept it for you to wear at a future time, taking out the \ul feather\ulnone .\'a0 But Aunt Mary meant to please me, but Ella being so much smaller than I am, if she had \ul thought\ulnone  about it, she would have known the bonnet was too small for me.\'a0 She has been kind to you, & I am \ul grateful\ulnone  to her, & will not let her know my disappointment. Ask Eliza the \ul price\ulnone  of \ul her\ulnone  cloak, materials & mating.\'a0 I can better judge by the \ul estimate\ulnone  she sent me, & wish to know what just such a one as hers costs.\'a0 I will be sure to get one, perhaps just like hers next winter.\'a0 Mrs. Robinson, Mrs. Thompsons Aunt says she will take down mine, next week.\'a0 I will direct it to Aunt Eliza & get her to send it to Aunt Mary.\'a0 Perhaps I may send you a sun bonnet, apron, and flannel petticoat.\'a0 You may have use for them as you are to stay longer & I will send you my gold chain to wear with your medallion when you take tea out, as I think you have nothing suitable to wear with it.\'a0 I see Eliza bought you two Collars 12 \'bd apiece.\'a0 If you need it, get some more, & if Eliza thinks you need undersleeves, buy or make some.\'a0 Tell Eliza anything you really need, I wish her to get for you, if she can get it with \ul convenience\ulnone . I have written word you may get a wicker box.\'a0 If you can get one, you will find useful for \ul every
\fs32 \ulnone  day use.\'a0 Generally they are only for \ul show\ulnone , & the scissors, thimble &c in them only for \ul ornament\ulnone .\'a0 Perhaps you can get one without thimble scissors & buy for it all that is needed, but consult with Eliza, & beg her to get you a \ul useful\ulnone  one.\'a0 Another Christmas I will get you a Writing desk, as you must keep up a correspondence with the relations who have been so kind to you, & will need a desk.\'a0 Inquire the price & let me know of a neat writing desk. & when you get the\'85box, tell me the price.\'a0You must continue to behave well as you have done, & not make your Aunt regret having to ask you to stay longer.\'a0 She is very kind to you.\'a0 Give my love to all my Aunts.\'a0 I will let you know when the box comes.\'a0 Your affectionate Mother, E.F.P.
