December 1852
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \

\fs32 Greenville
\f0\b0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \

\fs32 \'a0
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \

\fs32 Dear Anna
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \

\fs32 \'a0
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \

\fs32 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just written two letters one to your Papa the other to Mr. Elford on business, & will write to you now.\'a0 My pen is \ul bent\ulnone , so I cannot write well.\'a0 I suppose you have seen Mr. Elford before this.\'a0 If he stays \ul longer\ulnone  in town than you wish, or ought to stay, you can come up by any other opportunity you hear of.\'a0 He told me he might be only 10 days in town, but \ul perhaps\ulnone  3 weeks, so I thought he & his Wife would be the very best persons you could come up with, & the Stage at the time \ul he\ulnone  comes, will not be so crowded, as at the time the Legislature adjourns.
\fs29\fsmilli14667  
\fs32 I received a \ul long\ulnone  letter from you today.\'a0 I was glad to hear from you.\'a0 I am sorry your Cloak had not been made, as you must have needed it, ever since you have been in town.\'a0 I am sorry you did not mention the \ul price\ulnone  of the things you bought.\'a0 I your \ul next\ulnone  letter you must.\'a0 As you have written to your Papa for money I do not like you to write a second time for \ul me\ulnone  so unless you have money left, I may not send for the articles I wish until he returns \ul home\ulnone , & \ul then\ulnone  I will send the money.\'a0 I thought you would need more than 10 dollars.\'a0 He says you wrote for 10.\'a0 You write me if you have any money left, & then I can tell you what to get, but \ul first\ulnone  get all \ul you\ulnone  need, a \ul dress\ulnone  \ul frock\ulnone  for Fanny & a \ul cloak\ulnone  for her, are what I would first get, after you have supplied yourself, a pr of gaiters for yourself, myself, Fanny & Hext I wish, such as your cousin Eliza wears.\'a0 The price of a bonnet for Fanny, I would like to know.\'a0 The Candy if you do not write in time for, you can get as much as you think best.\'a0 Buy a pretty pair of Ear[r]ings, for yourself.\'a0 Eliza had best write the list of your purchases.\'a0 If you need more money send to your Papa.\'a0 He will send it to you, & I dare say you will need it.\'a0 I do not care to send to him for money for \ul myself\ulnone , but I wish you to get for \ul yourself\ulnone  all you need.\'a0 I can do without the things I intended sending for, for Aunt Maery McCall has got me what I most needed. I am glad you are enjoying yourself, & that your friends are so kind to you.\'a0 Remember me to them \ul all\ulnone .\'a0 I send you a little book to read\'a0 that your Aunt Eliza gave you.\'a0 I read it this morning to Fanny, & it contains just such advice as I would like to give you now, but I am obliged to stop, for since beginning this letter I have received by Mr. Beattie two letters from your Papa.\'a0 I had written to him & told him I had not heard, & now I must write again, which makes me shorten your letter.\'a0 I write so \ul badly\ulnone .\'a0 You must tell Aunt Eliza & your Cousins what I say, & can read \ul aloud\ulnone  \ul parts \ulnone but do not \ul show\ulnone  them the letters, for I am ashamed of them.\'a0 Beg Aunt Eliza to write to me.\'a0Willie Frank & Fanny & Hext will all be glad to see you again, also your Grandmama Aunts Papa & myself.\'a0 Your attached Mother, E.F.P.
