Tuesday night, [1852]
\f0\b0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \

\fs32 \'a0
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \

\fs32 My dear husband
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \

\fs32 \'a0
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \

\fs32 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 Tonight Reuben said that Kossuth ploughed well, & that that good quality ought to be mentioned in the advertisement.\'a0 I do not know what kind of advertisement Mr. Elford has written, but perhaps \ul you \ulnone had better write such a one as you would wish, & give it to Mr. Elford to put in \ul next weeks\ulnone  paper, for someone then may buy him to use on their farm to plough.\'a0 He certainly is fit for nothing else, though perhaps some person who understands breaking a horse, may in time break him, but I very much doubt it, for he seems by nature to be a[n] \ul obstinate\ulnone  \ul bad\ulnone  \ul horse\ulnone , & I cannot understood how Mr. Redwood can be a \ul truthful\ulnone  man, & at the same time say, Kossuth was a \ul good\ulnone  \ul Buggy\ulnone  \ul horse\ulnone .\'a0 I am truly thankful you are going to sell him.\'a0 I have not had a comfortable ride since you owned him.\'a0 Selim & Hocky\'a0 will do to draw together, until you sell Selim & get a fine pair.\'a0 Perhaps H\'85\'92s\'85you can buy & use with him, but I would rather be without horses, than have such a one as Kossuth.\'a0 He is not worth his food.\'a0 Goodnight.\'a0 Write by Mr. Elford, E.F.P.
