Monday morning, 10 January [1853]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Anna\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I received letters from your cousin Eliza & yourself yesterday.\'a0 Thank Eliza for hers, & as she says she will soon write again, beg her to, & I will write to her.\'a0 You have really passed your time pleasantly.\'a0 Your friends have been very kind to you.\'a0 I feel indebted to all of them, but more especially to your Aunt Eliza & her family.\'a0 Thanks Aunt Mary & Aunt Anna for the presents you say they have sent to the children, & thank Aunt Mary McCall for her presents.\'a0 She has been very kind.\'a0 I will send her the 2 dollars, she had to pay for changing the Cloak.\'a0 Your Aunt Suzy wishes to know the \ul price \ulnone of the black cape.\'a0 I do not know, as it cost me on account changing 23 dollars, so at Mr. Reed\'92s, inquire the \ul price\ulnone  that I may tell Susan.\'a0 You say I had better send a list of the articles I wish purchased, so I will.\'a0 I have almost forgotten what I have written for, you can add what I have overlooked.\'a0 The work box for your Aunt & yourself you must \ul first\ulnone  get, then what I have put on the list, & after that the Candy, cocoa nut cake & little presents you intended getting.\'a0 The 40 dollars I hope you have received, the 15 taken out for your expenses back leaves 25 dollars.\'a0 Eliza wrote word yesterday I must send 25, so I am glad you have exactly that sum.\'a0 It may not be enough, as I have written for knives, so if it is not let me know.\'a0 Tooth powder I cannot get here.\'a0 Be sure & bring 3 boxes of powdered Charcoal.\'a0 I used to get it 20 cts a box; not \ul paste\ulnone , but merely \ul powdered Charcoal\ulnone .\'a0 One of the boxes is for you.\'a0 If you have not got it yet, get it immediately & \ul use\ulnone , the \ul two \ulnone others bring home.\'a0 Sally Hoke came here this morning, & her teeth looked so black, it reminded me of telling \ul you\ulnone  to attend to yours.\'a0 I suppose you have not needed any Sarsaparilla.\'a0 The Lacets for Gaiters though trifling is important,\'a0 for every morning now I am delayed trying to lace with a \ul pin\ulnone , & then have to give up, & wrap the lacet round the boot, the tins come off, & the tinners here put on such large ones, they will not go trough the holes.\'a0 I send a button for you to get one dozen like 18 \'be cts.\'a0 Ask Aunt Mary McCall where she got it.\'a0 She did not send enough.\'a0 The Calico you sent in the box for your Aunt Annie, If it comes soon, I may take, if \ul you \ulnone are \ul willing \ulnone to make myself a dress to wear at home.\'a0 I need it very much, & your Aunt Annie has just had a worsted Gown made to wear at home. & bought a Calico one, & Clara is to make it for her.\'a0 I have made \ul none \ulnone to wear at home yet.\'a0 The \ul two \ulnone I have got, are what I sent patterns to you of.\'a0 The \ul blue \ulnone one is made & I wear to church, but if you prefer my \ul not \ulnone taking the Calico, you must say so.\'a0 I have written to Eliza to get me Calico for a dress, but it will be long before I get it, through I am very much afraid the box also will not be here soon.\'a0After you have purchased my list, & sent me an account, if you remain long enough, I may write for a few more things, two \ul nice\ulnone  pocket handkerchiefs, about 37 \'bd\'a0 apeice or the peice Susan, but cost 43 \'be, & your Papa wishes Linen for shirts which I may write for.\'a0 Send up as many things as you can by private opportunities, Mr. Jones & Thompson.\'a0 I hope before this my cloak has arrived safely & that I will soon get the other one.\'a0 When the ginger gives out, if you would like it, you can get your Aunt another Jar. I am glad you have fine weather now.\'a0 At least I suppose you have, as we have now delightful weather like Spring.\'a0 Yesterday was cloudy & drizzly, so we did not go to church.\'a0 In the morning your Grandmama sent to ask how Mrs. Sam town[e]s was & she is very ill, & not able to see anyone.\'a0 Her lungs are affected, & she can scarcely speak.\'a0 The roads to her house are almost impassable. So we did not go to see her, but if she gets better we will go.\'a0Beg Aunt Eliza to write to me.\'a0 Tell her \ul you\ulnone  write about \ul others\ulnone , & wish to hear from \ul her \ulnone about \ul you.\ulnone  I hope the Cholera will not increase.\'a0 If it becomes alarming, I suppose Mary Crayton will immediately return, & you would come with her.\'a0 Let me know when you think she will return, if she will soon or not, if she will return this month. Willie & Frank commenced school today, both at the Academy.\'a0 Mr. Hillhouse teaches Frank, Mr. Thomas Willie.\'a0 Willie has come back already, & says Mr. Thomas, as yet has only two scholars, George Wells & himself.\'a0 He is to buy more books today, & go back again this afternoon. I will go to see Mrs. Mauldin, & ask when her daughters are going.\'a0\'a0 You say you saw pretty key baskets.\'a0 If you choose you can get one as a present to your Aunt Suzy or Annie or for yourself, or for me.\'a0 It will not come amiss.\'a0 If they are \ul reasonable\ulnone , but if you prefer it, get something else.\'a0 The\'85of baskets Mr. Elford has got me.\'a0 I may spare some of them to your Grandmama as presents.\'a0 I think he said he had got a nest, but I may be mistaken, for I thought he had got knives & rods which he has not. You must excuse my shabby looking letter.\'a0 I am busy & often write so hurriedly I am almost ashamed to send my letters.\'a0 You must take Aunt Eliza & Eliza as your examples for neat writing, not me.\'a0 My gold pen is bent, & writes badly, which is my excuse.\'a0 I will send the carpet bag key by Butler Thompson.\'a0 Mrs. Robinson sent word she was going Wednesday.\'a0 I suppose he will go with her.\'a0 I will write a few lines by him.\'a0 I will soon write to Eliza.\'a0 If you would like it, you can buy a \ul pretty\ulnone  \ul work\ulnone  \ul basket\ulnone  \ul apiece \ulnone for your cousins Eliza & Susan, & not get any to bring home.\'a0 The nest of baskets will do for us. Give my kindest love to your Aunt & cousins & thank them for being so kind to you., & giving you so much pleasure, enough to think of & talk of a long time.\'a0 My love to my other friends.\'a0 Your affectionate Mother, E.F. Perry Buy some large sheets of letter paper & write longer letters.\'a0 \ul Burn\ulnone  up \ul my \ulnone letter.\
\'a0\
Anna Perry\
[Charleston]\
\'a0\

\f1\b 280\
Tuesday morning, 10 oclock, 11 January [1853]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Anna\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received two letters from you, & must answer them immediately, for the Mail now closes at 12 oclock, & the letters must be just in sooner than heretofore.\'a0 I hear very regularly from you, every day except Monday when no Mail comes, & you ought to hear every day from me except Monday, so Monday you get no letter from me. Your friends have all been as kind as possible to you,\'a0 You must thank Aunt Brewton for the present you say she has sent Willie, & tell her I hope her Godson will do credit to her.\'a0 If he is as \ul good\ulnone  as he is \ul smart\ulnone , there will be no fear but what he will.\'a0 I do not say so from \ul vanity\ulnone , but from the opinion \ul all \ulnone his Teachers have expressed, & not to \ul me\ulnone , but to \ul others \ulnone have they expressed it, so I know it is their real opinion.\'a0 Your Papa also has a high opinion of Willie\'92s mind, & he has a good judgement, & no vanity, either for himself or his children. Thank your cousin Eloisa for the cup & saucer.\'a0 It is in a box of paper &c. your Papa had packed in Columbia but it has not come yet.\'a0 The roads are in so dreadful a condition no waggons are transporting goods, either from the Laurens R[ail] Road, or the box would have come on from Hamburg, where our groceries are at present & the box with them that Aunt Eliza had packed.\'a0\'a0 Today your Papa received a letter from Jeffers & Cothran the factors who are to forward the boxes, & they say since Christmas no waggons have come, that the streets present every day the appearance of the Sabbath, & from the accounts they hear of the roads, it will continue so a long time, but by the \ul first \ulnone opportunity they will send on the boxes.\'a0 If I had imagined this delay, I would have done without several things I wrote for, & sent you the money instead, or bought things for summer use.\'a0 F\'85 & my bonnets, we will have to put up for next winter.\'a0 You will be here at the opening of the box I have no doubt, & witness the joy of the children.\'a0 A person in Mobile is writing sketches of distinguished men, & mentions Uncle Robert.\'a0 In a Columbia paper there is an extract in which Aunt Brewton is mentioned.\'a0 It will be published in the Patriot.\'a0 I will cut it out & send to you, & you can give it to Aunt Brewton.\'a0 Perhaps she has seen it, [but] if not, it will gratify her, to see honorable mention made of one whose memory she reveres as she does Uncle Roberts. It was kind in Eloisa to say, she would like to have you stay with her.\'a0 I appreciate her kind intention.\'a0 You must go often to see her, & Aunt Anna Turnbull & Aunt Martha & Aunt Mary & Aunt Anna Hayne, & any friend Aunt Eliza tells you to go & see. I am sorry Aunt Emily is sick, & Paul\'92s wife in delicate health.\'a0 Give my love to Aunt Emily when you next see her, & Aunt Susan, Aunt Brewton, Aunt Elizabeth & Uncle Arthur, Aunts in Logan st. & Meeting st.\'a0 Your Papa is now quite well.\'a0 All at your Grandmama\'92s are the same as usual.\'a0 Clara works every day for them.\'a0 I help them in that way, as much as I can, & work for myself.\'a0 Margaret at present can spare her.\'a0 Eliza has not worked for me since the birth of her baby, but will again next week.\'a0 Lindy is at home, at present with her child to attend to.\'a0 No one will hire her, but next summer we will get her a place. The new kitchen is building, & when it is done, our servants will be comfortably accommodated, & we will have a nice kitchen for our own use.\'a0 No one but the cook to stay in & an ironing room, for no purpose but ironing.\'a0 The two new chambers, Eliza & Lindy will have.\'a0 If Minerva wishes it, she can come over & sleep in the room Eliza now has.\'a0 Charles will either sleep in the cellar or the old kitchen, & the small house, you shall again have to keep as a play house.\'a0 Mr. Rosemond will repair it.\'a0 I will give Fanny the press in the little dining room as a baby house & put in the play house, all the toys you have bought her, shall stay there.\'a0 If you had kept all the presents ever given you, how many you would have had.\'a0 Begin now & keep them all carefully.\'a0 When you have bought the list I have sent you, I hope to send some more money.\'a0 Have you spent the 5 dollars you took out of your Bank.\'a0 Send as many things by Mr. Jones or Thompson as they can bring.\'a0 I expect you spent a delightful day at the island.\'a0 Your Aunt & cousins have been so kind in trying to gratify you in every way.\'a0 You must tell them I thank them for their kindness to you.\'a0 Tell them not to give themselves any trouble on your account.\'a0 The visiting among your friends, & seeing them, is an enjoyment to you & Greenville is so quiet.\'a0 A walk up King st.\'a0 is such a contrast to a walk here that it affords you delight.\'a0 The shells we will be glad of, & something new in Greenville.\'a0 You must keep them as a curiosity.\'a0 I am sorry you have not seen your cousin Sarah Taylor yet.\'a0 If you do, tell her the Scripture Biography she gave Willie, I find very useful in reading to the children & servants on Sunday, & tell Eloisa the basket she gave me in town, I use even now as a key basket. I saw in the Courier that your Papa had been alluded to by Mr. John Preston.\'a0 In Columbia last winter Professor Thornwell\'92s brother pointed to your Papa & said \'93See that person, two years ago, he was avoided by Politicians as death, & now he has more influence in the Legislature, than any other Member, & more coveted by aspirants.\'94\'a0 Your Papa has always acted independently, & in acting as he thought right, has gone against his own interests, which proves his sincerity.\'a0 Such conduct always in the end begets esteem, & he has in his opinion the best reward, a good conscience & his own self respect. Give my love to Aunt Eliza & your cousins.\'a0 Their kindness I will never forget.\'a0 Ask Aunt Eliza to write to me.\'a0 I will write to Eliza tomorrow.\'a0 Go & see Mary Crayton, & let me know when she expects to return.\'a0 Your affectionate Mother, E.F. Perry\
\'a0\
Anna Perry\
[Charleston]\
\'a0\

