Tuesday afternoon, [11 January 1853]\
[Greenville]
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Anna\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I wrote you a long letter this morning.\'a0 I now write only a few lines.\'a0 I will send them by Butler Thompson & send the key you asked for.\'a0 I will send this letter to Mrs. Robinson & she will give it to Butler Thompson, who I suppose is going with her.\'a0 His father a week or two ago said he was.\'a0 The weather is now clouding over & we will soon have rain again.\'a0 Write word when Mary Crayton intends returning so I may know when to expect you.\'a0 I suppose this month she will return.\'a0 Your cousin Eliza said about the 20
\fs24\fsmilli12222 \super th
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \nosupersub  of this month.\'a0Fanny goes to school, but she prefers staying at home.\'a0 She will like it better when you go with her.\'a0 I sent to ask Mrs. Mauldin when her daughters were going to school & she sent word, they were not going at all.\'a0 I sent Aunt Mary today the 2 dollars she paid for changing the Cloak.\'a0 I hope you have received the 40 dollars I sent you safely.\'a0 I write so hurriedly, you must tear up my letters, tear up this one.\'a0 I write so much & have other things to do, I write in haste.\'a0 Be a good girl.\'a0 I hope Mr. Jones or Thompson will bring the Cloak.\'a0 Mr. & Mrs. Bacon came to see me this morning & inquired about you.\'a0 I told then what Mrs. O\'92Driscoll said, & that you practiced every day.\'a0 Mr. Bacon says he has only 3 scholars now that for a short time in summer he had 23, but he ought to have 30 scholars the whole year round to afford him a support, that if he did not get more scholars he could not live here, but this climate agreed with his health, so he hoped he could get enough to enable him to stay.\'a0 I hope he will find you improved.\'a0 He says he has no objection to your buying any pretty peices for yourself.\'a0 Your Grandmama & Aunts send their affectionate love.\'a0 Your Grandmama says you write wonderfully well.\'a0 She is pleased at Aunt Brewton remembering Willie.\'a0 Give my love to your Aunts & cousins, whose kindness to you has been very great, & I know you feel grateful, & will never forget it, & when in your power return it.\'a0 Mrs. Sam Town[e]s is better & Mr. Hodges through very low, is not dead.\'a0 The report was not a mistake. You must soon buy the work box for Aunt Eliza as a testimony of your love for her, & a proof you feel gratified for her kindness.\'a0 Your affectionate mother, E.F. Perry P.S.\'a0 Get a Cornelian ring for yourself & one for \ul Fanny\ulnone .\'a0 Her silver comb I will give to \ul Annie\ulnone , which is more valuable than a ring.\'a0 Buy 2 dolls for Fanny & Annie.\'a0 You can dress them when you return & a small doll to L\'85a knife with 2 blades for Willie & Frank, \ul not \ulnone expensive ones.\
