\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 \'85like to get for yourself you may.\'a0 The knives for Willie & Frank need not be fine ones, as they will soon lose them.\'a0 Put on paper a list of what I have mentioned in this letter.\'a0 Your Aunt Annie wishes \'93Nelly was a Lady[.\'93]\'a0 The 75 cts for Music that was charged to you, your Grandmama wishes to add to her bit, so that 75 cts you will have to add to your money to buy something with.\'a0 I you need a thick pr of shoes for \ul school\ulnone , you had best get them now.\'a0 I hope to be able to get some more pocket handkerchiefs, as need more.\'a0 If I write for them, I will wish some at 16 cts, for you, & \ul marked \ulnone with \ul your name\ulnone \'a0 & some for 25 cts marked with \ul mine\ulnone .\'a0 Mrs. Sam Town[e]s is getting better, & sent word she would be glad to see me.\'a0 At the time Mr. Town[e]s was abusing your papa in his paper, I would not take pleasure in visiting his family, so gave her up, but your Papa has forgiven him, & Mr. Town[e]s looks to him to do more for him than anyone. A great change has taken place & the \ul very\ulnone  \ul persons \ulnone who during political excitement abuse your Papa the \ul most\ulnone , are \ul now\ulnone  writing to \ul him\ulnone . to use his influence with\ul  \ulnone Genl Pierce to give them \ul Offices\ulnone .\'a0 \ul They \ulnone say your Papa writes for them, would have an effect, more than anyone else.\'a0 He does for \ul them\ulnone , & those who have \ul injured\ulnone  him, what he \ul would\ulnone  not do for himself. I will go to see Mrs. Town[e]s when the roads are good.\'a0 Now they are at most impassable.\'a0 I dare say it will not be before you return.\'a0 You can go with me.\'a0 I will call Julia Sharpe to keep the seat at her desk for you.\'a0 I am certain she will.\'a0 Except Miss Hopkins there is no other school for girls.\'a0I hope Clara will be a valuable servant for you by & by; then her wages can even support you.\'a0 Margaret says she can do everything except make Pastry, & that \ul that\ulnone  she would soon learn.\'a0 Our servants are so expensive now, the supporting them &c, that if it were not for the hope of \ul future \ulnone profit, we would be obliged to sell them.\'a0 Eliza\'92s baby is a month old Monday.\'a0 Then Sarah will go back to Margaret, who I hope will take her, through she sent word she did not care for her.\'a0 She is useless here, & get[t]ing into bad habits.\'a0 Eliza\'92s influence & example to her children is so bad, I would be thankful if we could get rid of her.\'a0 Johnny at present seems a good boy. Give my love to all my Aunts.\'a0 If Aunt Harriet is at Mr. W\'85, ask Aunt Eliza to write to her, & beg her to come down for one day & see you.\'a0 It is only a short ride, & I am certain if she knew you were in town, she would come & see you.\'a0 I will send you stamps in this letter.\'a0 When they give out, it would be well to buy some. Aunt Anna\'92s friend was a pious lady, & so afflicted, that her death must have been a blessing, as they have every reason I hope to think she is happy now.\'a0 Mr. Elford has money of your Papa\'92s. but has had no settlement since he returned. So I do not know wat he bought for me.\'a0\'a0 Mr. Wm Watson I believe goes to town soon.\'a0 I had just written this sentence when your Papa came in & brought Mr. Elford\'92s bills.\'a0 He has bought the nest of baskets, the Calico for Comforts, the Fender, Andirons, shovel & tongs, broom & bellows, the nest of baskets is 3.87.\'a0 Mama I expect will take some of them, the Calico 6 \'bc a yd, the other things $18.19 cts. I have just heard Mr. Hodges is dead, that he was resigned, he had no children, & his Wife & himself not very happy.\'a0 Mr. Henry Thompson & your Papa got elected to Commissioner of\'85& he came this morning to ask if he would appoint his son Henry as keeper of the gate, which Mr. Hodges used to keep; that Henry will stay at Mrs. Hodges, keep the gate, & keep school at the same time, & attend to his studies.\'a0 He will make several hundred dollars a year, & is only 17.\'a0 You see when persons are poor & thrown on their own resource, how they manage to support themselves, & at the same time improve their Character & acquire habits of industry, they make their own fortunes, whereas, if their parents had a few hundreds to give them, they think themselves \ul above\ulnone  work. & become \ul idle\ulnone  & dissipated & ruined characters.\'a0 I am glad there is at last something cheering for Mrs. Thompson.\'a0 She has sent repeatedly to ask if there was bundle here for her, but I have heard of none that was coming for her, unless some of her friends intend sending one by you.\'a0 If Charlotte Smith hears of your being in town, I dare say she will send a bundle.\
