\f1\b 284\
Thursday morning, 13 January [1853]\
Greenville
\f0\b0 \
\'a0\
Dear Anna\
\'a0\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 I have just received a long letter from you & must answer it immediately as the Stage goes now at 12 oclock.\'a0 There is one thing that I wish to get & that is a pattern for the side of an Ottoman.\'a0 Get it the \ul length\ulnone  of the paper I send, & of the \ul shape\ulnone .\'a0 I have cut the paper, & one bunch of worsted like each colour in the pattern.\'a0 I have had broadcloth for you to work ottomans for your Grandmama, & this winter I would like to continue them at least.\'a0 I will teach you how to do the worsted work, & you must work a pincushion\'a0 for each friend who has shown you kindness, since you have been in town, tell them so.\'a0 I have plenty of Broadcloth & Canvass & some Worsted.\'a0 Also, buy one dozen worsted needles of different sizes, some of them very \ul small\ulnone , & you can commence when you return, & work them at your leisure.\'a0 You have made a pleasant visit.\'a0 I know you will need more money.\'a0 If I do not send what you need in time, if your Aunt advances it, I will immediately return it, as soon as I hear from you how much it is, but I much prefer your asking me for it, than getting it from anyone else.\'a0 So write & let me know what you need.\'a0 I am sorry Wm Ed had a pencil case.\'a0 Perhaps Eliza might think of something else for him, & be sure & buy the work box for Aunt Eliza, & a basket or something else for Eliza & Sue, & a handkerchief for each of the servants. I am glad you make yourself useful to your Aunt, & helped her fix the curtains.\'a0 I wish you would see Sarah Taylor, but if you leave before she comes, perhaps in Columbia you may have time to see her.\'a0 I am glad Aunt Anna & Aunt Martha you have seen again.\'a0 Tell them to write to me by you.\'a0 Bring as many letters as you can from our friends.\'a0 Let them know when you will leave, & beg them to write.\'a0 I suppose you have not seen K\'85\'92s relations, Mary, Sarah & Edward though they are not I believe estimable characters,\'a0 Still if you could see them & tell K\'85 you have, it would gratify her.\'a0 I am glad Mr. Jones will return soon, & that he will bring some of the things.\'a0 I sent a letter enclosing the key yesterday to Mrs. Robinson & she had \ul gone\ulnone .\'a0 It is no consequence, for since I have heard Butler Thompson was only going as far as Columbia with them, so I will send the key in this letter. We all will be very glad to see you.\'a0 Mr. McKay & the oldest Miss Hayden teach the large girls; the youngest Miss Hayden teaches the small girls.\'a0 Fanny says they are not cross.\'a0 Mr. Thomas teaches Willie a great many more studies than Mr. Leary did.\'a0 He wishes Frank to learn Latin, but we prefer not.\'a0 He is too young.\'a0 You must take good care of the children at school.\'a0 Only two of the Brooks go to school.\'a0 Mrs. Sam Town[e]s is getting better, & Mr. Hodges also.\'a0 Soon I must go & see Mrs. Mauldin & some others.\'a0 A Chinese ornament for 25 cts, or a little basket, or any little present, you can bring Mary Mauldin. Aunt Mary McCall today I heard from saying she had received the Check.\'a0 I hope she will receive safely 2 dollars I have since sent her.\'a0 Some pretty Calico get me for aprons for Fanny.\'a0 I would send you a \ul 5 dollar\ulnone  bill at \ul least \ulnone in this letter, if it had not the key & paper in it, for I know you would be glad of it.\'a0 If I write tomorrow I will send it.\'a0 I hear from you regularly each day except Monday, when no Mail comes.\'a0 I am surprised you do not receive one letter each day from me, instead of so many at one time.\'a0 Your Papa says I write too often.\'a0 I suppose that you have heard that Genl Pierce\'92s only child has been killed on the R[ail] Road, how sad.\'a0 I am glad you have some shells, & found it pleasant on the island.\'a0 It looks a good deal like rain again.\'a0 The roads will be worse than ever. Tell your Aunts you will work them a pincushion. & also Eliza & Susan.\'a0 I will help you.\'a0 I did wish you to buy some books, some of Miss Milfords & Mrs. Howitts works, but will have to put off for another time.\'a0 At the end of the year there are so many bills to pay, or I would have sent more money.\'a0 Another visit I will supply you better & not tell you to buy so many things for me.\'a0 I wrote to Eliza yesterday.\'a0 I do not know what our Eliza will name her baby.\'a0 Aunt Eliza has no name to\'85of her.\'a0 She is one of the \ul worst \ulnone servants I know of.\'a0 She has no \ul principle\ulnone , & I am afraid with such a Mother, her \ul children \ulnone will not have any.\'a0 They are corrupted from their infancy, & if it were not for \ul Missy\ulnone , who has been a \ul faithful \ulnone servant to Mamma, I would not feel it my duty to keep such a servant.\'a0 Do not forget Becky\'92s comb.\'a0 She is not near as good a cook as Minerva, but she is a \ul better\ulnone  \ul servant\ulnone , & makes all happier.\'a0 Minerva wishes to leave the Mansion House, says she is worked too hard, but she is always \ul dissatisfied\ulnone . Give my love to Aunt Eliza & your cousins, & my other Aunts.\'a0 I am sorry Aunt Emily is sick.\'a0 Let me know when to expect you.\'a0 Emily Earle & her sister go to the Academy.\'a0 It is the only female school now. Your Papa is quite well now.\'a0 It is no consequence when you see Augustus Hoke, & Mr. Smith must be wanting in steadiness to leave his business for such a trifling reason.\'a0 Hext is well; the other children at school.\'a0 Clara as soon as the new kitchen is finished is going to have a party or Fair.\'a0 I do not like to have such things in the yard, but disliked refusing, & if it is in the kitchen & not in the cellar, it will not distract us.\'a0 I hope to hear tomorrow, as soon as you have taken a list of the things you are to buy, that I have written in this letter, \ul burn \ulnone it. do not show it to anyone.\'a0 It is written so badly.\'a0 Your affectionate Mother, E.F.P.\
\'a0\
Anna Perry\
[Charleston]\
\'a0\

